</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-JOHNSON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
NEW YORK _ Don't even bother mentioning anything about a so-called
``tainted'' championship around San Antonio's Avery Johnson.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tell him that this year's title is bogus because of the
lockout-shortened, compressed NBA season, and he'll just shrug.
Mention that should the Spurs beat the New York Knicks tonight in
Game 5 of the NBA Finals at Madison Square Garden, giving the Spurs
their first championship, their rings should come with diamonds in
the shape of an asterisk, and he'll just politely smile, nod his
head and say, ``I'll wear mine with pride.''
</P>
<P>
   And don't talk about the Chicago Bulls not being around to
defend the title that had been theirs for six of the previous eight
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't know if they would have been able to win four in a
row,'' said Johnson of the Bulls. ``You don't know. Things happen
from year to year, and that's why (the Lakers') Derek Harper told
me, `You had better seize the moment and get it while you can.'
Injuries happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went from being a real good team to winning 20 games one
year (1996-97) when Dave (Robinson) and Sean (Elliott) and all
those guys got hurt. So you don't know from one year to the next
what is in store for you. It's hard to say. Yeah, you would have
liked to have had a chance to play them, but that's not going to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   There were many who doubted whether the Spurs would ever win a
title with Johnson at the helm, with Damon Stoudamire saying
exactly that. Indeed, ``the Little General'' has been treated more
like a buck private by coaches, his peers and the media.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Johnson, stung by his omission from the 1994 World Games
roster, said, ``The next thing you know, they'll be putting Avery
Johnson on the team.'' Though he later received a letter of apology
from K.J., Avery never forgot the slight.
</P>
<P>
   Nor has he forgotten the Christmas Eve in 1990 when Nuggets
coach Paul Westhead waived him. Former Spurs coaches Jerry
Tarkanian and John Lucas had little faith in the 5-11 guard from
Southern University, always on the lookout for someone better.
</P>
<P>
   No, Johnson, who has played for five NBA teams, including three
separate stints in San Antonio (and a brief time with the Rockets),
doesn't forget things like that. But he rarely talks about them,
and he never dwells on them.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who has matured into a steady point guard and honed his
jumper and flying hook shot to the point where he is capable of
scoring 20 points on any given night, just hopes that maybe winning
an NBA championship will change people's perception of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully,'' Johnson said. ``Hopefully, I will. You know,
you're in a situation where Kevin Johnson, John Stockton and Gary
Payton were, and hey, those guys have been here quite a bit and
kind of came away finishing second.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you have a chance to at least kind of set yourself apart
from them in that area. That's a challenge. And guys who say they
don't feel that kind of challenge, they're not telling you the
truth.''
</P>
<P>
   And Johnson will always tell you the truth. Always, which is one
of the reasons Johnson is so popular at the media sessions that are
a part of every player's NBA Finals routine.
</P>
<P>
   He's never dull.
</P>
<P>
   Suffice it to say that Johnson is to hyperactivity what Jolt
Cola is to caffeinated beverages. Johnson hardly pauses when he's
on the court, one reason he was able to pile up 14 points and a
game-high 10 assists in the Spurs' 96-89 Game 4 victory. And when
Johnson is off the court, his mind and tongue rarely take a break,
either.
</P>
<P>
   Even more so now that Johnson is 48 minutes away from his first
NBA championship. Just 48 more minutes against the Knicks tonight,
and Johnson's once-impossible _ or improbable _ dream could become
a reality.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson doesn't even allow himself the luxury of thinking
about such things as rings, banners and championship parades. Not
yet, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing is that you just try to get it out of your mind
as soon as possible,'' Johnson said. ``Once it happens, then you'll
be really, really excited, but right now there's still too much
work to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson thinks that way because he has to.
</P>
<P>
   The school of hard knocks has taught him to be wary and never
take anything for granted. So Johnson is almost afraid to let his
mind wander to the moment when the Spurs are raising a banner and a
ring is being slipped on his finger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kind of,'' Johnson said. ``The way the Knicks are when you
watch them on film, a shot here and a shot there, and they're still
in last night's game. Maybe if they don't get in foul trouble down
in San Antonio, maybe they get a split there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know. So it's a case of where I don't know if it's
afraid, but my favorite way of putting it in the playoffs is that
you just have a little fear in your attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   And should the Spurs close out the Knicks, Johnson will finally
get the credit he deserves _ plus some bragging rights when he
convenes his annual summer basketball sessions at Houston's
Westside Tennis Club. Johnson has had to take his licks from
Rockets past and present who earned championship rings in 1994 and
'95, so Johnson is looking for a little payback should he earn a
title for himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' said Johnson, who lives in Sugar Land. ``I'm looking
forward to seeing Sam Cassell, let's put it like that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
