<HEADER>
A8953 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     06-25 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRAN BLINEBURY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
NEW YORK _ To hear the Knicks tell it, they are right back where
they want to be, dangling over the abyss by the last few strands of
a frayed rope, or, like basketball's version of Indiana Jones, now
fueled by the adrenaline rush of having to outrun that giant
boulder one more time.
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the exception of their second-round frolic past gutless
Atlanta, this is how the Knicks have spent their spring and early
summer, scrambling to poke fingers in every new leak in the hull,
which is how the flimsy ship of the No. 8 seed from the Eastern
Conference managed to make it all the way to this championship
showdown with the pedigreed Spurs. They fought and battled and
bounced back to knock off Miami in an unlikely escape, and they
practically willed their way past Larry Bird's veteran bunch from
Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   Now though, all the will and perseverance in the world will not
get them past the Spurs. Not unless somebody in Manhattan can find
a washing machine big enough to hold both Tim Duncan and David
Robinson and shrink them down to a much more manageable size before
the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The bright orange T-shirts that were handed out for Game 4 on
Wednesday night said: ``I still believe!'' and they were supposed
to turn Madison Square Garden into the inside of a pumpkin carriage
that would take this Cinderella story onto an even more improbable
chapter as the Knicks tied the series.
</P>
<P>
   Didn't happen. Never will.
</P>
<P>
   The Stanley Cup has already taken up residence for the year in
Dallas, and the NBA championship trophy will surely join it in
Texas in just a few days _ following Game 5, Game 6 or Game 7, all
of which the Knicks must win in order to prevent the inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing to lose, nothing to lose,'' said Latrell Sprewell,
carrying the New York battle cry. ``We might as well let it all
hang out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely don't want them popping champagne on our
court,'' said Kurt Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   If not here, then back there in the shadow of the Alamo, but the
Spurs will eventually fill their mouths with the sweet taste of
those championship bubbles, which is what everybody outside New
York _ and perhaps a few long-suffering Spurs fatalists _ knew was
going to happen right from the start of this mismatch final series.
</P>
<P>
   For when you get through all of the emotion and some of the
problems the scrambling Knicks can present on a given night, it
still comes down to this basic basketball tenet: Size does matter.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs are bigger than the Knicks. And the bigger Spurs _
Duncan and Robinson _ are so much better than the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Without their warrior in the middle, Patrick Ewing, sidelined by
a torn Achilles' tendon, the Knicks entered this battle against
Goliath as David without a slingshot.
</P>
<P>
   For a game or two, or a moment or two, anything is possible. We
see it every March in the NCAA Tournament, where Gonzaga can knock
off Stanford or Weber State gets North Carolina. The Knicks had
their night of fantasy flight as well, riding Allan Houston's 34
points and a wave of emotion at the Garden to their Game 3 win.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA requires the underdog to pull off four upsets in a
best-of-seven series, and that is just not so likely to happen.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs regrouped after the loss Monday and were a different
team. They went back to doing all of the things that enabled them
to run up the best record in the league during the regular season
and win 45 of their past 52 games. Avery Johnson went back to
darting through the paint for driving layups or handing the ball
off for his 10 assists. Mario Elie returned strong and made big
plays one game after he had been cruelly taunted in his hometown.
Sean Elliott did an excellent job of shadowing Houston on defense
and finally broke out with key fourth-quarter baskets.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, there always were Duncan and Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have two big guys, and that means you can't take it to
the basket very much,'' Sprewell admitted. ``They're a little too
tall for us sometimes, and we don't have much of an inside
presence.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a harsh reality that is difficult to avoid. Which leaves
so many hoping for a miracle, like the night in 1970 when Willis
Reed made his limping, triumphant return before a roaring Garden
crowd and lifted the Knicks to a title. They are still showing that
scene, now nearly three decades old, on the video screen before
each game, as if such magic can be replayed and recreated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything is possible, if you believe,'' said the feisty point
guard Charlie Ward. ``They don't make up those shirts for
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   But they make them up in XXXL for Tim Duncan and David Robinson,
a simple fact that is easier to believe in.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
