<HEADER>
A8954 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-DIERKER-HN     06-25 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-DIERKER-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY WIZIG  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
At 5:10 p.m. Thursday, Larry Dierker strode as briskly as ever onto
the Astrodome field, and it was as if the Astros manager had never
been away.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``He looks great, relaxed as ever, and it's just great having
him back after everything that has happened,'' interim manager Matt
Galante said as the players took batting practice before their game
with Cincinnati. ``I've talked to him every day that he was able to
take calls after it (his grand mal seizure in the Dome dugout June
13) happened, and (general manager) Gerry Hunsicker told me this
morning that Larry would be coming out tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Same old Larry.''
</P>
<P>
   Except, of course, that instead of his baseball uniform, Dierker
was wearing one of his assortment of Hawaiian-style sport shirts
and a light-colored summer straw hat with a dark band.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always has a good-looking hat,'' Galante noted.
</P>
<P>
   So did Dierker in his first appearance at the ballpark since the
seizure that convulsed him so violently and, with nearly 40,000
fans and his players watching silently and prayerfully, sent him
away in an ambulance. The next day he underwent five hours of brain
surgery for a pair of masses of tangled blood vessels known as
arteriovenous malformations.
</P>
<P>
   Denis Menke, the former Astro who is now the Reds' hitting
coach, walked up to greet his old friend near the batting cage.
``I'm feeling pretty good,'' Dierker assured him. ``Same old me.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Menke said, ``He looks as natural as before it all
happened. He looks like he had never been gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Eleven days, 2 hours and about 20 minutes after the incident in
his brain that could have ended his life, Dierker was his usual
affable, joking self.
</P>
<P>
   During a brief 10-minute, on-field media session, Dierker was
asked if he would have a similar hat for every ensuing trip to the
Dome before he resumes his managerial duties. Said Dierker, ``You
only need one or two if you really like them.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker related how, after the surgery, he gradually regained
memory of the preceding events. ``On the third day, I was able to
get out of bed and have a cup of coffee and read the paper, the
things that a lot of people do the first thing in the morning,'' he
said. ``I thought it was like a miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   Watching the Astros play on TV from the hospital wasn't quite
the same as being there in person, and as soon as he received
medical clearance, Dierker was back, sooner than expected. He
wasn't expected in the Dome until later in the current homestand,
possibly by the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was told to come here and be like a fan and not like a
manager,'' Dierker said. ``So I guess I'll leave about the third
inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Which he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to see the team play, and the only way to do that was
to be here,'' Dierker reasoned. ``I'm sure I'll talk to Gerry and
Matt as the days go by. I think things have gone well. I don't see
any difference from before. I know I can't try to rush things to
get back too soon, so I'll do what they tell me to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker was given a standing ovation by the crowd of 25,543 when
he was introduced in the bottom of the first inning as he watched
the game with his wife, Judy, from Hunsicker's box on the press
level.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Spiers, Craig Biggio, Jeff Bagwell and Billy Wagner were
some of the Astros who greeted Dierker's unexpected return.
</P>
<P>
   ``To see him alive and well, it really is a lift,'' Wagner said.
``Just knowing he will be fine and things are OK, we've been
blessed.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Spiers: ``With all the things he's gone through and to see
him back in such a short time is really unbelievable. He seems like
the same old person.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe not quite, suggested Biggio, good-naturedly. ``He's
got a nasty zipper on his head, I'll tell you that,'' said Biggio,
``but he said he had plenty of hats (to cover the surgical scars).
He said he hadn't missed an inning of the games he'd been able to
watch. I told him he might have wanted to miss a couple or he might
have a relapse.''
</P>
<P>
   Turning serious, Biggio said, ``We've pretty much dedicated the
rest of the season to him. If anyone deserves anything positive, it
should happen to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell summed up the relieved mood in the Astros' clubhouse,
saying, ``It was just great to see him back. It was pretty crazy,
with what he went through, to see him walk back in in such a short
time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
