<SLUG> BC-RAC-HORSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD GOLD CUP LIMPS TO FINISH LINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Even before Old Trieste's foot abscess and
fever turned the ``now'' horse into the ``no'' horse this week,
something was missing from Sunday's Hollywood Gold Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The field was already small _ without Old Trieste, it's down to
four runners, leaving bettors with the fewest choices in 60
runnings of Hollywood Park's signature event and longshot players
up a creek. And it was already a locals-only affair _ every horse
based in Southern California, costing it the East-West intrigue
that ought to accompany a race in the ``NTRA Champions on Fox''
series.
</P>
<P>
   Show me anybody who's excited about the Gold Cup, even though
it's a $1 million race involving a Kentucky Derby winner, Real
Quiet, a rags-to-riches story, Budroyale, and two bullets from the
popular Richard Mandella barn, Puerto Madero and Malek.
</P>
<P>
   Where to place the blame?
</P>
<P>
   Blame bad luck for one thing. If not for untimely injuries to
Old Trieste, Santa Anita Handicap winner Free House and Strub
winner Event of the Year, and the fade and retirement of Silver
Charm, this would be an appealing Gold Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Blame the fact the nominating process began March 5, when owners
had to make their first, $1,000 payment, and supplemental
nominations closed 11 days before the race, when latecomers would
have had to put up $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to nominate way too early for these races,'' Real
Quiet trainer Bob Baffert said. He believes that keeps
opportunistic horsemen from jumping in after the withdrawal of a
favorite like Old Trieste weakens the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Blame what some see as the growing conservatism of trainers who
are too concerned about maintaining their win percentages to take a
calculated gamble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's so worried about whether they're a 10 percent
trainer, or a 20-percent trainer, or a 4 percent trainer, it takes
away their creativity,'' Mandella said.
</P>
<P>
   But save much of the blame for the National Thoroughbred Racing
Association series itself.
</P>
<P>
   The inaugural 11-race series is meant to induce top older horses
to race against each other from coast to coast, creating a
spring-to-fall story line worthy of network television. Ironically,
it has damaged the one race that already had a good East-West thing
going.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1992 the Gold Cup has been won by Eastern shippers Sultry
Song, Cigar and Skip Away. It's been the most welcoming of major
California races.
</P>
<P>
   But when Hollywood Park begged the New York-based trainer of
Behrens to send the NTRA series points leader here, Jim Bond said
no. He said he didn't want to ship west twice, knowing that the
series requires horses to run in the Aug. 29 Pacific Classic at Del
Mar to turn their accumulated points into cash. Behrens will stay
in New York and run in the series' July 5 Suburban Handicap.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood Park racing secretary Martin Panza has been polite
about it this week: ``I can't say the series did this to me.'' He
did, though, predict disaster for the Gold Cup when the series
format was unveiled last winter.
</P>
<P>
   NTRA officials speak of the series as a work in progress. The
format could change for next year. Unfortunately that's not
entirely up to the NTRA.
</P>
<P>
   Individual tracks won't necessarily cooperate on scheduling
races (though, now that Churchill Downs owns Hollywood Park,
Churchill's Stephen Foster Handicap and Hollywood's Gold Cup
probably won't be held two weeks apart again). Fox programmers must
be consulted.
</P>
<P>
   Most years, it will be the horses who decide if the series
succeeds. Give the NTRA a healthy Cigar or Skip Away every season
and watch it Go Baby Go. But horses aren't stock cars or golfers.
Injuries have to be expected.
</P>
<P>
   What can be done while we wait for a horse of steel? Suggestions
include: trimming the series schedule, so that trainers would have
less excuse for skipping a major race like the Gold Cup; sweetening
the purses, paying all the way down to eighth place, a safeguard
against four-horse fields; and flip-flopping the crucial series
finale, holding it in the West one year and the East the next, so a
race like the Gold Cup doesn't suffer every time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing succeeds overnight,'' Mandella said _ and, from
Hollywood Park's standpoint, certainly not the NTRA series.
</P>
<P>
   Also this weekend: The Gold Cup is one of eight stakes at
Hollywood Park tonight, Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   General Challenge will go without blinkers in Saturday's
Affirmed Handicap for 3-year-olds, the Santa Anita Derby winner's
first start since he finished a bruising 11th in the Kentucky
Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Chris McCarron, who lost a shot at his first Gold Cup victory
when Old Trieste fell ill, can get some consolation, he rides
odds-on Manistique against Gourmet Girl and four others in the
$400,000 Vanity Handicap for fillies and mares on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Breeders' Cup Sprint winner Reraise (Corey Nakatani) faces nine
horses in the 7-furlong Triple Bend Handicap on the Gold Cup
undercard.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Arcadia: These are unsettling days in the halls of
Santa Anita, where Frank Stronach marked six months behind the
track chairman's desk by shaking up the executive roster over the
past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Out: president and CEO Bill Baker and executive VP and GM Cliff
Goodrich. New president and CEO: Lonny Powell.
</P>
<P>
   Out: VP of racing Tom Robbins and racing secretary Tom Knust.
New director of racing: Mike Harlow.
</P>
<P>
   Out: marketing VP Craig Dado. New marketing director: Remi
Bellocq.
</P>
<P>
   Out: simulcasting director Bruce Matthias. New simulcasting
director: Andy Kure.
</P>
<P>
   Baker and Goodrich resigned after their influence waned.
Matthias took a leave of absence to run for the California Assembly
from Orange County. Dado was offered a position in the new Santa
Anita parent company and hasn't announced whether he'll accept it.
</P>
<P>
   Harlow, Belocque and Kure arrive on the coattails of Powell, who
spent nine years as an executive at R.D. Hubbard-run horse and
greyhound tracks, the past five as the boss of Turf Paradise in
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Powell, 39, grew up around racing as the son of jockey Taylor
Powell. The elder Powell rode Liberal Art, whose $322.10 payoff in
a 1956 race remained the highest win mutuel at Hollywood Park for
33 years.
</P>
<P>
   More lower-profile changes are expected at Santa Anita. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
A WEEK AT THE RACES &QL; 
Hollywood Park leaders: Jockeys (through Wednesday): Alex Solis, 45
wins; Garrett Gomez, 31; David Flores and Emile Ramsammy, 29;
Laffit Pincay, 23. Trainers: Ron McAnally, 20; Julio Canani and Ted
West Jr., 11; John Sadler, 10; Bob Baffert, Jack Carava, David
Hofmans and Mike Mitchell, 9. &QL; 
Handicapper helper: In the '90s the Hollywood Gold Cup has been a
race for horses with early speed. There have been four
front-running winners _ 27-1 Marquetry, 8-1 Slew of Damascus, 9-1
Siphon and 2-5 Skip Away. Only Best Pal and Cigar were able to
rally from more than 2{ lengths off the pace. &QL; 
On the stakes schedule: At Hollywood Park: tonight, $150,000 Fran's
Valentine, California-bred fillies and mares 3 and up, 1 1/16 miles
on turf, and $75,000 Arbor Vitae, 3-year-old fillies, 6{ furlongs;
Saturday, $400,000 Vanity Handicap, fillies and mares 3 and up, 1
1/8 miles, $125,000 Affirmed Handicap, 3-year-olds, 1 1/16 miles,
and $75,000 Jim Murray Memorial Handicap, 3-year-olds and up, 1{
miles on turf; Sunday, $1 million Hollywood Gold Cup, 3-year-olds
and up, 1\ miles, $300,000 Triple Bend Breeders' Cup Handicap,
3-year-olds and up, 7 furlongs, and $250,000 A Gleam Handicap,
fillies and mares 3 and up, 7 furlongs. At Belmont Park: Saturday,
$250,000 Mother Goose, 3-year-old fillies, 1 1/8 miles. At
Woodbine: Sunday, $500,000 Queen's Plate, 3-year-old
Canadian-breds, 1{ miles. &QL; 
Mileposts: First post at Hollywood Park is at 7 tonight. Gates open
at 11 a.m. for simulcast wagering on Belmont Park, Churchill Downs
and the Stockton fair. The last four Friday cards of the meet will
be held under the lights.... First post Sunday is earlier than
usual at 12:10 p.m. The Hollywood Gold Cup is scheduled as the
fifth race at 2:40. Gold Cup coverage on Channel 11 starts at 2
p.m.... This will be the first Gold Cup with a title sponsor _ San
Diego-based Sempra Energy.... Laffit Pincay's victory aboard Da Hot
Affair on Wednesday put him within 78 of Bill Shoemaker's record
8,833.... Pincay and Southern California rivals Chris McCarron,
Alex Solis and Chris Antley are among 12 riders in the third NTRA
All-Star Jockey Championship tonight at Lone Star Park near Dallas.
Gary Stevens won the four-race competition in 1997, Shane Sellers
in '98. Fans there _ but not here _ can bet on how the jockeys will
finish. Hollywood Park will take bets only on the last two
races.... The National Thoroughbred Racing Association and the
Daily Racing Form announced plans for the first National
Handicapping Championship to be held Jan. 7-8 at the MGM Grand in
Las Vegas. First prize: $100,000. NTRA-member tracks _ including
Hollywood Park, Del Mar and Santa Anita _ are to hold qualifying
tournaments with top-four finishers promised expenses-paid trips to
the finals.... Dramatic Gold has been retired following another
injury. The 8-year-old gelding won 9 of 39 starts, including his
'96 Meadowlands Cup victory and his '94 Breeders' Cup Classic
third, and earned more than $2.5 million for breeder-owners John
and Betty Mabee.... Tuesday's fire in trainer James Toner's Belmont
Park barn claimed a third equine victim Wednesday. Surely Handsome,
a 3-year-old maiden, was euthanized because of the effects of smoke
inhalation. The fire also killed Clear to Launch, a 3-year-old
gelding with one victory, and Graceful Finish, an unraced
2-year-old filly.... Excellent Meeting, who won Sunday's Princess
Stakes in her first start since being pulled up in the Preakness,
will aim for the July 17 Hollywood Oaks, trainer Bob Baffert
said.... Baffert's unbeaten 2-year-old filly Chilukki will run in
the 5{-furlong Debutante Stakes on Saturday at Churchill Downs.
Churchill's spring meet ends Sunday.... Sprinter Orville N Wilbur's
will miss the Triple Bend and perhaps four months after chipping a
sesamoid in a Saturday workout.... Fair-circuit racing moves to
Pleasanton on Wednesday.
</P>
