<HEADLINE>
JURORS MAY BE QUESTIONING STATE'S CASE IN SLEEPWALKING TRIAL
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD RUELAS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For what emergency would Scott Falater need a large hunting
knife?
</P>
<P>
   Why didn't any of Yarmila Falater's relatives testify?
</P>
<P>
   Did Scott Falater take a lie-detector test?
</P>
<P>
   These were among the questions jurors asked Judge Ronald
Reinstein on Thursday during the 12-member panel's first day of
discussing whether to convict Falater of first-degree murder.
</P>
<P>
   Falater said he was sleepwalking when he stabbed his wife,
Yarmila, 44 times and dragged her into the backyard pool in January
1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did Yarmila have any close family that she might of confided
in? If so, why didn't we hear from her side of the family?'' read
one of the questions, which were released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Reinstein answered that neither the court nor the
attorneys could answer the question.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact the jury asked it means it might be finding holes
in the state's case against Falater, said Michael Black, a longtime
criminal defense attorney said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's probing,'' Black said. ``They're probably trying to
find some kind of motive here or the absence of one.
</P>
<P>
   ``If something's wrong, you'd think she'd complain to an older
sister. It's indicative of a knock against the state on the motive
issue. . . . There's something they're reaching for that the state
didn't show.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Juan Martinez, the deputy Maricopa County attorney who
prosecuted the case, nor Michael Kimerer, the defense attorney,
would comment on the jury questions.
</P>
<P>
   Falater's attorneys have argued that Falater had no motive to
kill his wife of 20 years. They put on a ``nerd'' defense, saying
the mild-mannered electrical engineer was never known to raise a
hand against his high-school sweetheart, the only woman he ever
dated.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have hinted at trouble in the marriage. Martinez
said that sparks flew between the two because Yarmila was losing
interest in the couple's Mormon faith, and that she didn't want any
more children, as Scott did.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez also pointed out to the jury that Yarmila wasn't
wearing a wedding ring when she was murdered.
</P>
<P>
   But neither of the couple's children nor Yarmila's friends
testified that there were any signs of abuse or trouble in the
couple's Paradise Valley home.
</P>
<P>
   The jury got the case Wednesday at 3:30 p.m. and deliberated
until 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   It came back Thursday at 9:30 a.m., took a lunch at noon and a
quick break at 2:15 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The jury's five questions came from morning sessions and were
considered by Reinstein and attorneys on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   The question about Yarmila Falater's family members was the most
telling of the five submitted to Reinstein, according to Black,
after looking at them at the request of The Republic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these questions can be no more than jurors not able to
remember specifically what happened (in court),'' Black said.
</P>
<P>
   One question asked whether the jury is to accept as fact two
other sleepwalking cases mentioned in court.
</P>
<P>
   One involved a Canadian man named Ken Parks who was acquitted of
murder after saying he was sleepwalking when he killed his
mother-in-law. The other involved a lawyer who ran his car over two
girls while supposedly sleepwalking.
</P>
<P>
   The judge told the jurors that the court did not tell them to
assume those two stories are true.
</P>
<P>
   One question asked whether the clothes Falater put in the
Tupperware container in his car's trunk were the same ones that
were always kept there.
</P>
<P>
   The judge told the jury it must rely on individual notes and
recollections.
</P>
<P>
   The jury had more questions for Falater.
</P>
<P>
   The question asked what emergency would ever require Falater to
use a large hunting knife. Falater testified he always kept the
knife in the back of his car, along with an emergency change of
clothes.
</P>
<P>
   The question went on to ask Falater whether he stored any other
emergency tools in the back of his car.
</P>
<P>
   The defense theory is that Falater used the hunting knife to fix
a defective pool pump while sleepwalking when his wife touched him,
sending him into a violent rage.
</P>
<P>
   The judge told the jury Falater cannot be recalled to the
witness stand to answer the questions.
</P>
<P>
   Another question asked whether Falater was ever given a
lie-detector test. The judge responded that Falater was not and
that such evidence wouldn't be admissible in court anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Based on that question, Black, who has been a defense attorney
for 16 years, said the jury is trying to judge Falater's
credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``They probably made an assessment initially whether he's
believable or not, and by the nature of the question, they can't
tell,'' he said. ``And they are probably trying to figure out if
(the court) has gone the extra mile as to whether he's telling the
truth or not.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
