r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLEEPWALK-FAITH-AZR &LR;      06-25 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLEEPWALK-FAITH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIAL CASTS LIGHT ON MORMON LIFE
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD RUELAS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scott Falater's murder trial has concentrated mainly on
sleepwalking because that's what Falater says he was doing the
night he stabbed and drowned his wife.
</P>
<P>
   But it has also touched on the sometimes-secret tenets of the
Mormon Church.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors trying to present a motive for the electrical
engineer to viciously stab his beloved wife have looked frequently
to what they say was her waning interest in the Church of Jesus
Christ of Latter-day Saints.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps, she didn't want to attend temple. Perhaps it was her
refusal to have more children, as Scott wanted,'' Deputy Maricopa
County Attorney Juan Martinez said in his closing arguments to the
jury in Maricopa County Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   The jury itself has been curious about the religion, whose
practitioners live mainly in Western states.
</P>
<P>
   In questions submitted to witnesses, jurors asked about the
Mormon Temple ceremony, the garments Mormons wear under their
clothes, and whether there is pressure to keep family problems
secret.
</P>
<P>
   Marie Cornwall, a sociologist at Brigham Young University, said
the church does exert societal pressure on its members.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's comparable to any couple in any kind of conservative
congregation . . . where there's a high expectation of following
certain behavior,'' said Cornwall, a practicing Mormon who has
studied the sociological aspects of the religion for nearly two
decades.
</P>
<P>
   Mormons are expected, for example, to wear sacred undergarments,
abstain from coffee and tea and donate 10 percent of their income
to the church.
</P>
<P>
   Falater testified that he was raised a Catholic but converted a
year before he married Yarmila after two missionaries knocked on
his door.
</P>
<P>
   Yarmila converted a few months later after the two toured the
church's headquarters in Salt Lake City. She heard the church's
doctrine about eternal marriage, Scott said, and began to cry tears
of joy.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Falater, testifying in his own defense, said he and his
wife differed on some church doctrine, but they were not serious
disagreements. For instance, he said he wanted more children; his
wife didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Church literature encourages children, though the church does
not have doctrine requiring large families.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is true that I would have wanted more children . . . but I
also realized she ends up with 90 percent of the job then,''
Falater said.
</P>
<P>
   Cornwall, the BYU sociologist, said that a Mormon family with
fewer than three children would probably feel some pressure, not
from the church, but from fellow Mormons.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be some experience of social pressure that you've
stopped at two,'' Cornwall said. ``It would come from maybe other
members and come in the form of questions like, `So, do you plan to
have any more kids?' or, `When's the next one coming?' or things
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A mother's most important responsibility is to bring children
into the world and to care for and teach them,'' according to
Gospel Principles, a study guide prepared by the LDS church.
``Bearing children is one of the greatest of all blessings.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cornwall said the Falaters probably would have stopped
fielding those questions more than a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would have felt more pressure around that in their early
30s,'' Cornwall said. ``Once kids are teenagers, no one is going to
give them any pressure. There is a time clock operating there.''
</P>
<P>
   A juror wanted to ask Falater: ``Do Mormons keep their private
home lives secret even from their own?'' But the question was
rejected by Judge Ronald Reinstein.
</P>
<P>
   Cornwall said women do talk about family problems among each
other, and Yarmila Falater's best friends would have known about
any problems. ``How do you think they cope?'' Cornwall said.
``Those women are talking to each other.''
</P>
<P>
   But Martha Beck, a former BYU professor who spent a decade
talking to 300 Mormon women about gender roles, said domestic
problems are kept in the home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very close friends might hear, `We're having some problems,'
'' said Beck, who has renounced her Mormon religion. ``Often I
heard people talk about the face they show at church vs. their real
face.''
</P>
<P>
   Other jurors asked about Yarmila's not wanting to go to the
Mormon Temple in Mesa. ``Why would someone not want to go to
temple?'' one juror asked.
</P>
<P>
   Cornwall said the Mormon Temple is highly sacred and some church
members might not feel spiritually ready to attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not unusual for someone to say, `I don't want to go,' ''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Two other juror questions asked whether a wife's church activity
affects her husband's standing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would not affect his general standing if he wanted to be in
a high position,'' Beck said.
</P>
<P>
   But a wife drifting from the religious beliefs of the husband
will put a definite strain on any marriage, Cornwall said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conflict does occur when you've got two different approaches
to faith,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Mormon doctrine, a faithful couple will be united
in the afterlife for eternity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing can part us forever except our own disobedience. This
knowledge helps us work harder to have a happy, successful
marriage,'' according to the Mormon study book. ``Temple marriage
is worth any sacrifice. It is a way of obtaining eternal
blessings.''
</P>
<P>
   Beck said a husband could treat his wife's drifting from the
religion seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than other religions, it's very important to a faithful
Mormon that their spouse be faithful as well,'' Beck said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
