r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PEACEKEEPING-YUGOSLAV     06-25 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEACEKEEPING-YUGOSLAVIA-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNCERTAIN PEACE KEEPS U.S. SOLDIERS IN THRALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANON  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. MARINE CAMP MONTIETH, Yugoslavia -- Amid the tedium that
anchors a Marine's day, sentries were frisking three civilian
visitors Thursday morning when shots rang out. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Maybe a quarter mile off, maybe closer. Bursts of automatic
weapons fire. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``That's too damn close,'' shouted one Marine as his buddy
ducked behind a nest of sandbags. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Troops streamed down the hillside at this post near Cernice,
southeast of Pristina, to reinforce the checkpoint. Two helicopter
gunships soon buzzed over the pasture where the gunfire came from. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A half-hour passed. No gunmen were found, no casualties
suffered. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. troops walking the Kosovo beat as the world's police
officers so far have hardly fired their rifles. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yet the soldiers and Marines confess to a certain uneasiness
born of keeping peace between Kosovo's Serbs and ethnic Albanians
-- vengeful rivals the troops can't tell apart and who even in
civilian clothing are often armed and angry. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody here's got a grudge against somebody else,'' said
Maj. Erik Gunhus, a U.S. Army spokesman. ``And everybody's saying,
`This guy's a war criminal, that guy's a war criminal,' but we
don't have the manpower to police every situation.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And there is at least the threat of danger for the roughly 2,100
U.S. Army soldiers and 1,900 Marines holding down the American
sector of NATO's evolving peacekeeping mission in Kosovo. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last week, soldiers hustled Brig. Gen. John Craddock, commander
of U.S. forces in the Yugoslav province, out of a meeting with
Kosovo Liberation Army officers after an ethnic Albanian raised a
grenade in his hand. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday evening, Marines at a checkpoint in Zegra came
under fire from a small group of Serbs. The Americans avoided
injury in an incident that ended with two Serbs captured, two more
wounded and one dead. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no motive,'' said Col. Kenneth Glueck, commander of
the 26th Marine Expeditionary Unit. ``They could have been drunk.
... It puts our people on a high state of alert. You're out there
for a week and there's nothing and then there's shots coming at
you. You wake up a bit.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How the U.S. peacekeepers respond to their mission can differ
village by village and hour by hour. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The shootout in Zegra was clear enough. Marines say some men
were milling near a store about 150 yards from the Americans'
checkpoint. One Serb started shooting randomly, Glueck said, and
turned his fire on the Americans when he noticed them. A little
more than an hour later, the search of a few buildings was complete
and the deadly confrontation was over. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thursday brought a less clear-cut dilemma for the Marines. By
late morning, 20 Serb families fleeing vengeful ethnic Albanians
lined up in a convoy to wait for an escort to nearby Gomja Budriga
as flames swallowed their wood and brick homes. KLA soldiers
crammed in a compact car tooled up and down the main lane, popping
off their rifles in victorious spurts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Marines stood at their post about 200 yards away. They drove to
where the shooting and burning took place about 30 minutes after
the fighters left. The homes were mostly embers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to respond the best we can,'' said Capt. Robert
Riggle of Overland Park. ``If we see it, we're going to stop it. We
just can't be everywhere at once.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Albanians looted the homes of the mostly Serb
village and hauled the booty to their houses a few miles away in
Lladove. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We're taking back the things they stole from us,'' said Haziz
Haziri, his wagon overflowing with clothes, a washing machine,
radios and a freezer. ``It's right to take what is ours.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Marine Sgt. Alejandro Guzman Achacha watched the Albanians
loading up the Serbs' leftovers with a bemused grin. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They're clearing the place out,'' said the Queens, N.Y.,
native. ``As time goes on, they're going to test, test and test us
some more to see what they can get away with.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Across the road, 21-year-old Marine medic John Holmstrom of
Calumet, Mich., tended to an ethnic Albanian family whose car
windshield was bashed by a group of Serbs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Just let me put this cream on your neck, ma'am,'' he told
Shefquete Rrahmani. ``No, it won't hurt.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO is wonderful,'' said Rrahmani's daughter, Liridona. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Twenty miles away at the edge of tiny Klokot, a line of ethnic
Albanian men snaked around a storefront, waiting to claim goods
they said were stolen from them. A U.S. Army patrol unit stopped
the looting of a cache of household appliances there Wednesday, at
what had been a Serb police headquarters. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the troops tried to identify the rightful owners of
the property. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``People were taking stuff and putting it on their trucks,''
said Lt. Col. Mark Hennes, 39, of Knoxville, Tenn. ``Some of them
were taking back their own stuff, and some were stealing.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So on Thursday the U.S. soldiers forced the residents to pony up
evidence that they owned what they wanted to take. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We're asking for receipts or owners' manuals or a picture of
them with their blushing bride in front of the washing machine,''
Hennes said. ``Anything to show that they're not just looting.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the Marines' camp, Master Sgt. Mike Frankinburger, 42, of
Spring, Texas, barked orders to two of his charges. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I want a 10-foot-wide path swept for mines there and then
we'll put up a fence -- just enough to slow somebody down,'' he
said. ``You could throw a bag of grenades over there'' -- he
motioned to a cluster of domed pup tents -- ``and we could be dead
before we knew anything happened.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With that, Cpls. Jose Gutierrez and Gary May, both 21, pulled
out their green metal detector and began a fastidious walk around
the northern side of the camp. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Inside a tent a few paces away, Lt. David Everly listened to
radio traffic flooding in from patrols across 6,000 square
kilometers of Kosovo. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Random weapons firing is routine, he said. Radar tracks an
average of three mortar shells a day. Everly said the Marines have
been unable yet to tell who is firing the rounds. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys here can get kind of edgy,'' he said. ``It's only
natural.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
