<HEADLINE>
BURKETT SHARP IN VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Right-hander John Burkett endured six
atrocious starts, a five-week assignment as the Rangers' long
reliever and a 37-minute rain delay.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, his 11 1/2-week wait for that elusive first victory ended
last night when closer John Wetteland retired Oakland's Matt Stairs
for the final out of the Rangers' 5-2 triumph at The Ballpark in
Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the Rangers departed for Seattle by winning the first of
five consecutive three-game series against American League West
opponents with their second victory in as many nights against the
Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   Burkett (1-3) allowed two runs on six hits and recorded five
strikeouts during his 82-pitch, six-inning appearance that began
rather ominously.
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Tony Phillips greeted Burkett with a single and
advanced to third on a double by shortstop Miguel Tejada, and
surely the ``here we go again'' thoughts crossed the minds of many
at The Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Such thoughts would be short-lived.
</P>
<P>
   Burkett retired left fielder Ben Grieve on strikes and first
baseman Jason Giambi on a foul pop before inducing an inning-ending
ground ball from designated hitter John Jaha.
</P>
<P>
   Burkett also escaped a two-hit second inning and retired 10
consecutive batters before Tejada's sixth-inning bunt single.
Tejada would score on Jaha's two-out home run, but by then the
Rangers had scored five times against right-hander Tim Hudson
(2-1).
</P>
<P>
   Right fielder Juan Gonzalez delivered home the evening's first
run with his first-inning sacrifice fly, and designated hitter
Rafael Palmeiro followed with a two-run single.
</P>
<P>
   The support did not stop there.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Ivan Rodriguez, who entered this game with five hits and
four runs batted in during his previous 10 at-bats, collected his
second single in as many at-bats. His two-out, second-inning single
scored center fielder Roberto Kelly and shortstop Royce Clayton and
provided Burkett a five-run lead to protect.
</P>
<P>
   Burkett earned his May 18 demotion to the bullpen with five
horrendous starts that produced an 0-3 record and 13.24 earned-run
average, but the stint there did him well.
</P>
<P>
   Burkett regained lost arm strength and rediscovered success by
accumulating a 3.00 ERA in 18 innings as the Rangers' long
reliever.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
