<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DABBLING DAVEY IS DISAPPOINTED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Dave Hansen started at third and Todd
Hollandsworth was in center. Short of picking names from a hat, Los
Angeles Dodgers manager Davey Johnson continues to dabble in an
effort to find offensive consistency, using his 50th different
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no magic formula,'' recently acquired second baseman
Craig Counsell said. ``Everyone's looking for a magic formula. Guys
have to get on base and guys have to get them in. The first couple
guys have to get on for the big guys like (Gary) Sheffield and
(Raul) Mondesi and they have to drive them in.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have done neither well, which is why they're 13th in
the National League with 316 runs scored.
</P>
<P>
   In losing eight of their past 11 games, the Dodgers have scored
more than three runs three times and they're averaging 3.4 runs per
game.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's game against San Diego ended a nine-game homestand in
which the Dodgers performed abysmally on offense. Heading into the
game, the only regular to hit better than .280 on the homestand was
Sheffield, who was at .412.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Karros was tops at .280, followed by Adrian Beltre (.250),
Devon White (.217), Jose Vizcaino (.208), Eric Young (.158), Angel
Pena (.120) and Raul Mondesi (.111). ``I wish I knew (what was
wrong),'' Johnson said. ``I don't figure we can be any worse. They
have to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's latest attempt to find the nonexistent offense was
batting Hansen, who started for Beltre, second and sitting White to
get Hollandsworth's left-handed bat in the lineup. It came a day
after Young and Mondesi were given days off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beltre's kind of overswinging a little bit, so this should
kind of freshen him up,'' Johnson said. ``Devo, the same thing. I
haven't had Hollandsworth in there, and I want to get him in there
and see if I can get him locked in like he was in the spring.''
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn back on DL: San Diego right fielder Tony Gwynn admits the
worst part of chasing his 3,000th hit is answering the same
questions over and over. For another two weeks, though, he'll do
just that.
</P>
<P>
   For the second time in a month, a strained left calf sent Gwynn
to the 15-day disabled list. The Padres announced the move
(retroactive to Sunday) before Thursday's game against the Dodgers.
Gwynn, who is 18 hits shy of 3,000, is eligible to come off the
disabled list July 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've thought about this for so long and now I'm going to have
to sit and answer two more weeks of questions,'' said Gwynn, a Long
Beach Poly graduate. ``It'd be easy to sit here and be frustrated,
but I take the other approach. It could be my Achilles' (tendon)
again and I'd be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn is batting .338 in 45 games. He was originally placed on
the disabled list May 22, returned June 12 but was reinjured during
a weekend series with Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Pena's plate problems: Since taking over the top catching
duties, Pena has kept runners from stealing bases, but he's also
fallen in line with the rest of the Dodgers and can't hit a lick.
</P>
<P>
   Seven runners attempted to steal in the last eight games. Four
of them were thrown out. However, he's 3 for 25 in that span and is
hitting .190 with four RBI this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the games I'm coming in and watching the review on the
tape,'' Pena said. ``I'm in a slump. Sometimes I see it good. Maybe
I'm trying to do too much. I'm trying to hit the ball and I'm
opening too quick.''
</P>
<P>
   FYI: Reliever Doug Bochtler accepted his minor-league assignment
and reported to Triple-A Albuquerque.... Dodgers pitchers have
allowed 95 homers. Only Chicago, Colorado and Florida have given up
more in the National League.
</P>
</TEXT>
