<SLUG> BC-SHIP-LARGE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEHEMOTH SHIP `SUSAN MAERSK' DWARFS MANY THINGS IN ITS WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MIKE BARBER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TACOMA, Wash. _ If you laid Seattle's tallest building on its
side, the 943-foot tall Columbia Tower could hide in the shadow of
the behemoth that churned into the Port of Tacoma Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   At 1,138 feet long, the baby-blue, Danish-owned ``Susan Maersk''
is the world's largest container ship. And its 75,000 horspower,
12-cylinder, chartreuse diesel engine is the most powerful of its
kind in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Now halfway through her maiden voyage from Copenhagen, the ship
holds the record as the largest ever to visit a U.S. port. She
stopped in Long Beach, Wash., before reaching Tacoma.
</P>
<P>
   On the shiny, glass enclosed bridge resembling an air traffic
control tower, Capt. Per Hermansen says the vessel's size isn't a
concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``As captain, you don't think about the length of it,'' said
Hermansen, a 30-year veteran who started as a Maersk cadet.
Gradually working his way up aboard increasingly larger vessels was
good preparation, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like running a small factory,'' he said of the ship,
which sails for Japan on Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Having the latest fully integrated computer equipment helps. The
ship has 8,000 computer sensors _ including 2,000 in the engine
room alone _ that patrol everything from navigation to cargo, and a
satellite positioning computer and radar system that can detect the
tiniest craft.
</P>
<P>
   The Maersk's bridge is a captain's dream. ``This ship is one of
the first with enclosed bridge wings,'' Hermansen said from the
squeaky clean, vertigo-inducing bridge five decks above, with
heated windows and windshield wiper fluid sprayers all around.
</P>
<P>
   The Susan Maersk sat regal as a queen bee at the Port of
Tacoma's Sea-Land terminal Thursday morning, dwarfing swarms of
semi-tractor trucks and railroad cars buzzing about.
</P>
<P>
   Her immense scale seemed to shrink the Novios Mariner, a bulk
carrier unloading Australian alumina nearby _ no slouch itself at
700 feet long.
</P>
<P>
   Those who watched the ship from the port's observation tower
were forced to throw around big words to describe the big,
double-hulled ship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gargantuan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Humongous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gigantic.''
</P>
<P>
   And even ... ``titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to see if it was as impressive as I read it was.
It is,'' said Jim Warren of Seattle, as the cargo containers grew
like pyramids on the desk of the ship, stacked 17 across, seven
high, eight deep below.
</P>
<P>
   The ship is known as ``post-panamax,'' meaning it can't fit
through the Panama Canal, though it can slide down the Suez Canal.
Everything seems to have been made in a land of giants. A half-mile
of
</P>
<P>
   4-inch-wide links form a mile-long chain that ends at a 17-ton
anchor. The six-blade main propeller alone is as tall as a
three-story building.
</P>
<P>
   The ship can hold 6,600 containers, each 20 feet long and each
able to hold 78,000 Washington apples. That's two or three times
what most ships carry. It can accommodate 700 refrigerator units,
making it the biggest ``reefer'' carrier in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The Maersk is carrying fruit, wood pulp, chemicals, machinery,
computer parts, furniture and toys and other items on a rotation
that includes stops in China, Yokohama, Kobe, Singapore, Oman,
Rotterdam and Bremerhaven.
</P>
<P>
   Though bigger than the biggest aircraft carrier, the Maersk
doesn't require a navy to run it. It sails with 13 to 24 sailors,
with 22 on this journey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a floating hotel, this ship,'' said chief steward
Kai Tarp, who's in charge of feeding, storing and provisioning the
crew for three months at sea.
</P>
<P>
   Most hotel chefs would envy his stainless steel kitchen with
convection ovens and master-chef utensils, a pantry the size of a
7-Eleven and eight freezers that hold 1,600 pounds of meat alone.
</P>
<P>
   Plush accommodations are a necessity, said Tarp, 44, who has
been at sea since he was 15. ``We work 10-hour days, seven days a
week, for the three months we are at sea.''
</P>
<P>
   Each crew member has a private cabin with a private bath, all
somewhat like suites in a good hotel. There's a gym, video library
and infirmary.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Officer Marius Gardastovu runs one of the most important
and advanced sections of the ship on A deck, overseeing fuel
bunkering, ballast and the cargo operation. While the ship's
blueprints and fuel capacity is a secret, he said it only needs two
refueling stops on its 13-week voyage.
</P>
<P>
   From his perch, Gardastovu can adjust ballast, coordinating fuel
bunkers, for example, as the ship is loaded.
</P>
<P>
   The Susan Maersk, based in Hellerup, Denmark, was built at A.P.
Moller Group's Odense Shipyard in Denmark in 1997, and named for
Moller's aunt.
</P>
<P>
   Government and shipping officials say the Susan Maersk is at the
vanguard of future shipping, and port and shipping lines are
working together to ready themselves, said Port of Tacoma spokesman
Rod Koon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sign of the challenges that face both the ports of
Seattle and Tacoma,'' Koon said. The two ports realize the region
has to improve rail and truck infrastructures that work
symbiotically with ships, he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Tacoma port, the Sea Land terminal is readying cranes for
larger ships.
</P>
<P>
   When it arrived Thursday, the vessel's draft _ the depth of
water a ship needs in order to float, especially when loaded _ was
30 feet. When it leaves Tacoma around noon Friday, it will be at 40
feet in the 48 foot channel. The ship is expected to pass Seattle
two or three hours later.
</P>
<P>
   Expect to see more of her ilk hereabouts in the 21st century,
said Maersk spokesman Tom Boyd, whose company has called at the
Port of Tacoma since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   ``Economies of scale is the key in liner shipping,'' he said.
``We've got to put through more volumes to make it more
profitable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
