<HEADER>
A8987 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-REDS-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      06-25 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-REDS-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Maybe it was fatigue, or _ as hard as it may be to believe _ maybe
it was actually Ron Villone.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps it was a combination of the two. Regardless, there
wasn't nearly enough of what the Astros needed most in a 3-0 loss
to the Cincinnati Reds on Thursday at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you're Mike Tyson or Smokin' Joe Frazier in their prime,
one hit isn't going to win many fights. Consequently, the Astros
were floored in Round 1 of this midseason showdown between the top
two teams in the National League Central Division.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros saw their division lead trimmed to three games as
they were shut out for the first time since St. Louis' Matt Morris
blanked them Sept. 22, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Villone, who took a no-hitter to the seventh inning, and
reliever Danny Graves combined to hold the Astros to one hit _
their lowest hit total since Kerry Wood of the Chicago Cubs one-hit
them in his 20-strikeout gem May 6, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to give Villone credit,'' Astros third baseman Tim
Bogar said. ``He pitched well, but we swung the bats like .''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the Astros, that has the scent of a trend. The
team that was leading the NL in hitting a month ago has steadily
dropped to 10th in the league. The Astros are hitting .222 in their
last 10 games (4-6).
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't swing the bats very well, and we haven't for the
past couple of weeks,'' Astros interim manager Matt Galante said.
``It's been frustrating to watch a good-hitting team go through
this, but it happens.''
</P>
<P>
   The odds might increase when you're working on dead legs. Both
teams arrived in Houston in the wee hours of the morning and no
doubt felt the effects. ``My legs felt like they weighed about 100
pounds,'' Astros right fielder Derek Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   Villone's performance trumped a strong outing by the Astros'
Mike Hampton, who allowed three runs (two earned) on four hits in
seven-plus innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was happy with my stuff but not with the outcome,'' Hampton
said. ``This is a big series. The Reds have a good team, and we're
going to have to battle better than this to beat them or else we're
going to find ourselves tied (for first place in the NL Central)
before we get out of this series. This is certainly not a time to
start pressing, but we do need to start winning some games.''
</P>
<P>
   That hasn't been a problem for the Reds, who have won four in a
row and six of their last eight. They improved their NL-best road
record to 23-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has got to give them a boost,'' Bogar said of the Reds'
victory. ``But they have to remember it's June. They're playing hot
baseball right now and building confidence, but it's a long
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the limited scoring, Thursday's game didn't exactly take
on the identity of a pitchers' duel. The two pitching staffs
combined for nine walks and two hit batsmen. The Astros committed a
pair of errors, one of which figured in the scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Astros manager Larry Dierker, who watched the first three
innings from general manager Gerry Hunsicker's box, was wise not to
endure this one in its entirety. It wasn't exactly a masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were two teams that got in late and didn't really come up
with anything,'' Astros first baseman Jeff Bagwell said. ``We
combined for six hits; not to take anything away from the pitchers,
but that's ridiculous. You just don't expect that.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Thursday, the Astros and Indians were the only teams in
the majors that had not been shut out. Cleveland was blanked by
Toronto on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds took a 1-0 lead in the fifth when Mike Cameron tripled
off the short fence in front of the Coca-Cola Corner in right field
and scored on Aaron Boone's double to left.
</P>
<P>
   Bell crashed into the wall and nearly made the catch on
Cameron's drive. ``I was on it,'' he said. ``It hit my glove and
knocked it (the glove) over the gate.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Eusebio's seventh-inning single off Villone was the Astros'
only hit. Nothing in Villone's past indicated he had what he took
to do what he did against the NL's best-hitting team against
lefthanded pitching. This was only the fourth start of his career
after 162 consecutive relief appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Before Thursday, Villone had never pitched more than five
innings in a game, and he was 0-2 with a 10.80 ERA in his previous
three starts.
</P>
<P>
   When the first two Reds reached to start the eighth, Galante
lifted Hampton in favor of Scott Elarton.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lewis and Pokey Reese scored, although Elarton appeared to
have a chance to start his outing with a double play. Bagwell
charged Jeffrey Hammonds' popped-up bunt but let it drop so he
could attempt a double play. But shortstop Ricky Gutierrez couldn't
handle Bagwell's throw, and the Reds had the bases loaded with no
out.
</P>
<P>
   Reese scored on Hal Morris' fielder's-choice grounder. Barry
Larkin's broken-bat single pushed the Reds' lead to three runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baggy made the right play,'' Galante said. ``We had a double
play; we just didn't execute it very well. We turned what we
thought was a double play into disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell blamed himself for not making a better throw to second
base.
</P>
<P>
   In the grand scheme of things, all that mattered was that the
Astros couldn't handle Villone or Graves, who earned his 10th save.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
