<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 01:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8989 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-25 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
LARRY Dierker lumbered onto the Astrodome floor through the tunnel
that sits exactly opposite the one through which he was whisked
away only 11 days before.
</P>
<P>
   It was nothing if not an appropriate picture.
</P>
<P>
   Most everything about this night was on the other end of the
spectrum _ the total opposite of that heart-sinking feeling that
left Dierker's team and Dierker's town wondering if he was going to
be all right.
</P>
<P>
   This was Dierker stepping through the home-plate tunnel and onto
the turf as if it was all no big deal.
</P>
<P>
   He laughed for a while with the guys holding the microphones and
notepads. He winked at a few of the early-arriving fans who were
hanging over the dugouts. He stepped behind the batting cage and
talked with the fellas before the game.
</P>
<P>
   Then, he took an elevator up to Gerry Hunsicker's suite to
watch. Just watch.
</P>
<P>
   But on June 13, that was Dierker lying in an ambulance that sped
through the center-field tunnel. His wife sat in the front seat,
and thousands of stunned fans quietly filed out of the Dome.
</P>
<P>
   This was a surprise. That was a shock.
</P>
<P>
   This was Dierker wearing a garish Hawaiian shirt and his
favorite Panama Jack hat, looking like a cross between Don Ho and
Tito Puente, and filling the place with exactly that kind of hop
and good vibe.
</P>
<P>
   But that was Dierker lying on the floor of the Astros' dugout
with his shirt torn open, trainers and doctors scurrying about and
his players standing around him with looks of disbelief on their
faces.
</P>
<P>
   This was grand, as Dierker's return to the Astrodome for
Thursday's series opener against the Cincinnati Reds came much
earlier than anyone expected.
</P>
<P>
   But that was something called a grand mal seizure, a medical
term with which all of Houston has become much more familiar. That
was a potentially fatal condition that led to Dierker undergoing
five hours of brain surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Dierker returned to the Astrodome, all right _ emphasis on
all right.
</P>
<P>
   He showed everyone that he's going to be fine. He showed it with
those vibrant, Hawaiian colors and that casual, quippy demeanor
that might have been the best evidence yet that this is indeed the
same old Dierk.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Dierker met with his team in the clubhouse. He
didn't toss around any inspiring words. He didn't ask any ``win one
for me'' questions. He asked something totally different, something
totally Dierker.
</P>
<P>
   Wanna see my scar?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Dierk,'' Astros outfielder Derek Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   Before the first pitch, when asked how he would handle a tight,
emotional game, Dierker ho-hummed over it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was told to come here and be like a fan and not like a
manager,'' Dierker said. ``So I guess I'll leave about the third
inning.''
</P>
<P>
   And in fact, after the third was indeed when Dierker left, but
only because doctors, management and most significantly Judy
Dierker did not want to press their luck.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker's leaving proved to be quite the smart move, too.
</P>
<P>
   As healthy as Dierker's brain clearly is, the Astros' 3-0 loss
to the second-place Reds surely would have made his heart go
pitter-patter.
</P>
<P>
   Reds starter Ron Villone took a no-hitter into the seventh
inning. The Astros wasted the few opportunities they did have. And
a blundering, bumbling eighth inning sealed the Astros' fate on
this night.
</P>
<P>
   But on the other side of the outcome was the game's most popular
fan.
</P>
<P>
   When Dierker was shown on the Dome's giant video screen watching
from Hunsicker's suite, the crowd rose, cheered and called out his
name. Dierker also stood and waved, then punched the air a couple
of times as if to say, ``Go get 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Astros didn't go get anything but a loss. They had no
chance in this one, and Hunsicker's pre-game joke about Dierker
joining him in the suite proved prophetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can sit up there with me and help me second-guess Matt
(Galante) and complain about all the inadequacies of the players,''
Hunsicker said. ``He'll understand what it's like from where I
sit.''
</P>
<P>
   This one wasn't pretty from any angle. But as ugly as it was,
Dierker took all those sinking feelings from 11 days earlier and
turned them completely around.
</P>
<P>
   As important as it is that the Astros turn around their recent
trend of losing to good teams, Dierker probably would have joked
about his presence ``inspiring'' his team to its first shutout loss
since late last season.
</P>
<P>
   He was his old self, even if his team was not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
