<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 01:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8998 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARINERS-STADIUM-SPI &LR;      06-25 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARINERS-STADIUM-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STADIUM DISTRICT TO MARINERS: NO TO REQUEST ON COST OVERRUNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALAN SNEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Seattle Mariners' request for help in paying $100
million in Safeco Field cost overruns was met Thursday with a stern
reply: No way.
</P>
<P>
   The state panel overseeing construction of the $517 million
ballpark told the Mariners baseball team it is not willing to have
a mediator help determine who should pay cost overruns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not moving on this issue. As far as I'm concerned,
there's no way we're going to ask for more money'' from King
County, said Ron Judd, a member of the Public Facilities District
board.
</P>
<P>
   The ballclub's owners asked this week that $60 million from
excess ballpark tax surpluses be used to help offset the estimated
$100 million in cost overruns.
</P>
<P>
   Now it appears neither side is willing to budge.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no way to compromise,'' said Gerry Johnson, the PFD's
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Added PFD board member Bob Wallace: ``Normally in mediation you
have money involved, and the mediator beats up both sides and goes
back and forth until there is an agreement. But this is not a
split-the-baby kind of issue. It's a `what-does-the-law-say' issue.
</P>
<P>
   The PFD board's decision was unanimous after an hour-long,
closed-door session called to discuss a ``threat of litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They made a correct, proper and courageous decision,'' said
Chris Van Dyk, co-founder of Citizens for More Important Things, an
anti-stadium tax group.
</P>
<P>
   County Executive Ron Sims agreed, saying ``there is no need to
mediate something (the M's) contract does not entitle them to
have.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners, in a written statement, were disappointmented and
surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mediation is used routinely in this country to resolve complex
legal and business disputes. We had sought mediation so the
Mariners and the PFD could, with the assistance of a neutral third
party, attempt to resolve our conflicting views of the legislation,
our contract and other issues,'' the club said.
</P>
<P>
   The team's options include asking a court to compel the PFD to
join in mediation, although the contractual agreement between the
team and the district does not require binding mediation or
arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   The team also could sue over the money it-
</P>
<P>
   self.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners have not said what their plans are, and Thursday
would say nothing more than the written statement.
</P>
<P>
   But on Tuesday, Nintendo of America Inc. Chairman Howard Lincoln
hinted that the team wouldn't back down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize there's a lot of people who don't agree with us,''
Lincoln said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But even baseball owners are entitled to their day in court.''
Nintendon of America is the team's majority owner.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the $417 million construction budget set in July
1997, the Mariners agreed to pay $45 million while the public share
would be $372 million.
</P>
<P>
   The public funds would come from taxes on restaurant meals,
rental cars and ballpark admissions; a sales tax credit; and some
state lottery sales.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mariners say a study by an investment banker the team
declines to identify showed higher-than-projected tax revenues
could allow the state to issue bonds to generate another $60
million to help cover the $100 million in cost overruns.
</P>
<P>
   The team would agree to pay the other $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Ellis and Lincoln interpreted language in the 1995
state stadium financing law and the 1997 development agreement
between the team and the PFD to say the dis-
</P>
<P>
   trict is obliged to ask the county to float bonds when there is
a surplus of ballpark-related tax revenues.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday, PFD executive Director Ken Johnsen cited the same
documents in an analysis that argues the team is required to pay
all costs in addition to $417 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public's contribution to the project was capped at $372
million at the time that the PFD and the Mariners agreed on a
construction budget and King County issued the requisite amount of
bonds to support construction,'' Johnsen wrote in a memo to the PFD
board.
</P>
<P>
   He said state legislation requires extra tax revenues go for
early debt retirement and prohibits using public money for ``cost
overruns on initial construction.''
</P>
<P>
   He also cited King County ordinances authorizing the bonds that
forbids the refinancing requested by the Mariners and said it would
be an unconstitutional gift of public funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard to imagine how agreements that describe the
Mariners' responsibility for all `cost overruns' or `supplemental
funds' could be more clear,'' Johnsen wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Sims said the Mariners want windfall revenue that should be used
to retire the bonds early.
</P>
<P>
   ``So the question is, where will the benefits of our booming
economy go _ to the taxpayers or the Mariners?'' Sims asked.
</P>
<P>
   Sims' office received about 150 telephone calls and e-mail
messages about the dispute Wednesday and Thursday _ all of them
anti-Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   Van Dyk said the Mariners' position relies on legal language
taken out of context.
</P>
<P>
   He said the team cited a reference that first appeared in a
state Supreme Court brief filed by the PFD and King County in 1997
in response to an appeal by the group, Citizens for More Important
Things.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, the team is trying to use information furnished by
the stadium district in an unrelated case against the PFD in the
current dispute, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolutely the sleaziest trick in the business,'' Van
Dyke said. ``Any company that acted so cavalierly about their
public image and so discounted the value of good will and was in a
retail entertainment business, I would sell short their stock
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Hattori, the county's financial adviser on the ballpark
bonds, recalled that Mariners' attorneys and finan-
</P>
<P>
   cial consultants attended all County Council meetings on the
stadium bonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``At no time during any of those discussions did they ever raise
the idea that the county would be required to issue additional
bonds,'' Hattori said.
</P>
<P>
   The PFD session drew two speakers. Kit Hawkins, a lobbyist for
the 4,000-member Washington Restaurant Association, said the
ballpark benefits relatively few restaurants and some owners
already regret supporting the stadium financing deal.
</P>
<P>
   And Vincent Koskela, a representative from Taxpayers on Strike,
said he was disgusted with the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   This report includes information from The Associated Press.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
