u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-ORIOLES-BO     06-25 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX DO THE BASICS 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-ORIOLES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ No Pedro sighting in three nights. No Nomar for the
rubber game. No Tom Gordon for the forseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   No problem, it seems, for these Red Sox, a Whitman's sampler of
talent that may not offer the most appealing selection at first
glance, but somehow winds up being more satisfying than the pricier
selections in the display case.
</P>
<P>
   That includes the Baltimore Orioles, who were the hottest team
in baseball until the Sox arrived here to take two out of three,
including Thursday &UR;  &LR; night's 2-1 win over Orioles ace Mike Mussina
that was missing an injured Garciaparra but little else.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played good, they pitched good,'' said outfielder Darren
Lewis of the Orioles, who were winners of 11 of 12 after coming
from behind to beat the Sox in the opener of this three-game set,
but then scored one run in the last two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it seems that right now we're finding a way to get it
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Those ways Thursday night were as varied as a second-inning home
run by Troy O'Leary, his third home run in three starts and 16th of
the season; seven innings of one-run pitching by Mark Portugal, the
reluctant retiree who gave up a home run to Albert Belle and no
more; a two-out single in the fifth by Garciaparra's stand-in, Lou
Merloni, who scored the winning run, and a huge hit and
highlight-reel catch by Lewis, who tripled home Merloni, then
preserved the win with a full-sprint grab of Will Clark's line
drive that was still attempting to crawl out of the webbing of
Lewis's glove when he banged into the right-field corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm telling you, that was some play, a game-breaker,'' said
manager Jimy Williams, who at times seems to throw his lineup into
a Vegematic but comes up with the ideal blend more often than not.
``That kind of play, that was at least a double, maybe a triple.
</P>
<P>
   ``He `coned' it, then hit the wall, but maintained possession.
That was some kind of catch. That kind of play, in a 2-1 game in
the ninth, is magnified, but rightfully so.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Wakefield, whose signature pitch has been the brass knuckler
in his new role as closer, already had one out in the ninth when
Clark, who briefly entertained the idea of signing with the Sox
this winter, launched a drive that was curling toward the foul line
almost as soon as it left his bat.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal, who was already in the clubhouse after giving way to
Rheal Cormier to start the eighth, was watching on television as
Lewis gave chase.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way that ball was hit and breaking away from him, I didn't
think he had a chance,'' Portugal said. ``But he got a phenomenal
jump and whenever he gets a ball in his sights, I think he's going
to catch it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis didn't have the luxury of entertaining any doubts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing right field, you don't have the luxury of seeing the
ball go into the hitting zone,'' said Lewis, a center fielder by
trade, a right fielder by commitment. ``It was hit so hard, I was
running full speed, but I tried to run at an angle along the fence
instead of straight at the fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I've always done. I don't know if you can teach
that. It's instinct. I didn't know how I was going to get there,
but I tried to put it in another gear, kept gaining speed on it,
and was able to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   The last step before ball struck leather had a little
Baryshnikov hop to it, except ballet dancers never have to run into
a wall upon touching down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball kind of hit the heel of my glove,'' Lewis said.
``Fortunately, I held onto it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox were looking for anything to grab onto early against
Mussina, who was bidding to join Pedro Martinez as the only
pitchers in the American League with double-digit wins. Mussina,
who had allowed two runs or fewer in his last three starts, all
wins, struck out the side in the first on 11 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   He finished with 10 K's, catching leadoff man Jose Offerman
looking three times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mussina's always on his game,'' Portugal said. ``He's got
nasty stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   But O'Leary launched the first pitch he saw into the left-field
seats for his seventh home run this month, and the Sox pushed
across the winner when Merloni lined a single to left and Lewis
went the other way for his triple, his second in two nights, one as
leadoff man, one as No. 9 hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just got to continue to go out there and do my work,'' Lewis
said. ``Keep fighting and scrapping. You're not always going to
have success on a day-to-day basis, but you can't give in.''
</P>
<P>
   Three times Thursday &UR;  &LR; night, Portugal had two men on base but
never gave in. Except for Belle's 15th home run in the second, he
neutralized a team that began the night hitting .315 for the month
and 11 days earlier had scored 22 runs in one night against
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   After winning for the first time in seven starts, Portugal said
it was enough to make a man happy he didn't hang it up before his
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this team's going places,'' Portugal said. ``We came
in here against the hottest team in baseball and won the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our defense is as good as anybody's. We didn't have Nomar, and
we didn't miss a beat. Anybody Jimy puts in the lineup, it's like
they want that to be their day to shine.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Sons of Jimy Williams, winners of eight of their last
11, that shine shows no signs of wearing off.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
