<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 01:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9002 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-EMBASSY-BOMBING-     06-25 0433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-EMBASSY-BOMBING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE BELGRADE BOMBING MYSTERY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seven weeks after NATO bombs hit the Chinese Embassy in
Belgrade, Yugoslavia, Congress and the American people have yet to
receive a full explanation of the mistaken attack. The absence of
information only compounds the original error and fuels speculation
that the bombing was deliberate. The White House should insist that
the various agencies involved, including the Pentagon, which has
just announced its own review, pull together everything they know
and make a public presentation as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Lethal mistakes are sometimes made in combat, and this appears
to be such a case. But a detailed reconstruction of the targeting
work is the only way the administration can eliminate doubts in
Washington and Beijing. Confidential administration briefings given
to China and to Congress have been frustratingly incomplete.
Important questions remain unanswered about how the embassy
building was misidentified and why multiple target reviews did not
pick up the error. Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., and Rep. Porter
Goss, R-Fla., chairmen of the Senate and House Intelligence
committees, are right to demand a fuller accounting.
</P>
<P>
   Secrecy does not seem to be an overriding issue. The bombing
apparently grew out of mundane mistakes, like outdated maps,
transposed street addresses and breakdowns in the bureaucratic
communications. The multiple errors were made by more than one
government department.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the bombing, NATO political leaders were looking
for additional military targets, and the CIA had been called in to
suggest appropriate locations. The CIA's recommendations were then
reviewed by the Joint Chiefs of Staff at the Pentagon and by
American military commanders in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   A report by the CIA's inspector general has found that an agency
analyst familiar with downtown Belgrade ``persistently'' questioned
whether the correct location of the intended target _ a Yugoslav
arms agency _ had been selected. Yet his repeated warnings were
somehow overlooked. The Pentagon only added to the confusion by
suggesting that the analyst thought that the building selected,
though not the arms agency headquarters, may still have been a
legitimate target. In addition to the CIA inquiry, finding answers
will require an unsparing Pentagon investigation as well.
</P>
<P>
   The American people have a right to know what went wrong in this
embarrassing episode and to have credible assurances that the same
mistakes are not likely to happen again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-99 0130EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990625.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 01:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9004 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-US-NIGERIA-BOS &LR;      06-25 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-US-NIGERIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAMM SPARKS US ONSLAUGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Just for drama, they spotted their guests a goal on
their first shot. Can't have bored viewers channel-surfing 10
minutes into a match, after all.
</P>
<P>
   Then the US women's soccer team showed the planet once again why
it is odds-on to reclaim the World Cup, scoring six unanswered
goals on bewildered Nigeria by halftime and going on to an absurdly
easy 7-1 triumph Thursday &UR;  &LR; night before a capacity crowd of 65,080
at Soldier Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not the way we want to start a game,'' mused US coach Tony
DiCicco, after his squad calmly turned a shocker into a laugher
with three goals in four minutes. ``But there's no panic in this
team.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory, their second in two matches, all but assured the
Americans a place in the quarterfinals and the right to defend
their Olympic title next summer in Sydney. Unless they are utterly
routed by North Korea in Foxborough, Mass., Sunday night and
Nigeria rebounds to crush winless Denmark, the home folks are
through cleanly.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Americans expected otherwise. But when the
exuberant Super Falcons stormed into their end and got a goal from
Nkiru Okosieme 73 seconds after the opening whistle, the US got a
wakeup call that felt like a slap in the face.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a blessing in disguise for us,'' said forward Tiffeny
Milbrett, who ended up with a pair of goals. ``It really made us
get angry, really made us alert right away.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans, who had seven players on the field with more than
100 international appearances, quickly settled in and began to
dominate play. By the 23d minute they'd gone up, 3-1, and were
headed for a goalfest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't worried,'' said keeper Briana Scurry, who needed to
make only two saves for the rest of the evening. ``We were getting
at 'em and we had an entire game to play. We came back with a
vengeance.''
</P>
<P>
   As usual, it was Mia Hamm who brought her teammates back,
setting up the first goal and scoring the second less than a minute
later. The Nigerians didn't need a program to identify the world's
best player. They had been whacking, flattening, and chopping her
down from behind from the moment play began. ``We did our best to
track her down,'' shrugged Nigerian coach Ismaila Mabo. ``But,
unfortunately, she was not tracked down.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamm kept rising, kept running, kept creating. And in the 19th
minute she drew the US even with a deft free kick that was
deflected into the far upper corner of the net. Though Michelle
Akers originally was credited with the goal after sliding into the
ball, a replay indicated defending midfielder Ifeanyichukwu
Chiejene had knocked it in for an own goal.
</P>
<P>
   All the Americans cared was that there was a 1 on the
scoreboard. And almost immediately it was a 2, with a wide-open
Hamm taking a feed from Kristine Lilly and blasting it over keeper
Ann Chiejine's upstretched hand. Then Cindy Parlow set up Milbrett
in close for a third goal in the 23d minute, and the rout was on.
``We started playing and we started finishing goals,'' said Lilly.
``And it just snowballed from there.''
</P>
<P>
   That was how the US had envisioned the match evolving. The
Nigerians would be so intent on attacking that they'd be vulnerable
in their own end. ``Field day for our forwards,'' Scurry had
predicted _ and so it was, as the breathless Nigerians stood agape
while their white-jerseyed hosts sliced them up.
</P>
<P>
   In the 32d minute, Hamm swung a free kick toward Lilly, who
headed it in from 3 yards out. In the 39th came Akers again,
putting away a feed from Julie Foudy with a running header. And in
the 42d, a doubleheader for punctuation _ Brandi Chastain to
Parlow. At intermission the Americans had taken seven shots on goal
and scored on six.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time since Sweden scored that many on Japan in
an 8-0 blitz in 1991 that a team had managed half a dozen in a Cup
half. If the Yanks had wanted, they could have gone for a dozen,
but they'd long since made their point.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost by one goal to seven but I have no regrets
whatsoever,'' said Mabo, whose side can still advance by beating
the winless Danes in Washington Sunday. ``I know I lost to a better
side, a side that has been together since before women's football
was introduced in Nigeria.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
