u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      06-25 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
END OF KINGDOME ERA EVOKES SURPRISINGLY GOOD MEMORIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ So the bad marriage ends.
</P>
<P>
   After 23 years, major league baseball and the Kingdome are
divorcing.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday's dissolution shouldn't be considered the sum total
of the experience.
</P>
<P>
   As many of us know, bad marriages can still produce great kids
and wonderful memories. Unfortunately, it is often the most obvious
and superficial things that stick in the memory.
</P>
<P>
   Ever take adult friends to visit your childhood home? While you
bore them with the homestead's personal wonders, all they can think
of is Betty Davis' trademark line: ``What a dump!''
</P>
<P>
   To them, well, maybe. That's not the point. They didn't live
there. They can't know. So, hey, shut up already.
</P>
<P>
   That's how it is for me when out-of-town sportswriters trash the
concrete blister. Sure, the Kingdome is uglier than a federal tax
penalty. And even if it wasn't, it remains an indoor park. Since so
much of baseball's appeal is sensory, the deprivation-tank quality
suffocates the sporting dilettantes.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's OK if I insult the joint. It's not OK if it's
insulted by someone who didn't grow up in the shed, even if the
insult is accurate.
</P>
<P>
   As we all know, if there were no Kingdome, there would have been
no Mariners, no Seahawks, no Final Fours, no motocross, etc. The
problem with that point is it's an expression of functional
rationality about an experience that is fundamentally irrational _
sports fandom.
</P>
<P>
   Logic often has no place in our sporting tastes. So the utility,
economy and history of the building means to many fans as much as,
say, integrity to a Mariners owner.
</P>
<P>
   Say the word multi-purpose, and my first thought is a big,
faceless schoolroom. That was the Kingdome: OK for everything,
special for nothing.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of specialness wasn't helped by the fact that the
Mariners/Kingdome marriage seemed to be one long, unending gripe.
</P>
<P>
   From 1977's opening month, when Mariners executives claimed that
the park's dimensions were different than they were led to believe,
the relationship has been acrimonious and often adversarial.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, the club, then owned mostly by local businessmen,
actually filed suit against King County over allegedly broken
promises about the building. Poor lighting, schedule conflicts,
lack of office space _ hey, the Mariners even complained about the
ushers' uniforms _ put the franchise borne of a lawsuit back in
court.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 19 years later, the franchise, again owned by local
businessmen, is about to take King County back to court (remarkable
how the two carpetbagging, out-of-state owners, George Argyros and
Jeff Smulyan, never sued the taxpayers).
</P>
<P>
   By the time that suit is resolved, the Kingdome will be a
dustball. Imagine the irony for the King County Council _ it
believed a new ballpark and the Kingdome's murder would end its
misery as landlord for an entertainment business. Then it gets sued
from the grave.
</P>
<P>
   Still, all the bad manners, holiday fights, money disputes and
other familiar familial dysfunctions cannot obscure one startling,
if little appreciated, fact: Not only did baseball live in the
Kingdome, it thrived.
</P>
<P>
   Argyros once described Seattle baseball as ``pouring money down
a rathole.'' Smulyan once said, ``Seattle could draw 4 million and
it still wouldn't work.'' Well, both of those gentlemen profited
handsomely, upon sale, from their Seattle baseball experience, as
will the current owners.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of an industry hell-bent on self-destruction, Seattle
owners and players made it work and made big money. Fans, after a
17-year delay, finally were rewarded with a successful team rich in
marquee figures and destined for a place in history.
</P>
<P>
   Contradicting the dire forecasts of absolutely every single
person in baseball and nearly every local pundit, baseball fans
readily abandoned the heralded Seattle summers once they were given
a good reason to come indoors.
</P>
<P>
   The reason became obvious in September 1995 _ a magnificent run
to glory that forever fires the sports imagination and explains how
the game always rises above its contemptuous business
contentiousness.
</P>
<P>
   The emotional crescendo was reached late in the evening of Oct.
8.
</P>
<P>
   Having been privileged to bear witness to multiple Olympics,
Super Bowls, World Series and NBA Finals, plus many less heralded
but more rewarding events, the most compelling sports moment of my
scribing days came when Ken Griffey Jr. won a 270-foot race that
wiped out not only the New York Yankees but 19 years of baseball
agony.
</P>
<P>
   In the 11th inning of the finale in a deadlocked five-game
series already flush with sprawling drama against the most
legendary team in sports, Griffey's desperate sprint from first
base on Edgar Martinez's double still makes for aspirin-sized
goosebumps whenever my mind drifts into slow-motion replay.
</P>
<P>
   Jeez, I'm misting up, just writing this.
</P>
<P>
   Such was the exultation that the home field of the greatest
non-athletic advantage in American sports nearly imploded, years
before its time. At that moment, a million baseball fans would have
paid a million bucks each to be at the bottom of that delirious
home-plate pig-pile.
</P>
<P>
   If you weren't at the yard, well, you just can't know.
Fortunately, it was merely the best of many splendid baseball
moments experienced by a generation of fans in a place allegedly
unfit for the game.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball in the Kingdome wasn't pretty, wasn't romantic, wasn't
easy on player knees or pitchers' ERAs. For the longest time,
thrills didn't come often or cheaply. Those who weren't a
considerable part of the Seattle generation that grew up there will
assume the marriage didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   Let them think what they want. It worked, even thrived. They
can't know what they didn't live.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
