</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN ANTONIO'S LEGACY RESTS ON WHAT HAPPENS NEXT YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ We have seen enough, really. The Spurs are on the
verge.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence has been quite convincing. They have proved that
they are head and shoulders above the rest of the NBA this season.
Literally.
</P>
<P>
   That is why there will be no skepticism when the Spurs win their
first-ever NBA championship, which could come as early as Friday
night, even though the relentless Knicks are hell-bent on
preventing a San Antonio celebration on the hallowed hardwood at
Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   But no team has ever come back from 3-1 in the Finals. Not once.
Never. So see you later Latrell Sprewell and Larry Johnson. It's
been good to know you.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they bring that trophy in (Friday), guys are just going
to be looking at it and want hold it. That's why we feel we have
one more 48-minute game, let's go out there and get it done,''
Spurs guard Mario Elie said Thursday, not afraid to suggest that
the Spurs intend to put the Knicks away as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Tim Duncan, who is a lock for Finals MVP, and David
Robinson all but sealed the Spurs' fate in Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   All those rebounds. All that scoring. Duncan kissed the glass so
often he should crop up in Blistex ads sometime soon.
</P>
<P>
   Either that or they're going to start carving his plaque for
Springfield, Mass., because of the way Duncan can handle the ball,
his emotions and the moment.
</P>
<P>
   But is this the start of something _ if you'll pardon the
expression _ big and bigger for the Spurs?
</P>
<P>
   Or is this a one-time thing, which seems just as likely,
considering the questions surrounding the Spurs' future in San
Antonio and Duncan's future with the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens in South Texas, when the Spurs become the NBA's
newest title winners, they'll have a ways to go before they can
truly claim to be heirs apparent to the throne _ Sir Air's throne,
that is.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan is gone, and the Bulls are just a memory, but
what a blazing image they have left with us.
</P>
<P>
   It is one thing to win a title. Seven NBA franchises have won a
single title. Those are the Bucks, Blazers, Rochester
Royals/Sacramento Kings, St. Louis/Atlanta Hawks, Sonics, the
Washington Bullets and the defunct Baltimore Bullets.
</P>
<P>
   But all of those single-title winners earned their championships
before the 1979-80 season.
</P>
<P>
   Starting with that season, NBA championships belonged
exclusively to the Celtics and Lakers, the Bad Boys in Detroit and
then the Bulls. Houston, with Hakeem Olajuwon, won the two NBA
titles up for grabs in 1993 and '94 when Jordan was retired or
otherwise distracted by baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, the standard that's been set over the past two
decades has been all about consistency, about establishing a
dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of longevity and tenacity is not lost on anyone,
especially the fellas who have first-hand knowledge of what kind of
championship legacy Jordan and the Bulls (and all those other
dynasties) have left lingering.
</P>
<P>
   It is really tough to be ga-ga over a single title run in a
nutball 50-game, lockout-shortened season when Jordan and Co. won
those six titles in two back-to-back campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   It is no longer sufficient just to win titles. It is far better
to set a mandate for what it takes to be unbeata-Bull.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Kerr may be heading to another ring with San Antonio right
now, but even this former Bull said he could not pick the Spurs to
beat his former team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't bet against Michael. No one ever beat him So
because of that, I would say it would be an interesting matchup,''
Kerr said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bulls would have had to deal with Tim and David, and for
us, we'd have to deal with Michael and Scottie (Pippen). Mario Elie
would have to guard Michael. I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Will Perdue, another Bulls alum, said he, Kerr and Elie have
shown the rest of the Spurs their championship rings. The Spurs
have had a healthy curiosity about what it would be like.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the Spurs' focus on breaking through to that elite
class, Perdue said he understands the atmosphere in which the Spurs
are ascending to their first title.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe people will say its diminished this year because this is
an abbreviated season. They'll say we only played 50 games, and in
the same breath, they're going to say this is the first season that
Michael had retired. So, I think in order to establish ourselves,
we need to go ahead and win next year,'' Perdue said.
</P>
<P>
   There is little doubt that the Spurs have done themselves proud.
When they clinch the title, it will be validation for a franchise
that has never in its combined 26-year ABA-NBA history even played
in the Finals, let alone won one.
</P>
<P>
   But then the trick is to keep it rolling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe (in) what we've done and how we've gotten here.
Winning one will instill a confidence in this team that we can do
it,'' Perdue said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, I think this team has had for the longest time the
individuals to do it, but for one reason or another there's been
something that's prevented it from doing so. But once you win one,
that kind of eases the tension a little bit. And once you realize
you can win one, it's not that the second one's easier, but you
know your mental approach increases.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, even when the Spurs are holding the trophy,
we'll keep our eyes open for challengers, since the post-Jordan NBA
is still working out its new world order.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
