<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-NOTEBOOK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANKIE RODRIGUEZ ADAPTS TO RELIEF ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ When Frankie Rodriguez pitched for the Minnesota
Twins, he was never certain of his role. He would have some success
starting, then struggle and be shifted to relief. It was
frustrating, he said, a mental grind.
</P>
<P>
   So when Rodriguez was shifted to the Mariners' bullpen this
week, it seemed like a similar scenario. He'd had two solid starts,
then fallen apart Sunday in Cleveland. It was back to the bullpen,
and even Rodriguez wondered how he'd react.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was impressed with myself,'' Rodriguez said. ``I was
wondering, OK, after this bad outing, what's going to happen? Then
I just said: `You know what? Why? You were told what you were going
to do when you first got here.' That made it a lot easier to
handle, because I knew what was expected.''
</P>
<P>
   When Rodriguez was claimed off waivers at the end of May,
manager Lou Piniella told him he was going to middle relief. Now
that he's back in that role, it's no big deal. ``Anything I can do
to contribute,'' Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   If he pitches the way he did Wednesday, earning a three-inning
save in relief of John Halama, he'll contribute plenty. Piniella
thinks Rodriguez can fill the role intended for veteran Mark
Leiter, who is out for the year with a torn rotator cuff.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter was acquired to join Jose Paniagua as an option in the
sixth, seventh and eighth innings. His absence has caused the
Mariners to scramble, trying Ken Cloude, Rafael Carmona, even Jeff
Fassero _ however briefly _ in that role.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I was so pleased with the job Frankie did
(Wednesday),'' Piniella said. ``To me, that was impressive. We need
a couple of pitchers to do that type of job for us. It'll allow me
to keep Paniagua nice and rested and not have to lean on him
entirely. He's the one I've had to overuse a little at times, even
though he likes to pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Piniella said his goal is to keep each pitcher in a specific
role. Friday night's starter, Paul Abbott, will be the Mariners'
21st pitcher already, but Piniella said he's ``getting closer'' to
finding the right combination.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to put a staff together that we can grow with and
have pitchers in specific roles,'' Piniella said. ``We thought that
Rodriguez, of all the pitchers that we have here, would fit in that
middle to set-up type situation, and his arm bounces back very
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to put something here that we don't have to
tinker with anymore. Naturally, it depends on how pitchers pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   When Abbott is officially added to the roster today,
right-hander Aaron Scheffer will be sent to Class AAA Tacoma. The
Mariners still could use another left-hander in the bullpen, and
Piniella said the club would consider bringing back Sean Spencer or
Jordan Zimmerman, or promoting Damaso Marte for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're watching their progress carefully,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   DOME FAN: Count Matt Walbeck as one player who's sorry to see
the Kingdome go. When the Anaheim Angels catcher was 9 years old,
he and his dad drove up from their home in Sacramento for the 1979
All-Star Game. He saw batting practice from above the right field
wall, and got a souvenir from an Orioles coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked Ray Miller for a ball, and he threw it to me. I was
stoked,'' Walbeck said. ``I love it here. I love hitting here. I
always have. Out of all the domes, this is my favorite one.''
</P>
<P>
   AROUND THE HORN: First baseman David Segui was cleared to play
last night after missing two games with fluid in his left knee, but
received an extra day of rest. ... Why were songs like ``Evenflow''
and ``Jeremy'' playing from the Kingdome loudspeakers before last
night's game? Must have been the shaggy-haired friend of Jack
McDowell on the Angels bench. Pearl Jam's Eddie Vedder took some
batting practice as he visited the Angels' pitcher/musician. ...
The Mariners should surpass the 1 million mark in attendance Friday
night. The club failed to attract 1 million fans all year from
1978-81 and from 1983-84. ... A total of 3,623 fans took part in
``Buhner Buzz Night'' at the Kingdome Thursday night. Of those, 443
were already bald, and the remainder had their heads shaved _
including 56 women, a new record. In the six years of the event,
16,056 chrome-domes have packed the Kingdome.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
