<HEADER>
A9015 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-UNIONIZED-MEDICI     06-25 0488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-UNIONIZED-MEDICINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: UNIONIZED MEDICINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The American Medical Association has taken on the managed care
industry with its vote to create an affiliated labor union for
doctors who are salaried employees. The decision was surprising for
a hidebound organization whose members have traditionally and
sometimes arrogantly presented themselves as part of an elite
profession as opposed to members of a workers' group. But
unionization seems inevitable as doctors seek ways to recover their
clout against powerful health plans. For consumers, unionization
may be a positive force if doctors use collective bargaining to
negotiate for improved patient services rather than merely for
higher physician pay.
</P>
<P>
   One out of seven doctors are now employees working for others,
compared with earlier decades when nearly all doctors were
self-employed businessmen who set their own fees. Consolidation and
the rise of corporate-run networks serving hundreds of thousands of
patients have also reduced the autonomy of independent doctors who
contract with insurers to provide medical services. Frustration
with managed care has caused many to seek a collective voice in
dealing with health plans.
</P>
<P>
   The AMA move comes at a time when unionization of doctors is
already growing. More than 40,000 doctors who are employees of
HMOs, hospitals and public institutions are members of other unions
representing service workers and government employees. The AMA
entry into the union movement will probably increase those numbers
by giving doctors their own union, one governed by the profession's
principles. The organization has properly pledged that its union,
unlike other unions, will never strike, and will not focus on
matters like pay and job security. Instead it says the union would
allow employee-doctors a way to challenge restrictions on patient
services.
</P>
<P>
   Federal antitrust law prevents the AMA union from representing
self-employed doctors. But the association is strongly pushing for
a bill in the House that would provide an antitrust exemption to
allow independent doctors to band together to bargain collectively
with health plans and insurers. The implications of such a change
must be carefully examined by Congress. Some states are moving in
this direction. Texas recently passed a law to give self-employed
doctors more bargaining leverage.
</P>
<P>
   The rapid shift in the medical marketplace has been driven
largely by employers and insurers eager to hold down high medical
costs. For the most part, doctors have been bewildered observers of
the upheaval. The AMA's action shows that the profession is no
longer willing to stay out of the game. If doctors use collective
bargaining to improve patient care standards, unionization may turn
out to be a strong force against health plans that unfairly use
their market power to limit quality of care.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-99 0205EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
