<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 02:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9030 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINE-LAYOFFS-AZR &LR;      06-25 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINE-LAYOFFS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN MANUEL COPPER SMELTER AND MINE TO CLOSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JANE LARSON  
 and MARK SHAFFER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN MANUEL, Ariz. _ Pummeled by the lowest copper prices in 12
years, Broken Hill Proprietary Co. Ltd. announced Thursday that it
will shut its smelter and underground copper mine and lay off
nearly 2,200 workers here.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian mining conglomerate will also close its Nevada
mine, for a total of 2,630 layoffs by the end of August. About 430
employees will continue to work at the rod plant in San Manuel and
at copper-processing plants there and at its mine outside
Globe-Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``BHP cannot continue to operate in these financial
circumstances,'' Doug McGregor, president of BHP Copper North
America, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Copper prices have averaged 65 cents a pound this year, a 46
percent drop from the heady $1.22 of two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The shutdown decision came as BHP, based in Melbourne, announced
that it lost 2.3 billion Australian dollars in the year that ended
May 31, due to the restructuring. Without those charges, the
company would have posted a profit of 365 million Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian dollar has been trading at about 65 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
   Word of the closing hit like a ton of bricks at dusk as parents
gathered at San Manuel's Little League baseball field to watch a
practice session for the town's 9- and 10-year-old All-Stars.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Gomez, 47, a pipefitter for 25 years, stared vacantly at
the field. A voice yelled out that his boy doubled. Gomez hadn't
noticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready to make my break from this,'' he said, slowly and
unconvincingly. ``I mean, I'm a plumber, I can install commodes. I
can pay $10,000 and get bonded and do small commercial work.''
</P>
<P>
   But then he lapsed back into mine talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother is a foreman at the mine in Tyrone, New Mexico, and
he always said that they need fitters and he would take care of
me,'' Gomez said.
</P>
<P>
   The news that the mine would close came on the heels of an
increased presence of law officers near the mine entrance. Workers
said that they had been sent home from work Wednesday after a
threat was phoned in to bomb the mine.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Viramontes, a crane operator, said he was called in with
dozens of other workers to the mine's control room halfway through
his shift Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just said go home and don't come back and that they would
call us next week. It was all very matter-of-fact,'' Viramontes
said.
</P>
<P>
   BHP bought the San Manuel and Pinto Valley properties in 1996 as
part of its acquisition of Tucson-based Magma Copper Co.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have long believed BHP paid too much for the
properties, bought when copper prices were high and BHP wanted into
the U.S. market.
</P>
<P>
   It had been looking for a buyer, particularly for the
world-class San Manuel smelter, but no copper companies were
jumping at the chance in a slumping market.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you know somebody who has a desire to buy at a great price,
I'll talk to them today,'' BHP Managing Director Paul Anderson told
a Melbourne news conference. In a more robust copper market, the
U.S. properties would be attractive and BHP would have buyers, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He held out little hope the properties would be reopened soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the price of copper went up to $1 tomorrow, we'd be opening
the mines,'' he said. But he also later said he would prefer to
invest in the company's Chilean mine over the higher-cost U.S.
properties.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson joined the struggling conglomerate last year with a vow
to make cuts and refocus its business.
</P>
<P>
   Other copper companies and the industry worldwide had been
awaiting his action, in hopes it would reduce a global oversupply
of copper and boost prices.
</P>
<P>
   BHP's announcement sent copper prices and BHP stock up sharply
in early trading.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the circumstances, it's the right thing to do,'' said
Timothy Snider, president of Phelps Dodge Mining Co., the mining
side of Phoenix-based Phelps Dodge Corp., another major player in
the industry. ``It shows some leadership, and we think it will help
the business.''
</P>
<P>
   In its announcement, BHP said it will place the U.S. mines and
smelter on ``care and maintenance,'' meaning they could be reopened
if prices improve.
</P>
<P>
   BHP, which started a $54 million upgrade on the San Manuel
smelter in May, said it will complete the upgrade and then put it
in care and maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   The shutdowns will be phased in over the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Some areas will suspend operations immediately, BHP said, and
hourly workers will be placed on paid leave until the plans are
complete. Salaried workers will continue to report over the next 30
days.
</P>
<P>
   Employees will receive normal pay and benefits for 60 days, in
addition to the interim leave. The company also will provide career
counseling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize the impact the cessation will have on employees,
and we are committed to helping those affected to pursue their next
career move,'' McGregor said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
   An official with the Greater Tucson Economic Council said there
are job possibilities in Tucson, 40 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can we absorb it? Yes, we can, but people would have to be
retrained,'' said Sandy Garcia, vice president of the organization.
</P>
<P>
   A man sitting on the tailgate of a pickup near the San Manuel
baseball field was skeptical. He set off a round of groans from his
buddies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess Tucson is about to get flooded, ain't it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not going to be a job left north of downtown. Home
Depot sure is looking good about now.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-99 0213EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
