<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990625.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 02:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9042 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      06-25 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAUGHN JOLTS MARINERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Mariners manager Lou Piniella sat in his office before
Thursday night's game and considered his new starting rotation.
With Jamie Moyer, Freddy Garcia, John Halama, Jeff Fassero and Paul
Abbott, Piniella said, the Mariners could start winning
consistently.
</P>
<P>
   But he added a warning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the games up here are won from the sixth inning on,''
Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't know how accurate he'd be.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners' late-game foundation has shown signs of cracking
this month, and the whole thing crumbled Thursday night in two
horrific innings against the Anaheim Angels. The Angels scored nine
unanswered runs after the seventh inning, spoiling a strong effort
by Fassero, and left with a 12-7 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I have to say about this ballgame is, if we
keep walking three hitters in the eighth inning, like we did
tonight, and we did in Cleveland, you're not going to win too many
ballgames,'' Piniella said. ``That's all I've got.''
</P>
<P>
   Leading 7-3, Jose Paniagua retired the first Angels hitter in
the eighth. But a single and two walks loaded the bases, and
Piniella called on closer Jose Mesa, who failed in his only
previous attempt at a five-out save.
</P>
<P>
   He would not get one this time, either. Mesa walked Darin Erstad
to bring in one run. Randy Velarde followed with his fifth hit, a
single that scored two runs. Matt Luke scored the second run by
beating the throw from Charles Gipson, who had replaced center
fielder Ken Griffey Jr. Piniella said Griffey Jr. was dizzy and had
a bad cold.
</P>
<P>
   That made the score 7-6 Mariners, and it stayed that way for
about three seconds. Mo Vaughn smoked Mesa's first pitch 423 feet
to right-center, and the three-run homer gave the Angels a 9-7
lead. Mesa, who was roundly booed by his old fans in Cleveland in
his last outing, was booed by his new fans as he was pulled for Ken
Cloude two batters later.
</P>
<P>
   Paniagua and Mesa, so reliable over the first two months, have
not been sharp lately. Paniagua has been scored on in four of his
last five outings, allowing seven earned runs in six innings. Mesa
has been scored on in five of his last six games, with seven runs
allowed in five innings.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa, who converted his first 12 save opportunities, has blown
two of four. Paniagua's earned-run average is 3.92, the highest
it's been all season.
</P>
<P>
   They aren't the only struggling Mariners relievers. Coming in to
keep things close with two outs in the ninth, Allen Watson
surrendered a mammoth three-run homer to Vaughn, his fifth hit of
the night.
</P>
<P>
   Two of those runs were charged to Cloude, who has given up at
least two runs in five of his seven outings since leaving the
rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Watson, acquired last Friday in the trade that sent Mac Suzuki
to the New York Mets, has pitched in three games for Seattle. In
each of them, he has allowed a home run to the leadoff hitter, and
in three Mariner innings, he has allowed five homers. Watson is the
only left-hander in the Mariners' bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   The bullpen blowup not only spoiled Fassero's outing, but cost
the Mariners a game in the standings. For the first time in nine
games, the M's had a different result than the division-leading
Texas Rangers, who beat Oakland 5-2 yesterday and come to the
Kingdome Friday night with a five-game lead on Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see what comes out tomorrow,'' Fassero said. ``You can't
tell until we show up tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassero was pitching for the third time in four days, having
worked briefly in relief on Monday and Tuesday. He was re-inserted
in the rotation one turn earlier than expected, and Piniella did
not want to extend him much past 90 pitches. Fassero allowed a
two-run homer to Velarde in the third and one more run in the
fifth, but overall was solid.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The loss is) something you live with,'' said Fassero, who
said his concentration was better Thursday night. ``Maybe it's time
for the starters to pick (the relievers) up a little bit, with more
seven- or eight-inning stints.''
</P>
<P>
   In six innings, he allowed six hits and walked three.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim starter Chuck Finley, who normally masters the Mariners,
lasted just four innings, allowing seven runs on six hits.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the damage came from Mariners shortstop Alex Rodriguez,
who had a homer and two singles off the Angels' ace. Rodriguez had
just four hits in 24 career at-bats off Finley coming into the
game, but singled in the first to advance Brian Hunter, singled in
the second to drive in Gipson, and drilled a two-run homer in the
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   The home run was Rodriguez's 12th of the season, and gave the
Mariners a 7-2 lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
