</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-PADRES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PADRES EDGE DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _The body language is showing the toll that losing
is taking on the Los Angeles Dodgers. The jump in their step is
gone, and after sliding or diving after balls, it's taken time to
pull their bodies up again.
</P>
<P>
   They say it can't get worse than the mishaps of two weeks ago in
Oakland, or of Kevin Brown forgetting how many outs there were and
letting a run score.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the follies are fewer, but the results are the same.
It's not getting worse, but it certainly is getting no better.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers hoped to turn things around on their longest
homestand of the year. Instead, San Diego completed a three-game
sweep with a 2-1 win Thursday at Dodger Stadium. The Dodgers went
3-6 on the homestand.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers (32-38) and Padres (31-38) are tied for last in
National League West in the loss column. By the end of today, the
$80 million underachieving Boys in Blue might be dead last in the
division.
</P>
<P>
   But that really doesn't matter. If the Dodgers were in second
place, it wouldn't quite matter right now, not with the way they're
playing. This isn't about where they stand with other teams but
rather where they rate themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Just hours off the disabled list, Padres right-hander Andy Ashby
(7-4) retired the first 11 Dodgers he faced and allowed four hits
in six-plus innings. Gary Sheffield broke up any early thoughts of
history with a single to left in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers didn't get a runner to second base until Eric Young
reached on an error and stole with two outs in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   An inning later the Dodgers' offensive offense was in full
bloom. Gary Sheffield walked, Raul Mondesi singled and Todd
Hollandsworth singled to pull the Dodgers within 2-1. Donne Wall
relieved Ashby and got Eric Karros on a weak pop-up and got Jose
Vizcaino to ground back to the mound for a fielder's choice.
Pinch-hitter Devon White ended the inning with another weak pop-up.
</P>
<P>
   Padres right-hander Dan Miceli pitched the ninth for his first
save, though it was somewhat eventful. Hollandsworth singled with
two outs and Karros walked before Vizcaino struck out.
</P>
<P>
   In being obliterated by the Padres, the Dodgers scored four runs
in 27 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The perils of the offense are reciprocated, in a small-picture
way, by what's turning into strong pitching, at least for the last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers right-hander Darren Dreifort took the advise of former
Dodgers pitcher Doug Bochtler and trainer Stan Johnston during a
recent bullpen session and ran with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bochtler watched me throw and said, `That was the quietest
I've seen your head,' '' Dreifort said. ``Stan, he said the biggest
thing was getting strike one. You know it, but sometimes you forget
it. Sometimes it's trying to do too much stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Too much stuff? It sounds familiar. It's been the refrain coming
out of the Dodgers' clubhouse for the past month or so.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort (6-6) simplified things. He forgot about having the
perfect leg kick and didn't think about arm angles in the middle of
his delivery.
</P>
<P>
   It worked for 62/3 innings during an 8-1 win against
Philadelphia, Dreifort's first start since his near-banishment to
the bullpen, a decision by Dodgers manager Davey Johnson that
lasted for a day. The mere threat of Dreifort returning to the
bullpen, where he began his Dodgers career, might be enough to turn
him around.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time he pitched into the seventh inning in
back-to-back starts. Dreifort allowed two runs on five hits in
seven innings, but given the way the Dodgers have played, that
wasn't going to be enough. The Padres took a 1-0 lead in the first
on Dave Magadan's sacrifice fly and made it 2-0 in the third on
another Magadan sacrifice fly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
