r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NHRANOTES-LADN     06-25 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NHRANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOES FEEL FORCE CAN BE BEATEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE RAMIREZ  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is there a dent in John Force's championship armor?
</P>
<P>
   Some of his competitors think so.
</P>
<P>
   The eight-time National Hot Rod Association Funny Car champion
won six of the first eight national events, but he's failed to
visit victory circle in the past two races.
</P>
<P>
   Now drivers in the nitromethane-coupe class believe they have a
small amount of hope, especially at this weekend's Sears Craftsman
Nationals near St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Force can be beat,'' said Frank Pedregon, the defending event
champion. ``Both of those guys (including Force teammate Tony
Pedregon) can be beat. Tony (has) the quickest car in the world,
but we beat him at (the Gatornationals). I raced Force a couple
times, and we almost had him (at Englishtown, N.J.).
</P>
<P>
   ``He definitely can be beat and I think right now (the rest of
the competitors in Funny Car) should all start jumping in there and
try to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Pedregon may have the best chance at that this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is the older of the Pedregon brothers the defending
event champion, but his Pontiac Firebird is tuned by the crafty Jim
Dunn, who traditionally finds ways to get down a hot, slippery
track like St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it is, but I always seem to do better in the
last half of the season,'' Pedregon said. ``Right now, we're ready
to shine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think the last four races we started to come on. The
first part, we were just feeling it out, not do anything crazy.
Now, going into St. Louis we feel we can back up our win from last
year.''
</P>
<P>
   This weekend's event will feature the NHRA's first night race
since 1996. Qualifying, which began Thursday, included two 9 p.m.
(local time) sessions with eliminations slated to begin at 4 p.m.
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans are going to love this race,'' Pro Stock driver
Richie Stevens said. ``It won't make much difference for us in Pro
Stock, but for the (Top Fuel and Funny Cars) is going to be great.
When those race cars are shooting flames up into the darkness, it's
awesome to see.''
</P>
<P>
   The night air should also benefit Force, who had one of the best
weekends of his career at the last night event. Not only did he win
the 1996 Western Auto Nationals in Topeka, Kan., but he became the
first Funny Car driver to make eight consecutive passes in the
four-second barrier.
</P>
<P>
   You can call Kenny Bernstein the Bud King for a few more years.
</P>
<P>
   The five-time champion announced earlier this week that
Budweiser will continue to be his primary sponsor through 2005.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud to have had the opportunity to represent Budweiser
and I'm happy we've had so many successes together,'' said
Bernstein, winner of 52 national events in a career that dates back
to the early 1970s. ``My 20 years with Budweiser have been
phenomenal and I'm looking forward to our future together.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein, who currently is third in the Top Fuel points
standings, is the only competitor in NHRA to win both a Top Fuel
title and a Funny Car championship.
</P>
<P>
   He won four consecutive Funny Car titles in the early 1980s
before capturing the Top Fuel championship in 1996. Bernstein is
also the first driver to eclipse the 300-mph barrier, accomplishing
that milestone in 1992.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
