<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CALIFORNIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE PLUGS AWAY, INTO THE NIGHT, TO CAPTURE HEART OF CALIFORNIA
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  ABOARD AIR FORCE II _ Vice President Al Gore is leaning
backwards in a big, oversized leather seat in his private office on
board, phone glued to his ear.
<P>
   He's just raced 800 miles up and down California _ fund raising,
speeches, interviews, more fund raising, more speeches. But the
day's not over. He is on a mission.
</P>
<P>
   While his young staff chows down on a late-night snack of
buffalo wings, Gore is still working, working to become the next
president of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Gore knows California is a big place, but it's crowded these
days with presidential candidates vying for attention. Texas Gov.
George W. Bush arrives next week, and will be followed by a horde
of 80 reporters.
</P>
<P>
   With only a handful of media types following him this week, Gore
is already being described as the tortoise chasing the proverbial
hare.
</P>
<P>
   But with nine months to go before the California primary and the
candidate himself admitting that voters still aren't focused on the
race, Gore's campaign message in the nation's most populous state
has begun to emerge. And with it has come a steely focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to keep the prosperity going _ with my own values of
faith and family,'' he said again and again during his two-day trip
this week.
</P>
<P>
   He seized on gun control and hit the GOP hard (``The NRA is
calling the shots in the Republican Party today''). He talked of
revolutionary changes in education. And, though the economic boom
has been formidable, he said the task is now ``to reach out to
every member of our society, to make sure no one is left behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Just how unwaveringly the vice president adheres to his message
was illustrated in San Francisco, where Gore was interviewed by a
quartet of television reporters within 45 minutes on Wednesday.
Their questions varied widely _ the polls, Bush, gay rights, his
fund raising _ but each time, the vice president skillfully stuck
to his message.
</P>
<P>
   This election is a choice between risky tax schemes or focused
tax cuts, he argued. Will Americans want to protect gun
manufacturers, he asked, or ``should we shield the children'' from
gun violence instead?
</P>
<P>
   Will they want to invest in public schools or drain money away
in the form of voucher schemes? Is it going to be about privatizing
Social Security or preserving and protecting Social Security?
</P>
<P>
   Gore also faced up to those who would tie him to his boss,
saying, ``It is time for a clean start in a fresh century.``
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles Thursday, he started out with lunch, ended with a
fund-raising dinner and tucked between them a visit to a gay and
lesbian center.
</P>
<P>
   There, as in San Francisco, Gore appealed to more traditional
Democrats by talking about standing for those who are misperceived
and misunderstood, and for families ``of all kinds.''
</P>
<P>
   And he has begun to do what those who know him say is most
critical: telling voters who he is and why he wants the job.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president of the United States begins his talks to
supporters like a guy on a job interview. He tells crowds where he
grew up (``in two places''), that he's a Vietnam vet, about his
family and marriage to wife Tipper for 29 years, his stint as a
reporter. And even how he's going to be a grandparent in a few
days, and start spoiling the grandkid.
</P>
<P>
   So, Gore insiders say, let George W. Bush come to California.
</P>
<P>
   The hare is dashing in next week, they say, but the tortoise has
been here 57 times.
</P>
<P>
   He'll keep going, slow and steady, making phone calls until well
into the night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
