r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-PADRES-RE     06-25 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-PADRES-REWRITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PADRES BEAT DODGERS TO CAP SWEEP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 Daily News Staff Writer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The body language shows the toll that losing is
taking. The jump in the Los Angeles Dodgers' step is gone, and
every time they hit the ground, they take more and more time to
pull their bodies up again.
</P>
<P>
   They said it couldn't get worse than the throwing and fielding
mishaps two weeks ago in Oakland, or worse than Kevin Brown
forgetting the number of outs.
</P>
<P>
   The follies are fewer, but the results remain consistent. The
Dodgers aren't getting worse (because they couldn't), but they're
certainly getting no better.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers hoped to turn things around on their longest
homestand. Instead, San Diego completed a three-game sweep with a
2-1 win Thursday at Dodger Stadium. The Dodgers went 3-6 on the
homestand. The Dodgers (32-38) and San Diego Padres (31-38) are
tied for last in the National League West in the loss column and by
the end of today, the $80 million underachieving Boys in Blue might
be dead last in the division.
</P>
<P>
   Since firing pitching coach Charlie Hough to shake up the
then-.500 Dodgers, they are 10-16.
</P>
<P>
   In being obliterated by the Padres, the Dodgers scored four runs
in three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``If things were like this on other teams I've been on, they
wouldn't fire coaches, they would get rid of players,'' said left
fielder Gary Sheffield, who at .306 is the only regular hitting
better than .300. But where the Dodgers stand doesn't matter. If
the Dodgers were in second place, it wouldn't matter right now, not
with the way they're playing. This isn't about where they stand
with other teams but rather where they rate themselves.
</P>
<P>
   What is noticeable, to Sheffield, is teams seem to play harder
against the Dodgers. And there's a reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you make comments about winning the World Series, teams
are going to come after you,'' said Sheffield, who bucked the trend
and hit .400 on the homestand. ``We're not playing with any
enthusiasm. We're going out there and thinking they should hand it
to us. It's embarrassing to me. I don't know about everyone else.
I'm tired of it. I hope everybody else is.''
</P>
<P>
   Every day the Dodgers talk about turning it around, and then
nothing happens.
</P>
<P>
   Just hours off the disabled list, Padres right-hander Andy Ashby
(7-4) retired the first 11 Dodgers he faced and allowed four hits
in six-plus innings. Sheffield broke up any early thoughts of
history with a single to left in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers didn't get a runner to second base until the sixth,
and an inning later the enigma that is the Dodgers' offensive
offense was in full bloom. Sheffield walked, Raul Mondesi singled
and Todd Hollandsworth singled to pull the Dodgers within 2-1.
Donne Wall relieved Ashby, and Eric Karros, Jose Vizcaino Devon
White each failed to hit the ball out of the infield.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be able to drive that run in,'' Dodgers manager
Davey Johnson said. ``I hate to be thinking about squeezing in the
tying run, but that's what's going through my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Padres right-hander Dan Miceli pitched the ninth for his first
save, though it was somewhat eventful. Hollandsworth singled with
two outs and Karros walked before Vizcaino struck out looking.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a ball, outside,'' Vizcaino said. ``I saw it three
times. It was outside. There's nothing going our way.''
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, Darren Dreifort (6-6) took the loss because the
Padres were able to hit a fly ball. Dave Magadan drove in runs in
the first and third innings with sacrifice flies. The first run
scored despite Magadan's ball being the only one hit out of the
infield.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no answer,'' Karros said of the Dodgers' doldrums.
``If there were answers, I'm sure it would be addressed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
