<HEADER>
A9063 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEAHORSE-SURVIVAL-SFC     06-25 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEAHORSE-SURVIVAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SCIENTISTS HELP SEA HORSES BACK FROM NEAR EXTINCTION  &HT;     By DAVID PERLMAN 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The curious and quirky little sea horse, a
monster in mythic lore, faces extinction throughout the world's
oceans _ but a young biologist at the California Academy of
Sciences is using his experimental skills in an attempt to reverse
the widespread death toll.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Gomezjurado, 32, whose passion for sea horses began when
he watched them vanishing because of the illegal nets of fishermen
around the fabled Galapagos Islands, is now breeding them by the
thousands in his laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   Among all the denizens of the ocean, sea horses and their
relatives, the pipefishes, are the only species in the world whose
males get pregnant and give birth to the babies. Their entire sex
life is odd indeed.
</P>
<P>
   In Gomezjurado's laboratory tank the other day, where sea horses
by the score swam blithely amid tiny forests of kelp and coral, he
pointed to one lively specimen wearing a delicate identifying
plastic tag around its neck and a belly that was obviously bulging.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's No. 40,'' the biologist said, ``and he's very, very
pregnant _ he'll give birth to the babies within a day or two, and
an hour later he'll be ready to mate all over again. He's
incredible. He never stops, and he's always pregnant. Monogamous?
Not at all. He'll mate again with the first female that comes
along.''
</P>
<P>
   Sea Horse No. 40, in fact, did give birth to about 700 tiny,
free-swimming infants over the weekend, and he is ready to get
pregnant again _ the champion of the tank.
</P>
<P>
   A male's courtship ritual is lovely to behold. He changes his
mottled body color from mostly green or brown to a more attractive
golden hue, and his fins darken.
</P>
<P>
   Then, swimming vertically face to face with a willing female,
the couple swim into a slow dance through wide circles and rise
together toward the surface as they copulate. In that act, repeated
several times, the male opens the brood pouch on his belly and the
female deposits her eggs into the pouch, where the male can quickly
fertilize them.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later, the babies emerge from the pregnant male by the
hundreds to live their endangered lives completely on their own _
if they are not swiftly consumed by predatory fishes.
</P>
<P>
   Extremely delicate and harvested commercially by the millions,
dried sea horses are ground up for folk medicines that are sold in
Asian markets as cures for everything from impotence to heart
disease. And although they rarely survive long in home aquariums,
many hobbyists buy them and try to keep them alive, although they
are now on the World Conservation Union's ``red list'' as a
threatened population.
</P>
<P>
   At the academy's Steinhart Aquarium in Golden Gate Park, six
small tanks hold four species of sea horses from Gomezjurado's
laboratory on permanent public display.
</P>
<P>
   He will move sea horse No. 40 from the lab into one of the
display tanks this week so the virile champion can mate with a
female again and produce another few hundred babies in another two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Fisheries scientists at 35 institutions around the world are
joining in an attempt to replenish stocks of the 32 species of sea
horses that inhabit every warm-water ocean, according to
Gomezjurado.
</P>
<P>
   The young Ecuadoran biologist specializes in the world's largest
species of sea horses, the giant one called Hippocampus ingens that
grows up to a foot long and inhabits Pacific waters from central
Baja California to the Galapagos islands and northern Peru.
</P>
<P>
   In the open seas, the survival rate among newborn sea horses is
only about 1 percent. In the past, even under the best of
laboratory conditions, scientists have been able to keep only about
5 percent of their newborns alive.
</P>
<P>
   But by experimenting with varied diets, Gomezjurado said, at
least 30 percent of the newborn sea horses in his lab are thriving.
</P>
<P>
   Tall, green tanks in the lab hold thick cultures of saltwater
algae, the phytoplankton that forms the base of the intricate food
chain on which all oceangoing life depends. Microscopic animals
called rotifers feed on the algae, and nauplii, the free-swimming
larvae of larger but still tiny crustaceans, live on the rotifers.
Next on the food chain, devouring the lower orders, come the larger
crustaceans called copepods, and they provide nourishment in turn
for shrimp and other larger animals.
</P>
<P>
   Gomezjurado has created a similar food chain in his laboratory,
and nourishes his hundreds of sea horses with a pulverized pink mix
of frozen organisms and mysid shrimp, supplemented by drugstore
multivitamins and the same omega-3 fatty acids that humans consume
to help prevent heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   With their strange, equine heads, bony outer skeletons and
curving, prehensile tails, sea horses have long intrigued humans.
Their generic name _ hippocampus _ comes from the Greek hippos,
meaning horse, and kampos, meaning monster. In ancient Greece, the
myths held that the creatures were true monsters, born of Poseidon,
the sea god, and that they menaced humans with their two forefeet
and their bodies ending in a dolphin's tail.
</P>
<P>
   In real life, Gomezjurado's sea horses are no monsters, but a
priceless part of the ocean's diversity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our captive breeding project will reduce pressures on the wild
population by replenishing aquarium displays, and the data from our
research may someday be useful in reestablishing wild populations,
too,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
