<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLY SAFE PLACE IS BEHIND BARS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Honk if you're on the lam.
</P>
<P>
   Truly frightening, The Chronicle series about mountains of
unserved arrest warrants. I won't feel safe until I'm locked up in
San Quentin, where the violent criminals are at least supervised.
</P>
<P>
   Our courts should mail out those warrants with RSVPs.
</P>
<P>
   Now the authorities say they'll spring into action and start
rounding up some of the more annoying fugitive ax murderers. Why
are the authorities never aware of these problems until they read
about 'em in The Chronicle?
</P>
<P>
   Now the jails will become overcrowded. Possible solution: Chain
gangs. Massachussetts has them now, though they call them ``tandem
work crews.'' The man in charge says, ``My program ... builds
self-esteem and self-confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   So we round up the bad guys and gals, slap chains on 'em, and we
get our highways and cities cleaned up while the prisoners get a
new self-image. I picture them working alongside the freeway
singing tandem work crew songs like ``Just the Two of Us`' and ``Me
and You and a Dog Named Blue.''
</P>
<P>
   But why should convicts get all the self-esteem? What about us
cutting-edge self-improvement freaks? I'm chaining myself to Jon
Carroll, and I think you'll be noticing better work from both of
us.
</P>
<P>
   THE DICTIONARY isn't big enough for Willie Brown. Heather
Peterson was watching KTVU News, and da mayor was discussing a
run-down building.
</P>
<P>
   ``He must have been thinking decrepit and dilapidated at the
same time,'' says Heather, ``and it came out `decrapitated.' Then
he paused for a second _ must have been thinking, `Close enough.'''
</P>
<P>
   Good word, sure to have many handy uses in da mayor's city.
</P>
<P>
   DE NEW de Young Museum, judging from general response of
armchair architects, is already decrapitated. Does anybody like the
design?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the artist's rendering is a bad picture. As a daily victim
of that malady, I can sympathize. But the Golden Gate Bridge or
Palace of Fine Arts, this building ain't. It looks like a Howard
Johnson's of the future.
</P>
<P>
   A STEAL: Wow, Jennie Yabroff brings to our attention an ad in
Friday's Chronicle for a big on-campus sale at S.F. State. They're
selling ``new and used pianos on loan to the university.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Jennie, ``Now we know why Polonius told Laertes, `Neither a
borrower nor a lender be.'''
</P>
<P>
   And there's your culture for the day.
</P>
<P>
   Proceeds from the piano sale will fund the university's new
advertisement-proofreading chair.
</P>
<P>
   DING-DING, ZZZZ: It's late in the evening and we're at the Hyde
Street cable car turntable. A long line of tourists shiver in the
cold and fog. Half a block away, a long line of cable cars (often
four and five) wait and wait.
</P>
<P>
   What are the car crews doing while the tourists cool their heels
and freeze their assets? Some are dozing. I've seen 'em.
</P>
<P>
   Muni tells me the cable cars actually have schedules, and the
gripman and conductor are allowed a break between runs. But not the
30 and 40 minutes and more they often take at Hyde.
</P>
<P>
   It's costing the city. Tourists don't spend dough while they're
waiting 90 minutes for a cable car.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, it's rude. Let's get those car crews some fresh coffee
and an on-site dispatcher to provide wake-up calls.
</P>
<P>
   ARRIVEDERCI: Fuzio's restaurant in North Beach, the franchise
eatery that bullied its way in over strong local objection, has
gone quietly into that great good night (hey, another pretentious
literary reference!).
</P>
<P>
   The locals have an ongoing crusade to keep the area free of
chain restaurants and stores, but Fuzio's, owned by Chevy's,
sneaked in with a back-door play. Six months later, it was gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``North Beach spoke with its feet,'' says Aaron Peskin,
president of the Telegraph Hill Dwellers. ``The presumption was
that we have to fight the chains because if they come in, they'll
succeed. Now they know they'll have to fight to get in, then people
won't eat there.''
</P>
<P>
   Three other Fuzio's in the city hum along, but score a win for
the spirit of North Beach.
</P>
<P>
   YOU ARE the wings beneath my ice cube: Tom Sweeney, Beefeater
doorman at the Sir Francis Drake, is training for the Boston
Marathon, and he finished a run at Ocean Beach. Heading home, he
came upon a sidewalk lemonade stand on Fulton Street.
</P>
<P>
   Tom gave the kid two quarters. The kid gave Tom a lemonade and a
quarter back.
</P>
<P>
   Tom: ``The sign says 50 cents.''
</P>
<P>
   Kid: ``Yours had a fly in it.''
</P>
<P>
   OUCH: Betsy Bogel sends a clip from the Independent in San
Mateo, a brief report of a car accident in which ``One victim
sustained a two-inch evisceration in his head.''
</P>
<P>
   Coulda been worse. The guy coulda been decrapitated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
