<SLUG> BC-CELLULAR-CHARGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELLULAR ONE PLANS TO CHARGE FOR UNANSWERED CALLS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cellular One already charges cell phone customers when they make
a call or take a call. Now it wants to make sure it charges them
even when no one answers the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Starting July 1, Cellular One plans to start imposing charges
for 15 seconds (the equivalent of about three rings) after the
customer hits the send button on a call. The charges would apply
even if no connection is made.
</P>
<P>
   Because Cellular One bills in one-minute increments, the new
policy means calls that ring more than 15 seconds will carry at
least a one-minute charge, or anywhere from 10 to 52 cents
depending on the customer's calling plan. If the customer has free
calling minutes, minutes will start being deducted after 15
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Cellular One, a subsidiary of SBC Communications of San Antonio,
issued a two-paragraph statement Thursday defending the new charge,
stating that its network is utilized whenever a call is made. By
allowing a grace period of just 15 seconds, the company said more
channels will remain open for use by other customers.
</P>
<P>
   The company declined to comment further, other than to say
customers have been notified of the change.
</P>
<P>
   Cellular One's grace period in the Massachusetts-Rhode
Island-New Hampshire market has been steadily cut over the past few
years from 60 seconds to 30 seconds and now to 15 seconds. SBC's
wireless operations in Connecticut and Washington, D.C., are not as
miserly, allowing a 30-second grace period. By contrast, officials
from most of SBC's wireless rivals said they charge customers only
if a connection is made.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like they're picking on you guys,'' said K.C. Choi, a
spokesman for the Telecommunications Research and Action Center in
Washington, a consumer group.
</P>
<P>
   Choi said he did not think most consumers were aware of the
calling grace periods. He said he was not aware of them, and he had
just signed up with Cellular One in Washington. He also said 15
seconds seemed to be unreasonably short, given the length of time
it takes for some people to answer the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Cellular One's policy appears to be unique in the industry. John
Palmer, executive director of marketing for Bell Atlantic Mobile,
said his company does not buy into its rival's reasoning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our customers are demanding value and are not willing to
tolerate unnecessary or hidden charges that they wouldn't normally
expect to pay,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Marty Nee, a spokesman for AT&AMP;T Wireless, had a similar
reaction. ``If no one picks up on the other end, no one gets
charged,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Omnipoint and officials at Sprint PCS also said
their companies do not start charge until a connection is made.
</P>
<P>
   The grace period issue is very different from a proposal that
would change the overall billing structure for cellular phone
calls. Currently, cell phone customers are charged for incoming and
outgoing calls, but federal regulators are moving toward a billing
system that would charge all calls to the person placing the call.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
