<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-AYALA-TAPIA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHADOW BOXER: FORT WORTH FIGHTER READY TO STEP INTO SPOTLIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Johnny Tapia's rap sheet is almost as detailed as
his line-by-line ring record. It is a combination that has made
``The Baby Face Assassin'' a three-time world champion and one of
the most compelling draws in boxing.
</P>
<P>
   In comparison, the life and times of bantamweight contender
Paulie Ayala comes off as what? Boring?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's normal, man,'' said Ayala, the Fort Worth fighter who
will challenge Tapia for his World Boxing Association bantamweight
(118-pound) title at the Mandalay Bay Events Center here tomorrow
night. ``I knew the difference between right and wrong _ and I was
scared to do wrong. That's what I see myself as right now: Just a
normal guy who chose boxing for a career.''
</P>
<P>
   So did Tapia, the pride of Albuquerque, N.M., and blessed with
the blinding speed, the defense and the accuracy that separates
world contenders from world wannabes. But Tapia's rise to fame came
careening to a halt at the beginning of this decade, when his
addiction to cocaine led to a 3 1/2-year suspension from boxing.
With the help of his wife and manager, Teresa, Tapia has
resurrected himself, and reminded Ayala of what might have been.
</P>
<P>
   Ayala said that during his own ``party period,'' he rebelled
against the strict rules imposed upon him by his parents, Frank and
Gloria Ayala. Late in his promising Texas Golden Gloves amateur
career, Ayala burned out on boxing. He said he developed a fondness
for drinking beer. And whiskey. And he experimented with drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I've used 'em. I sure have,'' said Ayala, 29. ``I mean,
at the post office, that's all there was, man, believe it or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayala said he worked for the post office in 1990-91 on the
letter-sorter machine. His lunch break typically was topped off by
a marijuana cigarette.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was doing it even before I got into the post office,'' Ayala
said. ``I experimented with drugs. But I never used intravenous
drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayala also said he never has taken cocaine. Just that
``recreational'' use of weed.
</P>
<P>
   ``But all drugs are bad _ and beer and whiskey and cigarettes,''
Ayala said. ``A lot of the guys I hung out with are in prison, so I
could have been just like them. Easily, I could have been in jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to party. I remember going to a high school
graduation party that turned sour, where some guys started
fighting. We hid. We were standing behind a car and sure enough _
pow-pow-pow _ you hear gunshots. Everybody runs, and there was a
kid lying in the street. And this kid that got killed was an
innocent bystander who had just gotten off work. I've witnessed
that. That was scary. I just wanted to have fun. That ain't my kind
of fun. So, see you later, man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately, I had a good foundation.''
</P>
<P>
   Scared straight, Ayala returned to amateur boxing in time to
make a run at the 1992 Olympic Trials. He did not qualify for the
team to Barcelona, Spain, that summer but the rush of national
competition rekindled Ayala's love affair with boxing. In February
1992, Ayala married Leticha ``Letty'' Barrera. That fall, he turned
to professional boxing to support himself and his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Paulie came to us seven years ago, there was one thing I
told him. I'm sure he remembers,'' said Paul Reyes, head trainer at
the Boxing Management Inc. Gym in Fort Worth. ``And I hated to use
Stevie Cruz as an example.''
</P>
<P>
   Cruz, of Fort Worth, stunned the boxing world with an upset
15-round decision against unbeaten Irish hero Barry McGuigan to win
the WBA featherweight (126-pound) title on June 23, 1986, in Las
Vegas. Cruz celebrated long and hard and found it difficult to
return to his workout regimen. His reign unceremoniously was ended
nine months later, when ``Little Stevie'' was battered en route to
a 12th-round TKO defeat against Antonio Esparragoza in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stevie could have made a lot of money,'' Reyes said. ``He had
that Colgate smile. You couldn't help but like the kid. But he hung
around with the wrong people. That's what ruined him.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, I said to Paulie, `I heard you've been partying. I don't
care how good you are. You're doing that, staying out late, you're
going to be wasting our time and your time.' Since then, I've never
heard of him drinking or anything. He's dedicated himself to his
training and his family.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayala said he has not had an alcoholic drink since September
1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time I used drugs was way before that,'' said Ayala,
now fully settled and the father of a son, 7-year-old Paul II, and
daughter, Aleah, who was born seven weeks ago. ``That's why I'm
thankful to the Lord that I'm where I'm at. Basically, I had set my
goals when I turned pro, but we've been going through this by
faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayala's bid for his first world title ended in his only
professional loss, a sixth-round technical decision against
then-World Boxing Council bantamweight champion Joichiro Tatsuyoshi
in Japan on Aug. 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people said I wasn't going to get a title shot after
the Japanese fight,'' said Ayala (27-1, 12 KOs), the No. 2-ranked
WBA contender. ``I didn't believe that because, like I said, I'm
walking by faith. Not by sight. You don't know what God has in
store for you. You keep serving him and good things will happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glorifying the Lord. He's blessed me and my family. I've
got perfect health, that's what I've asked for. And just for a
chance to be the champion. And look. I was just hoping to fight
``any'' champion. But bam! You're fighting for a world title. Bam!
You're fighting Johnny Tapia. I mean, everything is just falling
into place, just by staying diligent and working hard in the gym.
And by serving Jesus.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Tapia also has been born-again, which is why Ayala is
not quick to pass judgment on boxing's Prodigal Son.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has skeletons in their closet,'' said Ayala, who
attends the nondenominational Teaching Word Faith Center in Fort
Worth. ``The thing about it, no matter what you've done, Jesus will
forgive you. That's why I don't judge people. Because I don't want
to be judged.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-99 0823EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990625.0060 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 08:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9143 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX     06-25 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T EXPLAIN GAMES, JUST X 'EM OUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A fervent prayer is offered here that at some point in the next
century, as they dig through the rubble that was 1999, they don't
find our ``TV Guide'' listings.
</P>
<P>
   I think we're going to have a hard time explaining the X Games.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-eight-plus hours of skysurfing, dirt jumping and assorted
other Sports Your Mom Wouldn't Let You Do.
</P>
<P>
   I don't get it, but then again, I'm not supposed to. I've never
busted a 900, I wore my last pair of Army camouflage pants 27 years
ago, and I don't have a single CD by the Dropkick Murphys.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN X Games, nevertheless, turn 5 years old today with the same
drooling silliness of any other 5-year-old, and with a list of
big-time sponsors that would turn even Jerry Jones an envious
green.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors, Disney, Sony, AT&AMP;T, Heineken, Visa and even that
loathsomely annoying Taco Bell chihuahua are among the X Games
sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect any Cadillac or Rogaine commercials. The X Games
are a blatantly created-for-TV pseudo-event designed to fill
network time during one of the slowest periods of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Their target is primarily that richest of marketing demographics
_ young males. Beyond the corporate sponsors, the X Games are
fueled by dozens of bicycle companies, equipment manufacturers,
clothing corporations and even the host cities themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, people actually bid to host the X Games.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco has the X-fest this year, which clearly proves
that effects from LSD can, indeed, linger into the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   As an ad for the X Games read, ``What better place to groove
than the land of Berserkely and North Beach, Acid tests and
six-hour jams, beat daddies and gone sisters ... Phone Tony
Bennett. Exhume Janis and Jerry ... because the city that put the
alt-dot in alternative will make X Games '99 the sweetest freak
show this summer.''
</P>
<P>
   The X-fest features competition in nine sports categories, some
of which are bicycle stunt riding, in-line skating, skateboarding,
climbing and the always-popular street luge.
</P>
<P>
   In street luge, competitors strap themselves to what appears to
be a loose association of ball bearings, and hurl themselves down
mountain roads at 70 mph with their brain pans roughly one-half
inch above the asphalt. The event also has introduced to the
vocabulary the endearing expression ``puke a wheel,'' which happens
to the luge and luger when the speeding rollers melt from the
intense heat.
</P>
<P>
   Extreme sports are nothing new and certainly not the
brainchildren of any cable TV executive. Ultra-marathon running and
the triathlon are considered extreme sports. No one would dispute
the athletic abilities of a triathlete or a true mountain climber.
</P>
<P>
   But what, beyond a stainless steel diaper and some Forrest
Gump-level brain activity, does it take to be a skysurfer? (One of
the sport's top competitors died in a jump last year).
</P>
<P>
   And what about skateboarding? Cool by ESPN, but still outlawed
in malls and church parking lots across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The top snowboarders at the 1998 Winter Olympics all had their
beginnings in skateboarding, and we saw how bogus that turned out
in Nagano, didn't we? Busted tricks, tasty buds, and a good zinc
oxide don't necessarily make for good spectator sport.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, at the X-fest, skateboarding and snowboarding thrive.
Organizers make the snow themselves, last time creating a giant
hill of shaved ice right on the ocean beach in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   In that future archaeological dig, I predict that scientists
will unearth skateboarding half-pipes and assume that they were a
crude early attempt to fly. In truth, we can verify that they are
merely modern attempts to escape homework.
</P>
<P>
   An alarming aside: The city of Escondido, Calif., has spent $2
million to build a 20,000-square-foot skating park, replete with
ramps, bowls and half-pipes.
</P>
<P>
   Let me guess. Is the mayor's name Jeff Spicoli?
</P>
<P>
   X Gamers might argue that theirs is a legitimate sporting
attraction. Right. Even the network that created them knows better.
Hence, ESPN's practice of taping everything, adding music and
over-caffeinated commentating, and showing it all on a two-day
delayed basis.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, according to the network, the fifth X Games will reach an
estimated 76 million households in the United States and another
171 million worldwide on ESPN International. Fans can buy X Games
skateboards, helmets, sunglasses, boxer shorts, video games and the
apparently must-have CD soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   I'll pass, thank you. But if they do exhume Janis and Jerry,
tell them not to puke a wheel in the street luge.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-99 0824EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
