<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 10:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9196 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CISNEROS-SCENE-$ADV27     06-25 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CISNEROS-SCENE-$ADV27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JUSTICE SYSTEM SLOGS ON TOWARD AN EVENTUAL TRIAL FOR CISNEROS
 &HT;    For release Sunday, June 27.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ U.S. District Judge Stanley Sporkin rocked back in
his loudly creaking chair, chewed on ice from his ever-present
plastic cup and fretted over how to find a jury in the coming trial
of former Housing and Urban Development Secretary Henry G.
Cisneros.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a pool of 300 people, you want to send out 2,500
notices?'' the judge asked incredulously last week, after the jury
clerk informed him that 90 percent of recipients either aren't
eligible to serve on a jury or don't bother to respond to a
summons.
</P>
<P>
   Sporkin has already delayed the trial's start until after Labor
Day after concluding that the search for jurors would be hopeless
during the summer, when Washingtonians are vacationing. Last week,
he suggested that federal marshals might be sent to the homes of
slackers.
</P>
<P>
   Seating a jury is just one more test for the judicial system as
it tackles the latest capital scandal to take center stage.
</P>
<P>
   Hopes for a speedy trial were abandoned long ago for Cisneros,
who was indicted in December 1997 on 18 counts of lying to the FBI
about paying roughly $250,000 to buy the silence of his ex-mistress
Linda Jones, then known by her married name of Medlar.
</P>
<P>
   The government charges that Cisneros had admitted to only about
$60,000 in payments when undergoing security checks before Clinton
appointed him to his cabinet. Cisneros has pleaded not guilty to
the charges.
</P>
<P>
   At a pretrial hearing last week, Sporkin looked out at more than
a dozen attorneys, including some of Washington's leading defense
lawyers and the prosecuting team of independent counsel David
Barrett, and despaired that a ``blizzard of motions'' threatened
even more delays.
</P>
<P>
   Costs of the prosecution have already soared, with the
independent counsel's spending already at $8.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't count the $500-an-hour billings from defense
lawyers led by Brendan V. Sullivan Jr.. Sullivan first tried to
have the case dismissed by arguing that courts have no right to
judge whether a presidential appointee tells the truth on
background forms. The pleading was rejected by an appeals court,
but not before delaying the trial for months.
</P>
<P>
   This focus in court last week was whether the prosecutors will
be able to use up to 34 tapes of Cisneros, secretly recorded by
Jones, discussing the payments to her and how to conceal them. The
defense teams wants the tapes to be excluded because Jones altered
the recordings, copying them and removing parts that might be
damaging to her. The judge is expected to rule soon on whether to
allow the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what happens on the tapes, the early skirmish makes
clear that the person most visibly on the hot seat at the Cisneros
trial will be Jones, his political fund-raiser when he was mayor of
San Antonio, who agreed in a plea bargain to testify against her
ex-lover.
</P>
<P>
   Now serving a 3 1/2-year sentence for bank fraud in a related
case, she told the saga of her downward spiral of divorce, mental
problems, financial ruin, and finally imprisonment for financing a
home in Lubbock, Texas, in the name of family members.
</P>
<P>
   Under unrelenting questioning from Sullivan about whether she
lied to the FBI, the IRS and to lawyers in a civil case, the
50-year-old Jones admitted again and again, ``Yes, sir.''
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros, who did not appear at the preliminary hearing, has
reconciled with his wife and is now chief executive officer of the
Spanish-language television network Univision, based in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
