   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   HOME-CLEANING _ WACO, Texas _ Christine Halvorson said she
believes mother knows best. Halvorson, who co-wrote ``Clean and
Simple'' (Yankee Publishing Inc.) with her husband, Kenneth M.
Sheldon, said the homemade cleaners that worked for her mother
still clean house. Includes recipes. (Kincheloe, Waco
Tribune-Herald) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   NATURAL-BEAUTY _ WACO, Texas _ The key to natural beauty may be
found in the kitchen, not the bathroom. Dig around in your kitchen
pantry and you'll probably find the ingredients to make an
assortment of natural homemade beauty products like
deep-moisturizing facial masks, minty hair conditioners and
honey-soothing cleansing scrubs. (Mays, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED
FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   WEDDING-BAIL _ AUSTIN _ ``What to do when 'I do' is 'I don't''
Let's do a story on bailing out of weddings, tagged to the Julia
Roberts movie coming out this summer about a bride who gets cold
feet. Will include advicde from marriage counselors, etc., about
why it's better not to marry the wrong person and save yourself a
divorce later, even though it means chaos for your family
temporarily. Also, practical tips on how to deal with the fallout.
the notes you send, the gifts you return, any money you could
possibly get back from the caterer, florist, etc. (is there
insurance for such a thing?) and how to make the best of a bad
situation. (Santos, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-ON-WOOD _ While it is true, I believe, that some outfits
do publish patterns for woodworking projects, it has always seemed
to me that patterns are intended for tailors, and not for
woodworkers. Our material cannot be cut with scissors. The fact is
that woodworkers often begin their projects with plans, but they
are plans that the woodworkers have drawn up themselves. (Warner,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED FOR SATURDAY.
</P>
<P>
   ECHAVESTE-PROFILE _ WASHINGTON _ Profile of Maria Echaveste, 45,
a ``sort of a one-woman band of diversity,'' the New Republic
noted. ``She's a Hispanic woman, a Jew, a corporate lawyer, a
Californian, a Texan, a New Yorker, a marathon runner, and a
gardener. Oh yes, she also knits.'' One thing she's not, though, is
a Southern good ol' boy _ which helped get her hired by Erskine
Bowles, the North Carolina businessman who was serving as Clinton's
chief of staff. (Dart, Cox News Service). 55. WITH PHOTOS and
LAYOUT. FOR SUNDAY
</P>
