   WITH
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH BRIEFS _ A column of health-related briefs from Cox News
Service.
</P>
<P>
   HYSTERECTOMY-ALTERNATIVE _ DAYTON, Ohio _ The question was never
if Lora Black would have a hysterectomy, but when. Medication
hadn't curbed the excessive menstrual bleeding that had made her
anemic and disrupted her life. Black's doctor told her about a new
alternative to surgery that uses a heated balloon to burn off the
uterine lining, which was her source of boundless bleeding. Doctors
expect this balloon therapy _ and some other new treatments for
different causes of heavy uterine bleeding _ will put a serious
dent in the 600,000 hysterectomies in this country every year.
(Lamb, Dayton Daily News). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   THEPILL _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Regardless of how much new technology
has arrived in gynecology, the first treatment for many causes of
uterine bleeding is still the birth-control pill. (Dayton Daily
News). 5.
</P>
<P>
   PILATES _ AUSTIN _ Pilates isn't new. But it's the newest
fitness trend to gain popularity _ poised to upend spinning and
Tae-bo as the Hot New Thing. (Santos, Austin American-Statesman).
15-18. WITH PHOTO. TECH-FITNESS _ Technology can help with your
physical fitness program. Sophisticated electronic gear can be used
to make sure your exercise regimen is efficient, to keep you
entertained while you work out and to keep track of your progress.
(Dayton daily News). 38. FOR SATURDAY
</P>
