<DOCNO> NYT19990625.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 10:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9204 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD26-COX     06-25 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Self-made plan can work for wood
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I have an e-mail query from a man who wants a
``pattern'' for a workbench with two drawers.
</P>
<P>
   While it is true, I believe, that some outfits do publish
patterns for woodworking projects, it has always seemed to me that
patterns are intended for tailors, and not for woodworkers. Our
material cannot be cut with scissors.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, our projects deal primarily with rectangles
and squares, things that are easily measured. As a result, plans
are more feasible than patterns.
</P>
<P>
   This leads nicely into my more or less standard rant about
plans, which examination of the archives indicates I have not
delivered recently.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I'll begin this one with a disclaimer: There is nothing
intrinsically evil or corrupting about commercially produced
woodworking plans. They can be helpful. But no woodworker, not even
an amateur, should be fearful of embarking on a project without
having a set of commercial plans in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   When I receive queries about where a reader can find a plan for
this or a plan for that, I always assume, perhaps wrongly, that the
question comes from someone who really hasn't a clue about working
wood. They are assuming, in my imagination at least, that one
always begins a woodworking project with a set of plans.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is that woodworkers often begin their projects with
plans, but they are plans that the woodworkers have drawn up
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   You don't need to be an artist or a master craftsman to make
your own plans. All you need is an understanding of wood and how
pieces of it are joined together to make furniture. This is not
rocket science. There are, admittedly, a great many ways to join
wood, but most of them are variations on a few standard techniques,
each of which is limited to a particular set of circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Let's explore this theory.
</P>
<P>
   A workbench is basically a table, is it not? It is constructed
in the same way you would build a coffee table, except for size and
allowance for necessary strength. Both of these articles are going
to have four legs, a top, and some means of holding the legs in
position and keeping the top on top of them. This sub-assembly, the
legs and the pieces that hold them together, could be called the
frame.
</P>
<P>
   Since the frame of a workbench will be subject to stresses
undreamt of by a coffee table, it would be prudent to add some more
members to strengthen it.
</P>
<P>
   Very well, let's look at some tables. Doubtless there are some
within view right now. Most of them will have good-size pieces of
wood running between the legs, right under the top. These perform
not only the task of keeping the legs where they belong, but give
the top something to rest upon.
</P>
<P>
   For the greater strength required by a workbench, it would be a
good idea to repeat this connecting framework farther down the
legs, a foot or so off the floor. No doubt you've seen tables
constructed this way.
</P>
<P>
   The ways in which the legs and the connecting pieces can be
connected are dictated by a basic trait of wood: It moves. It moves
with the seasons, swelling with the wet summer and shrinking in the
dry winter. It swells and shrinks across the grain. If you look at
your nearby table, you will see that the grain on the legs is
running vertically and the grain on the connecting members runs
horizontally.
</P>
<P>
   This is a cross-grain connection, and it must be dealt with
accordingly, or the construction will fail.
</P>
<P>
   I can hear you now _ ``Hey, buddy, I just wanna build a
workbench. I don't need no stinkin' theory.'' In that case, you've
come to the wrong place _ Hammers, 10-Penny Nails and Basic Oaths
are two doors down. The rest of you, come back next week, same
time, same place.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-99 1048EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
