<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990625.0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 10:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9206 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEDDING-BAIL26-COX     06-25 1474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEDDING-BAIL26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What to do when you have to say `I don't'
 &HT;    By Michele Chan Santos
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ He didn't see it coming.
</P>
<P>
   Mark and his fiancee dated for 4 1/2 years and had been engaged
for 1 1/2 years. They finished each other's sentences and were so
affectionate that strangers would come up to them in restaurants
and say, ``You two look so in love.''
</P>
<P>
   The wedding was going to be huge, a fairy-tale extravaganza with
more than 300 guests. Her dress was ready; the caterer, band,
photographer and florist were all hired. The cake was ordered, and
he had tickets for their honeymoon in hand, a cruise to St. Thomas,
Jamaica and Mexico. The invitations had been addressed by a
calligrapher and were ready to mail.
</P>
<P>
   They were eight weeks away from the day of the ceremony when she
called it off.
</P>
<P>
   It happened last summer, but Mark is still hurting. He was 26
then, and she was 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can compare it to a death,'' he says, ``but it's worse
because the person chooses not to be in your life.''
</P>
<P>
   It's high season for weddings this month, and from now through
October, hundreds of couples will be making vows, clinking
champagne glasses, cutting cake and dancing.
</P>
<P>
   But some people's weddings never make it to ``I do.'' The bride
or groom, or both, see their small doubts mushrooming into larger
ones, until suddenly they realize they can't go through with it.
Everyone seems to know a story of a wedding that didn't happen.
It's enough of a trend that a new movie, ``Runaway Bride,'' slated
for release July 30, stars Julia Roberts as a bride who leaves
three grooms at the altar. Richard Gere plays a reporter who wants
to write a story about her and ends up falling in love.
</P>
<P>
   Although the movie has a happy ending, most real-life canceled
weddings are messy: Bruised feelings, public humiliation and dashed
expectations quickly end a relationship that probably wasn't meant
to be.
</P>
<P>
   Mark's girlfriend called off their wedding because she felt she
lost her independence when she was with him, she says. The couple
had gone to college together in Austin, and after graduation she
decided she wanted to move to Louisiana. Four months before their
wedding, she moved. The plan was that he would stay in Austin and
live with his parents to save money; after their wedding, he would
join her.
</P>
<P>
   After she left, she made some discoveries. She liked being
independent, making new friends, living on her own. She wanted to
explore her new identity, and it didn't include being married to
him.
</P>
<P>
   Mark says he has finally come to terms with her decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``She didn't know who she was or what she wanted,'' he says.
``Even though we thought we were prepared, we weren't.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk with men or women whose weddings were called off at the
last minute, and one theme emerges: Horrifying as it is to call off
a big event, it's not nearly as terrible as a bad marriage. Though
it may be expensive and painful to end things, it's usually the
right decision. Still, it's embarrassing enough that those
interviewed for this story didn't want their names used.
</P>
<P>
   Big doubts
</P>
<P>
   It was more than 10 years ago, but Robert hasn't forgotten how
much hurt he caused.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since his engagement, he had been plagued with doubts about
his relationship with his fiancee. The wedding-planning process had
smothered him, and he was scared.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to think clearly when all this stuff is going on,''
he says. The dress, the cake, the ceremony, the music _ it was all
overwhelming. ``From the first moment, it was nothing but
preparation. The couple _ us _ got swallowed up into this raging
F-5 tornado of preparation. It was very distressing.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a week before the wedding day, he called it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't act very courageously,'' he says. ``I should
have acted much earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   His girlfriend was devastated, her family deeply hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, Robert says he and his fiancee didn't know one
another well enough. He doesn't regret his decision, just its
timing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept waiting for myself to get comfortable,'' he says. ``I
thought all of my reservations would disappear. They didn't.'' They
had not known each other very long, he says, and he didn't think
they knew each other well enough to be married.
</P>
<P>
   The woman's parents did the damage control, returning the gifts,
sending out announcements.
</P>
<P>
   He advises engaged couples not to dismiss their doubts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do not think that they are going to go away, especially if you
don't talk about them. It really is better to back out or air those
serious doubts,'' he says. ``Start dissecting it, figure out what's
at the root of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk it through early
</P>
<P>
   Diana Latham, director of Advanced Counseling Service in Austin,
has been conducting premarital counseling sessions with couples for
25 years. She suggests that engaged couples take advantage of
premarital sessions soon after their engagement _ and before
beginning any of the major planning for a large-scale wedding. Many
religious institutions offer premarital counseling, and some
require it.
</P>
<P>
   Couples who opt for a more secular route can consult a
therapist. Latham says that if you work for a company with an
employee assistance program, it may cover the fee for premarital
counseling.
</P>
<P>
   The age of each partner isn't necessarily a predictor of
happiness _ as many younger couples as older couples have
successful marriages _ but how long they have known one another
does matter, Latham says. The longer they have known each other,
the better, and it's also healthier if both of them have lived away
from their parents for a while. One couple Latham knows found their
marriage breaking apart when the woman was constantly leaving town
to visit her parents.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, a couple goes through counseling smoothly, only to
find they need it again later. Mark and his fiancee went through
counseling ``with flying colors,'' he says, but still didn't marry.
</P>
<P>
   If you do find yourself having serious doubts right before the
wedding, make an appointment with a therapist as soon as possible,
Latham says.
</P>
<P>
   It's useful to have a third party to hear your worries, and you
need to pay attention to your concerns, and not dismiss them as
``cold feet,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Making the best of a bad situation
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes a canceled wedding can still lead to fond memories.
</P>
<P>
   Amy was barely 21 when she was supposed to get married. She and
her fiance had planned a trip to Las Vegas with her parents,
sister, and her two best friends. They purchased the nonrefundable
tickets and reserved hotel rooms. Everyone took time off from work
or school to go, and they were all set to make the trip, planning
to hold the wedding in a Vegas chapel.
</P>
<P>
   Except Amy wasn't ready. ``I knew I didn't want to do it,'' she
says now, ``but I was afraid to call it off. We got really great
prices on the tickets, and I didn't want to say anything. I almost
went through with it because I was too afraid. I thought my parents
were going to kill me.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than three weeks before the trip, she got up the nerve to
tell her fiance, and her family, that she didn't want to get
married.
</P>
<P>
   Although her fiance was upset, her family and friends took the
news well. In fact, Amy, her parents, her sister and her friends
went ahead with the trip to Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a fabulous time,'' Amy says. ``It was all pretty
wild.''
</P>
<P>
   She still has the dress, and she isn't married. She doesn't have
any regrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scariest thing was just getting up the courage to say, 'I
don't want to do it,' `` she says. ``Anybody that has second
thoughts, if they are serious, they should back out.''
</P>
<P>
   Questions engaged couples should ask themselves:
</P>
<P>
   What are our values?
</P>
<P>
   Why are we getting married?
</P>
<P>
   Do we have compatible goals? Where do we want to be in 10 years?
</P>
<P>
   Have we discussed our finances? Do we agree on spending habits?
On a system for money management? Is one of us entering the
marriage in debt? How will we handle the debt?
</P>
<P>
   Where are we going to live?
</P>
<P>
   What does marriage mean to us?
</P>
<P>
   Do we want to have children?
</P>
<P>
   If we were not raised in the same faith, how will we handle
that? What religion will we raise our children in?
</P>
<P>
   Do my parents accept him? Do his parents accept me?
</P>
<P>
   Do we have something in common, a hobby, sport or interest, that
we enjoy in our spare time?
</P>
<P>
   Do we have friends in common?
</P>
<P>
   What ideas do we have about the roles of husbands and wives: Is
he going to expect me to do all the housework; do I expect him to
make more money?
</P>
<P>
   Are we both ready to make a commitment?
</P>
<P>
   Source: Diana Latham, director of Advanced Counseling Service in
Austin
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
