<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ Put simply, Texas needs tougher
driving standards and lawmakers more in touch with their state.
(Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald)
MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   MINTER-COLUMN _ FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ One of the several
frustrations of senior citizenship is being unable to understand
newspaper comics, which, in addition to being nonsensical, require
a magnifying glass to decipher the small print in
postage-stamp-size panels. (Jim Minter is a former editor of The
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   JOURNAL-KOSOVO _ PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ It took our landlord's
buddy about three seconds to figure out why someone tried to break
into our apartment last week, busting the lock and our composure in
the process. Shpetim checked the broken lock, then found something
I hadn't noticed _ a small piece of wood taped to the outside of
the door above my eye line, with the name of a Serbian family
printed in pencil. The previous evening, after we discovered the
break-in attempt, we had been sufficiently nervous to look for
help. NATO troops headquartered across the street had pronounced
repeatedly their mission to provide security for all the people of
Kosovo. That very day NATO announced it had taken over police
powers, so my colleague and I sharing this apartment figured they
could swing a patrol down our street. If the troops didn't care
much about a couple of western journalists, surely they would worry
about Serbian families we found also had been targeted in our
building. Some already were leaving. Others were distraught with
fear. Wrong assumption. (Kunstel, Cox News Service). FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (i) International and (c) Commentary categories.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ It is hard to imagine a much tougher mission in
rehabilitation than trying to buff the image of Sen. Joseph
McCarthy, the grandstanding Red-baiter of the 1950s. But the
historians and other wordsmiths of the cultural right have lately
taken up the task like manic elves. (Tom Teepen is national
correspondent for Cox Newspapers.) MOVED THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ Worldwide, tourist sites are beginning to
become inundated with people like me. I must confess it's not a
good thing. (Howard Kleinberg is a columnist for Cox News Service.)
MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ (Andy Glass is a columnist for Cox News Service
in the Washington bureau.) MOVED THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
