r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINTER-COLUMN26-COX     06-25 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nowadays, comics are a joke
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ One of the several frustrations of senior
citizenship is being unable to understand newspaper comics, which,
in addition to being nonsensical, require a magnifying glass to
decipher the small print in postage-stamp-size panels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you figure out the comics?'' I asked my wife. Being a
former child bride and not yet eligible for Medicare, I thought she
might understand contemporary humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some days I get the point in `Baby Blues' and `Herman,' but
most of the others are a puzzle,'' she admitted. ``They're as
incomprehensible as television commercials.''
</P>
<P>
   I liked the comics when they were called funny papers and you
couldn't cover up three separate strips with your palm and four
fingers. I miss Dick Tracy and his two-way wrist radio, a truly
miraculous means of communication that somehow preceded invention
of the computer chip. It was as far out as Flash Gordon's
spaceship.
</P>
<P>
   I miss ``Smilin' Jack,'' ``Steve Canyon'' and ``Little Orphan
Annie,'' although I was rather late in life realizing Daddy
Warbucks made his fortune in World War I profiteering. Social
issues infiltrated the comics long before ``Doonesbury.''
</P>
<P>
   I'd enjoy another Sunday with the Katzenjammer Kids and the
Gumps, back when a single comic took up half a page and you didn't
have to be an Ivy League egghead to figure out what it was about.
</P>
<P>
   Like many children of my generation, I learned to read by having
the funny papers read to me. Later I moved on to the sports
section, then the front page and eventually to the editorial page.
Most of what I know comes from reading newspapers, and limited as I
am, I wonder if I'd be any better off if surfing the Internet had
been an option.
</P>
<P>
   One of my advantages was being able to read the funny papers in
three different newspapers. We took the Georgian. One grandmother
took The Atlanta Journal, and one took The Atlanta Constitution,
all within walking distance. One of my favorite strips ran in the
Georgian, a Hearst newspaper, when Atlanta was a three-newspaper
town. I was particularly fond of Secret Agent X-9, who was always
getting into perilous situations.
</P>
<P>
   X-9 had been captured by very bad people. He was hanging from a
rock cliff with his hands and feet tied together when the Georgian
hit on hard times and went out of my life. I stayed awake nights
worrying about Secret Agent X-9.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a practice rather common in the depressed rural South
I was able to enjoy the Georgian's comics section long after the
newspaper was extinct. Our across-the-road neighbors, in an attempt
to brighten their three-room cabin, and to keep winter winds from
blowing through cracks, had papered a bedroom wall with Sunday
color comics from the Georgian. I spent many a pleasant afternoon
reading those walls.
</P>
<P>
   I still had a lot to learn about comics when my grown-up job
included picking the ones that ran in the newspaper. Newspapers buy
comics from syndicate salesmen, a breed not unlike old-time
drummers who traveled back roads peddling their wares to country
storekeepers. Syndicate salesmen try to persuade editors to throw
out some other salesman's comic and buy theirs. They always have a
new strip that's on the cutting edge.
</P>
<P>
   According to their sales pitch, if you don't buy it you risk
becoming a national laughingstock and seeing your newspaper go out
of business. If you do buy, you have to throw out one of the old
comics to make room, and that gets upset readers on the phone.
Editors, by nature very nervous people, are afraid to buy a new
comic, and afraid not to.
</P>
<P>
   They often ask advice from associates. When I was a relatively
youthful sportswriter, our editor invited me to evaluate a new
comic he was considering. I told him nobody in the United States
would be interested in a Cockney ne'er-do-well fussing with his
wife and guzzling beer in an English pub. We just wouldn't get it.
``Andy Capp'' turned out to be one of the most popular comics ever
to appear in The Atlanta Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the comics I bought on my tour at the
Journal-Constitution, only one survives. It's ``Cathy.''
``Peanuts'' and ``Nancy'' preceded me. ``Mary Worth'' is about the
same age as Martha Washington.
</P>
<P>
   When a syndicate man (excuse me, but I never met a syndicate
woman) came to peddle ``Cathy,'' I wasn't interested. I thought it
poorly drawn and humorless. I wasn't about to put ``Cathy'' in the
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   My secretary-assistant, Jean Stanley, thought otherwise. She
liked ``Cathy.'' Since Miss Stanley was such a good secretary, so
diligent at keeping reporters' expense reports honest, and keeping
me out of trouble, I decided what the heck. If Miss Stanley wanted
``Cathy'' in the newspaper, we'd put ``Cathy'' in the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   It's obvious I'm as out-of-date as ``Dick Tracy,'' ``Smilin'
Jack,'' ``Little Orphan Annie'' and the Gump boys. But I'd still
like to know whatever happened to Secret Agent X-9.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Minter is a former editor of The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
