<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Citified nannies ignore rest of Texas in killing speed-limit
boost
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ The recent legislative session showed again that
Texas lawmakers are more in touch with urban sprawl and traffic
jams than with cowboys and wide-open spaces.
</P>
<P>
   A reasonable bill to raise speed limits on selected Texas
highways failed to win the approval of Texas' urbanized,
homogenized lawmakers who have more in common with pasty-faced,
Eastern safety nannies than with the land of their more robust
ancestors.
</P>
<P>
   This bred-down flock of quivering lawmakers is more familiar
with traffic lights and skyscrapers than with stars at night big
and bright or prairie skies wide and high.
</P>
<P>
   More than 50 years ago, Texas' population began to shift from
the wide-open spaces of its rural heritage to the cities. For most
of Texas' history, rural Texas was heavily represented in the Texas
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   The tables have turned. Now a majority of citified Texas
lawmakers are more likely to adopt positions in tune with New York
City than they are to represent vast stretches of their own state.
</P>
<P>
   Just because Texas' heavily urban clusters elect the majority of
the state's legislators does not mean that the rest of the state,
which is still larger than any European nation, has disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   On behalf of all those Texans who live where roads run from
horizon to horizon, a lawmaker from West Texas introduced a bill
this past session to allow the raising of speed limits from 75 to
80 in nonurban areas.
</P>
<P>
   The filing of that bill was like firing a 30-30 carbine in the
middle of a herd of bedded-down longhorns. Texas' nervous
safety-nanny delegation screamed, ``Speed kills'' and stampeded off
in a cloud of Gucci loafer tassels to assure urban constituents
that this bill would never become law.
</P>
<P>
   The bill died, of course, which was reason for Texas' Ralph
Nader clones to celebrate with pizza and ice cream, two products
that assuredly kill more Americans annually than are killed due to
posted speed limits.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the facts. The most comprehensive study on speed limits
in 30 years found that speed limits had no meaningful impact on
traffic safety. The study, conducted under the supervision of the
Federal Highway Administration, measured and monitored driver
response to speed limits at 247 locations across the United States
for five years.
</P>
<P>
   After undergoing rigorous peer review, the study showed that
posted speed limits had virtually no influence on driver behavior
or accident rates.
</P>
<P>
   Speed limits have a lot to do with handing out expensive
speeding tickets, but practically nothing to do with safety.
</P>
<P>
   Motorists are not suicidal by nature. Research shows that 85
percent of motorists drive at a speed that is safe for the
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly without exception, American highways are engineered to
safely handle speeds far in excess of posted speed limits. Speed
limits should be set based on an engineering study of the
particular roads and other conditions, not an arbitrary and
needlessly low number.
</P>
<P>
   Natural traffic flow invariably exceeds posted speed limits.
When that happens, slower motorists become a safety hazard.
</P>
<P>
   It's rare that speed alone causes traffic accidents. More often
accidents are caused by bad drivers who use bad judgment by
tailgating, cutting off cars, passing on hills and curves,
recklessly changing lanes or failing to pay attention.
</P>
<P>
   Since Congress raised the one-size-fits-all 55 mph national
speed limit, highway fatalities nationwide have dropped by hundreds
rather than increase by the predicted thousands.
</P>
<P>
   Texas needs tougher driving standards and lawmakers more in
touch with their state.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor at the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: rnethaway(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
