A9213 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSICROW26-COX     06-25 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSICROW26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Country museum move new blow to Music Row
 &HT;    By Jane DuBose
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ For more than 30 years, the museum housing
Elvis Presley's 1960 gold Cadillac and Hank Williams' jackets has
been a mainstay of this city's Music Row.
</P>
<P>
   But those days are numbered, and the move of the Country Music
Hall of Fame to downtown Nashville is planned at a time when
country music and Nashville tourism are at a crossroads.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years, there's been a love-hate relationship between the
recording companies and the tourists,'' says Jim Cook, who owns a
hat shop near the Hall of Fame. ``In a way, they just haven't
wanted to be bothered with tourists.''
</P>
<P>
   If Cook is right, the executives of country music recording
labels may have their wish. At least a dozen tourist shops lining
Demonbreun Avenue have closed in the past two years, and those
remaining have seen significant drops in business.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, the city's downtown area just a few blocks away
has been thriving with new theme restaurants, the 3-year-old
Nashville Arena and other attractions.
</P>
<P>
   The new $37 million Hall of Fame will open near the arena in a
city redevelopment district in what was once the fading Lower
Broadway area. The four-story museum will include about 1,000
artifacts and will house a glass-enclosed office where visitors can
see archivists, recording artists and other staff at work
preserving country music's history.
</P>
<P>
   The Country Music Association, which held the museum
groundbreaking ceremony last week, is raising $15 million from
private donors and will contribute $5 million more when it sells
its old property. The rest is coming from city commitments of
industrial development bonds and proceeds from hotel-motel taxes.
The public commitment is much less than that for the Rock and Roll
Hall of Fame in Cleveland, says Kyle Young, director of the Country
Music Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   The development site will also feature a Hilton hotel opening
next year, a new park and an 86-unit apartment building in a
converted fire station, said Gerald Nicely, who heads Nashville's
redevelopment agency.
</P>
<P>
   The relocated Hall of Fame is scheduled to open in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Young said the museum is not worried about leaving Music Row.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many places left before us,'' he said, adding that a new and
expanded museum will boost country music more than staying put in
the old neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   While owners of small shop owners _ and even the annual County
Music Fan Fair _ have suffered the local tourism downturn, the Hall
of Fame itself has not been immune. In the 1980s, the museum
attracted about 500,000 people a year; now there's about 190,000.
Young expects that to increase to 550,000 at the new location,
despite higher ticket prices.
</P>
<P>
   Leo Waters, a Nashville city councilman representing Music Row,
said the demise of the storefronts has come at a time when tourism
is changing for the city. Bus tours and family groups diminished
when Opryland theme park closed two years ago. At the same time,
Branson, Mo., Pigeon Forge, Tenn., and Myrtle Beach, S.C., began
offering more live entertainment venues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we're in a down cycle,'' Waters said. ``But I see
some positive things happening. A study from the city showed this
is a transition time, and we can look for some specialty retail,
boutique shops and a combination of business/office on Music Row in
the future.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the bright spots for Music Row is an expected 2001
opening of a Ritz-Carlton hotel developed by Starstruck
Entertainment, owned by entertainer Reba McEntire. And the City
Council will be asked in July to approve $3.5 million in street
improvements to the area.
</P>
<P>
   As the landscape changes, Waters says it's important for
Nashville to market its uniqueness. Nowhere else is country music
recorded in such volumes _ thus the industry side of Music Row
should be heavily promoted, as well as the arena, the Ryman
Auditorium and the Tennessee Titans football team.
</P>
<P>
   Cook says his hat business is evaluating whether to move from
the Music Row area.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sad thing'' he said. ``Customers come in and ask what's
happened. We're losing the people who made us what we are.''
</P>
<P>
   But Young has another take on the change.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city is doing this, and we need to, too. Every once in a
while, you have to refresh your image.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
