<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 11:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9227 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-CLEANING-COX     06-25 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-CLEANING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mom's recipes for cleaners still shine
 &HT;    By Amy Kincheloe
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Christine Halvorson said she believes mother knows
best.
</P>
<P>
   Halvorson, who co-wrote ``Clean and Simple'' (Yankee Publishing
Inc.) with her husband, Kenneth M. Sheldon, said the homemade
cleaners from her mother's day are still around the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the commercial products are the same as the homemade
cleaners except they just have fancy names and added colors and
smells,'' sheHalvorson said. ``That all adds to the cost, and they
are less natural than the homemade cleaners.''
</P>
<P>
   Halvorson said items found around the home work well as
cleaners.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried out all of the recipes in the book, and our theory is
if you have these five con (oven cleaner, general-purpose cleaner,
easy scrub, heavy-duty disinfectant cleaner and furniture polish)
in your home, you can keep it clean,'' sheHalvorson said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Halvorson's homemade cleaners consist of at least one of
the following: water, lemon juice, dishwashin ol and baking soda,
all of which are fairly inexpensive.
</P>
<P>
   But do they work? Products that work
</P>
<P>
   ``Baking soda and vinegar make a great cleaning combination
(when mixed together on the cleaning site),'' sheHalvorson said.
``And baking soda itself is a great light abrasive that doesn't
scratch. Borax has fallen out of favor, but my mother used it and
I'm finding that it works well, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Halvorson said the natural aspect of th ade cleaners is a
definite plus.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do save money and time, and you're not contributing to the
landfills (with commercial cleaner bottles),'' sheHalvorson said.
``The closer you can get to natural products, the better. At least
you know what you've got in front of you _ it's a pure thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Household and Institutional Products Information
Council, an organization representing companies that manufacture
household and institutional care and cleaning products, doesn't
agree with the use of alternative cleaning products.
</P>
<P>
   According to information released by the organization:
``Unfortunately, natural does not mean safe or `nontoxic.' Most
chemical (natural or synthetic) substances, including vinegar,
borax, baking soda and castile soap, have a dose at which they will
cause a toxic response.''
</P>
<P>
   Halvor the recipes for her home cleaners are exact and have not
produced any chemical reactions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The measurements are precise for optimum cleaning,''
sheHalvorson said.
</P>
<P>
   Always check for warnings on the containers of the ingredients
used for home mixtures. For example, the label on a bottle of
American Fare Ammonia clearly states: ``Do not mix with chlorine
bleach leaner. Combining chemicals can produce poison gas _ results
can be fatal.'' For safety
</P>
<P>
   Also, for safety's sake, Halvorson advises people to label their
homemade cleaners.
</P>
<P>
   ``We say it several times throughout the book,'' sheHalvorson
said. ``You don't want to put your homemade concoction in a bottle
without a label. These cleaners are like commercial cleaners and
should be kept under and key and out of a child's reach.''
</P>
<P>
   Halvorson also suggests listin ipe on the container in case of
accidental ingestion by a child and also just to have the recipe
handy the next time a batch needs to be made.
</P>
<P>
   SheHalvorson added, ``It's not to say commercial cleaners don't
rival these, but if you can save a little money and help the
environment, why not?''
</P>
<P>
   MAKE YOUR OWN
</P>
<P>
   Here are some recipes for homemade cleaners from Clean and
Simple by Christine Halvorson and Kenneth M. Sheldon.
</P>
<P>
   OVEN CLEANER
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons dishwashing liquid
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons borax
</P>
<P>
   0.25 cup ammonia
</P>
<P>
   1.5 cups warm water
</P>
<P>
   Mix the ingredients together, apply to oven spills and let sit
for 20 to 30 minutes. Scrub with an abrasive nylon-backed sponge
and rinse well.
</P>
<P>
   GENERAL-PURPOSE CLEANER
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon borax
</P>
<P>
   0.5 teaspoon washing soda
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vinegar
</P>
<P>
   0.25 teaspoon dishwashing liquid
</P>
<P>
   2 cups hot water
</P>
<P>
   Combine all of the ingredients. If you don't have washing soda
(generally found in the laundry section of super- markets), use 1
teaspoon baking soda instead. For a more pleasant smell, use lemon
juice instead of vinegar. Be sure to label the bottle accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   EASY SCRUB
</P>
<P>
   0.75 cup baking soda
</P>
<P>
   0.25 cup borax
</P>
<P>
   Dishwashing liquid
</P>
<P>
   Combine the baking soda and borax. Mix in enough dishwashing
liquid to make a smooth paste. If you prefer a pleasant smell, add
1/4 teaspoon lemon juice to the paste.
</P>
<P>
   HEAVY-DUTY DISINFECTANT CLEANER
</P>
<P>
   0.25 cup powdered laundry detergent
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon borax
</P>
<P>
   0.75 cup of hot water
</P>
<P>
   0.25 cup pine oil or pine-based cleaner
</P>
<P>
   Slowly stir the detergent and borax into the water to dissolve.
Add the pine oil (available at hardware stores and supermarkets)
and mix well. For bathroom cleaning, use the mixture full strength.
In the kitchen, dilute with water.
</P>
<P>
   FURNITURE POLISH
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vinegar or lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon boiled linseed oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon turpentine
</P>
<P>
   Combine the ingredients in a glass jar with a tight-fitting lid
and shake until blended. Dampen a cloth with cold water and wring
it out until it's as dry as you can get it. Saturate the cloth with
the mixture and apply sparingly to a small area at a time. Let dry
for 30 minutes, then polish with a soft cloth. Note that this
mixture gets gummy as it sits, so make just enough for one day's
work.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS CLEANER
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons ammonia
</P>
<P>
   0.5 cup alcohol
</P>
<P>
   0.25 teaspoon dishwashing liquid
</P>
<P>
   A few drops blue food coloring
</P>
<P>
   Water
</P>
<P>
   Combine the ammonia, alcohol, dishwashing liquid and food
coloring,then add enough water to make 1 quart.
</P>
<P>
   If you prefer a non-ammoniated cleaner, substitute 3 tablespoons
vinegar or lemon juice for the ammonia. CUTLINES Staff photos _
Kelly Lemons KL 2 cleaning These are your mother's cleaning
products: dishwashing liquid, baking soda, vinegar, ammonia,
bleach, borax and alcohol. They can beused to make cleaning
products that are cheaper and less harmful to the environment than
store-bought products, according to one author. KL 1cleaning 24c
Always label homemade cleaning products for easy identification and
for safety's sake. KL 5cleaning 24c Lemon juice is a natural way to
add a pleasant smell to homemade cleaning products. KL 6cleaning
24c Baking soda and vinegar make a great cleaning combination when
mixed together on the cleaning site.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
