</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-DADDY (San Francisco) _ After victimizing dozens in
previous movies with his dufus-bullyboy assaults, ``Big Daddy''
finds Adam Sandler playing the apologist, going the Wallace Beery,
Charlie Chaplin route and stretching his aimless man-child persona
around the comic potential of being a ``dad.'' By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   TV-VEGGIETALES (Albany, N.Y.) _ This is the best television show
not on television, a kids program that touches on religious themes
but is as cool as ``Davey and Goliath'' was not. Using computer
animation, writing that is sharper than most adult shows and humor
far funnier than the average sitcom, ``VeggieTales'' fills a vacuum
for moral entertainment. But it's only available on video. By MARK
McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-VIOLIN (Undated) _ ``The Red Violin'' is tough to
classify. Call it an epic, but that would imply it's long. Call it
an art film, but that would imply it's dull. You could call it a
mystery, too. ``The Red Violin'' is all of that, but it's also a
breathless fable covering three centuries in the life of a single,
perfect instrument. By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   PACIFICA-RADIO (Berkeley, Calif.) _ When Pacifica Radio
Foundation executive director Lynn Chadwick meets with her board of
directors this weekend, she will likely be asked to explain the
battle raging at KPFA, the network's Berkeley flagship station
founded in 1949 on principles of pacifism. By ROBERT SELNA.
