<P>
   KILLER-KIDS (Houston) _ He's 34 now, with two kids of his own.
But 18 years ago, Christopher Carson was ``the worst of the
worst,'' according to the lawyer who prosecuted him for two
murders. Carson is out of prison now, and in an interview he talks
about why young people kill. So did two other young killers who
grew to maturity in prison. Their conclusion: It's not just video
games. By ALLAN TURNER. (Photos available on NYT database.) (Filed
Thursday.)
</P>
<P>
   KILLER-KIDS-EXPERTS (Undated) _ Homicide is the second leading
cause of death for minors nationwide. That many of those crimes
were committed by the victims' peers is a given, experts say. ``In
1974, we almost never saw a case involving a gun,'' said Elizabeth
Godwin, a 25-year prosecutor in Harris County, Texas. ``Now it's
completely off the map. ... Often kids don't have a real idea of
morally what's right or wrong, but they are streetwise about what's
legal.'' By ALLAN TURNER. (Filed Thursday.)
</P>
<P>
   KEFAUVER-RECALLED (Albany, N.Y.) _ A surprisingly innocent
America was shocked to discover in the 1950s that there was
organized crime rampant in this country. City after city was
revealed to have entrenched gambling interests linked to gangsters,
aided and abetted by corrupt police and compromised politicians.
The vehicle for this revelation was the Kefauver Crime
Investigation Committee, a select group of U.S. senators headed by
Tennessee Democrat Estes Kefauver. By FRED LeBRUN.
</P>
