<DOCNO> NYT19990625.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 12:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9278 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLLECT-BEANIES-KAN &LR;      06-25 1238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLECT-BEANIES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLECTING BEANIE BABIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAMES A. FUSSELL  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hmm, now where have we seen this before? Hot toys in hundreds of
colorful variations, each with its own personality, name and
oh-so-collectible identity.
</P>
<P>
   Can you say Beanie Babies?
</P>
<P>
   Other toy companies can. Fueled by the phenomenal success of the
ubiquitous bean bag toys, they're seeking success with some of the
same marketing techniques that turned Beanies into a cuddly money
machine.`
</P>
<P>
   Recognize these strategies?
</P>
<P>
   - Instead of making just one style of toy, make more than 100,
and feature them in a collect-them-all series.
</P>
<P>
   - Introduce sought-after limited ``special editions.''
</P>
<P>
   - ``Retire'' early versions to ratchet up the desire.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Crazy Bones, a popular new game aimed at elementary school
children that uses the same marketing techniques. The game pieces _
often called ``Bones'' or ``Go-Gos'' _ consist of more than 100
miniature, plastic figures to play with, collect, trade and win.
The bones, slightly larger than standard marbles, come in about 90
different colors, and are shaped to fit their names. (A bone named
``Frenchie'' looks like a bag of French fries, while ``Gu-Gu
Ga-Ga'' resembles a little baby bottle.) Each $2 pack contains
three to five bones, but the opaque packages prevent collectors
from seeing what pieces they're buying. And don't look now, kids,
but the first series of 60 original Bones has just been retired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom, these are going to be as big as Beanie Babies,'' one
excited child told his mother at a recent Crazy Bones night
organized at Zainy Brainy, a local toy store in South Overland
Park.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Pokemon (say poke-ee-mohn) toys. Pokemon _ a group
of 150 small, colorful cartoon characters, each with its own
personality, name and collectible identity, are seemingly
everywhere these days. Besides being the subject of a children's
cartoon, the characters also appear in a video game and as various
other toys. Hasbro, which manufacturers Pokemon toys, makes
products ranging from super balls, battlepacks and blasters to
electronic figures, plush toys and trading cards.
</P>
<P>
   The Pokemon motto: ``Gotta catch em all!''
</P>
<P>
   Lots of luck. Certain plush toys are often in short supply, and
some of the trading cards already have been retired.
</P>
<P>
   What's going on in toyland?
</P>
<P>
   Cliff Annicelli, the associate editor of Playthings, a magazine
that tracks the toy industry, thinks he knows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Collectibility is definitely one of the most popular ways for
toy companies to get consumers buying their products as often as
possible,'' Annicelli said. ``It's not a new phenomenon; there have
always been collectible toys. But the difference now is that the
manufacturers are a lot more overt about marketing things, about
being collectible. In the past, say with action figures, you had to
have six or eight to have a good play experience. Now you have to
collect all the Beanie Babies, or all the Crazy Bones or all the
Pokemon. The new wrinkle is toy companies retiring their toys.''
</P>
<P>
   Retired toys sell for much more than their original asking
price. For example, Ty Inc. sells its basic Beanie Baby for $6 or
$7. But recently retired Beanies bring from $15 to $50, with the
rarest fetching more than a thousand on Internet auction sites.
</P>
<P>
   What does this new strategy mean?
</P>
<P>
   ``It means,'' Annicelli said, ``that now, as well as being
collectible, certain toys will only be availible in limited numbers
or for a limited amount of time. That causes a feeling that if you
are going to collect these toys you better collect them now, or it
will be your last change. It creates a sense of urgency in the
collector.''
</P>
<P>
   Some parents called the marketing techniques innocuous, others
disagreed. Julianne Graves, a Kansas City mother of two, called the
techniques ``manipulative.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It just seems to me that toymakers try less to make good
products than to create these engineered sensations,'' she said.
``And that kind of bothers me.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter, said Jay Winter, a Southern California toy analyst.
You'll see more of the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way to sell something,'' he said. ``Make hundreds
of them, get everybody competing for them, then, wham! Limit their
numbers. It's human nature. It's pushing all the buttons. Greed,
competition, desire, desperation. But how many products you have
using this strategy is still an open question. You still have to
have a product that somebody wants. And that title still goes to
Beanie Babies.''
</P>
<P>
   McDonald's, of course, has raised that strategy to a fine art by
offering Teeny Beanie Babies in its Happy Meals.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Barneson, a New York marketing expert, said the marketing
of Beanies with Happy Meals is far more important than the food
that's included.
</P>
<P>
   ``The food is superfluous,'' he said. ``It's all about the toys,
and the unbelievable hype that's been created. Collectors are
hooked and they can't turn back... And since (Beanies) will only be
offered for a limited time... they've created the ultimate
competition.''
</P>
<P>
   The same strategies are working, on a smaller scale, for Crazy
Bones. The colorful bones _ and the games you can play with them _
have become a craze at more than a few area elementary schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been taking them to school and trading them on the
playground,'' Julia McCullough of Overland Park said of her two
sons, Adam and Matt. McCullough and other mothers said they
recognized a Beanie Baby-style marketing technique.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some special ones you can get,'' said Betty Mapes of
Leawood, ``and then they retire some, too. It's the same
philosophy. (My 9-year-old son, Danny) just told me I have to go
buy a bunch of Crazy Bones.
</P>
<P>
   Danny also collects Pokemon.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's 150,'' Mapes said. ``You have to collect them all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Danny,'' she called. ``How many Pokemon do you have now?''
</P>
<P>
   ``A hundred and thirty nine,'' he called back.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's captured 139 of them on his Game Boy,'' she said. ``There
are also trading cards. But you can't get those cause the adults
keep buying them,'' she said, ``It's crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   For some reason collecting in general has gone crazy.
</P>
<P>
   Take Pez dispensers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always been collectors,'' said Scott McWhinnie, the
president of Pez Candy Co. Inc. ``But it's bigger than ever now.
There are auctions at Christie's. There are five, six, seven
conventions around the country. There are books, 70 websites, there
are chat rooms with people sitting on line talking about Pez. It's
unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Collecting baseball cards, autographs and sports memorabilia has
turned from largely a child's pastime to a multi-billion dollar
industry dominated by adults. Even something as classic as the
Barbie doll has changed.
</P>
<P>
   Decades ago, many girls had just one or two Barbies, a Ken doll
and some friends. Once people had the core dolls, they didn't need
others.
</P>
<P>
   That is, until Mattel changed its marketing strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Barbies have distinct identities _ Doctor Barbie, Mermaid
Barbie, Cheerleader Barbie and so on _ thereby allowing Mattel to
sell the doll multiple times. In addition, Mattel also markets
``instant'' collector Barbies for hundreds of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world of toy collecting has changed from when I was a
kid,'' said Winter. ``And it's marketing that's changed it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
