<DOCNO> NYT19990625.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 12:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9285 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OPERA-ST.LOUIS-KAN &LR;      06-25 1518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPERA-ST. </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ST. LOUIS COMPANY OFFERS OUTRAGEOUS UPDATES OF MOZART AND MORE 
</HEADLINE>
 LOUIS-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANTRELL  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Opera isn't what it used to be, and a new production
of ``The Marriage of Figaro'' proved that Opera Theatre of St.
Louis is holding its place in the art form's vanguard.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which presents four productions each summer at the
Loretto-Hilton Center of Webster University in Webster Groves, has
made its name with new and off-the-beaten-path operas. Even
standard repertory tends to be presented in nonstandard versions _
and often controversial stagings.
</P>
<P>
   Updated to what looked like a cheesily pretentious hotel hallway
lined with mauve doors (Miami Beach's Fontainebleau, maybe?),
Christopher Alden's staging of ``The Marriage of Figaro'' pushed
all kinds of envelopes.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about en famille _ at one time or other, we saw virtually
every member of the Almaviva household in his or her smalls: bras
and slips, silk and cotton boxers. Marcellina, a woman of a certain
age, stripped to a black lace bustier suggesting she'd been
e-shopping at Frederick's of Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   But it also rang true to Mozart's own revolutionary _ and
irreverent _ spirit. An ``Othello'' strained at no novelty, but
dramatically and musically it was strong and affecting.
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out the season were a newly commissioned opera, ``The
Merchant and the Pauper,'' by American composer Paul Schoenfield,
and a reconstruction of the original spoken-dialogue version of
``The Pearl Fishers.''
</P>
<P>
   Presented separately at the Center of Contemporary Arts in
University City were five performances of a new one-hour opera for
young people, ``Joshua's Boots,'' with a libretto by Kansas
City-bred Susan Kander. (See companion story.)
</P>
<P>
   Three performances remain in the current festival: ``The
Marriage of Figaro'' at 1 p.m. today, followed by ``Othello'' at 8
p.m. and ``The Merchant and the Pauper'' at 7 p.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Cartoon opera
</P>
<P>
   ``The Merchant and the Pauper'' is based on a parable by Rabbi
Nachman, a Hasidic cleric who lived in turn-of-the-19th-century
Ukraine. The libretto is by Maggie Stearns, Opera Theatre's
much-loved director of communications.
</P>
<P>
   The prosperous Merchant supports the Pauper and rescues his wife
from an abduction. But with rich nobles offering money for the hand
of his daughter, Beauty, the Pauper turns his back on his
benefactor and sets his ruin in motion.
</P>
<P>
   Although Beauty has been promised to the Merchant's Son, the
Pauper, now wealthy and powerful, sends the Son fleeing into exile.
But the young lovers are reunited when Beauty is shipwrecked on the
same island. They return home to be married, everything is put
right and presumably everyone lives happily ever after.
</P>
<P>
   Tying the action together and supplying background is a
Narrator, who sings a little but mostly speaks. In the St. Louis
staging he was effectively portrayed by Spiro Malos _ warm of voice
and manner _ as Rabbi Nachman himself.
</P>
<P>
   By definition, these are cartoon characters. And they were made
all the more so in a Mark Lamos staging about as subtle as a silent
movie. (I thought these exaggerated gesticulations died with the
Keystone Kops.)
</P>
<P>
   Although the opera got enthusiastic notices in The New York
Times and The St. Louis Post-Dispatch, this observer was put off by
music that sounded like a cross between Kurt Weill and ``Fiddler on
the Roof.'' Largely conjunct, rhythmically straightforward, the
vocal writing was easy on voice and ear, but it registered little
personality.
</P>
<P>
   Within the constraints, Thomas Barrett's brought dignity and a
resonant baritone to the role of the Merchant. Thomas Trotter was a
sniveling, thoroughly annoying Pauper. Marcus DeLoach was appealing
as the Merchant's Son, his handsome baritone compromised only by
some suspect intonation.
</P>
<P>
   Both visually and vocally, Madeline Bender was well cast as
Beauty. Yaacov Zamir's hooty countertenor made for a suitably slimy
Wicked General and Pirate.
</P>
<P>
   Sets by Andrew Lieberman and costumes by Constance Hoffman
mingled Nachman-period historicism with childlike fantasy.
Christopher Akerlind's lighting, so effective in the three other
Opera Theatre productions, was unsubtle. John DeMain was the
assured conductor.
</P>
<P>
   Irreverent, loving `Figaro'
</P>
<P>
   An arc of hotel-room doors announced right at the start that
this would be very much a slamming-door-farce ``Figaro.'' With the
dramatis personae so much of the time in either underwear or
sleepwear, the production also underlined the domesticity of the
comedy.
</P>
<P>
   When on the job, Susanna was done up as a hotel maid, Figaro as
a waiter in a suit with an apron. Marcellina, usually portrayed as
a haggish old woman, here showed up in quite a snazzy dress; her
employer, Dr. Bartolo, mostly appeared in the lawyer's
quintessential pinstripe suit. But once their old liaison was
revealed _ and apparently rekindled _ here they were bumping and
grinding in their underthings.
</P>
<P>
   Basilio, the music master, was turned into a slithery queen,
with a towering bouffant and outre duds worthy of the creature
formerly known as Prince. Barbarina was a bosomy tart in bright red
skirt, sweater and shoes; her father, the gardener Antonio, sported
his own red suit.
</P>
<P>
   Doubtless there were patrons horrified by the irreverent
updating. But so much of the opera's anti-aristocratic nuance now
so totally eludes us that we might as well transpose its human
drama closer to our own sensibilities.
</P>
<P>
   In this case irreverence implied no lack of respect _ indeed,
love _ for the miracle wrought by Mozart and his librettist,
Lorenzo da Ponte. And surely the Mozart who delighted in
scatological humor would have loved it.
</P>
<P>
   The production was blessed with a fine cast: George Cordes as a
warm-toned Figaro, Sari Gruber as a real firecracker of a Susanna,
Deanne Meek as a pert Peter Pan of a Cherubino, Gary Lehman as a
commanding Count, Pamela Armstrong as a passionate Countess.
Praise, too, to Kevin J. Glavin's Bartolo, Kathryn Day's
Marcellina, Jon Kolbet's Basilio and Danielle Martin's Barbarina.
</P>
<P>
   The set designer was Allen Moyer; Gabriel Berry was responsible
for the costumes. I was perplexed only by brief switches to
18th-century duds toward the end.
</P>
<P>
   Matters were less happy in the pit. Alternately hurrying and
dragging, conductor Stefan Lano evinced little feel for singers'
needs to phrase and breathe. Surprisingly rough-hewn playing
suggested that these weren't the St. Louis Symphony's front-chair
musicians.
</P>
<P>
   More lovelorns
</P>
<P>
   The question with ``Othello'' was how Verdi's big-screen
orchestration would adapt to the Loretto-Hilton Center's sonically
cramped pit. But Opera Theatre music director Stephen Lord soon set
worries to rest with an urgent, finely nuanced command of the
score, and the orchestra played its heart out.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from Emilia's overdone pawing all over the distraught
Desdemona, director Colin Graham made strong, credible drama with a
capable cast.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Otey brought an admirably muscular baritone to the role of
Iago, and Robert Brubaker's big, commanding tenor underscored
Othello's agony. Marie Plette's diction was mushy, but her ample,
flexible soprano made for a most sympathetic Desdemona. It's too
bad Theodore Green's Cassio was so spongy-toned.
</P>
<P>
   The unit set _ with a huge lion's head, fangs bared, on the left
_ was by Gerard Howland; costumes were by Peter J. Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Pearl Fishers'' was mounted in a reconstruction of the
spoken-dialogue version that Bizet wisely discarded before the
premiere. Flimsy to start with, the opera was burdened with Travis
Preston's windily pretentious staging, complete with projected
interpretive titles for each scene.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Barreca's designs and Ellen McCartney's costumes
were fancy tails wagging this mutt of a dog. Was there no one just
to say no?
</P>
<P>
   And here, surely, was a compelling argument for singing in a
language _ any language _ that won't be understood by the audience.
(Commissioned by Opera Theatre, the new translation and performing
edition were by Washington University musicologist Hugh Macdonald.)
The spoken dialogue was delivered in stilted ``stage'' accents.
</P>
<P>
   Mel Ulrich, as Zurga, had a deep, crisp, focused baritone but
also a tendency to sing under pitch. Tenor Gregory Turay, as Nadir,
sounded freer, less forced, than last year, but he and Ulrich were
guilty of much over-singing. (The gentler art of French opera
eludes most singers nowadays.) Mary Dunleavy was a respectable
Leila, Alfred Walker the Nourabad.
</P>
<P>
   Conductor Steuart Bedford evinced little affinity for the score,
and the orchestra responded with coarse, leaden playing. Even Cary
John Franklin's usually splendid chorus sounded out of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   For next season, Opera Theatre's 25th, the lineup will include
the world premiere of Japanese composer Minoru Miki's ``The Tale of
Genji,'' the American professional stage premiere of Handel's
``Radamisto,'' Scott Joplin's ``Treemonisha'' and Verdi's ``La
traviata.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
