<HEADLINE>
SCANNER ANNIVERSARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DRU SEFTON  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Summertime is party time, so here's your excuse for a
celebration today: The 25th birthday of the supermarket scanner.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, on June 26, 1974, the first item with that little black bar
code was pulled across a grocery store scanner, which read the code
and electronically entered the price in the cash register.
</P>
<P>
   For you trivia buffs: Clyde Dawson made the historic purchase of
a 10-pack of Wrigley's Juicy Fruit Gum (67 cents) at 8:01 a.m. at
the Marsh Supermarket in Troy, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Folks at NCR Corp., the product's maker, suggest celebrating
this ``Silver Scanniversary'' (catchy, eh?) this way:
</P>
<P>
   ``When you hear that scanner `beep,' just let it remind you that
your neighborhood retailer is working to transform each transaction
into a stronger relationship with you, their customer,'' said Kelly
Kramer, an NCR spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Oh.
</P>
<P>
   We were thinking more along the lines of a cupcake with a
candle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
