<HEADER>
A9299 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-VIOLIN-HN     06-25 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-VIOLIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RED VIOLIN' IS MUSIC TO THE EYES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Red Violin'' is tough to classify. You could call it an
epic, but that would imply it's long. You could call it an art
film, but that would imply it's dull. You could call it a mystery,
but that would imply that Colonel Mustard just offed someone in the
library with a candlestick.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Red Violin'' is all of that, but it's something else, too:
a breathless fable covering three centuries in the life of a
single, perfect instrument. Hopping the globe from Italy to
Shanghai, intertwining five distinct plots crowded with ideas and
characters, the film is virtuosic filmmaking that dares failure to
a duel and wins. That it winds up with a nick of blood on its cheek
is almost beside the point.
</P>
<P>
   Directed and written by Francois Girard and Don McKellar, the
same duo that made the equally unorthodox ``Thirty-Two Short Films
About Glenn Gould,'' ``The Red Violin'' makes several assumptions,
the most important being that romance boasts no room for
moderation.
</P>
<P>
   Everything's a bold stroke: the acting, the dialogue, the
ecstatic photography (Alain Dostie's) and the unwavering faith in
hyperbole. It is big and dense and gorgeous.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Glenn Gould,'' ``The Red Violin'' takes a musical conceit
in this case, a riffing portrait of an instrument rather than a
performer and lets fly with the narrative possibilities. It begins
in late-17th century Cremona, Italy, where a master luthier (Carlo
Cecchi) is about to complete his greatest violin. Shortly before
giving birth, his wife (Irene Grazioli) hears her tarot cards read
by a psychic house maid. She later dies in childbirth; her husband,
wracked with grief, varnishes the violin.
</P>
<P>
   With such terse melodrama Girard and McKellar begin their story.
But there's more to this opening than meets the eye: Elements are
left out, not in some pique of editing-room slashing but
intentionally, mysteriously, to seduce us into watching.
</P>
<P>
   At first, we're just confused something's missing. Yet the
brilliance of the film is its stubborn insistence that we take it
on its own terms, that we follow this snaking tale all the way to
the end. Even when it infuriates, it beguiles. Any attempt to
condense the plot would be ill-fated and cruelly unfair, so let's
leave it at this:
</P>
<P>
   Over its 300-year history, the masterwork spends time in the
hands of an orphaned prodigy, a band of gypsies, a demonic (and
Paganini-like) English virtuoso, a pawn shop owner, a conflicted
Maoist operative and a disgraced Chinese music teacher. This
ordered provenance is broken with flash-forwards to a modern-day
auction in Montreal (where Samuel L. Jackson, as a crisp
auction-house expert, investigates the violin's origins) and
flashbacks to eerie tarot sessions in Cremona.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds unwieldy, and it is. Much of this is done so swiftly
that you've barely had time to consider one set of characters
before the next bunch comes waltzing through. And some of the
vignettes work better than others; the scenes involving the English
Paganini (Jason Flemyng, all wild-haired emoting) and his lover
(Greta Scacchi) are crazy chest-heavers, rapturously overdrawn in
the manner of Harlequin Romance book covers.
</P>
<P>
   Whether this charms or annoys you will depend on your mood. Yet
it's all of a piece it's all part of an exuberant fairy tale,
rippling with magic and grand swoops of emotion.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the general swoop is John Corigiliano's luscious
neo-Romantic score, all of it strings and percussion. Part lament,
part swirling dance, the heart of it is a gypsy-touched minor-key
theme for solo violin, played on the soundtrack by Joshua Bell.
(Bell, who pops up in a don't-blink cameo, served as musical
consultant for the film. McKellar himself appears in a small role.)
</P>
<P>
   Most movies feature music of some sort: a score, a few ambient
tunes, maybe a CD crammed with alt-rock hits. But Girard and
McKellar make films about music, movies in which the least tangible
of arts are given center stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Red Violin'' concerns a violin, of course, but it also
concerns the mysticism involved in all music-making the charmed
bond between the player and the played that can endure the passage
of centuries. Huge cast or no huge cast, music alone is the star.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Amy Biancolli is the film critic for the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. E-mail:
abiancolli(at)timesunion.com or call 518-454-5738.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-99 1236EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990625.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 12:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9302 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-VEGGIETALES-HNS &LR;      06-25 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-VEGGIETALES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIDS PROGRAM IS THE BEST TV SHOW NO ON TV 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ This is the best television show not on
television, a kids program that touches on religious themes but is
as cool as ``Davey and Goliath'' was not.
</P>
<P>
   The stars are a cucumber and a tomato, and issues like honesty
and trust and forgiveness and fear are broached with a style that
the makers say combines the sensibilities of Monty Python, Dr.
Seuss and Sunday school.
</P>
<P>
   I tried, but I could not come up with a better characterization.
The theme song says it best: There's never, ever, ever, ever, ever
been a show like ``VeggieTales.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever. Relying on computer animation, writing that is sharper
than most adult shows and humor far funnier than the average
sitcom, ``VeggieTales'' fills a vacuum for moral entertainment for
kids, with a keen eye toward keeping adults laughing at jokes
geared just for them.
</P>
<P>
   Available only on video (major stores and Christian outlets),
sales of half-hour ``VeggieTales'' videos exploded the past two
years, now topping 10 million overall.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, each episode can cost up to $1 million to make
and take up to six months to produce (trust us, the quality looks
it). To build up enough of a catalog to sustain a television series
will take time and tinkering.
</P>
<P>
   Computer animation (think ``Toy Story'') is more like clay
animation (``Davey'') than cell (or traditional) animation in that
the characters take on three-dimensional qualities. Artists still
draw ``key frames'' the major poses of the characters but computers
fill in the missing parts.
</P>
<P>
   Think of it this way: An artist draws A and E; the computer then
supplies the B, C and D. The results are startlingly vivid.
</P>
<P>
   The ``VeggieTales'' concept comes from Phil Vischer, founder and
chief executive of Big Idea Productions (and the voice of Bob the
Tomato) and co-creator Mike Nawrocki (voice of Larry the Cucumber).
</P>
<P>
   The two met at St. Paul Bible College in Minnesota, and were
working together at a Chicago video production house when Vischer
decided to go ahead with his dream of creating an animated
children's show founded on the Bible. Nawrocki signed on as well,
and ``VeggieTales'' was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no mention of (God) in popular children's media,''
Nawrocki said in an interview earlier this week. ``For us, it was
wanting to help kids.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early days, back around 1993 or so, distributors were
telling the pair that they loved the video, but didn't think it
would sell with the religious content.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody thought it would work commercially,'' Nawrocki said.
``They said, `We love your shows, but we would love them more if
you take the God part out.'''
</P>
<P>
   Thank God, and Vischer and Nawrocki, they didn't. Parents soon
realized they had a moral and entertaining alternative to the
Saturday morning fare that was benign at best and virulent at
worst.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the videos click _ there are 11 with a 12th, ``Larry
Boy and Rumor Weed,'' coming out next month _ is that while the
themes taken from the Bible are treated seriously, everything else
is played for laughs.
</P>
<P>
   Spoofs abound, including takes on ``Gilligan's Island,''
``Batman,'' ``Frankenstein,'' ``Grapes of Wrath,'' ``Tales from the
Crypt,'' ``Monty Python and the Holy Grail'' and ``Madame Bovary,''
to name a few.
</P>
<P>
   ``We both have offbeat senses of humors,'' said Nawrocki, whose
work with others on non-sequitur songs are fall-down hysterical
(``The Pirates Who Don't Do Anything'' is my favorite music video
of all time, period).
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, we like to write what makes us laugh,'' he continued.
``What we try to do with `VeggieTales' is try to identify a key
value that 4-year-olds understand. From there, we don't write humor
for kids. We write the humor for ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Other adults get the joke. At the Living Word Christian Book
Store in East Greenbush, N.Y., clerk Sonia Higgins said
``VeggieTales'' tapes qualify as a best-seller.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are selling a lot more than other videos,'' Higgins said.
``It's skewed toward younger kids toddlers and up but we have
college kids and adults buying them.''
</P>
<P>
   And laughing at them. What do you know? A truly funny television
show. Too bad it's not on television.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His e-mail address
is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
