<DOCNO> NYT19990625.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 12:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9309 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-DADDY-HNS     06-25 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-DADDY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE TO CHEER IN `BIG DADDY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yes, those are warm fuzzies breaking out all over Adam Sandler
and cast by the time ``Big Daddy'' comes to its set-up-for-a-sequel
(or a sitcom) close. And yes that might even be a reluctant tear
misting up your eye as a pivotal reunion in Central Park leaves an
irony-lite ``Kramer vs. Kramer'' aftertaste.
</P>
<P>
   In the time it'd take to execute a Bobby Boucher flying tackle,
Sandler goes from a guy to whom you'd want to feed a knuckle
sandwich to someone you just want to give a noogie.
</P>
<P>
   After victimizing dozens in previous movies with his
dufus-bullyboy assaults, ``Big Daddy'' finds Sandler playing the
apologist, going the Wallace Beery, Charlie Chaplin route and
stretching his aimless man-child persona around the comic potential
of being a ``dad.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an improbable transition for Sandler's Sonny Koufax, an
aimless Manhattan do-nothing and the world's only 32-year-old
curmudgeon. ``Big Daddy,'' written by Sandler, Steve Franks and Tim
Herlihy and directed by regular Sandler ringmaster Dennis Dugan,
has a great time exploiting that fact, but for some reason
restrains itself.
</P>
<P>
   A turnpike toll-taker with a Syracuse law degree living mostly
off the money he won in a sham lawsuit against a taxi company,
Sonny seems more like he's in early retirement than in a career
funk. His arrested development drives away his girlfriend (Kristy
Swanson) and forces his attorney father (Joseph Bologna) to harass
him long-distance from Florida.
</P>
<P>
   When his traveling roommate's kid, Julian (played by Cole and
Dylan Sprouse), shows up at his apartment door _ instructions
attached _ Sonny uses the situation to convince his now ex-girl to
come home and be ma to his pa.
</P>
<P>
   Really, the kid is an opportunity for Sandler to get his Dr.
Evil working and have a Mini-me of his own. Julian is an
impressionable ragamuffin with that adorable speech impediment that
softens ``l's'' and ``r's'' into ``w's'' and elects to be referred
to as Frankenstein (or ``Fwankenstein'' when he goes third-person.)
Outlandishly, Sonny gives the kid carte blanche to behave ``like a
adult'' (read: doing what he wants and not having to deal with his
old man's taunts the way Sonny has to).
</P>
<P>
   He shows him how to pee in public and trip Rollerbladers, and
lets him play in the autumn puddles in Washington Square Park.
</P>
<P>
   Sonny also teaches young Frank how to get a-third-off dented can
goods at the supermarket, how to help him pick up a new girlfriend
(``Chasing Amy's'' Joey Lauren Adams, the one with the Lollipop Kid
purr) and dirty ways to tease the busty girlfriend (Leslie Mann) of
his roommate (Jon Stewart).
</P>
<P>
   Laughs _ the low-brow, out-loud kind _ come often from Sonny's
child-rearing ineptitude and the eventual tension between pseudo
father and son that makes him aware that he's, uh, created a
monster. But ``Big Daddy,'' risible as it is, is subdued, somber,
where a film like the Jerry- Lewis-on-'roids ``Waterboy'' was
contagiously stupid. As a comedian, Sandler has always been able to
get away with malevolence because his victim-selection is
ridiculously arbitrary and sometimes even cathartic.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, Sandler is damned if he develops, damned if he
devolves. But he needn't apologize for being who he is by turning a
gold-mine sitcom into a tame ``Baby Boom'' for guys. Being a jerk
par excellence should mean never having to say you're sorry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-99 1253EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
