<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990625.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 12:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9310 &Cx1f; tad-z
s i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-DROUGHT-$ADV27     06-25 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-DROUGHT-$ADV27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DROUGHT REVEALS MEXICO'S WEAK WATER AND FARMING INFRASTRUCTURE
TO AID SMALL FARMERS
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    EDs: For purposes of a locator map, Zacatecas, the capital of
Zacatecas state, is in northern-central Mexico.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (f) Financial categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., June 27 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZACATECAS, Mexico _ A welcome mid-June storm was enough to bring
out black ants and thirsty rattlesnakes in Mexico's arid central
plains, but it didn't impress Apolonio Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   With a face as hardened and wrinkled as the land he tries to
farm, the fatalistic 76-year-old sat impassively under a mesquite
tree while rain clouds splattered the ground several miles away.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no water, and this land is tired and doesn't want to
produce,'' Hernandez said, watching his cows pick at desert plants
sprouting from parched soil where corn would normally be planted.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, Hernandez and hundreds of thousands of other
Mexicans are trapped by drought that's threatening to cripple
farming in central and northern Mexico. Five years of exceptionally
dry weather is jeopardizing everything from small plots of beans
and corn to cattle and fields of winter vegetables for export, like
tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the Mexican government declared 10 states, including the
semi-desert state of Zacatecas (pronounced, ``Sa-ka-TAY-kas''),
disaster areas and earmarked $360 million in emergency funds to try
to provide feed for starving cattle and help families make it
through the year.
</P>
<P>
   Between January and April, rainfall for some parched states was
more than 90 percent below average, and average reservoir levels
have fallen to about 21 percent of their capacity in the north.
</P>
<P>
   Drought has shut down eight hydroelectric plants in Sinaloa
state, on Mexico's northwest coast. And some predictions are that
the number of cattle in Mexico could drop from 22 million just a
few months ago to 16 million because of forced early slaughtering.
</P>
<P>
   Recent showers in Zacatecas gave some farmers hope for
reasonable harvests in the fall. But in a state like this -- where
irrigation methods are woefully antiquated -- summer will be a long
stretch of anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   Seasonal fear is nothing new here.
</P>
<P>
   Water problems, if not drought, are a way of life in these high
plains, where dams are few and poorly managed and 70 percent of
farmers don't even have access to wells and must rely strictly on
rain.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, bank loans for improvements are almost impossible
for most small farmers to obtain -- due to Mexico's 1994 peso
collapse and free-market reforms affecting the country's
agricultural policies, peasant associations complain.
</P>
<P>
   Modest government subsidies given to farmers who grow beans or
grains are often used to buy food or clothing, or wasted because
crops fail.
</P>
<P>
   ``The drought has revealed the defective agricultural system of
Mexico,'' Zacatecas' new governor, Ricardo Monreal, said in an
interview with Cox Newspapers. ``As long as the federal government
decides agriculture is not a priority, we won't advance.''
</P>
<P>
   A former member of Mexico's dominant Revolutionary Institutional
Party, or PRI, Monreal last year ran for governor under the banner
of the left-center Democratic Revolution Party, or PRD.
</P>
<P>
   The PRD and Monreal tapped into sentiment in Zacatecas that
Mexico is neglecting its small farmers, whose failure to thrive
over several generations has made Zacatecas one of the states with
the highest rate of migration to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   With rain and credit both drying up, an estimated 40,000
Zacatecans left the state each year between 1990 and 1995,
according to Dario Alejandro Escobar, an agricultural economist at
the Autonomous University of Zacatecas.
</P>
<P>
   ``After two or three years of not being able to harvest, they
have to look elsewhere to feed their families,'' Escobar said,
predicting a continuing exodus toward Mexico's big industrial
cities or the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Escobar said that according to studies by the Autonomous
University of Zacatecas about 270,000 of Zacatecas' natives now
reside permanently in the United States. The state has a remaining
population of about 1.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Farmer Hernandez, who grows beans and corn about an hour north
of the capital city of Zacatecas -- without the benefit of a well
-- is a case in point. He has two sons who live in Los Angeles and
send money home to their parents.
</P>
<P>
   Monreal said he is seeking investments from abroad -- including
Europe and United States -- to try to spur industrial employment in
his state to keep its inhabitants home.
</P>
<P>
   He also criticized his former party for handing out federal farm
subsidies, accusing the PRI of using the cash as a short-term way
of buying votes and keeping small farmers loyal to the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather use that money to build dams, canals, irrigation
systems, warehouses, equipment and to help boost commercialization
of products,'' Monreal said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he is powerless to change the system because the
subsidies are federally-controlled.
</P>
<P>
   Rain is scarce in Zacatecas, Monreal acknowledged, but he said
about 60 percent of it simply runs off in streams that are not
funneled into dams.
</P>
<P>
   In long valleys dotted with pines and date palms, Zacatecas has
pockets of land blessed by rich, red soil ideal for growing crops.
</P>
<P>
   But only 10 percent of land dedicated to farming is irrigated by
well water when rain is scarce. For those who have wells,
agronomists say, irrigation methods are often crude and wasteful.
</P>
<P>
   Inefficiency is also a problem -- and the butt of jokes by
farmers who have little faith in government.
</P>
<P>
   Tomas Rodriguez, 68, and his son Tomas(CQ), took advantage of
recent showers to plow their fields in anticipation of planting
beans about 60 miles north of Zacatecas.
</P>
<P>
   Their 25-acre farm, known as Ejido Cantuna, is only a few miles
from a dam built 15 years ago. But the dam was so small and
ill-conceived the Rodriguez's don't have access to it. The dam only
serves about 500 acres when at full capacity -- and now it's at
just a fraction of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the president of Mexico (Miguel de la Madrid) came to
inaugurate the dam,'' the younger Rodriguez said, ``he got really
angry when he saw how small it was. He said, 'You could have built
a bigger dam just by stacking up all the dollar bills we spent on
this.'''
</P>
<P>
   Some government officials stopped by the Rodriguez's farm a few
years ago to investigate whether the Rodriguez's could get a permit
and drill a well.
</P>
<P>
   But the officials never came back. The family says it can't
afford the costs of drilling a well and pumping water anyway.
</P>
<P>
   So the Rodriguez family continues to depend on what falls from
heaven.
</P>
<P>
   ``One lives always looking up at the sky, and listening to see
if the coyote barks or the rooster crows,'' said the elder
Rodriguez, only half-joking about folklore local farmers use to
forecast wet weather.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-99 1253EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990625.0087 </DOCNO>
