<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 13:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9325 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-VEGGIETALES-1STLD-     06-25 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-VEGGIETALES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIDS PROGRAM IS THE BEST SHOW NOT ON TELEVISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Subs hed to correct)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ This is the best television show not on
television, a kids program that touches on religious themes but is
as cool as ``Davey and Goliath'' was not.
</P>
<P>
   The stars are a cucumber and a tomato, and issues like honesty
and trust and forgiveness and fear are broached with a style that
the makers say combines the sensibilities of Monty Python, Dr.
Seuss and Sunday school.
</P>
<P>
   I tried, but I could not come up with a better characterization.
The theme song says it best: There's never, ever, ever, ever, ever
been a show like ``VeggieTales.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever. Relying on computer animation, writing that is sharper
than most adult shows and humor far funnier than the average
sitcom, ``VeggieTales'' fills a vacuum for moral entertainment for
kids, with a keen eye toward keeping adults laughing at jokes
geared just for them.
</P>
<P>
   Available only on video (major stores and Christian outlets),
sales of half-hour ``VeggieTales'' videos exploded the past two
years, now topping 10 million overall.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, each episode can cost up to $1 million to make
and take up to six months to produce (trust us, the quality looks
it). To build up enough of a catalog to sustain a television series
will take time and tinkering.
</P>
<P>
   Computer animation (think ``Toy Story'') is more like clay
animation (``Davey'') than cell (or traditional) animation in that
the characters take on three-dimensional qualities. Artists still
draw ``key frames'' the major poses of the characters but computers
fill in the missing parts.
</P>
<P>
   Think of it this way: An artist draws A and E; the computer then
supplies the B, C and D. The results are startlingly vivid.
</P>
<P>
   The ``VeggieTales'' concept comes from Phil Vischer, founder and
chief executive of Big Idea Productions (and the voice of Bob the
Tomato) and co-creator Mike Nawrocki (voice of Larry the Cucumber).
</P>
<P>
   The two met at St. Paul Bible College in Minnesota, and were
working together at a Chicago video production house when Vischer
decided to go ahead with his dream of creating an animated
children's show founded on the Bible. Nawrocki signed on as well,
and ``VeggieTales'' was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no mention of (God) in popular children's media,''
Nawrocki said in an interview earlier this week. ``For us, it was
wanting to help kids.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early days, back around 1993 or so, distributors were
telling the pair that they loved the video, but didn't think it
would sell with the religious content.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody thought it would work commercially,'' Nawrocki said.
``They said, `We love your shows, but we would love them more if
you take the God part out.'''
</P>
<P>
   Thank God, and Vischer and Nawrocki, they didn't. Parents soon
realized they had a moral and entertaining alternative to the
Saturday morning fare that was benign at best and virulent at
worst.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the videos click _ there are 11 with a 12th, ``Larry
Boy and Rumor Weed,'' coming out next month _ is that while the
themes taken from the Bible are treated seriously, everything else
is played for laughs.
</P>
<P>
   Spoofs abound, including takes on ``Gilligan's Island,''
``Batman,'' ``Frankenstein,'' ``Grapes of Wrath,'' ``Tales from the
Crypt,'' ``Monty Python and the Holy Grail'' and ``Madame Bovary,''
to name a few.
</P>
<P>
   ``We both have offbeat senses of humors,'' said Nawrocki, whose
work with others on non-sequitur songs are fall-down hysterical
(``The Pirates Who Don't Do Anything'' is my favorite music video
of all time, period).
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, we like to write what makes us laugh,'' he continued.
``What we try to do with `VeggieTales' is try to identify a key
value that 4-year-olds understand. From there, we don't write humor
for kids. We write the humor for ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Other adults get the joke. At the Living Word Christian Book
Store in East Greenbush, N.Y., clerk Sonia Higgins said
``VeggieTales'' tapes qualify as a best-seller.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are selling a lot more than other videos,'' Higgins said.
``It's skewed toward younger kids toddlers and up but we have
college kids and adults buying them.''
</P>
<P>
   And laughing at them. What do you know? A truly funny television
show. Too bad it's not on television.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His e-mail address
is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-99 1306EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990625.0089 </DOCNO>
