<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR GOOD OR BAD, PRESSLER CHANGED THE FACE OF THE SOUTHERN BAPTIST
CONVENTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Houston Judge Paul Pressler, in his new book, ``A Hill on Which
to Die,'' portrays himself as one of the saviors of the national
Southern Baptist Convention. But to many, Pressler is a villain
rather than a messiah.
</P>
<P>
   He has been accused of ruthless tactics in a historic revolution
that turned the Southern Baptists far to the right in embracing
stands such as boycotting Disney, proselytizing Jews and Mormons,
and approving statements urging wives to ``submit graciously'' to
the servant leadership of their husbands.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jerry Falwell, who became a Southern Baptist because of
the denomination's move to conservatism, says Pressler will go down
in history as one of the heroes of the faith for saving the
convention from liberalism.
</P>
<P>
   But Pressler is the man moderates love to hate.
</P>
<P>
   In his book, released by Broadman &AMP; Holman, the Baptist
publishing arm, Pressler says he and others followed Baptist
democratic rules in ousting moderates from leadership of the 15.7
million-member denomination. And he tells of having to fight for
his conservative faith since childhood.
</P>
<P>
   He fought peer pressure from liberal students and teachers in
practicing his evangelical faith at Phillips Exeter Academy, a prep
school in New Hampshire, and at Princeton University. He says he
was ``fired'' from teaching Sunday school at Second Baptist Church
in Houston because he dared to fight liberalism.
</P>
<P>
   In a very personal note, he tells how his father, a lawyer who
became vice president of Exxon, believed that Pressler, as a youth,
had gone overboard about being ``saved'' and put some constraints
on him.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Pressler, who grew up with the country club set in
Houston, had to hitch rides to church on Sunday nights. As a
teen-ager, he was not allowed to use the family car to go to
church. But he could use the car on Sunday nights to go on dates or
to dances at the country club.
</P>
<P>
   He says his father was a Southern Baptist, devout believer and
very supportive and loving. But he distrusted preachers because of
an incident in which one of his father's former pastors had run off
with a woman in the church.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps opposition to my Christian faith at an early age was
training that the Lord was giving me for future trials to come,''
Pressler writes.
</P>
<P>
   Pressler also got training in denominational power brokering in
the gritty field of Texas politics. He campaigned for state
representative in 1957 and won. He was appointed to a judgeship in
1970 and served as a state appeals court judge until his retirement
in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Pressler acknowledged that the conservative resurgence inflicted
pain on many moderates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I regret that tremendously, because my original view was that
we would work together,'' Pressler told me. ``My view was to have
parity between conservative and moderate views.''
</P>
<P>
   I can hear moderates guffawing loudly at those statements.
</P>
<P>
   Pressler said moderates, instead of agreeing to share some of
their power, widened the gulf by attacking him and other leaders of
the conservative movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most vitriolic, vicious attacks were leveled on us for
having the temerity to vote our consciences,'' Pressler said.
</P>
<P>
   Pressler became known early in the conflict for a
much-publicized statement he made about ``going for the jugular,''
meaning conservatives must find the vein controlling the lifeblood
of the national denomination.
</P>
<P>
   The ``jugular vein,'' he discovered, was determining who was
elected the convention president.
</P>
<P>
   It was little known, then. But Baptist presidents have almost
absolute power to name committees that can ultimately decide who
are named trustees of seminaries, mission boards, publishing houses
and other agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The conservatives began sending more voters to conventions and
electing their people as presidents. In 10 years, they were in
control. Moderates were fired or forced out of seminaries and other
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Pressler has some surprises in his book.
</P>
<P>
   Many, including myself, had given him credit for figuring out
that electing a conservative president was the key to controlling
the denomination. But Pressler writes that he got that information
from another avid conservative, the late Bill Powell.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the criticisms, Pressler said, the conflict was worth
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think of these young people now in our seminaries,'' he
said. ``So many of them would be on the garbage heap `because of
liberalism' if the conservative movement had not succeeded.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Pressler, hero or villain, always speaks his mind.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
