<DOCNO> NYT19990625.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9369 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BOURQUE-DREAM-BOS     06-25 1631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BOURQUE-DREAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOURQUE RELIES ON AN OLD MENTOR FOR HELP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LAURENT, Quebec _ The kids come and go, by the thousands,
with their teenage triumphs and tribulations. For 32 years now,
Benoit Leduc has listened to their stories.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Ray Bourque's story was just another young man's
dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``So . . . you want to be hockey player,'' Leduc said the other
day, sitting in his office at Emile Legault High School, repeating
the conversation he had with Bourque in that same office nearly a
quarter-century earlier. ``Hmmm. You know, Raymond, you have to
work very hard to be hockey player.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque, 14 years old at the time, muttered something about how
he liked to work hard, how he loved sports, all sports, but
especially hockey. He played it every day after school. He wanted
to make it someday to the National Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to become a hockey player, I can help you, I
think,'' said Leduc. ``But you have to listen to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Five Norris Trophies later, Bourque still seeks the advice and
wisdom of his former gym teacher. He has never stopped listening.
From the time of that initial conversation, the ever-determined
Bourque has followed Leduc's advice on many subjects, above all
when it comes to Leduc's demanding off-ice workouts that have been
the underlying secret of the Bruins defenseman's success that past
20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Following every hockey season, Leduc, now 51 years old, charts a
day-by-day workout routine for Bourque to follow over the summer.
After taking no more than a month off, Bourque picks up Leduc's
blueprint and takes to the road, the crux of the program a blend of
running and bike riding, rebuilding a broad base of aerobic fitness
that has kept him running longer _ and recovering faster between
shifts _ than perhaps anyone in NHL history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I work with the aptitude and the attitude of the athlete,''
said Leduc, who for 14 years also was a member of the Canadian
national track and field team, coaching Team Canada's long-distance
runners. ``I work with what you have between the ears. But I am not
a god, you know? In the end, the work is up to the athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque, whose career will be celebrated at Saturday's NHL draft
at the FleetCenter 20 years after he was selected No. 8 overall in
the amateur draft, skates and plays today with barely a trace of
his 38 years detectable in his game. He averaged 29.5 minutes per
game this past season, tops on the Bruins and third in the league.
In the playoffs, his average increased to 32.1 minutes, in part
because of the mind-boggling 53.26 he logged in the Game 5 OT
victory over Carolina in Round 1.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Boston, Bourque's marathon minutes and his metronomic
consistency have long been the standard of his game. He is out
there every other shift. As sure as there is traffic on the Central
Artery, there is Bourque on Causeway Street. It has been easy to
grow blase about his minutes. The puck drops on a new season and
Bourque, from Game 1 to Game 82 and beyond, plays without ever
catching the eye from Father Time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got good genes, in terms of my body, my strength,'' said
Bourque, who attended the NHL's award ceremonies Thursday night in
Toronto, once again nominated for the Norris Trophy as the league's
top blue liner. ``I think it's more will than anything _ the will
of never being satisfied and never patting yourself on the back and
saying, `You're good, you've done it now.' It's always that
thinking process that, `Hey, you haven't done enough . . . it's not
good enough . . . you have to do better . . . you've got to do
better.''
</P>
<P>
   A good measure of that attitude can be found in the annual
summer program Leduc hands his prized pupil. Bourque allows himself
one day off each week, always Sunday. For six straight days each
week, he'll run and bike the hills around his home on the North
Shore, Leduc intensifying the workout each week, adding more
sessions of high-intensity running and bike within each day's
workout. With about 10 days to go before the start of training
camp, Bourque begins to taper back slightly.
</P>
<P>
   The program, said Leduc, is designed with the idea of bringing
Bourque to peak condition and enable him to sustain his efficiency
for the duration of the protracted NHL season. The focal point is
recovery time. The aerobic base, built up over 20 years, allows the
220-pound Bourque to return to the bench after a shift and get his
wind back in a startling 45 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The workouts, said Leduc, have stretched and enlarged Bourque's
arteries and capillaries, bringing oxygenated blood to his muscles
at warp speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That recovery time, that is the difference,'' said Leduc.
``Take two athletes, one in shape, one out of shape. After one
shift they both will recover in 40 seconds. But after the next
shift, the athlete out of shape wil take 50 seconds to recover.
After three shifts, it could take him 2 1/2 or 3 minutes. But the
athlete in shape is back out there in 40 seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   The proof is in the pupil. Even with the odd strand of gray
creeping into his thick hair, Bourque springs back off the bench
with the same zip that he first showed when he arrived in the fall
of '79.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ben's given me, not only in terms of workouts and training and
all that, a mental toughness _ and what it takes to compete,'' said
Bourque. ``And to go out and compete and excel and be strong. He
has a lot of wisdom.''
</P>
<P>
   All these years later, Bourque and Leduc have grown to be best
pals. Bourque flew him to Nagano for the '98 Winter Olympics, when
Bourque suited up for Team Canada. Over the years, the Bruins'
captain has treated him to a number of golf outings along the
Eastern seaboard.
</P>
<P>
   In Bourque's high school days, Leduc recalled, the two would
play on a public course not far from the high school. Leduc would
hop in his car, a rusted-out '68 Rambler, and drive down the street
about a mile from the high school, where Bourque would be waiting,
sitting on the curb with his lunch in a bag. Leduc would pay the $9
that covered the greens fees for the two of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, the roles are reversed,'' said Leduc. ``Ray treats me _
and the courses are a lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the nicest courses they've played, said Leduc, have been
around here, including Salem, Ipswich, and The Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``We speak together in French when we're out on the course,''
said Leduc. ``And the thing about Ray is, he hasn't changed a bit
in 25 years. He'll turn to me sometimes, while were walking along
some beautiful course and he'll say, `Ben, do you believe it . . .
me and you . . . this course . . . 25 years . . . us?' ''
</P>
<P>
   When he visits Boston, Leduc stays at Bourque's house. There is
a bedroom kept for him. Uncle Ben also is Ryan Bourque's godfather.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he saw something in me,'' said Bourque. ``And we
connected.''
</P>
<P>
   A year from now, Leduc will be eligible for retirement from the
St. Laurent public school system. The student body has changed
considerably at Emile Legault, which rests under the low-flying
planes that make their way into nearby Dorval Airport. When Bourque
was a student there, Leduc said, the pupils were 100 percent
French-Canadian. Today, 99 percent are immigrants, representing 78
nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about retiring, I begin to choke,'' said Leduc,
looking around his office, the walls adorned with posters of
Bourque mixed in among some of the Olympic runners he has trained.
``I like my job. When I leave this office _ there are a lot of
stories here _ I'll have some tears.''
</P>
<P>
   If he does retire, Leduc would like to join an NHL team and work
with players who want to take their training seriously. The Bruins
last year sent him Jonathan Girard, their top pick in the '98
draft, and they've already seen the positive impact it has made on
his game. Ryan Milanovic, another Boston draft pick last season, is
expected to sign on with Leduc soon.
</P>
<P>
   Leduc began a track club, Regina Mundi (Queen of the World),
here about the same time he first met Bourque. He has worked with
some 800 runners at the club and, conservatively, figures he's
worked with 10,000 high schoolers in his 32 years at Emile Legault.
</P>
<P>
   ``I adopted Ray like a son, you know?'' said Leduc, who is
single and openly muses about the chance he'll one day start a
family. ``I never thought he'd be the star that he turned out to
be. But, he is an Olympian, a true NHL star. Of all the athletes
I've trained, he's the best, the most consistent athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   When the two spoke recently, Bourque told Leduc that this will
be the last summer program he'll have to design for him. Luduc has
learned to take lightly those kinds or remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was with him last summer, when he was on the program,'' said
Leduc, laughing at the recollection. ``He turned to me and he said,
`I hate you!' And I said, `What? I love you . . . and you hate me?'
He said it was the program. And I said, `Yeah, well you are 37
years old, it gets a little tougher.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The training for season No. 21 begins any day now. The Bruins
open the 1999-2000 training camp in about 10 weeks. Leduc will have
him start with some light running on Day 1, followed by a bike ride
in Day 2. He'll arrive in Wilmington, once more, the
best-conditioned athlete in camp. He'll skate in reverse faster
than some rookies, 20 years his junior, skate forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I push him to the limit,'' said Leduc. ``But you don't really
have to push Raymond. He is the horse that always wants to do more.
I tell him to run eight 200-yard sprints, and he calls to tell me
he's run nine. But that's OK, because I wanted nine _ that's why I
told him eight; I know my customer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
