<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9380 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BOURQUE &LR;      06-25 1376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BOURQUE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS HIT LOTTERY WITH BOURQUE PICK IN '79 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (itals)some experience, I'd like to be as good as Brad Park,
(Larry) Robinson, (Denis) Potvin, those guys. That's what I'll be
working for. Still a long way to go.''(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   _ Ray Bourque, Nov. 16, 1979 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Ray Bourque's name has been synonymous with the cream
of the National Hockey League crop since he came to Boston in 1979.
It's a given that Bourque will play 30 or more minutes a game, be
the quarterback on the power play, be the target of the opposing
team, and be the Bruins' best player. For 20 years, that's been as
consistent as the sun rising in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   He is a sports rarity; he has always been a Bruin and he has
declared that he will always be a Bruin. But there was a time when
there was a chance he might have been something else _ a budding
legend in another uniform. Hard to fathom, yes, but true.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, the league was in transition, folding four World Hockey
Association teams into the NHL. The newcomers were Quebec City,
Hartford, Edmonton, and Winnipeg and the minimum draft age was
lowered from 19 to 18.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike in recent years, there was no hoopla, no podium, no live
TV coverage, no cross-continent press junkets when Bourque was
taken that year with the No. 8 pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all done by phone,'' said Bourque, who will be honored
Saturday for the 20th anniversary of his draft year. ``I remember I
was teaching a hockey school in the afternoon and being called off
the ice, where I had a call from my agent saying I was drafted
eighth overall by the Bruins. Then I got the call from Bruins
management and then I talked to the press on the phone. We didn't
get to step up to the podium and have your name announced in front
of the full building. But it was nice.''
</P>
<P>
   The year before, Boston had dealt Ron Grahame to Los Angeles for
the Kings' pick, which wound up being Bourque.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles general manager Dave Taylor, who played 17 years for
the Kings (1977-94), could have been a Bourque teammate. ``Who's to
say that we would have picked Ray Bourque?'' said Taylor. ``But it
was a great pick by the Bruins . . . and all the credit should go
to Ray Bourque. He should have gone No. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   In any other year, it's likely he would have, but
president/general manager Harry Sinden said that teams picking
before Boston opted for the more experienced WHA players such as
defenseman Rob Ramage, who was taken with the No. 1 pick overall by
Colorado. The other defensemen taken before Bourque were Craig
Hartsburg, now the Anaheim Mighty Ducks coach who was grabbed by
Minnesota with the No. 6 pick, and Keith Brown, who was taken by
Chicago at No. 7. The Bruins had interest in Brown, too, but once
he was gone, Bourque was the only player Boston considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had him rated seventh and not because he was the seventh
best player,'' said Sinden of the man who now holds the Bruins'
all-time scoring record. ``But we felt (other teams) would go for
these WHA guys. We thought Raymond should be rated No. 7 and we had
the No. 8 pick and therefore we thought we'd probably have to take
Brown. But Chicago took Brown and Bourque ended up going eighth. We
had Keith Brown right there but there would've been a huge argument
at the table, and I think (head scout) Gary Darling would've won
out because he was a Ray Bourque guy. That's what I remember about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike today's draft setup, Bourque said he didn't interview
with a dozen or so teams. The only hint he had that the Bruins
wanted him was a call from Darling saying the club had interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't really say much more than that,'' said Bourque.
``That's the way it worked out. I didn't care where or which round.
I kind of knew I was going to go in the first round and probably
the first half of the first round, but I didn't know where or to
who. I didn't really care.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Bourque was rooting for his hometown Canadiens
against the Bruins during the second round of the playoffs in 1979.
The Habs wound up winning the Cup in five games over the New York
Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched the Bruins lose to Montreal in overtime of the
seventh game and I remember going by the Forum that night and kind
of giving it (a fist pump), yelling, `Yes, sir!' '' said Bourque.
``I was cheering for Montreal. A few months later, I was going to
Boston. It was kind of weird there was such a rivalry there. I was
going to the bad guys but a lot of people left Montreal with me
that day and became Bruins fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Darling, now in the real estate business in Peterborough,
Ontario, said it was clear early on that Bourque was special.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was like a young racehorse, all ready to win the Kentucky
Derby or the Triple Crown,'' said Darling. ``He was a free-wheeling
skater with great hockey sense and great puck sense. He could turn
on a dime and had a good heavy shot. He was very agile at that
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Darling said he spoke to Chicago's scouting staff the night
before the draft in an effort to detect whom the Blackhawks were
planning to take at No. 7, but he said the club wouldn't tip its
hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted Ray Bourque but we didn't know if he was going to
last or not,'' said Darling. ``It was fortunate for the Bruins that
he was available.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Darling was very high on Bourque from watching him play
with his junior team in Verdun of the Quebec League, he said there
was no way to predict just how remarkable a career Bourque would
have.
</P>
<P>
   ``A guy who plays 20 years in the league has got to be a
racehorse and he is a horse,'' said Darling. ``This is what you
hope for when you draft them, that they will be a star and they
will play for your club their whole career. I don't know when the
last time this has happened. It makes you feel proud that you could
draft someone like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Craig Hartsburg was a pretty good hockey player, Rob Ramage
was a good player, Mike Gartner. That was a pretty good draft. Ray
was by far the best talent that was available at No. 8. We liked
Keith Brown, too, don't ask me who we were going to take.'' When it
came time to negotiate a contract, Sinden said he was put in an
unusual predicament. The late Rodrig Lemoyne, owner and coach of
Bourque's Verdun junior team, was Bourque's agent, and when he and
Sinden met at the Montreal airport to talk about a deal, Sinden was
stunned at Lemoyne's tack.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a prosecuting attorney or district attorney in Sorel,''
said Sinden. ``He bragged about how he handled murderers and
rapists and not to fool with him. It was really strange. When we
got to talking contract with him, it was more than a veiled threat
to me that unless he could get the contract he wanted, I'd better
keep my eyes open as I walked around Montreal. I said, `Well, I
have friends here, too, and if you break my legs, I'm going to have
to have yours broken and now we've both got broken legs and the kid
doesn't have a contract. I knew his reputation by that time. He'd
been around a rough crowd and he was a little strange.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque said Lemoyne, while unconventional, wasn't all bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't always stick to the book when it came down to
negotiations, obviously,'' said Bourque. ``But in other ways, I
knew him a lot more than maybe some other people and he had another
side to him. As controversial as he was, he was a troubled man.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden said he is grateful for his association with Bourque over
the past 20 years, not only for Bourque's Hall-of-Fame caliber
career but for his off-ice class and leadership that is rare not
only in pro sports but in life. In that fateful fall of 1979, when
Bourque first started, Sinden said he had a hint of just what was
to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I saw him at a Bruins' practice at training
camp, I knew we had something special, I knew it,'' said Sinden.
``I didn't know it was going to be this special, 20 years of
excellence, but I knew he was a special player. Having done it so
long and so well, that in itself separates him from almost anybody.
That he was a Norris Trophy finalist at 38 makes him one of the
most incredible players the league has ever had.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
