<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9388 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-ISSUES-BOS &LR;      06-25 1509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-ISSUES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BOSNIA, A LESSON FOR KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARAJEVO, Bosnia and Herzegovina _ In a region of strange
intersections, the crossroads of Krtolji surely is one of the most
bizarre.
</P>
<P>
   Huge, horse-drawn haywagons compete for space on the roads with
air-conditioned busloads of Italian carabinieri on their way to
patrol duty. Farmers labor with 18th-century tools as passenger
aircraft and jet fighters zoom overhead.
</P>
<P>
   Off in one direction from the crossroads, the people of Sarajevo
work and live in an area that is part of the Federation of Bosnia
and Herzegovina, a nation-within-the-nation of Bosnia and
Herzegovina, where most citizens are Muslims or Croats. Off the
other way, former Sarajevans peddle pirated software at the gateway
to Republika Srpska, a separate nation-within-the-nation where
almost everyone is Serb.
</P>
<P>
   Among modest cinderblock-and-tile houses being rebuilt by
Muslims here and Serbs there, construction teams are raising a
huge, ultramodern barracks complex for the United Nations
stabilization force for Bosnia, a mute but convincing testament to
the conviction of 37 participating governments that they will be
trying to keep the peace in this shattered land for a long, long
time.
</P>
<P>
   This is the topsy-turvy world of Bosnia under the Dayton
accords, the peace agreement that, in 1995, ended the worst
European war of the last half-century. The agreement's shortcomings
provide a sobering preview of what lies ahead for the United States
and NATO in Kosovo if would-be peacemakers continue to equivocate
about disarming the Kosovo Liberation Army and controlling the
province's Serb minority the way they waffled and shied away from
hard decisions in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   There is an inherent contradiction between a multiethnic society
and an ethnically divided one, said Albert Rohan, secretary general
of the Austrian foreign ministry and a highly experienced diplomat
in the Balkans. The attempt of Dayton negotiators to have it both
ways, to create a state built around the rights of ethnic groups
but still guaranteeing Western-style individual rights, made Dayton
a document that cannot be implemented, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a serious problem in the law,'' said Vildana Helic, a
judge in the city of Tuzla and president of the League of Women
Voters of Bosnia and Herzegovina. ``Why would a Serb choose to be a
minority in the federation'' rather than a majority in Republika
Srpska? ``Why would a Croat or Muslim choose to be a minority in
Republika Srpska'' rather than a majority in the federation?
</P>
<P>
   The result is that there has been almost no progress toward the
goal of reestablishing a multicultural, multiethnic state.
</P>
<P>
   Judged by the goal of stopping 3 1/2 years of slaughter, the
accords are a clear success; Bosnia, said Jacques Klein, the
French-American soldier-diplomat who oversees Dayton implementation
as second in command in the Office of the High Representative,
``has a lower level of violence than many countries in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   But by any other standard, success is hard to claim.
</P>
<P>
   --Returning refugees and internally displaced people to their
original homes was supposed to be a primary goal, and throughout
the region there is widespread sentiment in support of this goal.
But almost all the refugees who have come back to Bosnia have
settled into communities in which they are in the ethnic majority;
those who lived in communities where they were minorities generally
are staying away.
</P>
<P>
   --Evolution of a unified central government, with participation
by Muslims, Serbs, and Croats, was another top priority. But the
central government hardly functions and the tripartite presidency,
as one military source put it, ``only meets when it's told to (by
foreign administrators) to meet foreign dignitaries.'' Republika
Srpska functions as an independent country, and in the rest of the
country Muslims and Croats, mostly Roman Catholics, are at one
another's throats.
</P>
<P>
   --Reconciliation among the peoples is no more than a concept on
paper. With the exception of some courageous nongovernmental
organizations, such as the League of Women Voters, national social
and political organizations do not exist. Dialogue among the ethnic
groups ranges from cool to cold.
</P>
<P>
   However, said Jakob Finci, head of the Soros Foundation's Open
Society Fund, which is promoting development of democracy and civic
institutions in Bosnia, ``there is no Holy Bible for this country
but the Dayton peace accord. Without Dayton, there is no Bosnia.''
</P>
<P>
   There are some notable developments that look like steps
forward: adoption of a new flag and national anthem that are not
identified with any ethnic group; a fully convertible national
currency pegged to the German mark; and new license plates that do
not identify which entity a car is from _ or, by implication, the
ethnicity of its owner.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, none of these steps were arrived at through
deliberations among the leaders of the Serbs, Muslims, and Croats.
Instead, the leaders objected and delayed until the issues were
resolved by the Office of the High Representative.
</P>
<P>
   Finci, a Jew, and one of a very few people able to run relief
supplies into Sarajevo during the siege of 1992-95, reflects the
confusion of many when he both embraces Dayton yet wonders at the
nature of an agreement that precludes him from running for high
office because he is not Serb, Muslim, or Croat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not so foolish as to run,'' he said, ``but what is the
human rights meaning of this? It is absolutely contradictory to all
the human rights resolutions and declarations. . . . It was just
the only way to have peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Dayton stopped the violence but did not end the war, said Klein,
asserting that the agreement in certain ways ``empowered the
warlords'' by creating a system in which most people are encouraged
to vote along ethnic lines. Many Bosnians also note that there has
been relatively little change within the ethnic groups from the
leadership that took them into war.
</P>
<P>
   The problems with Dayton are practical as well as conceptual.
Although roughly 31,000 troops from about three dozen nations are
in the United Nations-sanctioned, NATO-led peacekeeping force, in
general their commanders have shied away from aggressive pursuit of
indicted war criminals and other operations that could lead to
casualties.
</P>
<P>
   As long as an indicted war criminal like former Bosnia Serb
leader Radovan Karadzic remains free, ``it displays the impotence
of the international community,'' Klein said. ``It says, what can
you do? What is your authority?''
</P>
<P>
   He lashes out at what he sees as an overemphasis on avoiding
casualties, saying the international forces ``are professionals,
well trained and well equipped, and you expect to take losses. If
you aren't willing to take losses, you can't do the job and
shouldn't accept the assignment.''
</P>
<P>
   Swanee Hunt, who became deeply involved in Bosnian issues during
her tenure as US ambassador to Austria, calls the failure to
apprehend the war criminals inexcusable, and says it is a major
reason people do not return to their homes in areas where their
ethnic groups are minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not safe,'' Hunt said. ``We have indicted war criminals
who are still on the police forces, or running around as
rabble-rousers.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there are serious problems which cannot be
attributed to flaws in the peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Europeans pledged $20 billion to rebuild
the country, but only $5 billion ever came in, according to the
Office of the High Representative. Now, governments and
nongovernmental relief agencies alike are starting to turn their
attention to Kosovo and Serbia, where more recent fighting has
occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Also, here, as in Croatia, domestic politicians and foreigners
alike may have been mistaken in their approach to privatizing
businesses and housing, both of which were largely state-owned in
the communist era that preceeded the Balkan wars.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all these problems, there are some hopeful signs. Many
here say the recent NATO bombardment of Serbia over the expulsion
of ethnic Albanians in Kosovo is a plus, likely to make residents
of Republika Srpska happier about being part of Bosnia than an
appendage of a devastated Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   And there is the attitude of young people like Peda Skopljak,
25, one of the Serbs selling computer programs and music on CD
Alley, as the pirated software zone at the Krtolji entrance to
Republika Srpska is known.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I go to Sarajevo, and relax, and look in the
beautiful shops,'' he said. ``Right after the war, I thought that
was impossible. Today it is normal. I worried at first how my
friends would react, but everything was normal. . . . We are all
aware we didn't wish for this war. Nobody asked us.''
</P>
<P>
   Finci, however, warns that ``some politicians think (the Dayton
era) is just a cease-fire, and that when it is over they will
finish the war.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-99 1332EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990625.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9389 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS &LR;      06-25 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER CURE, TOLHURST IN `PROPER MODE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lol Tolhurst spent more than a decade as a rock star. He was the
co-founder, with Robert Smith, of the angsty new wave dance band
the Cure. They rose from cultdom and clubs to selling millions of
records and packing arenas. For Tolhurst, a
drummer-turned-keyboardist, that ended in 1989, when his former
pal, Smith, sacked him for excessive substance abuse.
</P>
<P>
   You want motivation? Here's motivation. ``Part of the reason I'm
doing this,'' says Tolhurst, who has put together a new group,
Levinhurst with his wife, Cindy Levinson, ``is I want to prove to
the people who hate me that I'm still alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Tolhurst sued Smith and the Cure after his ousting, but he now
says, they ``were pretty justified because I was pretty out of it.
Without trying to justify what I did I think people kind of expect
musicians to stare into the abyss for them an unfortunately I fell
into it for a while. I had a little time afterward to reflect and I
thought I'd go and see if there was a way to sort things out. I was
finding out myself that I was at the wrong end of the bottle and a
lot of other things, too. I checked into rehab, the same place that
Eric Clapton went to - at least there's a little musical
pedigree.''
</P>
<P>
   Tolhurst re-entered the music scene in the early '90s, forming a
band called Presence, which had little. The group recorded two
albums, released one and did not make a mark. Looking back,
Tolhurst says he came back too quickly _ ``my psyche or my soul
wasn't repaired enough by that point.'' After Presence, Tolhurst
tinkered with ``bits and pieces,'' did some low level
soundtracking.
</P>
<P>
   Levinhurst came together almost by accident. Tolhurst, who lives
in Los Angeles, was introduced to his future wife by a friend. ``As
we got further into the relationship,'' Tolhurst says, ``music
became one of the main driving forces. I guess I heard her singing
in the shower or in the garden and thought `There is something very
powerful there.' I don't look a gift horse in the mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   Levinhurst has recorded a six-song CD, which they'll sell at
shows. Tolhurst explains what to expect at shows: ``The show is in
three parts, what happened then, and what it's like now. We're
remixing some of the old Cure songs, then there's a half hour of
Levinhurst material and then a half hour of current stuff. At this
stage, it's just me and Cindy, with (former Cure drummer) Andy
Anderson, who's waiting for his visa to come through. The set-up is
this: The whole thing is sequenced and I play little lines here and
there. It's pretty electronic at this stage, but there's structure
and hopefully it holds a little melody. It reminds me of how I
started with the Cure, the do-it-yourself punk thing. This is the
real deal. This is me back in the proper mode.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WHERE HE HANGS HIS HAT IS HIS HOME: Dr. John, the Night Tripper,
is a roadhog, playing upwards of 250 gigs a year, tossing out his
New Orleans-deep-fried funk and hoodoo magic. He enjoys his nomadic
life, but says, ``I never have expectations about anything; I've
beeen in this racket too long to have any expectations.'' Which
sounds either cynical or practical.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little of both,'' says Dr. John. ``Getting to the gigs
can be a nighmare, but the gigs, when we play, we always have a
good time. That's what our job is, we get paid to have a good time
and we take a lot of pride in making people get up and dance.''
</P>
<P>
   But the good doctor can do more than that. He contributed key
parts to the English space-rock band Spiritualized's ``Ladies and
Gentleman, We are Floating in Space'' album. Just as a lot of the
veteran musicians took the young Dr. John under their wing as a
session man early in his career _ the Rolling Stones, Bob Dylan,
Van Morrison _ he enjoys the role of older statesman playing with
younger, different bands. ``I like all kinds of music,'' he says.
``They called me up about doing the session. They sent me a tape, I
thought it would be different from what the end result was'' but
that's part of the business.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John, like George W. Bush, 'fesses up to youthful
indiscretions _ ``I had a lot of legal and illiegal things going as
a teeenager'' _ and beat a heroin addiction ten years ago. Did the
drugs feed the music, did the music feed the drugs? ``I didn't have
a lot of time to reflect on that. You go where life takes you. I
chose a few paths that were probably not the best moves, but when
you're younger you make some rebellious, foolhardy maneuvers, drugs
and other things that go with that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Grammy-winning Dr. John, whose latest album is ``Anutha
Zone,'' calls his group Lower 911, 911 standing for the emergency
police number and Lower 9 standing for a particularly notorious
area of Louisiana. The show starts at noon. Also on the bill are
Entrain, Boogaloo Swamis, Fat City, the Shods, Dell and Exit In.
Tix are $12. It all takes place on the North Lawn behind the Tsongs
Arena on the banks of the Merrimack River.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
