<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV27-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USE MORTAR TO FILL GARAGE WALL HOLES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 27, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. The plastered walls of my basement garage have holes, and I
would like to plug them. The plaster doesn't look like plaster, but
a rougher finish, and I can see metal lath behind the holes. How
can I fill them?
</P>
<P>
   JOE REARDON, Newton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Those walls are mortar, basically concrete, set on the wire
lath. This is necessary to make the walls between garage and living
space or basement fire resistant, required by code.
</P>
<P>
   Fill the holes with Mortar Mix, a ready-mixed Sakrete product
(just add water) sold in hardware and building stores. If the metal
lath behind the holes is intact, press in the mortar; it will ooze
through the lath for a good hold. If there is no wire lath visible,
install hardware cloth, a quarter-inch steel mesh that will hold
the mortar equally well. If there is a stud behind the hole, nail
the hardware cloth to the stud. If there is no stud, jam the
hardware cloth into the hole, about halfway into its depth. To make
the new mortar match the wall finish, rub it with a wood board
after it begins to set up, usually in about 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Mike Brooks of Marlborough, Mass. called to ask why a
pressure-relief valve failed each time he installed one on his new
water heater, the handyman suggested he have a pro install it, then
blame the pro if it fails.
</P>
<P>
   The correct answer was to have a pro install a valve, but Joe
Green of Chelmsford, Mass., a plumbing inspector for three towns,
took exception to the rather facetious remark about blaming the pro
if it fails.
</P>
<P>
   Green added some reasons why the valve failed: If it is
dribbling, it may be due to too high a water pressure. If that
happens, install a pressure-reducing valve on the water inlet,
right at the meter. If the valve goes off like a shot, the water is
too hot, said Green. If that is the case, you should replace or
repair the gas valve, if it is a gas-fired unit, to control the
heat. If it is electric, the energy source should be fixed or
replaced, Green said.
</P>
<P>
   Good point, Joe Green, and the handyman has placed your name and
phone number in his files for future reference. And, installation
of valves and water heaters should be done by a professional. But
let's not blame anyone.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I countersunk the fasteners on my deck boards. Some are shiny
and some are not, giving everything an uneven look. Will a sealer
or stain even out that shininess? The countersunk holes are 3/8
inch in diameter. Some of the wood is discolored. Will a
semitransparent stain cover the wood evenly?
</P>
<P>
   BILL FITZGERALD, Taunton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. A sealer or semitransparent stain will dull the fasteners,
but not for long. Your best bet is to fill the 3/8-inch holes with
dowels, then stain the whole deck. Tap a 3/8-inch dowel into each
hole and cut it off with a flexible saw, such as a Japanese saw
that will cut the dowel off flush with the deck without serious
scratching.
</P>
<P>
   As for the stain covering the discolored wood, it depends on
what the discoloration is. If the wood is weathered, the stain will
cover fairly evenly. If the discoloration is mildew, the mildew
will grow right through the stain, making things even worse. If it
is mildew, wash the deck with a solution of one part household
bleach and three parts water. Let dry, then rinse and let dry
before you stain. Wear skin and eye protection when working with
bleach.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My three aluminum storm doors have jalousie windows. The
metal was spray painted brown, but now the brown is wearing off and
the brown is discolored. How can I repaint them? Are there any
companies that do this?
</P>
<P>
   ELEANOR McMANUS, Hyde Park, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. It's too bad the doors were painted, because painting
aluminum doors is always iffy. And, if a dark color is put over a
light color, or vice versa, if the new paint fails it will look
terrible because of the high contrast bewteen the two colors. But
to repaint, sand the finish as thoroughly as necesary to remove any
loose paint, roughen the finish and reduce gloss. Wash with paint
thinner. Then apply an oil-based primer and finish up with a spray
enamel. There are also companies who might be able to do it, too;
at least they do appliances and tile. Find one in the Yellow Pages
under ``Appliances _ Household Refinishing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My pressure-treated deck was installed eight years ago. The
installer said there was no need to treat it. He was right; it is
still in good shape. So why do so many sealer makers recommend
putting a clear sealer on it?
</P>
<P>
   JEAN MELANSON, Melrose, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Because they want to sell sealer. Well, that is not quite
fair, because sealer is recommended to make the wood
water-resistant to prevent splitting, splintering, and cracking of
the wood. Pressure-treated wood is green; that is, full of water,
and when it dries out and shrinks, it tends to split, splinter and
crack.
</P>
<P>
   I think you lucked out on your deck; the wood might have been
dry when it was installed, so it resisted cracking and splintering.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
