<HEADLINE>
KNICKS GUARD TRYING TO WARD OFF CRITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No one has taken more abuse during the NBA Finals than Knicks
guard Charlie Ward.
</P>
<P>
   OK. Maybe Larry Johnson. But he brings most of it on himself.
</P>
<P>
   Ward is different. As NBC's Bob Costas rightly points out, no
one questions Ward's athletic ability. He won the 1993 Heisman
Trophy as quarterback of Florida State, and the New York Yankees
and Milwaukee Brewers were interested in him. But he chose
basketball, and before the beginning of this season, he committed
himself to the sport for the long run, signing a five-year, $30
million deal with the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Costas raises the right question about Ward,
asking, ``Is he an NBA point guard?''
</P>
<P>
   During the first quarter of Game 4 against the Spurs Wednesday
night, Ward played like one. After the guard hit a surprising
3-pointer, Costas quipped, ``Ward has done next to nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Next thing anyone knew, Ward was, as analyst Doug Collins said,
``feeling it.'' Even Costas had to grudgingly acknowledge Ward's
play, saying, ``What's up with Charlie Ward tonight? He's a new man
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins pointed out that Ward was taking advantage of a matchup
that forced aging Steve Kerr to guard him. Ward was such a force
that Collins questioned why coach Jeff Van Gundy played injured
guard Chris Childs throughout the majority of the second quarter.
``Ward is playing really well, and I wouldn't let him sit out too
long,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   Ward reentered the game with about four minutes remaining in the
quarter. He finished the half with 10 points, three steals, two
assists, and, most important, no turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Isiah Thomas gave Ward a little respect during NBC's halftime
report, saying he had enrgeized his team with his scoring and
defensive play. ``Ward is keeping the Knicks involved,'' Thomas
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Walton wouldn't have any of it. A long-standing critic of
Ward, Walton dismissed Ward's performance, saying that for $30
million the team deserves as much. ``How about my man Charlie
Ward?'' Walton joked. ``Thirty million dollars, a couple of buckets
in a half of a half, PLEASE.''
</P>
<P>
   The real reason that the Knicks had remained close, Walton
argued, was that Spurs guard Avery Johnson and center David
Robinson had been on the bench for a significant portion of the
second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Ward soon would prove Walton right. He had a chance to tie the
game late in the fourth quarter with two free throws, but he made
only one. He then committed a turnover when the Knicks were trying
to stage a comeback. After going 4 for 4 in the first half, he
missed all five of his second-half shots.
</P>
<P>
   At least Ward is a decent guy. Unlike Johnson, who has been
abused by Tim Duncan throughout the series, Ward knows enough to
shut up and let his play do the talking.
</P>
<P>
   It's too bad he doesn't have much to talk about.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Finals rate
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night's game earned a 4.8 rating and 8 share in Boston
. . . Ratings for NHL playoff telecasts on ESPN increased by 16
percent from last year. ESPN aired three games of the Stanley Cup
final and earned a 3.09 rating; last year's games pulled a 2.65.
The three games were seen in 2.3 million housholds, up by 21
percent from last year's 1.9 million . . . ESPN's annual award show
is moving to the MGM Grand in Las Vegas this year. The ESPYs have
been at New York's Radio City Music Hall for the last seven years .
. . CBS's 12-game college football season starts with a
doubleheader Sept. 18: Penn State vs. Miami at 3:30 p.m., and two
regional 8 p.m. games (defending national champion Tennessee at
Florida, and Michigan at Syracuse). Sean McDonough serves as lead
play-by-play announcer, Todd Blackledge as lead game analyst. Tim
Brando hosts ``College Football Today,'' with Spencer Tillman . . .
CBS will air the Army-Navy game Dec. 4 . . . The Globe's Michael
Holley talks about sports journalism on ``Kids Talk Sports'' Sunday
at 7 p.m. on New England Cable News . . . ESPN's ``SportsCentury''
is coming to the Natick Mall July 16-17. The interactive exhibit
allows fans to see vintage photographs of the century's most
memorable moments, and make play-by-play calls on classic moments .
. . CBS will make television history by airing the Pepsi 400 July 3
at 8 p.m. It will be the first time a network televises an auto
race live in prime time. Greg Gumbel will host the three-hour show,
with Ken Squier. Mike Joy will handle the race call from Daytona
Beach, while Ned Jarrett and Buddy Baker will provide analysis.
</P>
