<HEADER>
A9399 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OVERWORKED-LIFE-BOS &LR;      06-25 1350
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OVERWORKED-LIFE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVERDRIVE ECONOMY GIVES FEW A CHANCE TO SLOW DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Through the open cabin door, John Goodhue can spy a sparkling
wedge of Purity Lake. Just out of sight, his 8-year-old son paddles
in a canoe near shore.
</P>
<P>
   This would be an idyllic summer scene _ save one small matter:
Goodhue is on the telephone with a coworker about a presentation
he's giving the next day at work. ``I promised it was going to be
an hour, and it was two,'' Goodhue says sheepishly about the call
on a recent Sunday afternoon from a New Hampshire resort he visited
with his wife and son.
</P>
<P>
   Goodhue, as chief engineer of a Chelmsford, Mass. unit of Cisco
Systems, is a busy man, and he has lots of company.
</P>
<P>
   With the United States well into its eighth year of a boisterous
expansion, demands placed on workers by their customers, clients,
and coworkers are unrelenting as the economy barrels along, month
after month.
</P>
<P>
   While economists crow about the rising productivity of US
workers, workplace experts say that many people are working harder
as well as longer hours. The arrival of summer has brought little
relief from the hectic pace of life at work.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Americans, in the view of other cultures, have
always been ``overworked.'' Italy has its lunch feasts; Mexico, its
siestas.
</P>
<P>
   But, there may be some new truth in Americans' longstanding
reputation. With US unemployment at a 29-year low of 4.2 percent _
Massachusetts' rate is an even lower 3.1 percent _ employers cannot
find enough people to handle all the work coming in the door.
Employees are being asked to do more _ often they are expected to.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to find workers. Labor is scarce and expensive.
People are working harder,'' said David Wyss, chief economist for
Standard &AMP; Poor's/DRI, a Lexington, Mass. consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Few begrudge a heavier workload, which is far better than being
unemployed. And a booming economy creates new opportunities,
promotions, and higher pay for those able to take advantage of it.
Yet, professionals interviewed for this article said they are being
called on to squeeze more into a single day's work.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Baressi describes her job as a juggling act.
</P>
<P>
   As marketing director for Shuster Laboratories, which tests
products for consumer-goods companies, ``I'm juggling multiple
marketing events, multiple direct mailings, multiple strategic
plans,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Baressi was so busy on a recent Tuesday morning that she walked
around Shuster's Quincy, Mass. office for at least an hour before
another executive discreetly mentioned the mint-green dress she had
worn to work was on backward. Despite the stresses of work, Baressi
can't ignore the opportunities presented by a strong economy, which
helped boost revenue by nearly a third last year at Shuster, a
wholly owned subsidiary of Colorado-based Hauser Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a big opportunity out there,'' she said, and ``you
have to do the work to get the business.''
</P>
<P>
   In theory, a tight labor market should give workers more _ not
less _ clout with employers. But Lena Lundgren, director of the
Center on Work and Family at Boston University, said employees who
are asked to work late or to do more work have ``difficulty saying
`no.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the economy is strong, many retain a mindset adopted
when times were bad, and they were afraid of losing their jobs, she
said. ``It's very difficult to move away from that,'' Lundgren
said.
</P>
<P>
   Jayne Burke works a 10-hour day as partner and consultant for
PricewaterhouseCoopers _ her days are much longer when she is
traveling to see the firm's clients scattered all over the country.
</P>
<P>
   Burke said that it sometimes seems everyone _ her clients,
coworkers and herself _ are ``trying to do more than one job.''
Because clients face extreme time pressures, this, in turn,
``forces me to be extra efficient. Everybody's pace is extremely
high right now.''
</P>
<P>
   James Erb, whose carpentry crew was renovating a house in
Cambridge, Mass. last week, can tell you all about that.
</P>
<P>
   Erb said he regrettably turned down a handful of jobs during the
past month _ he's been unable to find skilled workers to increase
the size of his crew. To keep up with the jobs he does take on, Erb
and his four employees are in overdrive. ``We work eight hours but
in that eight hours, we're actually getting nine or 10 hours of
work done,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Economists have a word for accomplishing more in a set period of
time: productivity.
</P>
<P>
   Productivity of US workers _ the amount of goods workers produce
for each hour of work _ surged 2.6 percent during the year ended
March 1999. That's a sharp rise from a 1 percent gain in
productivity in 1997. Through the 1980s, productivity growth
averaged less than 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Technology is a major force pushing up productivity in recent
years, economists say. With personal computers and high-speed
equipment on the factory floor, employees are empowered to
accomplish more at work.
</P>
<P>
   But while productivity is way up, the government statistics do
not accurately measure the productivity of many white-collar
professionals. That's because government statistics assume that
salaried workers put in the same 41.8-hour week as do workers paid
by the hour. About one-fourth of the US work force is in salaried
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If salaried workers are putting in a lot more overtime, that
gives you an artificial boost to productivity,'' Wyss said.
</P>
<P>
   Workplace experts say surveys of salaried managers clearly show
that they are working more than a 40-hour week _ and would like to
reduce their time at work. Kathleen Christensen, a research
director for the Alfred P. Sloan Foundation in New York who
specializes in work-family issues, said a study sponsored by her
organization found that well-educated professionals and managers
``increasingly are at risk of working 50-plus hours'' but are
compensated for only 40 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, both men and women executives and managers seem to view
the eight-hour day as a quaint convention, one that is unrealistic.
That is true especially in fast-growing companies, such as i-Cube,
a Cambridge consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Madden, an i-Cube vice president, said a 10-hour day is
``standard.'' She added, ``Sometimes it's 12. Sometimes it's
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, technology, which is credited with boosting productivity,
can create a longer day for executives _ both at the office and
away from it.
</P>
<P>
   Laptop computers free executives to travel more _ they can take
their office with them. Cell phones and voice mail mean the phone
calls and messages stream in, nonstop, when they are in meetings
and continue at night, on weekends, and on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Goodhue travels nearly every week for his employer. During a
typical week in June, Goodhue caught a 7:30 a.m. flight from Logan
Intrernational Airport and arrived, midmorning, in San Jose,
Calif., Cisco System's headquarters. When he returned to Boston, he
spent the night in own bed but took off the next morning for Nova
Scotia to visit a customer there. He returned on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   When he's on the road, a laptop computer and briefcase are his
office. He answers e-mail while in flight and listens to phone
messages when driving to the office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always looking for dead time where I couldn't be doing
anything else,'' he says. ``That's where I try to fit in the extra
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Thelma Sullivan can tell you all about fitting in the extra
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   For the publisher of The Black Pages, a directory of African
American-owned businesses in New England, a strong economy is a
mixed blessing. While advertising revenues are up 20 percent in two
years, Sullivan has had no luck in her search for two qualified
people to hire. To cope, she said, ``My day has to be really
structured to get more done.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan's work days spill into evenings and Saturdays. Sundays,
her day of rest, are where she draws the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything not done on Saturdays,'' Sullivan said, ``can wait
until Mondays.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
