<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV27-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BALANCED PORTFOLIO CONTAINS GROWTH AND INCOME ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 27, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am 66 years old and my wife is 63. We are both retired. Our
combined Social Security is $1,295 a month and my pension provides
a further $1,033. In addition to these sources of income, I
withdraw $500 a month from our other investments. We have a total
of $142,000 in IRA accounts, mostly invested in stock mutual funds,
and $384,232 in taxable investments, all in individual stocks
except a $94,000 CD and $10,000 in a money market fund. My goal is
to be able to withdraw $10,000 a year for living expenses, without
touching the principal. How would you allocate these investments?
Should I start withdrawing from my IRA?
</P>
<P>
   C.G., Newton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. The way I like to see a retirement portfolio set up to
provide an income stream is to create two distinct segments of the
portfolio -- one for growth and the other for the income. Your
example is quite tidy, since if all of your various IRA holdings
were consolidated into a fixed-income portfolio, it might provide a
$9,230 annual income stream, presuming a 6.5 percent average
portfolio yield. If you simply withdrew the yield from such a
portfolio, you could make up the differences through withdrawals
from the money market fund on the taxable side of the portfolio.
The effect would be that you'd have $274,232, or a little more than
half of your savings, remaining in stocks -- sufficient to protect
you against the likely effect of inflation during the latter years
of your retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Most mutual fund families offer funds in the categories I'd
suggest, which is roughly a quarter in either a money market fund
or a short-term corporate bond fund, 50 percent in a GNMA or
government securities fund, and the final quarter in a high-yield
(or ``junk'') bond fund.
</P>
<P>
   In a perfect world, it would probably be best to sell some of
your individual stock holdings to establish the fixed-income fund,
but the Internal Revenue Service codes have gone a long way to
render this world imperfect. Thus I would make all of the sales
within the IRAs, where there will be no short-term tax effect. This
will have the side effect of reducing your portfolio
diversification, since your stock market exposure will be in the 12
blue chip stocks you now hold. So I would slowly correct this by
reinvesting all of the dividends from the stocks in a mutual funds,
beginning with a Standard and Poor's 500 Index fund such as
Fidelity Spartan Market Index or Vanguard Index 500, and once that
position is solidly established, broadening out into more diverse
holdings such as you currently hold in the IRA.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Are there others like myself, aged 73, who might bee
interested in a safe parking place for funds from the sale of a
home, in the range of $125,000 to $150,000. I have been out of the
market since 1988, having been burned during the period from 1965
to 1980 when the stock market slumped, and I am not interested in
entering it at the high end. How about Fidelity Government
Securities? Municipal bonds? I don't want to risk the money, which,
along with a 401(k) account, is earmarked for my children and
grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   T.I., Baldwinville, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Fidelity Government Securities fund changed its name to
Fidelity Government Income last fall. Although it's been having
some tough sledding recently, it has a solid enough long-term
record. So rather than focus on its scant 1.49 percent 12-month
total return, or its 3.13 percent year-to-date loss, you might
consider the longer records -- an average annual total return of
6.55 percent over the past five years, and an 8.15 percent record
over a decade. Reflecting the tough recent results, it has been
downgraded from above-average to average by Morningstar Mutual
Funds, which posts its current yield at 6.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The decision whether to go with that fund, municipal bonds, or a
municipal bond fund, will probably be largely controlled by your
overall tax situation. All of the yield from Fidelity Government
Income is subject to federal income tax. Because income from
government securities is not taxable in Massachusetts, part of the
yield from this fund is free of Massachusetts taxes. The people at
Fidelity told me that last year 44.93 percent of the income from
the fund was thus free of state taxes last year. (The balance of
the portfolio is in issues such as GNMA, FNMA and FHLMC, which are
instrumentalities of the government, but do not quality for the
Massachusetts tax exemption.)
</P>
<P>
   If you decide to take the tax-free route, Fidelity Massachusetts
Municipal Income fund, free of both state and federal taxes, looks
attractive, with a current yield of 4.8 percent. Morningstar
credits it with above-average performance. Its comparable figures
for total return are a negative 1.03 percent year-to-date, 2.19
percent for one year, 6,59 percent for three years, 6.30 percent
for five years, and 7.40 percent over a decade.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am a 64-year-old single woman who will retire in June of
2000. My Social Security will approximate $1,105 a month and a
company pension will add an additional $2,258 per month. If
possible, I would like an annual income of $60,000 to $65,000 in
retirement. I am wondering if my portfolio is properly diversified
and whether I should be making any allocation changes. In
tax-deferred accounts, I have $396,637 in large-cap stock funds,
$15,728 in Vanguard Health Care fund, $611,409 in US Treasuries,
and $202,452 in Vanguard Short-Term Bond fund. In taxable accounts,
I have $19,695 in Vanguard Index 500, $172,934 in CDs and money
market funds, and $15,187 in Fidelity Dividend Growth fund.
</P>
<P>
   N.B., Tyngsborough, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Obviously you are in very good shape. From my point of view,
the portfolio may be a bit too conservative, with only 31.2 percent
of it in stocks, and all but the Vanguard Health Care fund in
large-cap diversified stock funds. But my point of view may not be
yours, and if this is all the risk you want to bear, that's fine;
the idea in retirement is to have a good time, and you've laid up
sufficient funds to do so without worrying about money even if you
stick with this.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if I were you I would divert about $100,000 from the
Vanguard Short-Term Bond fund, using it to buy another $10,000
worth of Vanguard Health Care, and to establish equal $30,000
positions in Vanguard Short-Term Index, Vanguard Mid-Term Index,
and Vanguard International Growth funds.
</P>
<P>
   If you're uncomfortable with the idea of moving more money into
the current stock market -- and that strikes me as a pretty
reasonable position right now -- I have an alternative suggestion.
According to my estimates, your income from the fixed-income side
of your portfolio will combine with your pension and Social
Security to provide you with a little more than $85,000 annual
income. (This figure may be a bit high, since I presumed an average
return of 6.5 percent from the fixed-income side, which may be
optimistic.)
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, the more cautious path would be to begin a
dollar-cost-averaging program once you retire, moving about $1,666
a month from your excess income into a portfolio of mutual funds
designed to give you the same kind of diversification that I
suggested above. As you probably know, this dollar-cost averaging
discipline shelters you from some of the shock that can materialize
if an investor moves a lump sum of money into stocks right before a
market downturn. You could also speed this process if you used any
distributions from your current stock funds to build the smaller
fund positions.
</P>
<P>
   But at bottom, I'm really as concerned about the diversification
as I am with the relatively small percentage of the portfolio
that's in stocks. You have probably heard the old saw that a
person's fixed-income portfolio measured as a percentage of the
whole should equal her age. That's fair enough as a very general
rule, but the better-feathered your nest is, the more stocks you
can afford to hold, and I think that 40 percent is a far better
figure for you than 31 percent -- and I'd think the same if you
were a decade older.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
