<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUT IT OUT, CIGAR JOCKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Professional sports commissioners should read upscale cigar
magazines to know why they should crack down on the glamorizing of
smoking by athletes and coaches.
</P>
<P>
   In a feature about pitcher Orlando Hernandez and last year's
World Series celebration of the New York Yankees, Cigar Aficionado
wrote, ``The clubhouse turned into a geyser of champagne and a
thick cloud of smoke. . . . With so much good fortune packed into a
10-month period, one can understand Hernandez's reasons for
celebrating _ and smoking _ more.''
</P>
<P>
   In a feature about hockey great Wayne Gretzky, when he was still
an active player, Cigar Aficionado wrote: ``Can Gretzky light up at
the Official All-Star Cafe in Times Square? `Sure, you can smoke
there,' he says. `They don't have a problem with that.' Being a
part owner helps. He recently brought his teammates to see a tape
of the Holyfield-Tyson fight after hours and the smoke was probably
as thick as a curtain that night.''
</P>
<P>
   The thick curtains have their cost. Recentlt The New England
Journal of Medicine published a study indicating that cigar
smoking, while not as damaging as cigarette smoking, still doubles
the risk of lung, throat, and mouth cancers and elevates the risk
of heart disease. The study said cigar smoke is curtains whether it
is inhaled directly or breathed in from the ``clouds.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cigar smoke contains the same toxic and carcinogenic compounds
that are found in cigarette smoke,'' the study said. ``Another
potential reason why cigar smoking may increase the risk of
coronary heart disease is the associated high levels of exposure to
environmental tobacco smoke. Even cigar smokers who do not inhale
are exposed to their own environmental tobacco smoke.''
</P>
<P>
   Jocks are still in the clouds, seeing cigars as a balm for
competitive lives. Gretzky said, ``I smoke with the guys: it's a
chance to relax.'' Baseball's Bobby Bonilla said, ``I smoke on my
way to the ballpark. When I'm smoking is when I'm most relaxed.''
</P>
<P>
   Mean Joe Greene, the Hall of Fame football lineman and coach,
said, ``Cigars are my escape from stress. When I'm smoking, it's a
delicious moment, like watching the ocean, enjoying some soft
jazz.'' Golfing great Tom Watson said of cigars, ``I enjoy them the
most when I'm outdoors, walking the raw land, and watching a dog go
to point when I'm quail hunting. Then you're at peace, free.''
</P>
<P>
   Cigars even get indirect credit for athletic performance. Cigar
Aficionado wrote that the passion for cigars of golfer Davis Love
III helped to ``diversify his life.'' Golfer and cigar-buddy Brad
Faxon said: ``I think he's a better player since he's taken on all
these things in life. I mean, I don't think he's a better player
because he smokes cigars, but he's a better player for getting his
mind off the game and avoiding burnout.''
</P>
<P>
   Cigars have become a new source of peer pressure. Asked by Cigar
Aficionado if any nonsmokers on the Chicago Bulls ever complained
about the clouds on team buses from the smoke of Michael Jordan,
ex-teammate and broadcaster John Salley said, ``We were just
apostles. Jesus was smoking, that's all there is to it. Jesus is in
the back of the bus smoking, so you don't say jack. Jesus and 11
apostles. What are you going to say?''
</P>
<P>
   Then Bulls coach Phil Jackson rationalized cigars by citing
Native Americans. ``Smoking cigars still retains a communal aspect
where a circle of friends can ruminate about the day, digest a
shared meal, and talk about their hopes and dreams,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioners should ruminate on this: All that hocus-pocus
might appear to work for athletes in the prime of their fitness,
but in actuality the typical cigar smoker, according to the study,
is fatter and has higher blood pressure, higher levels of
cholesterol, and is more likely to have diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   The denial of cigar-smoking athletes is embodied in Ahmad
Rashad, the ex-football player and four-to-five-a-day cigar smoker
who hooks young fans on basketball on ``NBA Inside Stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   His daughter has called him on his own stuff. When he saw his
doctor for a cough, the doctor asked Rashad if he smoked. ``I say,
Yeah, I smoke one or two a day,'' Rashad said. ``And my daughter
cuts in and says, `Dad, you smoke more than one or a two a day.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Sports leagues should cut in to say cut it out. Cigarette
billboards are now banned from stadiums. Athletes would now be
castigated if they glamorized cigarettes in interviews. Jocks
should likewise not be used to peddle cigars to impressionable
fans, especially when physical fitness is declining and cigar
smoking is increasing. Cigar smoking has risen mostly among the
wealthy but has also increased among teens and women.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the clouds of glamour, the extolling by athletes of the
communal and solitary pleasures of cigars is no less silly than
claiming the bumming of cigarettes outside office buildings in
January to be a warm, relaxing ritual. Contrary to Mean Joe Greene,
this moment of cigar smoking is not delicious. It is dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
