u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICS-REICH-BOS &LR;      06-25 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICS-REICH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER LABOR SECRETARY QUIETLY CONSIDERS RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS AND SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After four years locked, if not quite gagged, in the cabinet of
a centrist president, Bob Reich has broken free to reclaim his
progressive credentials.
</P>
<P>
   But can one of the left's leading policy intellectuals make the
transition from an appointed post to elective politics?
</P>
<P>
   The former secretary of labor is wondering just that as he
quietly talks to advisers and friends about running for governor of
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Reich tries to downplay his interest, although he admits he's
giving the idea some thought. ``I am on the fringes, sniffing
around,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But others who have spoken with him are more definite.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's more than seriously thinking about it,'' said one
Democratic activist who has talked with Reich about his political
ambitions. ``He'd love to run, but he's smart enough to know that
he has to assess whether it's at all viable.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a good and interesting question.
</P>
<P>
   For all his celebrity, the obstacles are formidable. For
starters, superficial though it may be, Reich, 53, is strikingly
short, standing only 4 feet 10 inches.
</P>
<P>
   Second, and perhaps most damaging in a heated political
campaign, he stands accused of fabricating events in his memoirs to
bolster his image.
</P>
<P>
   And though his progressive share-the-wealth message would surely
gladden liberal hearts, it may be out of touch with the cautious
politics of a prosperous era. Further, he has no built-in
constituency or base to launch a race.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Reich is acting like a man laying the groundwork for a
campaign. He is showing up increasingly as the featured speaker at
events where political figures are seen and heard: a teacher's
rally at the State House; a talk at Rosie's Place.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, his recent, well-covered address to a graduation
ceremony at the Pine Street Inn settlement house in Boston captured
the spotlight. Reich basked in media coverage that contrasted his
remarks with the Harvard commencement speech on the same day by
Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
   Politically, the billing couldn't have been better: the cautious
conservative capitalist credited with creating the current economic
boom versus the progressive champion who argues the country's vast
wealth is increasingly maldistributed.
</P>
<P>
   He is also quietly meeting with political consultants, studying
the politial side of the game, posing questions about running for
public office in Massachusetts, and showing a keen interest in the
campaign process.
</P>
<P>
   How keen? Well, in May, Reich, who teaches at Brandeis
University, convened several politically savvy friends at his home
to discuss a potential race. One good piece of advice he is
getting: Get to know Massachusetts, not necessarily geographically
but rather its constituencies, its special-interest groups, and its
political leaders.
</P>
<P>
   One key question: Could Reich raise the table stakes a
Massachusetts governor's race usually requires?
</P>
<P>
   If funded, the state's nascent system of publicly financed
elections could help. ``But you can't count on that, so he has to
have a contingency plan,'' said one friend who has discussed a
campaign with Reich.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the issue of campaign niche.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, Reich may be a celebrity, but Massachusetts Senate
President Thomas F. Birmingham would have a strong claim on many of
the progressive constituencies Reich would hope to tap,
particularly in the labor movement.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a Reich candidacy would add an interesting dynamic to a
2002 Democratic primary. Smart, crisp, and articulate, Reich is
media savy and can communicate well. He demonstrated that when he
used a relatively obscure cabinet post to become one of the
highest-profile Clinton appointees.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps just as importantly, as an author and thinker Reich
has developed a coherent world view that stands in stark
distinction to the me-too centrism of many Massachusetts Democrats.
His economic message _ namely that the country's prosperity has
enriched only those with assets and that the underclass and working
class are not better off _ would resonate well in the liberal wings
of the state party.
</P>
<P>
   His politics are hardly cautious. While most progressives
advocate raising the minimum wage to help those struggling at the
margins, Reich goes far further. He calls on the Wall Street
winners to finance services for those left behind. In exchange for
the programs that are benefiting them, ``the winners must agree to
apply a portion of their added booty to equipping the losers,'' he
wrote in a recent article in American Prospect.
</P>
<P>
   Is that too radical for modern, middle-of-the-road
Massachusetts? Reich admits that's a concern.
</P>
<P>
   There are other problems as well.
</P>
<P>
   Although it shouldn't matter, Reich is so short it colors
people's perceptions. And like it or not, physical stature does
count considerably in politics.
</P>
<P>
   Friends acknowledge the concern, but note that over the years
Reich has developed a knack for putting people at ease. As labor
secretary, for example, he was fond of starting an address to
business audiences by peering over the podium to ask: ``Now tell
me, do I really look like Big Government to you?''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps a more difficult hurdle for Reich would be dealing with
the firestorm he created in 1997 with his book ``Locked in the
Cabinet,'' a memoir of his four years as labor secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Reich was accused of fabricating the details and dialogue in
depicted events that make him look good. A C-Span tape contradicted
his description of his confrontation with a Republican senator at a
Senate hearing. Former AFL-CIO president Lane Kirkland angrily
denounced him for what he said was fabrication of the events at a
union gathering. A Democratic congressman said Reich had made up a
quote attributed to him.
</P>
<P>
   If Reich runs, that issue would surely be revisited.
</P>
<P>
   The former secretary has an explanation: the frailty of memory.
``Memory is powerful,'' Reich explained. For the paperback edition,
all the errors were corrected, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the humor he uses to defuse the height issue is lacking
when it comes to his book.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politics tends to be a gotcha game,'' he complained. ``The
trick in politics is to keep people focused on the issues _ but I
am not sure that is possible anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   If Bob Reich runs, that will be his challenge.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Frank Phillips and Scot Lehigh cover politics for The Boston
Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
