<HEADLINE>
FOR 82-YEAR-OLD, LUCK DELIVERS AT LAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROB NELSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILFORD, Mass. _ Nancy DeLuzio may get a cake to celebrate her
82nd birthday Friday (June 25). In fact, she could even buy the
bakery.
</P>
<P>
   The lifelong Milford resident, who hit a $3.1 million jackpot
Monday while playing a 50-cent slot machine in Atlantic City, N.J.,
is still recovering from the excitement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was amazing,'' she said Thursday, as she sat at the kitchen
table in her small, second-floor apartment. ``I thought I just won
about $1,000, but then the security guard came over and said, `You
just became an instant millionaire.' And I started to shake.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLuzio, who sold homemade macaroni for 20 years as a way of
staying active after her husband died in 1973, spent about $30 in
the Fabulous 50's slot machine at the Claridge Casino Hotel and was
about to slide over to try her luck at another machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something said to just play three more times,'' she said, as
flowers, candy, and photos taken after her big win covered her
table.
</P>
<P>
   DeLuzio will receive $160,000 annually for 19 years. She cashed
her first check Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Moments after she won, fellow gamblers and casino executives
swarmed around DeLuzio to congratulate her. Smiling, DeLuzio
Thursday recalled one man's reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy came up to me and said, `Mother, at last I found
you,' '' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives and neighbors gathered at DeLuzio's apartment Monday
night when she returned in a chaufferred limousine provided by the
casino _ a far cry from the tour bus she and three friends had
taken down to New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fanfare after hitting the big money, DeLuzio
remained unfazed, said Glenn Lillie, a hotel spokesman, adding that
it was the largest slot machine jackpot in the casino's history.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was as centered and genuine as anyone I've ever seen,'' he
said. ``She was funny and vibrant. This is one time that a good
soul won.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLuzio said her first priority as a new millionaire would be to
replace her wardrobe. She also promised to take good care of her
family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever they want, they can have,'' she said. ``I'm willing
to share.'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Annette Packard, DeLuzio's daughter, said she's thrilled her
mother will have no financial worries.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a good person, and she deserves every happiness from
this.'' her daughter said.
</P>
<P>
   Packard had been planning a surprise party for her mother's
birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a small dinner party planned, and now we don't know
what we are going to do,'' Packard said. ``It might expand.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLuzio, an occassional gambler who last fed slots at a casino
last December, plans to hire an acountant for financial advice. But
fun will be at the top of her list.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to take this day by day,'' she said. ``Whatever I
want to do, I am going to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
