<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FED-RATES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPECTED RATE HIKE DRAWS POLITICAL INTEREST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ What is the most effective federal social program?
Some economists say it is not college tuition grants or housing
subsidies. Instead, they point to the low interest rates set by
Alan Greenspan and other Federal Reserve policymakers.
</P>
<P>
   Low rates have encouraged businesses to add millions of new
jobs, pulling more minorities and low-income Americans into the
work force. Businesses, competing hard for workers, have had to
raise wages. In short, these economists say, low interest rates
have been the best medicine for the most Americans.
</P>
<P>
   But now, this program could be repealed. And a vocal minority is
complaining.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Fed policy-makers are likely to raise interest rates
in a ``pre-emptive strike'' against inflation. Greenspan all but
announced the rate hike in congressional testimony last week, and
investors are convinced he will follow through. Fear of higher
rates caused the Dow Jones industrial average to tumble 132.03
points Thursday, or 1.24 percent, to 10,534.83.
</P>
<P>
   Because higher rates cause businesses to lay off workers, a key
question hangs over next week's Fed meeting. Which is the greater
evil: Putting some Americans out of work in order to ward off
inflation, or letting everyone work at the risk that inflation will
rise and hurt the whole economy?
</P>
<P>
   Keep Americans working, Democratic lawmakers and minority and
labor leaders said at a press conference Thursday. There just
aren't enough signs of inflation to warrant any job losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most recent consumer price index numbers show zero
inflation _ zero,'' said John Sweeney, president of the AFL-CIO.
The mere ``fear of inflation,'' he said, should not cause anyone to
lose a job.
</P>
<P>
   Until only recently, said Representative Barney Frank, Democrat
of Newton, the nation's prosperity has excluded low-income
Americans. It would be ``tragic, wrong morally, wrong economically
. . . to now try to slow down the expansion, just when people who
are the victims of the economy become its beneficiaries,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``While a rising tide lifts all boats, for those boats stuck in
the mud, the tide must be allowed to rise longer,'' said Kweisi
Mfume, president of the NAACP.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the rate hike, however, are fighting some long-held
economic notions. Most prominent is that the Fed should move
against inflation at the earliest sign of its appearance.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed does not have to wait until the consumer price index
rises, argued Ben S. Bernanke, chairman of the economics department
at Princeton University and co-author of a book on central bank
battles against inflation. ``If they see inflation based on futures
prices or any other indicator, they should act now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another notion is that the Fed cannot hesitate to raise rates
when the market expects such a move, or it will lose its
``credibility'' as an inflation-fighter. When investors believe
that the Fed is on guard against inflation, they are willing to buy
bonds that pay low interest rates, and rates stay low across the
board. When they fear the Fed is weak on inflation, they panic and
demand high bond rates.
</P>
<P>
   Most controversial is the idea that the nation cannot enjoy low
inflation and low unemployment at the same time, that allowing
everyone to work will inevitably cause prices to rise.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional theory holds that when unemployment falls below 5
percent or 6 percent, businesses have to raise wages to attract
workers. Then they have to raise prices to cover the higher wage
bill. The result is inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan said as much last week. ``Should labor markets
continue to tighten, significant increases in wages . . . will
inevitably emerge, absent the unlikely repeal of the law of supply
and demand,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the vocal minority says this is not true. After all, Sweeney
said, unemployment dipped below 6 percent, then 5.5 percent, and
even below 4.5 percent, and there are no clear signs of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   High inflation is caused by wars and ``external shocks'' like
the oil crisis of the 1970s, said James Galbraith, a University of
Texas economist, in a phone interview. ``The notion that we live in
a world in which inflation is an ever-present threat _ that you
always have to be standing in a door with a crowbar to clobber it
on the head _ is contrary to fact,'' Galbraith said.
</P>
<P>
   Galbraith has long argued that low interest rates are crucial
for helping low-income Americans close the wage gap with wealthier
workers. In a series of research papers, he has showed a
correlation between unemployment and income inequality.
</P>
<P>
   When unemployment rises, low-income people lose their jobs or
accept lower wages, and the gap with wealthier Americans increases,
Galbraith says. When unemployment falls, lower-income workers make
up economic ground, and the gap between rich and poor becomes
smaller.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key factor here is stability,'' he said. With a long
expansion, people remain in their jobs longer, earn higher wages
and qualify for credit. They can buy more goods and obtain
mortgages. A range of social good follows, from lower crime rates
to smaller welfare rolls.
</P>
<P>
   Many other economists, however, say low-income Americans also
run a risk of losing their jobs if the Fed allows inflation to
creep up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two worst recessions of recent times _ 1973 to 1975 and
1981 to 1982 _ were brought about by the Fed having to crack down
on the economy because inflation was out of the bottle,'' Bernanke
said. ``If inflation gets out of control, then you get recession _
and that's what really hurts low-income people.''
</P>
<P>
   In setting rates, Greenspan and his colleagues look at more than
unemployment levels. They look at the stock market, which the Fed
chairman has suggested is trading at unreasonably high rates, and
at the global economy, which appears to have pulled back from
dangerous downturn. They also look at a range of more esoteric
measures, which reportedly include railroad freight-car loadings
and the lag-time in filling industrial orders.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after cutting rates last fall amid the global economic
crisis, Greenspan seems ready to don his inflation-fighting gear
again. ``When we can be preemptive, we should be,'' he told
lawmakes last week, ``because modest preemptive actions can obviate
the need for more drastic actions'' later on.
</P>
<P>
   But Fed critics say there is no pressing reasons to take such
action now. ``High employment and fair wages are not threats but
assets to the economy,'' said Representative Bruce Vento, Democrat
of Minnesota. ``The ivory tower that economists live in bears
little resemblance to Main Street USA. I urge chairman Greenspan to
take a long, hard look at the people this academic exercise would
harm.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
