<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9409 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAILEY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-25 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAILEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMER FICTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Today I'm soliciting nominations for what I hope will become
an annual award, The Simon C. Fireman Medal for Chutzpah.
</P>
<P>
   Be warned, the judges will be incredibly selective. All nominees
will be measured against the extraordinary example set by our
local-boy-turned-felon in his just-published memoir, ``No Justice,
The 6 Million Dollar Disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Fireman, you'll recall, is famed for paying the largest fine
ever levied in a campaign finance case. Fireman's attempt to be a
GOP moneybags to the Dole campaign in 1996 backfired, costing him a
$6 million fine and six months of home confinement.
</P>
<P>
   The 72-year-old Fireman's incredible explanation: It was my
secretary's fault. It was my lawyer's fault. And for good measure,
the judge ``despised'' me.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine that. And the judge hadn't even read this book, yet.
Think how I feel after wading through this muck.
</P>
<P>
   ``No Justice'' is the most whine you'll get in 244 pages on any
summer reading list. Some of the best slop is right up front when
Fireman recounts the hard time he served in his Marina Bay condo
with a monitoring bracelet strapped to his ankle. He could have
visitors only three times a week. His phone calls were monitored.
On his twice-a-day walks he couldn't ``stop at my favorite cafe for
a warm-up cup of coffee,'' even on a cold day.
</P>
<P>
   My personal favorite: ``And the bracelet denied my wife, Norma,
and me such simple spousal pleasures as the ability to roll over on
a foggy Sunday morning and intertwine legs and ankles while waking
up and watching the sun light the landscape outside the window.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider, Simon, who you could have been interwining legs and
ankles with at Cedar Junction, where you might have wound up.
</P>
<P>
   Fireman spends pages and pages blaming his troubles on his
former private assistant, Carol Nichols. Although he was the boss,
it was Nichols who wrote the thousand-dollar checks, all $120,000
of them, Fireman says. He was duped _ duped! _ by this woman he
treated like family. Why he didn't even know the color of the
company checkbook!
</P>
<P>
   ``Poor Carol,'' as he calls her. She's a single girl,
``tremendously hard working, but she was not a particularly
sophisticated or worldly person.'' Why, she came from ``modest
circumstances and is not a college graduate. She didn't have much
of a life outside the office,'' says the man known for hosting
$5,000-a-plate Republican fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   Why, why would she do such a thing? ``I was afraid Carol had
gotten a little carried away by the glamour of it all and with her
own misguided vision of herself as more of a player than she really
was.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge had a different take. US Judge William G. Young gave
Nichols a $7,500 fine, which she paid off in monthly installments.
Young told Nichols: ``I understand you got your orders from him
(Fireman) . . . In a very real way I believe you were just
following orders.''
</P>
<P>
   Fireman has also sued his former lawyer, Thomas Dwyer, for
malpractice and makes one of the city's best-known criminal
attorneys the alternative fall guy in the book. Dwyer, Fireman
tells us, ``was good at the con,'' and used ``scare tactics'' to
badger him into going along with a guilty verdict. Among Fireman's
many zings: ``Tommy Dwyer has come to a realization in midlife that
he's a lousy courtroom lawyer and didn't have the courage or
confidence to stand up before a Judge Young in open court and wage
battle over complex legal and financial issues.''
</P>
<P>
   But he told a very different story at his sentencing. Asked
repeatedly by the judge, Fireman said his lawyers had explained the
charges ``in great detail.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge: ``Are you satisfied with the representation that they
have given you?''
</P>
<P>
   Fireman: ``Yes sir.''
</P>
<P>
   All's well that ends well, I suppose. In ``Exonerated,'' his
final chapter, Fireman tells us of his amazement that day in May
1997 that a letter arrived from the Federal Election Commission,
saying the agency would not be pursuing a case against him. He had
been cleared!
</P>
<P>
   Cleared, I asked Fireman on the phone Thursday? Yes, he said.
But, no, the government hadn't returned $6 million, either.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steve Bailey is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
