<HEADER>
A9414 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOMEVIDEO-1stLEDE-WRI     06-25 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-1stLEDE-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (Resending to include section on new releases)  
(jt) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Demise of Divx Clears the Field
</P>
<P>
   However the collapse last week of Divx, the alternative digital
video disk, affects the spread of DVD, it at least relieves
confusion for consumers and perhaps increases the inclination of
studios and other distributors to commit more films to a new medium
that several months ago seemed to be getting tangled in a format
war.
</P>
<P>
   Divx, developed by Circuit City, the consumer-electronics chain,
was predicated on a marketing concept that made it incompatible
with standard DVD and required a different player. (Basically, the
Divx disk was designed to play once, whereupon, among other
options, the user could throw it away rather than return it to the
video store.)
</P>
<P>
   By late winter Divx was accounting for about 10 percent of the
overall DVD market. Nevertheless, Circuit City, citing high costs,
difficulty in getting movies for the format and distribution
problems, announced on June 16 that it was discontinuing the line.
</P>
<P>
   Backers of standard DVD stopped short of performing back flips,
but the Divx withdrawal disarms a situation that in its first
stages had disquieting intimations of video's VHS-Beta conflict of
the early 80's. Now the consumer no longer has to choose one form
of DVD over another, and that pleases the movie makers and
distributors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be more aggressive in changing all our VHS titles into
the DVD format,'' said Amir Malin, president of Artisan
Entertainment, an independent film and video company with a library
of 6,600 films, among them titles like ``Dirty Dancing,''
``Reservoir Dogs'' and ``Terminator 2.''
</P>
<P>
   Malin, a strong supporter of the standard disk, said the removal
of Divx positions DVD to replace videotape and the VCR eventually.
That remains to be seen, of course, but with DVD now in more than
two million households, one can at least agree with his observation
that it has overcome another format that had the misfortune of
competing against the VCR. ``Until now,'' Malin said, ``there was
always the issue of whether DVD was going to be the technology of
the future or another format like laser disk: high-end use and
limited availability.''
</P>
<P>
   Truffaut for the Home
</P>
<P>
   Thursday a two-month Francois Truffaut retrospective ended at
Film Forum in Manhattan, but videophiles should be aware that six
of the films are available in restored editions, on both tape and
DVD, from Fox Lorber, the distributor that provided the movies for
the Film Forum series. They are ``The 400 Blows,'' ``Shoot the
Piano Player,'' ``The Last Metro,'' ``Confidentially Yours,''
``Love on the Run'' and ``Two English Girls.''
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 24 seven more Truffauts will appear on tape and disk:
``Jules and Jim,'' ``The Soft Skin,'' ``The Woman Next Door,''
``Bed and Board,'' ``Stolen Kisses'' and two short films on one
cassette, ``Les Mistons'' and ``Antoine and Colette.''
</P>
<P>
   All the videos have been made from new prints and have newly
translated subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   The Thin Red Line
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from James Jones' Guadalcanal novel, Terrence Malick's
film, his first in two decades, skirts the nuts and bolts of
warfare to contemplate mankind's self-destructiveness, the unity of
soldiers, the destruction of nature and the emptiness of victory.
Despite a starry cast that includes Sean Penn (above), Woody
Harrelson and Nick Nolte, personalities and events tend to fade
into indistinctness, which will disappoint anyone in search of a
plot. But Malick's visual genius and lush Edenic images are, Janet
Maslin wrote in The New York Times, ``a visceral reminder of all
that made his past work so hauntingly majestic, even if this
movie's difficulties will soon announce themselves with equal
clarity.''
</P>
<P>
   _1998. Fox. $104.16. 170 minutes. Closed captioned. R. Release
date: June 29.
</P>
<P>
   Varsity Blues
</P>
<P>
   West Canaan High School exists for football under the hard-nosed
tutelage of Coach Bud Kilmer (Jon Voight). In Texas football
country a coach in pursuit of his 23d district championship gets
his way even if he is a racist bully and pumps injured players full
of drugs. But no amount of painkiller will restore Bud's star
quarterback, and that introduces the backup, Jon Moxon (James Van
Der Beek).
</P>
<P>
   A West Canaan rarity, Mox has a rifle for a throwing arm and an
application pending at Brown, which makes him smart enough to
challenge the coach in a ``crisply directed but entirely
predictable all-American morality play'' (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   -1998. Paramount. $104.16. 104 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
Release date: June 29.
</P>
<P>
   Rushmore
</P>
<P>
   A cocksure 15-year-old, Max Fischer (Jason Schwartzman)
organizes everything at Rushmore Academy from the chess club to
double-team volleyball. That kind of entrepreneurial flair attracts
Blume (Bill Murray), a local steel magnate and Rushmore's leading
benefactor.
</P>
<P>
   Sensing a budding kindred spirit, Blume, who is in a midlife
funk, befriends the boy and even underwrites a Fischer scheme or
two.
</P>
<P>
   But then Blume and Max fall for the same smart, attractive
teacher (played by Olivia Williams), turning Wes Anderson's film
into ``a particular treat for its skewed, hilarious memories of a
cutthroat boyhood'' (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   -1998. Touchstone. $104.16. Closed captioned. Release date: June
29. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release at one time, appeared on television or been on
videocassette in earlier editions.
</P>
<P>
   LANSKY. David Mamet's introspective treatment of the mob figure
whose gambling interests helped give us Las Vegas defies the
conventions of crime drama by providing a reflective essay of a
sedentary, aging figure stewing in his own frustrations. ``This
playwright's hope seems to have been to challenge the cartoon
nature of Mafia movies,'' Walter Goodman wrote of the HBO movie in
The New York Times. ``Although the screenplay may be more realistic
than bloodier crime chronicles, it is wan as drama.'' 1999. HBO.
$72.11. 116 minutes. Closed captioned.
</P>
<P>
   ALICE IN WONDERLAND. Miranda Richardson makes a screeching Queen
of Hearts in NBC's version of Wonderland, which also teems with
delightful puppets and animatronic characters. But awkward devices
and Lewis Carrol's language, so engaging when scrutinized on the
page, tends to fly past too quickly to make much sense (or
nonsense) in ``a quasi-faithful version,'' Caryn James wrote in The
Times, ``that preserves the shell but not the essence of Carroll's
tale.'' 1999. Hallmark. $19.98. 129 minutes. Closed captioned.
</P>
<P>
   STEPHEN KING'S STORM OF THE CENTURY. ``Give me what I want, and
I'll go away,'' says the stranger with the walking stick topped by
a wolf's head that comes alive. By then it's snowing very hard in
the six-hour ABC mini-series, which is, Caryn James wrote in The
Times, ``as chilling and gripping as any Stephen King film since
Stanley Kubrick's classic movie of the `The Shining.''' 1999.
Trimark. $79.99. 180 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
