<HEADER>
A9415 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     06-25 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER GILLETTE CHIEF DID NO FAVOR FOR SUCCESSOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anyone who succeeded Alfred Zeien as chief executive at Gillette
was going to have a tough act to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Zeien, who retired in February, presided over a golden age at
Gillette. In his eight years on top, the company's stock price
climbed about 500 percent, the razor franchise dominated the world,
and the company acquired a new business, batteries, that offered
the potential for robust growth in the future.
</P>
<P>
   But Zeien made life even tougher for the new guy, Michael
Hawley, with his final appearance before Wall Street analysts in
January.
</P>
<P>
   Zeien could hardly contain his bullishness that day. Yes,
Gillette had been hurt in the third quarter of 1998 by troubled
overseas economies, he admitted, but he dismissed the quarter as
``a singular event.'' Said Zeien, ``We had a bad third quarter and
everybody knocked the hell out of the stock. This is sending a
message that now we're catching up to where we should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Zeien used words like ``phenomenal'' and ``enormous'' to
describe the Mach 3 razor and he predicted that Gillette as a whole
would see its earnings growth rate rebound to its customary 15 to
20 percent level in the second half of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The stock climbed 14 percent on the day of his talk.
</P>
<P>
   It all sounded great. Too bad it wasn't right.
</P>
<P>
   The rebound Zeien envisioned has not materialized. In April the
company announced disappointing sales and earnings for the first
quarter. Last week Gillette said the second quarter would be
another poor one.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette said sales growth will be in the ``low single digits,''
a nice way of saying 2 or 3 percent. Profits will be down 20
percent from year-earlier levels. The return to those customary
higher growth rates has been pushed back to the end of 1999.
Gillette's stock is off 34 percent from its March high.
</P>
<P>
   Was Zeien suffering from irrational exuberance? Was he trying to
go out the door on a triumphant note? Hard to say. But what is
clear is that he has saddled his successor with a major credibility
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hawley's job is to make a realistic assessment of the problem
areas, not try to wish them away or hope them away,'' said William
Steele, an analyst with BancAmerica Securities in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem areas are foreign economies that have not
recovered to the extent Gillette thought they would. The company
listed Brazil, Germany, Japan, and Russia as markets that are still
troubled.
</P>
<P>
   The financial crises that plagued Brazil and Russia have eased
but that doesn't mean consumers are out spending money on razor
blades and deodorant. ``The worst may be over but that doesn't mean
there is reason for companies to shout for joy,'' says Ned Riley,
chief investment officer at BankBoston.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette is hardly the only company that has been hurt by a weak
world economy. Other consumer product companies, including Coke and
Procter &AMP; Gamble, have encountered similar problems. Just Thursday,
Goodyear Tire &AMP; Rubber blamed a weak second quarter, in part, on
poor sales in Latin America and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters look for better economic times ahead in most of the
world, but it remains to be seen whether the improvement will be
significant enough and fast enough to give Gillette much of a
boost. For instance, DRI Standard &AMP; Poor's, a Lexington research
firm, expects Japan and Russia to be in recession through the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette's other problem is the performance of its second-tier
businesses: stationery, toiletries, and Braun, a maker of small
household appliances. The three businesses accounted for about
one-third of Gillette's sales last year and all three are
performing below expectations, the company said last week.
</P>
<P>
   At least a few analysts wouldn't mind seeing Gillette pull the
plug on all three and concentrate on its strengths: razors,
Duracell batteries, and its line of Oral-B toothbrushes. So far
there is no indication that Hawley is contemplating anything that
radical.
</P>
<P>
   For a company that has disappointed Wall Street in three of the
last four quarters, Gillette still has quite a few fans in the
investment community. ``Their core products are doing phenomenally
well,'' says Rary Delaney, an analyst with Fleet Investment
Advisors.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what advice they would give Hawley most analysts and money
managers suggested no major changes. ``He should stay the course,''
says Jason Fox, an analyst with Olde Discount Corp., a brokerage
firm.
</P>
<P>
   We'd add some advice of our own: Keep expectations in check. If
things are going to get better, investors will find out soon
enough. Bullish predictions have a way of leading to bearish
performance. Right, Al?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
