<DOCNO> NYT19990625.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9416 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-SARGENT-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE     06-25 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-SARGENT-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... its debut.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   All three portraits seem utterly innocuous to contemporary eyes.
The controversies, it turns out, stem more from chauvinism and
social mores than from styles of art. Gautreau and Gardner were
judged uppity-looking and brazen. And the British public thought
``The Misses Vickers'' was too much in the French mode: Friction
across the English Channel was one of the themes of Sargent's
career.
</P>
<P>
   One undoubted French influence on Sargent _ though not on ``The
Misses Vickers'' _ was Impressionism. Sargent was willing to adopt
some of Impressionism's subjects (boating scenes and the like). And
he used flickering Impressionist brushstrokes _ but relegated them
to the background. He was too much the portraitist to let the
figures dissolve as they did in true French Impressionism. His
iconic ``Carnation, Lily, Lily, Rose'' is often called an
Impressionist painting, but its eerie suspension seems closer to
Symbolism. People love this painting. It's unbelievably pretty,
this scene of two moppets lighting paper lanterns, surrounded by a
garden suffocatingly full of flowers. But it also operates as an
homage to twilight, summer, and childhood, the fleeting aspects of
life.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While Sargent wrote a letter referring to the Misses Vickers as
``three ugly young women at Sheffield, dingy hole,'' for the most
part he left little record of how he felt about his sitters. So you
guess which ones he liked, and to which he was indifferent, or
worse. He surely must have liked Lady Agnew of Lochnaw, for his
1892 portrait of her is sublime. She lounges in a bergere
upholstered in flowered silk. Her gaze is direct, subtly sensual,
as is her pose: Under her white gown her legs are crossed, and her
left thigh twists slightly. In the center of her lap is a white
flower. She is all stillness against the agitated brushwork of the
background, as if her self-confidence had made her surroundings
jumpy, the same effect she'd have on men.
</P>
<P>
   Self-confidence overflows in the room that's the heart of the
show, a gathering of the wealthy and powerful from both sides of
the Atlantic. In portraits of Lord Ribblesdale and Lord Dalhousie,
Sargent frankly copies Van Dyck's elongation and hauteur, and the
use of columns and pilasters to accent the verticality and make the
subjects all the more monumental. His women are proud, preening
creatures. (How ironic that the MFA is also currently showing May
Stevens's paintings of the radical socialist Rosa Luxemburg, a
contemporary of Sargent's languid ladies.)
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Sargent wrote that the 78-year-old John D.
Rockefeller looked ``like a medieval saint'' and painted him as a
soulful, emaciated ascetic, cornflower-blue eyes aimed heavenward.
As for Sargent's friend Henry James, the artist made the author
seem astute and perceptive, and painted his plaid waistcoat as a
nonchalant grid.
</P>
<P>
   It's sometimes said that Sargent is the visual equivalent of
James, but literature allowed the latter a level of narrative and
nuance beyond the possibilities of portraiture. It's easier to
immerse yourself in James's excruciatingly detailled world of
privilege than it is to identify with Sargent's sitters. The most
Jamesian of the works in the MFA is the 1898 ``An Interior in
Venice,'' which depicts Boston's Curtis family, distant cousins of
the artist, at home in their Palazzo Barbaro _ where both Sargent
and James were frequent guests, and where James wrote ``The Wings
of the Dove.'' The shadows suggest centuries of European grandeur
muted in the modern age. While highlighting the figures inhabiting
this haunted space, Sargent let the paintings on the walls _
paintings surely by the Venetian masters _ slumber in morbid
darkness.
</P>
<P>
   After the turn of the century, Sargent gradually pried himself
loose from portraiture, turning to landscape, the murals, and the
informal watercolors that provide some of the most sparkling
moments in the MFA show. Watercolor was particularly well suited to
depicting Venice, that most aquatic of cities, whose back alleys
and working classes Sargent had earlier recorded in oils of
tenebrous tones. He resisted the tourist views of the Grand Canal,
preferring an odd corner of a church or the underside of a bridge.
His friends and family turn up in these less starchy pictures, too,
and in his affectionate views of them painting, reading, and
relaxing there is a hint of humor, not a quality often associated
with Sargent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   World War I closed the door on the languorous lifestyle Sargent
had recorded, one where socialites didn't need to justify their
existence any more than flowers did. Being beautiful was enough.
</P>
<P>
   Sargent went to the front, as a British war artist; one result
was ``Gassed,'' a huge, flat, horizontal scene of soldiers blinded
by mustard gas, stumbling across a landscape so barren and
featureless it could be the moon. In the background, barely
discernible figures are playing soccer. Life goes on.
</P>
<P>
   In the same room, the show's last, is an anomaly that is
arguably the most moving work of the 140 here, the MFA's own oil
study of Thomas E. McKeller. A bellman in a Boston hotel, McKeller
was among Sargent's favorite models. He was African-American, but
turns up in the MFA rotunda as a blond Greek god. He was a man, but
Sargent used him as a model for female figures as well. In the MFA
study, he is himself. He poses with knees parted, hands pinned
behind him, and head thrown back, a position that is open and
vulnerable, but no more or less suggestive than Lady Agnew's. He is
the essence of dignity. Golden light rains lovingly down on the
perfect musculature of his nude form. Sargent, master of sartorial
splendor, hit his most poignantly honest moment in this study of a
man unclothed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
