<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVER AND OUT, WELL ... SORT OF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: When I first bought my computer, I could go to
Start and then Shutdown, and the CPU would turn itself off. Now
when I do this it says, ``You may now shut off your computer,'' and
I have to do it manually. Is there any setting I may have
accidentally changed to cause it to do this?
</P>
<P>
   _ Major Turnoff
</P>
<P>
   DEAR MAJOR: Here's the really stupid part: You can't just turn
off your computer anymore. I remember the first coal-fired Apple II
that I used somewhere back around 1895. You could simply turn it
off or hit it with a hatchet or throw it out of a third-story
window, and it would still work when you turned it back on. Well,
except for the second time I threw it out the window, but that's
another story and it involves an unfortunate misunderstanding with
a very angry roommate, so we'll leave that for another time.
</P>
<P>
   Try turning your computer off with the power switch these days,
and you're in for a very unpleasant experience. There's so much
going on in the background that simply cutting the juice is going
to hammer something. If you want to get an idea how many different,
unseen programs are running, hit Control-Alt-Delete on a Windows
machine, and you'll see the list.
</P>
<P>
   In Windows, you have to do an orderly exit by using the Shutdown
routine. On older hardware, you eventually get that message Major
is talking about when it's safe to kill the power. Newer boxes are
smart enough to turn themselves off unless you tell them otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   There are a couple of places you need to check to get things
back to normal. First, try your PC's BIOS setup utility. Oh, stop
looking at me like some clueless cocker spaniel. Go look it up in
your manual. Once you're in there, don't mess with anything you
don't understand or you could wind up with a shiny new doorstop.
The thing you're looking for is probably called ``advanced power
management'' or something some misguided marketing department
thought sounded equally as flashy. Enable all the power goodies you
can and you'll most likely get the one that turns the computer off
automatically.
</P>
<P>
   The other place you might look is in the Power section of the
Control Panel. Just make sure Windows power management is enabled.
</P>
<P>
   Now the real question is why all hardware manufacturers don't
use the ``off'' switch to initiate a Windows shutdown. My laptop
does it. I've seen one or two other boxes that do it. I think we
should find a couple of ax handles and go ask some hardware guys
why they're not incorporating this handy, stress-relieving feature.
Of course, that may just be the medication talking.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I am using Netscape 4.5 and am wondering if
there is a way to monitor the time I am spending on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   _ On the Clock
</P>
<P>
   DEAR ON: Are you sure this is really something you're prepared
to learn? If you discover how much time has been drained out of
your life forever, you may become so depressed you won't want to do
much more than sit in a corner and drool all over yourself. Trust
me. I know. And I have the laundry bills to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   If you're strong enough to face it, surf over to TUCOWS (The
Ultimate Collection of Winsock Software) at www.tucows.com. There
are enough online timers there to send you running for the Prozac.
</P>
<P>
   (Noted computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay told us he spends more
than 185 hours a week online. He seems to think we're total idiots
who can't use a calculator. No telling what else he's lied about.
Complain to drbombay(at) star-telegram.com or via snail-mail at
Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101. Fax:
390-7257. In real life, Dr. Bombay is Michael Gerst, editorial
systems manager for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
