<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO RISK OF PRIVACY FOR SALINGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It looks as if J. D. Salinger picked the wrong century _ and the
wrong country _ to be a recluse. In one week, we've seen:
</P>
<P>
   --The public sale of 14 of his personal letters, against his
will.
</P>
<P>
   --His 43-year-old daughter Peggy's announced intention to
publish an autobiography, ``Dream Catcher,'' next year.
</P>
<P>
   --The release of a ``stealth'' biography that is now appearing
on bookstore shelves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Salinger: A Biography,'' comes after several years of research
by Paul Alexander, who has also written books about James Dean and
Sylvia Plath. The publisher, Renaissance Books, has issued no
advance publicity, to avoid provoking the kind of legal attacks
that torpedoed an attempted Salinger biography by British writer
Ian Hamilton in 1987. Indeed, fear of legal entanglements prompted
Alexander's original publisher, Doubleday, to bail out on the
Salinger book last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever Ian Hamilton did, we did exactly the opposite,''
Alexander explains. ``We never contacted Salinger, we didn't send
out any review copies of the book, and we didn't even tell the
sales force about the book. And of course we had to quote as little
as possible from Salinger's writings, so he couldn't block
publication.'' In battling Hamilton, Salinger's lawyers won a
landmark ruling that the recipient of a letter may not quote from
the document without the sender's permission, which placed a vast
trove of Salinger-iana off-limits to biographers.
</P>
<P>
   Why does Salinger fail at being a recluse, while, say, Thomas
Pynchon succeeds? One obvious reason is that Salinger has lived in
the same New Hampshire home for more than 30 years. But Salinger
also behaves in ways that can only bring him notoriety. His battle
royal against biographer Hamilton, for instance, forced him to give
a long deposition to opposing counsel, a portion of which is
reprinted in Alexander's book.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Salinger's curious habit of writing ``fan letters''
_ mash notes, really _ to attractive young women has brought him
unwanted exposure. One such fan letter initiated his brief romance
with Yale undergraduate Joyce Maynard, who has managed to keep his
name _ and hers _ in the papers for two years running. Alexander
writes of a second, similar relationship, with television actress
Elaine Joyce, which began with a piece of fan mail from the
reclusive New Hampshire author.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Press clips
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The July/August issue of Worth magazine revisits the flap over
the $8 million estate of Margret Rey, co-creator of the Curious
George books. The article may well be included in future public
relations primers, as local television station WGBH demonstrates
how to turn a simple wills-and-estates controversy into a PR
Waterloo. 'GBH declined to speak with the Worth writer, of course.
. . . A recent Research Note from Cambridge-based Forrester
Research offered up the not-so-startling conclusion that
Microsoft's on-line city guide Sidewalk was ``stagnating.'' But the
conclusion was unusual, considering the source: Lisa Allen, the
founder and original boss of Microsoft's Boston Sidewalk Web site.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Free plug
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When it comes time to exhume our civilization (if anyone
bothers), future archeologists have only to search out the one true
repository of contemporary American culture: our refrigerator
doors. For a number of months, I've had Doug Holder's poem, ``A
Moose in Boston,'' prominently displayed. One reason I like the
poem is that said creature _ remember the famous moose that led
police on a merry dance through Brookline, Waltham, and Brighton
two years ago? _ passed in front of my house. But I also like the
poem, excerpted here:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It strode
</P>
<P>
   along side the subway car
</P>
<P>
   with the precision of dancer's legs
</P>
<P>
   looking discreetly at the window frames
</P>
<P>
   of peoples faces
</P>
<P>
   like a museum of surprise
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All this to say that Holder and his wife, poet Dianne
Robitaille, have started a poetry journal called the Ibbotsen St.
Press, and have just published their first volume of poems. For
subscription information, please write to Robitaille or Holder at
33 Ibbotsen St., Somerville, MA 02143.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
