<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9420 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-HUSBAND-BOS &LR;      06-25 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-HUSBAND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`IDEAL HUSBAND' DELICIOUSLY WILDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
AN IDEAL HUSBAND 
Directed by: Oliver Parker 
Screenplay by: Parker (play: Oscar Wilde) 
Starring: Rupert Everett, Jeremy Northam, Cate Blanchett, Julianne
Moore, Minnie Driver, John Wood, Peter Vaughan, Lindsay Duncan 
Running time: 96 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (brief sensuality/nudity) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having plucked the works of E.M. Forster, Jane Austen, and Henry
James, to say nothing of the nonstop pillaging of Shakespeare,
what's film to do but look to Oscar Wilde to do his bit? Except for
``The Importance of Being Earnest,'' Wilde isn't done often,
although ``Lady Windermere's Fan,'' ``A Woman of No Importance,''
and ``An Ideal Husband'' are just as delectable. The latter emerges
as a sparkling cascade of sexual and other politics in Oliver
Parker's new film. Parker solves the big problem in Wilde, which is
how to get beneath the wit and keep the characters from seeming
brittle. That and a brilliant cast, some subtle pruning, and a
light-handed opening up of the confines of the drawing room make
this new ``Ideal Husband'' delicious.
</P>
<P>
   It strikes a satisfying balance between the stylized and the
simpatico as its wheels are mischievously set in motion when the
main characters converge on a party being given by Jeremy Northam
as a rising young pol, Sir Robert, and his adoring wife, Cate
Blanchett, the highly principled feminist activist Lady Gertrud.
Scarcely has the host had a chance to savor an exchange with his
playboy friend, the play's central character, Rupert Everett's
aristocrat, Lord Arthur _ who plays so earnestly at
superciliousness that you know it has to be a facade _ than he
finds his world about to crumble. It seems a guest, Julianne
Moore's demimondaine from Vienna, has arrived with a letter that
could ruin Sir Robert. She threatens to circulate it if he doesn't
throw his parliamentary weight behind a crooked Argentine canal
scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Having already declared himself against it, Sir Robert doesn't
see how he can switch on the eve of the vote without alienating his
wife, and even perhaps his spirited younger sister, Minnie Driver's
Mabel. So the intrigues and complications begin, many involving
clandestine visits to the house of Lord Arthur, whose boast of
never taking life seriously is about to come to an abrupt end.
Parker finds ways to keep things playful, one being a
thrust-and-parry romance between Mabel and Lord Arthur, spiced by
Driver's headlong forthrightness and Everett's droll control.
</P>
<P>
   It's he who has the play's best line: ``To love oneself is the
beginning of a lifelong romance.'' Part of the fun is John Wood's
stuffy father routine and unending exhalations of huffy disapproval
of his ne'er-do-well son, Lord Arthur. Before long, Lord Arthur's
uncharacteristic efforts to help his friends have them all
tight-lipped with anger at him. It spices the comedy played with
suave panache by the exquisitely tuned ensemble. The compromising
letters, secret meetings, and other potentially creaky devices are
more than surmounted not only by the lively and superb acting but
by the film's ability to do justice to the wit. It communicates as
well the considerable reservoir of subterranean sentiment the wit
conceals and renders palatable. In other words, the farce is turned
into comedy, and the comedy becomes romantic comedy.
</P>
<P>
   As with the season's other sublimely written period piece, ``The
Winslow Boy,'' its corner of London, in this instance circa 1895,
is pungently evoked, and efficiently, with no sign of the
resourcefulness dictated by a less than sumptuous budget. Parker's
rewrite even gets away with an audacious in-joke. He includes a
scene at the premiere of Wilde's ``Importance of Being Earnest,''
complete with the playwright's famous curtain speech (Michael
Culkin plays Wilde). But mainly it's the silken ensemble playing
that floats this period comedy into realms of civilized delight. I
loved Everett's underplaying. He makes even the simple act of
sitting down seem funny. Blanchett brilliantly and tangibly
calibrates her character's imprisoning morality. Moore is poised
perfection as the coolly glistening blackmailer. If the noisy toys
of summer have you ready to flee film, ``An Ideal Husband'' is
reason to go on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-99 1358EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
