<HEADER>
A9422 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-DADDY-BOS &LR;      06-25 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-DADDY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALCULATED `BIG DADDY' WILL PLEASE SANDLER FANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
BIG DADDY 
Directed by: Dennis Dugan 
Screenplay by: Steve Franks, Tim Herlihy, Adam Sandler 
Starring: Adam Sandler, Joey Lauren Adams, Jon Stewart, Allen
Covert, Rob Schneider, Josh Mostel, Cole and Dylan Sprouse, Leslie
Mann 
Running time: 93 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (language and some crude humor) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``Big Daddy,'' Adam Sandler softens the gross-out stuff by
putting a kid between himself and it. On the whole, it's a clever
piece of manipulation that should keep Sandler's fans happy,
especially the ones hungering for a heavy overlay of sentimentality
on his lovable goofball persona. Actually, the character Sandler
plays here, Sonny Koufax, isn't so much a goofball as a holdout
against adulthood, a law school grad who refuses to join his
buddies clawing their way up through the legal ranks because he has
unresolved issues with his own successful lawyer father.
</P>
<P>
   At 32, he sits around his loft, working one day a week as a toll
collector, living off an accident claim payoff he invested in the
stock market, sleeping late, and watching a lot of TV sports. Call
him irresponsible _ until a 5-year-old boy is dumped on his
doorstep. Sonny's absent roommate is the father of the kid, the
result of a one-night stand. Because Sonny doesn't emulate his
workaholic pals, he has time to play with the kid, cute, of course,
and vulnerable, to whom he immediately takes a shine, and who likes
him back. It doesn't take him long to blend unsuspected depths of
kindness and a flair for parenting with enough urine, spit, and
hooters jokes to fill the screen with a generous stream of the
gross-out humor so essential to megabucks at the megaplex.
</P>
<P>
   The long-term girlfriend we see him with at the outset writes
him off as a loser. So does his his buddy's fiancee, who inspires
all the hooters jokes, but is actually played with a likably gutsy
astringency by Leslie Mann. Her radiant sister, another workaholic
lawyer played by Joey Lauren Adams, who smiles a lot, fills the
girlfriend vacancy, attracted by Sonny's attentive parenting of the
motherless kid named Julian (played in winningly cliche-skirting
fashion by twins Cole and Dylan Sprouse). One of the reasons Mann's
character takes on the appeal she does during what amounts to a
smallish amount of screen time is that she's the only one who
stands up to Sonny. Otherwise, ``Big Daddy'' is a showcase
constructed to enable Sandler to win us over with displays of
sensitivity and crude wit as Sonny fathers his way to adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   The crude wit is a lot easier to take, and funnier, than the
calculated sensitivity. The film scarcely bothers to conceal the
blatant manipulativeness of its too conveniently trouble-free
bonding, relying on Sandler's charm to make us not care about it.
Well, the guy does have a few Mike-Myers-on-quaaludes moments. Some
of his stunts and one-liners are hilarious. He's certainly plugged
into the give-life-the-finger zeitgeist so irresistible to aging
jocks who like to think they're still capable of raising a little
hell. He's not enough of an actor to be able to always conceal a
certain I'm-the-boss-here vibe, and this works against the soulful
nice-guy quality he uses to sugarcoat the bathroom humor. But then
a large part of what's likely to be the widespread appeal of ``Big
Daddy'' is that nobody is going to think of it as brain candy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
