<HEADER>
A9425 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-SARGENT-2TAKES-BO     06-25 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-SARGENT-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASTER OF THE PORTRAIT GETS A FULL PROFILE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The beautiful people are out in force at the Museum of
Fine Arts: English aristocrats, American plutocrats, the occasional
swarthy exotic spicing the mix. They're the subjects of the
paintings in the John Singer Sargent exhibition that opens to the
public on Sunday, the largest display of his works since the
memorial shows following his death, in 1925.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's ``Sargent Summer'' is a grandiose look at the artist's
complete oeuvre, with companion shows of his late landscapes at the
Isabella Stewart Gardner Museum and his drawings at Harvard's Fogg
Art Museum. And of course there are the three mural cycles _ at the
MFA, the Boston Public Library, and Harvard's Widener Library _ the
only murals he ever did, all in the Boston area. What the whole
thing demonstrates, though, is that despite his efforts in other
directions, Sargent was peerless as a turn-of-the-century society
portraitist but had equals _ or betters _ at everything else.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the MFA show is luscious. It will be immensely popular
for many reasons, starting with the jaw-dropping talent Sargent
demonstrated from his teens. He was a bravura paint handler,
unquestionably, one who could alter the effect of brush strokes at
will, making you notice them individually when he felt like it,
then melding them into silken seamlessness.
</P>
<P>
   Sargent's Boston connections add to his local appeal. This city
was the expatriate's American base; many of his sitters were
Brahmins with names like Warren, Boit, and Higginson.
</P>
<P>
   And there is the startlingly contemporary beauty Sargent gave
many of those subjects: Their faces would be completely at home on
the cover of the current Vogue. Which brings up the point that
Sargent's real heirs in portraiture aren't painters, but
photographers from Cecil Beaton to Annie Leibovitz and Richard
Avedon, fellow specialists in glitterati.
</P>
<P>
   Sargent's predecessors, meanwhile, are 17th-century painters,
most notably Velazquez and Van Dyck. He emulated their daring
brushwork, their architectural backgrounds, the arrogant poses of
their sitters. He also emulated their mode of career building.
Sargent's career coincided with the Van Gogh-inspired myth of the
artist as eccentric loner, following inner voices. Sargent's art,
on the other hand, depended on patronage and public commissions, as
that of Renaissance and Baroque painters had.
</P>
<P>
   Americans are believers in progress in painting as much as in
other endeavors, and that's where there's a problem with Sargent.
Van Dyck made great forward strides in portraiture; Sargent's steps
were less direct. He was a consolidator and even a collagist of
sorts, borrowing from all sorts of sources, both in style and
subject. The recently restored murals in the MFA rotunda, for
instance, are a pastiche of classical myths that beam beneficently
down on you, their original palette of teal blue and golden ocher
brought back after a yearlong restoration. They are in perfect
harmony with their Beaux-Arts surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   They were unveiled a few months after the artist's death, in
November 1925. By then, a revolution in mural painting was
underway, thanks to the Mexican artists Rivera, Siqueiros, and
Orozco. Nowadays, even museums with neoclassical architecture are
wont to commission Sol LeWitt wall drawings rather than
historicizing murals. But there's much to be said for Sargent's
site sensitivity, the expansive serenity he created in the dome of
the Boston museum. Tiepolo he wasn't, but in the MFA rotunda he
achieved the kind of meshing of art and architecture that was,
until our own era, the goal of mural making.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By the time he was in his early 20s, Sargent had hit on
stylistic elements he would stick with for the rest of his career.
He would often deliberately restrict his palette to blacks, whites,
and neutrals, which gives an edge of severity to canvases that
might otherwise have gone sweet. His sitters sometimes look
directly out at the viewer, an unsettling effect. He liked murky
backgrounds of uncertain depth. He also liked a horizontal frieze
format, which he employed in the 1878 ``Oyster Gatherers of
Cancale,'' the 1908 ``Cashmere,'' and the 1919 ``Gassed.''
</P>
<P>
   Children were a frequent subject for Sargent. His are closer to
Lewis Carroll than to Renoir, knowing rather than innocent. Sargent
spent the first phase of his career in Paris, where his most
important patron was the wealthy playwright Edouard Pailleron. His
1881 double portrait of the Pailleron children _ 11-year-old
Marie-Louise and her 16-year-old brother, Edouard _ is downright
spooky. Essays in sullenness, the kids seem to like neither each
other nor the painter for whom they were sitting. The girl's
expression has a drugged intensity; the boy wears a slight sneer.
Their hands are even more revealing, as tense as the rest of the
picture. Marie-Louise makes a fist with one of hers, and spreads
the fingers of the other, clutching the edge of her seat. The
children's clothes are black and white, and Sargent poses them
against a regal red ground, seating them on an Oriental carpet he's
abstracted using a sophisticated shorthand.
</P>
<P>
   When the occasion demanded, though, Sargent could paint tightly,
producing highly finished, conventional, sure-to-please works like
the portrait ``Mme. Ramon Subercaseaux,'' for which he won a
prestigious medal at the Paris Salon of 1881. Sargent's successes
and scandals are hard to comprehend a century after the fact. It
astonishes that the 1884 triple portrait ``The Misses Vickers'' was
voted worst picture of the year in a plebiscite when it was shown
at London's Royal Academy. Reactions to his portraits of Virginie
Gautreau and Isabella Stewart Gardner seem equally out of whack.
Both sparked famous controversies. Sargent had to repaint the strap
of Madame Gautreau's dress, which he showed slipped off her
shoulder in the original, because the painting caused such a furor.
And Gardner's husband was so mortified at the gossip caused by the
portrait of his wife that he blocked its public exhibition after
its debut.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
