<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-ORPHANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ABSORBING LOOK AT THE CIA'S ROLE IN TIBET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
ORPHANS OF THE COLD WAR 
America and the Tibetan Struggle for Survival 
By John Kenneth Knaus 
PublicAffairs;  398 pp.; Illustrated; $27.50 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a young CIA operations officer in 1958, John Kenneth Knaus
was asked to lecture on Sino-Soviet relations to a group of men
identified only as ``Asians'' at a covert site near Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But realizing that his audience were Tibetan ``trainee
guerrillas,'' including a brother of the Dalai Lama, Knaus scrapped
his ``standard semi-academic presentation'' in favor of what he
hoped would be ``a useful exposition of how their fight was related
to the free world's stand against communism.'' Useful or not, Knaus
was invited to stay for a new year's celebration featuring Tibetan
dumplings and ``lots of American beer.''
</P>
<P>
   Now retired from the CIA and an associate at Harvard's Fairbank
Center for East Asian Research, Knaus recounts the story of the
Tibetan resistance, and the CIA's role, in an absorbing and
valuable book, resisting the temptation to turn the Tibetans' story
into a personal memoir.
</P>
<P>
   The CIA's involvement with the Tibetan resistance began in the
early 1950s, just a few years after Mao Zedong's victory in China
and the advance of his People's Liberation Army troops into Tibet.
As the Korean War was winding down, Knaus writes, ``covert action
against communism (had) attained an importance among the CIA's
missions that would not be equalled until the Reagan
administration.'' Support for the Tibetan resistance ``was
tailor-made for a covert action program designed to challenge
communist consolidation.'' And Knaus is almost certainly right when
he notes that ``if Americans had known about it, they certainly
would have supported it.''
</P>
<P>
   The first airdrop of arms and supplies to the Tibetan guerrillas
was made in the early summer of 1958. By early 1959, Knaus writes,
the Volunteer Freedom Fighters force controlled ``large pockets of
central Tibet'' and had the Chinese forces ``definitely under
siege.''
</P>
<P>
   There was now ``a full-scale commitment'' to support the Tibetan
resistance and the CIA's training camp was moved from outside
Washington to the more Tibet-like surroundings of a mountain pass
near Aspen and Vail, Colo. Knaus was the political ``ghegen,''
teaching propaganda techniques, ``supplemented by practical
instruction in the use of a portable mimeograph.''
</P>
<P>
   Quoting the officer then in charge of the CIA's China
operations, Knaus writes that ``there was something so `special'
about Tibet'' _ including a romantic ``Shangri-la factor'' _ that
well into the early 1960s there was ``no opposition . . . to
whatever the CIA proposed in support of the resistance.''
</P>
<P>
   But already the tide was turning. In response to the early
victories of the Tibetan guerrillas, China increased its forces in
Tibet. Within a month after the Dalai Lama fled Lhasa in March
1959, CIA Director Allen Dulles was reporting that ``the resistance
boys had been badly trapped.'' The revolt in Lhasa had been crushed
and there seemed to be ``nothing more'' that the CIA could do at
that time.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there was initial support for the operation from the
Kennedy administration, for whom a newly created Special Frontier
Force ``embodied the boldness and innovation of the New Frontier
and the new administration's desire to meet the challenges of the
Cold War in new ways.'' But John Kenneth Galbraith, the newly
appointed ambassador to India, took ``an instant dislike'' to what
he called ``a particularly insane enterprise'' involving
``dissident and deeply unhygienic tribesmen.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1968, the United States cut back on its support for the
guerrillas and in one of the many curious details of this story,
the last military operation of the New Frontier's SFF was with the
Indian Army during the Bangladesh War of 1971.
</P>
<P>
   Citing officials involved in President Nixon's meetings with
Chinese leaders in Beijing in February 1972, Knaus disputes the
notion that Nixon agreed to drop support for the Tibetans. But even
if ``Tibet had not been on the table in the Beijing talks,'' he
writes, ``the era of official support for the Tibetan cause was
over.''
</P>
<P>
   Knaus concludes that the ``basic flaw'' of the operation ``was
not in the logistics but in the concept.'' The Tibetan guerrillas
did not resemble the resistance fighters of Nazi-occupied Europe
who ``benefitted from a greater military effort,'' nor did they
operate from a ``secure territorial base'' as Mao's own forces had
done before 1949.
</P>
<P>
   ``Orphans of the Cold War'' is an authoritative account of
largely unknown events in a still-unresolved struggle. But it
derives its intensity from the personal factor. Knaus recalls his
relations with Gyalo Thondup, a brother of the Dalai Lama and the
man ``most responsible for obtaining the CIA's support for the
resistance.'' They shared a sense of ``the great danger and adverse
odds'' faced by the guerrillas sent back into Tibet. ``They were
the best and the bravest of their generation,'' Knaus writes, ``and
we wept together when they were killed fighting alongside their
countrymen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
