<P>
   &UR; FOR SATURDAY AM'S &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Saturday, June 26:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ Roundup: NATO says 15 people
were killed in last 24 hours _ 14 civilians and 1 Italian
peacekeeper in a gun accident. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; With photo. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-YUGOSLAVIA (Belgrade) _ Opposition politicians in
Belgrade acknowledge that they are a fractious lot whose infighting
plays into President Slobodan Milosevic's hands. By Blaine Harden.
</P>
<P>
   Editors: Other stories that may develop include one on Kosovo
comments made by President Clinton at his news conference, a report
on rising anti-Serb violence and one on the growing numbers of
Kosovan refugees returning home.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-LEBANON (Jerusalem) _ No major Israel-Lebanon
developments following Thursday's skirmishes, but 200,000 people
remain in bomb shelters in northern Israel. The story will also
look at the crisis coordination between the outgoing Netanyahu
government and the incoming Barak administration. By Deborah
Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-POLITICS (Jerusalem) _ Barak signs coalition deals with
Natan Sharansky's party and with the National Religious Party. By
Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-BBC (London) _ Report on the uproar over the british
government's choice for the new head of the BBC. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-HOLOCAUST ( Berlin) _ After years of dispute, the German
parliament approves construction of a Holocaust Memorial. By Roger
Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-POLITICS (Johannesburg) _ President Mbeke makes first
state of the nation speech. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Turning his attention to
domestic policy matters in a speech and news conference Friday,
President Clinton calls for Congress to pass gun control, health
care legislation and tighter restrictions on health maintenance
organizations. He also pushes for an increase in the minimum wage,
tax credits for school construction and development in poor
neighborhoods and distressed regions. By John M. Broder
</P>
<P>
   &UR; With photo. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FOSTER-CARE (Washington) _ The House passes a foster care bill.
By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   PRESBYTERIANS-GAYS (Undated) _ Presbyterians vote on repeal of
an anti-gay ordinance. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Coded f)
</P>
<P>
   J.C.-PENNEY (Undated) _ In mid May, the CEO of the J.C. Penney
Co., stood before shareholders at the annual meeting and predicted
that prosperity was just around the corner. But former employees
and other industry experts think optimism is premature. Penney's
stock may be undervalued because of the strong performance of the
Eckerd's drugstore chain, they say. But the core of the business _
the nearly century-old retail chain _ is as troubled as ever. By
Leslie Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   LOCKHEED (Undated) _ Lockheed Martin is reported to be weighing
the sale of $1 billion in assets and other changes. By Leslie
Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   TRADE-BLOCS (Rio de Janeiro) _ In an effort to bolster trade and
seek some sort of counterweight to American global economic
dominance, leaders of the world's second and third largest trading
blocs are to meet here this weekend and early next week in a
first-ever ``Latin American-European Summit'' that has already
proven divisive on several basic bread-and-butter issues. By Larry
Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-ECON (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ In the financial subplot
of Indonesia's political transformation, few events have
demonstrated the progress and pitfalls as clearly as the agreement
this week between PT Astra International and its creditors on how
the company will pay back more than $1 billion in debt. By Wayne
Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   NISSAN (Tokyo) _ For the first time ever, the Nissan Motor Co.
opened its shareholder meeting to the media, just one of the many
small signs that even the most traditional Japanese companies are
inching toward the greater disclosure and transparency demanded by
foreign investors. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   Editors: There will be no market coverage tonight; The Times
plans to use agency copy.
</P>
