<HEADLINE>
CITY CHALLENGES AT&AMP;T TO GIVE ACCESS TO INTERNET RIVALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GEORGE RAINE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Board of Supervisors President Tom Ammiano says
he wants AT&AMP;T to share its cable television lines with competitors,
enabling rivals to use the lines to provide access to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano told city employees who negotiated a tentative franchise
agreement with AT&AMP;T for cable television operation to return to the
table with his amendment: He wants a guarantee that AT&AMP;T will give
any Internet service provider access to its equipment, and he wants
it negotiated in a week's time.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T's response was succinct. ``It is my firm belief the
proposal is unlawful and unacceptable,'' said Richard Patch, a
lawyer representing AT&AMP;T. ``It would be very difficult, if they
really want to negotiate around this language, because it is not
acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that a formal response to Ammiano's request was ``being
contemplated.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, should negotiations fail, Ammiano said he had another
plan: compel AT&AMP;T to make its equipment available through a ballot
measure. ``That would put this in the hands of consumers,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of AT&AMP;T are energized by a June 4 ruling by a federal
judge in Portland, Ore.. The ruling upheld that city's requirement
that AT&AMP;T open its system to competing Internet service providers.
AT&AMP;T is appealing the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of buying cable giant TeleCommunications Inc. last
year, AT&AMP;T controls the cable entering San Francisco homes. But if
Ammiano has his way, the lines would be accessible to competing
Internet service providers.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano's statements came during a hearing Wednesday of the
Board of Supervisors' Public Utilities and Deregulation Committee,
which he chairs. AT&AMP;T is entering into a franchise agreement with
San Francisco because of the company's acquisition of TCI, which
has been the city's cable television provider.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T has declined to let any Internet service provider use its
cable television connections, which can provide Internet
connections many times faster than conventional telephone lines.
</P>
<P>
   The company maintains that ExciteHome Corp., the Redwood
City-based cable modem company, has exclusive rights to provide
access through the AT&AMP;T system.
</P>
<P>
   Critics interpret that agreement as monopolistic, although some,
including a group called the Bay Area Open Access Coalition, are
supported by Internet service providers and AT&AMP;T competitors such
as SBC Corp. and GTE Corp.
</P>
<P>
   At Wednesday's hearing, Keith J. Epstein, vice president and
senior lawyer for SBC, which owns San Francisco-based Pacific Bell,
spoke of innovation and other benefits that would flow from open
access to AT&AMP;T equipment and broader competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can help in any way in drafting language that we think
would be helpful in ensuring open access, we would be happy to do
so,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
