<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WONG-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON'S SIMPLISTIC PLANS TO COMBAT VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM WONG  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Whenever our society experiences something like
the Littleton, Colo., school massacre, politicians feel they must
``do something'' in response. So President Clinton and Congress
have been mucking about in a bunch of ideas they hope will stop
such a tragedy in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Restricting the availability of guns to kids is a natural idea,
but proposals to do that haven't gotten far because the National
Rifle Association pays a lot of money to influence powerful
legislators. Leaching our popular culture of violent images is an
equally expedient idea, and a few proposals along these lines have
actually survived.
</P>
<P>
   One is a House bill to give states the right to post the Ten
Commandments in public places, including schools.
</P>
<P>
   Can't you just imagine the poster now _ Charlton Heston,
depicted as Moses (but really the president of the National Rifle
Association), holding up stone tablets with the Ten Commandments
written on them? Yeah, that's really going to stop school killings.
</P>
<P>
   Another proposal has the blessings of Clinton, who _ as we all
know _ has voracious political and personal appetites.
</P>
<P>
   The president wants theater owners to strictly restrict
admission to R-rated movies to customers who can prove they are 17
or older.
</P>
<P>
   The president has done some smart things, but he's done some
dumb things too. This idea is one of the dumb things. Trying to
keep teen-agers under 17 out of R-rated films is an exercise in
futility. As one 14-year-old put it, ``I think if you put more
restrictions on it, kids will just want to go even more.''
</P>
<P>
   The main effect of the ticket policing will be to encourage
teen-agers under 17 to cheat. Clinton's plan is probably making
purveyors of fake IDs very happy.
</P>
<P>
   Some mid-teens don't even have to go that far. A favorite ploy
is to buy a ticket to a PG-rated film, but sneak into an R-rated
movie playing on another screen within the ubiquitous multiplexes
that our culture calls movie theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as many teen-agers have been telling the press in recent
days, they simply catch R-rated films on HBO or other cable-TV
channels, or go to their favorite neighborhood video store and rent
whatever R-rated films they want.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to believe theater operators will really crack down
on teens wanting to see R-rated films. Teen-agers are the bread and
butter of movie theaters, especially in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   It is simply not in the economic self-interest of theater
operators to discourage teen-agers from buying tickets. And will
theater owners want to incur the wrath of older movie-goers who
have to wait longer in ticket lines as kids get their IDs checked?
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's plan is typical of cynical political posturing that is
all form and little substance: Keep kids from seeing shoot-em-ups
in popular films today and that will solve the youth violence
problem.
</P>
<P>
   I am not dismissing possible links of violence in movies and TV
to more aggressive behavior among youths. But young people who are
loved and nurtured at home aren't likely to ``go psycho'' just
because they got into an R-rated film at the local cineplex.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (William Wong is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
