<HEADLINE>
WINDOWS 98 USER CAN RECLAIM TASKBAR OR CREATE MULTIPLE TOOLBARS AS
NEEDED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Note (at) replaces symbol in e-mail address.) 
 
By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Yesterday I upgraded to Windows 98 SE. My taskbar now
duplicates the same icons as on the desktop. The taskbar is now
about 1 inch high, and that gets to be valuable real estate when I
use AutoCAD. So, I went into ``Settings'' and hid the taskbar. Now,
I can't see the clock unless I reposition the mouse and recall the
taskbar. Can you tell me how to restore the default (or
``standard``) taskbar?
</P>
<P>
   A: Windows 98 lets you create multiple toolbars that dock with
the taskbar at the bottom of the screen. This can be handy if you
have a set of programs that you use all the time _ but maddening if
you somehow set it up by accident.
</P>
<P>
   In your case, the fix is very simple. Right-click on an open
area of the taskbar and choose Toolbars from the menu that appears.
One of the selections will be Desktop, and it's probably checked _
click on it to uncheck it. That should restore your standard
taskbar.
</P>
<P>
   To add a toolbar, create a folder on the desktop (right-click on
the desktop, choose New and then Folder) and create shortcuts
inside for the programs you want to use. Then drag the folder and
drop it onto the taskbar. It will create a second layer for the
taskbar that will include the icons you created.
</P>
<P>
   To undo this, just use the same solution listed above _ turn off
that particular toolbar.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a new computer that has a modem, speakers and a
microphone. But I can't figure out how to be able to use it like a
speakerphone.
</P>
<P>
   A: Unfortunately, you may not be able to, unless you replace
your modem.
</P>
<P>
   Just having a microphone, speakers and a modem is not enough.
The modem must be capable of handling voice calls. If it can't, no
software in the world will give it that ability.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of years ago, before the sub-$1,000 computer came to
prominence, nearly every consumer PC sold came with a voice-capable
modem. Computer makers loaded their systems down with fancy
voice-mail programs. But guess what? Most people didn't use them,
and found that the software often conflicted with software used to
access online services or the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for ways to cut corners, many PC makers have gone back
to simpler modems that just handle data and fax calls. That's
particularly true for budget PCs.
</P>
<P>
   A full-featured voice and fax modem with 56K speeds should cost
in the $100 price range. Most come with rudimentary voice-mail
software, but if you want something more powerful, you might
consider TalkWorks from Symantec. It also comes with the complete
version of WinFax Pro as a bonus.
</P>
<P>
   But remember, if your modem can't handle voice calls, then
TalkWorks will be worthless to you.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the difference between the Navigator and the
Communicator browser? Which one is better? Second, what's the
difference between the memory cache and the disk cache?
</P>
<P>
   A: Communicator is the name for Netscape Communications'
complete package of Internet access tools, which includes the
Navigator browser, the Messenger e-mail software, America Online's
Instant Messenger chat program, and other components. Navigator is
a component of Communicator.
</P>
<P>
   Memory cache is an area in your computer's random access memory
where pictures and text from the most recent Web pages you visited
are stored. The disk cache is similar, but it's larger and can hold
more images and text.
</P>
<P>
   When you hit the Back button on your browser, you're likely
pulling in the page from your memory cache, which is why it pops up
so fast. If you hit the Back button several times, you'll start to
draw from your disk cache, which is slower.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send e-mail to Computing columnist Dwight Silverman at
dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call 713-220-2000 and enter
access code 1001.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
