<HEADLINE>
NOVICE PC BUYERS TAKE DIRECT ROUTE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: note (at) replaces symbol in e-mail address.) 
 
By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the maturing home computer market, there's a
stereotypical image of the first-time PC buyer that goes something
like this:
</P>
<P>
   A bit nervous about technology. Needs hand-holding. Doesn't want
to pay a lot for this machine. Wants to buy it at retail, because a
high-dollar purchase needs to be touched first.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the first-time computer buyer at the close of the 20th
century is not a comfortable person. So why, then, are so many of
them starting to buy direct?
</P>
<P>
   Gateway, the North Sioux City, S.D., computer manufacturer,
sells its computers directly to consumers. You won't find Gateway
PCs in Best Buy, CompUSA or Micro Center. To get a Gateway, you
have to either call an 800 number, go to the company's Web site or
visit one of the 160-plus Gateway Country stores around the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The first two options require that you buy the computer sight
unseen, a serious act of faith when the purchase price is likely to
be more than $1,000. Yet Dataquest, a tech market research firm,
estimates that Gateway was the leading seller of desktop PCs to
consumers in the fourth quarter of last year and the first quarter
of this one, beating out Compaq Computer Corp., which is the
reigning consumer champ. Between 45 and 50 percent of Gateway's PC
customers are first-time buyers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
GATEWAY SERVICE MATCHES IMAGE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gateway has succeeded in two ways. First, the company has
created a brand that is warm and fuzzy and has backed that up with
customer service that matches.
</P>
<P>
   Second, it has created a hybrid direct-retail way of selling in
its Gateway Country Stores. They're direct, in that you don't take
the product you buy home with you; it's shipped to your house. But
it's retail, in that there's a physical location where you can try
before you buy.
</P>
<P>
   (This approach has been emulated in reverse by PC makers that
primarily sell consumer machines at retail. Compaq, for example,
has set up kiosks in electronics and computer stores where buyers
can custom-configure a PC, then have it shipped to their house.)
</P>
<P>
   Gateway does everything it can to play on the legend of its
origin _ that its founders got started by building computers in a
barn. It evokes this image shamelessly. Remember those TV ads with
founder Ted Waitt delivering a PC to his father?
</P>
<P>
   Gateway is not alone, though, in invoking its roots. Compaq used
to love to tout its design-on-a-placemat origin story, though it
has backed off that quaint tale as it tries to repaint itself as a
``big box'' company. And everyone knows the tale of Michael Dell
building PCs in his dorm room at the University of Texas at Austin.
</P>
<P>
   But none of Gateway's competitors has incorporated its roots
into marketing as well as Gateway. In New York for PC Expo, the
annual business trade show, I walked into a Gateway Country store
that's opened in the center of midtown Manhattan, just ``spittin'
distance'' from Central Park. It's quite a jolt to walk off the
hardened, hustle-bustle streets and into a motif filled with cows,
hay, barn implements and tractor seats for stools.
</P>
<P>
   The country-friendly motif is particularly evident where it's
most important _ in Gateway's sales force.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
FIRST-TIMERS GET EXTRA CARE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you call Gateway and profess to be a first-time buyer who
knows nothing about buying a computer, you're apt to get treated
with kid gloves. I called, pretending to be a novice, and was
gently walked through a series of questions that tried to determine
what I wanted to do with the computer. The salesperson was
infinitely patient with me. I pretended not to be sure about what I
wanted, just that I wanted to get on the Internet, maybe keep my
home finances, do a little genealogy.
</P>
<P>
   He ultimately recommended Gateway's lowest-priced PC, which
sells for $999, and did not try to sell me something more
expensive. It was, indeed, a comforting experience.
</P>
<P>
   There are still some barriers for some consumers in buying
direct. I get lots of e-mail from buyers who are concerned about
getting burned _ even with established brands like Gateway or Dell
_ and who are worried about what to do if the computer breaks.
</P>
<P>
   And there are still some folks worried about giving their credit
cards to someone over the phone, and certainly over the Web. But
these are fewer and farther between. Even the most hesitant are
being won over, and that's a fundamental change in the way PCs are
being sold.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Silverman can receive electronic mail via the Internet.
Address your comments and questions to
dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000 and enter
access code 1001. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
