<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANDMINE-DOGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN'S BEST FRIEND ALSO HELPS FIND LAND MINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Photo available on Wieck database.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZEKE MacCORMACK  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOMERSET, Texas _ In addition to the NATO security forces being
deployed in Kosovo, a squad of specially trained dogs is being sent
into the embattled province to help in the precarious task of
finding land mines.
</P>
<P>
   The Global Training Academy will supply 12 dogs and 12 handlers
for ``humanitarian de-mining'' efforts under a $1.6 million
contract approved by the State Department on June 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to go into the area until the State Department
says it's safe and they've gotten the snipers out of there,'' said
Dan Hayter, who founded the company in 1984 with Jim Parks.
</P>
<P>
   Both men learned to train dogs while in the Air Force and most
of the company's 28 employees are military veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were the first private company in the world to train mine
dogs,'' Parks, 59, said at his office in Somerset, a town southwest
of San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Mine-sniffing dogs now in another part of the Balkans,
Bosnia-Herzegovina, could begin work next week in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman James Rubin underscored the danger in
Kosovo: ``There are strong indications that during the crisis in
Kosovo, the Serbian army laid land mines so extensively that the
safe return of refugees and internally displaced persons, as well
as the provision of humanitarian assistance, will be hindered.''
</P>
<P>
   And Matt Murphy, a foreign affairs specialist with the State
Department, said troops from the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
are now marking mine fields for the dog teams to clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're waiting for word that the environment is secure,''
Murphy said from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, from our perspective, the de-mining season only
lasts through October before the weather gets bad,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Global is the sole provider of mine-sniffing dogs to the
Washington-based company, RONCO Consulting, which has the de-mining
contract with the State Department, Les Wexler, a company
spokesman, said by telephone from his office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know of any other American companies that train the
dogs for de-mining,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   German shepherds and Belgian Malinois were first trained at the
81-acre academy here to sniff out drugs and explosives and to work
as police dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Mine-detection training was added in 1990, and Hayter said
nearly 300 of the company's dogs are now sniffing for explosives in
Afghanistan, Rwanda, Angola, Mozambique, Central America, Bosnia,
Croatia and Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest advantage of using dogs is they can work in
terrain that's real difficult for a man to get into safely, and in
areas with a high ore content in the soil, where metal detectors
don't work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It takes about 16 weeks to train the dogs to detect mines, and
the dogs cost $12,000. Bomb-detection dogs go for $8,700, and
drug-sniffing dogs are $5,300.
</P>
<P>
   Trainers accompany the dogs to the client countries to supervise
mine searches until the new owners are proficient in mine-clearing
_ a process which can take three years.
</P>
<P>
   In the field, the dogs work on a 30-foot lead in a team that
includes a handler, three de-mining specialists, and a medic.
</P>
<P>
   Searching for mines has killed three dogs trained by Global,
Hayter said, but there have been no human losses on the staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dogs never know they're in danger,'' Hayter said. ``It's
all a game to them.''
</P>
<P>
   The work is dangerous enough, but it entails perils other than
explosives.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 while working for the United Nations in Angola, he said,
rebels surrounded mine-detection team's camp ``and threatened to
shoot anybody who left.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't want us taking their mines out of the ground,''
Hayter said.
</P>
<P>
   After a six-week standoff, he said, the team was allowed to
leave the country.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of run-in would sour many people on a career in mine
detection, but not Paul Brown, who was in Angola.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the job,'' said Brown, 31, who recently returned from a
three-year stint in the central African nation of Rwanda. ``I love
training the dogs, and I really enjoy traveling and working with
different people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This may sound kind of corny, but you feel kind of like a
pioneer,'' he said. ``You've got to learn to become kind of a jack
of all trades. It's very rewarding.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
