<SLUG> BC-OCEAN-LIVING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILDERNESS IS ONLY A WAVE AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HUEY D. JOHNSON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILL VALLEY, Calif. _ One reason I live in the San Francisco
area is because it is situated right next to the wildest wilderness
there is: the sea.
</P>
<P>
   I believe it is important to occasionally encounter the
wilderness of the sea. A taste of salt spray is an elixir that
refreshes your awareness and adds zip to your outlook on life.
</P>
<P>
   A friend who moved here from Chicago two years ago, in part
because of a love of the sea, had not yet been out on the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   I reflected that he might move back to Chicago and free up space
for someone who would appreciate the experience of living here.
</P>
<P>
   Sea winds have been screaming through the Golden Gate for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Driving huge waves against the cliffs and shores of San
Francisco, the swells from those cold winds off the north Pacific
are a reminder that wild nature is very close, even in this urban
setting.
</P>
<P>
   One needs to get out on the sea to really sense it. Sailing or
motoring under the Golden Gate in a small boat is the way to go; a
foot or so from the swells is about right. The beauty is
breathtaking, and the sense of the power of the sea is so immediate
and awesome that it makes humans adjust their outlook.
</P>
<P>
   It demands our respect; it is a force beyond our ability to
manage. The sea's strength is evident in the gentle movement of a
boat riding the swell, as well as in the twisted wrecks strewn
along most shorelines.
</P>
<P>
   The great beauty of the sea lies within one small drop, as well
as in the vast distances that stretch to the horizon, where one can
see the curvature of the Earth. The coast is breathtaking, mile
after mile of rugged rocks and sandy beaches marked with the white
foam of sea spray.
</P>
<P>
   Sea birds are immensely graceful. In summer here, the evening
sky is filled with thousands of sooty shearwaters that skim the
water in great, rolling flocks, never coming ashore except to nest.
Their nesting place is in New Zealand, 7,000 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   The pelican is another remarkable bird. Although it appears
ungainly when in slow flight or landing on the water's surface, it
dives with the utmost grace, plummeting into the sea to capture the
bait fish it has spotted near the surface.
</P>
<P>
   The tremendous force of the sea is evident twice each day when
the tide rushes under the Golden Gate with the force of water from
a giant firehose, the current like a mighty river.
</P>
<P>
   In the ocean, life pulses in endless forms: Whales, seals,
birds, fish and plants have all adapted to survive in a wilderness
environment that to humans can be difficult and sometimes deadly.
I've just finished reading a book titled ``A Fisherman's Son,'' by
a member of a family of fishing people from Half Moon Bay. It
reflects the beauty and harsh reality of those who live on the sea.
</P>
<P>
   The awe one feels for the sea is in part fear, and with good
reason. For many of us, the fear adds a bit of zest to the trip.
</P>
<P>
   But the skill of a good seaman includes a respect for the forces
involved, and there is little danger in taking a boat ride from
Fisherman's Wharf out under the bridge.
</P>
<P>
   A trip out onto the ocean awakens interests and stirs old
memories; it makes us more aware of how the sea flows around our
lives. Afterwards, looking out to sea will be more meaningful.
</P>
<P>
   Articles and books, visits to museums and aquariums _ even walks
on the beach _ are all enhanced by an trip out onto the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   The sea is a rich reward for living here.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Huey D. Johnson, former secretary of the California Resources
Agency, is president of Resource Renewal Institute in San
Francisco.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-99 1546EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
