<DOCNO> NYT19990625.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9533 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX     06-25 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LITTLE BREAK FROM FAMILY WORKS WONDERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last weekend, I did a good thing and left my husband, Jimmy, to
the whims of our two little girls.
</P>
<P>
   That might sound mean, but I like it when they rediscover that
they can carry on without me. No one looked starved when I
returned. The house was cleaner than I remembered. There were no
casualties.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, I know when the three of them need to be together;
it's usually when I need time alone.
</P>
<P>
   That might sound selfish, but every time I return _ whether it's
after a weekend or a week away _ I discover, and maybe they
discover, how much each of us has grown.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for instance, the hair thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was poufy,'' Asha tells me, drawing a circle around her
head with her arms. ``You know how my hair swells and gets
bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   I cringe, remembering the first time I let her hair hang without
twists or braids. It looked as if it had been electrified. She
cringes and, sensing my discomfort, er, mother's guilt, pacifies
me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sorta liked it,'' she says. ``Jamila said it looked like you
did it.''
</P>
<P>
   As they talk, I am reminded of all the things my daughters have
taught me over the years _ about myself, about life. But I think,
too, about how much of my timbre they have inherited.
</P>
<P>
   At 8 and 10, they have the self-confidence I sometimes wish I
had at 41. They are selfless and have the kind of love that can
peer inside my soul and each other's and provide whatever is needed
at the moment: a kiss, a hug, a reassuring word or a nod.
</P>
<P>
   They always seem older than their years, and after each time
away, I realize that they are no longer the babies I once fed at my
breast, or the toddlers who no longer wanted my help.
</P>
<P>
   Each time, it is like beholding myself in a mirror, twice over.
If you recognize your imperfections as much as I do, that can be a
scary thing. It can also be liberating.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the moment, they have been like a heavy coat
keeping me warm in winter or a cool, gentle breeze washing across
my hot face.
</P>
<P>
   I had both sensations Sunday as I listened to Asha's stinging
honesty and witnessed Jamila's self-confidence and the gentle way
she had tried to reassure her little sister about her hair.
</P>
<P>
   All of us hope that our children grow up to be emotionally
healthy. But as with a room that changes according to who picks the
furniture, the fine points can vary.
</P>
<P>
   Some people's chests swell when their children master the
alphabet, win the 50-yard dash or learn to play Beethoven's
Moonlight Sonata. I might be tempted to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   But the proudest moments I've had as a parent are when someone
tells me Asha and Jamila are sweet, well-behaved and kind, because
when all is said and done, those are the things that make it
possible for even strangers to sit down and connect. That's what
makes us human.
</P>
<P>
   We'd spent considerable time practicing the hair thing before I
left Friday. Nothing elaborate, just a single ponytail.
</P>
<P>
   After about an hour, I gave up and left, a bit worried that on
Sunday they would sit in church looking like Little Orphan Annies.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't happen. Part of me wishes it had, because I want to
be needed by my little girls. No amount of time alone will ever
change that.
</P>
<P>
   (Gracie Bonds Staples is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, You can call her at (817) 390-7791, or e-mail:
gbs(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
