<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9552 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-25 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFL-CIO SAYS HISPANICS PAID LESS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: note (at) replaces symbol in e-mail address.) 
 
By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The Harris County AFL-CIO once again loaded up the
Justice Bus and rolled through Houston on Thursday passing out
``awards'' to employers.
</P>
<P>
   The contingent, part of the more activist AFL-CIO that has been
holding similar events throughout the country this week, drew
onlookers and police as they handed out their plaques.
</P>
<P>
   Each plaque was actually a jab at the employers for alleged
worker transgressions: not negotiating in good faith, paying
Hispanic workers lower wages than white workers and locking workers
out of their plants.
</P>
<P>
   At the Lanier Public Works Building, the activists _ meat
cutters, masons steelworkers and others _ chanted ``No justice
here!'' to protest what the AFL-CIO believes is discrimination
against Hispanic construction workers.
</P>
<P>
   The Harris County AFL-CIO did a recent study and found that when
it comes to public construction projects, Hispanic employees are
paid less than white employees.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw said contractors who work for government entities _ like
the city, county, hospital districts and school boards _
misclassify Hispanic employees as semi-skilled or unskilled even
though Hispanic workers perform the same jobs as the white
employees who are classified as skilled. Federal, state and local
construction projects must pay a specified prevailing wage for each
job classification.
</P>
<P>
   The union's review of payrolls found that between 60 percent and
95 percent of misclassified workers were Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   It's bad enough for companies to cheat workers, said Maria D.
Jimenez, director of the American Friends Service Committee's
Immigration Law Enforcement Monitoring Program in Houston. It's
even worse for the government to cheat immigrants, Jimenez told the
chanting union members.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WORKING ON PUBLIC PROJECTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Richard Shaw, Harris County AFL-CIO secretary-treasurer, figures
the contractors on the recent rennovation of a Houston building
still owe their employees, who are mostly Hispanic, about $100,000
in back wages, along with penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw said the union found similar problems at other public
construction sites, and several misclassification investigations
are underway.
</P>
<P>
   The government entities should be monitoring the payrolls
better, Shaw said.
</P>
<P>
   John de Leon, director of affirmative action for the city of
Houston, said his office takes prompt action whenever it gets an
complaint. He said the office also does spot investigations if
something doesn't look right from the weekly payroll records that
contractors must submit.
</P>
<P>
   As for the renovation of the Houston building, a city
investigation uncovered misclassification and $5,000 to $10,000 in
back wages was repaid, de Leon said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CELEBRATING UNION VICTORIES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Union members also gathered to celebrate the United Food &AMP;
Commercial Workers, Meatcutters &AMP; Allied Food Workers' election
victory earlier this month at Sanderson Farms, a poultry processing
plant in Bryan, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   After rejecting the union last year, the 960 workers voted to
join Local 408 earlier this month after company promises of
bathroom breaks never materialized, said local president Emilio
``Red'' Gomez.
</P>
<P>
   A bigger turning point, said Gomez, was when the employees, who
earn between $6 and $8 an hour, found out that at union-represented
plants employees must be notified before their second break that
they'll be held over for forced overtime.
</P>
<P>
   That gives the employees, who are mostly women, a chance to
arrange for someone to care for their kids when they come home from
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not money,'' said Gomez, who still hopes to get a hefty
raise for the poultry processors when he negotiates the first
contract. ``It's self-respect and taking care of their families.''
</P>
<P>
   A supervisor at Sanderson Farms said she couldn't comment and
the division manager wasn't available.
</P>
<P>
   The bus also visited Maxxam's headquarters to give chairman
Charles Hurwitz an ``award'' for locking out the steelworkers at
Kaiser Aluminum and drove to Pasadena to present a similar
``honor'' to Crown Central Petroleum for locking out its refinery
employees. The bus paid a visit to Metropolitan Transit Authority
because of a labor contract dispute with its union.
</P>
<P>
   The union also gave an award to someone who might actually might
want to put the plaque on his wall _ to Jordy Tollett, head of the
Greater Houston Convention and Visitors Bureau, for being a friend
of labor.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've never forgotten the people in the organization who make
it work,'' said E. Dale Wortham, president of the Harris County
AFL-CIO.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To voice comments, telephone (713) 220-2000 and dial in code
1002. Send e-mail to lm.sixel(at)chron.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
