<DOCNO> NYT19990625.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9565 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-$ADV27-COX     06-25 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-$ADV27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT FUTURE STILL RESTS IN THE BALANCE
 &HT;    920&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories
for release Sunday, June 27.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``We are not a monopolist,'' said Bill Gates,
chairman and co-founder of Microsoft Corp., a firm admired,
courted, and feared by much of the high-tech world _ and the target
of the highest-profile antitrust case to come along in a
generation.
</P>
<P>
   Gates's assertion cut no ice with Joel Klein, the Justice
Department's antitrust chief. ``The evidence shows a pattern of
anti-competitive activity,'' he told Gates. ``We're going to
move.''
</P>
<P>
   The once secret Gates-Klein exchange took place on May 5, 1998,
around the mahogany conference table of Sullivan &AMP; Cromwell,
Microsoft's law firm, whose plush Washington offices overlook the
White House. A few weeks later, with the talks at an impasse, the
Justice Department filed its historic suit, joined by 19 state
attorneys general.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday, as 21 weeks of testimony before U.S. District
Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson came to an end, the long saga of
Microsoft Corp. vs. the United States entered yet another phase.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides have until Aug. 10 present competing ``findings of
fact.'' A month later, on Sept. 10, the two sides must submit their
revised findings after having assessed each other's submissions.
Once those two voluminous rounds of paperwork are out of the way,
Jackson said he will hear closing arguments in his courtroom on
Sept. 21.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the government, firmly persuaded that it has got the
best of Microsoft in the courtroom, will hone its remedial options
for Jackson's scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, the judge will quietly prod the antagonists to
settle the landmark case, thereby lifting the need for him to issue
a verdict early next year. The Wall Street Journal, citing people
close to the case, reported that further settlement talks took
place three weeks ago between Klein and William Neukom, Microsoft's
veteran general counsel, who sat at the head of the defense table
during the entire trial.
</P>
<P>
   But even as these legal mills grind away, the industry continues
to change at a remarkable pace. The judge's ruling late this year _
not to mention a final decision that may be reached after years of
appeals _ will emerge in a computing world greatly changed from the
one in which the suit was filed.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to Wall Street analysts a few weeks ago, IBM chairman
Louis Gerstner described the present torrent of new
Internet-related companies as mere ``fireflies before the storm,
all stirred up, throwing off sparks.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerstner added, ``The real disturbance in the force is when the
thousands and thousands of institutions that exist today seize the
power of this global computing and communications infrastructure
and use it to transform themselves. That's the real revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's lawyers argue that such revolutionary currents have
already all but swamped the government's case. But the plaintiffs
hold that the same currents make it all the more imperative to bind
Microsoft before it is able to leverage its vast market power to
wrest control of Internet commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mere fact that the lawsuit is taking place'' has brought
change, said William Kovacic, a former Federal Trade Commission
lawyer who has followed the trial as a professor at George
Washington University's law school. ``People see this as a window
of opportunity where Microsoft cannot react as forcefully as they
have before.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Compaq Computer Corp. and Dell Computer Corp., which have
long sold personal computers equipped with Microsoft's dominant
Windows operating system, recently began offering machines that run
the rival Linux system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Linux is selling, but our sales are very small,'' a Dell
official noted.
</P>
<P>
   T.R. Reid, a Dell spokesman, pointed to the so-called Internet
browser wars as yet another phenomenon that served as a central
issue during the trial but has gotten scant traction in the
marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just don't see our customers as voicing any preference at
all when it comes to browsers,'' Reid said. ``They're quite content
to use whatever browser comes with the computer.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Dell, which currently controls about 13 percent
of the PC market, that means Microsoft's Internet Explorer.
Customers, Reid said, could alternatively order Netscape
Communicator, now part of America Online Inc. ``But they would have
to pay separately for it, since we are being charged for the
browser,'' he noted.
</P>
<P>
   When Dell founder Michael Dell was recently asked why anyone
would want to pay his firm to pre-load Netscape for them when they
could just as easily download it for free from AOL and countless
other Internet Web sites, Dell replied: ``That's a very good
question.''
</P>
<P>
   Dell's response suggests how the march of technology could
outstrip the government's remedial formula for Microsoft, assuming
it prevails in court.
</P>
<P>
   At the time it filed its case, Microsoft had yet to ship Windows
98. That flavor of the basic computing platform is a focal point of
the complaint because, as the trial testimony underscored,
Microsoft chose to bind its browser tightly to its operating
system.
</P>
<P>
   But when the time comes to issue a verdict, Microsoft, in all
probability, will have moved on to release its next platform, known
as Windows 2000, a system that has hardly been mentioned in court.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to know what we'll be asking the judge or what it
would take to settle, go take a look at the original complaint,''
advised David Boies, the Justice Department's lead lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The government's initial ``prayer for relief'' was largely
overlooked at the time because it called for a preliminary
injunction against Microsoft that Jackson refused to grant.
</P>
<P>
   But another section calls on the court to strike down
restrictive pacts between Microsoft and firms such as Compaq and
Dell that curb ``their right to modify the screens and functions of
Microsoft's Windows operating system.''
</P>
<P>
   These arrangements, the government contends, violate Sections 1
and 2 of the 1890 Sherman Antitrust Act.
</P>
<P>
   In principle, Microsoft strenuously objects. But, in practice,
the Microsoft culture has changed since the trial began.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the software giant has looked the other way as at
least one computer manufacturer, Gateway 2000 Inc., modified the
Windows startup process so that it could promote its own Internet
access service.
</P>
<P>
   It has also quietly let Dell erase the icon for Microsoft's
Internet browser from the electronic desktops of Windows 98 and
Windows NT in business-class machines, pulling back from its prior
rigid policies.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-99 1612EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990625.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9566 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-$ADV27-COX     06-25 1152
