</P>
<P>
   In the case of Dell, which currently controls about 13 percent
of the PC market, that means Microsoft's Internet Explorer.
Customers, Reid said, could alternatively order Netscape
Communicator, now part of America Online Inc. ``But they would have
to pay separately for it, since we are being charged for the
browser,'' he noted.
</P>
<P>
   When Dell founder Michael Dell was recently asked why anyone
would want to pay his firm to pre-load Netscape for them when they
could just as easily download it for free from AOL and countless
other Internet Web sites, Dell replied: ``That's a very good
question.''
</P>
<P>
   Dell's response suggests how the march of technology could
outstrip the government's remedial formula for Microsoft, assuming
it prevails in court.
</P>
<P>
   At the time it filed its case, Microsoft had yet to ship Windows
98. That flavor of the basic computing platform is a focal point of
the complaint because, as the trial testimony underscored,
Microsoft chose to bind its browser tightly to its operating
system.
</P>
<P>
   But when the time comes to issue a verdict, Microsoft, in all
probability, will have moved on to release its next platform, known
as Windows 2000, a system that has hardly been mentioned in court.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to know what we'll be asking the judge or what it
would take to settle, go take a look at the original complaint,''
advised David Boies, the Justice Department's lead lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The government's initial ``prayer for relief'' was largely
overlooked at the time because it called for a preliminary
injunction against Microsoft that Jackson refused to grant.
</P>
<P>
   But another section calls on the court to strike down
restrictive pacts between Microsoft and firms such as Compaq and
Dell that curb ``their right to modify the screens and functions of
Microsoft's Windows operating system.''
</P>
<P>
   These arrangements, the government contends, violate Sections 1
and 2 of the 1890 Sherman Antitrust Act.
</P>
<P>
   In principle, Microsoft strenuously objects. But, in practice,
the Microsoft culture has changed since the trial began.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the software giant has looked the other way as at
least one computer manufacturer, Gateway 2000 Inc., modified the
Windows startup process so that it could promote its own Internet
access service.
</P>
<P>
   It has also quietly let Dell erase the icon for Microsoft's
Internet browser from the electronic desktops of Windows 98 and
Windows NT in business-class machines, pulling back from its prior
rigid policies.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
