<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATURAL-BEAUTY26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Make your own natural beauty produts
 &HT;    By Christi Mays
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ The key to natural beauty may be found in the
kitchen, not the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   Dig around in your kitchen pantry and you'll probably find the
ingredients to make an assortment of natural homemade beauty
products like deep-moisturizing facial masks, minty hair
conditioners and honey-soothing cleansing scrubs.
</P>
<P>
   From everyday food items and bath products most people already
have at home, such as honey, eggs, milk, oils, oatmeal and bath
soap, it's a cinch to concoct natural formulas of beauty products.
</P>
<P>
   According to the National Honey Board, foods such as honey have
been used throughout the centuries as part of skin- and hair-care
regimens. Honey was a popular ingredient in makeup in the 1800s,
and today manufacturers are increasingly using the sweetener in
skin moisturizers, facial masks, hair products and shower gels in
response to consumer demand for more natural formulas.
</P>
<P>
   Many foods can be used to make beauty products. Use highly
acidic fruits, such as lemons and grapefruits, to help dry oily
skin. Use low-acidic foods, such as carrots, avocado, honeydew
melon, mayonnaise and plain yogurt for moisturizing dry skin, as
well as any type of oils, including olive, coconut and vegetable.
Oatmeal, brans and almonds are nourishing exfoliates and eggs are a
nourishing deep cleaner.
</P>
<P>
   Some homemade beauty products (the ones that don't require
refrigeration) also make great gift ideas when poured into a
decorative bottle.
</P>
<P>
   When you're ready to experiment, try a variety of mixes to find
out which works best for your skin type. And remember, food isn't
just for eating.
</P>
<P>
   Home recipes to try
</P>
<P>
   Try some of these simple beauty product recipes or others at any
of the Web sites listed below.
</P>
<P>
   FACIAL FONDUE FOR TWO
</P>
<P>
   (Nourishes and softens)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup plain, thick yogurt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup oatmeal, blended to a powder
</P>
<P>
   1 large carrot, cooked and mashed
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons honey
</P>
<P>
   1 ripe avocado
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 egg yolk
</P>
<P>
   Mix ingredients together in a large bowl. Spread over the face
and neck. Relax for 20 minutes. Rinse thoroughly with warm water,
then with cold water.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Super Salve Co.
</P>
<P>
   HONEY CLEANSING SCRUB
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon honey
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons finely ground almonds
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Mix together. Rub gently onto face. Rinse off with warm water.
</P>
<P>
   Source: National Honey Board
</P>
<P>
   STRAWBERRY SKIN MOISTURIZER
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon each olive, coconut and vegetable oils
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons mashed strawberries
</P>
<P>
   Optional: 1 to 2 drops vitamin E oil
</P>
<P>
   Mix all ingredients in a small bowl. Rub into skin. Store unused
portions in the refrigerator in a covered jar between uses.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Makestuff.com
</P>
<P>
   CUCUMBER FACIAL MASK
</P>
<P>
   (Cleans and moisturizes)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon instant nonfat dry milk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 peeled cucumber
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon plain yogurt
</P>
<P>
   Put all ingredients into a blender and mix well until smooth.
Apply to your face avoiding your eyes. Leave on for 15 to 20
minutes then rinse off. Mix a fresh batch for each use.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Makestuff.com
</P>
<P>
   HOMEMADE SHOWER GEL
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup Victorian Essence Foaming Concentrate or substitute 1/2
cup unscented shampoo
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup water
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon table salt
</P>
<P>
   15 drops lime fragrance oil
</P>
<P>
   1 drop green food coloring
</P>
<P>
   Optional: 1 teaspoon powdered loofah for an exfoliating scrub
</P>
<P>
   Pour foaming concentrate into a bowl and add water. Stir gently
until well mixed. Add salt and stir until mixture thickens. Add
lime fragrance oil and food coloring. Pour mixture into a
decorative bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Note: You may use any fragrance oil you choose for this recipe,
including bubble gum-scented, which is popular with children.
</P>
<P>
   Source: HGTV, Carol Duvall Show
</P>
<P>
   PEPPERMINT HAIR CONDITIONER
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup cholesterol-type conditioner
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup water
</P>
<P>
   15 drops peppermint essential oil
</P>
<P>
   1 drop food coloring, any color
</P>
<P>
   Combine all ingredients in a bowl and stir until well blended.
Pour into decorative bottle. For oily hair, add 1 tablespoon aloe
vera gel to conditioner to help moisturize without excess oil. For
dry hair, add 1 tablespoon of corn oil to conditioner.
</P>
<P>
   Source: HGTV, Carol Duvall Show
</P>
<P>
   FACIAL TONER
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon honey
</P>
<P>
   1 peeled, cored apple
</P>
<P>
   Puree together in a blender. Smooth over face; leave on 15
minutes. Rinse with cool water.
</P>
<P>
   Source: National Honey Board
</P>
<P>
   Web sites:
</P>
<P>
   _ www.nhb.org/pressrm/beauty99.html
</P>
<P>
   _ www.gilanet.com/supersalve/recipes.htm
</P>
<P>
   _ www.hgtv.com/shows/CDS/cds-417.html
</P>
<P>
   _ www.makestuff.com
</P>
<P>
   _ www.gurlpages.com/other/a-flamingo/beauty.html
</P>
<P>
   _ www.wmur.com/touchofstyle/0199/facials.htm.
</P>
