</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Battling lame-duck status 19
months before leaving office, President Clinton challenges the
Republicans in Congress to approve his agenda to overhaul Medicare,
Social Security and education. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   HORMEL-LUXEMBOURG (Washington) _ Luxembourg's envoy to the
United States holds a small dinner to welcome James Hormel, the
soon-to-be-sworn-in ambassador to that nation. Hormel's appointment
was blocked for more than a year by conservative Senators who
objected to his gay rights advocacy. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-FLORIDA (Undated) _ The Bush brothers, Govs. George W. of
Texas and Jeb of Florida, travel across Florida to campaign and
raise money for the older man's presidential campaign. By R.G.
RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SERIAL-KILLER (Houston) _ The FBI plans to address reports that
Border Patrol agents in New Mexico had serial-killing suspect
Rafael Resendez-Ramirez in custody on June 1, but let him go
because his criminal history had not been entered into their
database. By S.K. BARDWELL. (Graphic available on NYT database.)
</P>
<P>
   HINDU-PRIEST-SEX (Houston) _ The Hindu holy man convicted in the
sexual assault of a 21-year-old Arkansas woman earlier this week is
back in court. State District Judge Ted Poe ordered Bhogeshwernand
Sharma to be held without bail on a new charge that was filed
against him as his last case wrapped up. By STEVE BREWER.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CALIFORNIA (Austin, Texas) _ When Texas Gov. George W. Bush
takes his presidential campaign of broad themes to California this
week, he may run into the hard issues that can confound a
candidate. California, a state that once was revered Reagan country
but in the last election left Republicans reeling, is seen as a
must-win for the Democrats in the 2000 presidential race. By LAURA
TOLLEY.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ Since both Republican George W.
Bush and Democrat Al Gore are expressing centrist positions, the
manner in which they present themselves is as important as the
messages they convey. In their first official sorties, Bush has
emerged the winner. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON. (Filed Wednesday.)
</P>
