<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CURBING SPECULATION, NOT INFLATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everyone expects that the Federal Reserve Board will raise
interest rates Wednesday. The only question is whether the Fed will
raise them 25, 50 or 75 basis points (a quarter of a percentage
point, half a percentage point or three-quarters of a percentage
point).
</P>
<P>
   Although everyone knows this will happen, it may well be the
most misunderstood story in American journalism. Federal Reserve
Chairman Alan Greenspan will not raise interest rates to ``stem
inflationary forces'' or ``keep inflation in check.'' He will do so
to take some air out of what he believes is a very dangerous
speculative bubble. Put simply, he's trying to ``soft-land'' the
rocket-fueled US financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan is not raising rates to ``fight'' inflation because
there is no inflation. And there isn't going to be any inflation to
speak of for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   How do we know this? One need only look at the commodity markets
and the cyclical stocks on Wall Street. Commodity prices are
through the floor. Gold is so far down it may, as Street.com
columnist Jim Cramer says, cost nothing in the near future. Silver
is down, copper is down, oil is lingering in the basement. Look
across the board of the major agricultural commodities and it's a
wonder that anyone farms anymore. Prices could hardly be lower.
</P>
<P>
   The cyclical stocks are equally moribund, as they stagger from
quarter to quarter without hope of maintaining what used to be
called ``price discipline.'' Price discipline is one of those
wonderful Wall Street phrases that means keeping prices high in
concert with the competition.
</P>
<P>
   The reason there is no such thing as ``price discipline''
anymore is Internet technology. The Web, as columnist Cramer points
out, is the greatest inflation fighter of all time. It makes
inflation impossible in all but monopoly markets. And where
monopoly (or duopoly) markets exist, the Web still creates downward
pressure on prices.
</P>
<P>
   Consider a company called Accompany.com., which aggregates
customers for a specific product. Let's say the product is a
refrigerator. One person could go to an appliance store and buy a
very good refrigerator for, say, $700. But if 100 people band
together and say they all want to buy the exact refrigerator, they
would get a bulk order discount of roughly 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Accompany.com (people accompanying other people to buy the same
thing) organizes individual buyers into a group of buyers and, via
Web technology, creates a bulk order. Everybody gets the same
refrigerator for $500. General Electric and Maytag can't raise
prices in an environment like that.
</P>
<P>
   And this technological force is in its infancy. It hasn't even
begun to reach into every nook and cranny of industry. Wait until
major corporations start aggregating their orders for raw materials
with other major corporations. Wait until 10,000 people come
together to buy that refrigerator. Wait until the fiber optic pipe
is fully operational and 75 million housholds in the United States
are aggregating their buying power through companies like
Accompany.com.
</P>
<P>
   How much do you think a gallon of milk will cost? Without
government price supports, it might cost a dollar. How much do you
think a roll of 36 film exposures will cost? It'll cost a dollar.
How much ``price discipline'' can be maintained in a market that
aggregates buyers like that? The short answer is none.
</P>
<P>
   Internet technology checks inflation at almost every turn, since
it makes markets exponentially more efficient. And Alan Greenspan,
more than any other Federal Reserve Board governor, understands
this. He has been talking about the productivity gains derived from
Internet technology for years now. He believes it is a transforming
technology that, among other things, acts like a power brake on
inflationary forces.
</P>
<P>
   What Greenspan is concerned about is not inflation, but
speculation. The roaring bull market of the last 16 years (and
particularly the last four) has led to a dramatic increase in
margin buying. Margin buying allows the owner of 1,000 shares of
Microsoft stock to borrow against that asset and buy, say, more
shares of Microsoft stock. As long as Microsoft stock keeps going
up, everything's grand. If Microsoft stock tanks, however, then our
hypothetical owner has to sell his original 1,000 shares to meet
his ``margin call.''
</P>
<P>
   Since margin buying of stocks is at record levels, it is not
hard to imagine a situation where a series of cascading margin
calls could lead to financial panic.
</P>
<P>
   This is essentially what happened in Japan in the late 1980s,
and that country has been in a depression since. Greenspan does not
want to end his tenure as chairman of the Federal Reserve
overseeing Japan redux. So he will raise rates slowly to deflate
what he regards as a speculative bubble. Senior Wall Street traders
believe he will do so in three increments, 25 basis points at a
time. They're guessing, but it seems like a good guess. It's not
about inflation. It's about speculation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(John Ellis is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
