<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANIMAL-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASSON TAKES ANIMAL BEHAVIOR TO HUMAN LEVELS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VICKI CROKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHERBORN _ As a camera focuses on them, Jeffrey Moussaieff
Masson turns to his 2-year-old son and mock whispers, ``Don't say
cheese here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Here'' is at a gathering of the Boston Vegetarian Society at
the Peace Abbey, where fromage is a four-letter word.
</P>
<P>
   The author of two best-selling books on animal emotions, ``When
Elephants Weep'' and ``Dogs Never Lie About Love,'' Masson, 58, has
become a guru in the animal rights world.
</P>
<P>
   But Masson _ Sanskrit scholar, onetime psychoanalyst, authority
on Freud, and famed libel litigant against New Yorker writer Janet
Malcolm _ stands out in his newfound crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Just moments before the picture taking, the earthy gathering had
parted in the driveway to allow Masson's flashy yellow VW bug to
pull up. Masson emerged handsome, tanned, and fit, with his young
family.
</P>
<P>
   The magic of his recent books may be that Masson is a bit of an
outsider looking in. In both books, he takes mountains of material
and weaves a captivating and convincing argument that our fellow
creatures do indeed have feelings. Masson's outsider status gives
him the sense that he is careening through the animal world _
unencumbered by scientific affiliations, but also hampered by the
lack of formal education in the subject.
</P>
<P>
   As he sits out at a picnic table on a muggy, overcast Sunday at
the peaceful abbey, Masson talks about crafting his books.
</P>
<P>
   He contends that many scientists are legitimately afraid to
probe the notion of feelings in animals, fearful that they will be
labeled anthropomorphic. But he says his perspective gives him
freedom to push the envelope.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the book he's working on now should ruffle a few
feathers: concerning, as it does, the emotional life of farm
animals. He will attack that issue with his scholar's zest _
reading through thousands of books in preparation. (He is shipping
1,500 books for the project home to California, from his temporary
digs in Boston.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, Masson frets about how much he doesn't know. And he is
constantly telling stories on himself. He appears the polar
opposite of the image that emerged from Malcolm's 1983 two-part
profile in the New Yorker _ that of a vain, intellectual gigolo and
academic hustler. The picture may linger still, long after his
much-watched and notoriously bitter $7 million libel suit, in which
Masson prevailed with one jury (that deadlocked over damages), and
lost to the next, in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Asking a scientist friend to look over one of his manuscripts
recently, Masson reports, the friend phoned him, shouting over the
line: ``Jeffrey! You said a grebe is a kind of duck!'' Masson is
laughing and shrugging. ``What do I know?'' Masson may confuse a
diving bird with a duck, but he's got some big thoughts right. He
has struck a chord with hundreds of thousands of animal lovers.
</P>
<P>
   Masson appears bemused and even baffled a bit by his rocketing
popularity. He has written many books in his varied career _ ``My
Father's Guru,'' ``The Wild Child,'' ``The Complete Letters of
Sigmund Freud to Wilhelm Fliess, 1887-1904,'' and ``The Peacock's
Egg: Love Poems from Ancient India,'' among them. But, he says most
of them drew few readers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was such a failure as a writer,'' he says, almost with glee.
``There were more reviews than copies sold.'' (Clearly, though, he
was a big enough deal to warrant the New Yorker's attention to
begin with.)
</P>
<P>
   So he decided to go back to writing about an early love _
animals. As a kid growing up in Berkeley, Calif., he collected fish
and frogs and turtles and other creatures.
</P>
<P>
   He says that he figured, ``As long as I can't make money anyway,
I may as well do something I'm interested in.'' Depressingly, he
says, his editor concurred. ``You might as well stick to what you
don't know,'' he was told. Not exactly encouraging. Neither was a
rejection of ``When Elephants Weep,'' by Sierra Club publishing.
The house didn't think it would sell, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Masson can afford to relish the memories now. ``When Elephants
Weep'' was on the New York Times bestseller list for nine weeks in
hardcover and three months in paperback. ``Dogs Never Lie About
Love'' was on for six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Masson could be arrogant about how things turned out, but in an
interview he's not. He seems humbled by the world of nature he has
been immersed in, comparing it to the best of human behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son Ilan is happy to be at the garbage dump if that's where
he is,'' Masson says. ``He thinks it has nothing on the south of
France. And (famed chimp expert) Jane Goodall has a Buddha-like
tranquility. I lack that, and I'm trying to learn . . . from
animals.''
</P>
<P>
   Masson, like many of us, believes that animals have something
profound to offer our species. ``I compare myself to dogs and I
come up short,'' he says. ``I really mean that. Dogs live in the
here and now. They're Zen masters.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
