<HEADLINE>
QUESTIONS LINGER IN WAKE OF EMPLOYEE CHANGES AT FORT WORTH ZOO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J.R. LABBE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Without question, the Fort Worth Zoo is one of North Texas'
premier community assets. A combination education and entertainment
mecca, the zoo has been successful at attracting millions of
visitors each year to help enhance Fort Worth's reputation as a
cultural center in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   As a public asset, it naturally draws scrutiny if something
changes at the park, and that includes personnel.
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Worth Zoo is instituting what officials described as
sweeping changes in its education program, in part to act as a
better resource for the public schools and to attract federal grant
and foundation money that is available for conservation and
education efforts.
</P>
<P>
   In the process of achieving those goals, officials swept out
some of the men and women who helped cement the zoo's distinction
as one of the top five zoological parks in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Zoo Director Gregg Hudson said that in an effort to be more
competitive with the other informal education programs from which
parents can choose to send their little ones, the zoo is requiring
that all paid teachers hold state teaching certificates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents wants certified teachers,'' Hudson said. ``They expect
certified teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Ken Seleske was laid off.
</P>
<P>
   Seleske, who holds a bachelor's degree in psychology and a
master's in zoology, has forgotten more about animals than most
people could ever absorb in a lifetime. An animal expert with 23
years' experience at the zoo, Seleske has been responsible for
expanding the knowledge of countless people _ young and old, at the
zoo and throughout Tarrant County classrooms _ about the wonders of
God's various creatures.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Barbara Opdenhoff, whose position was eliminated
through department restructuring, Seleske had daily contact with
the zoo's cadre of docents whose thousands of volunteer hours since
1972, valued at $1.5 million, are vital to the nonprofit zoo's
operations. Ken and Barbara O., as Opdenhoff is called, helped
train the docents in everything from conservation and general
taxonomy of animal species to the specific characteristics of each
animal found at the zoo. In turn, the docents helped teach the more
than 120,000 youngsters who came to the zoo during the 1998-99
school year for everything from one-hour sessions to full-day
classes.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, the docents were devastated at the news of the
layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Full disclosure: I have firsthand knowledge of just how upset
the docents are because my sainted mother is one of them. She
received the zoo's Volunteer of the Year award last year and
considers Ken and Barbara O. part of her extended family. In our
family, if Mama ain't happy, ain't nobody happy.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the parents of the more than 1,500 children who signed
up for zoo school this summer may have indeed asked about teacher
qualifications before registering their children. It's more likely
that there was an assumption on their part that the zoo wouldn't
have folks in the classrooms who didn't know their bisons from
their water buffaloes. The more intellectually honest explanation
is that the zoo hopes certified teachers will impress grant review
committees that have millions of collective dollars to dole out.
</P>
<P>
   Grant review applications are funny beasts _ credentials,
certifications, the amount of alphabet soup behind someone's name
carry a lot of weight. Just ask any college professor who's ever
applied for foundation money. The time they spend in a classroom
isn't worth a dime; it's how many advanced degrees they have, and
how much they've been published.
</P>
<P>
   Is there anything wrong with the zoo going after private and
public grant dollars? Absolutely not. As a nonprofit organization
that sweats out each year's budget allocations, it's a smart
business decision to look for any and all revenue streams.
</P>
<P>
   When the docents put aside their personal feelings about Ken and
Barbara, they can see the big picture of how the zoo must compete
in a world of increasing choices for people's discretionary
dollars. They don't have a problem with changing the curriculum so
that it complements the scientific principles that students are
expected to learn in each grade level under the Texas Essential
Knowledge and Skills established by the Texas Education Agency.
They don't have a problem with upgrading the classrooms to include
computer technology.
</P>
<P>
   They just don't understand why two people who possess incredible
knowledge of and love for animals weren't retained to help make the
changes, instead of being sacrificed to them.
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is senior editorial writer and columnist
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. She can be reached via e-mail at
jrlabbe(at)star-telegram.com or by phone at (817) 390-7599. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
