<HEADLINE>
EXHIBIT PART OF GAY PRIDE CELEBRATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL DOUGAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Participants in San Francisco's annual festival
of elegant ``excessories,'' now saddled with a cumbersome name _
the Lesbian Gay Bisexual Transgender Pride Day Parade _ will
promenade down Market Street on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   A ``museum-quality exhibit'' will be at the west end of this
ultimate block party, said Gerard Koskovich, a board member of the
historical society. It will trace the history of sexual minorities
in San Francisco's always accommodating milieu.
</P>
<P>
   While encased exhibits might seem staid amid the revelry,
Koskovich believes they will be popular. Two years in the making,
the eight distinct displays represent hundreds of hours of work by
volunteers and professionals from the San Francisco Museum of
Modern Art and the Fine Arts Museums of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   They also mark a milestone for the historical society.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1985, ``we're at that point where we're turning from
a small community-based nonprofit into a larger institutional
player in this town _ and this shows it,'' Koskovich said.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibits, on display at the Castro Theater, were curated by
the distinctive groups they represent, with help from the pros at
the big museums.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin Aguirre, a 31-year-old writer, headed the Latino/Latina
Community Exhibit Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to the display, Aguirre explained how it traces the
evolution of the Gay Latino Alliance (GALA) _ the first gay group
to march in the annual Carnaval festival _ into Projecto Contra
SIDA (the Project Against AIDS) today.
</P>
<P>
   ``GALA died out,'' he said. ``The energy behind GALA dissipated
for a while until the crisis of AIDS came into our community.''
</P>
<P>
   Aguirre said his committee began work on the exhibit about 2 1/2
months ago, with assistance from the staff at San Francisco Museum
of Modern Art. ``This is the first time the historical society has
made a conscious effort to bring in different groups,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Koskovich admitted that ``this just scratches the diversity of
all the queer communities in Northern California ... it just
represents a start.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the exhibit typifies a new concept in historical
representation: ``The term is public history _ bringing history to
those who lived it.''
</P>
<P>
   Participation by museum professionals in assisting the volunteer
groups is also rare, Koskovich said. ``Museums don't usually reach
out to people at that level.''
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit cases are as diverse as the people they represent,
ranging from somber (the devastation of AIDS) to playful.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Glimpse into One Bear's Drawers'' is cheery. ``Bears'' are
gay men who ``have a beard and a bit of flesh to spare, and
preferably some body hair,'' according to writer Adam Mars-Jones.
</P>
<P>
   The case contains a large teddy bear, a chest overflowing with
plaid shirts and publicity stills of Sean Connery, Mr. French from
the vintage TV series ``Family Affair'' and Steve Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their matinee idols,'' Koskovich said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
