<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-VIRUS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOLLOWING THE BEHAVIOR OF COMPUTER USERS, MOST DAMAGE NOW SPREAD BY
INTERNET E-MAIL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ On Thursday, June 10, tens of thousands of computer
users got e-mail from someone they knew, but it was not a message
they wanted to receive.
</P>
<P>
   Attached to the e-mail message was a program that purported to
be compressed word processing documents, a common way of bundling
files together. But when the program was launched, nasty things
happened.
</P>
<P>
   First, it scanned the user's e-mail inbox and sent itself to the
first 10 addresses it found. Then, it went looking for found and
damaged word processing, spreadsheet and other crucial data files.
</P>
<P>
   Dubbed Worm.ExplorerZip, it was the second malicious program
this year that spread so rapidly across the Internet that major
companies were forced to shut down their e-mail servers _ computers
that have become the lifeblood of 20th-century corporate
communications.
</P>
<P>
   Those who study viruses say a change in the nature of personal
computing has created a fertile environment for the spread of new,
virulent and complex malicious programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an explosion of the Internet, and we have a lot of
novice users who are not savvy when it comes to malicious code,''
said Carey Nachenberg, chief researcher for the Symantec AntiVirus
Research Center, which develops the popular Norton AntiVirus
product. ``These users are spreading these viruses very rapidly.''
</P>
<P>
   This is different than the early days of personal computer
viruses, when most were transmitted by users who shared programs
and data via floppy disk. Only a relative handful of users were
online, and occasionally they contracted computer viruses from
software downloaded from bulletin boards.
</P>
<P>
   These viruses either hid in the boot sector of the floppy disks
_ the part of the disk that tells computers how to find and handle
its information _ or hitched a ride on program files, infecting
other files when the programs were launched.
</P>
<P>
   Viruses were transferred between computers slowly, and their
spread was checked by simple logistics. Today, viruses have the
potential to spread like wildfire _ and so they do.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are definitely sharing information over the Internet,
and that's a good thing, but it's also a bad thing, because they
are sharing viruses as well,'' said Nachenberg.
</P>
<P>
   The Worm.ExplorerZip virus is a relatively new type, one that
exploits the newer features of network-connected computers. It also
exploits the behavior of PC users.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's insidious is that these virus writers have an increased
awareness of how people behave and the way they work,'' said Wes
Wasson, director of security products for Network Associates, which
makes the McAfee VirusScan, another antivirus product.
</P>
<P>
   This is known among virus writers and computer hackers as
``social engineering'' _ exploiting either the good will or
outright gullibility of people in order to achieve a malicious aim.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Wells, who has been tracking the spread of viruses in the
computer community since 1993, said he is seeing more and more
viruses that use social engineering. He compiles a list of the
common viruses found ``in the wild.'' Known as the Wild List, it
can be found at www.wildlist.org.
</P>
<P>
   The Melissa virus, which swept across the Internet in April _
clogging e-mail servers and shutting down corporate communications
_ was one of the best examples of these kinds of malicious
programs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Like Worm.ExplorerZip, Melissa used features found in
Microsoft's Outlook e-mail program to send itself to other people,
so it came from someone who probably was known to the recipient.
</P>
<P>
   ``Melissa used three levels of social engineering,'' Wells said.
``It came from someone you know. It said, `Here is the file you
asked for,' so it made you think this mail was a response from that
person. And it said in the text, `Don't show this to anyone else,'
which made you think it was important.''
</P>
<P>
   Melissa came in the form of a macro virus, utilizing a feature
in Microsoft's Word word processing program. Macros are like
mini-programs that can be run whenever a user looks at a Word
document that includes them.
</P>
<P>
   The practice of sending Word documents via e-mail has become
common _ even savvy computer users think nothing of routinely
opening one of these when they arrive attached to a message. As a
result, macro viruses are now the most prevalent type.
</P>
<P>
   The evolution of viruses and other malicious programs has
followed the evolution of Microsoft's Windows operating system,
said Wells. Although there are viruses that attack Apple's
Macintosh computers, there are far more viruses aimed at the
``Wintel'' platform (as in Windows and Intel Corp., the company
that makes most PC chips).
</P>
<P>
   The early boot sector and file viruses attacked MS-DOS, the
text-based operating system from Microsoft. But nearly as soon as
Windows 3.1 became popular as a graphical shell that hid DOS'
arcane commands, ``there were viruses that blew up Windows,'' Wells
said.
</P>
<P>
   When Windows 95 came out in August 1995, Microsoft also released
a version of Word to go with it in the Office 95 productivity
suite. It included the ability to use embedded macro commands.
</P>
<P>
   ``About a month later, we had Concept, the first macro virus,''
Wells said. ``One year later, we had Larue, the first Excel
(spreadsheet program) macro virus.''
</P>
<P>
   Office 97, the next version of Microsoft's suite, included
features meant to block macro viruses, and macro viruses written
for Word 95 didn't work with Word 97. But Wells said virus writers
soon began writing macro viruses for the new version. Melissa was
one of those, and it disabled Word's built-in virus protections.
</P>
<P>
   Network Associates' Wasson said a growing number of viruses
directly attack Windows 95/98 features. These strains, known as
Win32 viruses, can be particularly destructive.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best-known _ and most-feared _ is the W95.CIH virus,
which the press dubbed Chernobyl. Investigators recently discovered
the author of the virus, a 24-year-old man in Taipei, Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   W95.CIH infects program files on Windows 95/98/NT computers. The
original strain is triggered on April 26 (some variants trigger on
the 26th of every month), and has two ``payloads'' _ the
destructive component of a virus. One overwrites crucial parts of
the computer's hard drive, and can cause it not to boot. The other
attacks some computers' BIOSes, which contain key information about
the machine, such as hard drive type, and time and date.
</P>
<P>
   The virus, fortunately, is not designed to be transmitted via
the Internet. But it can be transferred this way if an executable
file is attached to e-mail, or downloaded via an Internet software
archive.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the speed with which viruses travel, companies such
as Symantec and Network Associates have changed the way they
respond.
</P>
<P>
   They used to offer updates to their antivirus products every 30
to 90 days. Now, those updates are available via the Internet a
couple of times a week _ or even daily, if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   For example, within hours of the Melissa and Worm.ExplorerZip
epidemics, both Symantec and Network Associates had fixes for them
on their Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Both Wasson and Nachenberg say they add 10 to 15 new viruses to
their databases each week _ sometimes even more. They receive
samples of viruses from customers, or from other researchers, break
them down and study them. The information is then included in the
product databases.
</P>
<P>
   Antivirus software looks for telltale characteristics of viruses
_ called fingerprints _ as it scans both a computer's memory and
its hard drive. The antivirus programs can also look for telltale
viruslike behavior, which provides some protection against new or
unknown strains.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the fact that there are tens of thousands of known
viruses, only about 200 to 300 are actively spreading in the wild.
</P>
<P>
   And many of the viruses are not unique, but variations of other,
existing viruses.
</P>
<P>
   Wells said that there are many reasons why viruses are written.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not always the stereotype of the punk with a lot of
pierced body parts,'' said Wells. ``Some people do it for revenge,
to get back at an employer, for example. Or they are messing around
with a programming idea, and they let it get away. Once it gets out
in the wild, it's almost impossible to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-99 1643EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990625.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9648 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV27-     06-25 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEITHER HEAT NOR POOR SOIL STAYS THESE SAGES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 27) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CASS PETERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The virtues of salvias, or sages, are well known to gardeners.
Few plants are more reliable and trouble-free, even if grown in dry
spots with less than perfect soil.
</P>
<P>
   Annual scarlet sage (S. splendens), with its spiky red flowers,
is a mainstay in the flower bed and looks especially good paired
with fuzzy white dusty miller, which can take equal abuse from
weather and soil.
</P>
<P>
   It's a rare herb garden that doesn't include common sage (S.
officinalis), even though its aromatic foliage doesn't make it into
the kitchen as often as it should. More often, culinary sage is
grown for its bluish-green foliage and spring flowers, borne in
spikes, as is typical of the family, and a lovely shade of blue.
They're edible, too.
</P>
<P>
   There's another species of sage that deserves to be as widely
grown as those two: Mexican bush sage (S. leucantha), also called
velvet sage.
</P>
<P>
   In my garden, Mexican bush sage is the undisputed star of the
perennial bed in late summer and autumn. I plant it there even
though it is not perennial in my south-central Pennsylvania climate
(it won't take temperatures below 25 degrees Fahrenheit), reserving
a large spot to accommodate it.
</P>
<P>
   If I put in three plants a foot apart in mid-May, I can count on
a mass of Mexican sage about four feet tall and equally as wide
when they start flowering in August.
</P>
<P>
   The stems are downy white; the leaves, a soothing shade of
mid-green with a slightly pebbly texture. Mexican sage is
attractive as a backdrop to early-flowering perennials until it
takes over with its own blooming show.
</P>
<P>
   And what a show. Mexican sage produces long spikes of bloom,
each up to two feet long with furry purple calyxes and white
corollas. The short-lived corollas drop within a few days (not
before receiving lavish attention from any resident hummingbirds
and butterflies). The calyxes stay fresh-looking for months.
</P>
<P>
   Since the old flowers persist and new ones keep forming, by
autumn the plant is covered with velvety blooms. The irresistible
texture, like the soft foliage of silvermound artemisia or the
furry leaves of lamb's ear, invites caresses.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican sage's height dictates that it be placed toward the back
of the perennial or annual flower garden, but it's wise to leave a
narrow path to it so you can pet it frequently.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican sage doesn't need much encouragement to produce profuse
quantities of flowers (commercial growers have been known to
harvest up to 200 long-stemmed cut flowers from a single plant),
but I do a little early-season pruning to insure plenty of
flowering stems and keep the plants in bounds.
</P>
<P>
   Like chrysanthemums, Mexican sage plants benefit from being
pinched or pruned back early, which results in more flowering stems
later in the season.
</P>
<P>
   Because I propagate my own plants from the previous year's
stock, the plants I put in in May often have a single long stem.
Before I plant, I cut the stem back by about half. This forces the
plant to branch out. When the new stems are 8 to 10 inches long, I
cut them back by half again.
</P>
<P>
   You can pinch back a third or even a fourth time. If you do, you
will get a more compact plant with shorter flower spikes. I like
the graceful, draping effect of long flower spikes, and I have the
space to accommodate a large clump of Mexican sage.
</P>
<P>
   If your space is limited, by all means pinch more often, but
stop by late July. That's when the plant starts to set its flower
buds, and any additional pinching will diminish the display.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican sage makes a spectacular cut flower. If you're
displaying it by itself, you needn't add water to the vase. The
stems are stiff enough to hold the flowers upright while they dry.
The white corolla will drop out, of course, but the calyxes will
retain their deep purple color for months if kept out of direct
light.
</P>
<P>
   Where Mexican sage is perennial (generally Georgia and south),
it will be happiest in soil that drains well, to prevent rot from
killing the plant over winter. Cut the plant back to the ground in
winter, and mulch it with loose straw or leaf compost to prevent
damage from abrupt freezes.
</P>
<P>
   Where Mexican sage is not perennial, take cuttings before frost.
Propagating is simplicity itself. Cuttings should be four to five
inches long, preferably from a nonflowering stem. Because almost
all my Mexican sage stems are in flower by late autumn, I am often
forced to propagate from a flowering stem, and it works. Just get
the shortest flowering stems you can find.
</P>
<P>
   Strip off the lower foliage, leaving one or two pairs of leaves
over a couple of inches of bare stem. Insert the stem in a pot of
wet vermiculite or sand. Keep the medium wet. After a couple of
weeks, test the cutting by tugging on it gently. If you feel
resistance, it has rooted.
</P>
<P>
   Move the rooted cutting into its own pot, using a light potting
mix with plenty of peat and vermiculite, and grow it in a sunny
window. If you cut it back a time or two during the winter, you can
root the additional cuttings.
</P>
<P>
   The cutting will likely bloom over winter, even if it has only a
single stem. Just cut the bloom off when you plant the sage out in
the spring. There's no harm in letting the plant flower indoors,
and it gives you something to pet over the winter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
