<HEADLINE>
A'S SALE IS A TANGLED WEB INDEED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY RATTO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Maybe we've been looking at this A's sale all
wrong. Maybe Major League Baseball is happy with Andy Dolich and
George Zimmer and Bob Piccinini and the depth and breadth of their
portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Bud Selig and the owners for whom he serves don't care who
owns the A's as long as someone does, and as long as they stay in
Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, that would be such a noticeable departure
from form that one should only make that assumption with the
greatest of care. Put another way, we should have our noses at the
ready.
</P>
<P>
   The morass of the Athletics' sale seemed to undergo a serious
detangling Tuesday when the Lyle Campbell/Michael Lazarus/Steve
Stone group announced it was withdrawing its $12 million in
good-faith money. Their version was that Campbell had found other
plans for his 12 large, and that they would await developments
regarding the Dolich group.
</P>
<P>
   It looked, frankly, like capitulation born of frustration. The
Lazarus people didn't like dealing with the Oakland political
structure (and in fairness, can you blame them?), accused the
Dolich people of various acts of sneaky behavior (as-yet unproved),
and thought the local media had been mean to them (largely true,
though sort of petty).
</P>
<P>
   But at the end of their apparent surrender, Michael Lazarus said
something that should cause your ears to twitch. ``We are still
interested in owning a baseball team, including the A's.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly surrender turned to hanging around and waiting for the
other hobnailed boot to drop.
</P>
<P>
   You see, baseball owners rarely allow one of their franchises to
pass freely from seller to buyer without some spirited intervention
tactics. Too much matters to them to let a team just roll itself
over _ location, sales price, lease terms, sales price, friendly
faces, sales price, total wealth, and of course, sales price.
</P>
<P>
   In the Oakland case, there is the added annoyance of the San
Francisco Giants, who have a new stadium arising and would
appreciate it greatly if the A's would (a) get lost, or if that
isn't possible, (b) die. The owners have pondered the Bay Area
problem since almost the day Charlie Finley moved the Kansas City
A's to the left, and despite a series of false starts, still have
two teams in what they all believe is a one-team market.
</P>
<P>
   They seemed amazed, then, to learn that not one but two groups
were interested in giving Steve Schott and Ken Hofmann, the current
owners, more than $120 million for a team everyone says (mostly
incorrectly) can never make money.
</P>
<P>
   Dolich had the local political clout, made possible by Schott
and Hofmann's decision to sell that part of their right to sell to
the city. Campbell chose not to play on Dolich's home court, and
his bid was therefore reduced to a backup's role. Thus, it made no
sense for them to stay in a contest they couldn't win.
</P>
<P>
   Unless, of course, it is a contest Campbell can still win, and
the only thing that didn't make sense was to let someone else hold
his money instead of him.
</P>
<P>
   Dolich won only the right to have his bid placed before the
owners, not the right to be approved. Campbell only surrendered
what he had already lost, the right to have his bid placed before
them first.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, if Dolich is turned down by the owners, a group
of men who know that Selig prefers the Campbell group (which means
that the owners Selig is closest to prefer the Campbell group) can
then have Campbell re-submit his offer, or one re-tailored to meet
Schott and Hofmann's mutual approval, and then vote up or down on
that.
</P>
<P>
   The other possibility is that Schott and Hofmann, thus freed by
Dolich's rejected bid, would keep the team and either continue to
squeeze out its annual profit or try to scout up a third bid to
create a new bidding war, one unencumbered by the political
process.
</P>
<P>
   Follow? Well, no, I can see you don't. Then again, this is
baseball, and you're not meant to follow it. You're just meant to
understand this one thing, and to never forget it: If this starts
looking like a simple process, beware. If you think what you saw
Tuesday from the Campbell group tells you something, think again.
And when you're done doing that, think a third time.
</P>
<P>
   This is like watching the Rockies in Denver on a night when the
wind is blowing out _ bring food, and plan to eat more than once.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
