<HEADLINE>
BLOOD TELLS AND SO DOES BURKE'S 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Great Britain, France)   (For release Sunday, June 27) 
 &HT;    (DW) 
 By MITCHELL OWENS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Call them what you will _ natural, illegitimate, by-blows or
that Old French word, bastard _ children produced outside the
marriage aren't just showing up on the covers of magazines, cradled
by beaming Hollywood moms. They are also being outed in
publications that kept out-of-wedlock children firmly swept under
the Savonnerie.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the new edition of Burke's Peerage and Baronetage, the
106th edition of a studbook of titled Britons that was first
published in 1826. Weighing it at 16 pounds, the two-volume
directory _ which was published last month and is available through
Fitzroy Dearborn in Chicago for $395 _ has something it never had
before: a whiff of tabloid journalism.
</P>
<P>
   Bound in scarlet cotton, the genealogies compiled in its 3,400
pages now include all children, legitimate or not. The Earl of
Snowdon, who was once married to Princess Margaret, is listed,
along with his present wife, Lucy, their 19-year-old daughter,
Frances, and, surprisingly, his year-old son, Jasper, from the
liaison of Lord Snowdon, 69, and the 36-year-old daughter of a
baronet.
</P>
<P>
   The journalist peer and beer heir Baron Moyne, a k a Jonathan
Guinness, is joined by his wife of 35 years, Suzanne, and his five
children _ and a son and two daughters by an extramarital
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   The Manhattan night life fixture Anthony Haden-Guest, 62, is
now, officially, identified as the eldest, though illegitimate,
child of his late father, the fourth Baron Haden-Guest. Since
Haden-Guest's parents did not marry until two years after his
birth, the barony went to his younger and legitimately born brother
Christopher, who is now married to Jamie Leigh Curtis.
</P>
<P>
   Haden-Guest appreciates the belated recognition, though he
considers hereditary titles, especially in an aristocracy riddled
with questions of paternity, ``a charming irrelevance.'' Still, he
said: ``I'm delighted, because I loved my father, so I'm glad it's
in black and white. But as for it's significance? Hell, I live in
New York, not England.''
</P>
<P>
   Burke's typeface may be tiny but the information is like ``Hard
Copy'' in ``Masterpiece Theater'' guise. A baron's son whose
Iranian companion may not be his legal wife, Burke's says flatly,
is in any event, the mother of his child. Lady Cosima
Vane-Tempest-Stewart is identified as the ``nominal'' daughter of
the present Marquess of Londonderry _ though with milady's caveat,
quoted in the book, that she ``claims that Robin Douglas-Home,'' a
politician who died in 1968, is her biological father.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this blunt honesty, Charles Mosley, the book's editor in
chief, said, ``We have a lot of information on people that we would
never publish.'' He mentioned prison sentences and drug addictions.
But when it comes to genealogical news, he added, ``if it appears
in the press, and there is no denial of the fact, we will put it in
the text.'' This was the case with Lord Snowdon's son by Melanie
Cable-Alexander, an editor of the tony British magazine Country
Life.
</P>
<P>
   Burke's sent a draft of its entry to Snowdon with his youngest
child included, and he raised no objection, Mosley said. This is
standard procedure for all potentially touchy entries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Curiously, we've got no complaints about listing an
illegitimate child,'' Mosley said. ``But some people have been
annoyed that we're listing someone they wish they could forget,''
like an ex-wife or former son-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, many of the world's top society directories, including
the Social Register in the United States, have been participating
in this quiet, well-mannered revolution. Children whose names do
not normally make it into public announcements are showing up,
albeit discreetly, in these social reference books.
</P>
<P>
   Burke's competitor, Debrett's, has listed bastard children for
``15 years or so, but we haven't made a great deal of it,'' said
its editor, Charles Kidd. ``Lord Moyne, for instance, had written
at considerable length about his second family in a magazine or
newspaper article, so it was public knowledge,'' he added. ``He
obviously considered them part of his family, so we wrote to him,
asking if he objected to our including them.''
</P>
<P>
   Moyne apparently did not hesitate, though three telephone calls
last week to his London home were not answered. Neither were three
calls to Snowdon's studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``One or two dowagers may have been a bit shocked at first,''
Kidd said. ``But times have changed so radically in the last 20
years that even the older generation is quite accepting. So it was
quite impossible for us to stand by the old policy of not including
natural children.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the Social Register, a New York publication popularly
regarded as staid to the point of inertia, can be a
reading-between-the-lines delight for insiders. (Copies are $105
through written request to the Social Register Association, 381
Park Avenue South, New York 10016.)
</P>
<P>
   According to its spokesman, Thomas Lee Jones, the SR, as it is
called, listed its first out-of-wedlock birth in 1987, in its
births and deaths announcements at the front of each volume. Since
then, there has been at least one in every edition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have people who read the book carefully, but it's not the
kind of thing that's touted,'' he added. However, the black book
with the distinctive tangerine racing stripes _ ``Social Register
orange,'' Jones said _ does not indulge in Burke's-style
exposition: just name of baby, date and place of birth, and,
occasionally, a grandparent's name rather than the unwed parents,
to cloak the circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's wonderful,'' Letitia Baldrige, the
common-sensical etiquette doyenne, said from her office in
Washington. ``Children deserve to be recognized and given their
status. It's not their fault what goes on in the bedroom. Sure, the
acknowledgment might be tough on the family, but when you think of
that bastard child . . .'' _ Ms. Baldrige paused _ ``identification
is the kind and compassionate thing to do. It doesn't meant that
the child's relationship with the father's wife or other children
will be any easier. But it clears the air.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-99 1649EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990625.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9670 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ILLEGITIMATE-CHILDREN     06-25 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ILLEGITIMATE-CHILDREN-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
undated: clears the air.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gertrude Himmelfarb, the conservative historian who wrote ``The
De-Moralization of Society: From Victorian Virtues to Modern
Values,'' was not so sure that the listing of illegitimate children
in social registries was a sign of progress. ``What can I say _
it's a sign of times,'' she said, laughing. ``It means they've
bought into the counterculture.''
</P>
<P>
   But the august Almanach de Gotha is adamantly against this
trend. Largely devoted to chronicling the noble families of
Continental Europe, the Gotha recently resumed production after a
55-year hiatus. Published in London by Almanach de Gotha Ltd., the
1999 edition is $110 and can be ordered through bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the parents can't be bothered to integrate illegitimate
children into the family, I don't see why we should do the job for
them,'' said John Kennedy, the editor. He makes a distinction
between legal and verbal acknowledgment of an out-of-wedlock child.
This explains why the Gotha did not publish the name of the
illegitimate son of Prince Konstantin von Schaumberg-Lippe until
this year's edition, after he legally adopted the child, Oliver,
who is now 11. The prince married the child's mother, Petra Maass,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now he is legally the man's child, and properly recognized by
law,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Bottin Mondain, since 1903 France's guide to its
officially defunct nobility, the situation is much the same. ``I
think I would say no'' to a request to list an illegitimate child,
said its manager, Blanche de Kersaint. ``The parents must be a
legally married couple,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   As for the issue of listing a same-sex couple _ say, the
hypothetical Vicomte de Pamplemousse and his male companion of 30
years _ Mrs. de Kersaint was apologetic but unyielding: ``It's
impossible to write them together. It's a rule of the house. They
would have to be separate. At the same address, yes, but not the
same listing.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, said Martine de Forges, the book's public-relations
officer, the Vicomte de Pamplemousse's companion would have to come
equipped with recommendations from two Bottin Mondain members, just
like any new applicant. (Copies of the Bottin Mondain can be
ordered from its office in Paris: -(33-1) 44.51.13.13.)
</P>
<P>
   At the turn of the century, same-sex couples often appeared
together in the thin pages of the Social Register, though cloaked
under innocuous Edwardianism: two unrelated ladies living at the
same address, like the decorator Elsie de Wolfe and her companion,
Elisabeth Marbury.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world is so `in your face' now, but back then, everything
was more subtle, which allowed that kind of thing,'' said Jones,
who is also the editor and publisher of the SR's sister, a smart
and sassy society magazine called The Observer.
</P>
<P>
   Male couples living together have also appeared, sometimes
together, though usually divided by the alphabet, separate but
equal. ``Ultimately, joint listings are the next step for all of
us,'' Jones added.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, he said, the Social Register received a request from a
woman who wanted her female companion jointly listed. ``So I sent
the mate a form, like we do for a man or woman who wants his or her
spouse in the book,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The news of that same-sex application was welcomed by Ms.
Baldrige. ``Providing it's a longtime union, and a serious
relationship,'' she said, ``why not?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
