u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-LAWLESS-0626-C     06-25 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-LAWLESS-0626-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NATO POLICE STRUGGLE TO KEEP ORDER IN KOSOVO'S LAWLESS CAPITAL
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ As refugees pour back into Kosovo in
record numbers, British police forces Friday said there were 14
murders around the capital the day before and the province verged
on a breakdown of law and order.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is quite a lot of lawlessness,'' said Maj. Martin
Williamson of the British Royal Military Police.
</P>
<P>
   The 14 murders Thursday were in the central region of Kosovo
alone, and brought the total there to 26 since NATO arrived two
weeks ago. The population there is difficult to gauge because of
the previous exodus of refugees now returning. But, it is likely
just a few hundred thousand.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the reported murders were thought to be by ethnic
Albanians seeking revenge for atrocities committed by Serbs during
a horrific ethnic cleansing campaign that intensified as NATO
warplanes dropped bombs of Yugoslavia. Looting of Serb businesses
also continued Friday.
</P>
<P>
   British Lt. Gen. Michael Jackson, NATO commander of the Kosovo
peacekeeping force, known as KFOR, met Friday with Serbs in central
Kosovo to reassure them that his troops were seeking to restore
order. Thousands of Serbs fearing retribution from angry Kosovar
Albanians have already fled to Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Also Friday, Serb officials released 166 ethnic Albanians they
had been holding prisoner in Serbia. There are likely more than a
thousand more being held.
</P>
<P>
   NATO troops moved in to control Kosovo on June 12 after the
signing of the military technical agreement that ordered the
withdrawal of Yugoslav forces, and Serb police and paramilitary
gangs. With about 21,000 troops in this war-torn province now, NATO
is responsible for keeping order until the United Nations
administrative government can establish its multinational police
force.
</P>
<P>
   But, NATO has been kept busy focusing on overseeing the
withdrawal of the Serb troops and the disarming of the rebel Kosovo
Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, crime and tension have been on the rise as Kosovar
refugees return to their homes from refugee camps in neighboring
Albania and Macedonia, and from makeshift hideouts in the
province's mountains.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees reported Friday that
48,000 Kosovars returned Thursday, the highest number to date.
UNHCR spokeswoman Paula Ghedini said it was the largest spontaneous
return of refugees in the 25-year history of the refugee agency.
More than 300,000 of the estimated 860,000 refugees that fled Serb
terror Kosovo have returned.
</P>
<P>
   Within days, the United Nations will begin its so-called
organized return, bringing refugees to the country on buses. The
refugee agency has been waiting as NATO-led ``de-mining''
operations have fanned out all over the province to remove
landmines, booby traps and unexploded ordnance like that which
killed two NATO peacekeepers and two civilians earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   The expected U.N.-sponsored return of refugees will only tax
more the already-strained law enforcement duties of NATO. For
example, there are only 144 British military police in the capital
region, where looting was rampant Thursday night as ethnic
Albanians stormed Serb businesses in Pristina. NATO officers vowed
to crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   But, in the afternoon daylight Friday, a group of about 20 teens
and children smashed the windows of a Serb candy store on
Pristina's main street and made off with boxes and pockets full of
sweets and pretzels.
</P>
<P>
   British troops arrived, arresting two and chasing the rest from
the store.
</P>
<P>
   What happens to those arrested is still undetermined, as there
is no court system. For now, military commanders review their case
after four hours and then every 48 hours to determine if they can
be released or bailed out.
</P>
<P>
   British troops have established three police stations in the
Pristina area, and Kosovars are lining up for hours outside to
report everything from car thefts to murders.
</P>
<P>
   Many were ethnic Albanians reporting crimes committed during the
Serb terror spree.
</P>
<P>
   Serbs, meanwhile, were left hoping NATO would soon increase its
presence. NATO is ultimately planning to have more than 50,000
troops in the province.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
