<HEADLINE>
NOT JUST ANOTHER WORKING GIRL: THE UPSCALE EX-WIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 27)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By MONIQUE P. YAZIGI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Growing up, Elise Henning did all the right things.
She attended the Ethel Walker School, made her debut at the Junior
Assembly, spent her junior year in Geneva and graduated from Sarah
Lawrence College. When she returned to her parents' home in New
Canaan, Conn., she asked her father, a Wall Street commodities
trader, if she could go to law school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elise, you don't need to go to law school,'' she recalls him
saying. ``Your brother does.'' His advice: ``Catch a good man, make
him happy and you'll be taken care of for the rest of your life.''
</P>
<P>
   That was almost 30 years ago, and Ms. Henning ended up marrying
a lawyer, settling with him in Palm Beach, Fla., and socializing in
all the right circles. She entertained, became active in the
Episcopal Church of Bethesda-by-the-Sea and had a daughter who
attended Palm Beach Day School.
</P>
<P>
   It was just as her father had said. Until her husband left,
moving to Vermont. He paid no child support after the divorce in
1992, she said, relating the story over iced tea at the Hotel
Carlyle.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't know what to do.
</P>
<P>
   Not wanting her status in life to change, and most important,
not wanting her daughter, who was 12 at the time, to feel deprived
in any way, she assessed her skills. She had never worked at
anything but entry-level ``glamour jobs,'' as she put it, but she
did have a knowledge of fine homes. (She and all her friends had
always lived in them.) She knew how to entertain and dress
tastefully, and she had many rich and socially connected friends.
</P>
<P>
   So Ms. Henning became a real estate broker at Martha A.
Gottfried Inc., selling luxury properties to the social and the
trying-to-be-social. By night, she was a Palm Beach party planner,
helping women create ``beautiful parties'' for around $200 a guest.
(By telephone, she helped her daughter with homework). ``I was so
out there, networking, meeting more people,'' she said. ``The jobs
gave me an income, access and a great reason, as a single woman,
for being at all the parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Henning, who has since moved to Manhattan to sell real
estate at the upscale Stribling &AMP; Associates, went the classic
employment route of upper-class former wives _ both divorced and
widowed _ in their 40s and 50s. Reared to expect husbands to be
their providers, they are left without careers of their own, and
usually with a financial settlement too meager to maintain the life
they are accustomed to.
</P>
<P>
   But many can turn to careers in glossy fields for which their
particular credentials _ high-maintenance tastes and a network of
rich and socially connected friends _ make them ideally suited.
These include luxury real-estate sales, interior decorating, event
planning and ``client liaison'' at the Sotheby's or Christie's
auction houses, where they help the best clients decide what to buy
and which of their houses to put it in.
</P>
<P>
   A not-so-incidental benefit of these glamour jobs is that they
put women in the right circles to meet the next multimillionaire
husband, if that's what they have in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Simone, 44, a man about town with homes in Manhattan and
Greenwich, Conn., has dated many such women. ``My first line is,
`Are you a real estate broker or a decorator?''' he said, laughing.
``They always say, `I'm a real estate broker, but I was a
decorator. How did you know?'''
</P>
<P>
   Sugar Rautbord, a socialite author in Palm Beach, said the
upper-class divorcee has two options (neither including the
possibility, exercised by at least some women, of returning to
college or professional school to prepare for a new career). For
one, she can go to Sotheby's. ``That's where part of the mythic
lure is that you sit behind the desk or have some knowledge of
French antiquities, and a gentlemen will materialize in front of
you, purchase a catalog and ask for your hand in marriage,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Option 2 is to sell real estate. She recalled that a
``multi-asseted single man'' she knows was home-shopping in Palm
Beach, where an army of leggy, attractive divorcees was competing
over him. One day, she said, he called a broker he had been working
with, and a colleague said the woman was out of the office with a
terminal illness, but she would be happy to take him to dinner.
``The first broker had a dentist's appointment!'' said Ms.
Rautbord, whose latest novel, ``The Chameleon'' (Warner Books,
1999), is about a middle-aged woman who changes her life and moves
on by remarrying.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the difficulties of re-entering the dating world and
the workplace are common to all divorced women whose husbands
supported them, regardless of economic status. A 1996 study in the
American Sociological Review found that women's standard of living
after divorce fell 27 percent, while men's rose 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But Lenore Weitzman, the author of ``The Divorce Revolution: The
Unexpected Social and Economic Consequences for Women and Children
in America'' (Free Press/Macmillan, 1986), said the economic slide
for stay-at-home wives from affluent households is greater than
average, because there is such a discrepancy between what the
husband made and what the wife can earn.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the ladies-who-lunch set, in divorce they end up with a
skimpier lunch than when they started,'' said Raoul Felder, the
celebrity divorce lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the glamour job. The access to financial information about
home buyers _ and, in the New York world of co-op sales, social and
personal references _ makes luxury real estate sales the most
popular field for the once and hopeful wealthy wife. (For those who
might not be in it to stalk a husband, of course, it doesn't hurt
that the work can pay quite handsomely.) Taylor Stein, an owner of
the clubby Brown's restaurant on the Upper East Side, who used to
sell real estate at William B. May, said: ``Think about it: When
you get a customer who calls and he tells you he's looking for an
apartment that is $5 million, guess what, he's rich enough for you.
And if it's a co-op, you have access to the most intensely personal
information _ W-2's, reference letters.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Henning agrees, to a point. ``The application still doesn't
tell you about his character, his values,'' she said. You also have
to sniff around, maybe look up divorce records. ``If the guy is
from Darien, go up to Darien and read the circumstances of the
divorce,'' she said. That way you won't end up, like one friend of
hers, dating a man with excellent financial references who was also
cross-dressing in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Henning, who is in her early 50s, has gone out on a date or
two with men she met through her jobs, but ``nothing's worked
out,'' she said. Either they didn't ask her out again, or they
didn't live up to her expectations, which are high. ``When they ask
me to pay half the check,'' she said, ``I cross them off my list.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There is also the problem of dealing with the towering egos of
the middle-aged bachelors some women in New York refer to as ``the
billionaire boys' club.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Henning recalled dating a retired executive worth $80
million who was used to people's bowing and scraping. ``He had a
level of self-absorption that was scary,'' she said. ``When I would
talk, he would say `shut up.' He would only relate as if I were a
corporate secretary.'' She made him a needlepoint pillow that said,
``It ain't easy being king,'' then ended the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Pearson, a divorced woman in her 40s who still looks a bit
like the cheerleader she was in college, also has high standards.
She would be thrilled to fall in love with a man with five houses
and a horse farm, though she acknowledged she would make do with
less: ``I just want a country house.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Pearson, who was divorced in her 20s, bounced around in some
not-so-glamorous jobs _ as an art director for CBS, then for Hearst
magazines _ before landing in the bona fide glamour field of
decorating. ``At CBS, I was working so hard, weekends, nights, I
never met anyone externally,'' she said. ``I sat at my desk all the
time. It was not the right existence, so I quit.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Pearson said that in 1997, she ran into a handsome, recently
divorced man at a fund-raiser for the very social Henry Street
Settlement. He was moving from Greenwich, Conn., to Manhattan and
asked her to help him find an apartment and to decorate it. She
found a place on the Upper East Side for him, then moved in with
him and started to decorate. The relationship was moving along _
she had met his family, and had even gone camping with his mother _
but just as the window treatments were delivered, her beau said the
relationship was too serious and asked her to move out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I had finished my job,'' she said ruefully.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Ms. Pearson said, she has a rule not to date clients. Or at
least not until her work is finished. It is part of the courtship
dance between the glamorous working woman and the wealthy bachelor
_ a working relationship full of moments of professional intimacy,
which allow the rare bloom and the buzzing bee to size one another
up.
</P>
<P>
   R. Couri Hay, a society columnist for Hamptons magazine, said
that all of the men and women who meet this way have something the
other wants. ``These women are looking for an American
billionaire,'' he said, ``and a man wants glamour, prestige, social
connections that he doesn't have. A man who has money and doesn't
have class wants to get himself a glamour girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Steve Pearlman, 43, a plastic surgeon, was a client of Ms.
Pearson's, though they never dated. But he has gone out with a real
estate broker who showed him apartments. He said a man can learn a
lot about a potential mate in such professional encounters. ``You
see their taste, their attention to detail, their attention to
budget,'' he said. ``Are they realistic? Are they frivolous?''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Pearson's white-blonde hair and trim figure (she works out
three or four times a week) mark her as virtually the universal
type among the glamorous divorced women of the Upper East Side. She
and many others tend to favor a uniform of Adolfo and Chanel at
lunch, classic 18-karat jewelry and, for lounging with friends,
white cotton blouses that seem chosen so the buttons gape slightly
across the chest. Most look far younger than their years, an effect
achieved through meticulous grooming and, in many cases, the magic
of a surgeon's knife.
</P>
<P>
   They are well aware that in looking for romance with men their
age, they are competing with women a decade or two younger.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard,'' says Mary Meehan, a stunning blonde from Dallas,
crossing her long legs on a blue velvet Louis XV couch in her New
York apartment. ``Men in their 50s ... there aren't that many for
us 50-year-olds.'' She is a student of the fashionable theories of
evolutionary psychology. ``Men are instinctively drawn to young
women of childbearing age, and women are drawn to men who can take
care of them, with power,'' she said. ``It's instinct.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Meehan, who has been divorced four times, is a decorator who
works and socializes hard. (Nina Griscom and Dr. Dan Baker are
close friends.) She only takes decorating jobs for $500,000 and up.
In her own apartment, a modernist white box, she spent many hours
adding moldings and gilding, and upholstering the walls to give it
the look of a European chateau.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned my work ethic in my 40s,'' she said. ``I wish I had
it in my 20s.''
</P>
<P>
   Growing up with wealthy parents, Ms. Meehan thought she would
never have to work. ``Proper young ladies got married,'' she said.
Her first husband hunted and fished, she said, living off inherited
money. After her latest divorce, from Michael Meehan, a former
partner at Salomon Brothers, he got the Southampton house, and
their nine-room apartment on East 72nd Street was sold to satisfy
the settlement terms.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Meehan traded down to a two-bedroom apartment on Park
Avenue, and she had to go to work nearly full-time. Fortunately,
her life of privilege had given her exquisite taste. At 19, her
father sent her, her mother and a sister to Paris to shop for
antiques for a year. Her decorating projects have been published in
Architectural Digest, which has won her the attention of bachelors,
though not always the most ideal ones. After publication, she said,
she received letters from men in prison _ avid readers of the
magazine, it turned out.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At Park Avenue tea parties, the popular theory is that a
divorced woman has five years from the time her settlement comes
through to meet the next husband.
</P>
<P>
   The deadline reflects the reality of modern divorce, which
rarely grants a woman long-term alimony. Most states, including New
York, award ``equitable distribution'' of assets in a divorce,
which means a greater share goes to the bigger contributor; wives
often receive a lump sum.
</P>
<P>
   Even some of the richest, most high-profile women can find the
financial carpet pulled out from under them. After her divorce from
the billionaire Henry Kravis, Carolyne Roehm lost his backing for
the fashion company she ran, so she took flower-arranging classes
to prepare for a new career writing books about flowers. ``I went
from running seven houses to running one, my own,'' Ms. Roehm said.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara de Portago said there is a difference between the hard
economic reality of the divorced woman and the myth of ``the
divorcee, with that first accent on the e.'' Being a divorcee, she
said, ``means that you're heavily subsidized by the former husband,
swathed in haute couture _ you're bejeweled. Of course, a divorcee
has no children, is massaged in oil and is lolling about on the
French Riviera or Gstaad.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. de Portago, thrice divorced, wouldn't mind being such a
figure. Instead, she works for glamorous employers _ Sotheby's,
Christian Dior and the Versailles Foundation _ largely trading on
the taste and connections acquired during a life in the beau monde.
``My work is all social,'' she said, mostly ``conducted over
lunch'' _ La Grenouille, Le Cirque 2000, Le Bernardin.
</P>
<P>
   Over Evian at the Pierre, Ms. de Portago said she did not want
to talk about her three former husbands (Anthony de Portago, a son
of Carroll Petrie; Jason Grant, a playwright, and William Tabert,
an investment banker), but she was happy to talk about work. As a
consultant to Christian Dior, which supplies her with a wardrobe,
she entices friends to buy the house's clothes. She gives a lunch
twice a year at Le Cirque for 150 women, all of whom must wear
Dior.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. de Portago grew up in the palace of Versailles. Truly. Her
stepfather, Gerald Van der Kemp, was the curator.
</P>
<P>
   At Sotheby's, where she works in client relations, she advises
new customers _ many of them newly wealthy _ on what and how to buy
at auction. She said that men fly her to their country homes,
introduce her to more people and, oh yes, sometimes propose
marriage. ``They say, `Please marry me, Barbara _ you could be such
an asset to me,''' she said, then added, ``There are so many men
out there, but no one I want yet.''
</P>
<P>
   While Ms. Henning, the real estate broker who moved to New York
from Palm Beach, encouraged her daughter, Cornelia, now 19, to make
her debut at the Junior Assembly, she is now warning her not to
follow her own example of neglecting a career and marrying for
security. Two years ago, after Cornelia left for Vanderbilt
University in Nashville, Tenn., she called home and said, ``Mom,
all the girls here want is their M.R.S.''
</P>
<P>
   Within a year, Ms. Henning brought her daughter to Manhattan and
urged her to enroll at New York University, where she is now
studying filmmaking.
</P>
</TEXT>
