<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV27-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE GREAT BOMB HEIST' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 27, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The federal government last week began administering polygraph
tests to the first of around 5,000 nuclear weapons scientists and
other employees in sensitive positions as part of its campaign
against Chinese espionage, according to The Washington Post. The
process is expected to take four years.
</P>
<P>
   It's the first time the ``lie detector'' has been used for
widespread screening outside the CIA and the National Security
Agency. The defense and telecommunications industries, merely
baffled when the fracas began two years ago over Chinese launches
of US satellites, today are genuinely upset. With China's
application to join the World Trade Organization in jeopardy, the
entire corporate establishment is involved.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the CIA is advertising for recruits, 35 or younger,
to its clandestine service. Qualities sought include an adventurous
spirit, forceful personality, superior intellect, tough-mindedness,
integrity, courage and patriotism. ``You will need to deal with
fast-moving, ambiguous and unstructured situations that will test
your resourcefulness to the utmost,'' say the ads.
</P>
<P>
   A central premise of those who worry about China is that there
exists a close analogy with the early days of the Cold War _ that
the famous ``W-88'' warhead plans obtained by the Chinese confer
the same sort of advantage as the blueprints that enabled the
Russians in the late 1940s to produce a perfect copy of one of the
first US bombs, a year or two earlier than a working bomb could
have been assembled independently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Feed the benchmarks into the codes on the supercomputer and _
presto! _ the People's Liberation Army leaps a decade ahead in its
race to nuclear weapon parity,'' writes William Safire, the New
York Times columnist who more than any other commentator brought
the crisis to a boil.
</P>
<P>
   ``The potential damage is on a magnitude of the Fuchs-Rosenberg
losses,'' says former Energy Department counterintelligence chief
Nola Trulock, invoking the names of Soviet spies who provided
information that may or may not have proved vital to the early
Soviet nuclear program.
</P>
<P>
   What if they are right? To get back in the spirit of the 1950s,
I re-read ``The Torment of Secrecy: The Background and Consequences
of American Security Policies,'' by Edward A. Shils. It offers the
same kind of reliable field guide to Red scares as does Charles P.
Kindleberger's ``Manias, Panics and Crashes'' to financial bubbles.
</P>
<P>
   Shils, the great University of Chicago sociologist, was, in many
ways, the first and best ``neo-conservative.'' A figure of enormous
importance in the second half of the 20th century _ comparable to
the better-known political philosopher Isaiah Berlin _ he died at
the age of 84 in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Shils wrote his book in 1956, when there wasn't the slightest
ambiguity about the threat posed by the Soviets _ that was the year
they crushed the Hungarian revolt. Without understating the dangers
in the least, he neverthless managed to untangle the many
mechanisms by which ``small bands of fantasy-obsessed extremists
spread thinly over many strata and professions'' managed to
precipitate the unpleasantness of the McCarthy era.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly there were some pretty striking similarities between
then and now. The deeper sources of fear today are much the same as
those he identified: hyperpatriotism, xenophobia, isolationism,
fundamentalism, fear of revolution and populism. The paranoid style
_ ``the belief that the world is dominated by unseen circles of
conspirators, operating behind our backs''_ is unchanged. The
natural antagonism among politicians, bureaucrats, and
intellectuals still yields the various divisive alliances that are
inherent in any triangle.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, motives are the same. Of the GOP in the early 1950s,
out of office for five presidential terms, Shils wrote, ``Passion
for office stirred the Republican soul, the blood ran more
vigorously in their veins as the thought of returning to power
became more immediate and more plausible to them. They became
ravenous. So long out of power and so close to it! Anything short
of insurrection might have appealed to many Republicans as a way of
getting back.''
</P>
<P>
   A mere eight years without the White House in the 1990s sufficed
to produced an impeachment drive.
</P>
<P>
   It's when you think about the differences between the early Cold
War and the present day that you begin to really wonder about the
judgment of those promoting the panic over Chinese espionage.
</P>
<P>
   For example, consider the wide diffusion of technology that has
occurred in the last 50 years. According to David Holloway,
director of Stanford University's Institute for International
Studies and author of ``Stalin and the Bomb,'' nuclear weapons
scientists at Los Alamos have been working closely with their
counterparts in the former Soviet Union, in large part in order to
prevent the impoverished Russians from selling their secrets to
willing buyers around the world. This arrangement now is endangered
by Congressional bullying.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the existence of this shadowy black market for nuclear
secrets is one plausible reason advanced for the central enigma
identified by the Cox Report on weapons spying. Why did China let
the CIA know they had stolen an important US secret? Just possibly,
Randolph Herber at Fermilab has ventured it was because China,
having gotten what it needed, wanted the United States to plug its
holes before the data leaked out to the next enterprising snoop.
</P>
<P>
   And as for computers? With the next generation of
over-the-counter personal computers about to exceed in power the
current limit for which a license currently is needed for sales to
China's military, it is simply silly to imagine that
number-crunching can be maintained as a meaningful constraint on
Chinese weapons shops. Says Robert L. Park, a commentator for the
American Physical Society, ``the discussion should return to the
hard reality _ you can't keep secrets forever so we better focus on
noproliferation and the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the differences between the deeply integrated world of
the present day and the Iron Curtain world of the early 1950s are
so great that anyone so fixated on the past as to bring up Klaus
Fuchs and the Rosenbergs is simply not to be taken seriously.
There's no doubt that the Chinese are arming themselves, nor is it
unreasonable to expect that they should, though what direction
relations will take over the course of the next century is far from
clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Great Bomb Heist'' (the phrase is that of The National
Journal), like Whitewater and the Blue Dress, will enter the
history books as a ploy manufactured mainly by fractious
out-of-power Republicans. It is this crazy willingness to go to any
lengths to impugn the opposition that we must hope will be
diminished by the outcome by the next election or two. For as
Edward Shils wrote, ``A free society can exist only when public
spirit is balanced by an equal inclination of men to mind their own
business.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
