<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRED-OFFICERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIVE FORT WORTH POLICE OFFICERS FIRED OVER MAN'S DEATH
</HEADLINE>
 (EDS: May be updated with afternoon news conference) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By KATHY SANDERS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Police Chief Thomas Windham has fired five
officers accused of ``hogtying'' a man who died in their custody,
and the district attorney and the FBI are investigating whether
they committed crimes or civil rights violations.
</P>
<P>
   The officers violated many departmental orders, used excessive
force, lied, falsified documents and orchestrated a cover-up about
the hogtying, Windham wrote in letters to the city Civil Service
Commission. The Star-Telegram obtained copies of the documents.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the officers were placed on indefinite suspension without
pay _ tantamount to firing _ last week, and the other three were
terminated Wednesday for their treatment of Luis Enrique Hernandez,
31, who died New Year's Day while being arrested.
</P>
<P>
   ``This death, coupled with the cover-up, is the most serious
thing that has happened in the Police Department since I've been
here,'' Windham, Fort Worth's chief for 14 years, said on
Wednesday. ``I have no explanation how this incident could have
occurred, and the subsequent cover-up.''
</P>
<P>
   The officers hid behind ``the so-called Blue Curtain or code of
silence,'' Windham wrote in the disciplinary letters. The death and
the officers' actions had the ``appearances of a classic case of
serious police misconduct,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The fired officers were identified as David N. Stefanos, 30, an
eight-year veteran; David P. Alkins, 27, commissioned in October
1995; Linn William Goodman, 27, an officer for slightly more than a
year; Hector Luis Melendez, 28, also with a year on the job; and
John R. ``John-John'' Ornelas, 25, an officer since December 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Sterling Gilliland, a Police Explorer Post scout and police
academy applicant, is implicated in the cover-up. His application
to the academy has now been rejected, Windham said.
</P>
<P>
   ``From all indications, these officers were good officers, and
the near-rookies, from all indications, were going to be good
officers,'' Windham said. ``The Explorer, they totally ruined him.
They included him in their cover-up. He even lied to
investigators.''
</P>
<P>
   The officers could not be reached for immediate comment.
</P>
<P>
   Windham said he called U.S. Attorney Paul Coggins to ask the FBI
to investigate the possibility of civil rights violations by the
officers. He said a criminal case will be submitted to the Tarrant
County district attorney's office for review.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our presentations to the U.S. attorney and the district
attorney will determine whether there is sufficient evidence that
it (the officers' actions) contributed to the man's death or caused
it,'' Windham said.
</P>
<P>
   Coggins said the FBI, a prosecutor in the Justice Department's
civil rights division who is based in Washington, and a prosecutor
from his office have been assigned to the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have opened a civil rights investigation,'' Coggins said.
``The civil rights division is working with my office, and the FBI
is investigating the case now. As soon as the FBI finishes its
investigation, they'll forward it to us and we'll make a
determination as to whether charges will be filed.''
</P>
<P>
   The firings and investigations come two months after Hernandez's
family sued the city of Fort Worth, alleging that the officers used
excessive and unreasonable force in subduing Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   Events leading to Hernandez's death began about 2:30 p.m. Jan.
1, when officer R.L. Hudson was dispatched to the 3200 block of
Hale Avenue to investigate a call saying that Hernandez had struck
a child, according to the documents.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, who suffered from schizophrenia, and Hudson began
struggling inside the house. When Hudson tried to use pepper spray
on Hernandez, both became incapacitated, Windham said. Hudson then
called for backup and remained blinded by the spray until
firefighters arrived to treat his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Hudson wasn't near the scene of the hogtying and had nothing to
do with the cover-up, Windham said.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman, Stefanos, Alkins, Ornelas, Melendez and Gilliland, who
was riding with Ornelas, answered Hudson's call for assistance and
handcuffed Hernandez, leading him outside the house.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said Hernandez continued to struggle. Stefanos, Alkins
and Goodman forced him to the ground, where restraints were placed
on his legs, according to the documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``According to Officers Alkins and Goodman, Officer Stefanos
told them to hog-tie Mr. Hernandez. Officer Alkins responded in
words to the effect that they couldn't do that, it was a General
Orders' violation,'' Windham's letters to the civil service say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Officer Stefanos answered in words to the effect that it did
not matter, hog-tie him anyway. Officers Stefanos, Alkins and
Goodman then in a reckless manner conjointly placed Mr. Hernandez
in an unauthorized hog-tie restraint with Officer Stefanos being
the officer that connected the leg restraints to the handcuffs,''
Windham's letters said.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez was left face-down in the street with a snap on the
leg restraints connected to the chain of the handcuffs, Windham
said. The snap is usually used to secure leg restraints to the
floorboard of a patrol car.
</P>
<P>
   Hogtying means to tie a person's bound feet and hands together
behind his or her back. It is specifically a violation of
department policy because in some cases, it has contributed to a
death, Windham said.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez became motionless and unconscious, and the officers
didn't respond to him other than to call for MedStar, the letters
say. Gilliland pointed out to Ornelas that Hernandez was neither
breathing nor responsive, but Ornelas left the prone man on the
street, pointing him out to MedStar attendants later, the letters
say.
</P>
<P>
   The restraints were finally removed at MedStar's request, but
Hernandez died soon. The cause of death was listed as cardiac
arrest and aspiration of gastric contents, but the manner of death
is still listed as undetermined, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors who saw the scuffle told investigators and reporters
that they had seen Hernandez hogtied, but the officers involved
repeatedly denied doing that, Windham said.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Haskell, who with Richard Henderson sued the city on
behalf of Hernandez's family, said the disciplinary action against
the officers was necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``My take on it is, this happened on a holiday; it was a bright,
sunny afternoon. There were a bunch of neighbors out, and they saw
what happened,'' Haskell said. ``We talked to the neighbors, and
they told us what went on. They said, `We wish we'd had a video
camera.' But they were the video camera. The Fort Worth Police
Department couldn't cover it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was Rodney King without the video camera. It ended up
happening, and too many people saw it. It makes it look good for
the Police Department to take this action, and they had to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez's sister, Gricelda Luna, said she believes that the
officers deserve to be fired ``because they did things they
shouldn't have. This way, they won't ever do what they did to my
brother again.''
</P>
<P>
   Luna was at home that day. She said she was forced outside when
she was overcome by pepper spray.
</P>
<P>
   Windham criticized the department's initial investigation and
pre-disciplinary review boards, saying too many questions had been
left unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reviewed that report, and there were so many loose ends, if
you were out in high winds, they would've beaten you to death,'' he
said. Many of the neighbors' reports that Hernandez had been
hogtied were apparently ignored or were not followed up, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that man was hogtied was screaming at you, although
every officer had omitted it from his statement, denied it and was
untruthful about it,'' Windham said.
</P>
<P>
   He then ordered an Internal Affairs Division investigation,
which resulted in the firings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing lacking out there was a hero who would have
stood up and said: `No way are we going to do this. We are not
going to hogtie him,' '' Windham said. ``That hurts.''
(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) .MDRV/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
