<HEADER>
A9771 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BASEBALL-BEST-NYTR &LR;      06-25 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASEBALL-BEST-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TOUGH LIST FOR CURRENT BALLPLAYERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BOB PADECKY   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Walk into a bar. Find yourself a guy who is sitting with his hat
on backward, staring at the television on the wall. Good. That
means he's a sports fan. Sit down next to him. Let him have it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kareem Abdul-Jabbar could score all right but, face it, he's
no George Mikan.''
</P>
<P>
   The guy laughs so hard his tonsils touch his teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Aw, just for the heck of it, keep it going.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barry Sanders can jiggle around a tackler but, boy, he ain't
Red Grange.''
</P>
<P>
   The guy falls off his stool and asks his friends to gather
around.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be intimidated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roger Clemens can throw hard but, come on, everyone knows
he'll never be Walter Johnson.''
</P>
<P>
   The guy will climb back on his stool, take a sip and then look
at you as if you just translated the Dead Sea Scrolls. You will
never be treated with more respect, never thought to be more
intelligent ... and you have just perpetuated a most unique sports
myth and you didn't even know it.
</P>
<P>
   In every other sport BUT baseball, we take it for granted the
athletes have become bigger, stronger, faster and quicker over the
years, that they can throw, jump, catch, run and crush skulls
better than they did, say, a half-century ago. Better medicine and
better nutrition produce a better product. Your basic athletic
algebraic formula.
</P>
<P>
   Except for baseball. We love its past so much we never want to
leave it, so we ignore reality.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, we received more evidence of that.
</P>
<P>
   The Society of American Baseball Research (SABR) announced the
100 Greatest Players of the 20th Century. Not one current player is
listed among the top 33, and only nine players still active are on
the list at all. In the top 10, for example, the most recent player
is Hank Aaron (fourth), who retired 23 years ago. In the top 25,
there are only two players who played in the last 16 years, Mike
Schmidt (16th) and Johnny Bench (19th).
</P>
<P>
   The message is obvious. Today's baseball is not worth a good
diddly. No one can play a lick these days. That line of thinking,
however, skips a few basic facts that should make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven of those top 25 players never played against
African-Americans and Latinos. Twelve of those 25 never had to play
a bulk of their season under the lights. Fifteen of those 25 never
had to fly across country to play games. Sixteen of those 25 never
had to play in an era when games were set up for a dominant relief
pitcher. Nineteen of those top 25 players never played in the
godforsaken numbers-numbing life-threatening Astrodome, or some
other dome nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   Meaning, there was a lot Tris Speaker (23) and Grover Alexander
(25) and Christy Mathewson (13) and Honus Wagner (10) and Rogers
Hornsby (9) missed. They missed the best competition because they
missed playing the best people in the most adverse conditions
tolerable.
</P>
<P>
   None of that it matters. Baseball historians always have become
misty-eyed when looking through the rearview mirror at the sport's
past. So many homespun homilies and florid poems have been penned
in baseball's name, all of it programming us into believing
baseball is America's soul, and please get out the hanky, well, we
don't want to leave warm and fuzzy for...
</P>
<P>
   ``If I ain't startin', I ain't departin''' was how Padres
shortstop Garry Templeton described his non-participation in an
All-Star Game. Yes, self-indulgence, no matter what the activity,
always comes with a price tag. If it's food consumed, it's a
waistline ready to zoom. If it's alcohol swallowed, it's Betty Ford
to follow. If it's pedal-to-the-floor, it's Officer Friendly
leaning against the driver's door. And if it's a pompous athlete
showing his feathers, then eventually he'll find bad weather.
</P>
<P>
   This is the bad weather. The people are exercising their opinion
by pushing the current players to the back of the bus, if they are
allowed on the bus at all. The game is not warm and fuzzy anymore.
It is a game of monopoly they are playing, not baseball, and so Ken
Griffey Jr. _ one of the top 10 talents in ALL of baseball history
_ shut up and take your place back there at No. 53. Grif, you're
not even good enough to beat out catcher Mickey Cochrane (50) and
his 119 homers and .323 average.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of sports? It can get bigger, faster, stronger, and no
one would dare claim Mikan could hold his own against Abdul-Jabbar
or that Red Grange could run for 150 yards against the Packers.
It's physical evolution, after all. Except baseball. In this sport,
you still want to believe Walter Johnson (11) is better than Roger
Clemens (34), even though Walter retired in 1927 in the midst of
the dead-ball era and Roger is still humping peas past moonballers.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball never changes. It's still a ball and a bat and a glove.
You could put Ty Cobb up there at the plate today, and he'd still
hit .400. Really. Honest. No kidding. Even with that ugly big bat
of his. And you resist questioning that logic every time you hear a
player today yapping. You stop clapping and send him all the way to
No. 65, which is where SABR put Barry Bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball never changes. You can compare 1920 and 1990. It's the
same game. Really. Honest. No kidding. It's still a ball and a bat
and a glove. And as long as you believe in that, let's take a ride
in my space shuttle I have parked out back and I'll tell you why
Addie Joss was No. 99 and a better pitcher than Pedro Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
