<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, June 26, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A heat wave will begin to build from the central Plains to New
England as sultry air streams northeastward on balmy breezes.
Clouds and thundershowers will continue to dominate the South. A
push of chilly air from the Pacific will spread farther inland
across the Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   High pressure will strengthen over the western Atlantic, and its
broad circulation will draw tropical air into the eastern half of
the nation. A corridor of sunny skies stretching from the Northeast
across the Great Lakes and into the western Plains will promote
temperatures above 90 degrees. Relative to seasonal levels,
northern New England should be the warmest.
</P>
<P>
   One disturbance will drift off the South Carolina coast while
another area of disturbed weather organizes over the western Gulf
Coast. Clouds will be abundant in the Southeast and the western
part of the lower Mississippi Valley. Weak winds, as light as 10
miles an hour, will be noted to 40,000 feet over the Deep South.
This will contribute to sluggish storms that may produce flash
flooding.
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of thunderstorms will drench south central Canada, and
a few will develop in the Dakotas and northern Minnesota as low
pressure treks eastward. The boundary with cooler air over the
northern Rockies will become active with a few storms in the
northwest Plains and eastern Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   The clouds over the Pacific Northwest will dissipate inland, but
onshore breezes will keep it dull and rather cool near the Coast.
High pressure near Oregon will turn the winds offshore in
California Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Rope Tornado
</P>
<P>
   A tornado in the form of a rope was spotted near Amarillo,
Texas, on Thursday. Such a ``rope tornado,'' which extends to the
ground from the base of the parent thunderstorm, is a visual clue
that the tornado is in its decaying stage. Indeed, as the parent
thunderstorm pulls away, the tornado is stretched into a funnel
that resembles a rope. Eventually, however, the tornado is
streched into oblivion. Though the rope stage of a tornado heralds
its imminent demise, the tornado can still be dangerous. After the
tornado dies, the parent thunderstorm may spawn another twister.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
