<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISGRUNTLED CONSERVATIVES FORM NEW SOUTHERN PARTY 
 HELPING SOUTHERN FARMERS  
 GOP ATTORNEYS GENERAL UNITE  
 CONSERVING THE REEFS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: The South)  (mk) 
 By CARL HULSE and SEAN LOUGHLIN   
 NYT Regional Newspapers   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The South will rise again.
</P>
<P>
   That, anyway, is the goal of a group of conservative activists
who are calling for a sovereign Southern nation and have formed a
new political party to promote the interests of the South.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're tired of the federal government telling us our heritage
is wrong, our beliefs are wrong,'' said Jerry Baxley, Virginia
state chairman for the new Southern Party. Their goal is to
organize as a formal political party in the 11 states of the old
Confederacy along with Kentucky, Maryland, Missouri, Oklahoma and
West Virginia. As they build political power, they plan to run
candidates for office and eventually push for secession.
</P>
<P>
   This action comes even though most of the top GOP leadership
posts on Capitol Hill are occupied by Southern lawmakers. The
president is also a son of the South as are the two leading
contenders to succeed him.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Southern Party officers contend that political leaders sell
out their home state and regional interests to appease a national
audience in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``The GOP loves Southern votes but hates to promote the social,
economic and cultural issues that matter to Southerners,'' said
George Kalas, chairman of the Southern National Committee. He
compared the South to Canada's Quebec, where many in the
French-speaking province believe their culture is threatened.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the party's organizers are former Republicans who have
grown disgusted with what they see as the GOP's waffling on issues,
whether it's fighting gun control, promoting school prayer or
restricting immigration. The group will formally launch the party
with a North Carolina rally in August.
</P>
<P>
   Earle Black, an expert on Southern politics at Rice University
in Texas, said it's difficult for any third party to get off the
ground, and he questioned whether there is much support for a
conservative, regional party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't see any future for this particular
enterprise,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cultivating Support
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to cut costs for Southern farmers, several lawmakers have
banded together to reform the federal crop insurance program.
</P>
<P>
   The Crop Insurance Equalization Act would establish discount
premiums for some farmers, increase coverage for fruits and
vegetables, allow cooperatives to sell crop insurance, limit
profits for insurance companies, stiffen penalties for fraudulent
claims and enact other changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Farmers need a forward-looking, more permanent solution to the
weather and pricing crises they can't control,'' said Rep. Saxby
Chambliss, R-Ga., a member of the House Agriculture Committee.
``This bipartisan bill moves us one step closer to providing a
workable risk management system.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Marion Berry, D-Ark., said many farmers feel the system
today is inefficient. ``Crop insurance isn't the answer to our
agriculture crisis, but it must be fair to Southern farmers,''
Berry said.
</P>
<P>
   Hot Seats?
</P>
<P>
   Watch for elections for state attorneys general to become key
battlegrounds between Democrats and Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   With Republicans in Congress trying to shift more power to the
states and curb the size and scope of the federal government, party
analysts realize that state offices may hold even greater power in
the years ahead.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, Republican attorneys general have formed
their own political group, the Republican Attorneys General
Association, to raise money and promote candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think competition serves the public well,'' said Alabama
Attorney General Bill Pryor, who serves as treasurer of the new
group. The chairman of the new group is Charlie Condon, attorney
general in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Pryor dismissed the notion that this new partisan effort would
somehow cheapen the office of attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vast majority of us are elected to public office and
therefore we go through a process that is the essence of
politics,'' Pryor said.
</P>
<P>
   Reef Madness
</P>
<P>
   Coral reefs struggling to survive off the Florida Keys and the
maritime border of Texas and Louisiana would get some relief from a
proposal advancing in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The new measure would authorize up to $100 million in reef
conservation programs over the next five years to halt the
degradation of the fragile resources. ``Environmental studies
indicate our nation's reefs continue to be threatened by pollution,
overfishing and severe climate changes,'' said Sen. John Breaux,
D-La., a backer of the measure.
</P>
<P>
   There's a bonus in the bill for Breaux and other reef
protectors: The measure allocates up to $15 million for research
grants. In Louisiana, the Louisiana Universities Marine Consortium
is engaged in the type of reef research the bill would promote.
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse and Sean Loughlin write from the Washington bureau
of the New York Times Regional Newspaper Group)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-99 1737EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
