<DOCNO> NYT19990625.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9778 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRIESTS-SCHOOL26-COX     06-25 1884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIESTS-SCHOOL26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Within a stone's throw of centuries-old St. Peter's Square, four
seminarians from Atlanta prepare hearts and minds for the modern
priesthood
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ They are men in black lined up row by row, table by
table, in the refectory of the Pontifical North American College,
the Vatican's school for American priests. Overhead, a design in
muddy colors on the ceiling draws sarcastic comparisons to the
Sistine Chapel across St. Peter's Square.
</P>
<P>
   This is Sunday lunch, both the fanciest and the most relaxed
meal of the week. More than 40 priests are here on sabbatical for
continued studies, joining the 170 seminarians _ including four
from the Archdiocese of Atlanta _ who are candidates for the
priesthood. Some are entertaining guests from their parishes and
dioceses back in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   After a multicourse meal in the Italian tradition, they will
visit with their guests and friends, study, watch videos, or play
basketball in the courtyard of their 1950s-vintage tan brick
building. It is a welcome respite from long weekdays of study and
worship.
</P>
<P>
   They will spend up to five years here. And, at the end of their
studies, those among the seminarians who have stayed the course
will leave this place, officially set apart by God and the Catholic
Church for a life of devotion and celibacy.
</P>
<P>
   The seminary was begun in 1859 when the Americans, upstarts in
terms of world history, requested their own institution at the
Vatican. It came to be called the North American College, instead
of the College of the United States, because the Civil War was on
the horizon and Catholics were not sure which side would win. A
young man named William Poole from the Diocese of Savannah was in
its first class.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of other seminaries serve students back in the States.
This one is special because of its proximity to the seat of the
Catholic Church.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1997 book called ``The New Men,'' journalist Brian Murphy
traced a group of students through their first year at what he
calls the ``elite'' college.
</P>
<P>
   ``Using the past as a guide, the voices coming out of the North
American College will be heard as a force far stronger than their
numbers,'' he predicts. ``Some will rise _ perhaps reluctantly _ to
be bishops, archbishops and possibly even a cardinal,'' he adds.
``Others will be called to work on Vatican commissions, its
diplomatic corps, or study to become canon law experts. And even a
once-inconceivable scenario _ the election of an American pope by
the College of Cardinals _ could grow ever more plausible in their
lifetimes, considering the ever-expanding size and strength of the
Catholic Church in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an exceptional opportunity for young men to be exposed to
the universal church and the experiences of Rome,'' says the Rev.
David Talley, vocations director for the Archdiocese of Atlanta,
``and it's good for some of our men to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-one men are preparing for the priesthood in the
Archdiocese of Atlanta. Each has been carefully screened and
counseled to determine where he should study.
</P>
<P>
   Of the four Atlanta seminarians at the North American College,
Talley says, ``They're wonderful and they're very different and
they're very committed, all four of them. They will be, God
willing, wonderful priests for the church of Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   Name: Theodore ``Tad'' Book
</P>
<P>
   Age: 22
</P>
<P>
   Placement: First year
</P>
<P>
   The youngest and tallest _ at 6-foot-7 _ of Atlanta's
seminarians at the North American College, Tad Book says he felt a
call to the priesthood when he was walking home from a Boy Scout
meeting during his senior year at DeKalb County's Druid Hills High
School.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very sudden,'' he says. ``It was clear to me that this
was what I was called to do. I took a deep breath and swallowed the
lump in my throat. I thought, `If that's what God is calling me to
do, I have to do it.'''
</P>
<P>
   The next day he went to talk to a local priest, who told him,
``Go to college, study, meet some women, and if you still want to
do it, go to seminary.'' Book followed the priest's advice and got
a degree in computer science from Georgia Tech before enrolling in
the North American College.
</P>
<P>
   Book admits that a degree from Georgia Tech seems to be strange
training for the priesthood. ``But,'' he said, ``I've certainly
ended up fixing a lot of guys' computers.''
</P>
<P>
   Book grew up in two churches. His mother is United Methodist.
His father is Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   He says he realized even as a teenager that ``religion has to be
an important quest. I couldn't go through life saying I believed in
something and not really living it. And I couldn't conceive of a
world without God. With that out of the way, I had to decide what
religion I belonged to. ... When it came down to choosing a
denomination, it seemed to me the Catholic Church was the only
church that could claim to go all the way back to Christ's
disciples.''
</P>
<P>
   He says he has come to terms with the commitment to celibacy.
``It seems to me very appropriate to the priesthood, a way you can
give yourself over totally to God. ... But it's certainly not
something everyone is called to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Book was born after the Second Vatican Council, which reshaped
the Catholic Church. He senses that the church has now settled in
to what, at the time, was radical change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a good time for the church, a good time to be a
priest,'' he says. ``I think the next 40 years are going to be good
years.''
</P>
<P>
   As a first-year man, Book will stay in Rome this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Name: Dung Nguyen
</P>
<P>
   Age: 28
</P>
<P>
   Placement: Second year
</P>
<P>
   As a frightened little boy of 10 years of age, Dung Nguyen left
Vietnam in 1980 on a small boat with other refugees, including a
brother and a sister. Even then, he knew the risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``My chance of surviving was 1 percent,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The boat sank, and the children were rescued by a merchant ship.
</P>
<P>
   ``To this day, I think a lot about it,'' says Nguyen. ``The
merciful, saving hand of God was instantly there.''
</P>
<P>
   He had a much older brother who had left Vietnam at the fall of
Saigon in 1975 and who was living in the United States as part of a
religious order. His brother left his religious order to take care
of his younger siblings. ``He was mom and dad,'' Nguyen says.
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen's parents finally arrived in America in the early 1990s.
``Not seeing my parents for 13 or 14 years was very difficult,'' he
admits.
</P>
<P>
   He lived in a religious community while attending college in
Santa Fe, N.M., then spent some time with his parents in New
Orleans ``to rekindle family ties and understand family life more,
to decide whether religious life or family life was right for me.''
</P>
<P>
   After five years of family togetherness, he went to Rome last
year as a lay student at the Pontifical University of St. Thomas
Aquinas, commonly known as the Angelicum, ``to discern whether I
wanted this way of life.''
</P>
<P>
   He concluded that he does.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer he worked in Our Lady of Vietnam parish in
Riverdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``After what God has done for me, I want to respond with my
utmost, whole being,'' he says. ``That's serving the church and his
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen will be assigned to Sacred Heart parish in downtown
Atlanta for the summer break, beginning in July.
</P>
<P>
   Name: Luke Ballman
</P>
<P>
   Age: 33
</P>
<P>
   Placement: Third year
</P>
<P>
   Two decades passed between the time Luke Ballman first thought
of becoming a priest and the time he actually entered seminary.
</P>
<P>
   Raised in a ``blue-collar Catholic family'' in Dayton, Ohio, he
attended parochial school. He remembers that a priest once came to
talk to the boys and girls about religious vocations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was excited about it,'' says Ballman. ``I went home, and my
parents didn't make a big deal. I forgot about it for 10 or 12
years.''
</P>
<P>
   In his early 20s, Ballman had completed the University of
Dayton, was living in Atlanta and working for Andersen Consulting,
an international management and technology consulting firm, when he
began attending Bible study with a friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``That experience deepened my relationship with Jesus Christ in
a way that was very personal,'' he says. ``I fell in love. That's
the only way to put it.''
</P>
<P>
   Again he thought of becoming a priest. Again he put the thought
away.
</P>
<P>
   At the consulting firm, Ballman was moving up the career ladder.
</P>
<P>
   At his parish, the Cathedral of Christ the King, he was also
growing more involved.
</P>
<P>
   At about age 27, he once again considered the priesthood. This
time, he consulted with the vocations director of the archdiocese.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I would take it slow,'' he says, so he spent more
than a year contemplating his decision.
</P>
<P>
   Telling friends at the consulting firm that he would be
attending seminary offered a great opportunity for evangelism, he
says. ``Here I was, in a professional environment, discussing my
faith,'' he says. ``I couldn't help but talk about God.''
</P>
<P>
   Ballman attended seminary for a year at St. Vincent's in
Pennsylvania before beginning his work at the North American
College.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all as Christians called to follow Christ, yet I feel
called to live that out in a radical way,'' he says. ``I think many
people have lost meaning in life. I hope to allow God to give them
meaning through me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ballman will spend the summer working in St. Pius X parish in
Conyers.
</P>
<P>
   Name: Charles Byrd
</P>
<P>
   Age: 35
</P>
<P>
   Placement: Third year
</P>
<P>
   As a small boy in the pews of Southern Baptist churches in
Columbus and Newnan, Charles Byrd got his earliest training in
Christianity. He had built a successful career in advertising when
his life began to move in a drastically different direction.
</P>
<P>
   When asked what drew him to Catholicism, Byrd ponders the
question, then says, ``The ultimate answer is God.''
</P>
<P>
   He graduated from the Portfolio Center, an Atlanta advertising
school, and landed a job with the largest advertising agency in
Louisville, Ky., handling accounts such as Kentucky Fried Chicken
and Humana hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   In Louisville, he began ``walking toward Catholicism,'' he says.
``I ended up dating Catholic girls and having Catholic friends.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Vernon Robertson, who had an inner city ministry with
Louisville's poor, gave him an impressive example of the Catholic
clergy. Robertson was a convert to Catholicism from the Episcopal
Church.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew to love this man and appreciate his faith,'' says Byrd.
``Ultimately, my being here is because of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrd also looks to another example of the clergy, Jesus' New
Testament precursor, John the Baptist.
</P>
<P>
   ``St. John the Baptist says, `I must decrease so that he can
increase,''' Byrd says. ``I think that's the role of a priest, to
be a servant. If he has the grace and will to stay faithful to
that, wonderful things will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrd says he considered returning to Louisville as a priest, but
decided to come home to Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really have a great respect for the Catholic Church in
Georgia,'' he says. ``Those people are my people, even though I
didn't grow up Catholic.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrd has been assigned to St. Joseph's parish in Athens for the
summer, beginning in July.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
