<DOCNO> NYT19990625.0190 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9780 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HASBEEN27-COX     06-25 1398
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HASBEEN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rock's revolving door brings blasts from past
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, June 27.
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cheer up, all you struggling former mega-stars _ all you fallen
gods of rock _ alone and forsaken since fame waltzed its fickle
waltz out of your life.
</P>
<P>
   Your fortunes may be about to change. While no one was looking,
it's become happening to be a has-been.
</P>
<P>
   Popular imagination thrives on rags-to-riches sagas, but what it
really loves are
rags-to-riches-to-rags-to-rehab-then-back-to-riches (or, at least,
a semblance of sanity) sagas. The phenomenal success of cable music
network VH1's ``Behind the Music'' program testifies to this. Since
the show debuted in 1997, water coolers throughout the nation have
been the site of passionate discussions of ... David Cassidy? Leif
Garrett? Tony Orlando?
</P>
<P>
   ``People are responding to these stories at a moment when there
aren't a lot of compelling new rock stars,'' says Alan Light,
executive editor of Spin magazine. Its latest cover features Axl
Rose of Guns N' Roses, who hasn't released a new album in seven
years. ``There's a hunger for larger-than-life survivors, or
victims, outsize personas in rock 'n' roll.''
</P>
<P>
   Proposing that ``What the World Needs Now Is Axl,'' Spin offers
an oral history on Rose. The archetypal bad-boy rocker of the late
'80s has become a recluse _ rock's answer to Howard Hughes or Garbo
_ since his band fell apart in the early '90s. But with a new
version of Guns N' Roses about to complete an album, there's
intense curiosity about Rose. And, as Light notes, the band's 1987
debut, ``Appetite for Destruction,'' still ``bangs out sales of
8,000 copies a week, and it can't all be 30-year-olds who are
buying it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose will have lots of company. Tuesday, the original lineup of
the theatrical 1970s rock act Styx will release its first album of
all-new studio material in 16 years. ``Brave New World,'' on the
Raleigh label CMC, will likely get a boost from fan Adam Sandler's
new screen comedy, ``Big Daddy,'' which prominently features the
band's music. British rock act Def Leppard, its record sales
boosted by its own booze-sodden ``Behind the Music'' special, has
released ``Euphoria,'' its first album since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Summer's tour circuit is crowded with acts on the comeback
trail. Some are making a steep uphill trek, others cruising on a
surge in their fan base. Vanilla Ice, pop-metal acts Poison and
Great White (two of those so-called ``hair'' bands of the '80s),
hard-rock Dokken, Lynyrd Skynyrd, Journey and the Doobie Brothers
are all on the road.
</P>
<P>
   But the real sizzler is Cher, who performs Wednesday at Lakewood
Amphitheatre. The former TV star, who first enjoyed a singing
career in the 1960s alongside her former husband (and recently
deceased Republican congressman from California) Sonny Bono, is an
exemplary model of pop's Lazarus syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe'' (Warner Bros.), her double-platinum album and single
of the same name, has vaulted her into a steady spot in the Top 10
of Billboard's best-selling albums chart. It has given Cher her
highest profile since 1988, when she won an Oscar for
``Moonstruck.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, her career has wavered. She won more attention for
her rock star romances and tattooed buttocks, coped with a
debilitating bout of Epstein-Barr virus and came to terms with
daughter Chastity's coming-out as a lesbian.
</P>
<P>
   It was time for a savvy makeover.
</P>
<P>
   The title song, which pumps along to the insistent, dance-happy
throb of house music, is a scorned lover's defiant kiss-off: ``But
after all is said and done/ You're gonna be the lonely one.''
Nothing new there. What's unusual is the way Cher's British
producers, Mark Taylor and Brian Rawling, have processed her vocals
on the tune's intro. Cher sounds chilly, computerized, not like
Cher at all. As the story plays out, the vocalist's gender remains
ambiguous. The song has registered strongly with gay audiences:
``If we didn't exist, Cher would have to invent us,'' writes
columnist Michael Alevar in Southern Voice, a weekly newspaper
devoted to Atlanta's gay community.
</P>
<P>
   Reviews of earlier shows on Cher's tour suggest that she hasn't
lost her flair for the theatrical. ``The appeal of the 52-year-old
diva has never been strictly about her voice,'' wrote Randy Cordova
in the Arizona Republic, covering the singer's first concert date
in Phoenix. The critic described ``a stage set that looked like a
medieval cave'' and Cher's ``flowing garb that made her look like a
sorceress from some 1960s King Arthur epic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe'' is a long way from the oldies Cher made famous on
TV, tunes like ``Half Breed,'' ``Bang Bang'' and ``I Got You,
Babe.'' But it's very similar to the way other artists of her
generation have reinvented themselves as strong, sexy survivors.
Tina Turner was rediscovered by the British dance act Heaven 17,
joining them in 1982 for a hit version of the Temptations' ``Ball
of Confusion.'' Tom Jones, surely a male diva if there ever was
one, lit a flame with the kids in 1988 when he cut a remake of
Prince's ``Kiss'' with British techno-popsters the Art of Noise.
That Cher, who has enjoyed her share of cosmetic surgery, seems
preternaturally ageless, also fits. We like our rebounding pop
stars to bust loose as if they've been hermetically sealed _ as
long as they don't forget their dirty laundry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just making it in the music business, by its very nature,
lends itself to sacrifice and personal drama,'' says George Moll,
VH1's vice president of productions, who oversees ``Behind the
Music.'' ``It's a natural. And especially with the older artists,
if you're hearing the music and understand where that music is
coming from, it puts you in a place that's very comfortable. Or it
reminds you of a comfortable time in your life, usually a time when
you had no responsibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   One man who deeply appreciates those insights is Tom Lipsky,
president and CEO of CMC International, a label affiliated with
industry major BMG that has built an empire on acts considered so
washed up no one else would sign them. ``There's perpetual value in
some of these artists,'' says Lipsky, whose roster includes Deep
Purple, Eddie Money, former Moody Blues singer Justin Hayward,
Lynyrd Skynyrd and Styx. ``And there's a new generation that's an
amazing group of rock historians. Go to a Lynyrd Skynyrd or a Styx
show, and you'll always see two generations of fans, sometimes
three generations.''
</P>
<P>
   Lipsky, who launched CMC in 1992 with ``Two dollars in my
wallet, a roll of duct tape and some Crazy Glue ,'' works within
certain parameters. He's not selling zillions of CDs, but his most
popular acts _ Styx and Skynyrd _ can sell 500,000.
</P>
<P>
   Lipsky says he doesn't count on radio for support. Classic rock
stations focus on the old hits. So the bands tour constantly to
promote sales. By carefully working his niche, though, he's tapped
into a surprising cultural current.
</P>
<P>
   A few months after CMC released its first Skynyrd title in 1997,
``Behind the Music'' debuted its episode on the indefatigable
Southern rock act. And, boom.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never saw MTV kids at a Skynyrd show before,'' says Kevn
Kinney , the Athens rock vocalist whose band, Drivin N Cryin was
touring as opening act. ``People were saying, 'What are all these
kids doing here? It must be that VH1 thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Upcoming CMC projects include albums from Little Feat, Blue
Oyster Cult and .38 Special. ``It's not easy to compete with the
big pop machinery and the critics who say their time is past.''
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, Lipsky accompanied his daughter to elementary
school for a show-and-tell session. ``It was `What My Daddy Does
Day,' and I was nervous,'' he says, prepared to be met with
indifference by a classroom of Backstreet Boys and N'Sync fans.
Lipsky's line of work turned out to be cooler than he could have
imagined. One little boy, whose parents had taken him to a concert
at the local amphitheater, piped up. ``He said, `Man, I saw the
Moody Blues. They really rocked!'''
</P>
<P>
   Cher
</P>
<P>
   With Cyndi Lauper
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. Wednesday. Only $25.25 tickets left. Lakewood
Amphitheatre, 2002 Lakewood Way S.W.
</P>
<P>
   404-249-6400.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Dollar writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
