<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9781 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-ATLANTA27-COX     06-25 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ATLANTA27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New wave of music producers scoring success in city that
nurtured heavy-hitting careers of Dallas Austin and Jermaine Dupri
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, June 27.
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Atlanta is no one-hitmaker wonder. For about the past decade,
music producers Dallas Austin, Jermaine Dupri and Organized Noize
have made sure of that.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Austin. His work with pop trio TLC has helped make it
the best-selling female group in the country. Teen singer Monica,
whom he discovered, is so big she regularly makes magazine covers.
And the Grammy winner's audience is so wide she's doing both the
Nickelodeon kids' tour and the more mature Lilith Fair this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Dupri. On May 26, he received the American Society of
Composers, Authors &AMP; Publishers' (ASCAP) Rhythm and Soul Songwriter
of the Year award _ for the second time _ for work, including
Usher's ``You Make Me Wanna,'' Monica's ``The First Night'' and his
own rap single, ``Money Ain't a Thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, consider Rico Wade, Pat ``Sleepy'' Brown and Ray Murray
of Organized Noize. They have taken Southern, Atlanta-specific rap
nationwide with the Grammy-nominated duo Outkast (``Rosa Parks''),
Goodie Mob (``Black Ice'') and Cool Breeze (``Creatine''), East
Point's unofficial booster.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time, you couldn't come through this city trying to
do rap or R&AMP;B without running into Dallas, J.D. or Rico,'' says
Chris ``Tricky'' Stewart, owner of Atlanta's studio/label imprint
Red Zone Entertainment, and a new producer himself.
</P>
<P>
   But now there is a growing number of out-of-towners who have
taken the highway south and are heading up what seems like every
music chart but country.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some producers you should know:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tim &AMP; Bob:
</P>
<P>
   Radio is playing their tunes, but there's a good chance these
two don't hear them.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Kelley and Bob Robinson (from left), the creators of
Billboard magazine's No. 2 R&AMP;B single of 1998 (``They Don't Know''
by Jon B) and one of its Top 10 R&AMP;B producers of last year, say R&AMP;B
has become redundant and boring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, the quality of the music these days is like, `Ugh!'''
says Kelley, 28. ``Everything sounds like the hit that was
happening last week. It's like, come on, be creative, do something
new. Please!''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Kelley and Robinson borrow stylistically from old
twosomes such as Gamble &AMP; Huff (who produced the O'Jays and Teddy
Pendergrass) and more recent urban music teams such as Jam &AMP; Lewis
(Janet Jackson, Jordan Knight) and Antonio ``L.A.'' Reid and
Kenneth ``Babyface'' Edmonds (Whitney Houston, Boyz II Men).
</P>
<P>
   ``They play the music on real instruments, write memorable
lyrics, arrange it beautifully _ Tim and Bob do it all,'' says
Austin. He hired the Peoria, Ill., natives at his Buckhead studio
six years ago, where they worked on million-selling projects for
Boyz II Men, Monica and Atlanta R&AMP;B quartet 112.
</P>
<P>
   Now they're using a studio in their sprawling Alpharetta home to
craft songs for Will Smith, Toni Braxton's sister Tamar and Kevon
Edmonds, Babyface's brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've broken in,'' says Robinson, 27, ``and now we're ready to
break R&AMP;B out of its slumber.''
</P>
<P>
   She'kspere:
</P>
<P>
   His name is familiar.
</P>
<P>
   It's just the spelling that throws people off.
</P>
<P>
   You've probably heard ``Bills, Bills, Bills'' by Destiny's Child
or the remix of Sam Salter's ``After 12, Before 6,'' songs for
which this 27-year-old California native (above) did the music.
</P>
<P>
   ``But his isn't the big `Puffy,' `R. Kelly' kind of name in the
industry,'' LaFace co-president Antonio ``L.A.'' Reid says.
``Yet!''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin ``She'kspere'' (pronounced Shakespeare) Briggs is slowly
and melodically establishing himself in the city he moved to only
18 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Since Briggs' first record, TLC's ``No Scrubs,'' hit No. 1 on
pop and R&AMP;B charts, ``people are calling for singles, not album
filler,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Among the artists with whom he's scheduled to work are pop
quintet 'N Sync, Grammy-winning vocalist Toni Braxton and Kandi
Burruss of Atlanta R&AMP;B quartet Xscape, his writing partner. She's
got a deal for a solo album.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think of She'kspere as one of the really big future
producers,'' Reid says. ``Because he understands the whole picture.
He understands the beat, the music. But there's also the importance
of melody and lyrical content ... and getting a good performance
out of an artist.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that is to say he is a well-studied producer, like guys
from the old days,'' Reid says. ``Not just a beatmaker.
She'kspere's a Renaissance man with a bright future.''
</P>
<P>
   Noontime:
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the name of the full-service record company for which
they work.
</P>
<P>
   The downtown Atlanta studio/
</P>
<P>
   label/management/publisher in which Teddy Bishop, Bryan Cox and
Jazze Pha (below, from left) record is a 24-hour operation.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop, 28, checks in during the daylight hours, lights incense
and lays down the track that could possibly top his breakthrough
hit, Montell Jordan's ``Let's Ride.''
</P>
<P>
   On this particular afternoon, the former Detroit resident is
working with Toni Braxton. Teen R&AMP;B singer Aaliyah was here days
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   When evening comes, Pha (Phalon Alexander) arrives in his black
Range Rover. Pioneering rap artists such as Slick Rick or Too Short
ease in shortly after. Or it could be a night the 25-year-old from
Memphis works on his own project.
</P>
<P>
   Cox is doing double duty at Noontime's studio as well as
alongside Jermaine Dupri, with whom he's produced songs for local
R&AMP;B quartet Jagged Edge and remixed part-time Atlantan Elton John's
``The Muse.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got a regular one-stop hit factory,'' producer Sean
``Puffy'' Combs says of Noontime, headed by Ryan Glover, Henry J.
Lee II and Christopher Hicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the great thing,'' Bishop adds, ``is artists aren't coming
here to work with us to get an `Atlanta sound,' so to speak. They
just know there's people in Atlanta with songs that hit big across
the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Sonia Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
