<DOCNO> NYT19990625.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9782 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR-STEWART-NY     06-25 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-STEWART-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEWART FEELS MORE AT HOME IN STOCK CARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LOWELL COHN   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO, Calif. _ Tony Stewart was wearing a Home Depot
shirt. It was stylish as Home Depot shirts go. Tony Stewart is
clean-shaven and mild-mannered, and if you didn't know he's the
hottest rookie in Winston Cup you'd think he works at Home Depot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excuse me, sonny. Which is the aisle for ceiling fans?''
</P>
<P>
   But Stewart doesn't work AT Home Depot. He's sponsored BY Home
Depot, in the Home Depot Pontiac Grand Prix, to be precise. Already
people are comparing him to Jeff Gordon _ in the sense that he's a
prodigy, in the sense that he knows instinctively what most drivers
never learn, and mostly in the sense that he's in sixth place in
the Winston Cup standings, two points behind Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   At Thursday's press luncheon for the Save Mart/Kragen 350,
someone asked Stewart if he sees himself as a rival to Gordon.
Stewart blinked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rival to me is a cold word,'' he said. ``There are more guys
to race other than Jeff Gordon every week.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that Stewart had gotten through the obligatory politeness,
he had this to add. ``I think a lot of fans are looking for someone
new to come in and challenge Jeff. I can remember passing Jeff at
Darlington and I could see the crowd stand up and get excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Can we stop here a moment to examine that last statement?
</P>
<P>
   Stewart was driving something like 3 million mph. He'd just
passed Gordon. And he had enough poise to look away from the track,
which must have been unfolding as fast as one of those race-car
videogames. And then he was able to observe the crowd. And not only
that, he could gauge its excitement.
</P>
<P>
   Well, if that's the case, then the mild-mannered Tony Stewart
must be Clark Kent to a Superman who exists only on race Sunday.
Someone in a position of authority should immediately investigate
this possibility.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of Stewart, 28, being a mere rookie is slightly
misleading in the first place. He started racing at age 5 when his
dad bought him what Stewart calls a yard cart. The tiny Stewart
immediately began tearing around the back yard of their Indiana
home. He also tore up the back yard.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually his dad got him a real go-cart, as much to save the
back yard as to please his son. And there was Stewart racing like a
madman _ make that a madkid _ at age 8. Stewart took to racing the
way other kids take to baseball or soccer. When he was in high
school he would sometimes call in sick on a Friday. Actually, he
would be in another state racing his go-cart. No big deal. His
teachers already knew the score. They'd even give him homework to
do on the road.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, he was the Indy Racing League champion. He sat on the
pole at his first Indianapolis 500 and he's the only driver to win
three USAC major division championships in one year. Oh, by the
way, he drives for Joe Gibbs, who used to win Super Bowls with the
Washington Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   Not your garden-variety rookie.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the matter of what he did on May 30. He
competed in the Indianapolis 500, finishing ninth, then raced in
the Coca-Cola 600 in Charlotte, N.C., and finished fourth. But that
summary doesn't begin to describe Stewart's day, which was
something like dining at two all-you-can-eat restaurants in
succession without once getting sick to your stomach.
</P>
<P>
   When he was done with the 500 at about 2:30, he jumped into a
helicopter that flew him from the track to the airport. There he
boarded the Home Depot jet where he changed uniforms. He flew to
Charlotte and was whisked from the airport to the track in Rusty
Wallace's private helicopter. And, hey, doesn't everyone own a
private copter?
</P>
<P>
   He arrived at the track during driver introductions, 10 minutes
before the race. When the race started, he was struck forcibly in
the puss by the difference between an Indy car and a stock car.
``It was like going from a Porsche to a school bus,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Stewart prefers school buses, although the Home
Depot Pontiac is orange instead of school-bus yellow. Why does he
like NASCAR more than Indy? For starters, Winston Cup has more
races than IRL. Also, in IRL he burned out a lot of engines and
that burned him up.
</P>
<P>
   ``You crash more than burn engines in this series,'' he said by
way of praise for Winston Cup. ``Blowing engines is hard to
digest.''
</P>
<P>
   May we please stop once more to dissect Stewart's words? If we
understand him correctly, he's saying it's better to crash than to
bust an engine. Say what?
</P>
<P>
   ``And why are you racing NASCAR, dear?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst thing that can happen is you can crash. I find that
reassuring.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course.
</P>
<P>
   Another thing Stewart likes about NASCAR is the car itself. Indy
cars are low to the ground and all that air rushes and hits his
head. In a stock car Stewart finds that his noodle's protected from
the breeze. Instead, he has an air conditioner which he often
adjusts by taking his hands off the steering wheel.
</P>
<P>
   Is this guy calm or what?
</P>
<P>
   He also can stretch in a stock car, but feels confined in an
Indy car. He didn't say whether he listens to the Rolling Stones on
the Home Depot Pontiac's radio. One assumes he does.
</P>
<P>
   Sears Point is the first road race of Stewart's Winston Cup
career, and to prepare for it he attended an intense one-day course
at Russell Racing School just before the California 500. He did
well except when he crashed the school's car into a fence and
busted a radiator and a few other things. None of that fazed him _
remember, this is the guy who likes crashing.
</P>
<P>
   The bill for damages came to a measly 800 bucks. He put the tab
on Gibbs' credit card and promptly forgot all about it, until Gibbs
called for an explanation. Stewart said he was more comfortable
with Gibbs paying instead of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm far from being a millionaire,'' Stewart said Thursday.
``But I do want to achieve that goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Me, too.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat of Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
