<HEADER>
A9787 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KEFAUVER-RECALLED-$AD     06-25 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEFAUVER-RECALLED-$ADV27-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICS LED TO MOB CRACKDOWN IN SMALL NEW YORK TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 27)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRED LeBRUN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ America in 1950 was blooming with optimism, full
of itself. We had just saved the world, survived the Great
Depression, and postwar opportunities seemed limitless.
</P>
<P>
   Opportunities, to paraphrase the well-known Tammany Hall saying,
when seen are to be took. It was a maxim some had secretly followed
for years.
</P>
<P>
   So it was that a surprisingly innocent America was shocked to
discover that there was organized crime rampant in this country.
City after city was revealed to have entrenched gambling interests
linked to gangsters, aided and abetted by corrupt police and
compromised politicians. The vehicle for this revelation was the
Kefauver Crime Investigation Committee, a select group of U.S.
senators headed by Tennessee Democrat Estes Kefauver, who beginning
in 1950 called up 600 witnesses in 14 cities and blew the lid off
corruption in every one.
</P>
<P>
   Kefauver even managed to clean up cities where hearings were not
held _ including small ones, like the ``sin city,'' Saratoga
Springs.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the hearings nor attendant television cameras ever made
it to the upstate New York community. Instead, witnesses were
called down to Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Kefauver closed up shop after sensational testimony
in New York City in the middle of March 1951, he had managed to
deeply embarrass New York's Republican governor, and the
world-renowned casinos at Saratoga Lake that had waxed and waned
for more than a century soon would be closed, putting an end to
casino gambling in Saratoga Springs.
</P>
<P>
   The Kefauver hearings captivated the country. People took off
work to watch them on television. While these were the fifth Senate
hearings ever to be televised, they were the first to draw huge
numbers of viewers, an estimated 20 million to 30 million. The
impact was enormous.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing his trademark coonskin cap, Kefauver made a serious run
for the 1952 and 1956 presidential nominations largely based on the
celebrity garnered from these hearings. The hearings also gave many
Americans their first view of real, live gangsters in Frank
Costello and Joe Adonis, although in Costello's case, only his
hands were shown. It was a theatrical touch that made the No. 1
syndicate boss all the more compelling a TV character. As the
result of Kefauver's committee, FBI Director J. Edgar Hoover sprang
out of deep denial that organized crime and racketeering existed,
which in turn radically changed law enforcement in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Closer to home and for better or worse, Kefauver's sincere
grandstanding _ followed by zealous New York Gov. Thomas E. Dewey's
attempts to outdo Kefauver _ utterly destroyed the gambling and
summer high-life culture that had abounded in Saratoga Springs and
along Saratoga Lake for a century. Dewey hastily assembled a state
crime commission two weeks after the Kefauver hearings closed to
``look into'' gambling in Saratoga. Then the governor impaneled a
special grand jury in Ballston Spa, whose rumblings lasted five
years and touched many lives.
</P>
<P>
   Dewey's investigation and grand jury came down on the Saratoga
gambling culture with a vengeance. Dewey had been stung by
Kefauver. The governor consequently vented his fury on both the
corrupt and the respectable citizenry who accepted gambling as the
status quo and accommodated it. When Dewey's grand jury was in full
swing, a bartender in Saratoga Springs moaned that his town was in
a sorry way. Everyone he knew had either been indicted or was under
subpoena to testify.
</P>
<P>
   Many to this day believe Saratoga Springs suffered the brunt of
Kefauver's inquiry because the senator from Tennessee needed to
solve a growing political problem.
</P>
<P>
   In city after city he showed pols on the take and cops turning a
blind eye while gambling interests thrived. Most of these cities,
however, tended to be Democratic bastions, and the corruption he
was exposing had intimate ties to his side of the aisle. He was
poking the stick in his own eye, which came back to cripple
Kefauver when the chips were down in the back rooms of the '52 and
'56 Democratic conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating this, Kefauver needed a good Republican city to
skewer, or at least one in a Republican state. New York was just
the ticket. Although Saratoga Springs was a bipartisan sin city,
there was no more prominent Republican in the country than Dewey.
The delicious irony was that Dewey lost the presidency in '48 by a
whisker, also trying to ride the crime-buster hobbyhorse into the
White House. But where Dewey had been a hard-nosed district
attorney seeking out corruption in New York City, as governor he
took more of a live-and-let-live approach to upstate gambling.
</P>
<P>
   In 1953, Meyer Lansky, the brains of the Mob, went to jail in
Ballston Spa for three months after being indicted by the Dewey
grand jury. It was the first time Lansky was ever imprisoned. He
had this to say about it all later:
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knew there was gambling up there. The place was full
of casinos. I had investments in the Arrowhead Inn and in the
Piping Rock, too. I'm sure the reason why the cops in Saratoga
suddenly took action was that Governor Dewey ordered an
investigation because of the Kefauver Report.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just bad timing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
