<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-$ADV28-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE QUEEN'S FIRST RESTAURANT MEAL
</HEADLINE>
  
 Advance for editions of June 28 or thereafter  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Queen Elizabeth &LR;  dined in a public restaurant last week, the
first such meal in her reign of almost 50 years. The Queen,
 &UR; Prince Philip  &LR; and  &UR; Prince Charles  &LR; ate at the Compleat Angler in
Marlow, as guests of Hungarian President  &UR; Arpad Goncz &LR;  and his
wife.
</P>
<P>
   The Mirror of London reported that no other guests were allowed
in the restaurant, and security personnel dived into the lake at
the end of the restaurant's garden to make sure no monster was
lurking. Restaurant staff were subject to security checks, and dogs
were employed to check out a church across the road. The meal
proceeded without incident.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PATTON'S DOCUMENT SOUVENIRS TO BE SHOWN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, administrators of the Skirball Cultural Center
Museum, which focuses on Judaic artifacts from all over the worlds,
announce  &LR; Monday  &LR; that they plan to create a permanent exhibit for
an original copy of the Nuremberg Laws and a ``Mein Kampf''
presented at the end of the war to General
 &UR; George Patton &LR; , who donated the material to the Huntington Library.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the documents, which bear wax seals of the Third
Reich, is a June 1945 letter from Patton explaining that the
documents had been discovered in a vault by the Third Army, when
they entered the city of Nuremberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``These soldiers of the 90th Division were very fond of me, and
I was very fond of them. They thought they would like to do
something for me, so they sent for me, and we had a great public
presentation. ... So it is my property.''
</P>
<P>
   As to the copy of ``Mein Kampf,'' Patton said it was alleged to
have been one of 100 copies of the unexpurgated text. ``It was
published by a man named  &UR; Emman &LR; . He is the No. 3 bad man in
Germany. I have him in jail now. We'll stretch him pretty quick!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEY LIKE TO WATCH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Preparing for the millennium, Daystar International Ministry, an
evangelical Christian group based in Richmond, Va., and Hereford,
England, has announced its intentions to set up www.messiahcam.org.
This site will enable computer-users to watch, live, for the coming
of the messiah at the Eastern Gate of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a multimedia ministry,'' Daystar's  &UR; Christine Darg &LR;  told
the Wall Street Journal. ``Webcams are popping up like mushrooms
all over the world. This seemed like the obvious thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ If she could sing a duet with anyone, More magazine asked
 &UR; Florence Henderson &LR; , who would it be? ``Since I love singing the
old church liturgy,'' she said, ``I'd really love to do a duet with
the  &UR; Pope &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Lloyd Chiswick &LR;  forwards a recent San Francisco Chronicle
television insert that included a description of ``Dead on Time,''
an Inspector Morse episode about the murder of a man ``who happened
to be a mob leader.'' That is, he was an ``Oxford don,'' translated
for an American audience.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Yogi Berra &LR;  turned up at the Metropolitan Museum of Art in
New York last week to celebrate the opening of an exhibit of
baseball cards honoring  &UR; Joe DiMaggio &LR; . The exhibit, which included
seven DiMaggio cards, also included cards for Berra,
 &UR; Billy Martin &LR; ,  &UR; Phil Rizzuto &LR;  and  &UR; Mickey Mantle &LR; , his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   On his way out of the museum, when Berra was asked who his
favorite painter is, he said, ``I don't know the painters. I look
at the picture. If I like it, I like it. Then I ask who the painter
is.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE COMMUTER'S EAR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sarah Fallon &LR; , riding the 5 Fulton bus, overheard the following
only-in-San Francisco or only-in-Bali conversation, which she took
down verbatim:
</P>
<P>
   Person 1: I have repetitive stress syndrome from playing an
instrument.''
</P>
<P>
   Person 2: ``Which one?''
</P>
<P>
   Person 1: ``Balinese Gamelan.''
</P>
<P>
   Person 2: (Without a hunt of surprise) ``Oh, really? I play
that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Despite the elevated cultural level evidenced by the
conversation above,  &UR; Caroline Louise Dignan  &LR; says the window of
Cover to Cover on 24th Street in San Francisco shows ``The staff's
pick for Muni riders: `Les Miserables.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``The adult world is full of tension. Regain the child within.
Pull a colleague's hair.''
</P>
<P>
   _ From ``The Little Book of Chaos'' by Craig Brown (Riverhead;
$7.95).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
