<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NISSAN-SHAREHOLDERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NISSAN SHAREHOLDERS' MEETING TAKES ON SOME WESTERN TRAPPINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Nissan Motor Co. permitted outside news coverage of its
annual shareholder meeting Friday for the first time, a sign that
even the most traditional Japanese businesses are moving toward the
greater disclosure and openness expected by foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the brief choreographed agendas that have been
customary at Japanese companies' annual meetings, the Nissan event
ran 2 hours and 25 minutes. It also featured some other
characteristics of Western annual meetings _ a slick video
presentation and an outraged shareholder, who in this case demanded
the resignation of the troubled company's president, Yoshikazu
Hanawa.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've made mistake after mistake in your management
decisions,'' scolded the shareholder, who identified himself only
as Mr. Tamura but could easily have been mistaken for the Japanese
version of an American shareholder gadfly like Evelyn Y. Davis or
John Gilbert.
</P>
<P>
   Hanawa is not the only Japanese executive now facing this kind
of scrutiny. Other Japanese companies are beginning to conduct
annual shareholder meetings of the kind held in the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know the investor base is shifting for them from the more
comfortable relationships they've had with banks and affiliates
that have traditionally been their shareholders to more active
types of investors like foreigners,'' said Craig Chudler, a
strategist at Nikko Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   The overwhelming practice for most companies is still to hold
their annual shareholders' meetings on the same day of the year,
forcing an investor who holds stock in two or more of them to pick
one, and to bar the press from attending.
</P>
<P>
   The Nikkei Shimbun, Japan's version of The Wall Street Journal,
puts the number of listed companies holding their shareholders'
meetings next Tuesday at 1,374, or 88 percent of the total. Nissan
was one of 109 listed companies that held their meetings Friday,
the paper said.
</P>
<P>
   The Nissan meeting was its first since the company signed a deal
with France's Renault SA in March that will combine some operations
of the two automakers and strengthen Nissan's debt-heavy balance
sheet.
</P>
<P>
   The executive that Nissan's shareholders had really wanted to
see Friday was Carlos Ghosn, the former Renault executive who
Friday became Nissan's first ever chief operating officer,
effectively putting him in charge of day-to-day operations.
</P>
<P>
   Two shareholders who spoke Friday expressed a vague concern that
Renault's purchase of a 36.8 percent stake in Nissan was the first
step toward a takeover, and Tamura, the outraged shareholder, noted
a recent interview in which Takashi Ishihara, a former chairman of
Nissan, described Renault as a second-rate car company. ``Don't you
feel sorry for Ghosn when people are saying such things?'' he asked
Hanawa, pressing the president to explain why a potential deal with
DaimlerChrysler AG had fallen apart.
</P>
<P>
   Ghosn, who was appointed to his new position during a board
meeting Friday, gave a brief speech in Japanese that was an effort
to assuage some fears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to emphasize to you that I have come to Japan not
for the good of Renault but for the good of Nissan,'' he told
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-99 1758EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990625.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9808 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABOUT-CARS-MERCEDES-A     06-25 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-MERCEDES-ART-2TAKES-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEXT BIG THING 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 27)  
 (af)  
 By JAMES G. COBB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Huge, heavy and haughty, bristling with technology under its
slab-sided styling, the Mercedes-Benz S-Class has been a global
symbol of power and success for princes and prime ministers,
generals and godfathers, capitalists who have conquered markets and
revolutionaries who have come to power.
</P>
<P>
   Reinventing such a car wouldn't be easy even without the
pressures on the product planners at Mercedes-Benz. They had to
lighten up one of the most overengineered, overbuilt vehicles on
the planet.
</P>
<P>
   They had to make it sleeker and more contemporary, yet retain
the family look and timeless quality of a big Mercedes. They needed
to showcase Mercedes' engineering prowess, but in a car that would
be less expensive and more competitive _ the keys to the company's
resurgence the last couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a car that is shorter, lower and narrower, yet
more spacious in the dimensions that count. Though 500 pounds
lighter, it rides as smoothly as any car on the market and promises
unparalleled crash protection. To the driver it is creamy, seamless
and capable of feats one would hardly expect of a 4,000-pound
luxury car.
</P>
<P>
   It also has the latest electronic gadgets. There is an optional
voice-activated phone and a Teleaid connection that calls up
technical or emergency aid from a live person, in the vein of
General Motors' Onstar.
</P>
<P>
   So the car talks to you and you can talk to it. It knows where
you are and how to get home. It cools or heats your backside, with
or without a massage. It compensates for dumkopf drivers by taking
over the braking in an emergency or halting a skid in midstream. It
won't cook your breakfast, but it can find a pancake house.
</P>
<P>
   If it knows your height it will adjust the surroundings to fit
you. There is memory for an array of preferences, including all
three mirrors. Next year, with the arrival of a smart cruise
control, the car will maintain a preset distance behind another
vehicle. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The S-Class is now slightly wedge-shaped, lower and sleeker than
before. Up front, the classic grille sweeps back, framed by
stylized headlamps that are not quite oval, not quite triangular,
not quite rectanglar.
</P>
<P>
   The rear is jaunty and purposeful with wraparound taillamps in
the style of the SLK roadster's. The brake lights consist of
light-emitting diodes instead of bulbs; they illuminate 15
milliseconds faster, giving tailgaters 16 extra feet of warning at
62 mph.
</P>
<P>
   More LEDs show up in side marker lights on the outside mirrors,
which display the turn signals to cyclists and pedestrians
alongside the car. Xenon gas headlamps are standard on the S500,
optional on the less expensive S430, and they provide marvelous
illumination _ though some oncoming drivers clearly find them
irritating.
</P>
<P>
   The six-cylinder S-Class is gone from America, but there are two
V8s: the S430 has a 275-horsepower, 4.3-liter power plant and the
S500 has a 5-liter, 302-horsepower unit. A V12-powered S600 will
arrive as a 2001 model, but the 5-liter is so smooth, so exuberant,
so overqualified for any North American road that a bigger engine
can only be an extravagance.
</P>
<P>
   The five-speed automatic has summer and winter modes and a
Sportshift control with just one forward position. When the shift
lever is in ``D,'' the driver taps the lever left or right for
gears 1 through 4.
</P>
<P>
   On two test cars, this shifter added a measure of control on
several jaunts through New York's mountains. Along with an adaptive
damping control that really works _ its firm or soft settings
emphasize either crisp handling or a soft ride _ an air-spring
suspension lets you raise or lower the car by about an inch, handy
for navigating bad roads. The ride height automatically drops by a
half-inch at speeds over 85.
</P>
<P>
   The car is capable of brilliant handling, and like the BMW
7-Series it feels considerably smaller than it is. The steering has
just the right weight, the correct amount of power assist, to
inspire confidence in high-speed turns or low-speed parking.
</P>
<P>
   The brakes are computerized for your protection: In addition to
an anti-lock function they are programmed to recognize panic stops
and respond with full braking force. And they modulate the force
among the wheels to prevent lockup.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, the S-Class has Mercedes' Electronic Stability
Program, which made its debut on the S-Class in 1996. The system
continuously calculates whether the S-Class is going where the
driver is steering it; if it senses a skid, it selectively applies
the brakes to keep the car on track.
</P>
<P>
   Let's go for a ride. Since it's a hot day, aim the key at one of
the front door handles and hold down the unlock button. The doors
unlock, the windows roll down and the sunroof retracts. Don't slam
the doors or the trunk; they finish closing automatically. As you
start the engine, the ventilated seats are already working, their
10 electric fans blowing air through the cushion and backrest.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Adjust the seat to get the proper leg room. If you push the
button marked ``E'' (for ergonomic) among the memory controls on
the door, various of the seat's 14 adjustments will automatically
move to accommodate your height. Or you can use the seat controls
to adjust the depth of the bottom cushion or the height of the
headrests, which also expand out to form a pillow.
</P>
<P>
   An option is an active lumbar feature; seven air chambers in the
seat slowly expand and deflate to stimulate the spine. Given that
this takes place within ultrasoft perforated leather, one has the
sensation of lounging against a very plush sleeping cow.
</P>
<P>
   The spacious back seat can be had with adjustable outer
seatbacks. Or if you're a master of the universe who leaves the
driving to others, order the ``two seat'' rear package. There is a
center console and seats with all the adjustments available up
front. Control freaks can manipulate the front passenger seat from
the rear.
</P>
<P>
   The dashboard is a flowing ``wave'' design with burl walnut trim
(calyptus in the S430; chestnut is optional). The gauges are clear,
simple and bright, but the speedometer tempts you to play Autobahn
racer with ``80'' at the top of the dial.
</P>
<P>
   The steering wheel also controls a multifunction display amid
the gauges, which provides readouts of all sorts of information,
from trip computer to navigation, audio and telephone functions.
</P>
<P>
   The showcase of the car's electronic wizardry is the COMAND
screen in the dash. This unit _ officially called the Cockpit
Management and Data System _ controls the standard navigation
system and Bose stereo and the optional telephone and CD changer.
It is a lot to ask of a handful of buttons and toggles, and few are
likely to master the system quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The navigation system showed the usual benefits and deficiencies
of its breed _ occasionally odd directions, out-of-date restaurant
listings, controls that can be distracting while driving. But the
voice-activated cell phone was a nice touch. Using controls on the
steering wheel (the first from Mercedes) you can tell the car's
automated operator _ I called her Ernestine, for the Lily Tomlin
character _ to dial a number or create listings in an audible phone
book.
</P>
<P>
   Ernestine's digital voice was pleasant even when apologizing for
not recognizing a command (``Sorry,'' she would say. ``Cancel,
cancel.'') But after being told several times that ``that function
is not possible,'' I found I was raising my voice with her.
</P>
<P>
   At least she allows a driver to focus on the road. Not so the
audio controls. Instead of logical buttons and knobs, Mercedes has
come up with page upon page of on-screen menus. Simple tasks like
lowering the bass or rewinding a tape are maddening.
</P>
<P>
   And the selections are not instantly obvious: Quick, at 70 mph,
what is the difference between ``FM presets'' and ``Auto presets''?
</P>
<P>
   The S-Class also shows a few signs of cost-cutting _ this in
cars that start around $70,000 for the S430 and $80,000 for the
S500. Some plastic pieces _ the mirror housing, the storage
compartments under the front seats _ feel cheap. The cup holders in
front are small and inconvenient, and those in the rear would be
objectionable in a Hyundai.
</P>
<P>
   In some respects, driving the S500 is a little like piloting
your computer. If your VCR still flashes ``12:00,'' this may not be
a car for you. Or it might be _ nothing prevents you from turning
off the electronic noise and reveling in the hush of the cabin,
concentrating on the road. The S500 performs so flawlessly that it
rises above any gimmicks that fall short of perfection. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: The benchmark for a class of very classy cars. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-99 1801EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
