<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9813 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COOKBOOK-MODEL-ART-$A     06-25 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COOKBOOK-MODEL-ART-$ADV27-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(RESENDING TO INCLUDE PHOTO ADVISORY)  
 THE VERY MODEL OF A GOOD COOK 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, June 27) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ALEX WITCHEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Cooking with cleavage is not an everyday occurrence
in my kitchen. Neither is cooking in heels. But when a model is
involved, it seems, anything is possible.
</P>
<P>
   Padma Lakshmi has walked the runway for Giorgio Armani, Gianni
Versace and Ralph Lauren, and has appeared in Vogue, Elle,
Mirabella and Glamour. She has also just published a cookbook,
``Easy Exotic: A Model's Low-Fat Recipes From Around the World''
(Miramax, $25.95).
</P>
<P>
   When I first heard about the book, I laughed. A model who cooks
what? Ice soup? Preposterous. Forget all this blather about a
backlash to Kate Moss, and Calvin Klein shunning supermodels to
photograph real people. I read magazines like everyone else, and no
one in sight has a thigh like mine. But Ms. Lakshmi's book signals
a potential revolution: models not only as real people, but also as
Mama. No more skeletal adolescents fueled by Champagne bubbles, but
robust beauties who shop and cook _ albeit braless, in a tank top,
like Ms. Lakshmi, sporting three miles of leg.
</P>
<P>
   Though she grew up cooking with her grandmother in Madras,
India, Ms. Lakshmi became head chef in charge of homesickness for
her glamorous pals languishing on exotic locations. She cooked them
hearty pots of food, minus any ingredients that could compromise
their employment. She admits to having no formal training, but I
wanted to see how she did it, anyway. I was hoping some magic might
rub off. Eat a model's meal, lose 10 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   As we set out to shop and cook, I felt the tiniest bit smug.
Someone who looks like Ms. Lakshmi _ 5 foot 9, with a 24-inch
waist, no hips and 34C chest (on the days she does wear a bra) _
probably seems like a culinary genius to other models. But the
relaxed-fit crowd would see right through her.
</P>
<P>
   They certainly saw something. At my corner market, the
stockboys, the manager and the men who passed her on the street
gaped. While she was perfectly pleasant chatting with me, somehow,
when men appeared, she seemed to effervesce _ like an Alka-Seltzer
dropped into water. Which I could have used just watching it. All
rationalizations to the contrary, it was stunning to see such a raw
display of beauty as power, because that's what it was, pure and
simple. Well, not simple, certainly. And certainly not fair.
</P>
<P>
   So I did the most rotten thing I could think of to a model,
knowing she hadn't begun her career until after she graduated from
Clark University in Worcester, Mass., and that she had lived for
six years in Italy and also in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``How old are you?'' I asked. She crossed her arms and said
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to tell me, are you?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never,'' she answered, heading straight to the produce,
snapping off a sprig of cilantro and tasting it. She slipped it
into a bag and zoomed forward, sniffing and picking the way my
grandmother used to. At the register, she looked dismissively at
the head of garlic I had chosen, and replaced it with a container
of peeled cloves. ``So we don't have to smell of it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Out of nowhere, the manager appeared, nodding and smiling, and
credited the head of garlic. I must be in that store twice a week
and I've never seen him do anything but scowl.
</P>
<P>
   We walked back to my apartment, and Ms. Lakshmi talked about the
transition she is trying to make to an acting career. She recently
appeared in a television miniseries in Italy and shot a film that
will be released there in October. It helps that she speaks five
languages: Italian, Spanish, English, Hindi and Tamil, which she
says is spoken mainly by Sri Lankans.
</P>
<P>
   Back in my building, I thought the doorman would faint at the
sight of her. When I mentioned it, she just smiled. ``Would I have
it any other way?'' she asked. ``Come on. But it's up to me to keep
up my end of the bargain.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be diet. Ms. Lakshmi said she never starves herself _
it makes her cranky _ but when it comes to overeating, she will
look at food and say, ``I'm worth too much to put this into my
stomach.'' I nodded, but she might as well have said that part in
Tamil.
</P>
<P>
   In the kitchen, Ms. Lakshmi went straight to business, cutting
and chopping a minimal amount, because in this recipe, misleadingly
called coconut chicken (requiring one can of light coconut milk),
most ingredients for the sauce, including onion, garlic, ginger and
jalapeno, went into the blender.
</P>
<P>
   I offered her one of my aprons, which she tied around her waist
_ twice. Does she exercise every day? She shook her head and
chopped cilantro. ``No, I have a trainer, or I won't go to the gym
otherwise,'' she said. ``Cardio is the best thing for weight
loss.''
</P>
<P>
   She deserves credit for keeping a reasonably sane take on
herself in a business where eating disorders abound amid the
unforgiving scrutiny of something like a runway walk in a string
bikini. Ms. Lakshmi said she had recently broken her engagement to
an Italian man she called ``a food fascist,'' who would tell her
what to eat, how much and when. Since then she dated yet another
food fascist, she said, whose ``waist was smaller than mine.'' She
added: ``If you can't have fun with food, that's a symptom to a
bigger problem. It's one of nature's biggest pleasures, as basic as
breathing.''
</P>
<P>
   She hasn't always been deprived, however. ``Because of what I
look like I've been wined and dined everywhere,'' she said easily.
``I've had my share of Eurotrash older guys and they've taken me to
wonderful restaurants. I could taste what was in the food, and I
stole the recipes.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The kitchen was starting to smell delicious. The way she came to
write ``Easy Exotic,'' which is separated into sections from
countries where she has lived and worked, including Spain, France,
Italy, India and Morocco, was by cooking for some actors in Los
Angeles, where she moved six months ago to pursue her film career.
They mentioned the meal to Harvey Weinstein, the co-chairman of
Miramax Films, whom she later met at a movie premiere. She told him
it was her dream to write a cookbook _ and voila. He sent her to
Miramax Books. ``This is honestly the food I make for myself and
for my friends,'' models and civilians, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The current craze for eliminating carbohydrates doesn't interest
Ms. Lakshmi, though she advises eating them during the day. ``If
you want rice you can have a tennis-ball-size portion,'' she said.
``But don't expect to lose weight eating a mountain of rice.'' I
felt myself blush. I guess I've been inspired more by footballs.
</P>
<P>
   ``And at night,'' Ms. Lakshmi went on, ``you can have some fish
with steamed vegetables. That's fine.'' How did I know she was
going to say that? It's like hearing the same bedtime story with
the bad ending that never changes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the food in the pot, which according to the cookbook
has only 10 grams of fat a serving, was looking sensational. Ms.
Lakshmi basically followed the recipe, though she didn't measure
many ingredients, preferring, she said, to ``eyeball it.'' She
broke into a piece of steaming chicken breast with her bare fingers
and didn't flinch. ``Nice and tender,'' she said, leaving the pot
uncovered so the liquid would reduce.
</P>
<P>
   We sat at the dining room table, where I smoked and she drank
mineral water. She said that for all the talk about a model
backlash, she doesn't see one. ``I think it's the opposite,'' she
said. ``I was considered thin when I first started modeling, but
not anymore. These girls today start really young. They don't even
finish high school. Without an education, I may never have
appreciated the places I went to if I didn't understand where I was
going.''
</P>
<P>
   The chicken was done, and Ms. Lakshmi ate two servings, which
would equal one of mine. No rice.
</P>
<P>
   My husband appeared, bewitched by both the smells in the kitchen
and the woman in the low-cut dress who put them there. But alas, my
stepson arrived from his basketball game too late. Ms. Lakshmi had
gone. He held up the book with her picture on the cover. ``She was
here?'' he asked incredulously. His ardor only grew once he tasted
the food.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's who I'm going to marry,'' he declared, as his father
looked on approvingly. ``A hot girl who can cook Indian food.''
</P>
<P>
   I smiled weakly. Bring on the Alka-Seltzer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
