u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HORMEL-LUXEMBOURG-HNS     06-25 0477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HORMEL-LUXEMBOURG-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUXEMBOURG ENVOY HOLDS WELCOME DINNER FOR HORMEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Luxembourg's ambassador to the United States,
Arlette Conzemius, held an intimate, four-course dinner Thursday
night at her country's embassy here to welcome gay rights advocate
James C. Hormel to his new post as U.S. envoy to Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
   About 15 people attended the affair on Washington's Embassy Row,
including Hormel's longtime partner, Timothy Wu of San Francisco,
and Hormel's daughter, one of his five children, according to one
of the guests.
</P>
<P>
   Hormel, 66, a San Francisco philanthropist and heir to a
meatpacking fortune, will be sworn in at a State Department
ceremony Tuesday and will become America's first openly gay
ambassador. He received a recess appointment from President Clinton
on June 4 after more than 18 months of Senate battles over his
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   California's Democratic senators, Dianne Feinstein and Barbara
Boxer, attended the send-off dinner. Feinstein, who has been a
friend of Hormel for 30 years, was accompanied by her husband,
Richard Blum, a San Francisco investment banker.
</P>
<P>
   Other lawmakers at the dinner were Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif.,
and Sen. Gordon Smith, R-Ore., a member of the Foreign Relations
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Smith had called for lifting the so-called ``holds'' put on
Hormel's nomination in the Senate by four conservatives who
objected to his gay-rights advocacy. Smith argued against his
fellow Republicans, saying Hormel should be judged on his
qualifications alone.
</P>
<P>
   The four senators said they feared he would pursue a gay agenda
in the Luxembourg post. Hormel said he would not do that. But
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott _ who has linked homosexuality to
alcoholism, sex addiction and kleptomania _ refused to lift the
holds. Hormel was said to have had the support of at least 60 of
the Senate's 100 members.
</P>
<P>
   Others at the dinner were Peggi and Alfred Bloom. He is
president of Swarthmore College, a small liberal arts school south
of Philadelphia where Hormel, a onetime student, serves on the
board of managers.
</P>
<P>
   The meal included a cold green soup, salmon, duck and asparagus
and a molded desert of blackberries and raspberries. Conzemius also
served a white wine from Luxembourg, a red wine and champagne.
</P>
<P>
   Guests toasted Hormel throughout the evening. Finally the
ambassador-designate raised his glass and delivered a toast to each
person there.
</P>
<P>
   His final tribute went to Wu, who teaches members of nonprofit
organizations how to raise money. Hormel thanked Wu for standing by
him through the long battle over his nomination. Hormel has said Wu
will not live with him in Luxembourg. Hormel and his former wife,
Alice Turner, were divorced after 10 years of marriage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
