<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PRELUDES-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANG YOUR DRUM LOUDLY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 27) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y.)   (af)  
 By ABBY ELLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Young entrepreneurs know the rule: To get ahead, you have to be
noticed. And once you discover how, you have to make every one of
your 900 seconds of fame count.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to be seen,'' said Rosalie Osias, a lawyer based in
Great Neck, N.Y. ``You have to open up the windows of opportunity,
get the people in power to notice you, mentor you, hold your hand
and teach you how. You have to network and learn the game that's
being played. There's got to be something to make the older guys in
power want to bring you into the fold.''
</P>
<P>
   Hard work, she believes, is well and good, but not nearly
enough: Attention must be paid. And she knows what she's talking
about.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, to find clients in the banking industry _ ``the
last of the old-boy networks,'' as she says _ Ms. Osias, then 37,
ran a yearlong series of provocative advertisements in industry
magazines like Mortgage Press and Mortgage Report.
</P>
<P>
   The ads showed Ms. Osias in a tuxedo and black spiked heels,
golf club in hand. Or Ms. Osias in her finest cowgirl wear,
chomping on a cigar. Or Ms. Osias in a blouse and a short skirt,
lying on a conference table, with the caption: ``Does this law firm
have a reputation? You bet it does.''
</P>
<P>
   Her campaign generated national and international interest and
outraged some other lawyers. But she says the ads helped her
attract banking clients, for whom she closes real estate deals,
from around the country. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other entrepreneurs, like Justin Blair, who opened the Church
Street Gym, a health club in Manhattan, are brazen, too, but in
other ways. ``This isn't the kind of industry where you get an
internship and work your way up the corporate ladder,'' said Blair,
28. ``You need to really stand out.''
</P>
<P>
   He wanted professional boxers to train at his club, so he
created a secluded studio in a corner of his gym, complete with an
elevated boxing ring and various kinds of training equipment.
</P>
<P>
   But how could he get the attention of said athletes, who
probably hadn't heard of him?
</P>
<P>
   In January, Don King, the promoter, held a news conference at
Madison Square Garden to publicize a fight between the welterweight
champion, Felix Trinidad, and Pernell Whitaker. Blair knew that
Trinidad would be there, so he hurriedly put together packets of
information for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just snuck onto the side where Trinidad and his father were
sitting, gave him my info, and said, in broken Spanish, `This is my
place, we've got a private gym for you, and I think it's something
you can review,''' Blair said. ``I was trying to convince him that
I wasn't a freak. They were pretty cautious, but they wound up
coming down that day because they needed a place to work out. He
felt right at home, and we've been friends ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   Radical schmoozing helps, too.
</P>
<P>
   At the Trinidad-Whitaker fight, Blair persuaded the stranger in
the next seat to give him his floor access pass to ``work the
influential boxing crowd.'' He promptly disappeared into that crowd
for the rest of the evening, much to the stranger's chagrin.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came back he was fuming,'' Blair said, ``but I had to
do what I had to do.''
</P>
<P>
   To get to the heavyweight champion, Evander Holyfield, Blair
gave the information to Holyfield's chiropractor, whom he found in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many layers to that onion; you never know if they
get anything, you fax it out and cross your fingers,'' Blair said.
``So you go through all the avenues.''
</P>
<P>
   His perseverance has paid off. He said his business had
quadrupled in the last six months, and Holyfield chose Church
Street to prepare for his March bout against Lennox Lewis, which
ended in a draw.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrity boxers have attracted other celebrity boxers: The gym
has also been an occasional host to Mike Tyson, Larry Holmes and
the former light heavyweight champion Jose Torres.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put my life savings into this gym; I spend every minute of
my time down there,'' Blair said. ``It's go big or go home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
