   KOSOVO-RDP (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ Roundup: NATO says 15 people
were killed in last 24 hours _ 14 civilians and 1 Italian
peacekeeper in a gun accident. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-YUGOSLAVIA (Belgrade) _ Opposition politicians in
Belgrade acknowledge that they are a fractious lot whose infighting
plays into President Slobodan Milosevic's hands. By Blaine Harden.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAID-DENTAL (Manchester, N.H.) _ Even though the vast
majority of the poorest Americans, particularly children, are
covered by Medicaid for dental care, they are not getting it. Most
dentists tend to be loath to take Medicaid patients and Medicaid
patients, often with transportation and daycare problems, are
likelier to miss appointments. By Carey Goldberg. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NY-SCHOOLS (New York) _ When New York City Schools Chancellor
Rudy Crew announced a sweeping shake-up earlier in the week,
closing 13 low performing schools and taking direct control of 43
others, Robert E. Riccobono, the superintendent known for some
innovative programs in District 9, was among those fired. His fate
is a telling example of the difficulty in reforming the city's
worst school district. By James Yardley.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-GORE (Washington) _ A look at the Clinton-Gore
relationship, in light of some of Gore's recent comments. By John
M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   INTEL-REVAMP (Washington) _ Top officials at the FBI, CIA and
the Pentagon have met in recent days to discuss a revamping of the
country's counterintelligence apparatus. By David Cat Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-HOLOCAUST (Berlin) _ After years of dispute, the German
parliament approves construction of a Holocaust Memorial. By Roger
Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   NY-DAVINCI-HORSE (Beacon, N.Y.) _ Five hundred years ago,
Leonardo da Vinci's long-held plan to cast a 24-foot-tall bronze
horse for his patron, Duke Ludovico Sfroza of Milan, crumbled when
invading French troops used the full-size clay model for crossbow
practice. Leonardo never completed the piece, which would have been
the largest equestrian sculpture in the world. Today, Leonardo's
dream, first articulated as a postage-stamp-size sketch, was
revealed in three jaw-dropping dimensions, in the form of a proudly
prancing 15-ton bronze stallion that was cast and assembled at a
foundry here, 60 miles north of New York City.
</P>
