<HEADER>
A9848 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-CALIFORNIA-HNS &LR;      06-25 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CALIFORNIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA A PROVING GROUND FOR BUSH CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 27)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA TOLLEY  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ When Gov. George W. Bush takes his presidential
campaign of broad themes to California this week, he may run into
the types of hard issues that can confound a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the early front-runner for the Republican nomination, has
been traveling around the nation all month gathering support and
money for his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The next stop is California, a state that once was revered
Reagan country and now is seen by many as a must-win for the
Democrats in the 2000 presidential race. It is a trove for a
presidential candidate: A state with more than 30 million people
and 54 electoral votes, and a political climate that runs from the
conservative Central Valley to the liberal San Francisco Bay area.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats won California's top post last year when Gray Davis
was elected governor after 16 years of Republican leadership.
Meanwhile, Republicans still are trying to recover from the two
terms of Davis' predecessor, Pete Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything Governor Bush can do to distance himself from Wilson
will be very beneficial,'' said Barbara O'Connor, director of the
Institute for the Study of Politics and Media at California State
University in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   Initiatives backed by Wilson such as Proposition 187, which
denied education and medical benefits to illegal immigrants,
alienated Hispanics. And with more than a million Hispanic voters
in California, that poses a challenge for Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Bush opposes California's Proposition 187, and he has criticized
proposals to wall off the United States from Mexico. He touts his
ability to reach out to minorities by pointing out he captured a
significant number of Hispanic voters in Texas _ as much as 49
percent of the Hispanic vote _ in his re-election last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Although he criticizes the ``politics of division,'' he has
stopped short of personally blasting Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue George Bush is going to face in California is
distancing himself from the politics of Governor Wilson,'' said
Harry Pachon, president of the Tomas Rivera Policy Institute in Los
Angeles. ``And I think he has already done that to some degree.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish-speaking Bush's more moderate message could attract
some Hispanics to the Republican fold.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be some very fertile ground for him to plow,'' Pachon
said of the Hispanic voter in California.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also may run into trouble in California on two other thorny
issues: guns and abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Cain, a political science professor at the University of
California at Berkeley, noted that in last year's election, the GOP
candidates for governor and U.S. Senate lost to Democrats on those
two issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both were pro-guns and anti-choice, and Democrats blew them
out of the water in California,'' Cain said. ``It's very hard for a
Republican to win, if he is pro-guns and anti-choice, and that's a
big challenge for Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush opposes abortion except in cases of rape, incest and the
mother's life. On the presidential campaign trail, he has said he
would not impose an abortion litmus test on his judicial selections
or his choice for vice president. As governor, he signed
legislation requiring parents to be notified before a daughter can
get an abortion, hailing it a measure that would decrease the
number of abortions in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he supports the right to bear arms, and he signed
legislation barring cities from suing gun manufacturers to recover
medical treatment costs related to gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   It may be hard for Bush to get his message of ``compassionate
conservatism'' across to California voters credibly, if he is
pressed hard on the abortion and gun issues, Cain said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question now is: Can someone who is anti-choice and
pro-guns win statewide. The suspicion is the answer is no. That's
the million-dollar question for George Bush,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cain and others believe Bush so far is looking like a winner for
the GOP nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people share the general natural (national)
infatuation with him at this point,'' Cain said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some people are supporting Bush not because they necessarily
like his ideology, but because they believe he is only Republican
who can recapture the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (support) is pretty shallow right now,'' Cain said. ``We
really don't know much about him. The tide could shift, if there
are a series of disasters.''
</P>
<P>
   In California, Bush does not enjoy the same strong lead over
Vice President Al Gore, the Democrats' front-runner, that he does
in other states. A recent poll showed the two in a statistical dead
heat in California.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush is still doing well in the state that Gore has been
scrupulous to keep on his radar screen. (Gore made his 57th trip to
California as vice president on Wednesday and Thursday.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Gore absolutely has to win California,'' O'Connor
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
