<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA A PROVING GROUND FOR BUSH CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 27)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA TOLLEY  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ When Gov. George W. Bush takes his presidential
campaign of broad themes to California this week, he may run into
the types of hard issues that can confound a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the early front-runner for the Republican nomination, has
been traveling around the nation all month gathering support and
money for his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The next stop is California, a state that once was revered
Reagan country and now is seen by many as a must-win for the
Democrats in the 2000 presidential race. It is a trove for a
presidential candidate: A state with more than 30 million people
and 54 electoral votes, and a political climate that runs from the
conservative Central Valley to the liberal San Francisco Bay area.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats won California's top post last year when Gray Davis
was elected governor after 16 years of Republican leadership.
Meanwhile, Republicans still are trying to recover from the two
terms of Davis' predecessor, Pete Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything Governor Bush can do to distance himself from Wilson
will be very beneficial,'' said Barbara O'Connor, director of the
Institute for the Study of Politics and Media at California State
University in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   Initiatives backed by Wilson such as Proposition 187, which
denied education and medical benefits to illegal immigrants,
alienated Hispanics. And with more than a million Hispanic voters
in California, that poses a challenge for Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Bush opposes California's Proposition 187, and he has criticized
proposals to wall off the United States from Mexico. He touts his
ability to reach out to minorities by pointing out he captured a
significant number of Hispanic voters in Texas _ as much as 49
percent of the Hispanic vote _ in his re-election last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Although he criticizes the ``politics of division,'' he has
stopped short of personally blasting Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue George Bush is going to face in California is
distancing himself from the politics of Governor Wilson,'' said
