<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  pennsylvania votechart
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON WATCH VOTE CHART Questions regarding this
transmission should be directed to 202-628-3100, ext. 224.
WASHINGTON, June 25 -- The following chart shows how senators and
representatives voted on key bills and amendments within the last
week. A ``Y'' means the member voted for the measure; an ``N''
means the member voted against the measure; a ``?'' means the
member did not vote; and a ``P'' means the member voted
``present.''
</P>
<P>
   SENATE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: STEEL
</P>
<P>
   Voting 42-57, the Senate on Tuesday blocked debate on a measure
that would have imposed limits on steel imports into the United
States. The bill was a response to the foreign steel that has
flooded the U.S. market in the wake of the Asian financial crisis.
Supporters said it was necessary to discuss the bill because the
import limits were needed to protect the U.S. steel industry from
unfair trade practices. Opponents said the quotas would violate
international trade laws and cause other countries to retaliate
against U.S. exports. A ``yes'' vote favors continuing debate on
the measure.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: HEALTH
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Tuesday failed to pass an amendment that would
have added the Democrat's managed-care reform proposal to an
agriculture spending bill. Voting 53-47, the Senate tabled, or set
aside, the proposal. The failure of the amendment led to a halt in
further consideration of the agriculture bill because Democrats
threatened to keep offering parts of the proposal as amendments
until the issue is addressed. Opponents of tabling the measure said
it is time for the Senate to address legislation that could remedy
the problems faced by patients when dealing with their health care
providers. Supporters of tabling the measure said the Democrat's
plan does not adequately address those problems. A ``yes'' vote
favors tabling the measure.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2
</P>
<P>
   --- ---
</P>
<P>
   SANTORUM (R-PA) Y Y
</P>
<P>
   SPECTER (R-PA) Y N
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: SAFETY
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, June 18, the House approved, 311-115, an amendment to
a larger gun legislation package that would have required handguns
be sold with child safety locks or storage devices. But the
amendment did not pass out of the House because the gun package was
defeated. Supporters said the measure would protect children from
accidental deaths and injuries by handguns. No members rose in
opposition. A ``yes'' vote favors the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: D.C.BAN
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, June 18, the House rejected, 175-250, an amendment to
a larger gun legislation package that would have repealed the
District of Columbia's law that prevents residents from owning
firearms. Supporters said D.C. residents deserve the same Second
Amendment rights as other Americans. Opponents said the gun ban is
important to the safety of D.C. residents and that Congress does
not have any business overriding their gun laws. A ``yes'' vote
favors the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   3) BILL NUMBER: D.C.GUNS
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, June 18, the House approved, 213-208, an amendment to
a larger gun legislation package that would permit law-abiding
District of Columbia residents to keep a handgun at home and to
carry an unloaded weapon. But the amendment did not pass out of the
House because the gun legislation package was defeated. Supporters
of the amendment said D.C. residents should have the same rights as
other Americans and should be able to protect themselves if an
intruder invades their home. Opponents said Congress does not have
any business overriding D.C.'s gun laws. A ``yes'' vote favors the
amendment.
</P>
<P>
   4) BILL NUMBER: GUNS
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, June 18, the House rejected, 147-280, gun legislation
intended to limit the accessibility of guns to criminals and
children. The package included measures that would require 24-hour
background checks for purchases at guns shows, ban the import of
large-ammunition clips and require safety locks to be sold with
handguns. Supporters said the bill was an effective way to keep
firearms away from criminals and children without compromising the
rights of law-abiding gun owners. Democratic opponents said the
legislation was too watered-down and would actually weaken current
gun laws while conservative opponents said gun control was not the
answer to the recent episodes of violence. A ``yes'' vote favors
the bill.
</P>
<P>
   5) BILL NUMBER: FLAG
</P>
<P>
   The House on Thursday approved, 305-124, an amendment to the
U.S. Constitution that would prohibit ``physical desecration'' of
the American flag. This is the third time that the House has
successfully garnered the two-thirds vote necessary to pass the
amendment. Now it goes to the Senate, where it has failed in the
past. Supporters said the flag is a national symbol that needs to
be protected. Opponents said flag desecration is a form of free
speech and therefore a guaranteed right under the First Amendment.
A ``yes'' vote favors the measure.
</P>
<P>
   6) BILL NUMBER: SEIZE
</P>
<P>
   The House on Thursday approved, 375-48, a bill that will make it
harder for law enforcement officials to seize private property that
is suspected of being connected to crimes. Supporters said law
enforcement officials have abused their power in recent years to
seize property before criminal charges are filed. Opponents said
the measure goes too far, and would make it more difficult to fight
crime. A ``yes'' vote favors the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2 3 4 5 6
</P>
<P>
   --- --- --- --- --- ---
</P>
