<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Saturday,
June 26, 1999. If you have any questions, please call Miranda
Kennedy or Dick Cooley on the Star's News Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   BBOX-CARS: KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ GM has installed on some vehicles
a black box-type recorder that will give information on how a
vehicle has been driven and will allow law enforcement to know
details about what happened in an accident. By ROBERT A.
CRONKLETON. With sidebar EASE-CARS. Story will move in the ``a''
category.
</P>
<P>
   TRACK-GREENE: KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The Kansas City, Kan., School
District would like to latch onto the speeding coattails of Maurice
Greene and build a $1.5 million track and field complex at his alma
mater, Schlagle High School. By JOHN T. DAUNER. Story will move in
the ``a'' category.
</P>
<P>
   NURSING-STUDENTS: KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Two weeks ago Delia Noselo
was living in a cardboard shack in Mexico. Now Noselo, who lost the
use of her legs in an accident, is being cared for in Kansas,
thanks to a group of nursing students. Developing. Story will move
in the ``a'' category.
</P>
<P>
   FIRE-DELAY: KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The Kansas City Fire Department
did not answer emergency medical calls during a four-alarm fire in
May. By STEVE PENN. Developing. Story will move in the ``a''
category.
</P>
<P>
   POPPER-JOURNAL: KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ In which we meet Paul
Bratton, EMS nurse and wildlife adventurer who recently slid his
kayak into a wild river, rolled over and was pinned against a rock
by rushing water. By JOE POPPER. Story will move in the ``a''
category.
</P>
<P>
   RYUN-TRACK: WASHINGTON _ An interview with U.S. Rep. Jim Ryun
about the fall of his 1963 record for the mile run. By DAVID
GOLDSTEIN. Story will move in the ``w'' category and the ``a''
category.
</P>
<P>
   PRISON-ABUSE: KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Details of a federal court
hearing on the proposed settlement for Missouri prisoners abused at
Texas prisons in 1996. Developing. Story will move in the ``a''
category.
</P>
<P>
   FED-RATES: KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Almost all the experts on Wall
Street agree that the Federal Reserve is likely to raise interest
rates a quarter of a point next week. By MARK DAVIS. Story will
move in the ``f'' category.
</P>
<P>
   WHEAT-RAIN: KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Wheat fields are too wet to
harvest, and farmers fear big losses. By VICTORIA SIZEMORE LONG.
Developing. Story will move in the ``f'' category.
</P>
<P>
   MONARCHS-PERSPECTIVE: KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ In 1924, the Kansas
City Monarchs were the first champions of the Negro Leagues. A look
back at that series _ played over the course of 10 games and 18
days in the fall of '24. By BLAIR KERKHOFF. Story will move in the
``a'' category.
</P>
