<DOCNO> NYT19990625.0227 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9860 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HINDU-PRIEST-SEX-HNS &LR;      06-25 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HINDU-PRIEST-SEX-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HINDU PRIEST GIVEN PROBATION IN SEX ASSAULT DENIED BAIL ON NEW
CHARGE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE BREWER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A Hindu priest given probation earlier this week after
being convicted of the sexual assault of an Arkansas woman who
sought his spiritual guidance was denied bail Friday on a new
charge of assaulting another woman.
</P>
<P>
   State District Judge Ted Poe's ruling will keep Bhogeshwernand
Sharma in the county jail, even though Sharma has filed a notice of
appeal and is entitled to post bond while appealing his conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Sharma, 37, was given 10 years probation by a jury Wednesday for
the April 3, 1998, sexual assault of a 21-year-old Little Rock,
Ark., college student at his Harris County home.
</P>
<P>
   The woman says Sharma assaulted her when she and her mother came
to Houston to visit him and his family. She said he bullied her
into sex under the pretext that it was a religious ritual to
``cleanse her womb'' with his ``holy sperm.''
</P>
<P>
   The 21-year-old's mother and aunt testified that Sharma had done
the same thing to them when he was in Arkansas in September 1997
and that he told them bad things would happen if they talked about
it.
</P>
<P>
   Sharma has not been charged in Arkansas, but the two women were
allowed to tell their stories to jurors in the 21-year-old's case
in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   As a condition of probation, Poe ordered Sharma to serve 180
days in jail. Sharma's attorney in the April 1998 case, Katherine
Scardino, filed the notice of appeal shortly after Sharma's court
appearance Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the law, that notice qualifies Sharma for an appeal bail
and means he won't have to live under the terms of his probation
until a higher court decides the case.
</P>
<P>
   But shortly before the jury gave Sharma probation Wednesday,
prosecutor Kelly Siegler filed a new charge against him.
</P>
<P>
   That charge alleges that he sexually assaulted a 20-year-old
Hindu woman in Houston on Jan. 6 _ days before he was charged for
the April 1998 assault _ using the same tactics.
</P>
<P>
   That woman says Sharma impregnated her and that she had an
abortion, Siegler said. Her family also says Sharma's relatives
talked them out of going public sooner.
</P>
<P>
   So, if Sharma is able to raise money for an appeal bail, it
would probably do him little good because he is going to be held
without bail on the new charge.
</P>
<P>
   Making his situation worse, once Sharma had filed his notice of
appeal, he stopped getting credit for serving time on the 180 days
Poe ordered him to do as part of the probation.
</P>
<P>
   That means Sharma stays in jail, but gets no credit toward the
jail time and will begin serving it only when _ and if _ his appeal
fails.
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side for Sharma, the appeal notice means that a jury
in the new case won't be allowed to hear of his conviction in the
assault on the 21-year-old Arkansas woman.
</P>
<P>
   But they could be allowed to hear the facts of that case,
including testimony from the young woman, her mother, her aunt and
yet another woman who recently contacted Siegler and said she had
also been assaulted by Sharma.
</P>
<P>
   Siegler asked Poe on Friday to deny bail to Sharma on the new
charge because he had been seen in a local passport office days
after he was charged in the April 1998 assault.
</P>
<P>
   That resulted in the revocation of his bail then, and Siegler
told Poe on Friday she's afraid Sharma will flee the country if he
is freed.
</P>
<P>
   Sharma tried to talk to the judge about the allegation he had
tried to flee in January, but Poe told him to remain quiet. Poe
said he would review the ``no bail'' status in the new case in 60
days.
</P>
<P>
   Sharma told Poe on Friday that he had no money for a lawyer to
represent him in the new case. So Poe may have to appoint him a new
lawyer, and possibly an appellate attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Poe will address that issue and the amount of the appeal bond at
a July 2 hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Scardino, who was not with Sharma when he appeared Friday, said
she has talked to his family about continuing to represent him
again, but was unsure if that would happen.
</P>
<P>
   Until the issue of his legal representation is cleared up, Poe
appointed defense lawyer Rachel Capote on an interim basis to
represent Sharma in the new case.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
