<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-DIARY-PERSONAL-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PERSONAL BUSINESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 27) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   More Years for Heirs To Benefit From IRAs &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Internal Revenue Service has approved a significant tax
break for some people who want to leave the money in their
Individual Retirement Accounts to two or three generations of
heirs.
</P>
<P>
   Under the ruling, each heir may use her own life expectancy to
determine the rate at which money must be withdrawn and taxes paid
on the withdrawals, said Seymour Goldberg, a tax lawyer in Garden
City, N.Y., who obtained the private-letter ruling for his clients.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, tax lawyers had been advising clients that payouts to
all heirs had to be based on the life expectancy of the oldest
heir.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling means years or decades of additional tax-sheltered
growth of IRA assets for young heirs.
</P>
<P>
   Under the ruling, an IRA that was left to six heirs ranging in
age from 48 to 61 will no longer tie all heirs' payouts to the
23-year life expectancy of the oldest heir. For the 48-year-old,
that means about 12 extra years over which to withdraw the IRA
assets, with the balance continuing to grow, sheltered from taxes,
for all of those years. ``Had a grandchild been involved, it could
have been 70 years,'' Goldberg said.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling, to be disclosed officially Aug. 6, applies only to
IRA owners who die before they must take their first payouts.
</P>
<P>
   David Cay Johnston &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Revising a Gold Standard &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What? A mere million dollars? Such a bundle may no longer be
enough to qualify its lucky owner as wealthy _ even if the person
you ask about the cutoff point is the one with the million. When
Neuberger &AMP; Berman, the investment management and mutual fund
company, surveyed 204 affluent Americans about their attitudes
toward wealth and estate planning, it found that many respondents
set a higher bar.
</P>
<P>
   In the survey, to be released Monday, 44 percent said the word
``wealth'' would not apply to a personal stash of less than $1
million to $5 million, and an additional 29 percent set the minimum
at $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   That thinking may not be shared by Americans at the median
income level _ $37,000 for a household _ but the survey
concentrated on people who met a fairly common current definition
of affluence: annual household income of at least $125,000 and/or
assets of $500,000 or more.
</P>
<P>
   Affluent they may be, but many respondents were under no
illusions that a modest fortune qualified as keeping up with the
Gateses. Almost half _ 49 percent _ of those with assets of more
than $1 million said they did not view themselves as wealthy. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
