<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9871 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-MED-CENTER-ART-$A     06-25 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-MED-CENTER-ART-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REACHING THE HEARTS OF TEXANS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 27) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas, Md.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By JANE WOLFE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Managed care and government cost-cutting are forcing
medical schools to retrench. But Dr. Kern Wildenthal can point out
the window of his 11th-floor conference room here to the three
medical research towers he has built over the last five years at
the University of Texas Southwestern Medical Center _ and describe
plans for three more. The buildings and programs they house reflect
his talent for separating Texans from their millions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm astonished at the amount of money Southwestern has been
able to raise from wealthy individuals,'' said Dr. Maxwell Cowan,
chief scientific officer of the Howard Hughes Medical Institute in
Chevy Chase, Md., and an expert on medical center finances.
``Because of changes in government funding of Medicare and
Medicaid, such institutions will find it necessary to rely on
private funding as they never have before.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Wildenthal, 57, became president of Southwestern in 1986,
it has drawn 6 of the 10 largest gifts ever given to a public
medical school. Ross Perot and Harold C. Simmons, a billionaire
from corporate takeovers and raids, have given close to $50 million
each, and other Texans have donated $450 million.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, according to the Chronicle of Philanthropy,
Southwestern received more private money than any other academic
medical center except the University of California at San
Francisco, a beneficiary of Silicon Valley's largess.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, Wildenthal made fund-raising his priority. He
met and cultivated Dallas' wealthy. Then he used their donations to
attract renowned scholars.
</P>
<P>
   Four Nobel Prize winners are on the faculty of Southwestern _
the only medical school with so many _ along with eight other
members of the National Academy of Sciences. All are vital in
attracting research grants _ $167 million in 1998, up from $36
million in 1983 _ which, in turn, attract more top faculty and
private gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Wildenthal became president the year after two faculty members,
Joseph Goldstein and Michael Brown, gave the center its first
Nobel, for research into how the body processes cholesterol. Their
work had already drawn Perot's attention.
</P>
<P>
   Wildenthal has managed to keep these researchers so happy that
they have rejected other offers, and Perot so happy that he has
donated $25 million to Goldstein's department over the years plus
$19 million for scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as you guys produce results, I'll keep sending you
checks,'' Perot has told the researchers.
</P>
<P>
   Wildenthal was born in San Marcos, Texas, near Austin, and in
1964 received his MD from Southwestern, where, by law, 90 percent
of the students must be Texans. He then was a Guggenheim fellow at
Cambridge, where he earned a PhD. Returning to Southwestern as a
professor in 1970, he became dean of the medical school in 1980,
when he was only 38. Six years later, he became chief of the
center, which includes three hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   He was regarded as a far more promising Mr. Inside than Mr.
Outside. ``He didn't seem to have the schmoozing personality that
goes with the role of fund-raiser,'' Goldstein recalled. ``But
then, he also doesn't have the salesmanlike quality that a lot of
philanthropists are skeptical of.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, his soft-spoken manner and candid approach are what
philanthropists find appealing. ``This may lead to a cure 30 years
from now, or it may not lead to a cure,'' Wildenthal often warns.
``So understand what you're investing in.''
</P>
<P>
   He had barely started as president when the state cut its annual
contribution sharply. ``We had no fund-raising structure,'' he
recalled. ``No staff. No mailing list. We needed money right away,
not 10 years from now. I decided I could either ask a million
people for 10 dollars each or 10 people for a million dollars
each.''
</P>
<P>
   He called on 10 of Dallas's wealthiest people, most of whom he
had only read about, and asked each for $1 million or more. They
were impressed with his style. ``He is very good at expressing how
your money helps the medical school grow and how private money is
the seed money that attracts government grants,'' said Simmons, who
has given chiefly to research in arthritis, which he has, and
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   As the gifts poured in, the city's rich began to embrace
Wildenthal and his wife, Marnie. An expert in fine wine and opera,
he entertained them in the manner to which they were accustomed and
took care to show up at their fund-raising events for other causes.
</P>
<P>
   In a city whose premier exemplars of national excellence wore
helmets and shoulder pads, they were eager for the different kind
of recognition that Wildenthal and his scholars were winning.
</P>
<P>
   His intimacy with Dallas society helps him match the school's
needs with likely donors. ``You have to really know the people and
find out what they're interested in,'' he said. ``Is it cancer?
Mental health?''
</P>
<P>
   The city's social columns are clipped for him daily, and he
never forgets a major donor's birthday or a prime social event. But
when he works a room, he avoids the overly familiar approach.
``Backslapping,'' he said, ``is not a part of fund-raising to me.''
</P>
<P>
   He says he usually lets the donor decide the amount to give. But
that may understate both his business savvy and his directness,
according to one major donor who explained, ``He is a master at
figuring out the maximum you can afford to give _ and then asking
for exactly that amount.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
