<HEADER>
A9875 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-WITH-DePRINCE/     06-25 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-WITH-DePRINCE/TIERNEY-ART-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALUE FUND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Fla., Ill., N.C., Mo.)  
 INVESTING WITH: GREGORY M. DePRINCE AND DAVID E. TIERNEY HARBOR (ART ADV: Graphic of Harbor Value Fund is being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 27)  
 (af)  
 By CAROLE GOULD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gregory M. DePrince, a portfolio manager at DePrince, Race &AMP;
Zolo in Orlando, Fla., says he barely knows David E. Tierney, a
managing partner at Richards &AMP; Tierney in Chicago. That is not
surprising _ until you consider that the two men jointly manage the
$185.5 million Harbor Value fund.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Tierney says he isn't even familiar with the stocks
picked by DePrince, who in turn describes their relationship this
way: ``I've met him, but I'm completely unaware of what he's
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   An odd relationship, to be sure, but a rewarding one. Harbor
Value returned 21.8 percent, annualized, for the three years ended
June 18, compared with 15.5 percent for its peer group of mid-cap
value funds, according to Morningstar Inc., the Chicago financial
publisher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index returned 28.7
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fund's structure is somewhat unusual, but it's worked
quite well,'' said Emily Hall, a Morningstar analyst. It's also
unusual that Harbor Capital Advisors, the fund's manager, is owned
by the packaging giant Owens-Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   How does the arrangement work? To fill the 70 percent of the
fund he runs, DePrince scours the markets for values among mid- and
large-capitalization companies _ but more on that shortly.
</P>
<P>
   As for the remainder of the fund, Tierney receives a quarterly
list of about 500 stocks from which DePrince plans to select his
part of the portfolio. Because Tierney knows the sector weightings
and other attributes of that universe, he can use a computer to
pick 150 stocks that _ when combined with DePrince's universe _ are
meant to match the Russell 3000 value index in terms of attributes
like price-to-earnings, dividend yield, sector weightings and
volatility.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the risk controllers,'' he said, because of the
diversification and balance he brings to the fund.
</P>
<P>
   DePrince's job, meanwhile, is to pick stocks that will
distinguish the fund from any index. It's a three-part process.
First, he screens 6,000 publicly traded securities for those with
above-average yields, market capitalizations of at least $1
billion, and sufficient liquidity. That gives him the diverse list
of stocks that is passed on to Tierney.
</P>
<P>
   Second, DePrince whittles down that list to 200 or so by looking
for issues that are undervalued both historically and relative to
the index. He uses four proxies for value: price-to-earnings and
price-to-book ratios, price-to-cash flow and a stock's yield
relative to the S&AMP;P 500 over time.
</P>
<P>
   Then he and two analysts make the final cut, to 75 stocks, by
looking for a catalyst that will cause investors to put a higher
valuation on the stock. Catalysts may include the start of a new
product cycle, a change in the pricing cycle of a company's
business or a restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   He now sees the most value incyclical stocks, especially paper,
chemicals, metals and machinery companies. ``After a three-year run
on growth stocks, these areas have become very undervalued,'' he
said. ``And on the fundamental side, we have the bottoming of the
Asian economies, the continuing strength in the U.S. economy and
relatively stable conditions in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   A favorite is Boise Cascade, the paper company. The stock yields
1.41 percent, and DePrince says it has a price-to-book ratio of
1.8, in the bottom third of all stocks. The catalyst for
improvement, he said, is rising demand for two key products _
uncoated freesheet and liner board, which should result in higher
prices.
</P>
<P>
   He first bought shares in July 1998, at $29.25, and has a
12-month price target of $48. The stock now trades at $42.625, or
28.7 times analysts' 1999 earnings estimates of $1.49 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Also last July, he bought shares of Emerson Electric, the
electrical equipment maker. Emerson, which yields 2.02 percent,
acquired Westinghouse Process Controls in the third quarter of last
year. ``We like the acquisition, because it gives Emerson the
opportunity to cross-sell all their other electrical equipment
products'' to Westinghouse's customer base, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Emerson's recently announced acquisition of Daniel Industries,
which makes measurement control devices for the oil and gas
industry, will provide a similar opportunity, he added.
</P>
<P>
   DePrince has a 12-month price target of $89 on the stock, which
now trades at $64.4375, or 21.49 times the earnings of $3 a share
that analysts estimate for 1999. Its price-to-book multiple is 4.7.
</P>
<P>
   In September, he acquired shares in Bank of America of
Charlotte, N.C., which yields 2.56 percent. ``The Nationsbank
acquisition of BankAmerica provides enormous cost-cutting
opportunities, on top of the successful integration with Barnett
Banks in Florida and Boatmen's Bancshares in Missouri,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His 12-month price target is $86; the stock now trades at
$70.375, or 2.6 times book value and 14.89 times analysts' 1999
earnings estimates of $4.73 a share.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
