<HEADLINE>
A CONSISTENT EXCEPTION TO THE RULE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic of performance based on Value Line Investment
Survey is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 27)  
 (af)  
 By MARK HULBERT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fischer Black, the late economist, made a remarkable statement
in 1971. Black was a father of the efficient-markets hypothesis,
which holds that no adviser or system can beat the market
consistently. But after analyzing the track record of the Value
Line Investment Survey, he conceded that it was a big exception.
</P>
<P>
   He concluded that almost all Wall Street firms ``would improve
their performance if they fired all but one of their security
analysts and then provided the remaining analyst with the Value
Line service.''
</P>
<P>
   I am not aware of any brokerage firm that ever took such action,
and Black later went to Wall Street himself, eventually becoming a
partner at Goldman, Sachs. But considering even the more recent
performance of the Value Line survey, which began its stock ranking
system in 1965, his observation may still be on target: Studies
have shown that the vast majority of firms have failed to match the
market with their advice.
</P>
<P>
   And the Value Line Investment Survey is one of very few
investment newsletters to have beaten the stock market since
mid-1980, when The Hulbert Financial Digest began monitoring the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   A portfolio of Value Line's top-ranked stocks has gained 18.2
percent, annualized, through April 30, versus 17.0 percent for the
Wilshire 5000, the broad market index.
</P>
<P>
   (Value Line is in second place in the digest's newsletter
performance rankings over that period, after The Prudent
Speculator, which returned 18.6 percent a year, on average. But
Value Line is in first place after performance is adjusted for
risk.)
</P>
<P>
   Value Line's system is proprietary, so we don't know its exact
methodology. But we do know that Value Line favors stocks, of
various market capitalizations, whose prices and earnings per share
are rising fastest. Each week, it ranks a universe of 1,700 stocks,
primarily from the New York Stock Exchange. The top 100, which
Value Line calls its Group 1, are those that it recommends most
highly.
</P>
<P>
   The performance of Group 1 has been relatively consistent,
regardless of the investment style in fashion on Wall Street. In
that respect, the Value Line system stands in sharp contrast with
many others, which shine when their chosen styles are in vogue but
otherwise may barely keep their heads above water.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Value Line's top-ranked stocks perform best when
small-cap stocks dominate the stock market, and when growth stocks
outperform value. But, surprisingly, they perform creditably even
when the opposites are true.
</P>
<P>
   During the years since 1980 in which growth stocks have
outperformed value, Group 1 produced an average annualized return
of 22 percent. In the years when value stocks have led the market,
the system still gained 12.5 percent, annualized.
</P>
<P>
   A similar pattern emerges when performance is judged by market
capitalization. Value Line returned 26.0 percent, annualized,
during years when small-cap stocks dominated, and 12.1 percent when
large caps performed best.
</P>
<P>
   If you're thinking of following Value Line's advice, however, it
would be best to do so in a tax-deferred account. Acting on its
ratings changes would lead to an annual portfolio turnover rate of
around 200 percent, thus creating a big potential capital-gains
liability.
</P>
<P>
   If you do want to follow Value Line in a taxable account, you
might want to ignore the week-to-week updates in the rankings and
update your portfolio less often. You could buy a set of Group 1
stocks each Jan. 1, for example, and hold them for the entire year
_ even those that are dropped from Group 1 along the way. Though
your pretax returns will likely be lower, my research indicates
that your after-tax returns will most likely be greater.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, your options are limited if you want to follow
the Value Line ranking system through mutual funds. Value Line's
no-load mutual funds adhere only loosely to the Value Line ranking
system and, on the whole, have underperformed it. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mark Hulbert is editor of the Hulbert Financial Digest, a
newsletter based in Alexandria, Va. His column on investment
strategies appears every other week. E-mail:
strategy(AT)nytimes.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
