<SLUG> BC-FBO-COLUMN-TITLETALK3-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TITLE CONCEPT FUELED BY ALMIGHTLY DOLLAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID THOMAS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let me get this straight.
</P>
<P>
   Texas can't even determine ``one'' high school state football
champion in its four largest classifications. Now someone thinks we
can determine a ``national'' champion?
</P>
<P>
   Or i$ it really that $omeone think$ there i$ money to be made
here?
</P>
<P>
   I smell a rat. Or maybe it's a Fox, as in Fox Sports Net.
</P>
<P>
   Fox plans the first high school football national championship
game for December 2000. As it stands now, University
Interscholastic League rules would not allow a Texas school to play
in that game.
</P>
<P>
   Thank you, UIL.
</P>
<P>
   Now let's hope the UIL _ which actually is a from-the-bottom-up
organization that enforces what its member schools tell it to _ can
take that line in the sand and make it a line set in stone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thou shalt not play for a national championship.''
</P>
<P>
   High school football is moving quickly toward the same level as
college football. Not only in the level of competition but also in
the competition for its athletes.
</P>
<P>
   The media attention. The recruiting experts. The shoe contracts.
The advertising dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Texas high school football sells.
</P>
<P>
   Check out the current issue of ``Texas Football'' magazine, that
red-breasted robin of Texas high school football.
</P>
<P>
   This is edition No. 40. ``Texas Football'' is successful because
advertisers support it. Advertisers support it because we buy it.
</P>
<P>
   (By the way, did anyone else find curious the Rawlings
advertisement for its Lone Star All-Star Team that stated, ``You
kicked  &LR; ! And we took names.'' Another line crossed for high school
sports?)
</P>
<P>
   That you're reading this page most likely means that you want to
read about high school sports. And football is the biggie.
</P>
<P>
   If any sport can support a national high school championship,
it's football.
</P>
<P>
   But should it? No.
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious reason is that a national poll will determine
the nation's top two teams, which would meet for the national
title. College football's poll system doesn't work, so how can a
national high school poll be expected to work?
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the lesser reasons, such as the potential for a
state champion to end its season with a loss, scheduling problems
and funding.
</P>
<P>
   But the bigger reason is that we don't need a national
championship.
</P>
<P>
   There's a two-question litmus test we can take to prove that.
</P>
<P>
   Question 1: If five years down the road, it's determined that
for five consecutive years the national championship game has not
crowned a ``true'' national champion, will the game be dropped?
</P>
<P>
   No.
</P>
<P>
   Question 2: If five years down the road, it's determined that
for five consecutive years the national championship game has lost
money, will the game be dropped?
</P>
<P>
   Yes.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is the bottom line. The national championship
game is not about making a national champion, it's about making
money.
</P>
<P>
   And it is there that this concept crosses the line. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
