<HEADLINE>
COLLEGE CONTROVERSIES SHOULD HAVE TAUGHT US
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDY FRIEDLANDER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's talk controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Let's talk college football's national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Has there been a subject in sports over the years that can touch
the annual brouhaha surrounding the crowning of a college football
national champion? Three times in the 1990s, the two major polls
have failed to agree on a winner. As recently as 1997, voters
couldn't decide between Michigan and Nebraska. And even when the
polls do agree, there are always a ton of contenders right behind
clamoring that they were robbed.
</P>
<P>
   Now, let's cut to the real issue here. Fox Sports Net has
floated the idea of a high school championship game, beginning in
2000, with the top two teams from Doug Huff's national poll duking
it out for the right to call themselves No. 1 in America.
</P>
<P>
   What's wrong with this picture?
</P>
<P>
   Let's see, we can't come up with a definitive champion out of
112 Division I-A colleges, more than half of which most of the
voters have seen in person or on television. So now we're to try to
get one out of the nation's 17,346 high schools, which is the
latest membership figure from the National Federation of State High
School Associations. And how many of them do you figure Huff has
seen?
</P>
<P>
   The notion that Fox or Huff or anyone else can even come close
to determining a national high school football champion is, in a
word, absurd. We can't even come up with a state champion in Texas
for crying out loud. Last year, the University Interscholastic
League crowned 10 _ count 'em, 10 _ state champions, and that
doesn't even count all the private-school organizations.
</P>
<P>
   You tell me: Was Midland Lee better than Duncanville? Were
either better than Stephenville? How about Aledo? Now extend that
nationally and try to sort through that mess.
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead, pick two teams to play in the game. I'll find 20 more
with legitimate claims. The poll will be skewed toward the largest
classifications in the traditional best football states, which is
to be expected. But an undefeated state champ from, say, Idaho
could well be better than undefeated state champs from Florida and
California. Class 4A Stephenville might be able to defeat any 5A
team. If Fox's proposed Impossi-Bowl becomes a reality, you will
still never know.
</P>
<P>
   The Fox idea is a fraud, every bit as mythical as Huff's current
national champ and far worse than the No. 1 vs. No. 2 bowl games
foisted upon us every year by the preposterous Bowl Championship
Series. Anything that can be done to make it go away _ including
the UIL's current stance prohibiting its members from playing in it
_ is welcome. If it is eventually played, it will be nothing more
than a get-rich quick scheme based on smoke and mirrors.
</P>
<P>
   We already have more than enough of those in sports. For a quick
count, start with the number of bowl games sanctioned by the NCAA.
Does anyone even know who played in last season's Humanitarian
Bowl?
</P>
<P>
   Let's not add one more to the list. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
