<DOCNO> NYT19990625.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9884 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-WORLD-NFL-ART-$AD     06-25 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-WORLD-NFL-ART-$ADV27-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELLING THE OTHER FOOTBALL TO THE EUROPEANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 27)  
 (af)  
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ It was past 10 p.m., and the Frankfurt
Galaxy was being pummeled by the visiting Scottish Claymores.
Despite the late hour and poor prospects, the home crowd of 30,000
noisy fans still packed a stadium throbbing with rock music.
</P>
<P>
   When Frankfurt scored a late touchdown _ still not enough to win
_ the crowd lapsed into the only German song of the night: ``Oh,
wie ist das schoen!'' (roughly, ``How sweet it is!''). When the
game ended, fireworks lit up the sky.
</P>
<P>
   For Oliver Luck, president of the National Football League of
Europe, it was an affirmation of a strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see what I mean?'' Luck shouted ebulliently over the
noise. ``This crowd has been sitting here for three hours, but for
them it seemed like 20 minutes!''
</P>
<P>
   And that is the name of the game. As maestro of the NFL's
improbable effort to export American football to Europe, Luck
decided long ago that he was selling more than a sport. After all,
football is a game that few Europeans have ever played and that
most find bewildering, with players who have unfamiliar names and
do not speak the local language.
</P>
<P>
   So Luck, 39, markets his sport as entertainment, with loud
music, long-legged cheerleaders (an alien concept at the soccer
games Europeans follow avidly), a four-hour pregame ``power party''
and stunts worthy of P.T. Barnum.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Luck pretended to fall out of a helicopter onto
the field _ a double actually made the leap as Luck's image flashed
on the giant scoreboard. Luck then popped out, grinning, from a
gaggle of cheerleaders.
</P>
<P>
   At the NFL Europe's World Bowl championship Sunday _ the Galaxy
versus the Barcelona Dragons in Dusseldorf _ the game ball will be
delivered by a jet-propelled ``rocket man'' who will fly in over
the stadium wall. Four squads of cheerleaders will be on hand.
Halftime festivities will include a fashion show.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a long game, three hours,'' Luck said. ``The last
thing we want to do is to bore people.''
</P>
<P>
   Marketing American football in Europe is about as strange as
teaching cricket in Texas, and after nine years the NFL and Luck
are still struggling to secure a foothold on a continent ruled by
soccer. Some teams draw well _ Frankfurt and Dusseldorf routinely
pack their stadiums at ticket prices as high as $35.
</P>
<P>
   But Edinburgh, Amsterdam and Barcelona continue to lose money,
and the London Monarchs ran into so much trouble that Luck shut
down the team last year, replacing it with a team in Berlin this
spring. (The league has six teams and plays a 10-week schedule,
from mid-April to mid-June.)
</P>
<P>
   Despite the obstacles, overall attendance and advertising
revenue are climbing, and the league now brings in about $30
million a year. Just as important to the NFL parent organization,
the European league seems to be stimulating new interest in the
game itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal is to bring the game close to fans in Europe, to give
them a magnet that will attract them more to the game,'' Paul
Tagliabue, commissioner of the National Football League, said while
on a visit to see the Berlin team earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   It would be difficult to find someone better suited to selling
football in Europe than Luck. He knows the game intimately, having
played for the Houston Oilers from 1982 to 1986 as the backup
quarterback to Warren Moon. He also speaks fluent German and is a
sports commentator on German television.
</P>
<P>
   While with the Oilers, he studied law in the off-season. Later,
he ran unsuccessfully for Congress in West Virginia, where he was
well known from his days as a player for the University of West
Virginia Mountaineers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a candidate for Congress turned out to be good
preparation for this job,'' he mused recently. ``In the campaign I
worked nonstop to get people to vote for me. But it's a lot like
selling tickets _ a lot of personal contact, and you never say
goodbye to anyone without trying to close a sale.''
</P>
<P>
   Luck arrived here in 1990, to start and manage the Frankfurt
Galaxy of the World Football League, an NFL-backed venture with
teams in both North America and Europe that lasted just two years.
After it was disbanded in 1992, Luck worked on plans for the
current, Europe-only successor league, which started in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Germans took to American football fairly readily, partly because
the American military presence here since World War II had given
them some familiarity with it. But a promising start in London
turned to disaster when British fans, intrigued by the original
World League, were soured by its shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we left, we really produced a lot of negative reaction,
and we never recovered,'' Tagliabue said. ``They had had their own
team, and they saw it as part of an international league that was
playing teams in the United States. It was a really big thing. And
we pulled the rug out from under them.''
</P>
<P>
   The coaches of all six NFL Europe teams are from the United
States, and most of the players are Americans on contract to NFL
teams at home or free agents hoping to be spotted by scouts, making
the Europe league something of a training ground for the parent
league.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a key problem has been to keep the game from being so
dominated by Americans that Europeans lose interest. To that end,
league rules require a minimum number of local players on each
roster and at least two locals on the field every second play.
</P>
<P>
   Luck has also recruited retired soccer stars as punters and
place-kickers. But their presence hasn't solved the image problem,
since virtually all the quarterbacks and most other high-profile
players are American. And Luck frets that featuring retired soccer
stars may make people think his game is for old people.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he has introduced some crowd-pleasing ideas, like the
rock music, the cheerleaders (who sometimes get more attention than
the teams in the tabloid papers) and, especially, beer. Beer is
banned at most soccer games in Europe because officials are
concerned about hooliganism in the crowds. But Luck won permission
to sell it freely at NFL games.
</P>
<P>
   In Germany, at least, the hoopla has attracted serious
commercial sponsors, including Ericsson, the Swedish mobile
telephone manufacturer, and Skoda, the Czech subsidiary of
Volkswagen.
</P>
<P>
   ``American football is targeted to a very unique young customer
segment,'' said Frank Farsky, Skoda's head of communications in
Prague. ``Football is a show. It's always been about cheerleaders
and music and Americana.''
</P>
<P>
   But what works in one country may not work in another. Most of
the league's games are scheduled for Saturday nights, perfect for
football in Germany because retail stores here close by 4 p.m. But
Saturday night is prime shopping time in Barcelona. League
officials thought about moving Barcelona's Saturday home games to
Fridays but settled on adapting to Spain's tradition of late-night
socializing by shifting the ``power party'' to after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more like a warm-up to Barcelona night life,'' said Willy
DeWitt, the Barcelona team's acting general manager, who is Dutch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-99 1853EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990625.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9887 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFRICA-POLITICS-550&AMP;     06-25 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-POLITICS-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MBEKI SETS PRIORITIES: PRIVATIZATION, CRIME, LABOR LAWS AND SOCIAL
ISSUES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Switzerland)   By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ South Africa's new president, Thabo
Mbeki, signaled Friday that he had his own way of doing things as
he opened parliament with a speech outlining dozens of new
initiatives from privatization efforts to tough new laws against
racketeering, money laundering and illegal weapons.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Far from the inspirational talk about reconstruction and
reconciliation that had often characterized former President Nelson
Mandela's speeches, Mbeki's hourlong address was more a list of the
work his administration was engaged in.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki offered the nation a detailed look at his priorities,
which included establishing centers for abused women and children;
stepping up efforts to combat AIDS and creating a long-awaited
state lottery.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki was often short on specifics, but there was hardly an
issue facing this troubled nation that he did not discuss. He even
named neighborhoods with the worst crime rates, saying they would
soon have pilot programs to test new policing methods.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While he continued to endorse the country's conservative
economic policies, he also seemed to suggest that he would take a
look at new labor laws that might give the impression that South
Africa was not a good place for foreign investment.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``At the dawn of a new life, our practical actions must ensure
that none can challenge us when we say we are a nation at work to
build a new life,'' Mbeki said &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He made clear that bringing down South Africa's soaring crime
rate _ an issue that had dominated the campaign trail _ was a
priority.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the central features of the brutish society we seek to
bring to an end,'' Mbeki said, ``is the impermissible level of
crime and violence.''
</P>
<P>
   The police force that was left over from the apartheid era was
one of the least educated in the world, trained mainly for riot
control. Convictions were often obtained on the strength of
confessions extracted by violence. About one third of the officers
are illiterate and can't drive. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Mbeki revealed plans to recruit new officers ``with the
requisite education'' and to put them on the fast track to
management.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He also announced that a new unit _ ``adequately staffed and
equipped'' to deal with ``national priority crimes'' including
corruption among officers would be created within 14 days. He
promised that new legislation making it easier to crack down on
organized crime and money laundering would be introduced.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, other legislation to ``ensure that we can
deal mercilessly with all crimes involving guns, including the
illegal possession of fireams, the killing of police officers,
corruption within the criminal justice system and the intimidation
of witnesses,'' would also be introduced.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki, whose African National Congress party won nearly
two-thirds of the 400 seats in the National Assembly in the June 2
elections, also vowed to tackle corruption in national and local
government. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to take this opportunity once more to reiterate
the commitment of our government to honest, transparent and
accountable government and our determination to act against anybody
who transgresses these norms,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But Mbeki's new government is already embroiled in controversy
on this issue. This week a provincial leader appointed by Mbeki,
Ndaweni Mahlangu, said that he did not see anything wrong with
politicians lying, ``It was done all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Mahlangu has re-appointed several officials who are under
investigation for lying or have been found ``unfit'' for government
by reviewing authorities. Mahlangu eventually apologized for his
remarks saying they were inappropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics had hoped Mbeki would use the occasion of his
speech to say something about the incident. He did not.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Economic issues were also clearly high on Mbeki's list of
priorities. Mandela's administration had been criticized for moving
slowly to privatize the South African government's extensive
assets.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Mbeki took the opportunity to announce that Swissair would
buy a 20 percent stake in South African Airways for more than $200
million, and he promised that more such deals were in the offing.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He said working groups would be looking at the development of
small businesses and, noting that interest rates remain high, he
said the Reserve Bank and the finance ministry would continue to
look at this issue very carefully. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Economists said the markets reacted well to the speech, although
the all-share index fell after a bout of profit-taking ahead of the
weekend and fears of interest rate increases in the United States.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki also said that South Africa intended to take an active
interest in trying to resolve regional conflicts and that Mandela
might be called on for such work.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot accept that war and violent conflict are a permanent
condition of existence for us as Africans,'' he said. Therefore, he
added, ``we will contribute whatever we can towards the resolution
of conflicts on our continent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
