<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990625.0241 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9889 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEORGEW-COX     06-25 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGEW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush rakes in $2 million during Florida swing
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA _ Hail hit the private jet and the aircraft bounced
violently for a few moments but those were the only minutes of
discomfort Friday for Texas Gov. George W. Bush, who scooped up $2
million in a one-day, four-city campaign trip to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   During the flight, Bush, who has been criticized by his GOP
rivals for not being specific enough about issues, said that the
purpose of this first stage of his campaign is to let people get to
know him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking a lot about policy every time I get asked
questions,'' said the 52-year old brother of Gov. Jeb Bush. ``We
have a long way to go in this campaign and unlike the others I've
been home in Texas doing my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who delayed campaigning outside of Texas until that
state's legislature ended it's session last month, said the first
thing he needs to do is let voters know ``what my goals are for
America.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting with his ``little brother'' in the comfortable cabin of
the large private jet, Bush said as recently as last Christmas he
was not sure he wanted to be a candidate for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in the groundswell thing,'' said the oldest
son of former President George Bush who looks strikingly like his
75-year old father. ``A candidate has got to really want to run''
for a campaign to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   With the trappings of a campaign that has quickly raised $20
million, the large Bush entourage looked and acted very much like a
campaign that has already won the GOP nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the level of expectation for his candidacy, Bush
acknowledged that it is ``out of sight.'' Comparing his campaign to
a start-up business, he said it has gone from a ``small
entrepreneurial start to the Forbes 500 almost immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting on his father's 1992 loss to President Clinton, Bush
said he remembered when his father started the year with a 92
percent approval rating and dropped to the low 30s 11 months later.
``I know what it's like to go from high to low. I know every
painful moment of that,'' he said. ``I've to make sure that doesn't
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush began his trip with at the Fort Myers home of Al Hoffman
where he collected $800,000 at a $1,000 per person breakfast,
according to campaign spokeswoman Karen Hughs. Hoffman is chairman
of Watermark Communities Inc., which is developing large areas of
northern Palm Beach County and Martin County. Then it was lunch in
Tampa, a reception in Fort Lauderdale and dinner in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   At each of his stops, Bush talked to the crowds about his belief
in compassionate conservatism. He said part of the compassion is
making sure that the economy remains strong so that people can have
jobs. He also said that with prosperity comes responsibility and
that corporations must do more to help their workers lead
successful lives.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also talked in general terms about the need to improve
education, build a strong defense and to help those who ``are
participating fully in the American dream.''
</P>
<P>
   With his brother as governor of Florida, Bush said he is
confident that he will win the state primary and the general
election if he becomes the GOP nominee. ``It helps to have friends
in high places,'' he said as his brother looked on during a news
conference in Tampa. ``For the first time in my life I'm doing what
my little brother tells me to do.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked questions by Hispanic reporters, Bush answered in
Spanish but without the ease of his younger brother, who is fluent
in the language. As the older brother spoke, the younger stood
behind him smirking and mouthed a couple of word's when his brother
struggled.
</P>
<P>
   It was part of a daylong ribbing that the two brothers gave each
other at each stop often to the laughter of the crowds. At one
point Bush was asked if he would appoint his younger brother to the
Cabinet. With Jeb Bush shaking his head in an exaggerated ``No,''
his brother looked at the crowd and just said with a grin, ``Well,
no.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he expects the money he is raising _ far more than any
other Republican candidate _ to scare off his rivals, Bush said,
``I'm not sure what's on their mind. The only thing I know to do is
to campaign hard. I'm pleased with the fundraising response. I
think it is an indication of the support this campaign has across
the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Crowley writes for the Palm Beach Post
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
