<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-WIFE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON DEFENDS WIFE'S USE OF AIR FORCE PLANE IN SENATE CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Stands for budgeted CLINTON-CONGRESS.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, defending Hillary Rodham
Clinton's use of Air Force planes for travel to New York state as
she weighs a Senate campaign, said Friday that the Secret Service
requires her to fly on government planes.
</P>
<P>
   The president also gave a boost to his wife's senatorial
prospects, praising her efforts on domestic policy and dismissing
suggestions that his sexual dalliance with former White House
intern Monica Lewinsky might handicap either her political
aspirations or the presidential campaign of Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``All elections are about the future and all candidates are
judged on their own merits,'' Clinton said, adding: ``I think that
the American people know the country is in good shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the Secret Service rule stems from the law
mandating that the Secret Service provide around-the-clock
protection to the first lady.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's aides say the first lady will start to partially
reimburse the Air Force for her travel after she forms an
exploratory committee in early July to raise campaign donations.
Regulations of the Federal Election Commission then will require
her campaign to reimburse the federal government a hypothetical
commercial airline fare for the itinerary rather than the actual
costs of operating the aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   That fare is a small fraction of the actual cost of the
government plane. The Air Force estimates that the costs for the
executive jets that Mrs. Clinton has used for her New York trips
range from about $4,600 an hour to more than $7,200 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   If Mrs. Clinton decides to run for the Senate, she would become
the first first lady in American history to seek a Senate seat
while living in the White House. The Senate seat is opening up
because of the retirement of Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The president and Mrs. Clinton are scheduled to travel aboard
Air Force One on Monday to Connecticut and New York City to attend
a series of political fund raisers designed to help underwrite
Democrats' efforts to retake control of the House and Senate from
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's confidantes say she is planning to move to New
York in the fall to devote full time to her expected Senate
campaign, returning to the White House on weekends, as her schedule
permits.
</P>
<P>
   New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, a possible GOP rival for the
Senate seat, has questioned Mrs. Clinton's reliance on
taxpayer-subsidized Air Force planes and traveling White House
staff during the exploratory phase of her Senate candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of how she travels is determined by the Secret Service,''
the president told a nationally televised news conference in which
he fielded 27 questions on foreign and domestic issues during 71
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he and his wife have often ``wanted to take trains
to New York'' during his presidency but the Secret Service has
insisted that the couple fly aboard the presidential aircraft known
as Air Force One.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd be amazed how many times in the last few years we've
wanted to take the train to New York, for example, and haven't been
able to do it,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton downplayed his wife's formal announcement of formation
of an exploratory committee. The announcement is expected on July
5, while the president is leading a group of corporate executives
around the nation to visit beleaguered communities that have not
benefited from the nation's overall prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   ``She hasn't made a decision to announce _ to run for the
Senate,'' Clinton emphasized. ``As a practical matter, she has to
have an exploratory committee to continue to talk to people in New
York about this. That's all this is.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said his wife of 23 years ``has not made a final
decision to run yet'' for the Senate from New York, adding: `` So I
think that's a whole different issue, and I think that you should
look at it in that context.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, praising his wife's work, said he was heartened by
House passage of legislation to extend federally-subsidized care
for foster children.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a vital issue, one that Hillary has championed for
many years, and I am very pleased by the House action,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also mentioned his wife's efforts and her book, ``It
Takes A Village,'' as he discussed White House steps to stem the
isolation of adolescents that some blame for the shootings in a
high school in Littleton, Colo., that claimed 15 lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Hillary and I decided that we ought to have this
grass-roots campaign to try to protect children against violence
... one of the things that we learned, obviously, is that a lot of
young people wind up being _ especially really troubled young
people can often be almost strangers in their own homes,'' Clinton
explained.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he hoped his administration's efforts would help
``develop the kind of supports that parents need to do a better
job,'' adding: ``Of course, that's one of the reasons that Hillary
wrote her book a few years ago. And she knows more about that than
I do.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said despite the couple's decision to move to New York
after leaving the White House, he will continue to spend about half
of his time in his native Arkansas to help create his presidential
library and public policy think tank.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have made it clear what I intend to do _ and what I intend
to do is to divide my time between Arkansas and New York,'' the
president said. Clinton said he would not be in Arkansas ``so much
I'll be underfoot'' but added: ``I'll be there quite a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via
E-mail: stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
