<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-ECON-COLUMN-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATES CHASING SALES TAXES DOWN THE INTERNET HIGHWAY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 27) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It is one of the more vexing economic issues of the
Internet age: how to insure that state sales tax revenues are not
eviscerated by the shift to online retailing, where borders are all
but meaningless and sales tax collection is spotty at best.
</P>
<P>
   The question has riled both state and local governments, which
fear that their tax bases will disappear down a phone line at 56
kilobits a second, and electronic retailers and Internet service
providers, which fear that revenue-hungry governments will view
electronic commerce as a cash cow to be milked every which way.
</P>
<P>
   The basic problem has been around as long as mail-order
catalogs. When consumers order books, compact disks or flowers from
an out-of-state retailer, they are technically liable to pay sales
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Companies, however, are bound to collect the taxes only from
consumers in states where the company has a physical presence.
Although some merchants collect the tax even where they are not
required to do so, most do not.
</P>
<P>
   So for orders by mail, or phone _ or the Internet _ consumers
can end up with a tax-free purchase. That reality has left
traditional retailers complaining of a competitive disadvantage.
And it has left state and local governments worried that technology
is leaving tax policy far behind.
</P>
<P>
   Denied reliable sales taxes, they may have to look elsewhere for
revenue, with unpredictable consequences.
</P>
<P>
   It is not too hard to come up with potential solutions. But
don't look for them to be agreed upon and implemented quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Last week saw a flurry of attention to the issue, but no
consensus on anything. The Clinton administration issued a report
on the ``breathtaking'' growth of electronic commerce and the
technologies that make it possible, suggesting that the nation is
only starting to get a handle on all the ways the Internet is
changing the economy and necessitating adjustments to public
policy.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the biggest names in business weighed in with a report
about lost sales tax revenues that suggested the states have gotten
themselves in a lather about nothing.
</P>
<P>
   And the Advisory Commission on Electronic Commerce, established
last year by Congress to help sort out the taxation issue, held its
first meeting and quickly got into a heated debate about ... office
space.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's report, prepared by the Commerce
Department, acknowledged that the government was only starting to
collect and analyze information looking specifically at the
quantity and composition of electronic commerce. But while it cited
only vague estimates of the size of that business _between $7
billion and $15 billion last year, growing to as much as $80
billion in 2002 _ it included a set of examples that made clear how
powerful a force electronic commerce has become:
</P>
<P>
   _ The online sales of Dell Computer more than doubled last year,
and by next year the company expects them to account for half its
revenue.
</P>
<P>
   _ Quicken Mortgage, an online mortgage provider from Intuit,
arranged $400 million in loans in the first quarter of this year, a
pace far ahead of the $600 million in all of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   _ US-Style.com recently started a service allowing Japanese
consumers to buy American goods through a Japanese-language Web
site. The report said the service highlighted the global nature of
electronic commerce and the potential for it to become a trade
issue.
</P>
<P>
   But what has all that activity meant for sales tax collections?
Not much, according to the study done by Ernst &AMP; Young for a
coalition that included America Online, Cisco Systems, Microsoft,
Time Warner and Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that state and local governments lost $170
million in sales tax revenue last year because of Internet
commerce, or 0.1 percent of total sales and use tax collections.
</P>
<P>
   ``The `revenue crisis' from Internet sales has not
materialized,'' it concluded. ``The Advisory Commission on
Electronic Commerce, state and local government and Congress have
time to carefully deliberate on the appropriate taxation of
E-commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   That is good news for the commission, which spent a portion of
its first session last week debating whether its executive director
had created a conflict of interest in accepting free office space
from an electronics-industry lobbying group that employs her
husband. (Like any good commission, it opted to study the matter
further before making a decision.)
</P>
<P>
   There are technical and political hurdles to creating a system
that would automatically add the appropriate sales tax to Internet
purchases and funnel the revenue to the proper government. But none
of them are insurmountable; the electronic payment systems used by
the credit card companies and banks are the obvious model.
</P>
<P>
   The real problem is whether the commission, Congress and the
administration can work quickly enough to get ahead of the Internet
wave, or whether public policy is doomed always to paddle in its
wake. Given the libertarian ethos that has always pervaded
cyberspace, perhaps the latter is just the outcome that the
E-commerce industry and Internet users want.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-99 1911EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
