<HEADER>
A9912 &Cx1f; tth-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOEING-MACHINISTS-SPI     06-25 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-MACHINISTS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUCH AT STAKE IN BOEING-MACHINISTS LABOR TALKS, AND MANY ARE
WATCHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL NYHAN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The International Association of Machinists and The
Boeing Co. will kick off negotiations for a new contract Tuesday,
and both sides hope history doesn't repeat itself.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the two groups met at the bargaining table, in
1995, the Machinists struck for 69 days, crippling production. As
union leaders prepare to hand their contract proposal to Boeing
executives at a formal ceremony in Wichita, Kan., both groups are
claiming they learned valuable lessons from the 1995 fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are more sensitive to the fine art of contract
negotiations ... on both sides,'' said David Olson, a political
science professor at the University of Washington in Seattle. ``If
you want to write a scenario about the negotiating process breaking
down, (1995) was a classic example.''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides have a lot at stake. Workers are fighting to preserve
their generous health care benefits, retain their traditional work
week, improve their pensions and protect their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing, meanwhile, enters the talks fighting to transform into a
leaner company and to bolster its image in the eyes of investors.
Executives say they want to avoid labor disruptions, but they can't
afford to be perceived as caving into the union, according to some
financial analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Even though negotiators from both camps say a strike is
unlikely, it's far from certain it can be avoided. Workers struck
in two of the past three rounds of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real question will be `can they reach an agreement?'''
said Peter Jacobs, a Seattle-based analyst for the Ragen MacKenzie
Group Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Although negotiations begin Tuesday, the two sides have been
talking for months. They already have agreed to suspend new
subcontracting and protect a group of maintenance jobs through
Sept. 1. The efforts have set a positive tone as the parties head
into the talks, according to Jeff Pittsburg, an analyst at
Goldis-Pittsburg Institutional Services Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is one of the keys that better relates management to
employees. ... This is no longer them or us,'' Pittsburg said.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations begin as both the Machinists and the company
stand at crossroads.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing workers are facing the prospect of up to 53,000
additional layoffs through the end of 2000, as the company strives
to lower costs and become more efficient, in part by turning to
more outside contractors. To offset the cuts, the union will seek a
greater voice in corporate decisions to hire outside companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a greater voice now. ... Is it where we want to be?
No,'' said Bill Johnson, president of the union's District Lodge
751. ``Our members want assurances they can have a job.''
</P>
<P>
   In a recent survey, union members said hiring outside U.S.
companies is the greatest threat to their jobs, placing it above
competition from Airbus Industrie and an economic downturn.
</P>
<P>
   Although Boeing officials have indicated they're flexible on
this issue, ultimately their company must retain authority to make
the decisions, according to analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side will discuss details of any contract proposals.
However, Boeing could try to resolve the subcontracting issue by
offering bonuses worth 8 percent to 10 percent, higher than
traditional contract offers, according to some financial analysts.
In exchange, the company would secure the flexibility it wants to
hire outsiders, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The company's generous health care benefits will also be a key
point of contention. Machinists want to preserve the existing
package, one of the last in the region where the company picks up
the entire tab. The company is searching for savings.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing faces a different set of challenges. The aerospace giant
is being buffeted on one side by Airbus Industrie, the consortium
of European nations that has been devouring a greater share of the
airplane market, and by investors on the other side, who are
demanding a more efficient, and more profitable, company.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street is paying close attention to the talks. That's
because a prolonged disruption would snarl production lines,
further eroding investors' confidence in the company just as it's
striving to rebuild its image.
</P>
<P>
   If Boeing can avoid a strike, and the accompanying production
problems, its stature would rise in the financial markets. Boeing
managers would also prefer not to slow production since the company
has pledged to deliver a record 620 planes to customers this year.
</P>
<P>
   The contract is also a major component of Boeing's balance
sheet. Union machinists represented 21 percent of the company's $12
billion payroll in 1998, the company said. And the agreement is
sure to serve as a model for other labor contracts throughout the
massive company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would put them right at the top'' among the company's
priorities, said Paul Nisbet, an aerospace analyst at JSA Research
Inc. in Newport, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing negotiators must walk a fine line, however.
</P>
<P>
   While financial analysts want the company to come to terms with
the Machinists, and keep delivering airplanes to its customers,
they don't want it to give away the store simply to secure peace
with its biggest union.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to see them get tough ... a little bit tougher with
the union,'' said Christopher Mecray, an analyst at Deutsche Banc
Alex Brown.
</P>
<P>
   To walk that line, Boeing has assembled a new team of senior
executives. Jerry Calhoun, seasoned as chairman of the Federal
Labor Relations Authority during the Reagan administration, took
over as the company's top negotiator in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are better off than we were in `95,'' Calhoun said
recently.
</P>
<P>
   And the former chief financial officer of General Motors Europe,
Debby Hopkins, came on board last year in the same role for Boeing.
Hopkins already is drawing rave reviews from Wall Street analysts,
as she helps develop a plan to pare unprofitable products and
services from the company. She could outline some decisions, which
may influence the contract negotiations, this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest change is the addition of Harry Stonecipher,
who joined the company as president after Boeing acquired McDonnell
Douglas Corp. in 1997. Stonecipher is a vocal supporter of
controlling Boeing's costs and is disliked by many rank-and-file
Machinists.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, only 10 percent of union respondents in a survey saw
Stonecipher in a favorable light, while 56 percent saw him
unfavorably.
</P>
<P>
   The upcoming labor talks are also drawing interest from beyond
the confines of Boeing and Wall Street. Executives and labor
leaders from around the world are scrutinizing the cooperative
approach leading into the negotiations for lessons that could help
their own labor relations, according to scholars.
</P>
<P>
   They are also sure to track how the two sides settle the issues
of ``outsourcing'' and health care, according to the University of
Washington's Olson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boeing is simply so important and so big (and) its reputation
is such that it commands not just national but worldwide attention.
There is the pattern of trend setting,'' Olson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-99 1918EDT &QL; 
