<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9913 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BO     06-25 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOURNIKOVA NEEDS NO SPOTLIGHT TO ADVANCE AT WIMBLEDON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ What greater cruelty to mankind could there be than
marooning the Glitter Girl of Wimbledon _ Anna Kournikova _ on
Court 2 for all three of her engagements?
</P>
<P>
   Is this a conspiracy, a cover-up? Here she is, Her Highness of
Hype, getting more ink and photo coverage than the entire
dysfunctional royal family, the prime minister, and the champion
Manchester United soccer team _ and she's banished to a back lot
where only a smattering of the record crowds can squeeze in to bask
in her glow. This just ain't cricket. Or tennis, either.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Kournikova's complaining. A tennis court has the same
dimensions wherever, and she's 3-0 on this one. Thus Anna entered
the Round of 16 Friday by scoring a TKO (7-5, 3-1) over Ines
Gorrochategui, who surrendered with a shoulder injury. But it's
Anna's dimensions that intrigue some patrons of the game, mainly
male. Mournful complaints from such were heard outside Court 2, an
overgrown closet with a capacity of 2,220.
</P>
<P>
   Just across the walkway is Centre Court, holding 13,813.
``That's where Anna belongs, every time she plays,'' wailed Dave
Tashjian, a New Yorker. ``I've got tickets for Centre Court, but
Court 2's where she's happening, and I can't get in.''
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke, guys were trying to climb the fences and being
shooed by stewards. Others were standing in a long line at the
grandstand, hoping that somebody inside would swoon at the sight of
the Glitter Girl and be carried out to make room for another
viewer.
</P>
<P>
   Hormones are hopping whenever Anna's around. Young men bayed for
her from the rooftops next to the stadium at Eastbourne, the
Wimbledon tuneup, and she returned their mating calls with smiles
that matched her golden costume. Gold is selling very short these
days in the Kournikova-model ensembles, although the rules here
require everyone to wear pristine white.
</P>
<P>
   But Wimbledon hasn't yet had the full benefit of her 18-year-old
attractions in whatever shade. She's been stuffed away in an
enclosure usually known as the Graveyard Court because so many
favorites have been interred there by lesser lights. But for some
disappointed attendees, entombing Anna at 2 has been like
consigning Cindy Crawford to a burnoose and veil or casting Julia
Roberts as a nun.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not fair,'' moaned another guy who'd been shut out. ``All
we see in the papers is Anna, but all I see here is a green wall
separating me from her.'' The life of a tennis connoisseur can be
frustrating.
</P>
<P>
   London's tabloids splash Kournikova all over the place and
suggest at numerous romances, which she denies with ``No comment!''
after ``No comment!'' But even a female columnist of a serious
sheet, The Times's Lynne Truss, applauds: ``Anna capitalizes on the
most common posture in sport _ i.e. flexing your legs and sticking
your bottom out.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Cold War were still on, you might suspect a CIA plot here
to keep the Russian blonde from getting too much attention and
making Communism alluring. Hiding Kournikova seems like something
out of the old days in Boston, where the Watch and Ward Society
frowned on titillation. It was surprising that no protesters
marched outside 2 with LIBERATE ANNA signs.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least,'' said the renowned photographer Russo Adamo, ``Anna
has made it to the second week. Last year, a sad one for all of us,
she was injured and not even here.''
</P>
<P>
   However, better days must be coming for those of the Kourni
Kraze persuasion. On Monday, the tournament committee certainly
will have to uncover her on either Centre or Court 1 with its
11,429 seats. She'll be up against Venus Williams, Friday crunched
Sarah Pitkowski, 6-1, 6-1, also on Court 2.
</P>
<P>
   Sex, of course, has always done well at Wimbledon, despite
official frowns. This temple of tennis was constructed on the
strength of Parisienne Suzanne Lenglen's magnetism. Once Suzanne
showed up in 1919 to begin her unbeaten run of six titles, Centre
Court over on Worple Road (about the size of today's Court 2) was
inadequate for the mobs that overwhelmed the place to see more of
her than any previous champion.
</P>
<P>
   In her airy, limb-freeing costumes, Suzanne wiped out the age of
shoetop dresses and whalebone corsets. So prim and disapproving was
the reaction that the ``new'' (present) Wimbledon was hurriedly
built in time for her fourth title in 1922.
</P>
<P>
   You can bet they never enshrouded Suzanne on Court 2. You don't
see Steffi Graf there. Maybe if Anna _ No. 17 in the world but No.
1 in the camera lenses _ wins the title, she'll be out of that
closet forever.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-99 1918EDT &QL; 
