<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9917 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-MCNEELEY-ESCH-BOS     06-25 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-MCNEELEY-ESCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCNEELEY-ESCH: 12-MINUTE MAIN EVENT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ As four-round fights go, this one will be about as
strange as any in boxing history.
</P>
<P>
   When Peter McNeeley tries to exorcise the memory of his last
trip to Las Vegas by going up against cult hero Butterbean Esch on
the undercard of the Johnny Tapia-Paulie Ayala/Stevie Johnston-Aldo
Rios championship doubleheader at Mandalay Bay, it will be a
preliminary fight that is being treated like a 12-minute main
event.
</P>
<P>
   Seldom is it possible to place a legal bet on such a bout, even
in Las Vegas, but McNeeley is an 8-1 underdog who bet $1,000 on
himself this week at the Las Vegas Hilton. That remains the only
money in his name, while someone has reportedly put down $13,000
against him for a chance to make $1,500, a questionable risk/reward
ratio unless you think you've got a sure thing.
</P>
<P>
   Seldom does such a fight show up on TV, yet it is listed as the
semi-main event in Showtime's broadcast, sandwiched between
Johnston's title defense and the Tapia-Ayala main event.
</P>
<P>
   And practically never does such a fight have what McNeeley and
Butterbean's had Thursday afternoon _ a televised, private weigh-in
the day before the rest of the card stepped on the scales. TV
cameras were rolling, and both fighters ended up on ESPN's
``SportsCenter'' at 11 because McNeeley is McNeeley, after all, and
the 318-pound Butterbean is the owner of an odd but lucrative place
in boxing after being converted from a tough-man contest winner to,
well, a tough-man contest winner.
</P>
<P>
   The Bean long ago laid claim to a nonexistent title, ``King of
the Four Rounders,'' and eventually he convinced someone
(admittedly, the fledgling International Boxing Association) to
give him a ``title'' belt to back it up. Along the way, he has also
made several hundred thousand dollars as a kind of working man's
champion, a title McNeeley (45-4) would love to wrestle from him.
Literally if necessary, the Bean understands.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's coming to fight, and so am I,'' Butterbean (44-1-1, 33
KOs) said. ``The boxing purists don't like me, but real boxing is
boring. Lennox Lewis and Evander Holyfield was your typical boxing
match. It was boring. Trust me, people don't want to see two men
hugging and clinching.
</P>
<P>
   ``If McNeeley fights like he fought Tyson (charging across the
ring at the former heavyweight champion and winging wild punches
until he was dropped three times), it will be the fight of the
night.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, but for McNeeley this is more than a circus act: It
could be his final act. After losing in 89 seconds to Tyson four
years ago, McNeeley has seen his life take some sad turns. He's
gone into drug rehab, been ill-treated by many fight fans who
consider him a bad joke, and tried without distinction or success
to prove that his small place on boxing's big stage is deserved.
</P>
<P>
   He made that point with force Wednesday, during a teary press
conference in which he bared his soul to the public. When he was
finished, the crowd cheered him, and he promised to prove that he
belongs on a card whose main event features one of the 10 best
fighters in the world, Tapia.
</P>
<P>
   Tapia (46-0-2) has not lost a fight in his 11-year professional
career, and he will be making his first defense of the World Boxing
Association bantamweight title he won Dec. 5 from Nana Konadu.
Frankly, he and challenger Paulie Ayala (27-1) are everything
McNeeley and Butterbean are not.
</P>
<P>
   They are smooth boxers who slip punches, land often, punch to
the body as well as the head, and move gracefully around the ring.
The same is true of Johnston (26-1), who won back the World Boxing
Council lightweight title in his last fight and is defending it
against Aldo Rios (20-0), a light-hitting challenger who has never
fought outside his native Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   The two champions and Ayala are the polar opposite of brawlers
such as McNeeley and Butterbean, yet promoter Bob Arum acknowledged
this week that, frankly, more people are talking about the circus
than the opera.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a fight I want to see and everyone wants to see,''
Arum said. ``Johnny is everything the sweet science ought to be,
but there's been so much betting action on McNeeley-Esch the odds
went from 2-1 to 8-1. We've got the super heavyweight king of the
four rounders and a guy who is a real fighter, and I can't wait to
see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Strange as it may be, Bob Arum is not alone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
