<HEADLINE>
ADL, INVENTOR SUE GILLETTE IN PATENT DISPUTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Arthur D. Little Enterprises and a California inventor
have sued Gillette Co., claiming the shaving giant infringed on a
1995 patent for a disposable razor with a built-in indicator.
</P>
<P>
   The suit filed Thursday in US District Court in Wilmington,
Del., claims Gillette's best-selling Mach3 shaving system includes
disposable cartridges that ``embody the invention'' of Siamak
Doroodian-Shoja, who for several years tried to sell the idea to
Gillette _ going so far as to license the patent to Arthur D.
Little, the Cambridge consulting firm, to help bring the idea to
market.
</P>
<P>
   The inventor obtained a patent in February 1995 for a ``wear
indicator'' that is gradually worn down by beard abrasion,
revealing a bright strip alerting users that the blade needs
replacing, the suit says. The suit seeks an unspecified award
``adequate to compensate'' the inventor for being ``irreparably
damaged.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillete spokesman Eric Kraus Friday called the suit
``preposterous'' and said the company had obtained patents on
Mach3's indicator strip well before the inventor's 1995 patent.
</P>
<P>
   He also said Mach3's indicator strip _ which starts out blue
then fades as the razor is used _ works in a different way than
Doroodian-Shoja's.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no patent infringement here at all,'' Kraus said.
``But we're not surprised someone would try to capitalize on the
phenomenal success more than a year after it was introduced.''
</P>
<P>
   After being rolled out in April 1998, the premium-priced,
triple-bladed Mach3 shaving system became an almost instant
worldwide hit, capturing some 17 percent of the market in the
United States and 13 percent abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Kraus said Gillette officials discussed buying the patent from
Doroodian-Shoja at one time. But ``we felt the patent was too
narrow and even that it didn't have any scientific merit,'' Kraus
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
