<HEADER>
A9921 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-DRAFT-JILLSON-BOS     06-25 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DRAFT-JILLSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JILLSON AT THE TOP OF EVERYBODY'S DRAFT LISTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- When he spotted Bobby Orr off behind the glass at the
end of the little rink in Milton, Jeff Jillson gave gave Orr a
wave, defenseman to defenseman. Orr, the fullest defensive package
of all time, Jillson dreaming and hoping and working so hard to be
a bit of the same, stay-at-home first, but carry the puck, too.
</P>
<P>
   Red Berenson had chuckled at a memory. There was one game this
season when Jillson had the puck at the point ``and the other
team's defenseman went down,'' said the Michigan coach, a former
Canadien who had seen Orr make a similar move against his Montreal
team time and again, ``and Jeff moved around him and then another
guy went down and Jeff pulled the puck around him and then went in
and deked out the goalie. Usually, you don't get away with things
like that in top-level hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   A memorable goal. So Berenson was asked if he remembered the
name of the opposing team. Berenson said he didn't, ``but I'm sure
if you ask Jeff, he'd know.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It came against Lake Superior State,'' said Jillson, who could
be the first North American defenseman taken in the National Hockey
League draft at the FleetCenter. Jillson then was asked to describe
the goal and his reply was the usual humble answer that hockey
players give when asked to talk about themselves. ``What upset
me,'' he said, ``was that we lost the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Jillson is from North Smithfield, R.I., and most certainly looks
the part of an NHL defenseman. He is 6 feet 3 inches and 215
pounds, can skate, can shoot, and his plus-minus numbers have
always been on the positive side. The bird dogs and denizens of the
Central Scouting Bureau note that Jillson ``has come a long way.''
</P>
<P>
   Scouts and personnel guys have come in waves to Berenson's
office in Ann Arbor, Mich. Some might ask this and others might ask
that about a prospect but, at the end, ``they all ask the same
question,'' said Berenson. `` `Can this boy play in the National
Hockey League?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Berenson said yes, of course. After all, he recruited Jillson
and somehow extricated him from New England and the clutches of the
Hockey East powers, especially Shawn Walsh in Maine. Even more, the
Michigan coach saw Jillson blossom last season as a freshman for
the Wolverines.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, nobody knows for sure who can play in the NHL. Even
now. Even with the draft only hours away. Proof enough was skating
along with Jillson and other top draftees at the Milton rink.
</P>
<P>
   Bruins defenseman Hal Gill had so little hope for the 1993 draft
he said he barely knew there was a draft underway. Gill was the
203d player taken that year and is a solid player for the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Grier of the Edmonton Oilers was also skating with Jillson
at the Milton rink and, unlike Gill, he did have hopes for the
draft of 1993. ``I remember the draft was up in Quebec that year,''
said Grier, ``and a bunch of us guys from St. Sebastian's (prep
school) all decided to drive up there. I remember waiting a long,
long time'' to hear his name chosen.
</P>
<P>
   Grier was taken even lower than Gill, selected 209th by the St.
Louis Blues. Like Gill, Grier is a fixture now in the NHL, even
though the scouts once regarded them more or less as afterthoughts.
They had that certain inner ``something''.
</P>
<P>
   Jillson, though, may be selected as high as 10th to 15th, and
his future seems very bright. Best of all, said Berenson, Jillson
also has that inner ``something.'' Berenson tried putting it into
words, noting Jillson ``obviously has size and toughness.'' Not to
be forgotten is how well he changed from an offensive threat at
Mount St. Charles Academy in Woonsocket, R.I. to a complete
defenseman at Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Berenson has seen all kinds of hotshots come to Michigan, high
school wunderkinds who suddenly are facing players as good as
themselves. Over the years, Berenson has learned an indicator as to
which player will succeed in college. The indicator, said Berenson,
is whether the player is humble or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some kids are just not as coachable,'' said the coach, ``and
usually these kids don't get better. But humble kids do get better.
The challenge is to take the next step.''
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, Jillson is humble. ``Jeff comes from a good
family,'' said his coach, ``and he has good values.'' He is a
student as well as an athlete, winning academic honors at Mount St.
Charles and performing well at Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Jillson came to Michigan and did not remain in New
England also states volumes. ``It takes a lot of toughness and
fortitude to leave his comfort zone (in New England),'' said
Berenson.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, Jillson could have remained in New England but he wanted
the personal challenge of going to an entirely new part of country.
Jillson said he didn't choose Michigan over Maine because the
Wolverines won the NCAA hockey championship at the FleetCenter just
when he was making up his mind. But it helped.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the real reason was that Jillson intended to be at
Michigan a year earlier. His former teammate, defenseman Bryan
Berard, left Mount St. Charles a year early to play juniors, the
year Jillson arrived at the Mount, and Berard, now with the Maple
Leafs, was the first player taken in the NHL draft four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of comparisons between us,'' said Jillson,
who planned to leave for junior hockey in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was heading to Plymouth (the Plymouth Township, Mich.,
Whalers, a junior team of the Red Wings) and they were playing in
the Ontario Hockey League and I was going to enter the draft after
my junior season of high school,'' said Jillson. ``That was my
plan, to go to Plymouth.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jillson came down with mononucleosis in June, just after his
junior year at Mount St. Charles, and junior hockey soon was out of
the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd come down with mono the end of June and that knocked me
down the whole summer,'' he said. ``I mean, I was still sick until
November and December and I was out of shape and I hadn't skated.
Most of all, I'd wanted to be an impact player in the OHL and I
just didn't feel like I could do that.''
</P>
<P>
   So Jillson remained in Rhode Island, won another state title
with the Mounties, and finished high school. Jillson found Ann
Arbor to his liking and Berenson was happy to have a quality
defenseman.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike forwards, said Berenson of hockey's age-old truth,
``defensemen are judged by their mistakes. Forwards are judged by
what they do, defensemen by what they don't do. A good defenseman
is hardly noticed. Jeff was like that.''
</P>
<P>
   By early Saturday afternoon, Jillson's name will be selected by
an NHL team. For the last two days he has been grilled by NHL
personnel seeking that elusive ``something''. Then Jillson will
talk with his parents, Berenson, and others about returning to Ann
Arbor for his sophomore season.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, Brian Lawton of Mount St. Charles was the first player
taken in the draft. In later years, Mathieu Schneider, Keith
Carney, Berard, and others from the Mount have been selected. Now
it's Jillson's turn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
