<HEADER>
A9925 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-SPITZ-BOOK-REVIEW-N     06-25 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-SPITZ-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`INSIDE PICTURE BOOKS:' THE WISDOM IN PICTURE BOOKS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to add publication notes)  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   By EDWARD ROTHSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I am pointing to the ever-darkening pictures in ``Goodnight
Moon,'' a book that has left its mark on three generations of
children. ``In the great, green room,'' I chant, hardly needing to
look at the text as I mention the red balloon, the cow, the bears,
the moon ...
</P>
<P>
   This time, though, sitting by a window through which a full moon
shines, my daughter, too young to talk, is struck by mental
lightning. Again and again she leaps from the book's pictures,
gesturing toward the night sky, making a connection that is as
profound as Helen Keller's identifying water with silent, fingered
symbols.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Handler Spitz, a lecturer in the art department at
Stanford University, will perhaps forgive this memory's intrusion
on a review of her ``Inside Picture Books,'' because that sort of
personal involvement is just what she is exploring. She tells, for
example, of one elderly woman who has shunned chamomile tea all her
life because it was the seemingly punishing beverage Mother Rabbit
gave to mischievous Peter.
</P>
<P>
   Such indelibly intimate responses are the result of what Ms.
Spitz calls ``conversational reading.'' New forms of mental life
are created by children's picture books. The words are not silently
read but are spoken aloud. The pictures are not illustrations of
text but creators of meanings. The most central figure may not be
Madeline or the Cat in the Hat but the parent whose voice shapes
the child's first sense of the world and whose pointing finger
articulates its objects and images. The child is ``transported into
the realm of the uncanny'' by the parent: a source of fear and
comfort who enacts dramas in which fear and comfort are
intertwined.
</P>
<P>
   There is something fine and rare in Ms. Spitz's book, with its
interpretations of picture books ranging from Margaret Wise Brown's
``Goodnight Moon'' to Marjorie Flack's ``Story About Ping.''
Despite the references to Magritte and van Gogh, and analyses that
are influenced by Bettleheim, Freud and Piaget, Ms. Spitz speaks to
her readers not as an academic but as a practiced reader-aloud,
knowing the relationships that exist between a storyteller and
listeners.
</P>
<P>
   If, in the preface, she risks sentimentality in urging her
readers to ``enjoy your children'' and ``treasure the days of your
life that are spent in their company,'' that admonition is
suggestive of her compassionate and passionate readings.
</P>
<P>
   Not just any picture book will do. Ms. Spitz recalls, for
example, a recent clearance sale of such books as ``My Big Sister
Takes Drugs,'' ``I Wish Daddy Didn't Drink So Much,'' and ``Our
Teacher's in a Wheelchair.'' While acknowledging that these titles
may occasionally serve a purpose, she argues that they pale before
others, more resonant with metaphor and allusion; such classic
books strengthen children in ``their ongoing discovery of the
limitations of the real.'' A list of all-time best-selling
children's books that appeared in Publishers Weekly a few years ago
is almost the opposite of its adult counterpart: it is dominated by
classics of the genre.
</P>
<P>
   What allows such books to be so popular and so powerful?
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Spitz's use of the word ``uncanny'' is suggestive. Great
picture books seem to dwell on a border between worlds: between
childhood and adulthood, fantasy and realism, darkness and light.
They mark transitions, dramatize transformations, and reproduce the
tensions that lie latent between parent and listener.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Spitz suggests that they also literally lead from day into
night, that a picture book's ``fundamental message will have to do
with its being the last human contact before sleep.'' In a sense,
she points out, every picture book is a bedtime story, not just
``Bedtime for Frances'' or ``Harold and the Purple Crayon'' or ``In
the Night Kitchen.''
</P>
<P>
   In Ms. Spitz's fine interpretation of ``Goodnight Moon,'' her
themes converge. Nothing happens, but the coming of night, with the
child (a bunny) first surveying the great, green room and its
objects and then releasing them with the coming of sleep. As Ms.
Spitz shows, this is ``not a pastel book.'' It incorporates the
vaguely sinister: a tiger rug, a cat eyeing a mouse, the
encroaching darkness.
</P>
<P>
   Like other children's classics the book encompasses dangers
without nullifying them; they become part of the child's
experience. Every assurance is tinged with worry and every worry
tempered by assurance, much like the nature of the final farewell
of the parent upon finishing the book, leaving the child alone in a
dark room.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Ms. Spitz's analyses are overdone (the reading of ``In
the Night Kitchen'' is too Holocaust haunted), and some themes
might have been more systematically developed. On the issue of
gender she also tends to use too crude an interpretive grid. For
example: Are there really many more picture books about boys than
girls? Not in my experience and not in the list Ms. Spitz herself
provides as a bibliography.
</P>
<P>
   While ``Madeline,'' like other picture books, plays with gender
expectations _ Madeline is boyish, her post-appendicitis gifts are
girlish _ these gifts do not seem to be rewards ``for assuming her
designated gender role.'' Ms. Spitz often treats gender
differences, which are central to picture books, as if they were
arbitrarily ``designated'' by cultural history, even though she
otherwise spurns ``scholars who want to historicize everything.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter. Reading aloud, as Ms. Spitz argues, is an
extraordinary gift for children, unmatched by any promise of new
media. It is also a gift for the parent, who becomes practiced in
crossing childhood's boundaries while bearing full knowledge of
what is yet to come, not just in the books themselves but in the
unfolding lives of their listeners. One night, in fact, the
farewell comes from the other direction: the child passes through
those boundaries and turns away from the parent's reading voice,
ready to proceed into texts in solemn and silent solitude.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PICTURE BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   By Ellen Handler Spitz
</P>
<P>
   230 pages. Yale University Press. $25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
