<SLUG> BC-ECONOMY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORPORATE PROFITS GAIN LEADS LATEST ECONOMIC REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The government reported Friday that corporate profits rose at a
rate of 6.3 percent in the first quarter _ two percentage points
higher than previously estimated and the biggest quarterly gain in
five years.
</P>
<P>
   The news, combined with a slightly higher than estimated growth
in gross domestic product in the first quarter, confirmed the
economy's remarkable expansion continues.
</P>
<P>
   But the rosier numbers contained no big surprises for analysts
who are considering what the Reserve Board will do when it meets
next week to discuss interest-rate policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't change our picture of the first quarter at all,''
Cynthia Latta, an economist for Standard &AMP; Poor's/DRI in Lexington,
said about the new reports.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market reacted with a shrug. After four consecutive
down days from Monday through Thursday, the Dow Jones Industrial
average stock index rose 17.73 points Friday to close at 10,552.6.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed is expected to raise its benchmark interest rate by a
quarter percentage point when members meet next week, but not
because there are any signs of inflation in the US economy. Rather,
members fear that if the Fed does not act to cool down growth and
the expansion goes on too long, it could cause inflationary
pressures to build in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts are now looking ahead to what data for the second
quarter, which ends June 30, will show. Economists anticipate a
modest slowing in GDP growth to a rate of about 3 percent. The wild
card is consumer spending, which has been propelling the economy
and remains very strong.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department said gross domestic product, or GDP,
expanded at a 4.3 percent annual rate from January through March,
instead of 4.1 percent, as estimated earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate profits, which had been estimated at 4.3 percent,
posted the biggest upward revision. Pre-tax profits fattened at a
6.3 percent rate in the first three months this year, a sharp
turnaround from last year's fourth quarter when profits shrank by
1.7 percent as tobacco companies paid money out to settle lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Commerce said the 6.3 percent rise in profits was the highest
for any quarter since a 14.9 percent increase in the second quarter
of 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The government cited a narrowing of the trade deficit as a key
reason the GDP numbers exceeded estimates. Exports rose faster than
expected and imports were lower as a brightening economic picture
in Asia improved overseas sales opportunities and stimulated a
pickup in US manufacturing activity.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-99 1929EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
