<DOCNO> NYT19990625.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9929 &Cx1f; tth-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CELLULAR-DEALMAKERS-S     06-25 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELLULAR-DEALMAKERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOICESTREAM, OMNIPOINT FOUND A FIT IN EACH OTHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RICHMAN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ When you're a small cellular service provider using
the least popular technology in America, just trying harder may not
be good enough.
</P>
<P>
   So John Stanton, chairman and chief executive of Bellevue's
VoiceStream Wireless Corp., and Doug Smith, his counterpart at
Omnipoint Corp. of Bethesda, Md., decided to join forces. Wednesday
night they created a merged entity with assets of $9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The merger, already approved by the boards and shareholders of
both companies, creates the second largest PCS (digital cellular
service) license holder in the nation and the fourth largest in
terms of people within the licensed areas, the companies said.
</P>
<P>
   It will hold licenses to serve more than 175 million people
across the country, in 17 of the top 25 markets.
</P>
<P>
   The merger ``creates some massive scale for the company,'' said
Deutsche Banc Alex. Brown analyst Jeffrey Hines.
</P>
<P>
   Before the merger, at opposite ends of the country, both
companies had been independently building cellular networks based
on GSM, a cellular technology far more popular in Asia and Europe
than in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   VoiceStream started building its GSM network in the west and
midwest. It currently serves 450,000 customers in 11 markets within
13 western states. Service areas include Denver, Phoenix, Portland,
Salt Lake City and Seattle. Dallas and Chicago are next.
</P>
<P>
   Omnipoint serves the Northeast and Midwest, with nearly 380,000
customers in Boston, Detroit, Miami, New York and Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   In this country, cellular giant AT&AMP;T Wireless Services uses a
competing technology _ time division multiple access, or TDMA _
while mega-provider Sprint PCS uses code division multiple access,
or CDMA. Most customers don't know or care about the difference,
but it matters to the providers, because the three systems are
incompatible. Building a nationwide system around one of the
systems requires a massive investment in FCC licenses, cellular
relay towers, and other hardware.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure is either to make a massive investment or find a
partner.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton and Smith, aided by a team of nearly 25 people, pursued
the latter course, launching the new company on Wednesday in the
offices of a New York law firm. The new company, which will retain
the VoiceStream Wireless name, will challenge the big guys, execs
say.
</P>
<P>
   The objective: to acquire the size and scope to provide
customers with a nationwide network for local, long distance and
data.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the GSM providers, who are a series of independent
companies, don't have is the ability to offer nationwide rate
plans,'' said Don Guthrie, VoiceStream's vice chairman and
director. ``I'd be very surprised if we don't have a nationwide
plan by the end of next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanton in prepared remarks said the merged company will be
better positioned than either company alone to offer service to
major customers like large corporations.
</P>
<P>
   The combined company will let VoiceStream save costs by
combining functions like billing and customer service, analysts
said. It will also reduce what VoiceStream pays other carriers to
serve its customers when they travel around the country.
</P>
<P>
   To finance its expansion, VoiceStream got additional cash from
Cook Inlet Region Inc., an Anchorage corporation with investments
in communications, tourism and real estate. That company invested
an undisclosed amount to form joint ventures to acquire licenses
from Omnipoint.
</P>
<P>
   In the third piece of Wednesday's deal, Hutchison
Telecommunications PCS (USA) Ltd., which already held 24 percent of
VoiceStream's stock, said it will invest another $957 million in
the combined company, including $150 million of preferred Omnipoint
stock. The investment will give Hutchison, whose parent company is
based in Hong Kong, approximately a 30 percent share of the
combined company.
</P>
<P>
   VoiceStream will exchange 0.825 shares of its common stock, plus
$8 in cash, for each share of Omnipoint common stock. The merger is
set to close in the fourth quarter, pending regulatory approvals.
</P>
<P>
   The next step for the new company is to ``start rolling up the
other GSM players,'' said Paul Judge, director of The Walter Group,
a Seattle telecommunications consulting and development company.
``John Stanton is a strong horse, and the financial community loves
him. Wall Street was looking for the horse to roll up all the GSM
players.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanton _ by most accounts the main force behind the merger _
will remain the chairman and chief executive of VoiceStream.
</P>
<P>
   Smith will become a vice-chairman of VoiceStream, leading the
development of a wireless data strategy for the new company. The
Omnipoint name will disappear.
</P>
<P>
   Those two ``have talked weekly for three years now, and it was
probably in the back of their minds five years ago,'' he said. He
couldn't say when talks first became serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys are entrepreneurs,'' Guthrie said. ``They have the
force, vitality, energy to drive an idea forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Other VoiceStream execs took on varied roles during the
negotiations, which Guthrie, an experienced financier, described as
extremely complex. His role was to coordinate Voice-Stream's and
Omnipoint's legal teams. Cregg Baumbaugh, VoiceStream's executive
vice president for finance, strategy and development, was the chief
negotiator with Cook. Alan Bender, general counsel, spent about
forty hours straight with his Omnipoint counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a day off qualifies as less than four hours, I think I had
one over the past two weeks, but I'm not sure when,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This report includes information from Bloomberg News.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
