<SLUG> BC-BKN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KERR   GIVING IT HIS BEST SHOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The idea was that after the ball went into David
Robinson or Tim Duncan it would come back out to Steve Kerr and he
would calmly stick a jumper, or perhaps even a three. After all,
isn't that the way it always seemed to work in Chicago?
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't worked that way. The man who three times shot in
excess of 50 percent as a Bull while taking it to the hoop about
once a month shot 39 percent during the regular season as a Spur
and has been a steady nonfactor as in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   But is he brooding? You kidding? He's about to be a champion for
the fourth straight year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been frustrating in an individual sense,'' he admitted on
the eve of Game 5. ``But it's been rewarding in a team sense. And
that's why I came here. I knew we had a chance to win. It makes up
for a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Kerr offers no excuses for his subpar performance. Most
people familiar with the game recognize that he left an optimum
situation for him in favor of just the type of circumstance he had
known in his five pre-Chicago years. He is not exactly in the upper
percentile of the league's superior athletes, and he had severe
problems getting open for his jumpers as he slid from Phoenix to
Cleveland and Orlando before striking career gold with a five-year
stay in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if he's never been open as a Spur. But somehow it
has not been the same for him as it was in Chicago, where he was
one of the league's most feared open shooters. He does, after all,
hold both the career (.463) and single-season (.524) record for
highest 3-point percentage, and that was compiled in the 1994-95
season, the year when Michael sat out until March.
</P>
<P>
   ``The triangle offense was ideal for me,'' he said. ``There
isn't any question that if I hadn't signed with Chicago in 1994 I'd
be doing something else today. I had no other offers at the time.
Four or five teams were willing to invite me to camp with no
guarantees. There were no guarantees from Chicago, either, but I
just felt that was my best shot at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   That led to a successful carer in Chicago, during which time
Kerr earned three rings. He would come in time after time to nail a
big three or provide a couple of pressure-relieving 18-footers. The
absolute highlight came when he took a pass and swished a foul-line
jump shot that clinched Game 6 against Utah in 1997 and gave
Chicago the fifth of its six titles in the 90s. It was a case of a
team deciding that Michael wasn't going to beat them, and Kerr was
quite willing to perform the task himself.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is a Spur, and he is, along with teammate Will Perdue, in
position to compare two very different championship teams.
</P>
<P>
   He cautions everyone not to get ahead of the story. He plays on
a good team, but he would like people to recognize that the Spurs
aren't the Bulls. ``That team won six titles,'' he pointed out.
``After the first title, there was a cockiness about them. This
team has yet to win one. Once we do it, the team may develop that
deep-seated confidence the Bulls had, but it will have to win one
first.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls were built around two fabulous mid-range players. The
Spurs are built around a pair of agile and athletic 7-footers. And
in case you've forgotten, one of those quality mid-range players
the Bulls had on their side was the greatest player ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be off-limits to discuss anyone playing today in
comparison to those Chicago teams.'' Kerr said. ``There was never a
presence like Michael Jordan. If I were comparing teams, I would
never bet against him.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerr doesn't dwell on all this. He was only addressing the
situation because he was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appreciated it while I was there; no question,'' he said.
``But I try not to think about it too much. When I retire, I'm sure
I'll be thinking about it some more.''
</P>
<P>
   He was pressed a little more, and now it was time to make the
case for his current team.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this team were playing the Bulls, the big question would
be, `How are we going to deal with Michael and Scottie (Pippen)?'
'' he said. ``And if the Bulls were playing the Spurs, the big
question would be, `How are they going to deal with David and Tim?'
It would all be very interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerr is 33. The reason for his poor shooting this year may have
only a little to do with not playing in the triangle offense and a
lot more to do with the possibility that he is simply on the down
side. If so, he will have nothing to apologize for. He was lucky to
find a proper home at a critical juncture in his career, sure, but
no one being asked to do what he did could have done it any better.
</P>
<P>
   There have been recent signs that his shot has been coming back.
It's not as if the Knicks were going to leave Steve Kerr alone,
particularly in the late stages of a close game. The Jazz did that
two years ago, and after he released the ball, they were going
home.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
