<SLUG> BC-BIZ-EARNER-FAMILY-ART-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COPING WHEN TWO INCOMES BECOMES ONE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Md.)   (ART ADV: Graphic of proposed asset allocation for the Edmonston
couple is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Photo is being sent to
NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 27)  
 (af)  
 By ROY FURCHGOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE, Md. _ Mark A. and Anastasia B. Edmonston are the sort
of people credit card companies hate and mutual fund managers love.
</P>
<P>
   After five years of marriage, Edmonston, 39, a college physics
professor, and his wife, 36, who until recently coordinated an
injury rehabilitation program at Sinai Hospital here, had accrued
combined savings, including those in their retirement accounts, of
more than $235,000 in stocks, bonds and cash. Their combined income
peaked this year at almost $7,700 a month, or about $92,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   They carry no debt other than a mortgage, they pay cash for most
of what they buy, and they contribute as much as they can to their
retirement accounts without depriving themselves or their
daughters, Hannah, 2, and Rachel, 7 months.
</P>
<P>
   But they are at a financial crossroads. Ms. Edmonston recently
quit her job to spend two years working on a master's degree in
special education, a pursuit that will cut their income by nearly
half until she graduates and starts a new career.
</P>
<P>
   Still, they wanted to stay ahead of the financial game, managing
for the next two years without having to dip into the savings they
have put aside for their children's education and a larger house,
let alone their retirement.
</P>
<P>
   They asked for help from a certified financial planner,
Catharine V. Fairley of Keller Brunner Financial Services in
Frederick, Md. Her goal for the couple was more modest. ``I'd like
to see you make it through this period without accumulating debt,''
she told them.
</P>
<P>
   Even that will not be easy. Ms. Edmonston's take-home pay, after
deductions for taxes and savings programs, came to $1,430 a month.
To cover expenses, they will have to find new ways to make up that
amount.
</P>
<P>
   Reviewing the Edmonstons' finances with them over french fries
at the Phoenix Emporium, a bistro-cum-antique-store in Ellicott
City, Md., Ms. Fairley found little fat to trim. The couple paid
cash for a used 1994 Volvo 850 wagon that costs less than $1,000 a
year to maintain. They are coupon clippers and store-brand buyers.
And Edmonston brown-bags his lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cheap!'' he volunteered, raising his hand.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Edmonston added that co-workers gave her a gift certificate
before her farewell party, so she could go to a fashionable salon
to have her hair done. ``They were afraid Mark wouldn't let me
go,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonston laughed. Both agreed that even he, the more stringent
saver, is not that Draconian. Still, he prides himself on finding
good dinner wines for $5 a bottle. ``Anyone can find a good bottle
at $10,'' he boasted. ``This is a challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Their new situation, though, will demand more than cutting the
wine bill. And there may even be some new expenses: Ms. Fairley
advised spending $50 a month for added life insurance and $80 a
month for long-term disability coverage for Edmonston while his was
the sole income.
</P>
<P>
   One big source of savings, however, may be Ms. Edmonston's new
schedule, which will let her take over some work the couple
previously paid for. Savings on day care and domestic help could be
$690 a month.
</P>
<P>
   As for Edmonston, the planner recommended some ways he could
increase his take-home income.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonston, who is paid twice a month, was putting $236 of each
check into the Towson State University 403(b) retirement plan. Ms.
Fairley suggested that he contribute even more, maximizing his
403(b) payment. With lower family income and the 403(b) adjustment,
his tax bracket would be lower and he could reduce his tax
withholding.
</P>
<P>
   She also advised him to stop having $300 a month of after-tax
money put into his credit union savings account for now, since he
already had more in retirement savings than what she would
recommend as necessary for someone his age.
</P>
<P>
   With the adjustments, Edmonston's take-home pay would rise by
$370 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Even with all those changes, the family would still be $500 a
month short of meeting its monthly budget, Ms. Fairley figured.
That means tapping into principal, though the planner said the
couple could minimize the bite by reinvesting some of the $48,000
they have in checking and savings accounts.
</P>
<P>
   For the short term, Ms. Fairley advised that the couple keep a
smaller emergency fund _ $4,000 in a checking account and $10,000
in savings _ than she would usually recommend in longer-term
planning. As a hedge against a huge emergency, she advised opening
a line of credit at the bank.
</P>
<P>
   She also suggested using a combined $4,000 to start Roth IRAs,
forming another kind of cash reserve. ``With a Roth,'' she said,
``you can withdraw your principal with no penalty and no tax
consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   That left $30,000 in cash to work with. By shifting $10,000 to a
money market fund and $20,000 to intermediate-term corporate bond
funds, Ms. Fairley said, the Edmonstons could withdraw $500 a month
for 5.8 years before reducing the total to zero.
</P>
<P>
   But the Edmonstons, of course, won't do that. They plan to make
withdrawals for only two years, leaving much of the money for the
future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
