<HEADLINE>
OFFICIALS SEE WORST DROUGHT IN DECADE SHAPING UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- It's not quite the Dust Bowl of New England yet, but
the drought of 1999 is shaping up as the worst in almost a decade,
federal officials said Friday, as rivers dry up, parched grass
catches on fire and even the region's biggest water supplier
appeals to customers to use less water.
</P>
<P>
   After 31 days without measurable rain, hydrologists at the US
Geological Survey said that water levels in Massachusetts rivers
are already 25 percent lower than they were at this time during the
last drought in 1995. If the trend continues, they said, this year
could rival 1988 when persistent dry heat brought a water crisis
across New England.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact we are so much lower in June without any long term
expectations of increased rainfall is a real reason for concern,''
said Roy Socolow, chief of the Massachusetts-Rhode Island stream
flow network at the Geological Survey's Northborough office.
</P>
<P>
   Precipitation in southern New England is 15 to 25 percent below
normal for the year, according to the National Weather Service,
with a ``dry and dusty'' weekend ahead.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the main victims have been farmers, forced to irrigate
heavily to keep crops from wilting, and small water suppliers who
have banned most outdoor water use. In addition, the dry conditions
have increased the risk of fires such as a large grass fire in the
Alewife section of Cambridge Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday's call for water conservation from the Massachusetts
Water Resources Authority showed that the drought is taking a toll
even on New England's biggest water supplier. Though MWRA
reservoirs are full, it can't keep up with high water demands,
causing low water pressure in Brighton, Everett, Newton and Saugus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The continued hot weather has pushed our system's peak
deliveries . . . to levels that have not been seen in many years,''
said Doug MacDonald, MWRA executive director. He asked customers to
avoid using water outdoors between 6 a.m. and 10 a.m. or between 6
p.m. and 10 p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-99 1931EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990625.0264 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9934 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REPUBS-ECONOMY-NYT &LR;      06-25 1242
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-ECONOMY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ECONOMY'S SILVER LINING IS A DARK CLOUD FOR SOME REPUBLICANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (dw) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The nation's long run of prosperity has left the
Republican presidential candidates with a crucial strategic choice:
embrace the strong economy as their own, look for the dark side or
change the subject.
</P>
<P>
   But even as they grudgingly acknowledge that a strong economy
helps the incumbent party in national elections _ and grapple with
why their signature economic issue, tax cuts, does not seem to be
lighting any fires among the increasingly well-off middle class _
the Republicans are unwilling to cede the issue to Vice President
Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The economy could still turn down in the 16 months before
Election Day, and the Federal Reserve's apparent impending decision
to raise interest rates has given a case of jitters to the most
visible indicator of confidence, the stock market. Morever, polling
suggests that voters in the early going are not giving Gore credit
for the economy or much of anything else.
</P>
<P>
   Still, no one knows the political power of the economy better
than the Republican front-runner, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas. He
watched a strong economy help his father, then vice president, win
the presidency in 1988, then watched as a weakened economy
contributed to his father's loss to Bill Clinton four years later.
</P>
<P>
   As he begins his campaign, Bush is openly celebrating, even
highlighting, the nation's prosperity. But he is arguing that the
American people, rather than Clinton or Gore, deserve the credit.
And he is asserting that it is his policies that can best nurture
the expansion and harness it to Republican ends _ while positioning
himself to attack should the economy falter before Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole's campaign is betting that good times mean
character and personality will eclipse the economy as an issue.
Steve Forbes says a solid economic foundation provides the
opportunity to address fundamental issues like taxes and education.
Pat Buchanan continues to pound away at the theme of economic
nationalism, saying the global economy is leaving many Americans
behind.
</P>
<P>
   Struggling like his fellow Republicans to move from defense to
offense on the issue, Lamar Alexander is trying a variant on the
question that Ronald Reagan used to skewer Jimmy Carter in the 1980
election: Are you better off than you were four years ago?
</P>
<P>
   ``Today the question is whether we will have a better country
four years from now,'' Alexander said in an interview, all but
conceding that the original formulation of the question would blow
up in the face of Republicans. ``The answer is that we won't if our
standards have sunk to a new low, if we have substandard schools,
if taxes are higher and regulations grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, of course, is aggressively laying out the case for why he,
along with Clinton, should be rewarded for the current combination
of steady growth, low unemployment, dormant inflation and a stock
market that will not quit. Democratic strategists say the economy _
assuming it remains on track _ is one issue on which Gore should be
all but invulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not much of an opening for Republicans on the
economy,'' said Geoffrey Garin, a Democratic pollster. ``The
Republicans are in a position of me too-ism, and having to promise
not to rock the ship.''
</P>
<P>
   History gives the Republicans little hope.
</P>
<P>
   In the 13 president elections since World War II, there have
been four cases where an incumbent president or a vice president
running to succeed him suffered through recessions that extended to
within less than two years of election day. In every case _ Richard
M. Nixon in 1960, Gerald R. Ford in 1976, Carter in 1980 and
President George Bush in 1992 _ the challenger won.
</P>
<P>
   (Nixon and Reagan cut the rule close in their re-election
campaigns. Nixon presided over an 11-month recession that ended in
November 1970, but went on to a landslide victory in 1972. Reagan
presided over a 16-month recession that ended in November 1982, and
went on to a landslide victory in 1984.)
</P>
<P>
   By the same token, incumbent presidents or vice presidents
running to succeed them have won six of the seven elections since
World War II in which they have been able to claim stewardship of a
growing economy. The exception was Vice President Hubert Humphrey
in his race against Nixon in 1968, when the Vietnam War
overshadowed all other issues.
</P>
<P>
   Cast in the role of challenger _ much like Michael Dukakis for
the Democrats against his father in 1988 _ George W. Bush is
clearly looking for a way to turn the situation to his advantage.
</P>
<P>
   His slogan, ``Prosperity with a Purpose,'' hints at a strategy
of acknowledging the obvious and looking to use it both to advance
traditional Republican goals like lower taxes and as a basis for
his advocacy of ``compassionate'' conservatism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of prosperity is to leave no one out, to leave no
one behind,'' Bush said in announcing his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said prosperity ``is not a given,'' was not invented by
Clinton and Gore ``any more than they created the Internet,'' and
that policies he supports, like tax cuts, restrictions on lawsuits,
free trade and partially privatizing Social Security, would help
keep the good times keep rolling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush has developed an economic program that will be
good for the country whether the current cyclical upswing continues
or the economy falters,'' said Michael Boskin, a Stanford
University economist who was President Bush's chief economist and
is now advising George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the economy softens notably, which is possible but not the
base case, that will hurt Gore,'' Boskin said. ``Most likely the
economy and economic policy and what presidents do about it will be
a plus for Bush because his view is closer to where most voters
are.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dole's advisers say that to the degree that voters feel
economically secure their interests will turn to other issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore's got big problems, and the irony is that the strong
economy is one of them because it's making people decide who to
vote for on the basis of character and personality,'' said Ari
Fleischer, Mrs. Dole's communications director.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes said the real credit for the strong economy should go to
President Reagan, for cutting taxes and checking the growth in the
size and influence of the federal government. With the basics taken
care of for most people, he said, now is the time for consideration
of more far-reaching changes, like simplifying the tax code and
giving parents more choice in where their children go to school.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can say, OK, I have a job or the prospect of a job,''
Forbes said in an interview. ``But what is the quality of life? Why
can't two incomes do the job that one income used to do? Why can't
we spend more time with the kids? Why are our schools lagging those
of other countries?''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Republican candidates find it easier to draw
distinctions with Gore than with each other on economic policy. The
exception is Buchanan, whose message of gloom could become more
appealing to the front runner, Bush, should the economy turn down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Factories leaving, communities uprooted, high-paying jobs for
the middle class leaving the country,'' Buchanan said. ``Economic
insecurity has become a pre-existing condition of the American
middle class.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
