<HEADLINE>
PRIME MINISTERS SEEK COMPROMISE TO PRESERVE IRISH PEACE PACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST _ British Prime Minister Tony Blair and his Irish
counterpart, Bertie Ahern, came here Friday with what they said was
their final offer of a compromise to save the Good Friday Agreement
of 1998 from collapse.
</P>
<P>
   The two prime ministers, whose success in fashioning a political
settlement last year has brought relative peace to Northern Ireland
for the first time in 30 years, met with the various parties here
in an effort to end a stalemate that has stalled the creation of a
power-sharing local government.
</P>
<P>
   The meetings took place at Castle Buildings, the place where
last year's Good Friday Agreement was forged, producing a
settlement that is supposed to end three decades of political and
sectarian violence.
</P>
<P>
   The two leaders are working against a deadline of Wednesday, set
by Blair because he believes the parties here will avoid making a
decision unless they are forced.
</P>
<P>
   The Ulster Unionists, who represent middle-class Protestants who
want to remain British subjects, refuse to sit in a government with
Sinn Fein, the political representatives of the Irish Republican
Army, until the IRA begins to disarm.
</P>
<P>
   But the IRA has refused to turn in any weapons, saying that
would amount to a surrender it did not make, and Sinn Fein says
there is nothing in the Good Friday Agreement that links disarming
the IRA to Sinn Fein's participation in a government.
</P>
<P>
   Blair and Ahern arrived Friday with a proposal that was
relatively simple. Under their plan, Sinn Fein would be allowed
into the government, but it would be expected to sign a commitment
to have the IRA decommission its weapons on a strict timetable. If
those timetables are not met, Sinn Fein would be thrown out of the
government.
</P>
<P>
   British and Irish officials said the proposal calls for
compromise from both sides and upholds both the spirit and the
letter of the Good Friday Agreement, which did not link
decomissioning to participation in the government but was supposed
to be completed by May 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA has flatly said it will not turn in its weapons, and
Unionist leader David Trimble Friday was still insisting that his
party, the biggest in Northern Ireland, will not join a government
with Sinn Fein until after the IRA turns in weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Blair and Ahern described Friday's meetings with the
parties as preliminary, and said that the real negotiations will
begin Monday. However, one Irish official said ``the only thing to
be negotiated is the timetables'' of decommissioning.
</P>
<P>
   If the deadline passes without agreement, it is likely that the
Northern Ireland assembly, which was to bring Catholic nationalists
and Protestant unionists into a power-sharing cabinet for the first
time, will be suspended.
</P>
<P>
   Blair has said that if compromise is not reached by Wednesday,
there could be renewed violence in Northern Ireland. The timing,
meanwhile, could not be worse, as Northern Ireland's volatile
``marching season'' of Protestant parades will peak over the next
two weeks, with several contentious parades planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once again we stare into the abyss. Somehow we must pull
back,'' Blair wrote in a guest column in The Times of London
Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
