<HEADLINE>
THE GLORY AND GAMBLE OF CREATING AN INDEX  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 27) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DYLAN LOEB McCLAIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lately, it seems, media outlets everywhere _ from trade
publications to glossy magazines to Internet sites _ have been
turning out stock indexes at a rapid clip.
</P>
<P>
   Wired magazine publishes its own index of technology stocks,
while Advertising Age does the same with a basket of advertising
agency, media and other stocks. And Business Insurance, a trade
publication, has its index of insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a way of branding,'' said Steven A. Schoenfeld, head of
international equity strategies at Barclays Global Investors. Some
of the indexes, he added, ``are clearly a public relations
exercise.''
</P>
<P>
   While creating and maintaining these performance measures is
much easier than it used to be _ computers make it an automated
snap _ there are no guarantees that anyone will use them, or that
they will last.
</P>
<P>
   As Exhibit A, consider the fate of the New York Times stock and
bond indexes.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times indexes? Indeed. For 62 years, beginning in
1911, The Times published daily stock indexes of 25 industrial and
25 transportation stocks (called railroad stocks back then), a
composite index of the 50 stocks and a bond index.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the indexes were used by The Times and others _
including John Kenneth Galbraith, who, in his 1954 book ``The Great
Crash of 1929,'' described them as ``somewhat more accessible to
the nonprofessional observer than the Dow Jones averages.''
</P>
<P>
   By the early 1970s, though, the Times indexes were largely
ignored; even The Times' own reporters referred exclusively to the
Dow.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Robards, then The Times' market reporter and now the owner
of a wine shop in Lake Placid, N.Y., said he used the Dow
industrials because that was what most people cared about. ``I was
reporting what everybody else reported on _ on the radio, on TV, in
The Wall Street Journal,'' he said. ``I was writing what my
instincts told me to write about.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Wall Street analysts followed the Times indexes, Robards
said, because they were broader than the Dow Jones indexes and the
analysts thought that made the Times indexes better. But that view
was clearly in the minority.
</P>
<P>
   When The Times stopped publishing the indexes in June 1973,
during a big bear market, ``there wasn't any need for them,''
Robards said, adding that he did not recall any complaints. (The
notice in the paper said only that the indexes had been
discontinued.)
</P>
<P>
   Given the obstacles to establishing a credible index, what,
besides brand development _ and a touch of vanity _ is behind the
index proliferation among media outlets these days?
</P>
<P>
   There isthe slight chance that an index can make money. Morgan
Stanley Capital International, which calculates more than 6,000
indexes a day, gets about $250,000 a year from each company
licensing the indexes as well as a fee from exchanges and broker
dealers for each derivatives trade based on the indexes, said
Suzanne Crosby, director of global marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the company is just breaking even, she said. Standard &AMP;
Poor's, with some of the most widely followed indexes, takes in
about $20 million a year from licensing, according to industry
estimates.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Times indexes, Nancy Nielsen, a company spokeswoman,
said the newspaper had no plans to revive them anytime soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-99 1941EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
