<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9948 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-J.C.-PENNEY-ART-2TAKE     06-25 1367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-J.C.-PENNEY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
J . C . PENNEY LOSES FOCUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By LESLIE KAUFMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In mid-May, James E. Oesterreicher, chief executive of the J.C.
Penney Co., stood before shareholders at the annual meeting and
predicted that prosperity was just around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   Though earnings had been stagnant and stock performance
disappointing since Oesterreicher took the helm four years ago, he
had a plan: $300 million for store remodeling, $75 million for a
huge push onto the Internet, and a further emphasis on in-house
brands. By the fall, he promised, these initiatives would add up to
significant gains in sales.
</P>
<P>
   These pronouncements, combined with news that Penney was raising
cash by selling the public 20 percent of Eckerd, its fast-growing
drugstore chain, were enough to convince Wall Street analysts that
a turnaround was near. Attitudes toward the company's shares moved
from a hold toward a thumbs-up buy, according to the First Call
Corp., which tracks analyst ratings. Penney's stock shot up 10
percent after the announcement about Eckerd and has hovered around
the new plateau ever since.
</P>
<P>
   But many former employees and other industry experts think Wall
Street's optimism is premature. Penney's stock may be undervalued
because of Eckerd's strong performance, they say. But the core of
the business _ the nearly century-old retail chain, which accounts
for roughly 50 percent of annual revenues _ is as troubled as ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``To renovate a store is not enough,'' said Kurt Barnard,
president of Barnard's Retail Trend Report. ``You have to have
focus, and Penney's has a total, utter lack of focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Oesterreicher is seen by his critics as something of
a Herbert Hoover, proposing modest corrections even in the face of
a deepening crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seems to believe they can fix it as it is,'' said one
frustrated former vice president, ``as if just by staying the
course, everything will be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind Penney's many shortcomings lurks one overarching problem:
more and better competition. For decades, Penney prospered by
serving a large but unglamorous audience. More affordable than
department stores like Bloomingdale's and Macy's, but more
up-market than discounters, Penney was a respectable, if never
particularly stylish, home for the budget-conscious shopper.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two decades, however, this segment of the retailing
market has gone through a sea change. Department stores have
slashed prices, making an obvious play for mass instead of class.
Meanwhile, retailers like Target and Old Navy are stealing
customers with cut-rate prices and hip environs to boot. It is
impossible to imagine Donna Summer's disco hit Hot Stuff, now a
retro classic, blaring over Penney's speaker system the way it
rocks at Old Navy outposts.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Penney has tried various tactics for
repositioning itself. In the early 1980s, the company evolved in a
more upscale direction, signing leases to be anchor stores in
fancier malls. Soon after, it stopped selling hard goods _ the
appliances and tools that are, by contrast, the mainstay of Sears'
business _ so it could concentrate on apparel and home furnishings.
In 1988, it introduced a series of private brands, most notably the
Arizona Jeans Company.
</P>
<P>
   At each juncture, Penney's moves were considered shrewd and
forward-looking. Some have been highly successful: Arizona Jeans,
for example, became a billion-dollar brand last year.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it has not been enough. For two years now Penney's sales
in stores opened at least a year (a standard industry measurement
of health) have increased less than 2 percent while the industry in
general has experienced robust growth. New competitors like Old
Navy chalked up double-digit gains over the same period.
</P>
<P>
   Oesterreicher acknowledges that the recent performance of his
Penny stores has not been what it should be, but blames ``dramatic
process changes,'' which he says will result in marked improvements
in the near future. No. 1 on this list is a culture-altering move
to wrench control of apparel buying from individual store managers
and hand it over to central buyers.
</P>
<P>
   As late as 1997, individual Penney's store managers bought over
90 percent of what went onto their shelves. By contrast, at almost
every other major retailer, from Sears to Bloomingdale's, buying is
now done centrally. In theory such an arrangement allowed Penney
managers to personalize inventories to suit their customers. In
practice, it meant that store managers, with an eye toward last
year's successes, purchased too little of the next season's hot
item, like capri pants, because it seemed foreign.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time we ordered the latest fashions, our competitors
already had them in stock,'' Oesterreicher said. To correct this,
he has phased in a system where central buyers purchase the first
round of clothes each season, while store buyers retain the right
to reorder.
</P>
<P>
   Other changes Oesterreicher says will yield results soon are a
new marketing strategy that will focus on spotlighting Penney's
private brands instead of just announcing sales events, a major
renovation budget to lighten and brighten stores, and a decision to
cull many underperforming lines of clothing from the stores.
</P>
<P>
   But some former employees and analysts counter that such changes
are not nearly radical enough to save Penney's in the long run.
Similar sweeping marketing and merchandising changes have usually
yielded temporary gains at Kmart and Sears, and even at Penney
before, only to stall again soon after.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turning around old retailers that have not kept pace with new
forms of competition and have repeatedly disappointed customers has
proven to be very difficult historically,'' said Richard Church, an
analyst with Salomon Smith Barney. ``It requires bold aggressive
moves.''
</P>
<P>
   Even there, Penney's seems behind its traditional competitors.
Kmart, for example, appears to have carved out a stronger image for
itself through its Martha Stewart line of home furnishings and its
ads featuring Rosie O'Donnell and Penny Marshall. But asked to
describe Penney's positioning for the future, Oesterreicher harks
back to the classic mid-market department store of the past: ``We
will offer more breadth in assortment and sizes and more
convenience, in terms of location, than other retailers.''
</P>
<P>
   That hardly speaks to a vision for a particular customer. ``The
time when you could be everything to everyone ended 35 years ago,''
Barnard said.
</P>
<P>
   J.C. Penney has been an American institution for almost a
century. That is its strength _ and its weakness. Decades of
shopping at stores with aging physical plants, outdated locations,
merchandise in disarray and ho-hum styles has left many consumers
with a distinct aftertaste.
</P>
<P>
   Even Penney's most devoted customers do not describe it as
fashionable. Michelle Mitchell is a perfect example of this
life-long Penney's shopper. ``They have the best children's
clothes,'' she gushes, ``and they are a lot less expensive than
Macy's.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ms. Mitchell, a casually chic Queens, N.Y., native,
admits that while Penney's clothes meet the sartorial needs of
kindergartners, she does not wear them herself. When it comes to
buying work clothes, she shops the much pricier specialty chain Ann
Taylor's. ``Quality is not the issue,'' she explains, ``it's the
styling.''
</P>
<P>
   To alter such deep-bred customer perceptions would require a
feat of Herculean proportions, but Penney's, with a notoriously
insular corporate culture, is averse to itinerant, superhero types.
Of the company's top managers above the senior vice president
level, only two have not spent their entire careers there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The norm is to be there your whole career, several are even
second generation,'' said Lucille Klein, who left as fashion
director of Penney's women's division three years ago, but still
consults with the company. ``It leads to tunnel vision, like the
Penney's way of doing things is the only way.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A 35-year veteran himself, Oesterreicher does not see this as a
problem, however. ``I don't think whether people come from the
inside or the outside is important,'' he said. ``The issue is
getting the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   Penney's most intriguing effort to alter its trajectory has been
a recent push to set itself up as a pre-eminent Internet retailer.
``We plan to be the biggest retailer of apparel on the Web by
2001,'' said George Stasick, vice president of Internet operations,
confirming the announcement his boss made to the annual meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Penney comes to this table with real advantages. For one, with
$4 billion in sales, Penney is the largest cataloger in North
America. It has in place the capacity to ship 65 percent of its
product within 48 hours and the rest within 72 hours.
Catalog-service desks take returns at all 1,200 J.C. Penney stores
as well as at 300 Eckerd's stores. Five hundred more Eckerd's
locations are planned in the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   But if Penney's raw promise is unmatched in the business, its
strategy for implementation seems less invincible. A week after
announcing that it would spend $75 million just on advertising the
Internet initiative, the company was backtracking. ``We all heard
them say that,'' said Theda Page Whitehead, a company spokeswoman,
``but they say they didn't say it.''
</P>
<P>
   The real strategy, as it turns out, is to spend the $75 million
on catalog advertising, with the Internet side piggy-backing on
that by adding Penney's Web address prominently in ads and signs.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond this media play, Penney's faces a fundamental challenge
that many of its moderate income customers do not even have a home
Internet connection yet. Its special cyberspace hook is to focus on
large and tall sizes not commonly available. At its Just4me site,
(www.just4meplus.com) heavier women can design models shaped like
themselves to try on outfits. But Penney is far from alone in
selling clothes to oversized women. Lane Bryant, a division of The
Limited that also specializes in plus sizes, has a much sassier
(albeit more cumbersome) site.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the other giants of middle-America retailing have big
plans for the Internet, too. Earlier this month, Sears, Roebuck
announced a multimillion dollar push to advertise its decision to
sell appliances online. Brian Kelley, Sears' vice president for
online marketing, said the move was part of a strategy to exploit
its strengths. Sears sells about a third of all appliances in this
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to take advantage of historic dominance in this
area, then engage the consumer in other categories,'' Kelley said.
</P>
<P>
   At its annual meeting, Wal-Mart Stores, while vague about its
plans, promised a major push on the Web this year, too. One analyst
estimates the company has spent $100 million to relaunch its
existing Internet site later this year.
</P>
<P>
   So what can Penney's do to keep up?
</P>
<P>
   The former vice president says that at one point management
toyed with taking the experimental stores in Dallas and turning
them into an entirely different concept. The idea was rejected, she
said, but it may still have merit.
</P>
<P>
   ``To succeed,'' the former executive said, ``they really just
need to get away from the Penney's name.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
