<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURIER OUTMARATHONS SCHALKEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Jim Courier turned Wimbledon into Woodstock Friday as
he continued his recent habit of upstaging the English in their own
theater.
</P>
<P>
   Great Britain, which has been searching in vain for the next
great Briton since Fred Perry won the last of his three straight
Wimbledons in 1936, scheduled three native sons _ well, two natives
and one with an asterisk _ on its showpieces, Centre Court and No.
1, for the third round. Courier was consigned to No. 3, a lesser
forum befitting a 28-year-old player who hasn't won a major title
in six years and is ranked 61st on the ATP Tour, and whose
opponent, Sjeng Schalken, is rated a gaudy 50th.
</P>
<P>
   They proceeded to wage an epic confrontation that was almost as
time-consuming as ``Long Day's Journey Into Night,'' and certainly
as gripping. Courier, the gallant, prickly US veteran, faltered
often but absolutely refused to surrender as he outlasted Schalken,
7-6 (7-2), 3-6, 3-6, 7-5, 13-11.
</P>
<P>
   During the match's 4-hour-25-minute duration, Court 3, just
outside Centre Court, became the central court. No. 3 seats a mere
800, but the crowd increased exponentially as the drama did. This
in spite of the fact that Britain's prime hope, sixth seed Tim
Henman, and its endearing oddity, Danny Sapsford, were on the major
stages _ Centre and No. 1, respectively _ at the same time.
Meanwhile, ninth seed Greg Rusedski, a Canadian by birth who used
the technicality of his mother's British heritage to switch tennis
allegiances, was waiting in the wings for the day's last match on
Centre Court.
</P>
<P>
   That came after No. 4 women's seed Monica Seles suffered yet
another disappointment in the only major whose championship has
eluded her. Seles, who has never regained her dominance since being
stabbed by a crazed German assailant during a 1993 match in
Hamburg, was eliminated by unseeded Mirjana Lucic, 7-6 (7-4), 7-6
(7-4), in the act between the British headliners on Centre Court.
``I think it's going to be very tough, obviously, to play like
(before the attack); time will tell,'' said Seles, whose exit aids
the cause of the top remaining women's seed, No. 2 Steffi Graf, a
6-1, 6-3 victor over Corina Morariu.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Seles, the British contingent performed as expected: two
wins, one loss. Henman ousted Lipton Championships winner Sebastien
Grosjean, 6-1, 6-7 (8-10), 6-3, 6-2, in the big house. Rusedski
entertained another capacity house of 13,813 with a 6-3, 6-4, 7-5
win over Magnus Norman. Doughboy Sapsford, the 30-year-old who is
to British tennis what Eddie ``the Eagle'' Edwards was to British
ski jumping, was ushered into retirement by top seed and defending
champion Pete Sampras, 6-3, 6-4, 7-5, in a match that began two
hours after Courier's and finished an hour before it. Thus ended
the indifferent career of Sapsford, who had promised before gaining
entry into Wimbledon as a qualifier that his next loss would be his
farewell and who prepared for the tournament by gardening at his
house for a week.
</P>
<P>
   But other than staunch loyalists, it seemed that everyone on the
grounds was flocking to Courier-Schalken, especially during the
24-game climax.
</P>
<P>
   The runways ringing Court 3 were stuffed five deep, and the
stairs to the main grounds _ officially off limits _ didn't have
room for one footstep.
</P>
<P>
   In a '90s version of the knothole gang, patrons scaled the wire
fence behind the green facade at one end of the court and tried to
peer through the geraniums atop the posts. Others standing on the
pavement, with absolutely no chance of seeing the action, massed
behind the walls, and some enterprising souls were hoisted atop
supporters' shoulders and delivered stroke-by-stroke accounts in
various languages before being hushed by security personnel.
</P>
<P>
   And for those in the main building that houses Centre Court, the
attraction across the way was no less compelling. People stood at
their office windows and along a public balcony viewing the
proceedings on 3. Even the staid, blue-blazered gents of the All
England Club took pause from their afternoon resfreshments,
stepping onto the balcony outside the players' tea room and placing
their white cups delicately on the railing as they watched,
spellbound.
</P>
<P>
   Courier has become worth all the attention. In April at
Birmingham, he outdueled Rusedski in a five-set classic that lifted
the US Davis Cup team over Britain and into the quarterfinals
against Australia July 16-18 in Brookline, Mass. And in his
second-round match here, his first on Centre Court in six years, he
made the wait worthwhile by bouncing 12th seed Carlos Moya in five
sets.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, weakened by a severe cold and the cumulative wear of so
many strenuous battles, he surpassed even his own dramatic
standards.
</P>
<P>
   After capturing the first set in a 7-2 tiebreaker, he looked
cooked in the midday sun.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth set, he faced match point at 4-5, advantage
Schalken, but kept breathing when the Dutchman hit a return long.
Then he broke serve to 6-5. Still in peril at 0-30 while serving
for the set, Courier again disinterred himself, forcing an extended
conclusion he didn't seem capable of surviving.
</P>
<P>
   Both players held serve through 8-8, but not before Courier had
survived another match point when he trailed, 5-6, 30-40. When
Schalken sent a return into the net, Courier exhaled in relief and
pumped his fist, which he continued doing after every successful
point.
</P>
<P>
   There were more histrionics from two demonstrative, drained
performers. Courier broke to 9-8, inspiring Schalken to hit a ball
in disgust toward the Members Enclosure four courts away, drawing a
warning. But Schalken had reason to celebrate when he broke right
back to 9-9. During a five-deuce game that tied the match at 10-10,
Courier gestured to the crowd to pump up the volume. And on they
battled, each holding serve through multi-deuce games until Courier
earned the advantage again at 12-11 when Schalken hit long.
</P>
<P>
   When Schalken finally yielded, volleying into the doubles alley
to lose a love game for the match, Courier pointed his racket at
the crowd, an imperial gesture of triumph. That was his last
exertion for the day; he required intravenous treatment because of
dehydration and declined to meet the press.
</P>
<P>
   But a devastated Schalken spoke on his behalf. ``He's a great
player, and it was a great match,'' said Schalken. ``He's always
fighting, and he had two incredible shots at the right time. It was
great for tennis, and I think that's why the queue is also long
here for these matches.''
</P>
<P>
   Henman, whom Courier beat in Birmingham and faces in the fourth
round Monday _ undoubtedly on Centre Court _ also put in a good
word for the stubborn American who refuses to go away. ``He seems
to pull through those matches,'' said Henman, ``and that's a sign
of a great player. He's a big-match player. I think when it's a
big-match occasion, he plays, you know _ that ranking is perhaps
lying a little bit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
