<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFUGEES IGNORE DANGERS, FLOOD BACK INTO KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ Despite the danger of land mines and an
escalating cycle of violence, an estimated 50,000 ethnic Albanian
refugees a day came pouring back to Kosovo for the last two days,
UN officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The movement of people, which a UN official called the largest
single ``spontaneous return'' of refugees in the last 25 years,
posed a grave challenge to international aid workers.
</P>
<P>
   A host of agencies are struggling to provide for the basic needs
of families and to identify and clear deadly land mines and
buildings booby-trapped by Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   With lines up to five miles long at border crossings from
Albania, Macedonia, and Montenegro, UN officials said they could
not hold back the flood of the dispossessed. Returnees said they
are eager to leave a life of tents and breadlines in refugee camps
even if it means returning to burned and looted homes and a
countryside littered with land mines.
</P>
<P>
   Selim Perquku, 50, drove a tractor with a trailer packed with
three adults and seven children, all family members. There was no
paperwork to do at the Albanian border, only a recording of the
family name and the number of people returning. UN workers also
handed the children a pamphlet warning about land mines.
</P>
<P>
   As the tractor ground its way along the mountain roads from
Albania, the family began to get its first glimpse of the
devastation caused by the war. Perquku had heard in the refugee
camp that their home in the village of Cecili had been destroyed by
Serb forces, and they planned to stay with relatives whose home was
still standing, though it had been ransacked and the windows shot
out.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest question on Perquku's mind was the whereabouts of
his son, who was taken from the family home by Serb forces before
the family fled in mid-April.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to start to rebuild our lives,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid what we'll see when we get home,'' he said. ``If my
son is there, I will be able to figure out the rest. If he's not, I
don't know how we will go on.''
</P>
<P>
   The influx brought to more than 300,000 the number of ethnic
Albanians who have streamed back into the province in the past 10
days, of approximately 860,000 who left when Serbian forces stepped
up their campaign of mass expulsions from Kosovo, which led to the
NATO bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the largest spontaneous returns that we have
ever seen in the last 25 years of any operation,'' said Paula
Ghedini, a spokeswoman for the UN High Commissioner for Refugees,
at a briefing in the province's capital Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who returned were some 166 ethnic Albanian prisoners
released from Serbian prisons after negotiations between the
Yugoslav government in Belgrade and representatives of the
International Committee of the Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees and prisoners are returning to a land ravaged by
war. Many of their homes have been burned and looted by Serbian
forces and paramilitary units. Many more still do not know the
whereabouts of families torn apart by the war.
</P>
<P>
   They are returning despite the pleas of UN officials and
President Clinton, who visited a Macedonian refugee camp this week
and asked ethnic Albanians to wait until UN and aid workers could
at least identify land mines and defuse booby-traps.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, President Clinton said he was ``concerned about'' the
ongoing violence in Kosovo, where NATO forces have been hard
pressed to prevent returning refugees from taking revenge on the
Serbs who remain, and on Serb-owned properties. But Clinton,
speaking at his first extensive press conference since March, also
insisted he was undeterred by the resistance facing NATO troops,
such as a firefight with US Marines Friday. The solution would lie
in the rapid deployment of more peacekeeping troops, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing what we can to stop'' the violence, he said.
``Obviously, if we could get all of our people in completely and
then get them properly dispersed around the country, we'll be able
to provide a far higher level of protection.''
</P>
<P>
   But an equally crucial part of the reconstruction, Clinton said,
would be giving an invisible type of aid to both sides _
``emotionally and psychologically, spiritually, morally.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of these children are going to need the mental
health services,'' he said. ``I think there are people who went
through the Holocaust who can help a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also denied he had been caught off guard by the
willingness of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to endure 78
days of NATO bombing. He said the bombing ``took only a little
longer'' than he thought it would.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had two models in my mind on what would happen with the
bombing campaign,'' Clinton said. ``I thought it would either be
over within a couple of days, because Mr. Milosevic would see we
were united, or if he decided to sustain the damage to his country,
that it would take quite a long while for the damage to actually
reach the point where it was unsustainable.''
</P>
<P>
   In Kosovo, many ethnic Albanians are turning on their Serb
neighbors as the refugees return after suffering the horrors of the
war and indignity of refugee camps. There has been widespread
looting and burning of Serb homes out of vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   And Serbs are also being killed _ 14 in the province's capital
Pristina alone in the last 48 hours _ in a cycle of violence that
poses a grave challenge to NATO peacekeepers trying to disarm both
sides. With Kosovar Serbs losing faith in NATO's ability to protect
them, thousands have fled their homes and headed north to Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   NATO Supreme Commander General Wesley Clark said Friday that
Kosovo urgently needs an international police force.
</P>
<P>
   There are plans to move 200 International Police Training Force
officers from Bosnia to initiate a UN-sponsored Kosovo police force
that will include both Kosovar Albanians and Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Another 1,000 UN police are also due to arrive soon.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone in this province is fanning the fires of
vengence. Some are trying to put them out.
</P>
<P>
   As the sun set Friday, an ethnic Albanian, Rifat Kadiru, saw
that the home of a Serb neighbor had been set on fire by teenagers
who claimed to be with the Kosovo Liberation Army. Saying the Serb
family were his friends, Kadiru and his children arrived with
buckets of water and tree branches to try to extinguish bales of
hay that had been ignited inside his friend's home.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a good neighbor and a friend,'' said Kadiru, ``I just
wanted to help him.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Anne E. Kornblut of the Globe staff contributed to this report.
Wire service material was used in its preparation.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
