<SLUG> BC-CANADA-DOLLAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME SEE US DOLLAR DOMINATING IN CANADA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Will the queen be forced to abdicate her spot on
Canada's dollar in favor of that old revolutionary rascal George
Washington?
</P>
<P>
   Perish the thought, say Canadian nationalists, fearful their
country's separate cultural and economic identity is already being
squashed under the bigfoot neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   But some prominent economists in Canada are arguing that a
monetary union with the United States is not only likely, but
inevitable, as national economies go global. They predict the
Canadian dollar will follow the beaver pelt and Hudson's Bay
blanket into oblivion as a North American currency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The US dollar is the most powerful in the world, and one way
or another Canada is going to have to tie to it,'' said Thomas
Courchene, professor of economics at Queen's University in Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   ``The march of events elsewhere in the Americas is moving toward
dollarization, using the US dollar as legal tender,'' he said,
referring to Argentina and other Latin American countries giving
consideration to adopting the greenback as their own.
</P>
<P>
   Canada is a rich nation, but in recent years its dollar has
exhibited the sort of instability usually associated with Third
World currencies, dropping to historic lows against the US dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Now the idea being floated by a few prominent Canadian
economists _ possibly at the tacit urging of Canadian federal
leaders _ is that North America must rally under a common currency
in order to compete against the euro, which is becoming the
monetary standard of an economically integrated Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But the suggestion that Canada should surrender control over its
monetary policy, assuming the US is even interested, is appalling
to many Canadians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big business wants a single dollar and no border,'' said Maude
Barlow, chairwoman of the nationalist Council of Canadians, saying
her country is already too Americanized. ``This would be one more
step toward sacrificing our cultural and political autonomy for
greater integration with the US.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue threatens to ignite the sort of bitter controversy
that divided Canada 10 years ago, when politicians and Canadian
corporate honchos propelled the country into a pact with the US
that would become the North American Free Trade Agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as then, the clamor in Canada has barely registered in the
US, where relations with Mexico are a touchy public issue while
relations with the supposedly ``just-like-us'' northern neighbor
rarely elicit more than yawns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a non-issue in the US,'' said Chris Sands, Canada
Project Director for the Washington-based Center for Strategic and
International Studies. ``Americans tend not to think much about
where the US-Canada relationship is going . . . while Canadians are
always thinking about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Top Canadian federal Cabinet officials are pooh-pooing the
notion of a unified currency, even as they prepare to huddle in a
special meeting next week that will focus on the country's
extraordinarily close economic ties with the US, as well as the
often tortured political ties.
</P>
<P>
   A common currency, said Finance Minister Paul Martin, ``would
not be a good thing for the Canadian economy.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the official line, and for good reason: Martin and other
top leaders must run for office, and open support for any move that
smacks of yielding even a smidgen of Canadian sovereignty to the
Yanks is surefire political suicide.
</P>
<P>
   But the Liberal Party government of Prime Minister Jean Chretien
has a reputation for loudly resisting the US embrace while quietly
snuggling ever closer to Washington. For example, Chretien was
elected partly on a pledge to oppose free trade with the US. But
one of his first acts was to join NAFTA, and his government now
champions greater trade integration.
</P>
<P>
   Given that history, the new talk of a common currency seems to
have the fuzzy markings of a trial balloon floated by Canada's
power elite.
</P>
<P>
   The issue was barely a murmur last month, but suddenly, it's all
the buzz. It tops the nightly news on CBC televison and has been
the subject of lengthy articles and commentary in leading
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   In a paper released this week, the C.D. Howe Institute, a think
tank whose forecasts often become the official line, urged Ottawa
to open negotiations with the US toward creation of a North
American Monetary Union.
</P>
<P>
   Such a union, argued economists Courchene and Richard Harris of
British Columbia's Simon Fraser University, would eliminate the
floating US-Canada exchange rate in favor of a monetary system
controlled by a new central bank in which Canada would hold one of
13 seats, with the rest going to US regions.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the scheme say world economic trends make such a
pact inevitable. ``Currencies are becoming supranational. . . there
will be very few of them left in the world,'' Courchene told the
Toronto-based Globe and Mail newspaper. ``You go through Europe
five years from now, and there will be no small, independent
currencies.''
</P>
<P>
   The big question, of course, is whether the US would ever allow
Canada even a tiny voice in setting US monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's position is that it's okay for other countries to
adopt the American dollar as their currency, but the US is
uninterested in entering any European-style monetary union. The
Clinton administration says there has been no talk of a special
deal for Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't had any official discussions between our two
governments about a unified currency,'' said State Department
spokesman James Rubin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
