<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICAID-DENTAL-ART-850(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENTAL ACCESS: A SCREAMING PROBLEM FOR POOR CHILDREN
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ Two-year-old Bryana Gammel's rosebud lips
gaped open, held by a retractor, to reveal baby teeth that were
rotted down to the gum line. Her long lashes lay against her cheeks
in the forced sleep of anesthesia.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, Jay Afrow's delicate forceps gripped, wiggled and
wrenched out the decay-stained teeth, until they lay, like tiny
arrowheads, on a surgical tray. Six of them.
</P>
<P>
   He was doing Bryana a great service, but Afrow was not happy.
``This is not the way you want a 2-year-old to grow up,'' he said.
As a dentist to the poor, Afrow sees a great many children who do
grow up this way _ with swollen abscesses, ``baby bottle decay''
like Bryana's, which eats away whole rows of upper teeth, cavities
left untreated until the pain brings screaming.
</P>
<P>
   His practice in New Hampshire is a window onto a chronic
national problem affecting millions of children, a striking
rich-poor inequality that is only beginning to attract concerted
federal attention and action, in Congress, the White House and
health agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The catch phrase for it is ``dental access,'' and its essence is
this: Even though the vast majority of the poorest Americans,
particularly children, are covered by Medicaid for dental care,
they are not getting it _ at least not in numbers anywhere near
children better off.
</P>
<P>
   Why not? Several reasons, experts say. Many dentists are
reluctant to take patients on Medicaid, the state-run health
insurance for the poor and disabled, because the program tends to
scrimp on payments and involves pencil-breaking bureaucracy. Also,
Medicaid patients, often with transportation and day-care problems,
are much more likely to miss appointments.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are what officials diplomatically refer to as
``cultural problems,'' illustrated by Afrow's tales of encounters
with parents who view their children's oral decay with equanimity
and say things like, ``Losing all your teeth is just a part of
life.''
</P>
<P>
   At work, too, is an underlying sense among everyone from
insurance planners to state officials to patients that dental care
is somehow secondary and optional. The health safety net has big
holes when it comes to dentistry. Only about half the federally
supported community health centers provide dental services.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are profound disparities in the oral health status of
children in the United States,'' said Burton Edelstein, a national
authority. ``Dental diseases, tooth decay in particular, are
overwhelmingly concentrated in a small subset of kids,'' he said, 5
million to 10 million mainly poor and immigrant children.
</P>
<P>
   Those cavity-riddled poor children belie the general impression
in more prosperous circles that with fluoride, dental sealants that
form barriers against decay, and other advances, cavities are
increasingly a thing of the American past.
</P>
<P>
   The National Institute of Dental Research predicts that children
born today can avoid cavities completely, but only if they are
given decent dental care. It has found that for children 5 to 17,
80 percent of cavities are concentrated in a subgroup of fewer than
25 percent of them.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Edelstein said, federal data show that the percentage
of children who experience tooth decay has stayed relatively steady
over recent years; but the percentage of children with decay who
get it repaired has dropped. So for the biggest sufferers, the
problem is actually getting worse.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, there seems little dispute over the seriousness of
the problem. Federal health officials call cavities the most
prevalent chronic childhood disease in the country, much more
common than asthma, and estimate that dental disease and treatment
are the cause of 52 million missed school hours a year. Recent
studies make an ever-stronger case that sick mouths can cause
serious problems, from rare heart damage to ``failure to thrive''
in young children. Most common, they say, are pain-induced
problems: malnutrition brought on by aversion to eating, inability
to concentrate in school, sleeplessness, loss of vitality.
</P>
<P>
   The surgeon general is preparing a special report to be released
next year on the state of America's oral health, focusing heavily
on children; three bills in Congress this term suggest solutions
like Medicaid reform and tax breaks for dentists who treat many
Medicaid patients, and the American Dental Association plans a
conference in August on children's access to Medicaid-covered
dental care.
</P>
<P>
   But at the state level, there is often dispute aplenty, and it
is of the finger-pointing kind. In New Hampshire, Cassandra
Hawkins, a mother who had to call more than 15 dentists to find one
willing to take her 6-year-old son, is suing the state. She says
that the state has failed on its federally mandated obligation to
provide Medicaid children the same access to care as their
private-paying counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   The state's initial response, said Assistant Attorney General
Suzan Lehmann, is that ``it believes it is in compliance with
applicable laws and regulations governing the Medicaid program.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
