<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9970 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGO-TALKS-BOS &LR;      06-25 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGO-TALKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALKS BEGIN IN EFFORT TO END CONGO WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIGALI, Rwanda _ After a long series of false starts and stalled
talks, negotiators from central and southern Africa came together
Friday in a determined effort to end the 11-month war in Congo.
</P>
<P>
   Following a flurry of high-level meetings in capitals across the
region over the past nine days, foreign ministers from the warring
states gathered Friday night in Lusaka, Zambia, hoping to agree on
an immediate cease-fire, a withdrawal of foreign forces, and
internal political dialogue among all factions in the Democratic
Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
   The talks were expected to culminate in a meeting Saturday of
the leaders of the countries represented, but it is doubtful if
ministers would be able resolve core disagreements and pave the way
for a signing ceremony by the heads of state.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the summit itself is postponed, several factors had
added fresh momentum to the peace process. The principle foreign
sponsors to the conflict, all showing signs of economic and
military fatigue, acknowledge that neither side can achieve an
outright victory on the battlefield. The Congolese rebels have been
allowed to participate in preparatory negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   And South Africa's new president, Thabo Mbeki, has pushed Congo
to the top of his foreign-policy agenda, giving fresh leadership to
a process beset by stubborn suspicions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still a debate about the structure of the cease-fire
and a draft on national dialogue among the Congolese, but there is
seriousness on all sides,'' said Jacki Selebi, director-general of
South Africa's ministry of foreign affairs, speaking by phone from
Lusaka, Zambia. ``Everyone is trying to find a peaceful solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite more than a dozen previous rounds of talks, the
fundamental concerns underlying the war remain unresolved. Rwanda
and Uganda backed a rebel insurgency last August to oust Congo
President Laurent Kabila for the same reason they supported a
similar movement a year earlier, that one led by Kabila, to
overthrow Mobutu Sese Seko, the dictator of what was then called
Zaire.
</P>
<P>
   Eastern Congo has been a staging ground for rebels to attack
Congo. For Rwanda, the security threat from its giant neighbor is a
matter of national survival.
</P>
<P>
   The 1994 genocide in Rwanda killed at least 800,000 people, most
of them from the Tutsi ethnic minority. Many of the killers, former
soldiers loyal to a previous Hutu regime, as well as discontented
Hutu civilians, are now scattered across Congo.
</P>
<P>
   Rwanda argues these fighters are determined to resume the
genocide, and it accuses Kabila and his allies of arming them.
Without garentees that these Hutu elements, numbered variously
between 10,000 and 20,000 armed men, will be contained, Rwanda
refuses to withdraw its forces from Congo or sign a cease fire.
Rwanda and Uganda also want Kabila to talk directly with the rebel
forces they back inside Congo.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Kabila refuses either to enter into talks with
the rebels trying to oust him or negotiate with Rwanda and Uganda,
which he regards as foreign aggressors. Backed by Zimbabwe, Angola,
and Nemibia, Kabila demands the withdrawal of all Rwandan and
Ugandan troops, as a precondition for a cease-fire. He also insists
that any accord must recognize his control of all territory inside
Congo, as the UN security council did in April in Resolution 1234.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides view their positions as non-negotiable, and no
previous round of talks has therefore managed to bring all parties
face to face.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two wars in Congo; one between the Congolese, and
one between Rwanda and its expatriates inside Congo,'' said Jan Zan
Eck, an expert on central Africa at the University of Cape Town. A
cease-fire must adress both conflicts simultaneously, he said, or
the fighting won't end.``Rwanda has specific interests in
overthrowing Kabila. It can't have a president in Kinshasa who
uses'' the Hutu rebels against it.
</P>
<P>
   THe current Lusaka round opened amid manuvering and posturing on
both sides. Zimbabwean president Robert Mugabe said earlier this
week that ``we have confirmed cases of agression by Rwanda,'' and
has deployed an additional force, reported to be 3,000 strong, to
defend the strategic mining town of Mbuji-Mayi from Rwandan backed
rebels. Those rebels, riding high on recent military advances, have
meanwhile placed new conditions for peace on Kabila.
</P>
<P>
   But both sides also show signs of strain. Zimbabwe has spent an
estimated $1 million a day to defend Kabila while its own economy
has spun into an unprecedented crisis. This week, Mugaba's
government complained the Kabila was not paying his share of
Zimbabwe's military burden inside Congo. Angola has all but pulled
out of Congo amid the resumption of its own civil war. Uganda is
besieged by at least two rebel groups in its western region as well
as by a border dispute with Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   Only the Rwandans vow to fight until their security needs are
met, and even they admit to feeling the strain. They claim to have
intelligence showing that Zimbbabwe's newly deployed troops are in
fact re-trained Hutu rebels. They deny Mugabi's claim of further
military advances, and question his good faith participation in the
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   `` The logic of reinforcong postions is the logic of preparing
to continue with the war. The issue is not what's on paper but
what's on the ground,'' said Wilson Rutayisira, director of
Rwanda's national information office in Kigali.
</P>
<P>
   At least three separate drafts form the basis of the Lusaka
talks. One, a draft cease-fire brought forward from the previous
round, provides only a vague agreement that ``the signatories
affirm the need to address the security concerns of (Congo) and the
neighboring countries.''
</P>
<P>
   The second is a detailed proposal by Rwanda requiring specific
schedules and sequences for troop withdrawals, clear guidelines for
political negotiations among the Congolese, the modalities of a
cease-fire, and a requirement that Kabila and his allies ``round
up, disarm, and repatriate'' the Rwandan Hutu rebels. All these
points are non-negotiable, said Patrick Mazimhaka, head of the
Rwandan negotiating team.
</P>
<P>
   A thrid draft brought by the south Africans calls for a joint
task team made up of representatives from all the beligerent
parties, the UN, and the Organization of African Unity, to monitor
compliance with the cease-fire until a multinational peacekeeping
force can be marshalled. It also calls for internal Congolese
political diologue.
</P>
<P>
   Both Selebi and Mazimhaka say the various drafts are being
molded into one working framework for peace. The contentious
issues, they said, were disarmament, foriegn troop withdrawl, the
extention of Kabila's authority across Congo, and the struture of
internal political talks among the Congolese. There was also doubt
as to whether Kabila would talk directly with the rebel delegation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been no breakthroughs,'' Mazimhaka said. ``But so
far no one has walked out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-99 2003EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
