<DOCNO> NYT19990625.0281 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9971 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICAID-DENTAL-ART-2     06-25 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICAID-DENTAL-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 MANCHESTER, N.H.: Medicaid program.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Medicaid is considered a great boon for children's health,
several health officials noted, and it is certainly better to have
Medicaid than no coverage at all. But so striking is the disparity
between Medicaid's mandates and the reality that such suits have
cropped up around the country. The New York Dental Society, a
professional association, sued the state in February, saying that
the state-run Medicaid program reimbursed dentists at rates so low
that most refused to treat Medicaid patients. Of New York's 17,000
dentists, fewer than 1,200 handled in Medicaid claims in 1997,
according to the state Health Department.
</P>
<P>
   The suits highlight the crux of the conflict: Dentists tend to
argue that for them to take more Medicaid patients, the state must
first raise its payment rates; the states tend to argue that
dentists have a social obligation to treat Medicaid patients, even
if payments are low.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Wendell, a pediatric dentist in Portsmouth, N.H., stopped
taking new Medicaid patients a year ago, and on May 1 he sent out
letters to most of his Medicaid contingent, some 700 of them,
saying he could no longer afford to treat them. When he did his tax
statements, he said, he found that though the state says it pays 73
percent of Medicaid claims, he had submitted bills for about
$120,000 and received only about $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   For the last year, Wendell said, not a single pediatric dentist
among 17 in New Hampshire has been taking new patients. The state
is ``not willing to pay a dollar more, and access gets worse every
year,'' he said, and in New Hampshire's Medicaid budget, dental
care takes up less than 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. William Kassler, the state's medical director, said: ``The
problem New Hampshire is experiencing is being experienced across
the country. Some people have said a Medicaid card is like a
hunting license: it gives you the privilege of going out and
hunting for a dentist.''
</P>
<P>
   But though the problem is clear, Kassler said, ``the issues are
complex, and the solutions are complex.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any one particular cause of the problem
and likewise there's not going to be any one simplistic solution,''
he added.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Kassler said, there does not seem to be broad
public support, in this time of rising health costs, for budgeting
more money to Medicaid programs for dentistry, and it is the state
Legislature that decides the state budget, including the Medicaid
chunk of it. Medicaid is paid by states with matching money from
the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the financial issues, he said, some dentists have an
aversion to treating the poor. In surveys, some dentists have made
comments like, ``Nothing empties my waiting room faster than one of
those patients,'' and, ``It's their fault. They're not compliant.
They don't pay attention to hygiene. Why don't they take a bath
before coming in?''
</P>
<P>
   The experience in other states shows that increases in payments
do not necessarily bring prompt increases in access, Kassler said,
but New Hampshire is working to make the Medicaid bureaucracy more
dentist-friendly, and may shift Medicaid money from orthodontics to
more basic children's procedures.
</P>
<P>
   At the federal level, an alphabet brigade of agencies is on the
case, it seems. They are bolstered in particular by new federal
money for children's health insurance, said Edelstein, who
coordinates a joint oral health initiative shared by the two
federal health mega-agencies, the Health Resources and Services
Administration and the Health Care Financing Administration. He
also runs the Children's Dental Health Project, an independent
effort to improve access.
</P>
<P>
   The additional federal health insurance money, budgeted at $4.2
billion this year alone under the government's new Children's
Health Insurance Program, is flowing partly to dental programs.
Also, Edelstein said, programs that deal with children, ranging
from Head Start to maternal-child health programs, are pushing
harder to get care for young teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, however, dentists like Afrow chafe at the system and
see no immediate signs of change. Both Wendell and Afrow often
practice a kind of extreme M.A.S.H. dentistry foreign to their
colleagues in prospering suburbs. It is not uncommon, Afrow and
Wendell say, for a poor child to come in with a dozen cavities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sad thing is, 95 percent of dental problems are
preventable,'' Afrow said. But by the time he gets to see many of
these children, only an operating-room session at $3,000 or more
will help them, he said.
</P>
<P>
   For adults on Medicaid, the picture is similar _ except that
they bear some of the blame for their own suffering, and they have
even fewer options. Their Medicaid plans often include only very
partial dental coverage, sometimes of the ``pill and pull''
variety, which covers pain medication and extraction, but not
restorative work like fillings.
</P>
<P>
   The access problem seems most pronounced in rural areas and in
the inner cities. One recent day in Milwaukee, Opal Caples reached
the end of her tolerance. A mother of four covered by Medicaid
through the state welfare program, she had tried spraying her
abscessed teeth with Chloraseptic to ease the pain, and even with
perfume, following the advice of an acquaintance.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Caples began calling dentists' offices. One said the next
opening was in three months; another said it did not take walk-ins.
She called her health maintenance organization back, and it sent
her to Celestino Perez, whose practice is full of Medicaid
patients. Perez ended up pulling 10 of her teeth over three
appointments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Opal is not the worst case, no,'' Perez said. ``The worst case
I've seen was 28 teeth _ all at once.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent operating-room day for Afrow in Manchester, he
counted nine decayed teeth in the mouth of a 5-year-old boy whose
foster mother said he had been sleepless for weeks because of the
pain. Bent over the unconscious child, Afrow quickly fell into the
familiar rhythm he describes as ``fill one, seal one, pull one.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he worked on 2-year-old Bryana, who showed the signs of
``baby bottle decay'' caused by children's sleeping with bottles
containing milk or sweet liquids in their mouths.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Croto, Bryana's grandmother, who had recently gotten
custody of her, said that she knew to take Bryana to Afrow. His
Manchester Dental Alliance clinic at Catholic Medical Center in
Manchester is the dental equivalent of a community health center,
the only major one in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   But when Bryana's brother had tooth pain before she knew about
the clinic, Ms. Croto said: ``I called dentist after dentist after
dentist. It took forever to find a dentist for him. They all said
they didn't take Medicaid.''
</P>
</TEXT>
