<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9975 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEWIS-LAWYERS-BOS &LR;      06-25 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-LAWYERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE PRESSURE, LEWIS LAWYERS SAY THEY'LL SEEK RETRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- With the key claim in the Reggie Lewis medical
malpractice trial flickered out in a mistrial, the question now
becomes: Will a second panel of jurors be asked to settle the issue
that the first one could not?
</P>
<P>
   After nearly seven weeks of testimony and six days of jury
deliberations, 15 people -- a racially-mixed, mostly female panel
-- could not agree on whether Lewis's chief cardiologist, Gilbert
H. Mudge Jr., was negligent in his treatment of the Celtics star
before his 1993 death.
</P>
<P>
   While lawyers for Lewis's widow, Donna Harris-Lewis, are vowing
``to do it again,'' it's not at all clear whether the small New
York law firm hired by Harris-Lewis -- which has filed for
bankruptcy protection -- has the resources and the resolve to
continue the fight, particularly given that this jury was just four
votes shy of clearing Mudge.
</P>
<P>
   At least for now, and for the public, Harris-Lewis's lawyers are
promising to press on, announcing at a news conference Friday that
they are ``determined'' to retry the case in an ongoing ``search
for justice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Donna wants justice and Donna wants closure, and this is not
closure,'' said attorney Robert G. Harley. ``One day, Donna's
children may turn to her and say, `Did you do everything you could
about daddy's death?' and she wants to turn to them and say, `Yes,
I did.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Harley declined to provide a time frame for a retrial, but said
he also intends to appeal the verdicts in favor of Mudge's two
co-defendants, Drs. Peter L. Friedman and Mark A. Creager, who were
cleared of malpractice charges by the jury.
</P>
<P>
   Mudge's attorney, William J. Dailey Jr., did not return a phone
call Friday seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   But Friedman's lawyer, John P. Ryan, said he believes
Harris-Lewis and her attorneys are ``firm in their purpose to try
it again,'' although he hopes they change their minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe it would be unfortunate if the plaintiff and her
counsel did not keep an open mind to the prospect of not pursuing
this action further,'' he said. ``The emotional turmoil that
everyone endures in a case of this magnitude should give anyone
pause before they'd engage in it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, several local attorneys were surprised that
Harris-Lewis, who did not attend the news conference, would be
willing to endure the psychological toll of another trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Medical trials are traumatic,'' said James McCarthy, a Boston
malpractice attorney. ``There's so much emotion and tension, it's
almost like waiting for an execution.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, McCarthy doubts there will be a retrial, and
speculates that the threat of one is little more than a legal
strategy meant to encourage an out-of-court settlement.
</P>
<P>
   By publicly resolving to retry the case, Harris-Lewis and her
attorneys ``create the chemistry, hopefully, to settle the case,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mudge reportedly is covered by a $5 million malpractice
insurance policy, which could be used for a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Donna and her lawyers have to let Dr. Mudge and his insurance
carrier know she isn't going to go away, she's not discouraged, and
she will press forward,'' McCarthy said. ``She says she wants to
try the case again, but that, more or less, will put pressure on
the other side.''
</P>
<P>
   But given the split jury, Mudge and his attorney may or may not
be susceptible to that pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both sides have shown they have the ability to convince jurors
of their case,'' said McCarthy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the risk implicit in a retrial should lead to a
settlement, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I predict that this case will be settled,'' said McCarthy. ``I
don't think it will be immediately, but probably in many months,
probably on the brink of another trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan and Harley both declined to comment on the possibility of a
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all the speculation about settling the case, there are
others who believe that Mudge and his lawyer should take seriously
Harris-Lewis's vow to return to court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they'll retry it,'' said Boston malpractice attorney
Frederic N. Halstrom.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has the financial wherewithal to pay for the financial
experts all over again,'' he added, noting that Harris-Lewis
received the $9 million remaining in Lewis's five-year, $16.5
million contract when he died.
</P>
<P>
   And with Friedman and Creager out of the way, Halstrom said,
Harris-Lewis's attorneys may have a stronger case by focusing
solely on Mudge.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the next case, they're not going to fool around with the
other two doctors, so I don't think Mudge is any better position at
all,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
