A9979 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIVILWAR-CEREMONY26-C     06-25 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIVILWAR-CEREMONY26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Union soldiers get full military funeral
 &HT;    By Tucker McQueen
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A bugler played Taps and three women in Civil War-era
mourning dress laid flowers on the graves of three Union soldiers
who were honored Friday 135 years after they died.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony at Marietta National Cemetery ended a 17-year
search by Athens writer David Evans, who discovered the identities
of the men while writing a book about Gen. William T. Sherman's
calvary raids around Atlanta in 1864.
</P>
<P>
   ``These three restless souls can be at peace now,'' Evans said.
``They can no longer be counted among our country's unknown.''
</P>
<P>
   Until Friday, privates William Britt, James Harris and David
Sage were listed among 3,000 unknown Union soldiers buried at the
cemetery. With their identities revealed, they were given a proper
funeral with full military honors by the 21st Ohio Living History
group.
</P>
<P>
   Prayers, both Catholic and Protestant, were said and dirt from
the County Tipperary, Ireland, grave of Britt's parents was
scattered on his grave. Evans said he did not know why the
38-year-old Irish immigrant joined the Union army.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's ceremony validates Evan's quest to have the men
remembered by more than a set of numbers engraved on six-inch high
marble markers. He identified a fourth member of the 5th Iowa
Calvary, Capt. William Curl, two years ago and he was recognized in
a ceremony then.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd Findlay, the great grandson of Harris, and his wife Katie
traveled from Poplar Bluff, Mo., for the service.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're so glad to see him honored,'' Katie Findlay said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought someone had tossed his body somewhere after he died
and he would never be found.''
</P>
<P>
   After the war, the remains of Union soldiers killed in Georgia
and Alabama were recovered and brought back to the cemetery for
burial. Evans found an old burial register at the Marietta cemetery
that listed two casualties from Alabama on July 18, 1864. The
burial register didn't name the dead men, but a list of casualties
compiled by doctors on both sides after a skirmish at Beasley Tank,
40 miles east of Montgomery, included Sage and Harris as killed.
Britt was among seven listed as wounded. Lists from the surgeon at
the Confederate hospital and the Union cavalry's surgeon both
listed Britt dying from his wounds in the Confederate hospital Aug.
8.
</P>
<P>
   Evans strengthened his case by documenting the release of the
six other wounded men from the Confederate prison camp in
Andersonville after the war.
</P>
<P>
   Cemetery administrator Jim Wallace said he reviewed Evans'
research last fall and found it convincing. He said before a
tombstone is engraved with a name, the identity has to be proven
beyond a reasonable doubt. Because Sage and Harris fell the same
day, it is impossible to tell who is buried in which grave. Their
stones identify them as members of the 5th Iowa Calvary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even my wife asked me why I spent so much time on this,''
Evans said. ``These men became real to me. They became my boys, my
family.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
