<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-GENDER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT CITES GENDER BALANCE ON FEDERAL COURT   STAFFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM F. DOHERTY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Unlike a similar report 11 years ago that found
widespread gender bias in the state courts of Massachusetts, a
survey released Friday found that women are proportionately
represented at nearly all levels of the federal courts in
Massachusetts and three other New England states.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, a survey of 2,000 court employees, lawyers and
litigants suggested that more women are needed in the high-level
court positions and minorities remain underrepresented throughout
the federal court system in the region.
</P>
<P>
   And, despite strides, vestiges of sexism remain, with women
attorneys reporting that they are sometimes addressed as ``honey,''
assumed not to be lawyers, or acknowledged for the outfits they're
wearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``While our problems are not as great as other circuits, any
manifestation of discrimination, no matter how slight, is still too
much and we ought not to tolerate it,'' said federal Appeals Judge
Bruce M. Selya, who coordinated two task forces which conducted the
gender, race and ethnic bias study in the federal courts of
Massachusetts, New Hampshire, Maine, Rhode Island and Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   The report said that the majority of court workers and lawyers
who use the federal courts believe there is little gender or racial
bias and the courts have taken steps to ameliorate any that does
exist.
</P>
<P>
   The contrast between the upbeat federal survey, the first ever
done in the First Circuit, and the earlier damning Massachusetts
state court survey, may be due to the passage of time, Selya
suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``As time goes by, people become more enlightened on these
issues,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The most frequent complaints against federal judges in the
survey was their unwillingness to accommodate lawyers' schedules
and a failure to take lawyers' views seriously.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers also complained about incivility, mostly on the part
of other lawyers rather than judges.
</P>
<P>
   Saying that the lack of civility interferes with effective case
management, the report recommended a policy statement on attorney
conduct. In addition, the report recommended that each court adopt
a local rule governing biased behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Selya said incivility among lawyers was ``a huge problem'' that
was being addresses by several committees of the American Bar
Association. ``I suspect it is emblematic of society as a whole,''
he said. ``People aren't as polite as they as they used to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The report found that women represent a slim majority of both
attorney and law clerk positions in the federal courts and a large
majority of staff positions, including nearly half of all
management positions.
</P>
<P>
   However, women are underrepresented as heads of court units,
holding only seven of 25 positions.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, there were four female judges in the First Circuit,
including the Court of Appeals, the district, magistrate and
bankruptcy courts. By 1997, 12 of the 82 judgeships were held by
women, almost 15 percent. However, that is still below the national
average of nearly 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, there were two minority judges on federal courts in
Maine, Massachusetts, New Hampshire, and Rhode Island. By 1997, the
figure had increased to three of 66 judges, or 4.5 percent, still
more than 50 percent below the national average of nearly 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Only eight percent of federal court employees in Maine,
Massachusetts, New Hampshire and Rhode Island are minorities, a
figure the report blamed partly on the low minority populations in
states like Maine and New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Only two of 20 unit heads are minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Selya said he hopes the circuit judicial conference will adopt
the task force recommendations, which include educational and
sensitivity programs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
