<DOCNO> NYT19990625.0289 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9983 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WALKER-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-25 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWIS'S LEGACY ALREADY SECURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIAN WALKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The unsanctioned monuments continue to pop up without
warning, walls adorned with images of the Celtics' Reggie Lewis in
full flight. Alive.
</P>
<P>
   They are more than the inspired doodlings of street artists;
they are the depiction of the continuing grief and shock caused by
Lewis's death at 27, a sort of people's tribute.
</P>
<P>
   They are one version of Reggie Lewis's legacy. Another, more
official, interpretation failed to emerge from the malpractice
trial that ended Thursday with no conclusion other than sadness.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of withering public criticism, Donna Harris-Lewis
has always maintained that this trial was never about money, and it
wasn't. It really wasn't about medical malpractice, either. It was
about heroes, about whom we worship and why.
</P>
<P>
   Three days before jury selection began, Harris-Lewis said the
catalyst for her suit was not her husband's death but rather Dr.
Gilbert H. Mudge Jr.'s allegation that Lewis had confided cocaine
use to him shortly before his death.
</P>
<P>
   Despite assertions that a pattern of drug use would be revealed
at trial, the actual evidence turned out to be scant. Job Fuchs,
the 82-year-old retired health director at Northeastern University,
Lewis's alma mater, was expected to testify that Lewis tested
positive for cocaine in 1987 while playing for the school. Instead,
in the space of ten minutes on the witness stand, Fuchs testified
both that Lewis had and that he had not tested positive. So
confused was his testimony that Judge Thayer Fremont-Smith ordered
jurors to disregard it.
</P>
<P>
   Harris-Lewis's lawyers didn't have to shoot holes in the
deposition given by Wayne Brown, who claimed to have snorted
cocaine with Lewis during their Northeastern days. He did that
himself, admitting that he was high during most of the time he was
testifying about. Brown did not actually appear on the stand, in
what would seem an uncharacteristically shrewd move.
</P>
<P>
   A third defense witness, Ronald J. Marks, a recovering addict,
testified that he saw Lewis snorting an unspecified white powder in
a bathroom during a Celtics' charity auction. Legal analysts have
said they doubt the cocaine evidence influenced the outcome of the
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Until I met Harris-Lewis for the first time shortly before the
case went to court, I was almost prepared to believe that this
lawsuit was an exercise in unbridled greed, a grab for more money
by someone who was already worth millions.
</P>
<P>
   In person, my cynicism evaporated. Her passion was obvious. Her
conviction that her family had been wronged, that her husband could
have survived his heart condition, was powerful. She considered it
her duty to her children to absolve her husband of allegations of
drug use.
</P>
<P>
   She has done that. And while it may be legally correct to say
there was no verdict, that technicality is hardly the whole story.
The finding was that her case did not clear the high bar that
proves medical malpractice. Given the painstaking preparation that
went into this case _ it is reputed to be the most expensive
malpractice case in Massachusetts history _ it's hard to see why
Harris-Lewis would fare better in another trial.
</P>
<P>
   Her lawyers, Bridget Assaro and Robert G. Harley, said Friday
they expect a second trial in a matter of ``weeks or months, not
years.'' They said Harris-Lewis, who was secluded at home with her
family, will not stop until she believes justice is done. I hope
she reconsiders and accepts the partial victory she has already
achieved.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people who found it easy to believe that a young black
athlete was a cocaine user thought this trial was a slam dunk for
Mudge. They were wrong. But there is more to winning a malpractice
trial than simply prevailing on one issue.
</P>
<P>
   For thousands, Lewis was a hero, not only for his play on the
basketball court, but for the way he conducted himself off the
court _ his tireless work for youth, his unassuming demeanor and
gentle manner. For those people, I believe, neither this trial nor
any succeeding trial will shake that faith.
</P>
<P>
   To those invested in believing the worst, they will continue to
do so, lack of evidence be damned. Neither group took any solace
from what happened, and neither were any minds changed.
</P>
<P>
   Reggie Lewis was a basketball player, plain and simple. He
surely did not lead a perfect life, any more than do any of the
rest of us. But his legacy does not depend on perfection. The
people Reggie Lewis cared about most have had their say on the
meaning of his life. And that verdict _ secure from critics,
doubters or juries _ is the only one worth fighting for.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Adrian Walker can be reached by e-mail at Walker(at)Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-99 2008EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
