A9985 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-SUIT26-COX     06-25 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-SUIT26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Judge seals Coke documents
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The federal judge overseeing the race discrimination
case against Coca-Cola Inc. has ruled that personnel information
about individual employees and any documents that, if disclosed,
may put the company at a competitive disadvantage will remain from
public view.
</P>
<P>
   In an order signed Wednesday in U.S. District Court in Atlanta,
Judge Richard Story defined what will constitute ``confidential
information'' during the litigation and be kept secret.
</P>
<P>
   Story said his protective order will expedite pretrial discovery
_ the period when both sides exchange information to build their
cases. He said the order also represents the ``least-onerous
alternative for balancing the public's access to its judicial
process with the specific, legitimate interests of the litigants
and other affected persons.''
</P>
<P>
   The four black plaintiffs in the lawsuit allege discrimination
in pay, promotion, performance evaluations and terminations. They
are seeking class-action status for their case. Coca-Cola has
strongly denied the accusations and wants the judge to block the
class-action effort.
</P>
<P>
   Story's ruling does not restrict information that Coca-Cola must
provide to the plaintiffs and their attorneys during the discovery
phase, which could last into next year. It affects what can be made
public.
</P>
<P>
   In his six-page order, Story said confidential information will
include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Business information that could cause ``a financial hardship''
or would place the producer of the information ``at a competitive
disadvantage and could include, for example, trade secrets,
manufacturing processes, customer lists, technical or research
information and internal financial information.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Individual employee information, including the contents of
personnel files, medical records, complaints of discrimination in
which an employee is identified and documents describing an
employee's compensation, promotion, employment history,
disciplinary action or termination.
</P>
<P>
   These restrictions do not appear to include Coca-Cola documents
that outline company employee practices, internal documents that
may criticize or applaud the company's hiring and firing of
minority employees, or conclusions reached by experts who examine
the Coca-Cola's employee computer database.
</P>
<P>
   But if any restricted information is included in a court motion
or is discussed in a transcript of pretrial testimony, this must be
deleted before being placed in the public court file, Story ruled.
Undeleted versions will go to the judge and be kept confidential by
the parties, the judge said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's fair,'' Coca-Cola spokesman Rob Baskin said of
Story's order. ``It restricts individual salaries and personnel
information from being public. We think that's appropriate in a
case like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Cyrus Mehri, an attorney for the African-American
plaintiffs, ``We believe that court secrecy should be limited to
narrowly defined areas, such as trade secrets and individual
personal information.''
</P>
<P>
   In his ruling, Story said either party can designate parts of
the information that they think must be kept confidential ``so long
as the party who seeks confidentiality has a good faith belief that
it is entitled to confidentiality under the terms of this order.''
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs in the case are administrative assistant Motisola
Malikha Abdallah, security officer Gregory Allen Clark, consumer
information specialist Linda Ingram and former director Kimberly
Gray Orton.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
