   Story's ruling does not restrict information that Coca-Cola must
provide to the plaintiffs and their attorneys during the discovery
phase, which could last into next year. It affects what can be made
public.
</P>
<P>
   In his six-page order, Story said confidential information will
include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Business information that could cause ``a financial hardship''
or would place the producer of the information ``at a competitive
disadvantage and could include, for example, trade secrets,
manufacturing processes, customer lists, technical or research
information and internal financial information.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Individual employee information, including the contents of
personnel files, medical records, complaints of discrimination in
which an employee is identified and documents describing an
employee's compensation, promotion, employment history,
disciplinary action or termination.
</P>
<P>
   These restrictions do not appear to include Coca-Cola documents
that outline company employee practices, internal documents that
may criticize or applaud the company's hiring and firing of
minority employees, or conclusions reached by experts who examine
the Coca-Cola's employee computer database.
</P>
<P>
   But if any restricted information is included in a court motion
or is discussed in a transcript of pretrial testimony, this must be
deleted before being placed in the public court file, Story ruled.
Undeleted versions will go to the judge and be kept confidential by
the parties, the judge said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's fair,'' Coca-Cola spokesman Rob Baskin said of
Story's order. ``It restricts individual salaries and personnel
information from being public. We think that's appropriate in a
