<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9990 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON26-COX     06-25 1230
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON CALLS FOR 'SEASON OF PROGRESS' ON ISSUES
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton asked the Republican-controlled
Congress on Friday to set aside partisan politics for ``a season of
progress'' on a host of domestic issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be judged on what we do with this opportunity, whether
we seize it or squander it,'' Clinton declared.
</P>
<P>
   The president used a speech at Georgetown University and a
lengthy news conference at the White House _ his first since March
19 _ to focus attention on issues that have eclipsed this year by
his impeachment trial and the NATO bombing campaign in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that ``obviously, the closer you get to the
election, perhaps the more difficult it will be'' to enact major
legislation, Clinton vowed to ``keep working right up to the very
end'' of his term in January 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be plenty of time for politics in the year and a
half ahead, but this summer must be a season of progress,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Prominent on his list of priorities were Medicare, Social
Security, gun control, education and campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   But with the 2000 presidential election already heating up, and
his wife considering a bid for the U.S. Senate from New York,
Clinton inevitably faced questions about whether his personal
behavior would be a political liability, especially for Vice
President Al Gore, the Democratic presidential front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   ``All elections are about the future, and all candidates are
judged on their own merits,'' he said. ``I think that the American
people know the country is in good shape.''
</P>
<P>
   He defended Hillary Rodham Clinton's use of Air Force planes for
travel to New York state as she weighs a Senate campaign, saying
the Secret Service requires her to fly on government planes.
</P>
<P>
   And although he insisted that the first lady still has not made
a final decision on whether to run for the Senate, he boosted her
senatorial prospects by praising her efforts on domestic policy.
</P>
<P>
   The president's dual appearances marked a new phase in the
partisan battle with Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Clinton's morning speech, House Republicans held a
morning rally at the Capitol in an effort to steal his relations
thunder.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert of Illinois told reporters that the
GOP has ``the best agenda for the American people.'' He promised
the GOP-led Congress would focus its energy on a national missile
defense, education reform, Social Security and, most prominently,
tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ask the president: please include tax relief in your
agenda,'' Hastert said.
</P>
<P>
   At his press conference, Clinton responded: ``I'm not against
tax cuts.'' But, he added, ``The question is, what kind of tax cut?
Who benefits from it? How should it be designed? And how should it
be handled to guarantee that we're going to take care of first
things first _ strengthening Social Security and Medicare, paying
down the debt, continuing to secure the health of the American
economy?''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton appeared relaxed and upbeat during the unusually long
75-minute news conference, occasionally joking with reporters as he
fielded 27 questions on a variety of subjects.
</P>
<P>
   The president said he plans next week to unveil a plan for
Medicare that would extend prescription drug coverage to elderly
Americans. ``I don't think there's any alternative here,'' he said,
noting that prescription drug coverage is ``the most significant
health care need that senior citizens have today.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he sought to delay the election-year politics that are
quickly overtaking legislative action in Congress, the president
continued assailing the Republicans for failing to enact a bill to
require background checks on purchases at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't expect young people to stand up to violence when
Congress won't stand up to the gun lobby,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton acknowledged that Americans are ``worried'' that ``the
fabric of life (is) still under great strain,'' as evidenced by the
``shattering effect'' of this spring's high school shootings in
Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the events of the past year _ his impeachment and
admitted sexual liaison with former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky _ placed him at a disadvantage when it comes to pressing
moral issues, Clinton said he had acknowledged that what he did was
``dead wrong'' and that he is going to spend ``the rest of my life
trying to rectify that.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he is more comfortable taking personal
responsibility for his actions, as opposed to those who ``go around
trying to give a lot of speeches about how good they are and then
open the door for the gun lobby to run the Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton tried to refocus public attention on his
domestic agenda, questions about Kosovo, Chinese espionage and
peace in Ireland were among the issues raised at the news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he is ``not particularly surprised'' that ethnic
Albanians are taking revenge on Serbs upon returning to their homes
in Kosovo, but said NATO is ``doing what we can'' to stop the
violence as refugees return home.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the Serbian people would have to ``come to grips''
with the atrocities Yugoslavian leader Slobodan Milosevic ordered
in Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to have to decide if they think that is okay,''
he said. ``And if they think it's okay, they can make that
decision, but I wouldn't give them one red cent for reconstruction
if they think it's okay because ... I don't think that's the world
we're trying to build for our children.''
</P>
<P>
   When a questioner asked about the $5 million U.S. reward offered
for the arrest of Milosevic and colleagues for alleged war crimes,
Clinton locked his gaze and said, ``We have not put a price on Mr.
Milosevic's head for someone to kill him. ... So let's get that
clear.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his biggest surprises during the NATO bombing of
Yugoslavia were that NATO did not lose any pilots and that the
Chinese Embassy was accidentally bombed. ``I was surprised and
heartbroken,'' he said of the embassy bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Despite investigations revealing lax security at U.S. nuclear
labs, Clinton gave Energy Secretary Bill Richardson a vote of
confidence. Richardson is ``being very, very aggressive'' in
tightening up security at the labs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He urged all sides to break the deadlock in the Northern Ireland
peace agreement and meet a crucial deadline next week for
implementing the accord.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who played a major part in securing the Good Friday
peace accord last year, said he would do whatever he could to help
the parties save the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   About his own critics at home _ ``particularly the right wing''
_ the president said he cannot allow them to distract him from the
nation's business. He said he tells his staff: ``We have no right
to harbor anger'' that would interfere with the obligation to serve
the public.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also promised that his long-delayed report on race would
be published soon. ``I want to make sure that when we put this
document out it is in the form of a book which can be useful and
have something to say, and move the conversation and the efforts
beyond where we were in the presidential initiative on race,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
