u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EMBASSY-AFRICA-NYT &LR;      06-25 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMBASSY-AFRICA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
6 U.S. EMBASSIES IN AFRICA CLOSED TEMPORARILY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Gambia, Madagascar, Namibia, Senegal, Liberia, Togo, Kenya
and Tanzania . )   By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Several U.S. and British embassies in Africa
remained shut Friday in response to evidence that they might be
under surveillance by terrorist groups planning an attack, Clinton
administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Both countries closed their embassies temporarily in Gambia,
Madagascar and Namibia. The United States also closed its embassies
in Liberia and Togo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had information suggesting suspicious individuals were
surveying the sites,'' said James Rubin, the State Department
spokesman, ``and as a precautionary, prudent measure, we suspended
operations.''
</P>
<P>
   The department said that all operations had been suspended at
the embassies.
</P>
<P>
   The only employees on duty are U.S. Marine guards, the
department said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, intelligence officials said there was
evidence that Osama bin Laden was making final preparations for
another attack on U.S. installations. Bin Laden, a Saudi exile, has
been indicted in the United States as the mastermind of the
bombings of the U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania last summer.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and British officials said suspicious individuals had been
seen carrying out surveillance of embassy compounds in Africa in
recent days, but the officials would not say if they believed them
to be associates of bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Rubin said Friday that ``we have seen a pattern of
activity indicating continued planning for terrorist attacks by
members of Osama bin Laden's network, and we take reporting of such
threats seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the embassy bombings last Aug. 7, the United States has
closed a number of embassies around the world _ often in Africa _
for short times in response to reports of terrorist threats.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department said that the six U.S. embassies closed on
Thursday would remain shuttered through Sunday, and that a decision
would be made during the weekend whether they would reopen on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin insisted that terrorists were not having an impact on U.S.
foreign policy. ``We have foiled their objective of stopping our
determination to have an American presence around the world and to
interfere with our determination as a global power to have American
troop presence in various countries,'' he said. ``So they have
failed.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added, ``That doesn't mean we don't have to adjust our
practices, that we don't have to spend more money to protect our
people, and we are determined to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   In London a spokesman for the British Foreign Office said it had
closed its diplomatic missions in Africa because ``we have
information of a possible threat to diplomatic missions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are taking the threat seriously and have taken the
precautionary measure of temporarily closing our missions in these
countries,'' the spokesman said, adding that diplomatic staff
members were not being evacuated, because ``the possible threat is
to diplomatic missions, not to British nationals.''
</P>
<P>
   He declined to say if the closings of the British embassies had
been coordinated with Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're aware of the closure of U.S. missions in a number of
African countries,'' he said, ``and we do maintain close contacts
with the Americans on security matters. But we never comment on any
security or intelligence matter.''
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press quoted a spokesman for Gambia's Foreign
Ministry, Cherno Jallow, as saying his government had not seen the
need for additional security measures in its capital, Banjul.
</P>
<P>
   ``The temporary closure is warranted by external factors _ that
is, the Americans' fear that bin Laden is planning to mount
terrorist attacks on U.S. installations in the Gambia,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
