A9996 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-DIARY-$ADV27-NYT &LR;      06-25 0350
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-DIARY-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON SURVEYS, RESEARCH AND NEW PRODUCTS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 27) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ohio)   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Birthday Greetings To the Bar Code &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Do you remember where you were on June 26, 1974?
</P>
<P>
   As memorable anniversaries go, it probably doesn't stick in most
minds like Nov. 22 (1963) or July 20 (1969) or, for really long
memories, Dec. 17 (1903 _ think Kitty Hawk).
</P>
<P>
   But 25 years ago Saturday, at the Marsh Supermarket in Troy,
Ohio, the very first product _ a pack of Wrigley's Juicy Fruit gum
_ was swept across the very first checkout scanner, and shopping
would never be the same.
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe that's a bit of an exaggeration, since it had long
been obvious what was coming. There were pen-type bar code readers
in use at that time, and the idea of putting standardized bar codes
on products dates from a grocery-industry initiative in the late
1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was the advent of scanners at the supermarket checkout
that injected the technology into popular consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   NCR, the company whose scanner it was that fine June day in
Ohio, has had a rocky time of it since then, passing in and out of
ownership by AT&AMP;T and in and out of the PC industry, among other
travails.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, though, it stuck with point-of-service systems
(you know, cash registers), and it now estimates that its scanners
ring up 1.4 billion items a day.
</P>
<P>
   (The company is also a big player in another
pocketbook-transforming technology, the automated teller machine.
It likes to say it is in ``the business of translating transactions
into relationships.'')
</P>
<P>
   Bar codes have since penetrated all corners of modern life,
helping to keep track of everything from freight cars to blood
samples to carry-on baggage. Cattle are branded with them. A few
years back, a millenarian cult even handed out fliers warning of a
nefarious government plot to tattoo them on everyone's forehead.
How the authorities would get people to rub their foreheads across
checkout counters, the fliers didn't say. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Patrick J. Lyons &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-99 2015EDT &QL; 
