u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-EXPAND-ATLANTA-BO     06-25 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-EXPAND-ATLANTA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS RETAIN TALLAS, LOSE ROBITAILLE IN EXPANSION DRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Rob Tallas went nowhere. Peter Ferraro went to
Atlanta, but was back before he knew it. Randy Robitaille, who
opened the Stanley Cup playoffs as the Bruins' substitute
first-line center, Friday became a charter member of the expansion
Atlanta Thrashers.
</P>
<P>
   So went the 1999 expansion draft from the Bruins' perspective.
In order to avoid losing the gregarious and reliable Tallas, their
primary backup to Byron Dafoe, Boston gave up the 23-year-old
Robitaille, who collected 24 goals and 102 points with Providence
this past season as the AHL's No. 2 point-getter.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never want to give up a player you think can help you,''
said Bruins assistant general manager Mike O'Connell. ``We looked
at what we had at the position, and the fact that, for us, Randy
Robitaille has to be a first- or second-line player.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's selections, which took GM Don Waddell only some five
minutes to announce at the FleetCenter, provided the NHL's 28th
club few scorers. If Robitaille can show anywhere near the kind of
pop he had in both the AHL and earlier in college (Miami-Ohio), the
Thrashers might have maneuvered for a viable scoring force.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins, in turn, may have dealt one away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it would have been nice to play for Boston, the
club that gave me my first opportunity in the NHL,'' said
Robitaille, signed out of college as a free agent March 27, 1997.
``But if you look at their center position, they're pretty well set
up the middle. It's not like Jason Allison or Joe Thornton are on
the brink of retirement. Maybe there's room there for a checking
center or a fourth-line guy in the middle, but that's not my
role.''
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille's window of opportunity here in the Hub of hockey was
about the size of Liechtenstein. Prior to 1998-'99, he was given
limited ice time in five games and was unable to produce a point.
He picked up only a pair of assists in four regular-season games
and then got one chance in the postseason, moving to the pivot in
Game 1 vs. Carolina when Thornton was sidelined with an injured
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Working between Sergei Samsonov and Dmitri Khristich in the
playoff opener, Robitialle looked out of synch, constantly behind
the play. The following morning, he was back on a plane to
Providence, where in the next six weeks he helped lead the Baby B's
to the Calder Cup championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can understand why they got rid of me,'' said Robitaille,
who finished second only to Rochester's Dominic Pittis (38-66_104)
in AHL scoring. ``There's really no room for me. I can't fault
them, but I thought I had done a pretty good job at the minor
league level.''
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille was on the Bruins' protected list, which was
submitted to the league within 48 hours after the Stars clinched
the Stanley Cup Saturday night in Buffalo. When it became clear the
Thrashers were going to take Tallas, O'Connell began negotiating
with Atlanta GM Don Waddell. Waddell agreed to pass on Tallas and
take Ferraro, provided the Bruins in turn would make a
Robitaille-for-Ferraro swap.
</P>
<P>
   As the night played out, the Thrashers contined to work more
deals. Their biggest move was sending netminder Trevor Kidd, whom
they selected from the Hurricanes, to the Florida Panthers for a
package that included former Bruin Gord Murphy, originally acquired
by the Panthers in the '93 expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   The Thrashers also picked up the free agent rights to veteran
defenseman Ulf Samuelsson, who finished the season with the Wings
after being dealt from the Rangers. The Wings didn't want to lose
veteran center Igor Larionov and agreed to give up Samuelsson if
the Thrashers selected someone else. Atlanta took netminder Norm
Maracle, the 24-year-old backup to Chris Osgood. Samuelsson is an
unrestricted free agent. If he signs anywhere other than Atlanta,
the Thrashers will receive a compensatory pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough decision,'' said Waddell, asked about passing
up the chance to select Larionov, who many suspect one day will be
a head coach in the NHL. ``He has one of the best minds of any
player I've ever met. We talked at length about taking him, but we
just felt, for an expansion club, he wasn't the right player for us
at this time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
