u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CISNEROS-HEARING-HNS &LR;      06-25 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CISNEROS-HEARING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYER SAYS EX-MISTRESS REJECTED CISNEROS SETTLEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A lawyer testified in federal court Friday that
Linda Jones rejected a $30,000 settlement he brokered with former
Housing Secretary Henry Cisneros following the collapse of their
extramarital affair.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer, Pat Maloney, was one of three witnesses who
contradicted testimony from Jones in a pre-trial hearing to
determine if her taped telephone conversations with Cisneros can be
used by the government when Cisneros goes on trial Sept. 7 for
alleged conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   The San Antonio lawyer said he told Jones, also known by her
married name, Linda Medlar, that she had weak legal standing
against Cisneros at the end of the affair because his promises of
financial support were verbal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The legal vineyards were sparse, indeed,'' Maloney told U.S.
District Judge Stanley Sporkin.
</P>
<P>
   She then rejected the settlement Maloney had arranged, although
it was accepted by Cisneros through his lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, 50, denied earlier this week that Maloney had dismissed
her chances of winning a breach of contract lawsuit against
Cisneros, and she denied receiving a letter from the lawyer saying
he would not proceed with legal action.
</P>
<P>
   Maloney, though, recalled her being upset with his assessment
that her case was weak.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Marine Corps, we tried to avoid the language she
used,'' Maloney said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones later sued Cisneros for breach of contract. It was during
proceedings in that lawsuit, which was later settled for $49,000,
that Cisneros and his attorney learned that she had secretly taped
their telephone conversations.
</P>
<P>
   The recordings are the guts of Independent Counsel David
Barrett's case against Cisneros, 52, who is charged with
orchestrating a conspiracy to conceal $250,000 in hush money he
paid Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Jackowski, a prosecutor for the independent counsel, said
Cisneros paid for Jones' silence to protect his nomination to the
Department of Housing and Urban Development, where he was secretary
from 1993 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
   He is currently the president of the Spanish-language television
network Univision in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' lies to the special prosecutor landed her in the Carswell
Federal Medical Center in Fort Worth where she is serving a
42-month sentence for bank fraud, money laundering and obstruction
of justice.
</P>
<P>
   She agreed to testify against Cisneros in exchange for a
reduction in her sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Jones has testified she underwent detoxification for
prescription drugs and received counseling for depression after she
was in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors are seeking to suppress Jones' psychiatric and
medical records, which they say defense lawyers should not have
received under subpoena from prison officials.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors contend Jones did not waive her right to release the
information.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Bureau of Prisons has opened an internal
investigation to determine whether policy and privacy rights were
violated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The matter has been referred and is currently under
investigation by the Federal Bureau of Prisons,'' said Scott
Wolfson, a spokesman in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who spent four days testifying about the tapes, admitted
she altered and edited 88 recordings to bolster her civil lawsuit
against Cisneros. Jones also said the editing was done on the
advice and with the knowledge of two Bruce Magness and Floyd Holder
of Lubbock, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But Holder contradicted that testimony, saying he never knew of
the editing and had not instructed her to alter the recordings and
lie about it under oath to the court.
</P>
<P>
   Holder said he had advised Jones and Magness against sending
Cisneros a letter demanding settlement in the case. Holder argued
that such a demand could be construed as blackmail or extortion.
</P>
<P>
   But he also told the court that Magness had become
``infatuated'' with Jones, whom he had called a ``Marilyn Monroe
look-alike.''
</P>
<P>
   Holder said that at the time Magness took the case, he had filed
for bankruptcy protection and was ``down on his luck.''
</P>
<P>
   Magness thought the lawsuit would generate a settlement from
Cisneros, and represented a potential bonanza with publishing and
television opportunities, according to Holder.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thought it was his retirement check,'' Holder said of
Magness.
</P>
<P>
   Magness is expected to testify when the hearing resumes on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Another Lubbock lawyer, Michael Carper, said he declined to file
a civil lawsuit for Jones in 1990 when she came to him with tapes
she said were ``very embarrassing'' to Cisneros.
</P>
<P>
   Although Jones testified she never spoke with Carper, he said
she came to his office to solicit his help. He said he declined to
pursue the case against Cisneros, which he called ``nothing short
of a shakedown.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
