u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-DRAFT-BRUINS-BOS &LR;      06-25 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DRAFT-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALLAS NOT GOING ANYWHERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The suspense is over _ goalie Rob Tallas is staying in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins made a deal to ensure that the Atlanta Thrashers
would bypass Tallas in Friday's expansion draft held Friday at the
FleetCenter. In return, the NHL's newest franchise selected Peter
Ferraro, and the Bruins then sent center Randy Robitaille to the
Thrashers for Ferraro.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried not to put too much pressure on myself and not react
until it happened,'' said Tallas, who received a call from his
agent, Jay Fee, some 10 minutes after the proceedings ended.
``Right now I'm excited. I can finally let go of this deep breath
I've been holding. I know now I'm going to have a lot easier
summer.''
</P>
<P>
   It makes for an easier draft for the Bruins Saturday.
President/general manager Harry Sinden said the club was worried
about its depth at goaltender and they would have had to make a
deal for a backup. Most of the available candidates are overpaid
thirtysomethings who don't fit in with the Bruins' youth movement.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins select at No. 21 in the first round, and Friday,
assistant GM Mike O'Connell said the club was exploring the option
of moving up or down.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible that in addition to swapping draft picks, the team
could work another kind of deal, perhaps packaging forward Dmitri
Khristich and a draft pick for an established forward to play with
Jason Allison and Sergei Samsonov.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some discussions with a number of teams regarding
either moving down or moving back,'' said O'Connell. ``When it gets
to around our pick or before, it's really one of the first drafts
in a while where there's no clear-cut No. 1, 2, or 3. There are
some question marks. I think when it gets to the 10th pick, we'll
have an idea if we want to move forward if it's still available to
us. When it gets down to around the 15th or 16th pick, we'll have
an idea if we want to move back. There are a few scenarios but how
it plays out, we don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell said they were very happy to be able to keep Tallas,
who is a restricted free agent this summer. As good a season as
John Grahame had in Providence last year, leading the team to the
Calder Cup championship, it's not known if he's ready to make the
next step.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like Robbie and we like what he's done for us,'' said
O'Connell. ``He's a terrific, terrific kid. We look for him to play
as many games as he did last year or more. Our goaltending on both
sides of Robbie is very strong, with Byron (Dafoe) and with John
Grahame. We didn't want to have to go out and find another
goalie.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden said the club's biggest concern is at forward. The team
plans to load up on them Saturday. But he said that could also
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot of good prospects, I mean, if you've got three
or four you've got a lot,'' said Sinden. ``With (defenseman)
Jonathan Girard (in junior hockey) and Bobby Allen at BC and
Mattias Timander and Kyle McLaren and Hal Gill, we're pretty good
on defense. That's if both Girard and Allen make it. We think they
will, but you don't know. So, I think if we can find ourselves a
good centerman, we'd be better off to do that. Having said that,
when it comes to your pick, all of sudden there's a defenseman
there and he's much better than the forward available, so you end
up taking the defenseman.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden said there might be more diamonds in the rough later in
the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they're telling me is whether we were 14th or 28th, it
wouldn't make any difference,'' said Sinden. ``What we're going to
get at 21, we wouldn't get any better at 14, either. Some of the
best choices may be made in the better rounds. Not better players,
but to get a guy in the third round who makes it, there might be a
better opportunity to have it happen this year than in other
years.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Bruins had Steve Heinze rated at No. 15. They
wound up getting him at No. 60 in 1988. Sinden said an even more
dramatic example was Stan Jonathan. In 1975, the Bruins took him
86th overall with their fifth choice. Sinden said he was beating
the drum for them to take him with their second, third, and fourth
picks but he wound up listening to his scouts. ``They took me to
see him play and he was just what I thought we needed, it looked
like the fans would love him,'' said Sinden. ``He was pugnacious
and really fit the times in the '70s with the type of team we had.
We got to the third round and I wanted to take him and (then-head
scout) Gary Darling said, `No, he'll be there.' I said, `If you
guys lose him by waiting, I'm going to lose you.' But they were
right. For some reason, they knew other clubs weren't that high on
him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
