<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUCENT-NEXABIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUCENT BUYS DATA-SWITCHING DEVELOPER FOR $900 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lucent Technologies Inc., the world's leading maker of telephone
equipment, Friday agreed to pay nearly $900 million in stock for
privately-held Nexabit Networks Inc., a developer of high-speed
switches for moving data traffic on telecommunications networks.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase ended a brief bidding war for Nexabit, whose
technology is coveted for its ability to route data swiftly over
the Internet. Analysts said Nexabit will enable Lucent to better
compete against Cisco Systems Inc., which controls the market.
Lucent was reported to have offered between $600 million and $800
million for Nexabit earlier this week, a deal that was rejected by
Mukesh Chatter, Nexabit's founder and chief executive. Chatter
maintained that the company, which has no revenue, was worth more,
prompting the final $900 million price. Analysts predict the
company could have sales of $100 million under Lucent ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Chatter formed the Marlborough, Mass. company in 1997 and
received early funding from individual investors led by Ray Stata,
founder and chairman of Analog Devices Inc. of Norwood, Mass. He
developed a device called a terabit router _ literally, a router
that can move more than one trillion bits of data per second, or 25
times the speed of current equipment _ that is being evaluated by
several companies including Frontier Corp., the fifth-largest
long-distance company and by Road Runner, the second-largest
supplier of high-speed Internet access over cable lines.
</P>
<P>
   The announced acquisition came on the same day that Juniper
Networks Inc., a Nexabit rival whose early investors included
Lucent, launched one of the more spectacular initial public
offerings among telecommunications companies. Juniper stock soared
from its $34 initial offering price to $105 on the first trade
before closing at 98 7/8, a gain of 64 7/8. At day's end, the
Mountain View, Calif. company, had a market capitalization of $4.88
billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope to get a couple of paydays like Nexabit and Juniper''
chuckled John McQuillan, whose McQuillan Ventures in Concord, Mass.
was an early investor in Avici Systems Inc. of Tewsksbury, Mass.,
another Nexabit competitor. ``This deal with Nexabit strengthens
Lucent's hand in selling against Cisco because they can now offer a
broad array of products and services to telephone carriers.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement with Nexabit, Lucent will issue about 14
million shares for Nexabit, which last summer received $25 million
in financing from Hambecht &AMP; Quist, Fidelity Ventures, and Vulcan
Ventures, a venture capital firm owned by Paul Allen, co-founder of
Microsoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Lucent's closing price Friday of 63 11/16, the Nexabit
purchase was worth $891.63 million.
</P>
<P>
   The hefty price tags for Nexabit and Juniper are due to industry
expectations that vast amounts of new equipment will be needed to
manage the spiraling demand for data traffic over the networks of
telephone companies and Internet service providers.
</P>
<P>
   To insure that trillions of bytes of data are routed quickly and
reliably, the major telephone carrier are looking for the next
generation of equipment from big companies like Cisco, Lucent, and
Nortel, as well as from smaller companies like Juniper, and several
new companies developing high-speed routers such as Avici and
Ironbridge Networks Inc. of Lexington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   They are all after an emerging market of Internet-based routers
and switches that is expected to soar to $5.5 billion in 2003 from
$169 million this year, according to Ryan Hankin and Kenty, a San
Francisco-based market research firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Building the next telephone company infrastruture means
producing high-speed equipment that rarely fails and can still work
in the event of earthquakes,'' said Anthony Lavia, Ironbridge
president and chief executive, whose 120-employee company recently
received $33 million in venture financing to develop its own
terabit router.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
