A0013 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-WATCH-ART-$ADV     06-25 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-WATCH-ART-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WANT TO BUY A STOCK MARKET? 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 27)  
 (af)  
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On its face, it's hard to imagine a less appealing
investment: the No. 2 company in a cyclical, capital-intensive
business, rapidly losing market share to newer, more nimble
competitors not subject to its strict federal regulation.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it could become one of the most intriguing investment
opportunities of the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   The company is the NASDAQ Stock Market. At its board meeting
next month, NASDAQ's parent, the National Association of Securities
Dealers, will consider a proposal to issue NASDAQ stock to some of
the 6,000 brokerage firms that make up the association and the
5,000 companies whose stocks are traded there. Later, NASDAQ shares
might be sold to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our thinking is to open up our stock markets to investment
from participants and eventually the public, so they can
participate in our growth and financial success and so we can raise
the needed funds to grow and continue to modernize,'' Frank G.
Zarb, the NASD chairman, said last week.
</P>
<P>
   The precedent comes from Down Under. In October, the Australian
Stock Exchange converted from mutual ownership to a publicly traded
company. Its shares have since risen 135 percent, six times the
gain in the All Ordinaries, the bellwether Australian index.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Stock Exchange has also considered public
ownership. But the tectonic shifts taking place in the financial
markets worldwide have put particular pressure on NASDAQ. Two years
ago, the implementation of new rules for handling orders for NASDAQ
trades _ a result of the settlement of the government's charges of
collusion among NASDAQ dealers _ gave rise to a growing number of
electronic trading systems.
</P>
<P>
   Those private, for-profit electronic systems used inexpensive
technology to take away a significant share of NASDAQ's trading
volume. Seeing their advantages, big Wall Street firms began to
invest in the fledgling electronic markets. Suddenly, the interests
of the NASDAQ Stock Market and the brokerage firms that make up the
NASD diverged.
</P>
<P>
   Realigning those interests, therefore, is what is leading NASDAQ
down the path toward an initial public offering. And by offering
shares to traded companies, NASDAQ would have an incentive for new
listings, and for its current listings to stay put.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of a NASDAQ IPO has generated excitement, much of which
can be traced to the financial reward that attaches itself to those
three magic letters. But will that make NASDAQ a good investment?
</P>
<P>
   It could, if NASDAQ uses the proceeds to improve its technology,
pay for vigorous oversight and forge greater links with overseas
markets. That will keep it ahead of competitors, whose ranks,
history shows, are likely to thin.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1850, there were 250 stock exchanges in the United
States,'' said Frank E. Baxter, chairman of Jefferies Group, the
brokerage firm, and head of the NASDAQ committee studying the
public offering proposal. ``We're in a small bubble where they're
proliferating, but that goes against all of history.''
</P>
<P>
   NASDAQ recognizes, however, that it probably has a fairly small
window in which to act. Baxter adds, ``I would say there is a mood
of urgency.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-99 2023EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990625.0306 </DOCNO>
