u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RDP-ART-2TAKES     06-25 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RDP-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLOOD OF REFUGEES STRAINS POLICING POWER OF NATO PEACEKEEPERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(rm) 
 By   CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA Yugoslavia _ Refugees are flocking back to Kosovo,
which has been increasingly plagued by deaths and violence, leading
the top NATO commander to call for international police to keep
order in the province.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO is doing all that it can to grip the situation on the
ground. We're very much aware of the challenges in an environment
in which whatever authority there was has departed and new
structures and institutions must be formed,'' Gen. Wesley Clark
told Reuters in an interview in which he called for an acceleration
of plans to bring in U.N. police. A force of 3,000 is planned, but
it is expected to take three months for the full force to arrive. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some 48,000 refugees crossed into Kosovo Thursday alone, Paula
Ghedini, spokeswoman for the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees
said Friday. Some 300,000 of nearly 1 million Albanian refugees
have returned since NATO intervened two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the one of the largest spontaneous returns of refugees
we have seen in 25 years,'' Ms. Ghedini said at a news conference.
The Albanian border town of Kukes, once choked with over 100,000
refugees, is already empty, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The flood of refugees is placing enormous pressure on the
peacekeeping force, which in the absence of any civilian law
enforcement agencies is having to perform policing duties along
with military duties.
</P>
<P>
   In village after village, as Albanians have returned to their
homes, Serbs have fled, and houses have burned and looted.
</P>
<P>
   There have been 16 civilian deaths in Kosovo in the last 36
hours, one of which occurred when U.S. Marines of the 26th
Expeditionary Unit shot and killed a civilian in Gniljane Friday
when their unit came under fire from the former Serbian police
headquarters. No American soldiers were injured.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton addressed the issue of violence, particularly
that by returning Albanians against Serbs, in a news conference
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO is not letting it happen,'' he said. ``We're doing what
we can to stop it, and I'm concerned about it.'' He added, ``I'm
not particularly surprised, after what they've been through,''
referring to the Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   NATO troops were out in evident force on the streets and in the
suburbs of the provincial capital Friday, after a night of looting
and killing that shook the residents of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Gen. Richard Dannatt, a British officer here, said, ``We
are aiming to provide a secure environment and will hold the fort
until the U.N. can take over.''
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Michael Jackson, the commander of the NATO peacekeeping
force in Kosovo, KFOR, meanwhile, went to calm some 200 local Serbs
who gathered to protest the violence in the Serb suburb of Kosovo
Polje.
</P>
<P>
   Together with Sergio Vieira de Mello, the special representative
of the U.N. secretary general in Kosovo, Jackson pledged to protect
all the citizens of Kosovo equally and urged the Serbs not to flee
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that you are concerned and worried,'' said Jackson,
speaking to the crowd from the steps of the Orthodox church in
Kosovo Polje.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have now 22,000 soldiers in Kosovo. In one month, I will
have double that number. Every day more are coming in, and you will
soon start to see a police force in Kosovo. Every day the security
forces of KFOR are becoming stronger,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His words brought unhappy murmurs from the crowd and a few
grumbles of ``occupiers'' from the more disconsolate. But the
majority were hanging on the general's words, desperate for some
assurance of security after several highly publicized slayings of
ethnic Serbs in the city in the last two days.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   One woman, a medical worker who only gave her first name,
Marica, said she had fled to the town of Nis in Serbia, but then
returned after hearing the general give a similar speech last week.
``I understand English; I heard Jackson say he would make it
safe,'' she explained. ``But it is not safe, KFOR is doing nothing
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The British police refused to release details of the murders
they had recorded, but said they had been at the scenes of the 14
killings that occurred in their sector in the 24 hours prior to the
morning press briefing.
</P>
<P>
   In the morgue of the city hospital, Nexhmi Kameri, an Albanian
medical technician, mournfully turned the pages of his register. He
had admitted 16 bodies in the last 24 hours he said, five of them
newborn babies who had died on delivery. The others were all men,
almost equally split between Serbs and Albanians. He estimated that
11 had been killed. ``With both hot and cold weapons,'' he said.
``It's horrible to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Looters and car thieves are taking advantage of the vacuum of
law enforcement. NATO military police have recorded 196 serious
crimes over the last two weeks and have started filling the
prisons, left empty by the Serbian police when they evacuated.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The clashes are expected to get worse as the ranks of returning
refugees swell. Refugees were on the move from camps in the south
of Albania, from Montenegro and from Turkey. They will require
food, medicine and shelter, because thousands will return to find
their houses burned. Ms. Ghedini cited just one settlement near Pec
in western Kosovo, where 150 returning refugee families had been
found living in their cars or in the open.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The British said that in their sector they are trying to contain
the violence without excess force. ``We have a society in shock,
that has lost its infrastructure, and suffered greatly. We have to
be firm but fair,'' said Dannatt at a press briefing. ``We have had
a number of murders reported, it all stems from tensions between
Albanians and Serbs,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He avoided a question on whether the force was considering
shooting looters and answered with the question: ``Would you shoot
looters here?'' The police were, however, increasing spot checks
around town and conducting extensive patrolling, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Albanians and Serbs alike are nervous; the Albanians of robbery
and looting, &UR;  &LR; the Serbs of murders that they feel are designed to
terrorize them into leaving the province.
</P>
<P>
   In Kosovo Polje, they said, they felt they were on a knife edge,
poised to flee at any moment. They had gathered to try to make a
joint decision on what to do, some in the crowd said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are asking KFOR to protect us because in two or three days
it will not be possible to talk to these people anymore, they will
be gone and there will only be Albanians,'' Momcilo Trajkovic, a
moderate Serb politician and leader of the Serbian Resistance
Movement, told the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``But those who go from here will lose everything, their houses
and families,'' he said. He urged people to find the courage to
stay. ``Our biggest task is to stay here, maybe we will have
casualties, but we have to stay in our houses and on our land. Our
place is not in Serbia, but here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
