<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990625.0308 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0019 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-CAMERAS-NYT     06-25 0445
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-CAMERAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIA'S HIDDEN CAMERAS CAN VIOLATE WORKPLACE PRIVACY, COURT RULES
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The California Supreme Court has ruled that journalists' use of
hidden cameras in a workplace can be an invasion of privacy,
upholding a verdict against ABC News over a story about telephone
psychics.
</P>
<P>
   The unanimous opinion, announced on Thursday, reversed a 1997
appeals court ruling that had overturned a $1.2 million jury
verdict award to Mark Sanders, an employee of a company that sold
telephone psychic readings.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders' conversations with an ABC employee posing as a
co-worker were videotaped and broadcast in a 1993 ``PrimeTime
Live'' report, purporting to show that the psychics did not take
their jobs seriously and were cheating gullible callers paying
$3.95 a minute to get advice.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court had ruled that because his conversations could
have been overheard by other employees, Sanders' privacy had not
been violated. But the state Supreme Court ruled that ``in an
office of other workplace to which the general public does not have
unfettered access, employees may enjoy a limited but legitimate''
right to expect that private conversations with co-workers will not
be secretly videotaped and broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   The case was returned to the appeals court for any decision on
damages. The state Supreme Court said that for a plaintiff to win
damages, the invasion of privacy would have to be ``highly
offensive to a reasonable person.'' But the court said it ``took no
view on the offensiveness or inoffensiveness of defendants'
conduct'' in Sanders' case.
</P>
<P>
   The court also said its ruling did not mean it was always
illegal for news organizations to record events secretly in places
of work.
</P>
<P>
   Television news executives have often argued that the use of
secret cameras can sometimes be the only way to expose malfeasance.
The California court indirectly noted this, saying that a news
organization could defend itself against liability by using the
offensiveness standard to argue that the privacy infringement
committed was ``justified by the legitimate motive of gathering
news.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC, a subsidiary of Walt Disney Co., said it was considering an
appeal of the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   But Neville Johnson, a Los Angeles lawyer who has brought
several suits against news organizations over the use of hidden
cameras, said the ruling had ``firmly established the right to
privacy in the workplace,'' at least in a workplace not open to the
general public.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be different if you taped workers in a 7-Eleven or a
department store, for example,'' Johnson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
