<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BRIEFS-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PEOPLE AND PERSONALITIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 27) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   40 Years of Wheeling, Dealing and Mealing &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first word Thursday night at New York's Four Seasons, which
was celebrating 160 seasons as the setting of as many transactions
as the stock exchange floor, came from the architect Philip
Johnson, about why the restaurant and his design for it had
survived.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have good management and good food; all I could do was
give them the background,'' he said on the way in. Johnson,
regularly found at a Grill Room (not Pool Room _ more on this
later) corner table for lunch, soon agreed that he was too modest.
``Of course, I had something to do with it. I'm quite a good
architect.''
</P>
<P>
   The next words came from Steven T. Florio, chief of Conde Nast,
and Marvin R. Shanken, owner of Cigar Aficionado and Wine Spectator
magazines, both recalling Christmas staff lunches there so fondly
that a writer who was listening all but asked them for a job.
</P>
<P>
   Tina Brown, the founder of Talk Media, gamely described some of
her company's efforts to meld books, movies and a magazine, by
saying, ``Synergy is a guy in the next office with the same
tastes.''
</P>
<P>
   After further words from movie stars, politicians and business
leaders like Ronald O. Perelman, Ellen Barkin, Barry Diller, Bruce
Wasserstein, Steven Rattner, David N. Dinkins, Edward I. Koch,
Bianca Jagger, Jonathan M. Tisch and Henry R. Kravis, came one more
word, from Graydon Carter, Vanity Fair editor and a co-host, with
Edgar Bronfman Jr. Carter, his gray crest bobbing above the Grill
Room crowd, recalled his Time magazine farewell lunch in 1983 _
$1,000 for four, on an expense account. ``We were so young we
thought the Pool Room was hot,'' he said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Shoe on the Other Foot &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dennis D. Dammerman, the longtime General Electric finance chief
who recently became chief executive of the relentlessly profitable
GE Capital Services unit, has a no-nonsense, tough-guy reputation.
</P>
<P>
   But on Thursday in a talk at the Japan Society in Manhattan, he
took pains to speak warmly about Japan, its economic reforms and
its companies, in which GE Capital has invested about $14 billion
lately.
</P>
<P>
   When a Japanese reporter dared to ask, though, whether rising
unemployment there was spurring nationalistic resentment toward
companies like GE that are going on shopping sprees, it was the
rougher Dammerman who responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, my Manhattan office is in 30 Rockefeller Plaza,'' he shot
back, calling to mind the 1989 purchase of the building by the
Mitsubishi Estate Co. as a flush Japan collected trophy properties
across America. ``There was a little resentment here, too.''
(``Thirty Rock'' returned to American hands in 1996.)
</P>
<P>
   Dammerman's more measured response was that he did not expect an
anti-American backlash among Japanese consumers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jim Schachter &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now They Both Feel Good &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Papa's got a brand new moneybag. For a concert Saturday night in
New York, James Brown, the Godfather of Soul, had plans to welcome
on stage David Pullman, whose Pullman Group investment firm raised
about $30 million for Brown by issuing bonds based on future
royalties. Besides becoming the Underwriter of Soul, Pullman has
sold bonds for David Bowie and Ashford &AMP; Simpson. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Name Is a Name Is a Name &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Bruce Berkowitz, chief financial officer for Gotham Capital
Management, a Manhattan-based hedge fund, was arrested last week on
charges of defrauding his company of up to $5 million, another
investment fund manager and firm suffered, too.
</P>
<P>
   David P. Berkowitz, co-founder of the $550 million Gotham
Partners fund, also in Manhattan, heard plenty from worried
investors and managers of companies in their portfolio _ including
Jonas P. Lee, chief executive of Giftcertificates.com. Lee got a
phone call at 2 a.m. from a friend warning him that his lead
investor was in deep trouble, then checked the news on line to
discover that it was someone else's trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Ackman, the other co-founder of Gotham Partners, and
Berkowitz have sent letters to his investors, who include the Ziff
family, saying that it was the (italics)other(end italics) Gotham
and the (italics)other(end italics) Berkowitz.
</P>
<P>
   Gotham Partners' Berkowitz has also suffered from confusion with
another David Berkowitz, the serial killer known as Son of Sam,
whose name is again making headlines with the coming release of the
Spike Lee movie ``Summer of Sam.''
</P>
</TEXT>
