A0022 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRADE-BLOCKS-NYT &LR;      06-25 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRADE-BLOCKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPEAN, LATIN AMERICAN TRADING BLOCS MEET 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil _ In an effort to increase trade and gain
a counterweight to American global economic dominance, leaders of
the world's second- and third-largest trading blocs are to meet
here this weekend and early next week in a first-ever Latin
American-European Summit that has already proved contentious on
several basic issues.
</P>
<P>
   The gathering will bring together heads of state from 33 Latin
American and Caribbean countries and their counterparts from the 15
nations of the European Union. The centerpiece of the meeting is
the prospect for negotiations for a free-trade agreement between
the European Union and MERCOSUR, the six-nation South American
bloc.
</P>
<P>
   With a population of more than 200 million and a combined
economy of more than $1 trillion a year, MERCOSUR is the largest
trading bloc after the North American Free Trade Agreement group,
composed of the United States, Canada and Mexico, and the European
Union. MERCOSUR's full members are Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and
Uruguay. Bolivia and Chile are associate members.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are really going to be two meetings going on, one with
all of Latin America and the Caribbean present, which will be
largely rhetorical,'' said Helio Jaguaribe of the Institute for
Political and Social Studies, a research group here. ``But there
will also be a meeting within the meeting between Europe and
MERCOSUR, where the real business will take place.''
</P>
<P>
   For Latin America, the conference offers a rare opportunity to
gain concessions from the United States and Europe by playing them
off against each other.
</P>
<P>
   At the December 1994 Summit of the Americas in Miami, the United
States and 32 Latin American and Caribbean nations agreed to
establish a Free Trade Area of the Americas and set 2005 as a
deadline. But that process has stalled, and many nations in the
region have shifted their focus to reaching agreements among
themselves and with European and Asian nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the Brazilian point of view, we are not putting too much
pressure on the hemispheric free-trade area idea,'' Fernando
Henrique Cardoso, the president of Brazil, said in a recent
interview.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the European-Latin American summit meeting emerged
from a visit to Brazil in 1997 by Jacques Chirac, the president of
France. The notion was endorsed by Brazil and its MERCOSUR
partners, who see stronger ties to Europe as offering the only
possible counterweight to the United States' historical hegemony.
</P>
<P>
   But as talks for an agenda for the conference advanced, France
has proved to be the main obstacle to beginning formal negotiations
aimed at a free-trade pact. The MERCOSUR group wants nothing
excluded, while the French, fearing that a flood of meat, grain,
sugar and even wine from MERCOSUR would ruin its heavily subsidized
farmers, have been insisting that agriculture be excluded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Europe has to make a decision,'' Cardoso said. ``If it really
believes that it has a role to play, it has to take into account
that the interests of other parts of the world include
agriculture.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Europe insists on its current agricultural policies, he
said, ``Well, then we always have the Free Trade Area of the
Americas.''
</P>
<P>
   The French position has been resisted both by Germany, the
European Union's biggest member, and Portugal and Spain, which have
built on their historical linguistic and cultural ties to become,
along with Britain and Italy, large investors in the region.
``Europe must understand that it is strategic for its global
position to deepen relations with MERCOSUR,'' Portugal's prime
minister, Antonio Guterres, said recently.
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting in Luxembourg on Monday, the European Union agreed
to grant its delegations here the power to authorize formal talks.
MERCOSUR officials said that step was no guarantee that there would
be success here.
</P>
<P>
   Had Europe failed to grant that authority, it would have created
``a very awkward, very difficult, incomprehensible situation,''
Manuel Marin, a Spaniard who is the European Union's top expert in
Latin American affairs, told reporters. ``I can't propose marriage
and then 20 days before the wedding say, `I don't like you,''' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   There has also been some disagreement about a timetable for
negotiations. The Latin Americans are eager to begin talks
immediately and want to set a deadline of 2005 to coincide with the
schedule of the hemispheric free-trade talks, while the French have
been suggesting a delay.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the United States, the best thing that could happen would
be a postponement'' of talks between Europe and MERCOSUR, said
Gilberto Dupas, coordinator of the International Affairs division
of the Institute for Advanced Studies at the University of Sao
Paulo. ``The tracks are already being laid for the Free Trade Area
of the Americas, and once you have that in place, it is easy for
the locomotive to start moving.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
