<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT IS QUITE EVIDENT LEWIS USED DRUGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- When we thought it was all over, Donna Harris-Lewis
said she had proven that her husband, Reggie, did not do drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Pardon me.
</P>
<P>
   Three people, none of whom knew each other, all testified under
oath in either pre-trial depositions or in court that they were
present and ``doing'' drugs with Reggie Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   One, Wayne Brown, a classmate of Lewis's at Northeastern, said
he not only did cocaine with Reggie, but also provided it to him.
Harris-Lewis later labeled Brown a loser.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Lebeaux, who worked for the Celtics when Lewis was on the
team, said in his deposition that he did marijuana with Lewis and
two women.
</P>
<P>
   Businessman Ronald J. Marks said he witnessed Lewis sniffing a
``shiny white powdered substance'' in a public restroom at a Saugus
pizza parlor. Lewis was a Celtic at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Losers? I don't think so. I give them all the credit in the
world for standing up under the toughest of circumstances, with
absolutely nothing to gain, to tell the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Who in their right mind would be willing to testify to being
involved with drugs?
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, most business professionals or athletes who may
have been caught up in the cocaine vogue of the '80s and early '90s
have that behind them today. They've moved on to have families and
potentially rewarding careers. They are reluctant to admit today to
any unlawful activities in their past.''
</P>
<P>
   That statement comes from Bob Long, former Massachusetts State
Police detective and president of LCF Associates of Braintree, the
investigative firm working with attorney William Dailey on the
Lewis litigation. ``It is very difficult to get people to come
forward in any type of drug investigation,'' said Long, who
declined any further comment because this Lewis farce may have
another day in court.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was last Sunday morning. The setting was beautiful. A
sun-filled Nantucket morning, sitting under a tent enjoying
breakfast just yards from the harbor.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcaster Bob Lobel was speaking openly of his personal
frustration in this matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the most frustrating thing I have had to deal with in
all of my years in television,'' said Lobel, who has been one hell
of a reporter for WBZ over the years. ``You know what the truth is.
You talk to people who were there with Reggie. Did that (cocaine)
with him. They tell you all about it, and when you ask them to come
forward, they fold on you. They don't want to get involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had one guy, a friend of mine, a top guy, very successful,
who was there when Reggie was doing it, but he wouldn't come
forward. I told him we'd put him in a disguise. Or we would put him
behind a screen where you would just see his shadow, and hear his
voice, but not see him. He still wouldn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Only God knows if cocaine killed Reggie Lewis, but only a fool
would think that sometime in his life he didn't use drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Reggie was a happy-go-lucky, easygoing guy. He was easy to meet
and easy to like. There is no reason for anyone to make up stories
about him, or reporters to want to work on stories about this case.
</P>
<P>
   To date, some of the luckiest guys in the world are Lewis's
former Celtic teammates, who came within a whisker of being brought
into this case to have their own use of drugs, and partying with
women, put on public record.
</P>
<P>
   There was this one chilling line from a former Celtics' wife
(off the record, of course) telling someone, ``In our house,
cocaine flowed as freely as wine.'' She is no longer married to the
player and couldn't be induced to come forward to expose the secret
lives of several players from that era.
</P>
<P>
   There was a female ``groupie'' from this era, who was part of
the drug/sex scene, now married with children. Her family does not
know of her past. She fainted when asked to testify.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I have written from the beginning that, at minimum, this is a
$17 million fraud. When Reggie Lewis filled out an insurance form
that covered his contract, he was asked if he had ``ever'' done
marijuana, cocaine, etc. He answered no. There is substantial
evidence that that answer was a lie, which makes it a fraud. The
Equitable Life Insurance Co. can now open the case and reclaim $5
million from the Celtics. We will see how the officers of that
company respond, on behalf of their stockholders, who were
defrauded.
</P>
<P>
   The other insurance companies can't get their $12 million back
from Donna Harris-Lewis. The two-year statute of limitations has
run out on the money, and even though it now appears to have been
fraudulently obtained, does not have to be returned. That's one law
our great legislators should rewrite. How could they ever put into
law something that says if you can deceive the insurance company
and survive two years, you can keep the money? Ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This week, I spent some time with Boston College athletic
director Gene DeFilippo. On Tuesday, he asked how I thought the
case was going to come out. I said two doctors would be not guilty,
Dr. Mudge would get a hung jury. Not bad, huh?
</P>
<P>
   Let me tell you why. I'm a realist. When I saw the makeup of the
jury, I thought I knew the answer. For either side to win, it had
to get 13 of 15 votes. That, in my mind, wasn't going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   The other two doctors never should have been brought into this.
The judge said as much at the halfway mark, but said he would let
them stay in the trial because he didn't want that to be used as a
reason for an appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Here's my take on Mudge. Nice guy. Terrific doctor. Wanted to do
all he could for Lewis. Tried to make it look like he could play
again, even though the Celtics had already told Lewis that he
wouldn't be playing for them the next season. Lewis isn't dead
because of Mudge.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Donna Harris-Lewis has said this case was not about the money.
She wanted to prove that Reggie didn't do drugs. She said after the
trial that she proved Reggie didn't do drugs. But her attorney
said, ``We'll be back to do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   She has just tied up a Massachusetts courtroom _ and the lives
of many people _ for eight weeks at the cost of hundreds of
thousands. She will still need to get 13 of 15 votes if she goes
through it again, and hopefully, enough jurors on the next case
will have the courage to do what enough of these jurors did _ find
Mudge not negligent.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, many of his former teammates can continue to sweat
bullets. And many who knew Reggie's other life, who were on the
verge of stepping forward, will have enough character and courage
to do so the next time around.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, some alleged experts said there would probably
be a settlement rather than another trial. If I were Mudge, I
wouldn't give Harris-Lewis anything. She said it wasn't about the
money, and as long as some people are still willing to speak up and
tell the truth, she'll never get 13 of 15 votes, either.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
