<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following for
clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of Saturday, June
26, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please call Veronica
Villarreal at (206) 448-8342.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBLICANS (Seattle) An interview with Gov. Frank Keating of
Oklahoma, chair of the Republican Governors Conference, and former
Gov. Roy Romer of Colorado, general chairman of the Democratic
National Committee. Topics include why George W. Bush is so
popular, why congressional Republicans are so unpopular, the
importance of the West Coast in the 2000 election.
</P>
<P>
   By Joel Connelly. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   KILLER-TRAIN (Undated) _ The suspected serial killer wanted in
connection with eight slayings committed near railroad tracks
reportedly once lived in the Pike Place neighborhood of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   By Kimberly A.C. Wilson. (Story will move in the ``a''
category.)
</P>
<P>
   KALAKALA-MICROBE (Seattle) _ They knew the ferry Kalakala was
historic. And they knew it was a rust bucket. What they didn't know
was that the old boat rescued from the Alaska mud was really a
giant petri dish growing a new strain of oil-eating bacteria. The
microbe, found in the old boat's bilge gunk, has been tentatively
been named for the vessel: pseudomonas Kalakala 98. Now being
studied by a local bio-tech firm, the life form could take a bigger
bite out of nasty oil spills.
</P>
<P>
   By Mike Barber. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BUDDHIST-TEMPLE (Seattle) _ Ceremonies opening the largest Thai
Buddhist temple in the United States will be Friday, with
worshipers coming from across the country and overseas. The 47,000
square foot structure took seven years to build, essentially by a
three-man construction crew.
</P>
<P>
   By John Iwasaki. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-MACHINISTS (Seattle) _ The International Association of
Machinists and Boeing kick off negotiations for a new contract on
Tuesday and both sides hope history doesn't repeat itself. Union
leaders will hand their demands to Boeing executives at a ceremony
in Wichita, Kansas. The last time the two groups met at the
bargaining table, in 1995, the machinists wound up striking for 69
days, crippling production.
</P>
<P>
   By Paul Nyhan. (Story has moved in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   CELLULAR-DEALMAKERS (Seattle) _ When you're a small cellular
service provider using the least popular technology in America,
just trying harder may not be good enough. So John Stanton,
chairman and chief executive of Bellevue's VoiceStream Wireless
Corp., and Doug Smith, his counterpart at Omnipoint Corp. of
Bethesda, Md., decided to join forces. Wednesday night they created
a merged entity with assets of $9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   By Dan Richman. (Story has moved in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-ANDERSEN (Seattle) _ He nailed us. Professional satirist
Kurt Andersen came to town to chronicle, in novel form, Seattle and
its fellow outposts on the raw frontier of the new techno-economy
as the 21st century dawns. And he did his job exceptionally well in
his book, ``Turn of the Century.''
</P>
<P>
   By Bill Virgin. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-MARINER (Seattle) _ Seattle hosts the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   By Tyler Kepner. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-MARINERS-NOTEBOOK (Seattle) _ Notebook items from Friday's
against Texas. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-FINALS (New York) _ Game 5 of the NBA Finals, San Antonio at
New York. By Ron Tillery. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
