<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPBELL-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPBELL WARNS OF LOWER EARNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SHOLNN FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Acknowledging more trouble in its soup business, Campbell Soup
Co. said Friday that it would not meet analysts' earnings
expectations for this quarter and that it planned to reorganize its
soup operations.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell warned that its earnings for the fiscal quarter ending
July 31 would be 8 cents to 10 cents a share below the consensus
estimate of 38 cents a share from analysts surveyed by First Call
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell also said that it planned to combine its Canadian
business with its U.S. soup and sauce operations to create a North
American division.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the reorganization, Mark Leckie, the president of the
Campbell's domestic soup division, will leave the company. He will
be succeeded by F. Martin Thrasher, the company's president of
European and Canadian operations who has worked at Campbell 11
years. Thrasher headed the soup division from 1992 to early 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the company said it would make unspecified cuts to
save $18 million to $25 million a year. The action could result in
an after-tax charge as high as $45 million in the current fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, based in Camden, N.J., attributed its the earnings
problem to reduced soup purchases from grocery stores. One reason,
analysts said, was that Campbell had discontinued its traditional
end-of-quarter promotional discounts on soups. Grocers used to buy
large quantities during the sale and warehouse them, but now they
were reducing their inventories. Campbell expects shipments to drop
10 percent in the final quarter.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the company announced a similar earnings decline
because of the same problem.
</P>
<P>
   The stock was down 50 cents, closing at $41.9375; it has fallen
25 percent the last six months, while the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index has risen 7.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Leckie, who headed the company's domestic soup operations _
three-quarters of the company _ was brought on less than a year and
a half ago to turn around the soup business, which has changed
leaders repeatedly in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to wonder if leading the soup business is such a
difficult problem _ is it the person or is it the business
itself?'' said Eric Katzman, a food industry analyst at Merrill
Lynch. ``To once again change the head of the soup business, seems
to suggest other problems in the health of that business going
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Other industry analysts also said they saw Campbell's long-term
goal of growing the domestic soup business 3 to 4 percent as too
ambitious. Campbell already dominates three-quarters of the
domestic market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Campbell's expectations that led Wall Street to
unrealistic earnings expectations,'' said Nomi Ghez, an analyst for
Goldman, Sachs. ``The company has been trying to stimulate growth.
They've been trying very hard with new products and product line
extensions. The problem is that the category is already big, and
Campbell already dominates, so it's hard to increase market
share.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Buckley, Campbell's spokesman, said the company would
continue to innovate its soup products. In the fall, the company
will begin to sell ready-to-serve tomato soup in a plastic package,
as well as a soup-to-go product in a bowl that can be used in
microwaves, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Friday, Campbell's chief executive, Dale
Morrison, acknowledged that the company had had a challenging year.
In January, the company announced a plan to reduce inefficiencies
on its manufacturing side that would save about $150 million a
year, starting in its fiscal year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Morrison predicted the company would regain earnings momentum
next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
