<HEADER>
A0029 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-KERNEY26-     06-25 0385
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-KERNEY26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons sign first-round choice for $5.6 million
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Patrick Kerney's dream of getting paid to play
lacrosse officially died Friday. After signing a five-year contract
worth $5.6 million, however, the Falcons' first-round draft choice
is smiling all the way to the bank.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-5, 269-pound defensive end, who went to the
University of Virginia on a lacrosse scholarship and then walked on
the football team, got a signing bonus of $1.52 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of it will go straight into savings . . . but I've got a
new house at Lake Lanier, and I guess maybe I'll buy a boat,'' he
said. ``The Major Indoor Lacrosse League is paying a lot better
these days, but probably not enough to take summers off and go play
for the Philadelphia Wings.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerney is the fifth first-round choice to sign an NFL contract,
and his deal set in motion a flurry of signings. Atlanta signed
four other draft choices, including tight end Reggie Kelly, the
team's second-rounder.
</P>
<P>
   Both starting defensive ends, Chuck Smith and Lester Archambeau,
are entering the final year of their contracts, and one of them
might not be re-signed. Kerney, though, said he has no plans to
wait until next year to break out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel an urgency to compete this year,'' he said. ``The
players at this level are all bigger, faster and stronger, but I
want to make plays this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The other first-rounders to sign are Cleveland quarterback Tim
Couch, the No. 1 pick, New Orleans running back Ricky Williams, the
No. 5 pick, St. Louis wide receiver Torry Holt, the No. 6 pick, and
Green Bay defensive back Antwan Edwards, the No. 25 pick.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons considered themselves fortunate when Kerney was
still available at the No. 30 spot in the April draft.
</P>
<P>
   He blossomed late, and was projected to go as high as the No. 20
spot after a senior season in which he had 14 sacks and 21 tackles
for a loss.
</P>
<P>
   All scouting reports on Kerney speak of his ``big motor,'' good
quickness and above-average football intelligence. He has worked at
both end spots in passing camp but generally has been projected to
back up Smith at right end.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
