<HEADER>
A0031 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-DEAF26-COX     06-25 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-DEAF26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Signs of the cross
 &HT;    By Steve Gushee
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ They sing the praises of the Lord in
sublime silence.
</P>
<P>
   Their hands become a symphony of movement, making a glad but
silent shout to the Lord.
</P>
<P>
   This congregation sings hymns in sign language at the First
Baptist Deaf Church. They meet in a small, windowless chapel in a
building on the campus of the First Baptist Church in West Palm
Beach, which sponsors them.
</P>
<P>
   But their obvious joy only partly masks the multiple
difficulties of living in a hearing world.
</P>
<P>
   A deaf man watches the song leader sign words. He mimics the
movements as his hearing wife listens to music piped over the sound
system.
</P>
<P>
   A woman who is both deaf and blind gently places her hand on the
moving hand of a deaf friend signing the song. That way, Eleanor
Clay can feel the joy and the promise she can neither hear nor see.
</P>
<P>
   The church _ the only known deaf church in South Florida _ is
all the family she knows.
</P>
<P>
   The 50 members of this little community care for each other
under the watchful eyes of their deaf pastor, the Rev. Jeff
Jackson, 31, the only full-time deaf Baptist minister in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seen God's hand leading us to do this,'' said the Rev.
Keith Thomas, senior pastor of First Baptist Church. ``Pastor
Jackson is an extraordinary leader in this ministry. He's
passionate about what God has called him to do in the deaf
community. He is a relentless servant.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson understands, as hearing clergy might not, the silent,
trying world of the deaf.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge of forever communicating in the shorthand of sign
language, trying to embrace, silently, a world filled with sound
can be exhausting. Most deaf people have limited, if any, speech
ability. Frustration is a constant companion.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a deaf couple will go to a restaurant without
reservations and not get a table. They drive across town to visit
friends and, upon arrival, are told the time is not convenient. The
obvious solution is impossible for them. They cannot call ahead,
Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   He recalls trying to order a meal at a McDonald's restaurant
using his hands to communicate. The startled server gave him a
Braille menu.
</P>
<P>
   The variety of relationships in the deaf world tend to
complicate things further. Hearing and deaf partners fall in love
and marry. Deaf children are born to hearing parents, hearing
children to deaf parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to be patient,'' Jackson said through an interpreter.
``I try to show the right attitude. I try to do it by example.''
</P>
<P>
   Most people in both the deaf and hearing worlds are unaware that
Sunday is the first day of Deaf/Blind Awareness Week observed
annually in honor of Helen Keller's birthday on June 27.
</P>
<P>
   The Deaf Service Center, a nonprofit United Way agency in West
Palm Beach, does serve the deaf and hearing impaired.
</P>
<P>
   The center offers classes, support and access to the growing
telecommunications technology designed for the deaf.
</P>
<P>
   A few Christian and Jewish congregations interpret hearing
services with sign language. Some have modest programs to engage
and support the deaf.
</P>
<P>
   But few faith communities have tackled the complex problems of
working with a people who cannot easily communicate with the
majority population.
</P>
<P>
   Language preserves and promotes so much of what it means to be
human that the deaf, with a unique language, easily become a unique
and isolated community.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are a culture, a people group, unto themselves. They are
not just deaf,'' said Caroline Partin, Jackson's secretary and an
interpreter at the church. ``The biggest problem is getting the
church to recognize the needs of the deaf community.''
</P>
<P>
   Partin, 40, is an example of the complexity of the deaf world.
She is a hearing child of deaf parents and grandparents. She has a
hearing brother, but her cousins were deaf. She grew up in West
Palm Beach, married a deaf man and has four hearing children.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're buried,'' Partin said of hearing youngsters in deaf
families. ``We isolate ourselves. We don't want to be associated
with the deaf community. I want to change that.''
</P>
<P>
   She is trying to do that at First Baptist where there are 18
hearing children of deaf parents. They moved easily between the
hearing and the deaf church, she said. Two deaf children are part
of the church's hearing preschool, which meets twice a week.
</P>
<P>
   The church has interpreted services for the deaf for many years
but realized that ministry was inadequate. First Baptist hired
Jackson two years ago to develop a full-service deaf church.
</P>
<P>
   Partin is Jackson's colleague and interpreter for worship, at
hospitals, in homes, meetings, at weddings, funerals and baptisms.
</P>
<P>
   The church sponsors a deaf basketball team for young men in
their 20s. The men have a 13-1 record playing in a hearing league
at Palm Beach Atlantic College in West Palm Beach. Jackson is the
playing coach.
</P>
<P>
   More than 40 deaf supporters showed up for a game Tuesday to
cheer _ with their hands. The team won.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the pastor who makes the difference among the deaf.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson coaches sports, teaches the Bible and supports his
silent flock.
</P>
<P>
   He moves easily among his people at worship, offering a pastoral
prayer in American Sign Language, signing Scripture and preaching
sermons with his hands. Partin interprets in English.
</P>
<P>
   Relaxed, enjoying himself and clearly comfortable with both the
word of God and God's deaf people, Jackson's silent signing of the
sermon speaks volumes.
</P>
<P>
   ``A deaf pastor is much better than a hearing minister,'' said
Alcides Monroig, 30, through an interpreter. Monroig is a deaf
member from West Palm Beach married to Laura, a hearing woman.
``Hearing pastors talk too fast. Deaf pastors share by
interacting.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was born in Gainesville, deaf but not Baptist. He grew
up attending the Church of God of Anderson, Ind., and the
Presbyterian church. He read lips to get along, not knowing sign
language.
</P>
<P>
   He attended a school for the deaf in St. Louis and went to
Bakersfield College in California. He learned sign language there
and began to attend the Deaf Fellowship Chapel at the First
Southern Baptist Church in Bakersfield, where there was a deaf
pastor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understood the Word of God for the first time because of
sign language,'' he said. ``I gave my life to Christ in 1989.''
</P>
<P>
   The next year, he joined a group of deaf Christians riding
bicycles from California to South Carolina. They stopped at
churches along the way to offer the gospel according to the deaf.
He was ordained at the Bakersfield chapel in 1995 and served there
until he came to West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   He and Partin work together in parallel and vastly different
cultures, trying to enable each to understand and embrace the
other.
</P>
<P>
   Partin, speaking and signing at the same time, explains their
passion:
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in what I do. I want to be a bridge _ connecting two
worlds.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
