</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990625.0317 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0032 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-XGAMES26-COX     06-25 1279
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-XGAMES26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    X Games getting extreme exposure
 &HT;    By Israel Gutierrez
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The face in the advertisement may not be
the most recognizable, but it does make a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen-year-old Tara Hamilton is famous enough to be
photographed in her wet suit wearing a pair of Oakley sunglasses.
However, what better displays her popularity is the man in the
Oakley ad a couple of feet away.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all the Sunglass Huts in all the malls, there's a big
picture of me and one of Mark McGwire,'' Hamilton said. ``So that's
pretty cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, a Lantana native, is an X Gamer. More specifically,
she is a wakeboarder.
</P>
<P>
   The X Games, an annual Olympic-style event for extreme sports,
began its fifth run Friday, and continues through July 3 in San
Francisco. And as evidenced by Hamilton's sunglasses ad sitting
side-by-side with baseball's home-run king, the event has helped
carry extreme sports away from the highly select scene and almost
into the mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 version features a nearly $1 million purse and more
than 400 athletes, many of whom will be covered head-to-toe with
sponsor logos. The U.S. Postal Service even is launching a series
of extreme sports stamps in conjunction with the start of the
games.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Stiepock, director of marketing and communications for the
X Games, was around in 1994 when the idea of an extreme game
Olympics was an attempt to find programming for the new ESPN2
network. While he was trying to sell the idea to anyone who would
listen, he had no idea 19 million U.S. households, and 180
countries, eventually would be watching.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first started this job, I had to spend 15 minutes on
the phone just describing what the concept might be,'' Stiepock
said. ``The only reason anybody ever took my phone calls was
because it had the four letters E-S-P-N next to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I can't handle all the people calling me.''
</P>
<P>
   Those calls come from athletes trying to enter, fans wanting
information about attending and advertisers looking to get their
products shown during the X Games telecast.
</P>
<P>
   And it's often men ages 12-34, the target audience for the X
Games, on the other end of the line.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN knew whom it wanted to reach when Ron Semiao, vice
president of programming at ESPN, conceived the X Games idea. There
was an audience of active young men waiting to be captivated by a
unique sporting event. Within the X Games' five years of existence,
advertisers have learned ESPN was quite precise, and they have done
their own part in boosting the success of extreme sports and the X
Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The X Games is age-targeted, so you can't say it's Final Four
or Super Bowl,'' said John Lazarus, head of the buying department
for the Bozell advertising agency in New York. ``But for reaching
young men in sports, it has created its own successful niche.''
</P>
<P>
   Mountain Dew, Taco Bell, Snickers and milk are just a few of
this year's X Games sponsors that plan to profit from that success.
</P>
<P>
   Mountain Dew was the first company on the X Games bandwagon in
1994, and has since made extreme sports the main focus of its ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what people are participating in right now or what a lot
of people want to participate in. It's just what they aspire to
do,'' said Jon Harris, a spokesman for Pepsi, which makes Mountain
Dew.
</P>
<P>
   ``A great example of all this is how popular the individual
athletes have gotten.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides Hamilton and McGwire side-by-side at sunglass shops, the
X Games increased skateboarder Tony Hawk's prominence enough that
he now sports the white mustache in milk ads. And Rick Thorne,
four-time X Games participant and host of ESPN2's monthly show ``X
2day,'' said he is often recognized by his tattoos alone.
</P>
<P>
   But along with the extreme sports growth the X Games helped
generate has come the possibility of overexposure.
</P>
<P>
   In October, NBC will launch its version of the X Games, called
the Gravity Games, largely to fill the void left when it lost NFL
rights. The Winter X Games also is an annual event for ESPN and
ESPN2. And those networks combine to show hundreds of hours of
extreme sports programs throughout the year.
</P>
<P>
   Stiepock said ESPN is confident the extreme sports phenomenon is
not a passing fad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like anything that becomes popular, it's impossible to predict
whether it's going to be around five years from now,'' Stiepock
said. ``ESPN thinks it is, and ESPN is devoted to continuing this.
But at the same time, we have woven into our system things that
allow for change.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the open-ended policies include never guaranteeing a
sport will be part of the games from one year to the next. Downhill
in-line skating is one casualty, replaced this year by Motocross-X,
a motorcycle stunt event.
</P>
<P>
   Other networks, however, are not so quick to join in on the
craze, afraid the audience is being spread too thin.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's only so many 12-34 demographic dollars that can go
around,'' said Vince Wladika, senior vice president of media
relations at Fox. ``You may be better off looking at a different
area, creating your own franchise instead of being the third man
in.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many extreme games franchises can you have? I guess we're
going to find out with NBC starting theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC has yet to see the down side.
</P>
<P>
   When the network began its Gravity Games project, one sign that
showed extreme sports popularity was still on the rise was how
quickly the ad time sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imitation is the best flattery, and ESPN has like a four-year
head start on the Gravity Games,'' said Lazarus, who bought time
during the Gravity Games for the Marines. ``But the Gravity Games
got sold out pretty quickly because there isn't that much
television that really targets this young teen audience.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, at least, the X Games, which has won five Emmy awards,
is still drawing hundreds of thousands of fans (250,000 attended
the 1998 games in San Diego). Hamilton and her fellow extreme
athletes are still gaining sponsors and raking in prize money. And
attempted rivals to the X Games, like the Gravity Games, signal the
steady growth of extreme sports.
</P>
<P>
   They're not yet popular enough, though, to have their own sports
metaphors.
</P>
<P>
   ``For five years, ESPN has been the guy shooting hoops in his
driveway,'' Stiepock said. ``Now, we're finally going to the park
to get a pick-up game.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Aggressive in-line skating:
</P>
<P>
   Aggressive? Try suicidal. Flying through an obstacle course or a
giant half-pipe on skates just cries ``Hurt me!''
</P>
<P>
   _ Bicycle stunt riding:
</P>
<P>
   Only men compete here, which creates an added hazard _ the
bicycle seat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Freestyle Moto-X (new): Motorcycles: Because regular bikes
just weren't dangerous enough.
</P>
<P>
   _ Skateboarding: For skateboarders who don't have enough scars,
trying tricks on an
</P>
<P>
   obstacle course or half-pipe should leave a mark or two.
</P>
<P>
   _ Skysurfing: Keep a sickness bag handy. Humans with cameras
spinning toward Earth probably won't make athletes ill but may
affect viewers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Snowboarding: It's fake snow, but the athletes must have ice
in their veins when they try to get ``bigger air'' than the
competition.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sport climbing: Climbers use ropes and harnesses for the Speed
competition, but the real fun should come during Bouldering. All
restraints are gone and the climbers are free to fall to the mats.
</P>
<P>
   _ Street luge racing:A kid's dream: Sledding down a street with
only bales of hay to
</P>
<P>
   protect you.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wakeboarding: Like snowboarding, but here, at least the water
cushions the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
