<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0036 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-ANDERSEN-SPI &LR;      06-25 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-ANDERSEN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN ANDERSEN'S `CENTURY' NOVEL, SEATTLE IS U.S. CAPITAL BUT THERE
ARE DIGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BILL VIRGIN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ He nailed us.
</P>
<P>
   Professional satirist Kurt Andersen came to town to chronicle,
in novel form, Seattle and its fellow outposts on the raw frontier
of the new techno-economy as the 21st century dawns.
</P>
<P>
   And he did his job exceptionally well.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle's problem is that it's not nearly raw enough. One
Microsoft Way: is that not the address of a cult? Notwithstanding
the soccer field and arcade games, the lack of suits and ties and
regular hours, a 1950s corporate DNA showed itself in these boys'
blood strongly and immediately. ... It's the same with their
immense bland houses in Hunts Point and Clyde Hill, and the
Microsoft flag flying next to the Stars and Stripes, and the lame
little fake waterfall trickling through the Red West campus _
billionaires spending, not to transcend suburban backyard-patio
boyhoods, but to reproduce them. It's not your father's Oldsmobile,
but it sure is an Oldsmobile.
</P>
<P>
   That is a passage from Andersen's first novel, ``Turn of the
Century,'' and there's plenty more where that came from. But if
that seems disrespectful of our wonderful city by the Sound,
consider that in this novel-length snapshot of American business
and culture of the near-future (the year 2000), Seattle has been
elevated to the status of capital of the United States, on a par,
and in uneasy if necessary coexistence with, New York and Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Necessary, because each supplies something _ publicity,
technology, money _ the others need. Uneasy, because:
</P>
<P>
   The New York (and L.A.) contempt for Seattle (and for Silicon
Valley) can't be argued away. In the last few years it has
diminished some, and changed in texture _ from dismissive and
stupid, to alarmed and baffled, to supercilious and slightly less
baffled. Her husband and her friends regard residents of Seattle
(and Milpitas and Sunnyvale and all the rest) the way Americans
think of Canadians _ they seem like us, and their lives look clean
and civil, but ... who wants to hang out with earnest grad students
full-time.
</P>
<P>
   What's fascinating about this construction is what city is not
included in this geometric construction _ the nation's nominal
capital, Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't accidental, Andersen said in an interview in Seattle
this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington (D.C.) was very pointedly left off this geometry of
power and influence for a reason, because I think it's not very
important,'' he said. The Washington, D.C., of his youth, as the
center of debates over the Vietnam War and civil rights, did
matter. Not so with the marriage of money and technology that is
transforming commerce and society today. ``Right now Washington is
important only to itself and viewers of MSNBC.''
</P>
<P>
   That raises the question of whether Seattle (as a shorthand for
the Puget Sound to Bay area digitocracy) is merely the city of the
moment, the way the oil-crisis-enriched cities of Dallas and
Houston were in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, Andersen believes. Not that anything is permanent about
the technology business, but Seattle does seem to be ``at the
center of something more important, transformational. ... This
triangle, with the asterisk of depression or wars, will remain the
linchpin of this society.''
</P>
<P>
   So Seattle becomes one of the three principal settings of ``Turn
of the Century,'' and the convergence of capital, entertainment and
software becomes the theme. But why did Andersen, co-founder of Spy
magazine and more recently an essayist for The New Yorker, tackle a
novel rather than an essay or a non-fiction book?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there was a chance to have more resonance and global
impact by weaving (those themes) in a story than a one-off essay in
The New Yorker,'' he said. ``Some of the excitement _ and terror _
really isn't transmittable in an essay.''
</P>
<P>
   Going the fiction route had its challenges at first _ ``like
being on a different planet with different laws of physics,''
Andersen said. But it also gave him the freedom to set the novel in
the near future and to play with reality. Among the things to look
forward to next year: We'll be watching cable networks like ``The
Chopper Channel'' (nothing but shots of chases, disasters and other
events from the air) or, in a masterpiece of brand extension across
media channels, ``South Park'' as an ice skating show.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been some confusion among readers, `Is that real or
did you make that up?' That pleases me,'' Andersen said. ``Some
friends have said, `Why waste those ideas on a novel? Sell them to
(cable TV industry giant) John Malone.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Turn of the Century'' extends that sort of ``it ought to be
real, even if it isn't'' take on the very early 21st century to
Seattle. One character visits a Pioneer Square software company
whose employees wear identification badges with high-tech readouts
that display not their identification numbers but the number of
shares and options they hold.
</P>
<P>
   Andersen has some local connections _ his grandfather David
Swarr and father Robert Andersen both served on the board of
Washington Natural Gas. The utility, now part of Puget Sound
Energy, has a Renton facility named for Swarr.
</P>
<P>
   But as an outsider (raised in Omaha, living in New York), his
reading of Seattle is all the more pointed because he skipped the
tired rain-and-coffee jokes about the town.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there are some too-delicious-to-resist hits, like
restaurants as pretentious as they are trendy. (In the novel, an
obsequious waiter recites the evening's specials including
``ragouts of free-range north Oregon weasel''.)
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some obvious jokes, but I tried to get at what I
thought was some of its quirkiness,'' Andersen said.
</P>
<P>
   There was one other advantage to mining a relatively untapped
lode of material like Seattle. ``People in L.A. have heard
everything there is to say about L.A. that is satirical.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
