<SLUG> BC-FLEET-BANKBOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE DEPT. REVISES ITS POSITION ON BANK MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- With barely 72 hours left until the bidding closes for
branches that New England's top two banks must sell to meet
antitrust concerns about their merger, the US Department of Justice
told Fleet Financial Group Inc. Friday it would not insist all the
assets be sold to a single buyer.
</P>
<P>
   The letter, which supersedes a policy letter that the Washington
agency sent to Fleet last week but later rescinded, appeared to
formally signal a change in position by the agency, one of several
federal and local entities that must approve Fleet's proposed
merger with BankBoston Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In a one-page document addressed to a senior Fleet lawyer in New
York and copied to Massachusetts Attorney General Thomas F. Reilly,
the agency wrote that its letter was designed to ``clarify'' that
the Justice Department was ``not imposing any requirements on who
may bid for any or all of the assets being auctioned by Fleet.''
</P>
<P>
   Reilly, whose office plays a role in reviewing the merger, has
said in the past that competition can be best preserved by a large
bank acquiring most of the assets.
</P>
<P>
   The three-paragraph letter said that Justice needed ``to ensure
that the disposition of assets addresses our substantive antitrust
concerns relating to middle market lending that you are well aware
of from our discussions.
</P>
<P>
   ``That being said, however, we are not insisting that all assets
be acquired by a single buyer so long as there is a buyer in the
mix that will preserve competitive conditions in middle market
lending.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleet and BankBoston are combining into the nation's eighth
largest bank, with $160 billion in assets after divestiture. As
part of their merger, they are selling more than 290 branches with
$12.5 billion in deposits and $2.2 billion in loans across three
New England states. The two banks are selling the assets because
their combination, which has attracted considerable scrutiny from
regulators concerned about maintaining competition in business
lending, will leave the region with no similar-sized competitor.
</P>
<P>
   Bidding for the assets, which constitute the largest divestiture
in US banking history, is set to close Monday afternoon. The
process has attracted a storm of controversy over whether or how
small community banks, which want to buy some of the assets, should
be allowed to participate in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians, community activists, and banking sources expressed
conflicting views on the meaning and import of Justice's new
letter, which came from the agency's antitrust division and was
signed by deputy assistant attorney general Donna E. Patterson.
</P>
<P>
   US Representative Barney Frank of Newton, the leading Democrat
on the House Banking Committee and a vocal proponent of a role for
local community banks in the bidding process, said Friday that the
letter reflected a ``reversal of position'' on the part of Justice
after fierce lobbying by himself and his Democratic colleague,
Representative J. Joseph Moakley of South Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Frank said the agency had sent a letter to Fleet earlier this
month stating that the assets should go to a single large bank from
outside the region. The letter, he said, reflected Justice's
thinking that New England does not have banks large enough to
compete with Fleet-BankBoston.
</P>
<P>
   Several days later, Justice suspended, then withdrew, the
letter, Frank said, adding that the retraction came after he and
Moakley met with a senior Justice antitrust official, Joel Klein,
to lobby for a role for community banks.
</P>
<P>
   A Justice spokeswoman declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Other officials said Friday's letter did not change Justice's
original intent _ to create competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to interpret exactly what this (second letter)
means,'' Reilly said. ``People can read whatever they want into
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank said Justice was prepared to favor a sale in which
community banks acquire around 10 percent of the assets on sale,
but Friday's letter made no mention of that element, saying only
that ``we understand that the process (sale) will be conducted in a
way that enables anyone to express in interest in any of the
assets.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleet and BankBoston have always said that bidding is open to
any bank. Industry sources said Fleet executives were reportedly
confused by the letter.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet spokesman James Mahoney declined to comment, saying only,
``We have sent bid packages to a wide range of banks, from
community banks to large banks, and are awaiting the bids.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
