<SLUG> BC-HKN-DRAFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THRASHERS, AND NHL, SEEM COOL TO OLYMPICS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Atlanta Thrashers, who chose their first roster in
the expansion draft Friday, are the junior partners in the 28-team
National Hockey League, at least until Columbus and Minnesota join
next summer. But the Thrashers' corporate backing and executive
lineup suggest that this fledgling franchise could already be an
influential player in hockey's boardrooms, perhaps on major issues
like Olympic participation in 2002 in the Winter Games at Salt Lake
City.
</P>
<P>
   The Thrashers' president is Dr. Harvey Schiller, who is also the
president of Turner Sports, as in Ted Turner, as in ``a Time Warner
company.'' Before joining Turner, Schiller served as executive
director/secretary-general of the U.S. Olympic Committee. Friday
afternoon in Fleet Center here, after the Thrashers drafted players
like defensemen Chris Tamer from the Rangers, Kevin Dean from the
Devils and David Harlock from the Islanders, Schiller expressed
mixed feelings about NHL Olympic participation after its mixed
experience in 1998 in Nagano, Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he was as enthusiastic about NHL Olympic
participation as some are, Schiller answered, ``Probably not.''
And, although he continues to work toward Olympic participation,
commissioner Gary Bettman seemed to put it in a new perspective
Friday when he said, ``For us, the all-star game is more important
than the Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked to elaborate, Schiller said, ``My feelings may be
different than many other people's,'' and that the NHL is different
from the National Basketball Association, whose players dominate
primarily the U.S. Olympic team, because ``hockey has become an
international sport in this country.'' This complicates matters
when the athletes are repackaged as an Olympic product for several
countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Olympics are supposed to be a place where athletes perform
at the highest level in a competitive way,'' Schiller said. ``Are
you doing that right now in the NHL and the Stanley Cup? You are
already seeing the mixture of the best players.''
</P>
<P>
   Schiller was asked if he meant to imply that the Olympics are
not as good an idea for the NHL as some people think. ``It might
not be,'' he said. ``In 1992, in Barcelona, the No. 1-selling
licensed article for the NBA was the Dream Team. The question is,
on a business perspective alone, would that be true for the NHL in
2002? We have a lot of discussion ahead of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Network exposure is a major issue. During the Nagano Games, CBS
carried games in the early morning hours. Bettman has tried to
persuade NBC to maximize exposure for Olympic hockey, possibly in
prime time. Bettman said again Friday that the International Ice
Hockey Federation has set a Sept. 15 deadline of this year for the
NHL's decision. ``What we have to assess between now and the 15th
of September,'' Bettman said, ``is whether or not the circumstances
are such that it makes sense to go. If it makes sense, we'll do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bettman refused to be specific when asked about circumstances or
prime-time television, either on NBC or on its cable partners MSNBC
and CNBC. He said, in general, that the league wanted to know
``whether or not the exposure and the conditions under which we
would go warrant stopping the season.'' The break in the season
probably would be 12 days, Bettman said, instead of the 16 in 1998.
He said the NHL would not give up its all-star game, which requires
another break. ``The Olympics would be secondary to our season,''
Bettman said, adding that the all-star game is part of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Lou Lamoriello, president of the Devils, managed the American
hockey team in Nagano and said Friday: ``I don't think we have
enough information now. There have to be some guarantees as far as
times before the NHL can even consider it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-99 2050EDT &QL; 
