<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Russia: Moving Closer to IMF
</P>
<P>
   Russia moved a step closer toward securing a new $4.5 billion
loan from the International Monetary Fund when the
Communist-dominated parliament passed several laws to raise
government revenue and restructure the collapsed banking sector.
Russia has not done everything the IMF has demanded. A new tax on
car purchases, for example, was watered down to protect domestic
automakers. An IMF team is scheduled to visit Moscow next week to
review Russia's progress in meeting the fund's conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Ireland: Progress Reported
</P>
<P>
   Prime Ministers Tony Blair of Britain and Bertie Ahern of
Ireland said they had made progress in talks in Belfast in
persuading Protestant and Catholic leaders to compromise in a
dispute over disarmament of the IRA and membership of its political
wing, Sinn Fein, in a new executive cabinet of the Northern Ireland
Assembly. If no agreement is reached by Wednesday, transfer of
power from London to the Assembly will be delayed, which could
bring a return to sectarian violence.
</P>
<P>
   Switzerland: Appeal On Mines
</P>
<P>
   The International Committee of the Red Cross appealed for $69
million to finance its land-mine awareness and victim
rehabilitation projects in the next five years. Land mines kill an
estimated 25,000 people a year. The money would help pay for
awareness programs in six countries and artificial limb-fitting
centers in 11 countries.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey: Ocalan Lawyer Cleared
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Kurdish rebel leader Abdullah Ocalan and his
secretary were acquitted of charges of aiding the rebel group. They
had sought to take documents related to Ocalan's treason trial,
including a copy of the indictment, out of the country. The trial
ended this week, and one of the judges said a verdict was likely on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Argentina: Menem Mandate
</P>
<P>
   President Carlos Saul Menem told his Cabinet that he would issue
presidential decrees mandating a restructuring of the nation's
pension system and labor laws to give businesses more flexibility
to dismiss workers if Congress failed to pass such measures. The
move was seen by political analysts as an effort by Menem to retake
the initiative amid concerns that he has become a lame duck in his
final months in office.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Auditor's Complaints
</P>
<P>
   A Canadian auditor under contract to Congress to look for
irregularities in the way President Ernesto Zedillo's aides carried
out a $65-billion bank bailout complained in a letter to Congress
that authorities had been uncooperative in providing access to
financial data, the newspaper Reforma reported. Michael Mackey sent
the letter to explain why he needs more money and time to finish
the audit, which is due in July.
</P>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS
</P>
<P>
   Joint Pledge on Peace Force
</P>
<P>
   Britain and France agreed to provide a rapid reaction force of
up to 13,000 soldiers for U.N. peacekeeping missions. Britain is
ready to provide up to 8,000 troops from its existing rapid
deployment force, including logistics, communications and command
and control specialists, as well as elite fighting units. France
will provide up to 5,000 soldiers on similar terms.
</P>
<P>
   Warning on 2000 Bug
</P>
<P>
   Failure to address problems caused by the so-called year 2000
bug may lead to serious trade disruptions and breakdowns in customs
operations, the U.N. Conference on Trade and Development in Geneva
warned. A senior official said as many as 40 countries confront
major problems because they are using customs systems that are not
equipped to deal with the bug.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   Iraq: Expert Help on Laboratory
</P>
<P>
   Four technical experts from the Organization for the Prohibition
of Chemical Weapons, based in The Hague, will help the United
Nations dismantle a laboratory in Baghdad containing potentially
dangerous substances. A spokesman for the group, which monitors
chemical weapons agreements, said that while some of its officials
questioned the urgency of the mission and still had concerns about
the experts' safety, they felt an obligation to respond positively
to a U.N. request for help.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-99 2052EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
