<DOCNO> NYT19990625.0322 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0040 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-DOMESTIC-BOS &LR;      06-25 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DOMESTIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGES ACTION ON PRESSING DOMESTIC NEEDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Turning his attention from success in Kosovo to his
stalled agenda at home, President Clinton Friday urged lawmakers
not to ``run out the clock'' before the next election and to work
instead to shore up Social Security, raise the minimum wage, rein
in health insurance companies and help seniors pay for prescription
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The president used a speech to Georgetown University students
and a formal news conference to try to revive his domestic agenda,
warning that the presidential and congressional races for the year
2000 will soon harden political positions and make it difficult for
Congress to pass new laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be plenty of time for politics in the year and a
half ahead,'' he said, ``but this summer must be a season of
progress.''
</P>
<P>
   In a lengthy and wide-ranging news conference, his first since
March, Clinton also said NATO was doing all it could to stop ethnic
Albanians from seeking revenge on Serbs in Kosovo. He suggested
that wealthier Americans might be asked to pay higher Medicare
premiums. He said he misspoke earlier this year when he claimed
that no security breaches occurred at US nuclear labs under his
administration.
</P>
<P>
   The president also acknowledged complaints from hospitals and
nursing homes that the government has cut their funding too steeply
in an attempt to shore up the financially shaky Medicare program.
Boston teaching hospitals have been among the loudest protesters.
But Clinton said the cuts helped extend the solvency of Medicare by
15 years, and he did not offer any relief.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to reflect on impeachment and the Monica S. Lewinsky
scandal, the president brushed off suggestions that his personal
behavior would hurt the political fortunes of his wife, who may run
for senator from New York, or of Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``All elections are about the future, and all candidates are
judged on their own merits,'' Clinton said. He said Americans gave
him credit for working to be ``the best president I could be'' and
to ``repair my family life.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's policy offensive came only two days after he returned
from a weeklong European trip, where he had celebrated NATO's
victory in Kosovo and talked with NATO and Russian leaders about
how to patrol the peace in the Yugoslav province.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans appeared surprised by Clinton's speedy return to
domestic themes, and they called their own rally on Capitol Hill to
lay out their agenda. Top items include a bigger defense budget, an
effort to strengthen Social Security finances and a cut in income
and other taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will fight for tax relief for working Americans,'' said
House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert. ``I ask the president, please
include tax relief on your agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   The prospects for passing any major legislation this year are
weak, many analysts say. With only a six-vote margin in the House,
Republican leaders have found it difficult to build a majority for
major programs. In the Senate, GOP leaders have been unable to move
legislation in recent days because Democrats keep trying to tack on
a contentious HMO-regulation measure.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, positions have hardened on some of the major issues.
Both parties, for example, say they want a ``patients bill of
rights'' to force health-maintenance organizations to offer better
insurance coverage. But Republicans are against a Democratic plan
to allow HMO patients to sue their health plans when care is
denied. Most HMO members are barred from suing under existing law.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are expected to push for a broad tax cut package
that would eliminate the so-called marriage penalty, end death
taxes, cut the capital gains tax and possibly have more earnings
taxed at the lowest current level, 15 percent. Clinton has said he
does not oppose tax cuts, but he wants any package to include
breaks to help families cover the costs of child care and long-term
care for seniors.
</P>
<P>
   To put Medicare on a stronger financial footing, Republicans
want to allow seniors to leave the program and enroll instead in
private plans, which would compete for members by offering
attractive benefit packages.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats fear this would draw the healthiest seniors into
private plans, leaving Medicare with the sickest and most expensive
patients. But Democrats are divided over how to improve Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Clinton will propose a new benefit that would help
seniors cover the cost of prescription drugs. To fund the plan,
however, he might propose that wealthier Medicare enrollees pay
higher premiums than low-income seniors _ an idea that is drawing
Democratic opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Reischauer, a Brookings Institution scholar who tracks
economic policy, said the Republican and Democratic press events
laid down political markers for some important economic
announcements next week.
</P>
<P>
   The White House budget office on Monday and the Congressional
Budget Office on Thursday are expected to release new estimates of
government spending and revenues. The last estimates predicted a
modest deficit of between $5 billion and $12 billion for next year,
even when the massive Social Security surpluses that fund much of
government are excluded.
</P>
<P>
   But next week, Reischauer said, the new projections are expected
to show that the small deficit will actually be a small surplus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference between a negative and a positive number has
immense psychological importance,'' Reischauer said. ``This is
going to set off a feeding frenzy, where members of Congress are
going to say there's money that can be devoted to tax cuts,
discretionary spending, whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   Responding to more than 25 questions at the news conference
Friday, Clinton also:
</P>
<P>
   -- Made an emotional appeal for Yugoslav Serbs ``to get out of
denial'' about the violence in Kosovo conducted under President
Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs are ``going to have to come to grips with what Mr.
Milosevic ordered in Kosovo ... And then, they're going to have to
decide whether they support his leadership or not, whether they
think it's OK that all those tens of thousands of people were
killed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   -- Amended his March 19 statement that ``no one has said
anything to me about any espionage'' by China at US nuclear labs
during his administration.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, news reports revealed that a Los Alamos National
Laboratory scientist downloaded information from classified
computers into his personal computers during Clinton's tenure.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I should have said was I did not know of any specific
instance of espionage, because I think that we've been suspicious
all along ... We did not have any specific instance, as we now do,
of the off-loading of the computer,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   --Said he would produce a book on race, building on Clinton's
advisory panel on race.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Post reported this week that the book project had
become mired in disputes among its writers. Several drafts have
been produced, with Harvard law professor Christopher Edley Jr.
serving as the top consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the book was delayed only because his other duties
have distracted him from the project. ``It's got to be first of all
mine,'' he said. ``It's got to reflect what I believe and where I
think we need to go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
