<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-FEDERAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RULINGS A SETBACK FOR PATENT HOLDERS AND STATE WORKERS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Vt., Fla., Me.)   By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The closely decided federalism cases at the Supreme
Court this week not only enlivened the debate about the
relationship between Congress and the states but also profoundly
changed the rights of two categories of people: state employees and
holders of patents and copyrights like inventors, authors and
composers.
</P>
<P>
   In three 5-4 rulings, the court said that the ``sovereign
immunity'' of states shielded them from private lawsuits to enforce
federal laws governing the workplace as well as those protecting
patents and trademarks.
</P>
<P>
   One major practical effect of the ruling, many lawyers say, is
that private companies, inventors and scientists who hold patents
have no immediate recourse to obtain damages when they believe
those patents have been violated by state agencies.
</P>
<P>
   While it might surprise many people to learn that states compete
with private interests in such commercial activity, many state
university systems _ arms of the state governments _ are deeply
engaged in research and aggressively seek to accumulate patents to
increase their income.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Wexler, a New York lawyer with the New York Intellectual
Property Law Association, said Friday that, for the moment, ``if
the state is out there infringing your patent,'' you will not be
able to collect lost profits; damages, if the infringement was
willful, or attorneys' fees.
</P>
<P>
   A friend-of-the-court brief filed by Wexler's group noted that
the University of Florida system, for example, holds more than 200
patents, a fact mentioned prominently by Justice John Paul Stevens
in his dissent from the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Wexler said the Florida university patents included items or
processes as varied as an insect repellent, a way to enhance the
images on projection screens, a method of reinforcing supports used
in construction made of plastic and concrete and a system to
recycle atmosphere in closed spaces.
</P>
<P>
   A patent may be obtained by anyone for a process as well as a
product. One of the Supreme Court cases was about a complaint from
a bank that it had patented a college tuition savings plan that was
unfairly copied by a Florida state agency. The ruling means the
bank may no longer sue the state for damages in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, a lawsuit brought by Genentech, a California
biotechnology company, charging that the University of California
improperly appropriated patented research involving human hormones
is now almost certain to be dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Shannen W. Coffin, a Washington lawyer and authority on the
issue, said that the courts' rulings had effectively taken away the
strongest incentive for a potential plaintiff to challenge state
patent infringements, as well that of public employees to complain
that states are not complying with federal employment laws.
</P>
<P>
   Under the rulings, Coffin said, it may still be possible for
patent-holders or aggrieved employees to sue to prevent the state
from continuing to violate federal employment laws or patent
infringement. But such lawsuits, under a specific 19th-century
precedent, could deal only with future violations and could not
seek to recover damages like back pay or lost profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Often it's not worth a party's time to sue to stop a future
violation,'' he said. ``The incentive has been greatly changed.''
</P>
<P>
   An alternative is for the federal government to take legal
action against the state. The Justice Department or the Labor
Department may sue a state, but the patent and fair labor laws were
based on the notion they would be enforced by private lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Robert T. Scully, the executive director of the National
Association of Police Organizations, said that the rulings meant
that law-enforcement officers might no longer sue to force states
to comply with federal laws on issues like overtime. Scully's group
had filed a friend-of-the-court brief in one of the cases, in which
parole officers in Maine tried to sue the state for overtime
guaranteed by federal law.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court said that the federal government itself, maybe the
Labor Department, could bring suit,'' Scully said. ``But that's not
going to happen. To do that, they would have to hire hundreds of
more lawyers.''
</P>
<P>
   The court's re-alignment of the relationship between the states
and the federal government is likely to continue. The court
expanded its review of state immunity by accepting a new case, for
argument in the fall, on the question of whether whistle-blowers
can sue states under the federal False Claims Act.
</P>
<P>
   That law enables people to bring lawsuits, in the name of the
United States, for fraud against the government. If a suit is
successful, the private plaintiff receives part of the penalty as a
bounty.
</P>
<P>
   The lower federal courts have disagreed over whether states can
be named in such suits. The Justices on Thursday accepted an appeal
by Vermont, which was charged by one of its employees under the
False Claims Act with filing false claims in connection with a
federal grant from the Environmental Protection Agency. The 1st
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, in Boston, rejected the state's
claim of immunity under the 11th Amendment and ruled last year that
the lawsuit could proceed. The case is Vermont vs. U.S., No.
98-1828.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
