<SLUG> BC-FBN-DILLON-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COREY DILLON'S LIFE NOW REVEALS A SOFTER, MORE GROUNDED SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FEDERAL WAY _ There are baby pictures on the wall, the table and
the big-screen television set. A padded baby carrier sits next to
the leather couch.
</P>
<P>
   This is home for Corey Dillon, one of the most talented, and
perhaps misunderstood, athletes to emerge from Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   His name is in the NFL and University of Washington record
books, his jersey in pro football's hall of fame, rewards for
carrying a football like no other.
</P>
<P>
   Yet you should see Dillon, 24, run a juice bottle to 6-month-old
Cameron Antoine-Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday afternoon, the gifted Cincinnati Bengals back will
host the second Corey Dillon Football Camp at Seattle's Garfield
High School, for boys ages 8 to 15. He will hand out T-shirts and
advice. He will serve up lunch and sign autographs. He will pay for
it all himself.
</P>
<P>
   He also will let as many as 200 little Corey Dillons smother him
to death.
</P>
<P>
   And on Sundays and Tuesdays, you can find him at the Faith
Deliverance Assembly church in South Seattle, attending services
and bible study, a member and born-again Christian since Easter
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a whole lot of things needed changing in my life,''
said Dillon, a large gold cross hanging around his neck. ``I feel
extremely better. I can't measure how good I feel from before to
now. It's a great change.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the soft side of Corey Dillon - one often obscured by
the explosive manner in which he plays pro football and by a
simmering temperament that has led to well-publicized brushes with
the law.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't deny the unpleasantness, a wide range of juvenile
missteps and a couple as an adult, most for fighting. But he says
one episode - a conviction as a 15-year-old for selling crack
cocaine to a police officer - was not fully explained and unfairly
tainted him.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday at Garfield, Dillon will lecture to his camp
followers about the evils of drug use. He does not wish to be a
hypocrite. He wants the record set straight.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, Dillon was arrested in downtown Seattle with three
other youths after one of his friends was found with drugs. All
were charged with intent to sell. Prosecution was tough whenever
police sweeps netted street drugs, geared to wipe out gangs, which
were widespread across the city back then.
</P>
<P>
   Dillon was told by a public defender to plead guilty for lesser
punishment or face the possibility of one year of incarceration if
he didn't and lost. He was told the record would be sealed when he
turned 18. He took the easy way out legally. He suffered for it
more than he could have imagined.
</P>
<P>
   Instant football fame at Washington led to a presidential-like
scouring of his past, and the drug conviction turned up. People
looked at Dillon in a different light. He gave up trying to defend
himself. No more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I invite anybody to do this: open the file and I want them to
show me where it says I sold drugs to a police officer; I'll give
them a million bucks if they can,'' he said. ``I took the rap for
someone else. I come from a decent family. I know better. I never
sold drugs. I never will. I don't use drugs. They stop you from
performing. Everything I've got, God gave it to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides his camp-goers, Dillon wants one other person to have
the full story behind his teenaged drug bust.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got my own family and whatever comes out on this reflects
on them,'' he said with a piercing stare. ``I don't want my
daughter reading how her father went into drugs or was selling
drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   In time, Cameron Antoine-Dillon might have difficulty weaving
her way through all the tales of her father's extraordinary
football feats to find any dirt. In three short seasons, Dillon has
been nothing short of spectacular, if not mystical. The
possibilities for the rugged back are endless.
</P>
<P>
   In his three-month stay at Washington, he rushed for 222 yards
in a quarter against San Jose State, 259 yards against Oregon and
five touchdowns against UCLA. In just eight games, he ran for a
school-record 1,555 yards and scored 23 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Two seasons with the Bengals have netted him a pair of
1,000-yard seasons and a record-breaking 246 yards in a game
against the Oilers, eclipsing Jim Brown's rookie rushing mark.
</P>
<P>
   Football immortality would be fine by Dillon, who carries a
sculpted 6-foot-2, 220-pound frame honed by disciplined offseason
workouts at Bally's in Federal Way.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's everybody's dream when they leave the game, if not be
the best, to be one of the best,'' he said. ``I'd be lying if I
didn't say it was a goal of mine.''
</P>
<P>
   His first contract made him a millionaire; his second, after
this season, should triple or quadruple his earnings. Yet he has
been somewhat restrained in his spending habits. He bought his
mother another Rainier Valley house. He lives in a modest
condominium in south King County with his fiancee, Desiree Antoine,
and their young child.
</P>
<P>
   Dillon's only vice has been cars. He has five of them: a
Mercedes Benz, BMW, Range Rover, Cadillac and, his personal
favorite, a 1968 Mustang. His fiancee drives one; his best friend,
Wayne McDade, drives another at Dillon's insistence. The fleet
serves as a measuring stick for Dillon's life struggles and
successes.
</P>
<P>
   ``My toys are my cars; that's all I ever wanted,'' Dillon said.
``I basically came from nothing. I cherish everything I have. I
know how it's like not having something to eat or begging for
rides, riding the bus or riding a bike. When I'm alone in my car, I
praise the Lord for everything I have.''
</P>
<P>
   Said McDade, a social worker: ``He's still just Corey to me. No
matter how much money he has. Other friends want to hang around him
for status. We just sit around and talk. It's hard for me to
separate Corey and the professional football player. He's the same
old funny Corey. He's the same friend I knew in high school.''
</P>
<P>
   Dillon attended Franklin, but his football beginnings came on
Central Area Youth Association teams that played at Garfield, hence
the camp site. He has seen positive change in the neighborhood and
wants to be part of it.
</P>
<P>
   McDade and he came up with the idea to hold the camp. It will be
a permanent fixture.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're making strides, making it better,'' Dillon said of the
Central Area, a rugged, intercity neighborhood in Seattle. ``From
what I can see, it looks real good. They're building Garfield up
real nice. Those were things I was wishing for.''
</P>
<P>
   There were no Corey Dillons when he was growing up, no local pro
athletes returning home to encourage the next generation to dream
big. He wanted one. He might have avoided some of his youthful
scrapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll send a message to them: There's going to be a lot of hard
times in life, but if you'll work hard, you'll achieve your
goals,'' Dillon said of the camp youngsters. ``Basically what it
takes is someone to tell them they can be what they want to be. I
didn't have that.''
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, there are diapers to change, bottles to prepare, the
future to consider. He's a father now. There won't be any more
Dillons running around wild. Not his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, I'm going to be one of those guys waiting in the
(window) blinds, waiting for her to come home,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
