<HEADER>
A0058 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NUREMBURG-DISPLAY-NYT     06-25 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUREMBURG-DISPLAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIGNED NUREMBURG LAWS TO GO ON VIEW 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the closing days of World War II in 1945, U.S.
troops of the 90th Infantry Division entered Eichstaett, a German
town. Tossing grenades as they moved down a building stairway, the
soldiers found a vault containing a package marked with the wax
seals of the Third Reich.
</P>
<P>
   Inside were four sheets of typewritten paper dated Sept. 15,
1935. The papers _ the original text of the Nuremberg Laws, which
legally excluded Jews from German life and were a critical step in
initiating the Holocaust _ were signed by Hitler and other German
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Within weeks of their discovery the papers were given to George
Patton Jr., commanding general of the 3rd Army. ``They have given
me a lot of other things, but this is the one important one,''
Patton said in presenting the papers _ as well as a limited and
unexpurgated text of Hitler's ``Mein Kampf'' found by U.S. soldiers
in Weimar _ to the Huntington Library in Pasadena, Calif., on June
11, 1945.
</P>
<P>
   The Huntington has rare books, an art gallery and, most
important, an extensive library focusing on British and American
history and art.
</P>
<P>
   Since Patton's presentation, the documents have been kept locked
at the library. But on Monday the Huntington is to announce that
the text will be lent for an indefinite time to the Skirball
Cultural Center in Los Angeles. The Skirball, not far from the
Getty Museum, off the San Diego Freeway, is a three-year-old museum
dealing with the Jewish experience in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I visited the Skirball and came to the Nazi persecution
of Jews, I realized they ought to have these documents,'' said
Robert Skotheim, president of the Huntington. ``We're primarily an
Anglo-American research center. Here was material that was really
outside our research scope and outside the expertise of our
curators.'' He said the museum had not given any thought in recent
years to displaying the documents until his visit to the Skirball
in the summer of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Although the documents do not reveal any new historical
knowledge, he said, the papers have considerable emotional
resonance. ``When one looks at the actual papers that Adolf Hitler
held in his hands and signed, it causes not merely an intellectual
reaction but a visceral one,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Skirball's president Uri Herscher, whose parents fled Germany in
1935 for Palestine, said that some board members who serve jointly
at both museums had told him about the materials. Herscher, who is
also a rabbi, said that when he saw the documents, ``I felt like I
was holding evil in my hands.'' It is rare, he said, for the public
to see an original document with Hitler's signature.
</P>
<P>
   The documents will be on display at the Skirball from Tuesday
until Sept. 5. They are to go on permanent display in December
after museum renovations.
</P>
<P>
   The selection of the Huntington was a personal decision by
Patton. He had grown up in Pasadena, and his family had been
friends with Henry Edwards Huntington, the real estate and railroad
magnate who founded the library and art center in 1919.
</P>
<P>
   The three Nuremberg Laws were drafted at a hastily assembled
meeting of German leaders at a police station on Sept. 14, 1935,
and became law the next day. The laws prohibited marriage,
cohabitation and relations between ``Aryans'' and Jews, and defined
a citizen of the German Reich as being of ``German blood.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a theoretical document,'' Herscher said. ``It's a
blueprint for what became the death camps.'' The next big step, he
said, was Kristallnacht in 1938, then the wearing of yellow stars,
followed by deportations and finally the camps.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
