<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALICHMAN ANCHORS REVOLUTION DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ A year ago, Dan Calichman would have had difficulty
imagining that he would be the most dependable and durable field
player on the Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   But Calichman's life changed dramatically after his fibula and
tibia were broken in the eighth game of the 1998 season. He had
been captain of the Los Angeles Galaxy, which was favored to
challenge for the MLS Cup title. But the Galaxy was eliminated in
the playoff semifinals and Calichman was considered expendable by
former coach Octavio Zambrano.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution acquired Calichman in January, and he has
anchored the defense, playing every minute of the first 14 games of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing what I get paid to do,'' Calichman said while
preparing for Saturday night's game against the Dallas Burn. ``But
I still don't think I'm playing up to the way I was playing before
the injury. It will be another month and a half or two months
before that happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm content with the way the team is playing now, and you can
see we're making progress. It's obvious we are getting to be a
closer-knit group on the field, and we're getting results because
of that. But if you look at our starting lineup, we haven't had the
same 11 out there for two games in a row yet. All year, we've been
fighting injuries. Once we get a healthy team on the field,
consistently, we'll be a lot stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution will be missing Richard Goulooze (Achilles
strain), John Harkes (left hamstring pull) and Ivan McKinley and
Carlos Parra (suspensions) against Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   That should open the way for Argentinian defender Mario Gori,
acquired from Miami in exchange for Edwin Gorter this week. Gori
could move into Ted Chronopoulos' left back position, with
Chronopoulos moving to midfield.
</P>
<P>
   Calichman and goalkeeper-coach Walter Zenga are the only
Revolution players to have started every game this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have four key players out, but when guys are out we just
have to get out and battle,'' Calichman said. ``It's not as pretty
when you do that, but we have to make up for it in effort. When
guys are injured, someone else has to step up, and it gives them a
chance to show what they can do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather have us winning some games, 4-0 or 5-0. But, if
not, we're having to fight hard to win games and that can build
chemistry and bonding.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Calichman became accustomed to some high-scoring
blowouts while playing for the Galaxy. Most home games were like a
celebration, with the largest crowds in the league and celebrity
players ranging from the actor Andrew Shue to Mexican
goalkeeper/striker Jorge Campos to the US striker Cobi Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Calichman has been greeted by equally receptive crowds in New
England, but the Revolution coaches and players are in a pragmatic
mode, with little concern for aesthetics or extraneous
pyrotechnics. The approach has produced 15 points and a third-place
standing in the Eastern Conference. The team's aim to qualify for
the MLS Cup title game, scheduled Nov. 21 at Foxboro Stadium,
seemed unrealistic a few months ago. Now, two games from the
halfway point in the season, the Revolution have a chance to gain
some credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``You haven't seen the best of New England yet,'' Calichman
said. ``It's coming, and the more we train together and keep away
from injury, the better chance we have to keep improving.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NOTES -- The MLS will conduct ceremonies for its 10 millionth
fan at games this weekend and July 4, when the Revolution plays
host to the MetroStars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
