<SLUG> BC-PRESBYTERIANS-GAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESBYTERIANS AGAIN SAY NO TO GAY MINISTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   An effort to repeal a law that effectively bars ordination of
gay men and lesbians in the Presbyterian Church (USA) was defeated
by a 3-to-2 ratio Friday by the church's General Assembly, the top
policy-making body.
</P>
<P>
   The 319-198 vote by commissioners, as the assembly's delegates
are called, came after a committee had recommended deleting an
amendment to the denomination's constitution, the Book of Order.
The assembly has been holding its annual meeting this week in Fort
Worth, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment, approved by the assembly in 1996 and adopted
through a vote of the presbyteries, or regional jurisdictions,
requires ministers, elders and deacons to live in ``fidelity within
the covenant of marriage between a man and a woman, or chastity in
singleness.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the amendment applies to everyone ordained, it has been
regarded as primarily a bar to the ordination of noncelibate
homosexuals. The question of whether the church should allow gay
men and lesbians to be ordained has roiled the 3.6 million-member
denomination for years.
</P>
<P>
   An effort two years ago by the amendment's opponents to soften
its language passed in the assembly but failed when a majority of
presbyteries voted against that change.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's vote, following an hour's discussion, came after a
majority of the assembly's Committee on Church Orders and Ministry,
in a surprise move on Tuesday night, had recommended deleting the
amendment. A repeal would have been a two-part process, requiring
the assembly's approval and then ratification by a majority of
presbyteries.
</P>
<P>
   Had the process succeeded, supporters of gay ordination would
still have had to overturn a 1978 assembly policy that
``self-affirming, practicing homosexual persons'' could not be
ordained within the denomination.
</P>
<P>
   Friday the assembly adopted another recommendation, put forward
by a minority on the Church Orders committee, which called for
retaining the amendment and imposing what amounts to a two-year
moratorium on further discussion in the assembly. The minority's
report also called for discussions on church unity within the
presbyteries.
</P>
<P>
   After the vote, the Covenant Network of Presbyterians, an
organization that opposes the amendment, said that it would
continue to work for its removal but that it wanted to do so
``without tearing apart the church we love and serve.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jack Haberer, the former moderator of the Presbyterian
Coalition, which supports the amendment, said in a telephone
interview that he was pleased by the assembly's vote but concerned
that a struggle could resume when the moratorium was over.
</P>
<P>
   Haberer also said he welcomed the discussions on church unity,
saying Presbyterians needed to talk about many issues, like
addressing differences in worship styles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-99 2114EDT &QL; 
