<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-DETAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH KOREA RELEASES DETAINED TOURIST 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By CALVIN SIMS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ North Korea Friday released a South Korean tourist
detained earlier this week on charges of trying to lure North
Koreans to defect. The move is expected to ease Korean tensions,
which have been rising since a clash of warships in the Yellow Sea
last week.
</P>
<P>
   The tourist, a 35-year-old woman who was taken into custody on
Sunday during a tour of the Mount Kumgang resort in North Korea,
was handed over to officials of the Hyundai Group, the South Korean
conglomerate that operates the tour, South Korean officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She appears to be in good health,'' a Hyundai spokesman, Lee
Young- kyu, said. ``Our doctors in the North will give her a brief
medical checkup, and then she will leave for the South on a Hyundai
tugboat.''
</P>
<P>
   North Korean security authorities said the woman, Min Young-mi,
had tried to persuade a North Korean tour guide to defect to the
South. The North's official Korean Central News Agency said the
government had decided to release her because she admitted that she
had ``preached defection'' to the guide. The news agency said that
the woman ``begged for lenient forgiveness for her criminal act.''
It was impossible to verify the account.
</P>
<P>
   The detention once again raised tensions between the Koreas,
which have never signed a peace treaty formally ending the 1950-53
Korean War. Last week, the two countries' skirmish in the Yellow
Sea resulted in the sinking of a North Korean boat and the deaths
of 20 North Korean sailors.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of North and South Korea held long-awaited talks in
Beijing on Tuesday to discuss reuniting families divided by the
war, but those discussions ended with both sides trading
accusations over which was responsible for the marine conflict. The
talks are scheduled to resume on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   It remains unclear exactly what North Korea hoped to accomplish
in detaining the South Korean tourist. South Korean officials, who
spoke by telephone from Seoul, interpreted the detention as a
response to the sinking of the North Korean vessel.
</P>
<P>
   The detention severely tested President Kim Dae-jung's policy of
engaging North Korea despite its confrontational nature. At home
and abroad, particularly in the U.S. Congress, critics say Kim's
policy of social and economic engagement is largely ineffective
because North Korea remains hostile.
</P>
<P>
   He had threatened to halt the tourism program, which is the
countries' largest joint commercial venture, and a major source of
income for North Korea, if the woman was not released.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Kim, Park June-young, applauded the release,
calling it ``a result of our government's firm position to
guarantee the safety of our tourists in the North.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We urge the North to take foolproof measures in the future to
guarantee the safety of South Korean tourists,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-99 2115EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
