</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-TRIAL-JUROR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUROR SAYS PANEL FAVORED MUDGE BY 9-6 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLEMENT AND JUDY RAKOWSKY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- After six days of dissecting medical evidence, nine
jurors out of 15 concluded on a fourth and final ballot that Dr.
Gilbert H. Mudge Jr. was not negligent in his treatment of Boston
Celtics star Reggie Lewis, one of the jurors said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The 9-6 vote Thursday in favor of Mudge came after 38 hours of
sometimes emotional, but always collegial, discussion during which
jurors set aside allegations of Lewis's cocaine use and focused
solely on the reams of medical evidence introduced during the 6 1/2
week trial, the juror, Marian Regan, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was 9 to 6 in favor of Dr. Mudge,'' said Regan, who was one
of the nine people who voted to clear Mudge. ``I think it was very
thorough deliberations. I don't think we left an angle undone.''
</P>
<P>
   Regan said the jury did not split along racial lines; some of
the seven minorities on the panel voted with Mudge, while some of
the eight whites favored Lewis' widow, Donna Harris Lewis. Race
``wasn't an issue'' during deliberations, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a race thing at all. It definitely wasn't an
issue,'' Regan said.
</P>
<P>
   She said the evidence she heard convinced her that Mudge had
made a dual diagnosis -- she easily rattled off the now-familiar
medical phrases of neurocardiogenic syncope and ventricular
arrthymia -- and that he treated Lewis appropriately under those
two medical approaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a terrible thing to happen. It wasn't Dr. Mudge's
fault. It wasn't Reggie Lewis' fault, '' Regan said of Lewis'
death. ``I just didn't feel he was negligent,'' she said of Mudge.
</P>
<P>
   Regan said she also believes that Donna Harris Lewis -- even
though she did not win the malpractice case -- has acheived her
publicly stated goal of restoring her husband's reputation that was
tarnished following his death when allegations of cocaine use
surfaced.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not how I am going to remember him,'' Regan said of of
the allegations that Reggie Lewis, the one-time Celtics captain,
was a cocaine user.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she said, she will remember the video played repeatedly
during the trial during which Reggie Lewis was shown with his son
at a Celtics event. ``He was a father and a husband,'' Regan said
of Reggie Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Regan said she dismissed the evidence of cocaine use introduced
during the trial by defense witnesses called by Mudge's lawyers.
``Personally, I didn't feel that it was an issue,'' she said of the
cocaine use. ``There was no substantiated proof so I didn't even
use it in my deliberations.''
</P>
<P>
   Regan, who works in the loan operations division of US Trust
bank, is the mother of a six-month old son, Kyle. She also has a
13-year-old son, Jimmy. During deliberations, she said she set
aside her emotions as a mother -- and distanced herself from the
power of Harris Lewis' tearful recounting of her final days with
her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Regan said the 15 people who were strangers when they first were
selected to sit on the case in May slowly evolved over time into a
group of friends. Before they left each other, at least 13 of the
jurors exchanged telephone numbers with fellow jurors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very emotional thing when we didn't render a
decision,'' she said, recalling the moments when it was clear to
the 15 jurors that they were deadlocked. `It was emotional for
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Several jurors took off on vacations Friday, Regan said, while
others just wanted some time to think about what they had been
invovled with before speaking with reporters about the case.
</P>
<P>
   Regan said that jurors had to vote twice before concluding that
Dr. Peter L. Friedman had not commited malpratice. A majority on
the first vote sided with Friedman with just one or two of the 15
considering themselves undecided. By the second vote, it was
unanimous.
</P>
<P>
   It took only one vote for the panel to side with Dr. Mark A.
Creager, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, jurors concluded the doctors were ``just
consultants'' who had no direct responsibility for Lewis' medical
care. That, she said, was Mudge's responsiblity.
</P>
<P>
   For Mudge, the jurors voted four times, Regan recalled. The
first vote showed the jury split evenly between Mudge and Harris
Lewis with several members reporting they were undecided. As
discussion continued over the following days, the panel finally
split into an irrevocable 9 to 6 division, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the trial is over, Regan said she would like to meet
the three doctors, chat with the lawyers, Suffolk Superior Court
Judge Thayer Fremont-Smith, and meet Harris Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   She also said that ``without hesitation'' she would become a
patient of Mudge's if she ever needed a cardiologist. ``I have a
lot of respect for Dr. Mudge because he could have taken the easy
way out and settled. But he believed in himself and went the whole
way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-99 2115EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
