<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0071 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-680&AMP;ADD     06-25 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-680&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITHOUT DAD TO DISTURB HER, LUCIC UPSETS SELES
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ A year ago, Mirjana Lucic sneaked away from
Wimbledon determined to sever all ties to her father/coach,
Marinko, a taskmaster she has accused of mental and physical abuse.
</P>
<P>
   The Croatian prodigy, now 17, had won her first professional
event at 15 only to find her career imperiled by family discord by
the time she turned 16. According to Lucic, the pressure inflicted
on her by her father was so crippling it rendered her little more
than a listless puppet on the tennis court.
</P>
<P>
   So Lucic packed a suitcase, slipped out the back door of the
family's Zagreb apartment and escaped to the United States last
summer with her mother and four siblings, a flight that has, she
said Friday after upsetting fourth-seeded Monica Seles at
Wimbledon, restored her to life on and off the court.
</P>
<P>
   Lucic believes the estrangement from her father, whom she has
not seen in a year, has left her free to love her sport again and
to resume pounding out the high-voltage shots her opponents love to
hate. Lucic's backhand cross-courts and forehand drives were
everywhere in evidence on Center Court in her 7-6 (7-4), 7-6 (7-4)
dismissal of Seles.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, the past year was so difficult, I had a lot of
personal problems, and then I was injured for a very long time,''
said Lucic, sidelined last fall by elbow and shoulder trouble that
hindered her segue into 1999 and sent her ranking plummeting to
134. Coming into Wimbledon she had played just eight events and had
not won more than two matches in a row at any of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here and really decided to change a lot of things,''
said Lucic, now coached by Joe Guliani and safely through to her
first round of 16 in a Grand Slam tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Lucic maintained her positive outlook Friday even after being
handcuffed in the opening set by Seles' serve. ``I hardly even
touched a ball,'' she said. ``I was just trying to stay in there
and play well; it was funny, but I was really enjoying myself, and
I didn't feel like that in a long time, maybe never.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second set, it was Seles who saw her shots desert her.
``It was all about who hit the ball harder at key times, and she
returned double better than I did,'' said Seles, who maintains it
is premature to write her out of future Grand Slam contention just
because things did not go well here on the surface most alien to
her game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly, Steffi, it all came together for her,'' said Seles,
referring to Steffi Graf's French Open triumph earlier this month.
``But so many things for that to happen have to come together; time
will tell.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the event is singles or mixed doubles, everything is
coalescing for Graf, whose mixed doubles partnership with John
McEnroe became official Friday. Graf, the owner of 22 Grand Slam
singles crowns, is not accustomed to providing, or receiving, comic
relief on the tennis court, nor is she accustomed to sharing her
court. But her decision to create a 70-year-old team (she's 30,
he's 40) by inviting McEnroe to partner her in the mixed doubles
was all about novelty.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the sight of the combative gray-haired New Yorker, a
regular now on the senior circuit but an absentee from mixed
doubles for two decades, was a sight for sore eyes at Wimbledon,
where his misdemeanors earned him the nickname Superbrat but his
duels with five-time champion Bjorn Borg enthralled the masses.
</P>
<P>
   Aware that Graf is winding down her career and piling up magic
moments, McEnroe agreed to be her co-pilot in mixed, then declared
them equipped to win it. The ninth-seeded duo took their first step
toward mixed doubles immortality Friday afternoon on Court 1, where
their entrance prompted a standing ovation and their unseeded
opponents, Jeff Coetzee and Eva Melicharova, proved cooperative,
and wilted, 6-2, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was meant to be; onward and upward,'' said McEnroe, who
dropped his racket in mock exasperation when Graf flubbed her first
shot of the match, a return, and then received the same treatment
from her when he missed his return. But the dream team quickly
buckled down. ``I'm not totally extinct yet,'' McEnroe said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One player who felt extinct Friday afternoon was 61st-ranked Jim
Courier _ and he felt that way despite surviving a 4-hour-24-minute
marathon against 50th-ranked Sjeng Schalken of the Netherlands. The
28-year-old Courier has won his last five five-setters, but he left
the All England Club without commenting on this one, a 7-6 (7-2),
3-6, 3-6, 7-5, 13-11 struggle that left him dehydrated and in a
state of nervous exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   Courier saved two match points, the first with a forehand pass
as he served at 4-5 of the fourth set, and the second at 5-6 of the
fifth set when he provoked a backhand volley error from the
Dutchman.
</P>
<P>
   But Courier, blessed by a weekend off, expected to make a full
recovery in time to play upset artist and villain in his round of
16 match with this tournament's resident hero, sixth-seeded Tim
Henman, who advanced with a 6-1, 6-7 (8-10), 6-3, 6-2 defeat of
Sebastien Grosjean.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's a big-match player; that's the best way to put
it,'' said Henman, who downplayed their 55-spot ranking disparity.
``When it's a big occasion, that ranking is perhaps lying a little
bit. I think it's fair to say it's why I've practiced, to play on
Center Court in these type of matches, and I'm sure it's the same
for him.''
</P>
<P>
   The most intriguing round of 16 confrontation on the women's
side will belong to two teen-agers, sixth-seeded Venus Williams,
who needed just 45 minutes Friday to subdue Sarah Pitkowski, 6-1,
6-1, and 17th-seeded Anna Kournikova, who advanced with a 7-5, 3-1
victory after her opponent, Ines Gorrochategui, withdrew with
injuries to her knee and shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to become upset or a statistic,'' said Williams,
who leads their rivalry, 2-0, but evidently regards Kournikova as
one of the more dangerous threats among the teen peer group. ``She
has a lot of strengths. She has a solid backhand and forehand and a
nice serve and moves well. It's going to be the person who comes in
more and takes more opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Kournikova, a semifinalist here in 1997, said she intended to
treat the encounter like a chess match on grass. ``She has a big
serve, she's a big girl, so I have to just out-think her,''
Kournikova said. ``Grass is obviously not her favorite surface, so
we'll see; I'll just have to play smarter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
