A0082 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-NYT &LR;      06-25 1219
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENSE CALM SETTLES ON BORDER OF ISRAEL AND LEBANON  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ After Israel's most severe bombardment of Lebanon
since 1996, a tense calm reigned along the border between the two
countries Friday as civilians on both sides waited for the next
rocket or bomb to fall.
</P>
<P>
   By late Friday night, however, there were no new rockets fired
at northern Israel by the Party of God, or Hezbollah, guerrillas in
southern Lebanon. The Israeli army, which undertook its wide-scale
bombing on Thursday night in response to guerrilla attacks, said it
would strike again only in retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Hezbollah stops firing, we have no interest in any
escalation,'' the Israeli army chief of staff, Shaul Mofaz, said.
``But if the Hezbollah continues, our targets are ready, our planes
are armed, and our pilots are on standby.''
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring the fact that the conflict has intensified at a
time of political transition in Israel, Benjamin Netanyahu, the
departing prime minister, visited the north Friday to show support
for its battle-weary residents.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak instead tended to political
business and continued the public silence that he has maintained
since he won an overwhelming victory on May 17.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, who has not been sworn in, issued no comment on the
conflict. ``He is not the prime minister,'' a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts here said it strained credulity that Barak, who is
carefully strategizing his every move, had not at least been
briefed about the bombing before it began.
</P>
<P>
   Cities in northern Israel looked like ghost towns as 200,000
residents camped underground in small, spare and stuffy bomb
shelters. At 8 p.m., after 27 hours, the government lifted the
state of emergency and allowed them to go home.
</P>
<P>
   In the daytime, only the brave and the foolhardy emerged to join
the soldiers on the empty streets. Some attended the funeral of one
of the two civilians killed on Thursday. Others, impatient with
government-ordered restrictions, went to the beach where Katyusha
rockets had landed 24 hours earlier.
</P>
<P>
   In Lebanon, the government, which is still trying to rebuild
after a devastating civil war, met to assess the damage caused by
the Israeli air strikes, which left eight dead, 62 wounded and
important bridges and power plants demolished.
</P>
<P>
   A power station that serves the Beirut region suffered an
estimated $6 million in damages. The destroyed transformers
continued to smolder this morning. Officials estimated that it
would take at least a week for the capital to emerge from its
blackout.
</P>
<P>
   The bridge over the Awali River, a critical link between
southern Lebanon and Beirut, is in ruins. Friday Lebanese soldiers
helped travelers sidestep down rubble while holding ropes and
teeter across a kind of concrete balance beam through the water.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel, some analysts suggested that Barak was keeping at a
remove from the bombing so that he could enter peace negotiations
with Syria, which in effect controls Lebanon, with a clean slate.
The analysts noted that although Barak had not voiced public
support for the bombing, he did not condemn it either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot imagine that the action was taken without the assent
of Barak,'' Yaron Ezrahi, a political scientist at the Israel
Democracy Institute, said. ``I think that Israel took keen
advantage of this interim period. They made a huge show of force.
But at the same time, Barak gets to keep his hands clean.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Radio Damascus Friday pinned the blame for the bombing on
Netanyahu, saying that he was trying to sabotage Barak's intention
to resume talks with Syria after a three-year freeze.
Optimistically, some people saw the bombing as a last show of force
by both sides and an overture to the impending negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has pledged to withdraw Israeli troops in a year from
southern Lebanon, where they have been mired since 1985 in a
low-level war with Shiite Muslim guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   For many residents in Qiryat Shemona, an Israeli town on the
border, the conflict could not end soon enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we are approaching the year 2000, and still once every two
weeks we find ourselves in the shelters,'' a lifelong resident,
Shimon Biton, 31, wrote in the newspaper Yediot Ahronoth. ``In my
opinion, we must proceed in negotiations with the Syrians, and then
finally we will be able to raise our children in security without
asking all the time what is this boom and what was that crash and
when will the next attack come.''
</P>
<P>
   In one shelter, No. 987, Fahima Flori, 60, said she was ready to
give up on her town. She spoke in a claustrophobic bunker in which
bunk beds hung from the walls like shelves, submarine style.
Children whined and cried.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't they just take Qiryat Shemona and make a military
base out of it?'' Ms. Flori asked. ``Then they can help us start
our life again somewhere else. Here it's fear that does the
talking.''
</P>
<P>
   Above, grief was speaking, as a few hundred people, mostly men,
gathered at the town cemetery to bury Shimon Elimelech, 45, a
construction engineer and father of four. On Thursday night,
Elimelech, a volunteer at the city crisis center, stepped above
ground for some air and to help out when a Katyusha rocket struck
City Hall. He was killed instantly.
</P>
<P>
   Television cameras repeatedly showed the pool of blood that
stained the ground beneath his body. In it was a cellular phone,
abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   The funeral service was under a concrete overhang, so that it
would be difficult to see from Lebanon. The body was surrounded by
armed guards, and the presiding rabbi was tearful and angry.
</P>
<P>
   ``He who rises to kill you, kill him first,'' the rabbi said.
``And we say to the government of Israel, `Hit them as they have
hit us.'''
</P>
<P>
   Appearing on television, a spokesman for Hezbollah said: ``We
are not afraid of deaths. We are not afraid of bombs or bombing.''
</P>
<P>
   But it appeared that after a night of fires had raged through
Lebanon, the Lebanese government had turned to Damascus and asked
the Syrians to rein in the guerrilla forces. In the afternoon,
along the coastal road leading to the demolished Awali Bridge and a
Syrian Army checkpoint, Syrian soldiers ``bunkered down'' in the
low dunes that face the sea. They were on the lookout for Israeli
gunboats, but none were visible.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed Haj had made his way up the coastal road to the bridge in
a minibus taxi. He lives in the south, but makes his living selling
vegetables in Beirut, and he was intent not to be derailed by the
bombardment. Haj climbed up a steep, makeshift walkway to the top
of the ruined bridge, where he was counting on the soldiers to help
him down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israel wants to destroy our economy to make us vulnerable,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli army officials said they had specifically focused on the
Lebanese public works, and not just guerrilla strongholds. Israel
holds Lebanon responsible for security.
</P>
<P>
   Public Security Minister Avigdor Kahalani told Israel Radio that
the Lebanese government could ``no longer remain apathetic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This time,'' Kahalani said, ``the pain on the Lebanese side
will be at least the same as the pain on the Israeli side.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
