u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOCKHEED-NYT &LR;      06-25 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOCKHEED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOCKHEED WILL SELL ASSETS WORTH $1 BILLION 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LESLIE WAYNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin Corp., the nation's largest military contractor,
plans to sell assets that are valued at around $1 billion,
according to people close to the company. The sale is aimed at
winnowing out noncore businesses and, perhaps, providing some lift
to a stock that has fallen more than 30 percent during the last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Announcement of the asset sales actually came earlier this
month, but without a price tag, when the chief executive of
Lockheed, Vance Coffman, warned that earnings for the next two
years would be about half of analysts' expectations. At that time,
he said the company, which is based in Bethesda, Md., would
consider shedding noncore assets through sales, spinoffs and public
offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, a more detailed account of just what assets could be on
the block was presented to the Lockheed board at a regularly
scheduled meeting. As details of the plan leaked out, Lockheed's
shares rose as much as 5 percent in midday trading, but settled
back to close at $35.875, up 68.75 cents. As recently as last
November, Lockheed traded at around $55 a share.
</P>
<P>
   No decision was taken by the board Friday, nor was one expected.
Instead, the board heard a review that said the company planned to
keep everything it currently has in the aircraft, space launching,
satellite and global telecommunications businesses. But areas that
could be shed include the non-military information services
business, energy and environmental operations, government
facilities management and electronics, including aircraft
electronics.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Lockheed repeated Friday a statement that
Coffman made earlier this month that this strategic analysis will
not be completed until the end of September. ``We decline to
comment on any specifics,'' said James Fetig, the Lockheed
spokesman. ``We have publicly acknowledged and announced last June
9 that we are undertaking a comprehensive strategic review. That
review is in progress and will take place over the next few months.
We will make announcements as decisions are made.''
</P>
<P>
   On June 9, as Coffman announced the anticipated earnings
decline, he also said the company would focus on its core military
and aerospace business and sell other assets: ``These changes are
what should bode well for us in the future,'' Coffman said then.
``Defense and aerospace are our core businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Loren Thompson, a military analyst with the Lexington Institute,
a research group in Arlington, Va., said that ``basically there are
two things going on here. First, Lockheed has determined it has too
many different product lines to manage efficiently. It has
determined it's not practical to try to be No. 1 or No. 2 in
everything. So it is trying to fashion a portfolio in areas where
they can be genuinely world class or that have exceptional growth
potential.''
</P>
<P>
   Credit Suisse First Boston analyst Pierre Chao said Lockheed's
actions are part of a natural evolution in the military industry.
After a decade of industry consolidations, many companies are now
left with unrelated business they acquired through acquisition of
other companies, but really do not need.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a step of portfolio cleaning,'' said Chao. ``When you put
together these big companies through mergers, you don't have a
choice about every single business you take in. It comes to the
inevitable point that companies are saying they don't have to be in
everything and now they are having to figure out what they have and
what they should get out of.''
</P>
<P>
   Another analyst, who asked not to be named, put it more bluntly:
``Sometimes you have to get smaller before you can get bigger or
focused before you can be successful. This is an attempt to get rid
of the distractions, the dead wood and the dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Lockheed's potential targets _ primarily the aircraft
avionics business _ resulted in some head-scratching.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's surprising is that Lockheed is finding that the
aircraft electronics business is an area where they cannot compete
very well,'' said Paul Nisbet, an analyst with JSA Research Inc. In
this line of business, Lockheed competes directly with Raytheon
Corp. and Northrop Grumman Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under such competitive pressure, they haven't been able to
make it perform very well,'' Nisbet added. ``Obviously, what
Lockheed is attempting to do is to trim from its portfolio the
businesses that are the lowest performers and add on where they
feel they can get much better performance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
