<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN LAWMAKERS APPROVE KOSOVO TROOP DEPLOYMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The upper house of Parliament on Friday approved the
deployment of 3,600 Russian peacekeeping troops in Kosovo despite
concern over the high price tag.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian defense ministry told the Parliament in closed
session that the deployment would cost $69 million this year, a
sizable sum for a nation that has chronic problems paying wages and
pensions on time.
</P>
<P>
   Col. Gen. Nikolai Staskov, the deputy commander of Russia's
peacekeeping troops, said the lead element would leave for Kosovo
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the constitution, the deployment of troops abroad requires
the approval of the Federation Council, as the upper house is
known. Voicing overwhelming support for the deployment, 158
representatives supported the move. Three abstained. None voted
against it.
</P>
<P>
   About 200 Russian troops raced to the Pristina airfield in
Kosovo earlier this month without the council's approval. But the
move attracted widespread support nonetheless from Russian
politicians, who boasted that Moscow had beat NATO troops to the
province.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian troops will be deployed under a compromise agreement
on command relations worked out between American and Russian
negotiators in Helsinki, Finland, last week.
</P>
<P>
   The United States says the arrangements insure that NATO remains
in overall charge of the peacekeeping effort. But Col. Gen. Leonid
Ivashov, a hard-line defense ministry official, underscored Friday
that the Russian troops will not be obliged to carry out NATO's
orders and would remain under Moscow's control.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
