<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0094 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONLINE-BONDS-ART-3TAK     06-25 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-BONDS-ART-3TAKES-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADING IN BONDS ON LINE, AT LAST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa., Calif., N.J., Ohio, Minn., N.Y., N.C.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic showing
5 electric trading systems for bonds; costs to retail investors in
bonds is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 27)  
 (af)  
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARRISBURG, Pa. _ It was a bold experiment in cyberspace
finance, and at 11:30 one recent Tuesday morning, it was about to
be tested in the real market.
</P>
<P>
   Robert A. Schoch, business manager of the Lancaster, Pa., school
district, huddled around a computer screen with Louis J. Verdelli
and other advisers here, waiting to see if anyone would bid over
the Internet for $29.2 million of the district's bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Five minutes, then 10, went by without a bid. Schoch grew
apprehensive. Then, just as the noon deadline for the auction was
drawing near, the screen came alive. Offers appeared from as far
away as Utah.
</P>
<P>
   At last Schoch allowed a smile to crease his poker face. The
district's first Internet financing had succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   The Lancaster auction was one small part of an accelerating
electronic revolution. The bond market is being dragged out of the
dark ages of fragmentation and opaque pricing, and thrown into a
fiercely competitive and still ill-defined future.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a thick veil of secrecy in the bond market,'' said
Marilyn Cohen, president of Envision Capital Management, a
fixed-income specialist in Los Angeles. ``It's one of the last
dinosaurs to fall.''
</P>
<P>
   By replacing old bonds with new through the electronic auction,
Lancaster will save $1.1 million, plugging an immediate budget hole
and allowing the city, the thrifty heart of Amish country, to avoid
raising taxes next year. Lancaster's advisers say the savings come
from the bigger market created by the Internet, which drew distant
underwriters who had rarely vied for Pennsylvania school bonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the impact of that is to lower their interest
rates,'' said Verdelli, senior managing consultant at Public
Financial Management, the adviser who arranged the bidding on a
system run by a Pittsburgh-based creature of the Internet,
MuniAuction.
</P>
<P>
   Click-of-the-mouse bidding on new issues is a striking leap
forward from past practice in the bond industry. Like most issuers,
both municipal and corporate, Lancaster used to negotiate bond
deals with a single underwriter; in many places, bidders must still
show up in person to drop a written bid into the equivalent of a
ballot box.
</P>
<P>
   And the upheaval in the secondary markets, where dealers,
brokers and investors trade bonds after they are issued, is bound
to prove more profound. After all, some $350 billion of bonds and
other debt securities are traded daily, 12 times the volume on the
New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Most stock trades are executed on exchange floors or through
NASDAQ's electronic dealer network, and each trade's volume and
price is immediately displayed to all. Not so with bonds, which
change hands much as they have for most of the century, mainly
through a patchwork of private channels. Bond trading on the New
York Stock Exchange is trivial, confined mainly to small lots.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was ever a market that needed liquidity and
transparency, it's fixed income,'' said Douglas M. Atkin, president
of Instinet. His firm, a unit of Reuters, operates the biggest
private stock-trading service for institutions. And later this
year, Instinet plans to start a dealer-to-dealer bond-trading
service, initially for United States Treasuries.
</P>
<P>
   While there are big changes under way in the bond business, they
have attracted far less attention than the more advanced revolution
in stocks, where instantaneously available prices have made
possible a frenzy of speculative activity and driven even Merrill
Lynch to announce a plan for cut-rate commissions.
</P>
<P>
   But the impact could be just as far-reaching. Already, spreads _
the difference between the prices at which professionals buy bonds
and the prices at which they sell them _ are beginning to narrow,
eating into bond dealers' profits.
</P>
<P>
   So, naturally, the dealers, are trying to hold off the
electronic tide. And brokers, the middlemen between investors and
dealers, worry about survival in a world where investors have new
power.
</P>
<P>
   Changes in how bonds trade are not always visible to ordinary
investors, most of whom own bonds only through mutual funds. But
ruptures in the system tend to echo loudly.
</P>
<P>
   An example was the virtual paralysis of the market for any bonds
other than Treasuries in the latter part of 1998, when foreign
turmoil touched off a ferocious flight to quality. The Federal
Reserve found itself obliged to engineer a rescue of a big hedge
fund that had bet disastrously on historic relationships among
various types of bonds. Surging interest rates shook stock markets.
</P>
<P>
   But while prices of securities can move at the speed of light,
market structures have been slow to change, and then only under
duress, as when industrywide fixed commissions for stocks were
abolished in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, Congress charged the Securities and Exchange
Commission with overseeing the creation of integrated markets for
both stocks and bonds. The bond part of the mandate has largely
been ignored.
</P>
<P>
   But now the pace is picking up: Arthur Levitt, the chairman of
the SEC, is pushing bond market openness. And this month, the House
of Representatives overwhelmingly passed a bill that would direct
the commission to adopt rules for collecting and publishing price,
volume and other transaction data for corporate bonds and enforce
them within a year. (The measure has no Senate counterpart yet.)
</P>
<P>
   Initially, modernizing bond markets will benefit mainly
institutional investors, but consumers stand to gain indirectly
through their stakes in mutual funds, pensions and retirement
accounts. Taxpayers will gain in places like Lancaster that exploit
the new systems.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   And within a few years, retail customers are very likely to be
in possession of basic information about bonds like transaction
charges and meaningful market prices. Until now, ignorance has cost
them more than $20 billion a year, by one estimate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fixed-income investor is the odd-man out in the market,''
said Arthur F. Goat, a retiree in Short Hills, N.J. ``You're flying
blind.''
</P>
<P>
   Dominated by the giant dealers who benefit most from the status
quo, the Bond Market Association, the industry's chief trade group,
has lobbied hard to slow and restrict the modernization process.
The industry has pledged to improve transparency in the corporate
bond markets, but says it is concerned that the costs involved
might outweigh the benefits by impeding trading activity and
harming market liquidity.
</P>
<P>
   But, prodded by regulators and some in Congress to fill the
market's information vacuum, even the trade group sees the writing
on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Electronic trading systems are rapidly becoming essential
tools in the portfolio and trading operations of both sell-side and
buy-side participants in the United States fixed-income securities
markets,'' the association's director of research, Andy Nybo,
acknowledged in his survey of 1998 industry developments. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the market's fragmentation, even professional
investors face serious disadvantages in trading corporate and
municipal bonds. To get a market price, they must conduct an
unwieldy and imprecise shopping expedition among a dozen or more
dealers, or rely on what one dealer tells them _ or, for less
active issues, fall back on what may be little more than a wild
guess.
</P>
<P>
   Individual investors, who hold only 5 percent of corporate but
30 percent of muni bonds, have even less clout.
</P>
<P>
   In municipal bonds, for example, the best an individual investor
can do is to view the prior day's prices for the 1,000 or so issues
that may have traded, out of 1.4 million outstanding, on a Web site
run by the bond association (www.bondmarkets.com). Some of those _
there is no telling which _ are dealer-to-dealer prices unavailable
to ordinary investors.
</P>
<P>
   With comparison shopping so difficult, dealers can charge large
markups, especially on lesser-quality bonds, and generally get the
better of any bargain. Quoted prices can be all over the map.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday afternoon, for example, different dealers were
offering Ford Motor Credit 5} percent notes due in February 2004 at
anywhere from $95.472 (yielding 6.9 percent) to $96.034 (yielding
6.75 percent) per $100.
</P>
<P>
   ``Price competition is at the heart of the free-market system,''
said Rep. Michael Oxley, R-Ohio, who heads a House subcommittee
that held a hearing on bond trading last September. ``And you can't
have true competition if people have a hard time figuring out
exactly what they're paying.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a big reason the industry has dragged its feet: dealers'
fear that the traditionally wide spreads in bond trading will
shrink.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who are living off the spreads, their profits are
going to come down,'' said Frank D. Korth, a portfolio manager at
the National City Investment Management Co. in Cleveland. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Threatened, too, are the firms that advise issuers and
underwrite bond issues. ``The intermediaries are scared to death,''
said Myles Harrington, a founder of MuniAuction, the firm that owns
the system used in the Lancaster auction.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the company drew a $6 million investment from the
Carlyle Group, a private Washington investment firm whose
principals include former Treasury Secretary James Baker III and
Frank Carlucci, a former Defense secretary.
</P>
<P>
   As with Merrill Lynch's belated decision to embrace online stock
trading, bond dealers are being forced to weigh what they would
lose in narrower spreads against the risk of losing business to
upstarts and the possibility that trading volume would rise if
investors found the market less treacherous.
</P>
<P>
   An early effort to breach the wall was Capitalink, J.P. Morgan's
1989 venture into direct sale of corporate bonds to institutional
investors, bypassing other financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional bond market players howled. ``The competitive threat
Capitalink poses to our industry cannot be overemphasized,'' a
Merrill Lynch official, Richard Fuscone, wrote in a memo quoted in
a 1996 paper by Robert J. Kauffman of the University of Minnesota
and Arthur R. Kennedy III of Morgan. After Merrill bought an entire
issue of Deere &AMP; Co. notes at a dog-in-the-manger price to pre-empt
its trading on Capitalink, Morgan gave up.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, Larry E. Fondren, an entrepreneur who ran a
sort of computer-dating service for insurance companies _ arranging
joint ventures and advising on mergers and reinsurance _ tried his
hand. He set up Intervest Financial Services, which allowed clients
to trade anonymously with one another and with dealers, and tried
to negotiate a deal to link it to computer terminals of Bloomberg
L.P., then on 60,000 clients' desks.
</P>
<P>
   Fondren struck a deal in 1995, but Bloomberg pulled the plug
after six months, partly relented, and then cut Intervest off for
good in 1998, said Fondren, who has filed a breach-of-contract
suit.
</P>
<P>
   In court papers, Fondren said Bloomberg told him it had acted at
the insistence of bond dealers, because clients were getting too
much price information.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Bloomberg, which is partly owned by Merrill,
said that Intervest was dropped because of low trading activity and
that the allegations were groundless.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill itself has had a change of heart since it helped thwart
Capitalink. ``Ten years ago, we did not believe electronic
distribution was in the best interests of clients or the
industry,'' said Timothy Gilles, a Merrill spokesman. But the
markets and technology have evolved, and Merrill now backs
electronic trading, he said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In any event, the concept is back with a vengeance. The Bond
Market Association says there are now more than two dozen
electronic systems for marketing or trading bonds. At the start of
1998, there were 11. ``It's a brave new world out there,'' said
Edwin McGuinn, president of Limitrader Securities, one dealer that
has hung out a cybershingle.
</P>
<P>
   Entrants in the electronic race include individual
entrepreneurs, banks, securities dealers, bond brokers and
information purveyors like Bloomberg and Reuters. Most focus on
attracting institutional buyers of bonds, whose high volume they
hope will make their systems viable.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, a consortium of seven giant financial-services
companies announced a new trading system for dealers called
Brokertec.
</P>
<P>
   So far, most of the electronic systems are bulletin boards for
dealers to post offerings; final prices are set when trades are
consummated by phone. In a few cases, buyers and sellers see prices
on the screen at which they can count on executing a trade.
</P>
<P>
   Other systems bring dealers and institutions together for
real-time trading or periodic order-matching sessions, with
traders' anonymity a big selling point.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the new-issue auction systems like MuniAuction,
which make possible innovations like permitting bidding on selected
maturities out of a series that formerly had to be bought in its
entirety
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, bidders see where their offers rank (though not their
rivals' specific bids) and are free to raise their bids repeatedly,
as some did in the Lancaster auction. In traditional auctions,
bidders get just one shot.
</P>
<P>
   Lancaster's electronic auction of new bonds is one of about 200
such municipal borrowings since MuniAuction's first deal in late
1997. As for corporations, many now routinely market commercial
paper _ short-term i.o.u.'s _directly to investors, bypassing
broker-dealers, and there are systems being developed for selling
longer-term corporate debt this way.
</P>
<P>
   The government's Treasury Direct program allows investors with
as little as $1,000 to bid for new bills, notes and bonds.
</P>
<P>
   But while the old methods are crumbling, the process is likely
to take several years _ and it may never make bonds as transparent
as stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Micah S. Green, executive vice president of the Bond Market
Association, told a House panel in March that he supported the
goals of the proposed legislation and said his group would soon add
to its Web site the previous day's dealer-to-dealer prices for 100
or so of the most active investment-grade corporate bonds. (The new
data are due to make their debut this week.)
</P>
<P>
   But he sought to persuade lawmakers that there were key
differences in bond and stock markets. For instance, he said, most
bonds do not trade actively: only 4 percent of about 400,000
corporate issues outstanding in 1996 traded even once that year. He
also contended that too much transparency could increase volatility
in thin markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Revealing prices and trading volumes instantaneously could
hurt market liquidity,'' Green said, by, say, making it obvious
when someone was trying to unwind a large position piecemeal. He
asked Congress to choose evolutionary change, led by the private
sector, over government-mandated change.
</P>
<P>
   Whichever path is chosen, it is clear that the bond business is
galloping toward an automated electronic future with fewer
intermediaries.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, ``if you wanted to sell a block of $10 million
in municipal bonds, you'd call up 20 brokers and ask them to give
you a bid,'' said Peter J. Allegrini, managing director of
Prudential Investments, who runs a portfolio of high-yield
municipals. ``Today, you plug your bonds into the Bloomberg and
press a couple of buttons, and the whole process is down to 15
minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   In a few years, perhaps one-third of trades in Treasury debt
will take place electronically, said F. James Claire, director of
taxable fixed-income trading for a unit of First Union Bank in
Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   But if Claire's attitudes reflect those of many bond traders,
electronic trading will develop more slowly in markets for
corporate and tax-exempt bonds, where trading is thinner.
</P>
<P>
   There simply is no substitute in a decentralized market, he
said, for communicating by voice with the other players. ``You want
to be able to talk to a guy and hear noise in the background; you
need that color to hear what's going on,'' Claire said. ``You're
not going to get any color looking at the screen.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he said, screen updates sometimes lag when trading
action heats up, and electronic screens do not leave behind as
solid a transaction record as do telephone calls, which are
routinely recorded.
</P>
<P>
   So much of Levitt's lament about the least-liquid sectors of the
bond market seems likely to linger. ``The sad truth,'' the SEC
chairman said, ``is that investors in the corporate bond market do
not enjoy the same access to information as a car buyer or a home
buyer or, dare I say, a fruit buyer. And that's unacceptable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
