<SLUG> BC-GLF-BUICK-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAGGERT JOINS PERRY FOR SHARE OF LEAD IN BUICK CLASSIC
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARRISON, N.Y. _ Chris Perry has a father who pitched in the
major leagues and an uncle who is in the Baseball Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, people expected Perry to excel in athletics, too. But
Perry believes that choosing golf over baseball made life easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if I had played baseball, there'd be a lot more
pressure,'' said Perry, son of the former major league pitcher Jim
Perry and the nephew of Gaylord Perry, a Hall of Fame pitcher.
``With golf I got to where I am not because of my name; I got to
where I am because of what I did.''
</P>
<P>
   What Perry did Friday was good enough to share first place after
the second round of the Buick Classic. Taking advantage of a
favorable 7:42 a.m. tee time and shooting a 6-under-par 66, Perry
stood at 6-under par for the tournament (136), tied with Jeff
Maggert, who shot a 65 Friday. Stephen Ames, the first-round
leader, shot a 72 and was one stroke off the lead at 5-under par.
He was tied for third place with Duffy Waldorf, who shot a 67.
</P>
<P>
   This has already been a big year for Maggert, who is fourth on
the PGA Tour money list with more than $1.64 million in earnings,
including his $1 million victory at the Andersen Consulting Match
Play Championship. After his 65, which included a streak of four
consecutive birdies, Maggert looked forward to what could be
another successful weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the way I played the last nine holes put a good
taste in my mouth,'' said Maggert, who teed off on No. 10 and
finished with a 31 on the front side. ``I've had some good
tournaments here in the past. I'd like to win here before I'm done
with my tour days. Who knows? Maybe this is the year.''
</P>
<P>
   But the weekend will be wide open. Four players were tied at
4-under par after Friday: Fred Couples, Lee Janzen, Tom Byrum and
Frank Nobilo. Janzen, a two-time U.S. Open Championship winner who
won the 1994 Buick Classic, shot a 67, while Couples, the 1992
Masters champion, shot a 69.
</P>
<P>
   With early morning sun, warm temperatures and afternoon breezes
making the greens at Westchester Country Club table-top firm,
conditions were more difficult than during Thursday's
opening-round. But Perry made the most of his &QC; 5 a.m. wake-up call,
finishing before some players even started and making four birdies,
one bogey, and an eagle at the par-5, 505-yard No. 9.
</P>
<P>
   Perry's eagle came via a strong drive, a solid 4-wood shot that
landed in the center of the green and a 35-foot putt that dropped
into the cup. Showing a steady putting stroke all day, Perry also
made a 9-footer for birdie on No. 8 and an 8-footer for birdie at
No. 10. When Perry gets on the green, he does not lack confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always been a great putter; I have always had a good
touch,'' said Perry, who grew up in Minnesota playing a variety of
sports but gravitated to golf around the ninth grade. ``When I get
the speed of the green, and when they are fairly smooth, I'm fairly
confident that I'm going to be around the hole. Playing here for
years I feel I know the breaks of the greens.''
</P>
<P>
   After he joined the tour in 1985, it took Perry 377 starts to
win his first event, last year's B.C. Open. But Perry, who is 37,
has been very consistent in recent years, finishing 48th on the
money list in 1997 and 39th last year. He entered this week's
tournament No. 31 on the money list ($720,423), and winning this
weekend's $450,000 first-place check would vault him over the $1
million mark for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Perry tied for 42nd at last weekend's U.S. Open, but he finished
the last round in memorable fashion: crawling the final 10 feet to
the 18th green as a salute to the difficulty of Pinehurst Resort
and Country Club's No. 2 course.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was funny,'' said Perry, who finished at 17-over
par at Pinehurst. ``I tried on every shot, I didn't play that
badly, and I still shot 17-over par. I had to do something to
release the whole week. I didn't do it to mock the USGA or
anything. I did it as a funny way to laugh off the week, and the
fans loved it. I'm looking forward to the weekend.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
