<DOCNO> NYT19990625.0358 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0109 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NY-SCHOOLKIDS-     06-25 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NY-SCHOOLKIDS-ART-950(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBANIANS ADD A WRINKLE TO SCHOOL PEACEKEEPING EFFORTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Before Broadway ever imagined a Shark or a Jet,
Robert DeSena knew all there was to know about turf and colors,
about ethnic feuds and the sting of a punch thrown in a rumble.
</P>
<P>
   As a teen-ager in the days of doo-wop, when gangs had names like
the Fordham Baldies and the Bergen Street Dukes, he ran with his
own crew in the Bay Ridge section of Brooklyn, called the 86th
Street Boys. ``I could deliver 300 guys; that's what I was known
for,'' said DeSena, now 57.
</P>
<P>
   As an English teacher, 20 years later, DeSena stepped in to make
peace between battling Italians and blacks at John Dewey High
School in Brooklyn in 1975, carving from that experience an
organization known as the Council for Unity. Today, the council is
still being called into New York City public schools, like Herbert
H. Lehman and Christopher Columbus High Schools in the northeast
Bronx, to keep things calm.
</P>
<P>
   At these schools, DeSena and his program are being used to ease
simmering tensions between blacks and whites, Bloods and Crips,
Latin Kings and Albanians, and other groups that have had a history
of antagonism. But DeSena says he has encountered a significant
obstacle to any lasting accord: the Albanian teen-agers, a central
group whose numbers are swelling with the arrival of Kosovar
refugees, have not sat down with the others.
</P>
<P>
   Isolated by the circumstances of their recent migration and at
times mistrustful of outsiders, many Albanian youths have balked
for 16 months at joining the Bloods and the Zulus, the Latin Kings
and the Netas in the circle of desks at Lehman where the council
mediates disputes and brokers harmony.
</P>
<P>
   DeSena fears a similar reception at Columbus, where the number
of Albanian students is larger and where the council will set up an
identical program in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is not hypothetical. Although neither Columbus nor
Lehman is besieged by violence, there are gang flare-ups outside
the schools, the majority of them escalating from small
misunderstandings. In the most recent one, which took place six
weeks ago outside Lehman, the Bloods, who claim the colors red and
black as their own, spotted a teen-ager outside the school wearing
a red and black Albanian flag as a bandanna.
</P>
<P>
   It became a matter of honor: Blood pride versus the sort of
ethnic identification that led young Albanian-Americans to Kosovo
to battle Serbs. The fight engulfed about 15 students. One of them,
a Blood, was badly beaten.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand that that's the flag of their homeland,'' said a
Blood who uses the nickname Elmo and was involved in the fight.
``But we don't like it. That's our point of view. We really don't
care.''
</P>
<P>
   Burim Shabaj, 19, a senior at Lehman, said he could not fathom
such an attitude at a time when ethnic Albanians were dying. On his
left arm is a tattoo of the Albanian flag, a double-headed eagle
with its talons extended, imprinted in black against a red
background. ``That has always been our colors,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The colors issue has also surfaced at Columbus, Altin Kamberaj,
17, said. ``We are very nationalistic,'' he said, pulling out a
wallet emblazoned with an image of the Albanian flag. ``We wear a
red flag. People think we are doing it just to start trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   When there are fights, the impact can extend beyond the small
number of students involved. Mimoza Novaj, 16, said that after the
fight with the Bloods over the Albanian flag, things were a bit
tense at Lehman for several days, even for the many Albanian
students like her, whose only collective activity has been raising
money for the Kosovar refugees. ``A lot of us had nothing to do
with it, and we got approached,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Even their rivals acknowledge that Albanian students do not
start many fights, although they often do not shy away from them,
at times showing up in a group of 40 to redress a slight to one of
their own.
</P>
<P>
   At Lehman, about 100 of the 4,000 students are ethnic Albanians.
At Columbus, the number is about 250 out of 3,400.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't bother nobody,'' said Shabaj, who is in his fifth
year at Lehman. ``We just like to have fun. But if they do bother
us, we go after them. If we have to, we fight them.''
</P>
<P>
   DeSena said the perceived influence of the Albanian students
makes it essential to bring them into the dialogue sponsored by the
Council for Unity, especially as the Albanian population in the
Bronx, estimated at 26,000, grows with the arrival this year of an
expected 5,000 refugees from Kosovo. He is trying to reach the
teen-agers by working through leaders in the local community of
Albanians, whose real estate investments, success in starting small
businesses and devotion to family life are credited with
stabilizing several Bronx neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Although Albanian students have been invited to join the Council
for Unity, many are reluctant to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most Albanians like to keep to themselves,'' said Vlad, a
17-year-old from Lehman. ``They don't like anybody looking into
their business. They try to stay with their own kind.''
</P>
<P>
   At Lehman, many Albanian students gather in the afternoon
outside the East Tremont Diner, opposite the school, segregating
themselves by ethnicity as many groups do. The Bloods, for example,
congregate in nearby Westchester Square, several blocks away.
Unlike the Albanians, however, these other groups are represented
on the council.
</P>
<P>
   Several Albanian students said it was inaccurate to read their
ethnic pride as arrogance. One Columbus student said he did not
understand why Albanians were even being asked to join such a
program. ``Why are we Albanians even involved in this?'' Kamberaj
asked. ``We don't even have a gang.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Members of groups like the Latin Kings and the Bloods do not
embrace the term gang either, although these groups have
reputations for violence. Their members said they viewed them as
associations or nations and described their mission as defensive,
not predatory. But many of those groups have ranks and initiation
rituals.
</P>
<P>
   Several Albanian youths said they were simply members of a
tight-knit ethnic group. Some teen-agers, however, have confused
matters by referring to themselves as ABI, or Albanian Boys Inc.
</P>
<P>
   That name is also occasionally found scrawled on school walls,
but officials do not believe it is an active gang. At both high
schools, the principals said that the hallways were safe and the
atmosphere unthreatening. Nonetheless, they said, they support the
council's mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't see a problem,'' said Robert Leder, principal of
Lehman. ``But it could happen here or anywhere, and the more these
kids feel comfortable, then obviously the less chance there is of
anything happening.''
</P>
<P>
   At Columbus, principal Gerald Garfin said, ``Tolerance goes on
and then, every now and then, something explodes, creates tension,
and then we work to make sure it dissipates.''
</P>
<P>
   Historically, there have been several incidents in the
neighborhoods of the two schools. In two separate bias incidents in
1992, black and Hispanic children on their way to local middle
schools were accosted by white teen-agers who identified themselves
as members of ABI and tried to paint them white, investigators
said. In another incident, outside Columbus four years ago, two
teen-agers were hospitalized after a brawl between Albanian youths
and members of the Zulu Nation street gang.
</P>
<P>
   Donika Shehu, executive director of the Albanian Assistance
Center, which is helping refugees resettle in the Bronx, said she
was concerned that as the immigrants arrived, their children might
be drawn into groups that taught them to distrust strangers. ``This
is not a territorial war,'' said Ms. Shehu, who supports the
council's efforts. ``We have to integrate the society.''
</P>
<P>
   The council runs programs in 45 schools, where it tries to ease
tension by letting members vent and having them discuss set topics
like cultural diversity. Several days ago, DeSena saw his first
glimpse of progress. A few teen-agers in the Albanian-American Club
at Lehman indicated that they would join the council in the fall.
They said they had not previously known of the group's existence.
DeSena said he was delighted that Albanians would be taking part in
the dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a global city,'' he said. ``You have to have some
awareness of diversity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
