<P>
   (NYT21) BEACON, N.Y. -- June 25, 1999 -- NY-DAVINCI-HORSE, 6-25
-- Craig Arnoff, 8, looks at ``Il Cavallo'' a 24-foot-tall bronze
sculpture of a horse which is faithful to a design by Leonardo da
Vinci on Friday some 60 miles north of New York City. The public
showing here is the last step before the sculpture's seven pieces
are dismantled and flown in an Alitalia jumbo jet to Milan, where
the horse will be erected on a pedestal, welded into a single
piece, and unveiled on September 10, the 500th anniversary of the
day the French army occupied the Ducal palace and disfigured Da
Vinci's original prototype. (Joyce Dopkeen/New York Times Photo)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) FT. McPHERSON, Ga. -- June 25, 1999 -- POLLOCK-COX, 6-25
-- Marteller Pollock Jr., left, receiving a Bronze Star from Col.
Dennis Hardy during ceremoinies at Ft McPherson on Friday;
Pollock's wife, Rosa, center. Pollock fought in World War II and is
only now receiving his medal. (Louie Favorite/Atlanta
Journal-Constitution Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- June 25, 1999 -- NY-LECTURES, 6-25 -- The
composer Philip Glass addresses an audience at the Kitchen on
``Collaboration and the New Technology.'' New Yorkers could also
hear lectures about cross-hybridizing corn and democracy in Cuba.
Call them seminars or lectures or discussions, but the city is
truly brimming with forums for the thinking man, woman and child.
(George M. Gutierrez/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- June 25, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 27 --
ILLEGITIMATE-CHILDREN, 6-25 -- Anthony Haden-Guest, now officially
acknowledged in Burke's Peerage and Baronetage. Haden-Guest, 62, is
now, officially, identified as the eldest, though illegitimate,
child of his late father, the fourth Baron Haden-Guest. Since
Haden-Guest's parents did not marry until two years after his
birth, the barony went to his younger and legitimately born brother
Christopher, who is now married to Jamie Lee Curtis. (Miles
Ladin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) UNDATED -- June 25, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 27 --
ABOUT-CARS-MERCEDES-2, 6-25 -- The Mercedes-Benz S-Class now has
steering-wheel switches and a screen that controls various
accessories. Huge, heavy and haughty, bristling with technology
under its slab-sided styling, the S-Class has long been a global
symbol of power and success for princes and prime ministers,
generals and godfathers, capitalists who have conquered markets and
revolutionaries who have come to power. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) UNDATED -- June 25, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 27 --
ABOUT-CARS-MERCEDES-1, 6-25 -- Some big Mercedes sedans through the
years. From left, Mercedes Benz 300, produced 1951-'62; 300SE,
produced 1961-'65; 450SE, produced 1972-'80; 550SE, produced
1979-'91; S500, produced 1991-'98; the 2000 model S-Class. Huge,
heavy and haughty, bristling with technology under its slab-sided
styling, the S-Class has long been a global symbol of power and
success. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) DJAKOVICA, Yugoslavia -- June 25, 1999 -- KOSOVO-RDP-2,
6-25 -- A vendor sells his products from the back of a truck near
what is left of the market area on Friday. Despite NATO's attempts
to bring security to the province and the ethnic Albanian rebel
Kosovo Liberation Army's promise to demilitarize, Albanians openly
and unapologetically are taking revenge on Serbs for the ethnic
killings this spring and for years of oppression beforehand.
(Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) UROSEVIC, Yugoslavia -- June 25, 1999 -- KOSOVO-RDP,
6-25 -- An Albanian man, left, lights a cigarette for a Serb
neighbor who was leaving the town on Friday. A group of Serbs left
to escape reprisals from ethnic Albanians. The man at left was
chastised by passing Albanians for talking to the departing Serbs.
(Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) ORLANDO, Fla. -- June 25, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 27
-- INVEST-WITH-DePRINCE/TIERNEY, 6-25 -- Gregory DePrince, a
portfolio manager at DePrince, Race &AMP; Zolo, plays basketball with
his daughter Jessica, 9, in the driveway of their house. DePrince
jointly manages the Harbor Value fund with David Tierney, a a
managing partner at Richards, Tierney in Chicago, whom he hardly
knows. An odd relationship to be sure, but the formula seems to
work. Harbor Value returned 21.8 percent, annualized, for the three
years ended June 18. (Andy Lyons/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) LANCASTER, Pa. -- June 25, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE
27 -- ONLINE-BONDS, 6-25 -- Louis J. Verdelli, center, a financial
adviser, shows Robert A. Schoch, left, the business manager of the
public school district in Lancaster, the online system for
auctioning $29.2 million of the district's bonds. The auction was
one small part of an accelerating electronic revolution. The bond
market is being dragged out of the dark ages of fragmentation and
opaque pricing, and thrown into a fiercely competitive and still
ill-defined future. (John Zeedick/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- June 25, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 27 --
COOKBOOK-MODEL, 6-25 -- Padma Lakshmi, author of a new cookbook,
``Easy Exotic:: A Model's Low-Fat Recipes From Around the World,''
is at home in the kitchen. ``Because of what I look like I've been
wined and dined everywhere,'' she says. ``I've had my share of
Eurotrash older guys and they've taken me to wonderful restaurants.
I could taste what was in the food, and I stole the recipes.''
(Nancy Siesel/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- June 25, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 27 --
RICH-DIVORCEES-JOBS-3, 6-25 -- Mary Meehan, a decorator, says that
when she was growing up, ``proper young ladies got married.'' She
did but, now divorced, she finds that ``men in their 50s ... there
aren't that many for us 50-year-olds.'' (Jeffery A. Salter/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- June 25, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 27 --
RICH-DIVORCEES-JOBS-2, 6-25 -- Barbara de Portago says there is a
difference between the hard economic reality of the divorced woman
and the myth of ``the divorcee, with that first accent on the first
e.'' Being a divorcee, she says, ``means that you're heavily
subsidized by the former husband, swathed in haute couture - you're
bejeweled. Of course, a divorcee has no children, is massaged in
oil and is lolling about on the French Riviera or Gstaad.''
(Jeffery A. Salter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- June 25, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 27 --
RICH-DIVORCEES-JOBS, 6-25 -- After her divorce in 1992, Elise
Henning became a real estate broker, selling luxury properties to
the social and the trying-to-be-social. By night, she was a Palm
Beach party planner, helping women create ``beautiful parties'' for
around $200 a guest. ``I was so out there, networking, meeting more
people,'' she says. ``The jobs gave me an income, access and a
great reason, as a single woman, for being at all the parties.''
(Jeffery A. Salter/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) ALPHARETTA, Ga. -- June 25, 1999 -- PET-RESORT-3-COX,
06-25 -- Wanda Lawhorn plays with two clients of Pet Lodge, on a
raft in the pet kennel resort's pool. Darby, the English Bulldog on
the front on the raft, can't swim, so Ms. Lawhorn pulls him on the
raft so he can be part of the fun. Pet Lodge's canine guests get
one-on-one attention with 30-minute walks on trails in the wooded
areas of the resort, playtimes in groups or with an employee, swim
times and even a workout with a tennis ball machine. (Phil
Skinner/Atlanta Journal-Constitution Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) ALPHARETTA, Ga. -- June 25, 1999 -- PET-RESORT-2-COX,
06-25 -- Ben, a golden retriever who was rescued from a local
animal shelter, has lots of toys to choose from at the Pet Lodge,
one of the newest, upscale kennels in the Atlanta area. ``We've
been taking him there for about a year,'' says Lloyd Smith, Ben's
owner. ``He gets playtime and goes swimming. It's a treat for
him.'' (Phil Skinner/Atlanta Journal-Constitution Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) ALPHARETTA, Ga. -- June 25, 1999 -- PET-RESORT-1-COX,
06-25 -- At Pet Lodge, Ben, a golden retriever who was rescued from
a local animal shelter, dives into the pool after a tennis ball.
His friend, Sailor, waits for his turn. Pet Lodge is one of the
newest, upscale kennels in the Atlanta area. (Phil Skinner/Atlanta
Journal-Constitution Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) LONDON -- June 25, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 27 --
BIZ-MANAGEMENT-ENRON, 6-25 -- Frustrated that he couldn't influence
profits at a New York bank, Thomas Gros took a marketing job at
Enron. Now, from sites in London (shown) and the United States,
he's setting up a system to let companies trade their excess
telecommunications capacity. (Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEAR SIDON, Lebanon -- June 25, 1999 -- ISRAEL-LEBANON-3,
6-25 --Members of the Lebanese Army assit pedestrians in
negotiating what is left of the Awali Bridge on Friday. Israeli
jets and helicopters destroyed this bridge as well as two power
substations outside of Beirut on Thursday. The Israeli army said
its planes carried out the bombings in response to Hezbollah rocket
attacks on northern Israel earlier Thursday. (Courtney Kealy/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) KIRYAT SHEMONAH, Israel -- June 25, 1999 --
ISRAEL-LEBANON-2, 6-25 -- Comforted by an Israeli officer, the
children of Shimon Elimelech pay their respects to their father
while standing near the doorway of their bomb shelter on Friday.
The children's father was killed last night during a rocket attack
on this northern Israeli town. Due to the continued threat of
attacks, the body was brought to the bomb shelter for the family to
pay their respects before it was taken to the cemetery. (Rina
Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) KIRYAT SHEMONAH, Israel -- June 25, 1999 --
ISRAEL-LEBANON, 6-25 -- Mourners during the funeral for Shimon
Elimelech on Friday. Elimelech was killed last night during a
rocket attack in the northern Israeli town. The cemetery's
perimeter, in the background, is guarded by an Israeli soldier as
it lies near the Lebanese border and Israel's self-imposed
``security zone.'' Beirut was without power and residents in
northern Israel huddled in bomb shelters on Friday during the
heaviest fighting between Israel and Lebanon in three years. The
attacks killed nine Lebanese, two Israelis and wounded at least 57
others. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
