<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Friday, 06/25/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) UNDATED -- June 25, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 27 --
BIZ-WORLD-NFL, 6-25 -- As maestro of the NFL's improbable effort to
export American football to Europe, Oliver Luck decided long ago
that he was selling more than a sport. After all, football is a
game that few Europeans have ever played and that most find
bewildering, with players who have unfamiliar names and do not
speak the local language. So Luck, 39, markets his sport as
entertainment, with loud music and long-legged cheerleaders. ``The
last thing we want to do is to bore people,'' he says. (Kevin
Terrell/NFLP Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) NEW YORK -- June 25, 1999 -- KOSOVO-NY-SCHOOLKIDS, 6-25
-- Some Albanian youths wonder why they should join talks with
street gangs. ``We don't even have a gang,'' says Altin Kamberaj,
center, with Fidain Elzaj, left, and Sadik Mirjovic outside
Columbus High School in the Bronx. (Chris Maynard/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) WASHINGTON-- June 25, 1999 -- CLINTON-GORE, 6-25 -- Vice
President Al Gore delivers a statement in support of President
Clinton at the White House following Clinton's impeachment in
December, 1998. Clinton is angered and hurt by Gore's conspicuous
efforts to distance himself from Clinton's behavior in the Monica
Lewinsky scandal, according to presidential aides and advisers.
They say the Gore's words have created a friction that never before
existed between the two men. (Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) WASHINGTON-- June 25, 1999 -- CLINTON-CONGRESS-3, 6-25
-- Vice President Al Gore delivers a statement in support of
President Clinton at the White House following Clinton's
impeachment in December, 1998. Clinton is angered and hurt by Vice
President Gore's conspicuous efforts to distance himself from
Clinton's behavior in the Monica Lewinsky scandal, according to
presidential aides and advisers. They say the Gore'sz words have
created a friction that never before existed between the two men.
(Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) WASHINGTON-- June 25, 1999 -- CLINTON-CONGRESS-2, 6-25
-- President Clinton walks down the stairs from the Old Executive
Office Building followed by Press Secretary Joe Lockhart and
flanked by National Security Advisor Sandy Berger, right, on
Friday. In a marathon news conference, Clinton challenged
Republicans to work with him on domestic legislation so ``this
summer should be a season of progress,'' but made clear that he was
just as willing to blame them for failure as to share credit for
success. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) WASHINGTON-- June 25, 1999 -- CLINTON-CONGRESS, 6-25 --
President Clinton during a news conference on Friday. Clinton
challenged Republicans to work with him on domestic legislation so
`''this summer should be a season of progress,'' but made clear
that he was just as willing to blame them for failure as to share
credit for success. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) WALLULA, Wash. -- June 24, 1999 -- LABOR-IMMIGRANTS-2,
6-24 -- Maria Martinez, a leader of the striking meat-plant
workers, during a protest march. In a sign of the increasing voice
of new immigrants in the labor movement, a group of workers at a
local meat processing plant that includes Laotians, Mexicans,
Vietnamese and Bosnians has organized a wildcat strike because as
Martinez put it: ``Enough is enough.'' (Jackie Johnston/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- June 25, 1999 -- NY-SCHOOLS, 6-25 -- Robert
Riccobono, superintendant of a district in the Brownsville section
of Brooklyn, in one of his classrooms on Friday. When New York City
Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew announced a sweeping shake-up earlier
in the week, closing 13 low performing schools and taking direct
control of 43 others, Riccobono, the superintendent known for some
innovative programs in District 9, was among those fired. His fate
is a telling example of the difficulty in reforming a city's worst
school district. (Ruby Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) MANCHESTER, N.H. -- June 21, 1999 -- MEDICAID-DENTAL-2,
6-21 -- Opal Caples waits for the anesthesia to take effect before
her dentist extracts some of her teeth. Even though the vast
majority of the poorest Americans, particularly children, are
covered by Medicaid for dental care, they are not getting it. In
some cases, dentists loathe the paperwork involved in putting
forward a Medicaid claim. In others, Medicaid patients, often with
transport and day care problems, are likelier to miss appointments.
(Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) MANCHESTER, N.H. -- June 25, 1999 -- MEDICAID-DENTAL,
6-25 -- Dr. Jay Afrow performs dental work on a five-year old boy
at his clinic last month. Even though the vast majority of the
poorest Americans, particularly children, are covered by Medicaid
for dental care, they are not getting it. In some cases, dentists
loathe the paperwork involved in putting forward a Medicaid claim.
In others, Medicaid patients, often with transport and day care
problems, are likelier to miss appointments. (Evan Richman/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) BEACON, N.Y. -- June 25, 1999 -- NY-DAVINCI-HORSE, 6-25
-- Craig Arnoff, 8, looks at ``Il Cavallo'' a 24-foot-tall bronze
sculpture of a horse which is faithful to a design by Leonardo da
Vinci on Friday some 60 miles north of New York City. The public
showing here is the last step before the sculpture's seven pieces
are dismantled and flown in an Alitalia jumbo jet to Milan, where
the horse will be erected on a pedestal, welded into a single
piece, and unveiled on September 10, the 500th anniversary of the
day the French army occupied the Ducal palace and disfigured Da
Vinci's original prototype. (Joyce Dopkeen/New York Times Photo)
LITE
</P>
