<HEADLINE>
CLINTON REQUESTS `SEASON OF PROGRESS' WITH CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(kd) 
 By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON &UR;  &LR; _ President Clinton challenged Republicans Friday to
work with him on domestic legislation so ``this summer should be a
season of progress,'' but made clear that he was just as willing to
blame them for failure as to share credit for success.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech at Georgetown University and in a news conference
later, Clinton identified four bills as available for quick action
because of broad bipartisan agreement. But one, campaign finance
legislation, is strongly opposed by Republican leaders, and a
second, the so-called patients' bill of rights, has Democrats
seeking very broad application and a right to sue health
maintenance organizations, two features opposed by most
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The two other bills _ one that would allow disabled people
returning to work to retain federal heath benefits, the other a
raise in the minimum wage _ are measures that Republican leaders
seem ready to accept.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Nicholson, the Republican national chairman, attacked the
president's comments, saying he ``passed up an opportunity to work
for real bipartisan solutions to America's problems.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He chose instead,'' Nicholson said, ``to create issues for the
election campaign of Al Gore and other Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans, eager to leave town for the weekend before
the late-afternoon news conference, held a rally Friday morning to
urge the president to back a major tax cut, a national missile
defense and legislation to allow states to spend federal education
dollars more freely. Speaker Dennis Hastert attacked inheritance
taxes and the income-tax feature known as the ``marriage penalty,''
which subjects some married working couples to higher taxes than
they together would pay if they were single.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was asked about only one of the Republican proposals,
use of money from the federal budget surplus to cut taxes. ``I'm
not against tax cuts,'' he said, but Medicare and Social Security
must be dealt with first. And he opposed any tax cuts whose result
would be ``to cut education or cut health care or cut our
investments in the environment.''
</P>
<P>
   The president spoke at Georgetown about his desire to proceed in
a spirit of ``honorable compromise'' on issues where the parties'
approaches differ, as on Medicare and Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   But at the news conference he assailed House Republicans for
their action on gun control legislation, saying they had voted to
weaken ``current law by letting criminals store their guns at
pawnshops.'' A provision that would have eliminated background
checks when guns are retrieved from pawnshops was included in the
gun bill that the House defeated last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   At Georgetown he condemned Republicans over education, saying
their budget sought to repeal last fall's commitment to spend
billions to help school systems hire 100,000 new teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want Congress to keep its word,'' he said. ``I think
when you tell people something in an election year, you ought to
still be for it the next year, when there is no election.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called on Republican leaders to appoint conferees on
juvenile crime who would adopt the gun controls passed by the
Senate. Those provisions included a mandate that licensed dealers
sell child safety devices with every handgun, a ban on the import
of large ammunition clips and a requirement that all purchasers at
gun shows be subjected to background checks that vendors would have
up to three business days to complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really not a partisan issue,'' he said, ``anywhere but
Washington, D.C.''
</P>
<P>
   His Georgetown speech also dwelled on the subject of
partisanship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that those of us who work here now,'' he told the
assembled students, ``will be judged primarily by whether we choose
to seize this opportunity to ensure your future _ not just the
short term, but the long term _ or will it be squandered with petty
arguments and animosities and special-interest politics? I regret
to say that the atmosphere in Washington has become increasingly
poisoned by bitter partisanship. I don't understand exactly why,
since we keep doing better and better and better in America. It may
be that some people believe they have the luxury of engaging in
shortsighted partisanship because the country is doing so well.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Some in Washington, he said, ``really believe that because the
presidential election season has already started, the battle for
Congress has already started _ even though it's a year and however
many months away _ that the best politics is just to run out the
clock and wait for the next election and hope that the country is
doing so well and we enjoy the lazy days of summer so much nobody
will notice.''
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference, he was reminded by a questioner that
some congressional Democrats also favored inaction, thinking their
best chance of victories next year lay in accusing the Republicans
of running a do-nothing Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton conceded in his reply how widespread that feeling was,
but said: ``Not all Democrats believe that. You see a number in the
House, and I think probably a majority in the Senate, do not agree
with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Reporters repeatedly asked him about polls, which they said
showed a lack of support for him, and he replied that the polls he
had seen showed support for his policies.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he understood why he generated such antagonism
from his opponents, he said he was not sure. But he added that
``the right wing _ you know, I've been accused of murder and all
kinds of things _ and it seems, it's almost that the better the
country got, the madder some of them got.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, citing the bitter attacks encountered by Franklin D.
Roosevelt, he said that ``generally, in our country's history, the
people who are progressive, people who try to change things, people
who keep pushing the envelope, have generally elicited very strong,
sometimes personally hostile, negative reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   The president was asked whether he thought his ``personal
behavior'' had made him a liability to Democrats like Gore and the
first lady, a likely Senate candidate in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``All elections are about the future,'' he replied, ``and all
candidates are judged on their own merits. And I believe that is
the case here. But I think that the American people know that the
country is in good shape, and that not only our economic policies,
our crime policies and our welfare policies, but our family
policies are good for their efforts to raise their children. And
the best thing that I can do, it seems to me, is to do the right
thing by my country, to just keep working at being a good
president, and they'll do fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton defended his intention to propose a prescription drug
benefit for Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really think there's any alternative here,'' he said.
``You've got 15 million Americans, seniors out there, without any
kind of coverage for their medicine. You've got millions and
millions of others with inadequate or highly expensive coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   The only element of his four-bill legislative package on which
reporters pressed him was the campaign finance measure. Clinton
said his strategy on that bill, which would ban soft-money
contributions and curb ``issue'' advertisements, was to ``keep it
on the front burner so that the discomfort level rises high enough
that an actual vote is allowed.''
</P>
<P>
   He identified Senate Republican leaders as the obstacle, saying
that ``they don't want their people who will vote against it to
have a recorded vote on it, and they don't want to run the risk
that they've got enough of their folks that would vote with all of
ours'' and pass the bill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
