A0125 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISS-TEEN-TROUBLE26-C     06-25 0382
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISS-TEEN-TROUBLE26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lack of citizenship causes beauty queen's dethroning
 &HT;    By Gita M. Smith
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Jane Kim has looks, charm and talent _ all
qualifications for the title of Miss Georgia Teen USA.
</P>
<P>
   All the qualifications but one: She's not a U.S. citizen.
</P>
<P>
   But for that pesky fact, the title Kim won last October would
have carried her to the Miss Teen USA finals in Shreveport, La., in
August. This week, she had to relinquish her crown.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Miss Teen USA discovered the discrepancy last week
when Kim, 17, could not produce a U.S. birth certificate or
citizenship papers.
</P>
<P>
   The teen was crushed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I prepared so hard for it. It's a sad loss,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Born in South Korea, Kim came to the United States with her
father, Chong Sok Kim, and mother, Yong Kim, 15 years ago. They are
permanent U.S. residents with proper documentation, but had not
become citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought if I lived here that long, I was American,'' said
Kim, who recently graduated from high school.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Kim traveled to Seoul on a South Korean passport in 1997
when she was invited to compete in the Elite Super Models world
competition. That was a year before the Miss Georgia Teen USA
contest.
</P>
<P>
   Did she state she was a U.S. citizen on her pageant application?
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, I don't remember,'' Kim said Friday. ``I signed my
name on a line that asked me if I was complying with all the
contest regulations, where they asked us if we were pregnant or
ever married or a U.S. citizen or resident of Georgia, and I signed
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Georgia pageant people never asked me for papers. I don't
want the blame to go on them, they were so busy it probably slipped
their minds,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Whitehead, state coordinator for the pageant, could not be
reached for comment Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Dara Arbeiter, a New York City publicist for the Miss Teen USA
contest, said Keely Wright, first runner-up, now will go on to
represent Georgia in the finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will turn 18 two days before that pageant and it was going
to be such a great birthday for me,'' Kim said. ``At least then
I'll go and apply for citizenship. I'll do that for myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
