u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SPREWELL-CAMBY-NY     06-25 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPREWELL-CAMBY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPREWELL AND CAMBY SEE FUTURE AS KNICKS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Marcus Camby and Latrell Sprewell had their issues
with Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy during a tumultuous season. But
while neither player appeared jubilant Friday after learning that
Van Gundy said he had been assured of his return by Dave Checketts,
the Madison Square Garden president, both expressed a desire to
return next season as well.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, winning has softened their stance on Van Gundy. But
at different times during the season, Sprewell and Camby privately
expressed their discontent with Van Gundy and told friends that
they were not sure if they wanted to play for him next season.
Midway through this season, Sprewell openly expressed his dismay
with his sixth-man role, and Camby has said he felt caught in the
middle of the feud between Van Gundy and Ernie Grunfeld, the former
general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by their abbreviated responses Friday before Game 5 of
the National Basketball Association finals, some residual tension
still seemed to exist. Sprewell gave polite yes and no answers to
questions regarding Van Gundy.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he wants to return. No, he won't ask to be traded. Camby
was more forthcoming but did not want to discuss Van Gundy's
situation hours before the Knicks were to play the San Antonio
Spurs at Madison Square Garden in an attempt to stave off
elimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's good that he has his money, and he has his job,'' Camby
said after the Knicks' shoot-around. ``But we can't worry about
who's going to be here, and who's not going to be here. We've got
to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even want to talk about Jeff right now. All I'm
talking about is the Spurs. When the time is right, then I'll
speak. Right now, I'm just focused on the Spurs. No hostility
toward Jeff or anything. We're cool, we're close.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, all is well for Camby and Sprewell. After injuries to
starters in the playoffs, including Patrick Ewing's season-ending
partial tear of an Achilles' tendon, Van Gundy made both starters.
One issue that will be discussed after the season is what roles
Sprewell and Camby will play when Ewing returns to full health.
Will they go back to the bench? Will the team revert to a more
Ewing-centered, half-court style?
</P>
<P>
   If Camby and Sprewell have anxieties about the Ewing issue, they
will have the opportunity to express them to Checketts in
post-season meetings. Sprewell indicated Friday that if he had to
go back to the bench, he would bite his tongue and accept it.
</P>
<P>
   Without interference from management, Van Gundy's decisions
regarding how he uses Camby and Sprewell will be more binding than
ever. Throughout this season, Van Gundy endured criticism over how
he used his newcomers. He also survived political machinations and
held onto his job. Despite the personal toll the behind-the-scenes
division took on him, Van Gundy has not reached a point where he
wants to say enough is enough. He wants to return as coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of those things are difficult to understand,'' Van Gundy
said. ``But I love coaching, and I love a chance to win. I think
New York will always try to create an opportunity to win. I like
that opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy has already ensured himself $6 million by coaching his
team to the finals, and he is under contract until 2001. Given the
high salaries of the league's top coaches, Van Gundy could land a
contract extension in the area of four years and $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since Dave took over, he had told me the same thing: he wanted
me back,'' said Van Gundy, referring to April 21, when Checketts
took over the day-to-day operations of the team after demoting
Grunfeld. ``Now, were the results going to be good enough to be
brought back? That wasn't sure until probably two or three weeks
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Allan Houston provided some job support for Van Gundy by hitting
the game-winning shot in Miami on May 16 that eliminated the Heat
in the first round of the playoffs. On May 24, the Knicks finished
a sweep of Atlanta in the second round and advanced to the Eastern
Conference finals for the first time since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   During the series with the Hawks, a secret meeting six weeks
earlier between Checketts and the former Chicago Bulls coach Phil
Jackson was disclosed. But during the conference finals against
Indiana, Van Gundy said, Checketts told him he was assured of his
position.
</P>
<P>
   There are many issues to be decided in the off-season, including
whether the Knicks want to use any of their current players in a
trade for a star point guard. But both Camby and Sprewell made it
clear Friday that they wanted to be back and did not want to be
traded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy,'' Camby said. ``I'm happy I'm in New York. I love
my teammates, and I like being around these guys. It's definitely
been up and down. The beginning of the season is in the past. I'm
happy for what we have here. We have a nice, young team with a
strong nucleus. I hope everyone can come back here, and we can go
out and do it again next year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
