<DOCNO> NYT19990625.0374 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0131 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-25 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: R.I.)  
 REPENTING SLAVERY AND CELEBRATING HUMAN LIBERTY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By GUSTAV NIEBUHR    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Acknowledging a past wrong can be a formidable task, whether for
an individual or an institution _ not least for religious
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   One dramatic instance came four years ago, when the Southern
Baptist Convention apologized to American blacks for the
denomination's support of slavery before the Civil War. The
Southern Baptists came into being as a denomination in 1845, when
Southerners broke away from Northern Baptists in a dispute over
whether a slaveholder could serve as a missionary.
</P>
<P>
   Early next month another denomination, the United Church of
Christ, plans a public act of repentance for the role that
Northerners (including some associated with the denomination)
played in the trans-Atlantic slave trade.
</P>
<P>
   The event will be held on July 5 in Providence, R.I., where the
denomination's business session, its General Synod, will be
meeting. Delegates will gather in Abbott Park, a slice of greenery
beside historic Beneficent Church, where they will dedicate a
schoolhouse-sized bell as a symbolic act repenting of slavery and
celebrating human liberty.
</P>
<P>
   The idea came from the Rev. H. Daehler Hayes, the conference
minister (an administrative post) for 34 United Church of Christ
congregations in Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   But why do it in New England, a region many people associate
with liberty, either through Roger Williams, the 17th-century
advocate of religious freedom and founder of Rhode Island, or the
resistance to British rule in the American Revolution? Why do it
during a meeting of the United Church of Christ, a denomination
that does not shy from pointing to its historic ties to
anti-slavery leaders?
</P>
<P>
   The reason, Hayes said, is that in the 18th century, ports like
Bristol and Newport, R.I., served as the northern apex of the
``triangle trade.'' Merchants sent rum and iron to West Africa, in
exchange for slaves to be sold in the Caribbean, from which
molasses and sugar were bought and shipped back to New England. The
journey from Africa to the West Indies became known as ``the middle
passage,'' on which countless Africans died.
</P>
<P>
   ``That trade went on a long time,'' Hayes said.
</P>
<P>
   When he became conference minister 16 years ago, he said,
African-American clergy members reminded him that he would serve an
area historically linked to the slave trade. Their message was
reinforced when he learned that a social hall attached to a church
in his jurisdiction was named for a family involved in the trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not interested in bringing judgment on anyone,'' Hayes
said. But he added that he wanted to keep historic memory alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people say forget about this stuff, but I think we do
that at peril to the future,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The United Church of Christ, with 1.4 million members, was
formed in the 1957 merger of two churches. If some members of the
denomination in its past, particularly wealthy members of
congregations in coastal cities, had dealings in the slave trade,
the denomination also claims a rich anti-slavery heritage.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Richard Taylor, pastor of 256-year-old Beneficent
Church, which is affiliated with the denomination, said some of
slavery's fiercest opponents came from churches in interior New
England, which belong to the present denomination. He cited the
Rev. Samuel Hopkins, who served in the Berkshire Hills in western
Massachusetts until he became minister of a church in Newport in
1770.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopkins was just aghast at the large number of slaves and the
slave economy when he came down here,'' Taylor said. ``He became a
significant friend of the African community and a significant
opponent of slavery.'' (Rhode Island abolished slavery in 1784, six
years before it ratified the Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   In the July 5 ceremony, Hayes said he hoped volunteers from the
synod would take turns tolling the bell ``in a penitent act''
during the morning. Later, he said, it will be rung joyfully, as a
symbol of freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``American history is a complex matter,'' Hayes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to let the past inform us,'' he added, but in a way
that those who study it ``become the welcoming and inclusive people
we need to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-99 2159EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
