<HEADER>
A0132 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REWARD-NYT &LR;      06-25 0398
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REWARD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. OFFERS UP TO $5-MILLION REWARD FOR MILOSEVIC  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States has offered a reward of up to $5
million for information leading to the arrest and conviction of
President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia and others indicted by
an international tribunal for war crimes in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic and the former Bosnian Serb leaders Radovan Karadzic
and Gen. Ratko Mladic are the most prominent among the suspects
wanted by the war crimes tribunal in The Hague.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said Friday at a news conference that the
reward was not meant to encourage the assassination of Milosevic,
nor to encourage bounty hunters, but was intended as an incentive
because Serbia does not comply with extradition treaties. In the
case of Milosevic, whose whereabouts are well known, officials said
they assumed that at some point he might travel outside Serbia and
that the reward would still apply.
</P>
<P>
   Mladic has lived in Belgrade for the last three years, and the
Clinton administration chose not to put pressure on Milosevic to
hand him over when the Yugoslav leader was still the
administration's partner in the search for peace in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Karadzic lives in the Serbian-controlled area of Bosnia, and the
Pentagon long opposed any operation to seize him, fearing that some
American soldiers might die in the operation or be attacked
afterward. Others argued that NATO should be forced to arrest him,
but he has remained at large.
</P>
<P>
   At a briefing this week, the State Department spokesman, James
P. Rubin, noted that Clinton had recently encouraged other
countries overseeing military sectors in Bosnia to arrest indicted
war criminals in their jurisdictions.
</P>
<P>
   The reward is being offered under a special State Department
program begun a decade ago and originally intended to encourage the
arrest of terrorists responsible for the killings of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Under the program, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright has
discretion to determine the size of a reward if a suspect is
captured. State Department officials said that the amount would be
linked to the type of information provided and other factors, and
that American and other NATO soldiers in the Balkans would not be
entitled to the money since apprehension of war criminals is
considered part of their assignment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-99 2201EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990625.0376 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0136 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-JOINT-VENTURE-N     06-25 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-JOINT-VENTURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME WARNER BOOKS, SIMON &AMP; SCHUSTER CONSIDER JOINT VENTURE FOR BOOK
OPERATIONS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In yet another sign of the pressure to merge that is
reshaping the publishing industry, Time Warner Books and Viacom's
Simon &AMP; Schuster are in serious talks to form a joint venture for
their book operations covering such aspects as warehousing,
marketing and sales.
</P>
<P>
   The venture would reduce operating costs and would provide the
combined companies more leverage in negotiating terms with such
giant retailers as Barnes and Noble and Amazon.com, a person close
to the discussions said.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors of the deal, which is inherently logical, had been
sweeping the publishing world for days, but neither company would
discuss it. Simon &AMP; Schuster is the fourth largest trade publisher
with 1998 sales of $564 million, and Warner/Little Brown is the
sixth largest with estimated revenues of $320 million.
</P>
<P>
   Combined, they would have had $900 million in 1998 sales, making
them the third large publisher trailing HarperCollins, which has
agreed to acquire Avon/Morrow. Both would still trail giant Random
House. With nearly $2 billion in 1998 sales, it is nearly twice as
large as its two nearest competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Book companies are merging in an attempt to improve profit
margins by amortizing operating costs over a broader base, and
improving their leverage with the handful of retailers that
dominate the industry.
</P>
<P>
   On the revenue side, the issue is not so much the price
retailers can charge for books, as the clout publishers have to
assure their books a good display in bookstores and on the web, a
person close to the negotiations pointed out. Size also helps by
giving publishers the leverage to see that both potential mega-best
sellers as well as smaller books get some exposure, this person
said.
</P>
<P>
   There had been rumors earlier this year that Time Warner was
considering acquiring Simon &AMP; Schuster. However several weeks ago a
Time Warner executive confirmed that his company was not interested
in investing heavily in the book business, with does not generate
either large profits or rapid growth.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner already has a large magazine publishing operation
and owns the Book of the Month Club. So a joint venture is an ideal
solution because it has the potential for enchancing the
profitability of a business that is a strategic fit for a
diversified media company. Additionally, it is not necessarily easy
to sell book companies, even if Time Warner had wanted to do so.
Generally the only buyers are other publishing entities.
</P>
<P>
   Viacom sold its educational publishing business to Pearson PLC
in 1998 for $4.6 billion. At the time, its chairman, Sumner
Redstone, said the company wanted to hold on to Simon and Schuster
largely because it fit with the company's other entertainment
operations. For example, Simon &AMP; Schuster had published both
``First Wives Club'' and ``Forrest Gump'' which Viacom's Paramount
Pictures produced as feature films.
</P>
<P>
   Simon &AMP; Schuster had sales of $564.6 million in 1998 and cash
flow, or earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation and
amortization of $71.2 million. That gave the division a 13 percent
cash flow margin, which is high for the publishing business. Among
the company's star authors are Frank McCort, Mary Higgens Clark and
Bob Woodward.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Viacom was under some long-term pressure to
control costs. Last year as part of its deal with Pearson, it
negotiated a five-year arrangement with the buyer to provide
customer service and other back-office operations. While such
agreements would help keep Simon &AMP; Schuster's costs down for the
near-term, they helps explain Viacom's interest in creating a joint
venture that would insure continued hefty profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner's authors include Sandra Brown and Nelson DeMille.
Time Warner does not break out the book company's sales and cash
flow.
</P>
<P>
   Two people familiar with the talks said that the joint venture
would retain separate independent editorial operations, but
Bertelsmann, which owned Bantam Doubleday Dell, said the same thing
after it bought Random House, only to combine several smaller
imprints.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner Trade Publishing is headed by Larry Kirshbaum, and
Simon &AMP; Schuster is run by Jack Romanos. The two companies are
expected to set up a joint board to oversee the operations.
</P>
<P>
   One of the people close to the talks noted that book companies
are valued on at 10 to 15 times cash flow, so that if a merger
saves $30 million to $40 million, the companies have increased the
value by $300 million to $400 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
