A0140 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES26-CO     06-25 0512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    C. Jones getting his left-side pop back
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Chipper Jones may have finally found what he's been
looking for most of this 1999 season: some rhythm from the left
side.
</P>
<P>
   In three games against Montreal, the switch-hitting Jones was
5-for-10, all against right-handed pitchers, bringing his average
from the left side up to .264 from .257. Add that to his .371 from
the right side and Jones is hitting .292, matching the highest his
batting average has been since the end of the Braves' first road
trip in April.
</P>
<P>
   This was a long-awaited stretch, especially after Jones struck
out in five consecutive at-bats against the Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   ``My contact is starting to pick up,'' Jones said. ``When that
happens the hits should start coming in. Now it's time to start
getting some multi-hit games, getting the average up where I like
it, hoping some guys get on ahead of me for some RBI chances. It's
been an uphill climb this whole year. I'd rather hit .300 than
anything else (statistically).''
</P>
<P>
   The left side has typically been Jones' dominant side, but it's
been a struggle this season. Part of that comes from having
pitchers attacking him inside, so he couldn't get that powerful
extension.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teams were pounding me inside so much, I got into some bad
habits trying to get to those inside pitches,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Injury update
</P>
<P>
   Walt Weiss has been putting his sore quadriceps to the test for
the last couple of days, running a 40-yard dash while assistant
trainer Jeff Porter timed him with a stopwatch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was able to go 68-70 percent,'' Weiss said. ``I talked to
the trainers (Friday) and they said as soon as I can run a little
bit better, I'll be activated. I want to be able to run at least 80
percent.'' Weiss said he's still shooting to make it back before
the end of this Mets series.
</P>
<P>
   Randall Simon was scheduled to have an MRI on his sore left knee
Friday morning but overslept and will have to reschedule for today.
</P>
<P>
   Javy Lopez, who's on the disabled list with a sprained right
knee, said he will not be making the trip with the Braves to New
York and Montreal next week. He plans to stay in Atlanta with his
family and get treatment every day at Turner Field. He's eligible
to return July 6 when the Braves are home against the Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty good physically,'' Lopez said. Mentally?
``Frustrated. Going crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Braves Heritage Salute
</P>
<P>
   This weekend is the third annual Atlanta Braves Heritage Salute.
The following players and coaches are scheduled to run
instructional clinics today, though these are subject to change: at
Adams Park _ Chipper Jones, Brian Jordan, Kevin McGlinchy, Kevin
Millwood, Gerald Williams and Ned Yost; at Gresham Park _ Don
Baylor, Brian Hunter, Otis Nixon and Mike Remlinger; and at Medlock
Park _ Pat Corrales, Ozzie Guillen, Andruw Jones, Eddie Perez,
Odalis Perez and Mets pitcher Masato Yoshii.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
