<HEADER>
A0141 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-HUMMER26-COX     06-25 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-HUMMER26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hockey, welcome to Atlanta
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Allow me to perform the re-introductions. Pro hockey,
this is Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know anything about Atlanta,'' confessed Ed Ward,
plucked from the Calgary Flames in Friday's expansion draft by the
embryonic Thrashers. Didn't know the name of the arena that would
be his new home. Wouldn't know if this particular thrasher was noun
or verb. Couldn't name the best local golf courses, although being
a hockey player, he's bound to solve that mystery first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back where I come from (Western Canada), everybody's making
jokes about a thrasher being a combine (that's farm equipment to
you city folk),'' said Terry Yake, the St. Louis Blues'
contribution to expansion. He was interested to learn that it is
also a small, fiesty bird.
</P>
<P>
   What they hear about the city is secondhand; what they
understand about Atlanta's hockey tradition comes from the fuzzy
recollections of childhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to a few friends about it,'' Ward said. ``They've
said nothing but great things about Atlanta. I got to know Stan
Drulia (former Atlanta Knights captain) when we played together in
Detroit (IHL). He loves the place, plans to retire there.'' Hope
driving the Connector at 5:30 p.m. doesn't spoil any illusions.
</P>
<P>
   We _ the capital of the New South and the sport birthed by the
hard freeze _ have so much to learn about one another. When the
Thrashers are deep into their inevitable struggles, maybe the
fascination will begin to fade. But, now, it's hard to resist that
new-team smell.
</P>
<P>
   Thus we launch into our voyage of discovery. Even Rob Knight,
the illustrated fan from Kennesaw who won a trip to the draft after
having ``Let's Go Thrashers'' tattooed on his chest, has far to go
from here. Although, I don't even want to consider what his next
step might be.
</P>
<P>
   This is a team that picked a hockey player named Hull, but
settle down. Jody has no relation to that royal pucks family.
</P>
<P>
   Their hometowns range from Red Deer, Alberta, to Dearborn,
Mich., to Krasnoyarsk, Russia. Don't even know how many of these
expansioneers ever will see the Philips Arena home locker room.
They are human junk bonds and Thrashers GM Don Waddell _ who
brokered eight deals this first day, with more pending _ is
apparently not one to sit on his portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   This first list of Thrashers is not terribly glamorous, just a
tad more exciting than the average shopping list.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of meat and potatoes, like Ed Ward. When asked to
characterize his draftees, Waddell emphasized leadership and
character. Ward concurred: ``There's no really big names. What you
want is third- or fourth-line character players who work their
butts off every night. You want to establish the work ethic as a
basis.''
</P>
<P>
   There aren't many goals in this first batch of Thrashers, a
problem yet to be addressed. Yake, the 36-year-old center, was the
leading NHL scorer on the expansion list, carrying just nine goals
and 27 points from the 1998-99 season. He's anxious to get a chance
to expand on those numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Much traveled _ this is his fifth NHL stop _ Yake also has
experience with hockey missionary work. ``I was one of the happiest
guys in the league going to Anaheim (1993). It was a lot of fun
making connections with new people, getting new fans to fall in
love with the sport,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that first year, even guys who aren't stars in the league
can get out there and be stars in their own town,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta, this is pro hockey. And what a good first impression it
makes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
