<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0142 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-YUGOSLAVIA-1ST     06-25 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-YUGOSLAVIA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EGO PREVENTS OPPOSITION FROM SEIZING POWER AS MILOSEVIC FALTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to remove extraneous word in lede; no other changes.)  (rm) 
 By BLAINE HARDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ For opposition politicians in Yugoslavia,
this should be showtime.
</P>
<P>
   President Slobodan Milosevic has lost his fourth war in a row
and surrendered the sacred Serbian homeland of Kosovo to heavily
armed foreigners. He has been indicted as a war criminal, the Swiss
are swooping down to close any bank accounts he might have and the
United States has offered $5 million to anyone who helps nab him. A
third of Yugoslavia is out of work, incomes are down 40 percent
this year and, according to a credible poll by a private firm this
week, 70 percent of Serbs blame Milosevic for the whole sorry mess.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as has been the case for nearly a decade, the opposition
seems incapable of seizing the day. United in their eagerness to
dump a dictator and end Serbia's isolation as an international
pariah, opposition leaders remain hobbled by their competing egos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Milosevic could not choose a better opposition because, if
it repeats its unforgivable mistakes, he will be in power
forever,'' grumbled Slobodan Vuksanovic, vice-president of the
Democratic Party, one of a cluster of pro-Western parties here.
``We have an ego problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit A in the disunity of the Serbian opposition and the
primacy of ego is Vuk Draskovic, the only opposition figure with a
sizable national following, his own television station and the
populist razzle-dazzle to lure large numbers of Serbs out into the
streets.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic's haughty disdain for a fractured opposition movement
that desperately needs his charisma, his television station and his
political machine helps explain why democracy in Serbia has been so
much more elusive than in the rest of post-Communist Eastern
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Tall, bearded and prone to self-dramatizing soliloquy,
Draskovic, 52, a former best-selling novelist of blood-soaked
nationalist novels, is not humble about his political gifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am the king of the streets,'' Draskovic said in an interview
Friday at the headquarters of his Serbian Renewal Party. ``I know
better than anyone in the world what could be the real moment for
demonstrations to bring down Milosevic. This is not the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of nearly every other opposition party in Yugoslavia
disagree on the question of timing. They have joined an umbrella
group called Alliance for Change and announced that next Tuesday
they will begin mass protests around Serbia to demand that
Milosevic resign and that free elections be held under the
supervision of European monitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must harness the anger of the Serbian people,'' said Vladan
Batic, coordinator of the alliance. ``After Kosovo, everything is
different. People finally understand that political changes are
necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic, who also senses that the loss of Kosovo will prove to
be a mortal blow to the Milosevic regime, said he wishes the
alliance a lot of luck, but he does not feel like hanging out with
``small political parties.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not ready to waste time in closed rooms discussing stupid
things,'' Draskovic said.
</P>
<P>
   As much as other opposition leaders may resent Draskovic's
uppity tone, they tend to agree that without him and his party,
which has been able to turn out tens of thousands of protesters
against the Milosevic regime for weeks on end, it will be difficult
to sustain pressure on Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vuk won't call us, and we don't want to call him, and
Milosevic is rubbing his hands together in delight,'' conceded
Vuksanovic, a prominent leader in the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic's hubris is the result of strong recent poll numbers
for his party, his surprisingly successful cameo performance as a
government minister during the 10-week Kosovo war and a new
go-it-alone strategy cooked up by his advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Those advisers say that Draskovic was betrayed by other
opposition leaders in 1996-97, when he helped lead three months of
protest rallies in Belgrade that came tantalizingly close to
toppling the Milosevic regime. They vow he will not be duped again.
</P>
<P>
   During the last big round of protests, Draskovic complained that
he was undermined by Zoran Djindjic, the leader of the Democratic
Party and the other big fish in the opposition sea. In the fall of
1997, Djindjic encouraged opposition parties to boycott an election
when Draskovic ran for president of Serbia. The boycott contributed
to Draskovic's dismal third-place showing in the vote.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Never again will he trust Djindjic or other ``very selfish''
opposition leaders, Draskovic said Friday, as he painted a dark
scenario of what he believes would happen if he were to participate
in a pre-election opposition alliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Immediately before elections, they will start to quarrel, to
accuse each other, to blackmail each other, and Milosevic would see
a way to manipulate them,'' said Draskovic. ``He would use smoke,
coffee, whiskey and be very, very satisfied by the stupid ambitions
of the opposition. No. I am not a part of it. I tried for nine
years to unify them without any success. OK. That's it.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A poll last week suggests that, in the aftermath of the Kosovo
war, Draskovic can afford some petulance. His party's popularity
rose smartly during the conflict, from about 7 percent in March to
about 15 percent this week, according to a nationwide poll by
Medium, a private polling firm. The poll, which other politicians
here say is credible, places Draskovic's party behind only the
ruling Socialist People's Party, whose popularity slid during the
war to from 29 to 21 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic, who has been severely beaten and imprisoned in
anti-Milosevic protests this decade, stunned many in Serbia in
January when he accepted the Serb leader's invitation to join the
Yugoslav government as a deputy prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   During the war, he attracted considerable attention here and
around the world by condemning the NATO bombing of civilian targets
in Serbia as brutal and inhuman. At the same time, he demanded that
the foreign press be allowed to operate inside Serbia and distanced
himself from Milosevic, accusing his government of lying to the
Serb people about who was winning the war in Kosovo. In late April,
he was fired by the regime, but not before he had shown himself off
to many Serbs as a strongly nationalist, yet sane alternative to
Milosevic's policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I prevented many stupid things from happening during the
war,'' Draskovic boasted. `` risked my life. I did my obligations.
I did it by staying in Serbia.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic noted that his opposition rival, Djindjic, did not
have the courage to remain. Citing threats to his life, Djindjic
fled Serbia in May and has yet to return. His absence, which has
been criticized as cowardly, even by members of his own party, has
hurt the Democratic Party's fortunes. Djindjic is expected to
return to Serbia next week for the demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Many of his critics here believe the real reason Draskovic is
reluctant to take on the Milosevic regime is that he does not want
to lose his political trump card, Studio B television. The station,
a real alternative to state-controlled TV, is controlled by
Belgrade city hall, which is run by a coalition of Draskovic's
party and the ruling Socialists.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Vuk pushes too hard, he could lose the support of the
Socialists,'' said one analyst here who did not want to be
identified by name. ``He could lose Studio B, and then he would be
in the same position as everybody else in the opposition.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about this, Draskovic was indignant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a total lie,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most vexing complication in the political evolution
of Draskovic is what exactly he believes in. He has been a somewhat
promiscuous populist over the past decade, alternating between
fist-pounding nationalism and sophisticated sensitivity to the
rights of ethnic minorities. In the early 1990s, he liked to draw
maps showing how big a Greater Serbia should be. He often seemed
unsure of whether Milosevic had erred by starting wars or losing
them.
</P>
<P>
   As with many politicians in Serbia, it is difficult to discern
how much nationalism colors his commitment to democracy and human
rights. Asked about this, Draskovic said there is no confusion at
all.
</P>
<P>
   ``My nationalism was always healthy, Western nationalism,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-99 2208EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
