<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
(HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
  c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASDAQ AND S&AMP;P DECLINE; DOW JONES RISES 17 POINTS
</P>
<P>
   The technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index dropped 1.34 points,
to 2,552.65, as trading was slow and investors awaited the meeting
Tuesday and Wednesday of the Federal Open Market Committee.
Investors expect the Federal Reserve's policy-making panel to raise
short-term interest rates a quarter percentage point to head off
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell 0.47 point, to
1,315.31, while the Dow Jones industrial average rose 17.73 points,
to 10,552.56. The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond declined to
6.15 percent from 6.16 percent on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ECONOMY GROWING AT A 4.3 PERCENT RATE
</P>
<P>
   Torrid consumer spending helped the gross domestic product _ the
nation's output of goods and services _ grow at a brisk annual rate
of 4.3 percent in the first quarter of the year, the Commerce
Department reported.
</P>
<P>
   PRIESTS SAY FRANKEL DUPED THEM
</P>
<P>
   In Rome, two priests, the Rev. Peter Jacobs, 73, an American
activist, and Monsignor Emilio Colagiovanni, 79, a scholarly
Italian, provided a clerical cloak of respectability for a money
manager who authorities suspect embezzled more than $300 million
dollars from American insurance companies. Both men insist they
were duped by Martin R. Frankel, who disappeared last month and is
wanted by the Federal Bureau of Investigation.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPBELL SOUP EARN TO FALL SHORT
</P>
<P>
   Campbell Soup said that earnings for its fiscal fourth quarter
would fall 8 cents to 10 cents a share below analysts' forecasts of
38 cents a share and that it planned to reorganize its soup
operations. Mark M. Leckie, the president of the company's domestic
soup division, will leave the company. He will be succeeded at the
new North American division by F. Martin Thrasher, now the
company's president of European and Canadian operations.
</P>
<P>
   NISSAN'S WESTERN-STYLE MEETING
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, where annual shareholders' meetings, are traditionally
closed affairs, Nissan Motor moved to Western-style openness,
allowing news coverage. But the reward for the troubled company's
president, Yoshikazu Hanawa, was a scolding gadfly shareholder who
identified himself only as Mr. Tamura and demanded his resignation,
saying, ``You've made mistake after mistake.'' Next Tuesday, 1,374
companies, or 88 percent of Japan's listed companies, are to hold
their meetings.
</P>
<P>
   LATIN-EUROPEAN TRADE MEETING SET
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to increase trade and gain a counterweight to American
global economic dominance, leaders of Latin America and Europe, the
world's second- and third-largest trading blocs, are to meet in Rio
de Janeiro this weekend and early next week. Their first-ever
summit meeting has already proved contentious on several basic
issues, notably French insistence that farm products be excluded
from any free-trade pact.
</P>
<P>
   IN INDONESIA, A STEP TOWARD HEALTH
</P>
<P>
   In Indonesia, the agreement this week between PT Astra
International and its creditors on how the big company, which
assembles Toyota utility vehicles and Honda motorcycles, will pay
back more than $1 billion in debt is being heralded as evidence
that the nation is on the mend. But Indonesia is by no means well.
</P>
<P>
   BBC'S NEW HEAD STIRS CONTROVERSY
</P>
<P>
   The British Broadcasting Corporation stirred passionate debate
by appointing as its new head Greg Dyke, a millionaire Labor Party
supporter associated with ``Baywatch'' and a puppet called Roland
Rat. He has been head of Pearson Television, but the Conservative
opposition focused on his Labor ties.
</P>
<P>
   COVANCE AND PAREXEL HALT MERGER
</P>
<P>
   Covance and Parexel International, two drug-development
companies, called off their planned merger, originally valued at
more than $600 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
