<HEADLINE>
BURN HAS ONE GOAL IN MIND: CONSISTENCY 
WITH MLS PLAYOFF OUTLOOK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Blane Bachelor 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Burn is one game above .500, one point out of first
place in the Western Conference and one game from the midpoint of
its season.
</P>
<P>
   But the team is well ahead of where it was a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Burn's 8-7 record might not look impressive, but there is a
different feeling around the team this year. Last year, injuries
led to frustration. Recovering from injuries and adding a group of
talented newcomers has gone a long way to helping the Burn turn
heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a much different team than in years past,'' forward
Dante Washington said. ``We have the same players, basically, but I
think our attitude and mentality is different. I think years past
have helped us get to where we are now. We're not losing sight of
what the big picture is.''
</P>
<P>
   The big picture being the Major League Soccer finals, which the
Burn has yet to reach in three seasons despite reaching the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Getting to that point will mean, first of all, staying healthy.
Extra attention to training this season has helped reduce injuries,
which will become even more of an emphasis with U.S. Open Cup games
added to the Burn's schedule in mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   Just as essential will be keeping a close check on the team's
mental outlook.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a history of having a very strong first part of the
season, a weak middle third, and an almost weaker final third,''
midfielder Ted Eck said. ``We've done things a little bit different
in the preseason. I feel each player made it a point to get
focused, do their job and do the things we need to do to prepare
for the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   The Burn's longest winning and losing streaks are the same: two
games.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, some of the Burn's opponents have been a little
more shaky this season. Defending champion Chicago was averaging
more than three goals per game when it jumped to the top of the
West early, before slumping to fall to third behind Colorado. The
Los Angeles Galaxy rebounded from an abysmal start to improve to
8-6. Tampa Bay opened the season 0-4, then posted a five-game
winning streak before going 1-3 in its past four games.
</P>
<P>
   A lot can be said for peaking at the right time, but the Burn
continues to emphasize consistency in reaching the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been real even-keeled,'' goalkeeper Mark Dodd said. ``I
think we can be a lot better; we all know that, but at the same
time we haven't allowed big lapses, which is going to really set
you off course.''
</P>
<P>
   That pretty much summed up a disheartening finish to last
season. The Burn lost nine of 11 games at the end of the season,
but managed to make the playoffs against LA. The Galaxy swept the
best-of-three series, which included a 6-1 thrashing of the Burn at
the Cotton Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Players vowed to never again suffer such an embarrassing loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just a team firing on all cylinders at the present
time,'' MLS commissioner Doug Logan said of the Burn. ``I could go
on and on. But what has impressed me the most is the way \Rcoach\S
Dave \RDir\S has gotten that team playing together. They have a
look in their eye that they'll never lose a match again like they
lost to LA in the playoffs.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
