<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-MLS-OUTLOOK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MLS PLAYOFF OUTLOOK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BLANE BACHELOR 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the second half of the Major League Soccer season begins, the
playoff picture comes into focus. The top four teams in the Eastern
and Western Conferences advance to the playoffs. A look at the
teams: Likely
</P>
<P>
   D.C. United: The perennial powerhouse of the MLS has lost its
past two games. But D.C.'s depth and leadership make it a favorite
to advance to the MLS championship game for the fourth consecutive
year. Chicago Fire: Last year's Cinderella team, the expansion Fire
made an unforgettable MLS debut by winning the 1998 championship.
Chicago jumped ahead early with a three-game winning streak this
season, before faltering a little to fall to third in the Western
Conference. Burn: A much healthier lineup, promising newcomers and
stellar play from forward Jason Kreis have gone a long way toward
sparking renewed optimism. For the past three seasons, the Burn
hasn't been able to shake its middle-of-the-pack reputation. But
continued production from the talented mix of veterans and
newcomers could make this season the time to change that. LA
Galaxy: LA has turned a shaky start into an 8-6 record, which
includes a 2-1 victory against United. Things seem to have fallen
into place under coach Sigi Schmid, who replaced Octavio Zambrano
earlier in the season. The Galaxy's future looks brighter with
newly acquired international Carlos Hermosillo and attacking
midfielder Roy Meyers. Colorado Rapids: The Rapids, who advanced to
the MLS finals in 1997, appear to be on course for another strong
postseason. Colorado boasts a 5-0 record at Mile High Stadium, is
in first place of the tough Western Conference and has won nine of
its past 10 games. Columbus Crew: The Crew has given its fans
reason to celebrate with an 8-5 record for second in the Eastern
Conference. Columbus' talented Caribbean connection of players has
performed well this season and should help the Crew earn a playoff
berth, but securing the top seed ahead of D.C. isn't likely. New
England Revolution: The Revolution (7-7) is third in the East
Conference. But New England is only one point out of second, and if
forward Joe-Max Moore keeps up his scoring tear, the Revolution
could challenge Columbus. In the hunt Tampa Bay Mutiny: The Mutiny
stumbled out of the blocks, going 0-4 before a five-game winning
streak. But Tampa Bay has slipped again, going 1-3 in its past four
games. The return of playmaker Carlos Valderrama, moved from Miami,
has helped. Kansas City Wizards: Under new coach Bob Gansler, the
Wizards have made a little more magic than they did at the
beginning of the season. Kansas City has started to fix its early
scoring problems, routing New York/New Jersey, 6-0, in its previous
match after scoring just nine goals in 12 games before that. But
the Wizards will have to rely on a mostly unheralded roster to come
up big if they hope to be in the hunt for the postseason. Unlikely
Miami Fusion: The Fusion has been unable to break out of the
Eastern Conference cellar. Coach Ivo Wortmann points to a young
squad as hope for the future. Forward Eric Wynalda was recently
moved to the Fusion, but unless he makes a speedy recovery from
knee surgery, Miami doesn't have much hope for a significant
turnaround. San Jose Clash: The Clash posts the most deceptive
record in MLS, with seven of its eight victories coming in the
shootout. Consequently, San Jose has just 10 points, one ahead of
last-place Kansas City. Raul Diaz Arce needs to break out of his
slump, and the Clash needs to learn how to win in regulation. New
York/New Jersey MetroStars: The MetroStars have lost nine of their
past 10 and five in a row, the most recent an almost comical 6-0
loss to struggling Kansas City. A postseason berth seems highly
unlikely, and at this point, even breaking .500 would be an
accomplishment.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
