<SLUG> BC-COMPANIES-CHOICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 SMALL COMPANIES WITH 3 ROUTES TO GETTING BIGGER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Calif., Canada)   By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Business students, pay attention.
</P>
<P>
   There are few days when an entire new industry segment comes
into focus all at once, especially in the fast-growing business of
communications technology. Friday, however, was one of those days,
and it was full of lessons about how small companies try to become
big and the tough choices they make on the way.
</P>
<P>
   The day's cast was a trio of companies that are leading
developers of the next generation of Internet switches _ products
that can route billions, even trillions of bits of digital
information a second. They are Avici Systems Inc., based in North
Billerica, Mass.; Juniper Networks Inc., based in Mountain View,
Calif., and Nexabit Networks Inc., based in Marlborough, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Until Friday, all three were independent private companies.
</P>
<P>
   But before financial markets opened, Nexabit announced that it
would be acquired by Lucent Technologies Inc., the communications
equipment giant, for $900 million in stock. Then, a few hours
later, Juniper's initial public stock offering hit the market,
giving the company a market value of almost $5 billion. Around the
same time, Avici's chief executive said he had broken off his
company's marketing partnership with the Nortel Networks Corp. of
Canada, one of Lucent's main rivals, with an eye toward a future
initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   Executives for the three companies do not hesitate to point out
the technical differences among their products. But they are in
basically the same market. So why does one company choose to sell
itself to an industry giant while another opts for an IPO?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is that Avici, Juniper and Nexabit have each made
classic risk-reward choices given their different stages of
development and their different visions of the sales and
distribution landscapes in the communications business.
</P>
<P>
   By offering shares to the public, Juniper has taken the biggest
risk of the three. While the appetite for communications stocks may
have never been stronger, that could always change. Friday, of
course, Juniper's stock performed brilliantly. After an initial
offering at $34, the company's shares closed at $98.875 Friday, up
$64.875, in Nasdaq trading, giving the company a market value of
$4.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder at least some Lucent executives Friday thought they
had found a $900 million bargain in Nexabit, though the price was
within the company's original range of expectations.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not as if Nexabit's executives should be kicking
themselves. Juniper was able to go public because it has real
customers who are paying for its products. While Nexabit's
technology is considered in some ways superior to Juniper's,
Nexabit is not yet selling products to paying customers, making it
tough to convince investors to buy the stock.
</P>
<P>
   For Lucent, however, Nexabit's immaturity could even be
considered an asset. Lucent can now direct the final development of
Nexabit's technology to fit its own needs, rather than having to
wedge a fully-developed product into its portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you really think you can make it in the public markets,
you'll get a higher valuation in the public markets,'' said Sender
Cohen, an analyst for Lehman Brothers. ``But I can understand
Nexabit's choice. If you get offered $900 million and you can't go
public for another year, the question is whether the market is
going to be there. In that case I would sell out also.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Friday's news reflected drastically different
conceptions about how telecommunications equipment is sold and
distributed.
</P>
<P>
   Nexabit played it safe in this way as well. As part of Lucent,
Nexabit gains access to a large and experienced sales force that
enjoys strong relationships with a customer base that includes the
nation's biggest communications carriers. When Alcatel of France,
one of the world's biggest makers of communications gear, agreed
last year to acquire the DSC Communications Corp., an old-line U.S.
equipment maker, for $4.4 billion, it was largely because Alcatel
wanted DSC's sales channels into big U.S. carriers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have gone IPO and perhaps done better financially,
but as a smaller company we would have ended up with a smaller part
of the market,'' Mukesh Chatter, Nexabit's chief executive, said
Friday. ``We needed someone's channels, support and service
systems.''
</P>
<P>
   Avici and Juniper have decided they do not need that kind of
help.
</P>
<P>
   Avici made that choice in particularly stark fashion Friday as
it ended its sales partnership with Nortel, which still owns 20
percent of Avici (though it will cede its seat on Avici's board).
</P>
<P>
   Surya Panditi, Avici's chief executive, said Friday that he
wanted to follow Juniper into the stock market and that some
distance from Nortel would help in that effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found that small companies no longer need the relationships
with the bigger companies to be successful with customers,'' he
said, ``and in the public market we also thought it would be more
helpful to be more independent.''
</P>
<P>
   But once again, Avici had the luxury to make that choice because
it is farther along than Nexabit in deploying its products.
Investment bankers are already pawing over Avici, hoping to take
the company public. Avici, for all of Panditi's talk, could still
decide to sell itself before an initial public offering. (Avici's
split from Nortel also probably had a lot to do with Nortel's
acquisition of Bay Networks Inc. last year. At some level Bay and
Avici could be seen as competitors.)
</P>
<P>
   But in trying to understand why different small companies follow
different paths to size, perhaps the most interesting thought came
from Daniel Smith, chief executive of Sycamore Networks Inc., a
private company in Chelmsford, Mass., that is developing an
advanced communications switch based on optical, rather than
electrical, technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to look to the personal side as well,'' he said,
speaking generally. ``If you've never made any money and you've put
some energy into something and put some time into it and someone
comes along and says, `I'll give you this value' and you have an
opportunity to monetize, then it's hard as an individual if you've
never made money to let your bet ride.''
</P>
<P>
   While Ray Stata, Nexabit's chairman, made money as one of the
founders of Analog Devices in 1965, until Friday Chatter, who is
considered the father of Nexabit's technology, had not yet
participated in the spectacular wealth-creation of the 1990s. By
contrast, Scott Kriens, Juniper's chairman and chief executive, was
a founder of Stratacom Inc. before that company was acquired by
Cisco Systems Inc. in 1996 for about $4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Smith should know what he is talking about. He and Desh
Deshpande, Sycamore's chairman, were the top two executives at the
Cascade Communications Corporation before that company was acquired
by Ascend Communications Inc. in 1997 for $3.7 billion. Smith says
Sycamore is in no rush to go public.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
