<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERIAL-KILLER-HOME-1STLD-WRITETH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIFE CALLS SUSPECTED SERIAL KILLER A `MODEL' HUSBAND AND FATHER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Sub to clarify quote in 2nd gragh and correct spelling in
20th graph to ``Maturino'' sted of ``Mauturino.'') 
 
(Attn: Ill., Ky., and Texas) 
 
By JIM PINKERTON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RODEO, Durango, Mexico _ The common-law wife of suspected serial
killer Rafael Resendez-Ramirez said Friday the man she has lived
with since 1995 is not a rapist or a killer _ she says a wife would
know.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say his motive was rape and all that. But I, as his
sexual companion, would know to what degree those tendencies he
might have had. But he was absolutely normal,'' said Julieta
Dominguez Reyes, who added Resendez-Ramirez has been a ``model''
husband and father.
</P>
<P>
   Dominguez, 42 and a laboratory technician at the state health
department clinic in this remote Mexican town, talked about her
husband as she cared for the couple's 3-month-old daughter, Lirio
Judith,
</P>
<P>
   Dominguez said she is cooperating with authorities and opened
her home in recent days to U.S. law enforcement authorities,
turning over some of her husband's letters, underwear and a guitar
he brought back from one of his many trips to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez, who is on the FBI's Ten Most Wanted List, is a
suspect in at least eight slayings in Illinois, Kentucky and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But Dominguez said if authorities can prove her husband's guilt,
he should be prepared to pay for his crimes with his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say, if he did something, he should pay,'' Dominguez said
Friday afternoon in the simple white, stucco home she shares with
Resendez-Ramirez. Her husband's pet dogs, a white German shepherd
and a black mutt, lolled on the front porch.
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``If he was involved in this, if he touched death,
then death should touch him, right? It is cause and effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Dominguez said Resendez-Ramirez was last home June 10. She said
her husband received a call that authorities were looking for him
in the central Mexican city of Puebla _ where he was born _ and he
quickly packed a few things and was gone in 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he's the one, because he would have to be
extremely cold and calculating... and he would have raised some of
the details in front of me, but there was absolutely nothing,''
Dominguez said. ``He was a person who was absolutely exemplary in
his treatment of me and his daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband told her U.S. authorities were after him because of
his past activities with a group of anti-abortion activists.
</P>
<P>
   Dominguez said her husband claimed he was prosecuted in the
United States in 1988 _ an investigation that cost $4 million _ and
the government was still after him.
</P>
<P>
   Dominguez said her husband, who often sent home his earnings,
worked at ``honorable jobs'' in the United States, mostly as a
seasonal agricultural worker.
</P>
<P>
   ``His income was not fixed,'' she said. ``He worked at temporary
jobs, picking oranges in Florida, tobacco in Kentucky, asparagus in
Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   And he also smuggled local people across the border, Dominguez
acknowledged, but she said he charged only $400 apiece instead of
the going rate of $2,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, he took people, one or two people he would take to cross
illegally and that's when he would get a little bit of money
because he didn't charge what they usually do.''
</P>
<P>
   Local police in Rodeo, a small town of 3,569 residents that
straddles the main highway heading north to Juarez and the border,
say Resendez-Ramirez often appeared in town with late model cars,
which he either gave to relatives or sold.
</P>
<P>
   Rodolfo Ramirez Ceniceros, commander of the Durango state
judicial police in Rodeo, stressed that Resendez-Ramirez had never
been involved in any crime in the small town or was even the
subject of a complaint. Local officers said Resendez-Ramirez was
apparently a member of an evangelical Christian group and did not
smoke, drink, attend dances or go out to dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is an introverted person, he was always alone,'' Ceniceros
said. ``He would ride his bike with his dogs, wearing shorts and a
T-shirt. He didn't have any friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Police said Resendez-Ramirez's mother, Virginia, and step-father
_ a Mexican Army retiree named Luis Maturino Morales _ moved to
Rodeo and built a small house eight years ago and Resendez-Ramirez
moved there about five years ago. Dominguez said her husband told
her he was the illegitimate son of a musician who refused to
acknowledge him.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Resendez-Ramirez for a short time taught English as
a bilingual instructor at a private school on the town square that
offered technical courses and is run by an order of nuns.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very serious. He didn't talk to anyone except his
dogs,'' a police officer recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Said another, ``He didn't have any friends. He didn't talk to
anyone or go into bars; he wasn't friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   Dominguez said she met Resendez-Ramirez in Rodeo in 1994 when
she heard he had a car for sale. She bought another car, however,
after he could not provide proper Mexican registration papers for
the vehicle he was trying to sell. Resendez-Ramirez volunteered to
teach her how to drive her stick shift car and the lessons lead to
romance.
</P>
<P>
   By 1995, they were living as man and wife in the modest,
three-bedroom house she bought on Avenue of the Palms, Dominguez
said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday afternoon, Dominguez still held out hope that all the
accusations against her husband would prove to be a case of
mistaken identity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have confidence in him that these things they are checking
on _ that it's not true. Like I said before, if he had done
something over there (in the United States) he wouldn't be going
back over there every little while.''
</P>
<P>
   As she held her infant daughter, Dominguez expressed fear that
``unscrupulous persons,'' tempted by rewards totaling $125,000,
could harm her or her daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I fear in this situation, that in some form they
will harm my daughter, use her as a hook'' to get to
Resendez-Ramirez, Dominguez said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
