<HEADLINE>
WINDY, THE STARS WON THE CUP, SO PLEASE GET OVER IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
Windy Ruff Head Coach Buffalo Sabres Losersville, N.Y.
Dear Windy:
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just wanted to drop you a line to see how you're enjoying the
off-season so far. Has it snowed yet? Thanks for timing summer
during the week we were there. Just can't tell you how much we
enjoyed our stay. Hope you feel the same.
</P>
<P>
   It's certainly been a tumultuous week since we last saw you
foaming all over yourself after the Stars' 2-1 Game 6
triple-overtime victory buried your Sabres once and for all in the
Stanley Cup Finals. Was that already a week ago tonight? Seems like
it happened just yesterday, doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   Yep, that's a night we can savor forever.
</P>
<P>
   It was really sweet the way you played to the crowd last week
when everyone got together there in Buffa-lose to honor the
second-place finishers in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``No goal!'' you shouted. ``No goal!''
</P>
<P>
   Nice try, Windy, but we've got the Cup and those aren't sour
grapes we're filling it with in these glory days of wine and roses.
Get over it.
</P>
<P>
   In case you hadn't noticed, you were scored on again Thursday
night at the NHL awards ceremony, and by none other than ``The
Great One'' himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it means anything, I thought it was a goal,'' five-time
Lady Byng winner Wayne Gretzky said at the end of his acceptance
speech.
</P>
<P>
   That hard, rubber cylinder clogging the back of your throat,
Windy? That's the puck ``The Great One'' just zipped into your
craw. Take a hint and shut your mouth before you choke.
</P>
<P>
   Show a little uncharacteristic class here, Windy. Your team was
outstanding and the series was something the NHL desperately
needed, a nightly jaw-to-jaw showdown, not another four-game sweep.
</P>
<P>
   ``This series did a lot for hockey, but maybe not in the way the
league intended,'' your own general manager, Darcy Regier, told
Sports Illustrated when it was over. ``We've been doing everything
the past few years to get more offense. This wasn't an offensive
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you equate offense with excitement, you might not have
liked seeing the two teams with the lowest goals-against average
during the season go at it. But for the fans who've been around the
game, they understood this was about character. This was about the
soul of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   You must have been pleased when SI bailed on a Stanley Cup
Finals cover for this week's edition. I hate to bust your bubble
but the magazine's editors insist it had nothing to do with the
controversial game-winning goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as the controversial call, that would have been more of
a reason to put them on the cover,'' SI senior publicist Joe Assad
said yesterday. ``The decision this week was more difficult than it
usually is, because of the volume of potential covers. We had the
Stars, the NBA, Payne Stewart winning the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, the last couple of years the NBA has taken the
cover from the NHL. We didn't have the Wings on the cover last year
either. The NBA seems to be what our readers prefer and that seems
to be reflected in the TV ratings, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Throw in the fact that by the time this week's issue hit the
stands, the game was a week old and that the magazine's editors
didn't really think they had a great photo from the game for a
cover, either.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds reasonable, if a little contrived, just like the NHL's
explanation of why Brett Hull's goal counted. He had control, he
shot, he scored. End of discussion.
</P>
<P>
   You don't like it, Windy, let me refer you to the solution
proposed by your Stars' counterpart Ken Hitchcock, who always cuts
to the chase: ``Don't be afraid to score more than one goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, the Stanley Cup? Guess you didn't get much of a look at it
last week, just a brief glimpse from a distance, so let me catch
you up.
</P>
<P>
   It's had a blast.
</P>
<P>
   There's already a dent in it _ nobody's sure how it happened,
dropped on the plane, or in the locker room or somewhere _ but once
Stars officials were able to peel Eddie Belfour off of it, it's
been making the rounds.
</P>
<P>
   It showed up at The Ballpark in Arlington the other night and
sat on the grass by the pitcher's mound while Craig Ludwig was
tossing the ceremonial first pitch. Later that same night, it was
spotted doing the two-step with several pretty young things at
Cowboy's in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was off to the awards ceremony in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Looks like it's going to have one heck of a year. We'll mention
that you asked about it.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously this has been hard on you. You need to stop watching
re-runs of Hull's shot. Get out of the house, take a walk, shovel
the snow off the driveway. Just don't forget your parka.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and Windy, one more thing.
</P>
<P>
   It's a goal.
</P>
<P>
   Even ``The Great One'' says so. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
