<SLUG> BC-BOX-TAPIA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAPIA OVERCAME MOTHER'S DEATH, DRUG WOES ON WAY TO TITLE FIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOEL ANDERSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If there has been one constant in Johnny Tapia's life, it's that
he has always been fighting. Unfortunately for him, not all of his
fights have come in the ring, as it will tonight against Paulie
Ayala.
</P>
<P>
   Tapia, a bantamweight, gets paid heavyweight bucks to fight as a
professional. But as a youth, Tapia's fights were more of a
reaction to a circumstance that landed knockout blows.
</P>
<P>
   After his mother was raped and stabbed to death when he was 8,
Tapia turned to the unforgiving streets of his hometown of
Albuquerque, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I was pretty much a troublemaker when I was little,''
Tapia said. ``I got in a lot of street fights.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Arum, president of Top Rank Inc., and Tapia's promoter, said
Tapia had a reputation as a thug.
</P>
<P>
   ``The incidence of street fights for Johnny is legendary,'' Arum
said. ``He's utterly and completely fearless to the point of
idiocy.''
</P>
<P>
   Tapia, who never knew his father, was rescued by his
grandfather, Miguel, who introduced him to the boxing ring at the
age of 11. The grit and fire that made Tapia a force on the streets
manifested itself into remarkable boxing talent. Tapia won two
Golden Gloves national titles in high school, and compiled more
than 100 victories on the amateur level.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the fight against drug addiction that nearly floored
Tapia.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after a successful foray into the professional ranks of
boxing, including a U.S. Boxing Association super flyweight title,
Tapia tested positive for cocaine after a title defense in October
1990. Two failed drug tests later, Tapia was suspended from boxing
for 3 1/2 years, sending him into a tumultuous period. He was
convicted of aggravated assault against his wife, Teresa, and
suffered through two near-fatal overdoses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just so thankful that I didn't die on the streets,'' Tapia
said.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fighter in Tapia that allowed him to stay troublefree
since getting back into the ring in 1994 and become the man people
close to him say he is now: a doting father and loving husband, as
well as an undefeated bantamweight champion.
</P>
<P>
   Tapia, 32, credits a strong network of family and friends,
headed by his wife, as the reason he escaped addiction and
probably, death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where I'd be today if it wasn't for Teresa,''
Tapia said. ``She and my family and friends are everything to me.
All of the credit goes to them.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, Tapia and his wife became the legal guardians
of 6-year-old Salo Jonathan Chavez, Teresa's nephew. Tapia said he
doubled his efforts to become a better husband, and he's now a
Christian.
</P>
<P>
   ``\RSalo\S is the love of my life,'' Tapia said. ``And Teresa
has been there for me through so many tough times. She may leave
me, but I won't let her go. If I lose her I'm nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Teresa, who also is Tapia's manager, blushes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so proud at what he has become out of the ring,'' she
said. ``Johnny is still an exciting person. He has the biggest
heart out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The family life still hasn't diminished Tapia's taste for the
flamboyant. Tapia sports a huge, jewel-encrusted replica of the
crucifixion around his neck and a large religious tattoo on his
chest. Arum, who has seen his share of entertaining boxers, said
Tapia now funnels his anger inside the ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a real showbiz flair,'' Arum said. ``To beat Johnny,
Paulie is going to have to fight the fight of his life.''
Johnny Tapia (46-0-2, 25 KOs) vs. Paulie Ayala (27-1, 12 KOs)
Length: 12 rounds At stake: Tapia's World Boxing Association
bantamweight (118-pound) title When: Tonight; four-fight undercard
starts at 8 Where:Mandalay Bay Resort &AMP; Casino, Las Vegas TV:
Showtime Event Television, pay-per-view
</P>
</TEXT>
