<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-AYALA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AYALA'S PLAN FOR TITLE BOUT INCLUDES DICTATING PACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ The question facing Paulie Ayala in his bantamweight
title fight against reigning champion Johnny Tapia tonight is
simple, but one 48 boxers previously have been unable to answer.
</P>
<P>
   How do you beat the undefeated Tapia, the World Boxing
Association champion at 118 pounds, and a man whose harshest fights
historically have been waged against personal demons?
</P>
<P>
   During the past six weeks, Fort Worth's Ayala and his training
team of Henry Mendez and Paul Reyes have devised a strategy they
believe will ambush the mercurial three-time champion at the
Mandalay Bay Events Center. And it begins with due respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said that Johnny Tapia is possibly the best junior
bantamweight in the world. Maybe even legendary,'' said Ayala,
alluding to Tapia's 40-month reign at 115 pounds. ``But I see
myself as the best bantamweight. And he has never faced an opponent
like me. Never.''
</P>
<P>
   The undercard is scheduled to start at 8 p.m. with the
championship bout expected to begin around 10 p.m. Showtime Event
Television will be carry the fight on pay-per-view.
</P>
<P>
   Stung by a title-fight loss in Japan 10 months ago, Team Ayala
has resurfaced with a revised map for the scheduled 12-rounder.
Mendez and Reyes want their left-handed challenger to dictate the
pace while incorporating more body punches, head movement and
combinations than Ayala previously has displayed in 28 bouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to see a new Paulie Ayala in this fight,'' Reyes
said. ``Paulie knows that if he wants to win this title, he's got
to go get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayala, 29, plans to be ``tactical'' in hopes of not only
displaying his ring generalship, but also as a way of frustrating
the champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a chess match,'' said Ayala, the No. 2-ranked WBA
contender who will earn a career-best $60,000. ``You want to
counteract something that they have and want to use.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he can get easily distracted, and I can get him off
his game plan by aggravating him. He's an emotional fighter. He
fights off the crowd. But if you frustrate him and aggravate him,
he's going to come after you and get off his game plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Tapia, 32, seems flattered by the attention Ayala (27-1, 12 KOs)
has paid to his style and its perceived shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to fight Johnny, but beating him is a
different story,'' said Tapia, of Albuquerque, N.M. ``I'm ready to
cut, I'm ready to bleed, I'm ready to do whatever. I'm not
losing.''
</P>
<P>
   Tapia, a 3 1/2-1 betting favorite after starting at 6-1, speaks
with the confidence of a fighter who has forged a 46-0-2 record
with 25 knockouts during a career that began with one of his two
draws 11 years ago. Tapia also speaks with the resolve of a man
who, after having been floored by an addiction to cocaine, has
regained his self-esteem and place in boxing history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in the ring where I'm safe,'' said Tapia, who will be
making the first defense of the WBA belt he took from ``Nana'' Yaw
Konadu of Ghana via a 12-round decision on Dec. 5. ``It's out of
the ring I have problems. So, what can you do to me?''
</P>
<P>
   Tapia said he fully expects Ayala to be in his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope so,'' said Tapia, who has been knocked down twice in
his career. ``He is very easy to hit. If he doesn't pressure me,
I'll pressure him. He doesn't have big power, but I've seen him
sting some guys. Don't make no difference. I'm too strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Mendez and Reyes contend that Ayala's left-handed style will
present Tapia with a fresh set of concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paulie's not an average left-hander,'' Mendez said. ``He's a
superb left-hander, the kind I know Johnny's never encountered. In
fact, he ain't never encountered a right-hander in our caliber. He
cannot knock us out.''
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Freddie Roach and Tapia, who will earn $250,000, both
brushed off the suggestion that Ayala's southpaw style is a huge
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been sparring left-handers. Johnny fights left-handers
very well,'' said Roach, who noted that Tapia went through seven
sparring partners during his seven-week camp. ``The thing is, this
guy \RAyala\S is game. He may be too game for his own good.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a lot of heart and I respect that. But it takes more
than that to win the bantamweight championship of the world from
Johnny Tapia.''
Punching in A comparison of key statistics in the professional
careers of bantamweights Johnny Tapia and Paulie Ayala, the No.
2-ranked contender: Tapia Category Ayala 48 Total bouts 28 95.8
Winning pct. 96.4 52 Knockout pct. 42.8 323 Career rounds 190 6.73
