<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRESBYTERIANS-GAYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESBYTERIANS DELAY DECISION ON ORDAINING GAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By TARA DOOLEY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Faced with a recommendation to move the
Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.) toward ordaining gays and lesbians,
denomination leaders voted on Friday to spend two more years
mulling the issue.
</P>
<P>
   With support of 61 percent of the voting clergy and lay church
leaders, the church's 211th General Assembly instructed
denomination officials to provide materials so that local
congregations and regional associations can discuss whether gays
and lesbians should be ordained as ministers and lay leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The move came with a recommendation that ordination requirements
not be revisited until the General Assembly meets in 2001, and it
effectively upheld the denomination's prohibition against ordaining
gays and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is searching for a broader degree of understanding on
various sides of the issue,'' said Stephen A, Moss, pastor of
Thyatira Presbyterian Church in Salisbury, N.C., and presenter of
the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week, a committee approved a proposal that could
have led to the removal of the prohibition on gay and lesbian
ordination. That suggestion to the General Assembly _ had it worked
its way through a long church process _ could have left ordination
decisions up to local churches and regional organizations called
presbyteries.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal was not voted on by the entire General Assembly,
which decided instead to consider the more conservative approach.
</P>
<P>
   The vote, 319-198, was among the most controversial of the
meeting, which began at the Fort Worth Convention Center a week ago
and will end on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The assembly's action was appropriate in light of tensions among
those with strong feelings about the ordination issue, said the
Rev. William F. Galbraith, pastor of St. Stephen Presbyterian
Church in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure there are people who would have liked to have seen
some decisive vote taken,'' he said. ``This vote does seem to be in
the spirit of the desire ... that we spend more time reflecting,
praying and seeking clarity about what God would be leading us to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   In prayer, General Assembly moderator Freda A. Gardner called
the discussion and the vote ``a very significant moment in our
lives and the life of the church.''
</P>
<P>
   The discussion on the convention center floor ranged from
analytical to emotional, as youth and adult leaders told the
General Assembly how they interpreted the issue and how it would
affect their lives.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Alexandra Lusak of the West Jersey Presbytery in New
Jersey spoke about exemplary members of her congregation who were
excluded from leadership roles because of the church's prohibition.
</P>
<P>
   In a tearful plea for a decisive stand for gay and lesbian
ordination, youth advisory delegate David White of the St.
Augustine Presbytery in Florida urged the assembly to remember that
the church teaches unconditional love.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to deal with it,'' he said. ``We can't discriminate,
no matter what.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Rev. Bryan Smith of the Detroit Presbytery, who said he
is still wrestling with the topic, urged the assembly to allow time
for discussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping we can find a way to keep talking about this in a
way that those of us who have strong convictions can understand
those of us who are still waiting and praying,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ordination of gays and lesbians is not a new issue for the
denomination. Since 1978, church policy has restricted them from
being ordained as elders, deacons and ministers. The prohibition
was officially written into the denomination's Book of Order in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Some meeting participants saw this year's discussion as a move
away from the strife the topic has inspired.
</P>
<P>
   Youth advisory delegates on the recommending committee
overwhelmingly supported ending the prohibition, said the Rev.
Kathy Runyeon, an adjunct faculty member of the San Francisco
Theological Seminary and the moderator of the committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hope expressed was that the climate would change to a more
open reality,'' Runyeon said.
(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
