<SLUG> BC-EASE-CARS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EASE SIMULATION OFFERS PARENTS CHANCE TO RECORD TEENS' DRIVING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. CRONKLETON  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- While most crash-recording devices are used
to collect data to help explain why an accident happened, a New
Milford, Pa., company is trying to use the technology to help
prevent crashes.
</P>
<P>
   Ease Simulation earlier this year introduced AutoWatch, a
product that allows parents to spy on their teen-agers' driving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Statistically, teen-agers are the most dangerous drivers on
the road,'' said Richard Wilbur, controller at Ease Simulation.
``By providing AutoWatch, we thought we could help change their
driving habits before it is too late.''
</P>
<P>
   AutoWatch, which works with Windows-based personal computers,
monitors a vehicle's speed, engine speed, gas-pedal position and
engine load. It also keeps track of the date and time the vehicle
was used.
</P>
<P>
   The system works by having parents set the limits on their
computer, such as every time the vehicle exceeds 65 mph. The
AutoWatch device is then hooked up to the vehicle. Whenever the
limits are exceeded, the module reports a time and date stamp along
with the violations.
</P>
<P>
   To prevent tampering, the module records a date and time if the
device is disconnected. To download the information, parents remove
the device from the vehicle and hook it back up to their home
computer.
</P>
<P>
   Wilbur said the product also appealed to corporations wanting to
monitor the driving habits of employees.
</P>
<P>
   The company offers two versions that work on almost any vehicle
from 1980 and later. The units cost $295 to $325, depending on the
model.
</P>
<P>
   Wilbur said parents who use AutoWatch should let their children
know it is there. He said the device was designed as a deterrent to
driving irresponsibly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fact of life. If you know you are being monitored, you
are going to behave differently,'' Wilbur said. ``In the
teen-ager's world, if you know your parents will know how fast you
are going, you are not going to go 85 mph too often.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
