<SLUG> BC-HKN-DRAFT-PREVIEW26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thrashers ready if Tampa tabs Stefan
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Patrik Stefan met with officials of the Tampa Bay
Lightning Friday morning and with Thrashers officials Friday night.
About noon today, he'll find out which team he'll be spending his
immediate future with.
</P>
<P>
   After picking up spare parts from other NHL teams in the
expansion draft, Thrashers general manager Don Waddell will begin
to build the team's foundation, with the second pick in today's
entry draft.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa general manager Rick Dudley would not disclose who his
team's first overall pick would be, but he appeared to be leaning
toward Stefan, the Czech native who played last season with the
IHL's Long Beach Ice Dogs. If Stefan goes first, Waddell was
leaning toward taking Czech forward Pavel Brendl second over Swede
Daniel Sedin.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Tampa takes Stefan, the bottom line is we have four
options,'' Waddell said. ``We can take Daniel Sedin, we can take
Brendl, we can take Henrik Sedin, or we can make a trade.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if those choices were listed in order of probability,
Waddell said, ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Waddell nor Dudley are concerned about Stefan's health,
despite the players' multiple concussions that limited him to 33
games this year. Stefan's agent, Rich Winter, has held off
disclosing recent medical reports on the player, but Waddell said,
``I'm sure Rich will let us see anything we need to see.'' But
Winter said that Waddell's ``confidence is not yet well placed.''
Winter was to meet Friday with a ``medical consultant'' before
speaking to Waddell.
</P>
<P>
   Waddell might not have a decision to make on Stefan, and Brendl
is not a bad runner-up choice. Brendl had 73 goals and 61 assists
in 68 games with Calgary of the Western Hockey League. Waddell
thinks that Brendl could step right in and play in the NHL next
season, although he's not considered as far along as Stefan, who
already has played in a pro league.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get either Czech, he can play next year,'' Waddell said.
</P>
<P>
   Brendl, who as recently as two weeks ago did not express much
confidence in playing in the NHL next season, appeared more
confident Friday. ``I believe I can make the next step. But I have
to work out hard during the summer, and then we'll see in training
camp what the team wants to do,'' Brendl said. ``I have always
scored a lot of goals, so I think I can score again.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel and Henrik Sedin, the Swedish twins, probably are two
years away from playing in the NHL. Both are represented by the
same agent, Michael Barnett, who was hoping to orchestrate a trade
so the brothers end up on the same team. The team most likely to
pull that off in the draft is Vancouver, which picks third.
</P>
<P>
   Stefan won't fall that far.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice to be number one,'' Stefan said. ``But I
don't know what is going to happen. It is a question I ask myself
all the time. But I don't ask the teams. I don't think that would
be so good.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
