<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DRAFT-THRASHERS26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thrashers deal for defense
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ About one hour before he was to step onto a stage and
read a list of names that would form his franchise's nucleus, Don
Waddell decided several weeks of trade talks involving a blur of
names and draft picks would come to an end.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, eight trades with a ninth on deck is quite enough for
one day.
</P>
<P>
   Waddell selected a 26 NHL leftovers, then wheeled and dealed to
swap two players, add eight more, then acquired three more picks in
today's amateur draft to punctuate the Thrashers' expansion draft
Friday at the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line: Atlanta was left with pretty much what Waddell
had projected _ a roster that is fairly solid in goal (Damian
Rhodes and Norm Maracle), decent on defense and mobility but devoid
of any goal production.
</P>
<P>
   ``From where we started this process to where we are today, we
feel really good about this,'' Waddell said. ``We know we don't
have all the answers yet. We need to add some pieces to the puzzle.
But it's a good start.''
</P>
<P>
   The Thrashers confirmed eight trades five hours after the draft
ended. The biggest ones:
</P>
<P>
   _ Goalie Trevor Kidd, who had been selected as an expansion pick
from Carolina, was traded to Florida for veteran defenseman Gord
Murphy, minor-league forward Herbert Vasiljevs, defenseman Daniel
Tjarnqvist (an unsigned draft pick from Sweden) and a sixth-round
pick (of Ottawa's) today.
</P>
<P>
   _ Detroit shipped would-be unrestricted free agent Ulf
Samuelsson to the Thrashers, who agreed not to pick forward Igor
Larionov off the Red Wings' unprotected list (Waddell would've
dealt Larionov to Anaheim or Vancouver). The Thrashers instead
chose Maracle. They likely won't sign Samuelsson but will gain a
compensatory draft pick next year (second- or third-rounder) when
another team signs the defenseman.
</P>
<P>
   _ In a complex deal with Boston, the Thrashers agreed not to
select goalie Robbie Tallas, picked up right wing Peter Ferraro,
then traded him back to the Bruins for top prospect Randy
Robitaille, who had been on the Bruins' protected list. Robitaille
led Providence (AHL) in scoring with 24 goals and 78 assists for102
points.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fourth- and sixth-round draft picks were acquired from
Vancouver to not draft goalie Garth Snow, who was unlikely to be
taken anyway. Instead, the Thrashers chose forward Steve Staios.
</P>
<P>
   Pending future deals, the Thrashers' weak offensive attack _
based on this year's regular season statistics _ is centered by St.
Louis' Terry Yake (nine goals), Phoenix's Mike Stapleton (nine) and
Florida's Johan Garpenlov (eight). Waddell chose not to take Los
Angeles's Vladimir Tsyplakov (11 goals), who would have become an
unrestricted free agent next year, or two high-priced talents he
had considered _ Tampa Bay's Alexandre Daigle and Vancouver's Trent
Klatt. He said neither was worth their near seven-digit salaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought a fresh start with a new franchise might be good
for Alexandre, but we just decided to go in another direction,''
said Waddell, who used his Tampa pick on goalie Corey Schwab.
</P>
<P>
   Waddell used the Kings' pick on tough left winger Matt Johnson,
who accumulated 131 penalty minutes last season.
</P>
<P>
   The Thrashers selected three goalies (trading Kidd), the maximum
10 defensemen and 13 forwards in the draft. One defenseman,
Anaheim's Jamie Pushor, is expected to be dealt to Phoenix for a
second-round draft pick next season.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta also gained minor-league goalie Scott Langkow from
Phoenix in exchange for picking a player (Stapleton) off the
Coyotes' short list of three players. New Jersey, which didn't want
to lose a forward, agreed to send the Thrashers defenseman Sergei
Vshedkevich if Atlanta didn't select a forward (the Thrashers took
defenseman Kevin Dean). A similar deal with Buffalo (concerned
about losing winger Geoff Sanderson) netted Atlanta minor-league
defenseman Dean Sylvester in addition to defenseman Darryl Shannon.
</P>
<P>
   The Thrashers also reached agreement with Calgary a few weeks
ago to not draft defenseman Phil Housley if he was left
unprotected. As it turned out, Housley was protected, but the
Thrashers gained unsigned Swedish draft pick Andreas Karlsson, in
addition to their pick of forward Ed Ward.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got all the bangers and checkers we need, now we just
need some goal scorers,'' Waddell said. ``But if you look at our
board, all of the guys we took can skate. That's the key ingredient
as we build a team. We want to make sure we've got guys who can get
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
