<SLUG> BC-Y2K-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER Y2K PITFALL REPORTED IN NEW MICROSOFT PRODUCT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HAYES and FINN BULLERS  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Office 2000, Microsoft's flagship software package released
earlier this month, could cause new Y2K problems for corporate
users, according to a leading British Y2K expert. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Karl W. Feilder, chief executive officer of Greenwich Mean Time,
said a lack of standardization in the way Office 2000 reads the
date could cause problems for corporate users who use a network to
share databases or files. Greenwich Mean Time is a Y2K repair
consulting firm based in the United Kingdom that markets a year
2000 software fix. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Instead of converting its software to read each year as four
digits -- say 1999 or 2003 -- Microsoft Office 2000 continues to
use a two-digit date field to identify the year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The software uses a common ``windowing'' technique to tell the
computer which century the years refer to. For instance, software
can be programmed to see any year ending in 50 and above as year
19xx, and any year beginning with 49 or below as year 20xx. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   However, Feilder said, Office 2000, combined with Microsoft
Windows 98, allows users to set their own date fields. For
instance, a user can decide that any year ending in 25 or above
should start with a 19. And it allows users to set different
parameters for different types of software included in the Office
2000 suite. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Office 2000 now allows users to set up to 99 date windows of
their own choosing,'' Feilder said. ``Two different users type the
same two-digit date into the same spreadsheet and it means two
different dates because each user has set their own date window.
This is particularly dangerous in a networked environment where
users share access to common databases.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Feilder describes Microsoft's Y2K efforts as checkered. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Recently, great strides have been made by their year 2000
group, but I fear Office 2000 has undone all that work. For over
three years I've been trying to help them understand the need to
remove all two-digit year possibilities from their products. Now
they're going in the opposite direction.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft says the technique used in Office 2000, known as
sliding windowing, gives customers maximum flexibility. &QL; 
 &QL; 
What, me worry? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After organizing a Y2K summit for 150 elected officials this
week, Kansas City, Mo., Councilwoman Teresa Loar said she is not
overreacting. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we are going to have any major disasters in
Kansas City'' on Jan. 1, said Loar, co-chairwoman of the
Mid-America Regional Council's Y2K Elected Officials Task Force.
``There may be some glitches at the ATMs and traffic lights, but
other than that, I don't see any problems.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In fact, she is so confident in the region's Y2K response that
her family isn't planning to make any just-in-case preparations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Utilities, public safety, banking and water department leaders
-- everybody assures me that their systems will be up and
running,'' Loar said. ``I seldom plan an hour ahead anyway. Y2K
won't be any different for us.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Co-chairwoman Joan Bowman, mayor of Lenexa, Kan., said she is
following the advice of the American Red Cross and planning for
Jan. 1 as if it were a bad winter storm: some bottled water, some
food and plenty of firewood and candles. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Rehearsals for madness &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Calls streamed in every 45 seconds for nearly 2 1/2 hours to a
unified command center in Lawrence, Kan., this week as part of a
``Millennium Madness'' Y2K preparedness drill. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ring: Six dead in suicide pact at Stull Cemetery. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ring: Power outages in Lecompton and Lawrence. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ring: $3,000 price tags on used generators. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ring: Rioting, looting, missing children and litter. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was all designed to test the mettle of the 52 emergency
responders in Douglas County who participated in the drill designed
by emergency management director Paula Phillips. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And after a frenetic morning of staged Y2K woe, Phillips said
her notebook was crammed with useful tidbits to prepare for
anything that a computer crash, or general mayhem, may throw at
emergency responders. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Public works officials learned they need more staff on duty to
help barricade streets or service emergency vehicles. Emergency 911
dispatchers say they need a cadre of couriers to expedite response
actions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And when the drill called emergency workers to deal with hungry
passengers on a stalled Amtrak car in east Lawrence, Phillips
learned the importance of the American Red Cross bearing food. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time it was over, people were tired and exhausted,''
she said. ``But it was definitely worth it.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Tidbits &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -- In Las Vegas, Y2K has delayed the January 2000 retrial of a
man implicated in the alleged murder-for-hire slaying of a woman
with ties to the wealthy DuPont family. During the first couple of
days of 2000, only the most necessary court hearings will be
conducted, said Clark County court administrator Chuck Short. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -- Bad computer programming 14 years ago caused a June 16 sewage
spill in Los Angeles that dumped 3 million gallons of raw sewage
into a city park, officials now say. The spill occurred when the
plant was testing a Y2K scenario in which the power failed. The
emergency generator kicked in as expected, but a gate failed to
reopen when a computer malfunctioned. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -- The high-tech industry, which also is asking for protection
from lawsuits filed by consumers and companies harmed by Y2K-caused
computer malfunctions, is banding together to make sure its own
suppliers are ready for Jan. 1, 2000. A group of 27 companies
joined together this week to form the High Tech Consortium -- Year
2000 &AMP; Beyond. The consortium will allow the companies to share
information about the Y2K readiness of suppliers that supply
crucial components for computers and other equipment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -- In Venezuela, officials have hired psychologists to find a
way to inform -- but not panic -- citizens about Y2K. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -- In Norway, prisoners at minimum-security prisons may be
released during the date rollover to avoid potential problems if
security measures fail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-99 2248EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
