</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERIAL-KILLER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BORDER AGENTS FREED SUSPECTED SERIAL KILLER JUNE 2, FBI SAYS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Graphic available on NYT database) 
(Eds.: Also see: Serial-killer-home) 
 
By JERRY URBAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Suspected serial killer Rafael Resendez-Ramirez was
taken into custody by immigration authorities earlier this month
but was returned to Mexico soon afterward, federal officials said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Linked through physical evidence to eight deaths in Illinois,
Kentucky and Texas, Resendez-Ramirez was detained by U.S. Border
Patrol agents June 1 after he crossed into the United States
illegally about seven miles east of Santa Teresa, N.M. He was
released into Ciudad Juarez, Mexico, in the early morning hours of
June 2.
</P>
<P>
   Because Resendez-Ramirez, believed to be 38, was using an alias,
agents were not aware that he was the man wanted at that time in
connection with three slayings in Texas and one in Kentucky, said
U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service spokeswoman Mariela
Melero in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had no indication at the time that he was a fugitive from
justice,'' said Melero.
</P>
<P>
   His fingerprints were taken and entered into the INS fingerprint
identification system, which is primarily a database of information
about people apprehended for crossing the border illegally, Melero
said.
</P>
<P>
   Agents had no reason, she said, to make a separate and specific
inquiry to such databases as the National Crime Information Center,
which could have identified him as the wanted man.
</P>
<P>
   Melero said Resendez-Ramirez, who is known to have used at least
30 aliases, was treated like the other 1.5 million illegal
immigrants detained each year along the U.S-Mexico border.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies of four of the eight people alleged to have been
killed by Resendez-Ramirez were found after June 2: Josephine
Konvicka, 73, of Fayette County, Texas, on June 4; Noemi Dominguez,
26, of Houston, on June 5; and George Morber, 80, and his daughter,
Carolyn Frederick, 52, in Gorham, Il., on June 15.
</P>
<P>
   He is also a suspect in the murders of Christopher Maier, 21, in
Lexington, Ky., on Aug. 29, 1997; Dr. Claudia Benton, 39, of West
University Place, an enclave of Houston, on Dec. 17, 1998; and The
Rev. Norman ``Skip'' Sirnic, 46, and his wife, Karen, 47, in
Weimar, Texas, on Apirl 30, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities believe he rides freight trains around the country
because all the crimes in which he is a suspect occurred near
railroad tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Tomas Zuniga, another INS spokesman, said Resendez-Ramirez was
processed at the Santa Teresa Border Patrol station, where his
photo and fingerprints were taken.
</P>
<P>
   In the early morning hours of June 2, he was taken in a
government van halfway across an international bridge and released
into Ciudad Juarez, across from El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if he even broke a sweat while he was in
custody,'' Zuniga said.
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez was first detained for slipping into the United
States illegally in 1976, and has served state prison time in New
Mexico and Florida. He had been deported at least four times.
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference Friday in Houston, the FBI displayed the
photograph taken June 2 of Resendez-Ramirez, along with several
other photos of him that law enforcement has gathered.
</P>
<P>
   Special agent in charge Don K. Clark did not blame anyone for
the release of Resendez-Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to discuss whether it was a mechanical error or
an error at all,'' he said.``Clearly we would have liked to have
had him some time ago. But what it does do is give us the most
current photograph that we can get out to the public in the hope
that somebody may have seen this person.''
</P>
<P>
   On June 8, the FBI formed a multiagency task force, ``Operation
Train Stop,'' based in Houston, and the nationwide publicity about
Resendez-Ramirez began shortly after that.
</P>
<P>
   The reward for information leading to the arrest and conviction
of Resendez-Ramirez, who was put on the FBI's Ten Most Wanted list
Monday, has grown to $125,000.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone with information about his whereabouts should contact the
FBI command center at 1-800-889-8161.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
