<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBLICANS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEATING, ROMER HAVE DIFFERENT ANSWERS ON STOPPING VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Neighbors knew each other, guns were used for sport,
and teenagers' rivalries were settled with shoving and occasional
fists in days when Frank Keating was growing up in Oklahoma and Roy
Romer was a boy in small-town Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a child, I hunted with shotguns and rifles after
school, but I never hunted my classmates,'' said Keating, the
two-term Republican governor of Oklahoma who dealt with the 1995
bombing that killed 168 people at the federal building in Oklahoma
City.
</P>
<P>
   Romer, a Democrat who retired in January after three terms as
governor of Colorado, went to the funerals after this year's
Columbine High School shooting and talked extensively with young
people, teachers and parents about what might have caused two
seniors to go on a shooting rampage, leaving 15 people dead,
including themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``People always thought they would be safe in the suburbs,''
Romer said. ``The violence elsewhere couldn't happen to you.
Littleton was a `safe' suburb.''
</P>
<P>
   Romer was in Seattle for a meeting of state Democratic chairs.
Keating is speaking Saturday to a session of Team 100, an
organization of the Republican Party's biggest donors.
</P>
<P>
   Out of tragedy, the two prominent politicians have come to very
different conclusions about what needs to be done about violence,
and school violence, in America.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the two weapons used in the Littleton massacre in
April came from gun shows, Romer has become an outspoken crusader
for such safety measures as a 72-hour period to check the
backgrounds of persons buying firearms at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a sea change public attitude'' in favor of gun
safety laws, Romer said. ``It was the knowledge of parents that
they cannot protect their own children that caused it.''
</P>
<P>
   A former FBI agent, Keating has taken the opposite stand. He
cited similarities of the Oklahoma City bombing and the Columbine
High School shootings in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``The perpetrators in both crimes could have done what they did
no matter how strict the laws on the books,'' he said. The crimes
were caused not by weak laws but by ``a huge vacancy in their
souls.''
</P>
<P>
   Keating acknowledged that passing laws making it more difficult
for children to obtain weapons ``will have an impact.'' But he
denounced those who have used the Colorado shooting to call for
tighter firearms laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taking an extreme and irresponsible view that the gun did it
rather than the kids shows that people are proposing political
solutions and hunting for political gain,'' Keating said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the federal government should step up prosecutions of
convicted felons caught with guns.
</P>
<P>
   But, he cautioned, ``I think anything that discourages the
rights of citizens to protect themselves would be calamitous to the
good order of our country. We would have only the criminals
armed.''
</P>
<P>
   Romer acknowledged the National Rifle Association's success in
lobbying the U.S. House of Representatives to reject the 72-hour
waiting period.
</P>
<P>
   He argued, however, that the NRA's victory may be brief. Romer
took on the gun rights group when he persuaded the Colorado
Legislature to pass a law banning ownership of handguns by anyone
under 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elected officials see the NRA's ability to come in and
organize, and they read it wrong,'' said. ``The issue has moved out
of the isolated world of the special interest group into public
discussion. People are saying, `Hey, we've had enough of these
shootings.' In that realm, the NRA can only lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Romer and Keating also had predictably different views of a
possible presidential showdown between Vice President Al Gore and
Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Romer said Republicans are ``annointing'' Bush as their
candidate, despite his apparent lack of in-depth knowledge of many
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``George W. Bush would not be a candidate for president if he
did not have his father's name,'' Romer said. Noting the vice
president's role in ending the air war over Yugoslavia, he added:
``I take comfort that it was Al Gore on the phone with the
Russians.''
</P>
<P>
   Keating, however, depicted Bush as a skilled negotiator who has
pushed tax cuts and tort reform through a Democrat-dominated
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``He comes from remarkable stock,'' Keating said of Bush. ``His
father is a saint. ... His mother and father inculcated values in
him. ... ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
