<SLUG> BC-SOC-WCUP-CHINA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA FACES LONG ROAD TO FINALS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: China, Australia, Ghana, Sweden, Norway, Russia, Canada,
Japan ,  N.J., Ore., Calif., Mass.)   By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service     
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   No team from among the 16 in the Women's World Cup will cover
more miles during the tournament than China. So no one could blame
the Chinese for skipping a walk-through Friday at Giants Stadium
designed to acclimate them to the grass for Saturday's clash with
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese will meet Australia after Russia takes on Canada in
the opening game in East Rutherford, N.J., where a crowd in excess
of 40,000 is expected. The Chinese went directly to their hotel to
rest after practice at nearby Montclair State University.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese traveled for almost 13 hours on Thursday following
the team's 7-0 triumph over Ghana in Portland, Ore., on Wednesday
night, a victory that assured China a place in the quarterfinals.
The Chinese coach, Ma Yuanan, through a team spokesman, simply
called the scheduling of the games for his team unfair.
</P>
<P>
   China opened the tournament with a victory over Sweden in San
Jose, Calif., then moved on to Portland before traveling to New
Jersey. They will have to return to San Jose for Wednesday's
quarterfinals. Then, if they reach the semifinals, as expected, the
Chinese will have to come east again to Boston, for a game next
Sunday. A victory there would send them west again, to Los Angeles,
for the championship game.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the U.S. team, projected to be China's opponent in
the final, can reach the championship game by going from New Jersey
to Chicago to Boston to Washington to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The weary Chinese might use second-stringers Saturday against
Australia, which needs to beat China and have Ghana beat Sweden in
order to advance.
</P>
<P>
   Russia can advance with a victory over Canada, which can advance
only by beating Russia by three goals and having Japan upset
Norway. This will be Russia's third game in seven days and Canada's
third in eight days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
