A0286 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFL-LADN     06-25 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIVALS JOIN FORCES, FOR NOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ And now for something totally different in the bid
to return an NFL franchise here _ Team Los Angeles?
</P>
<P>
   In the latest twist to the process of trying to gain a Los
Angeles expansion franchise, the two groups competing for the team
have apparently agreed to cease fire and present a unified
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   For now at least, Eli Broad and Ed Roski Jr. are rivals no more
with Michael Ovitz and Ron Burkle. Anyway, that's what Broad said.
</P>
<P>
   Broad said both groups met with NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue
and Gov. Gray Davis' new point man, Bill Chadwick, on Wednesday and
agreed to work together on Coliseum redesign, a site plan and
financing, and present it as a single package to owners at their
July 28 meeting in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to get the best out of everyone,'' Broad said.
``The main thing is, we're working together and not separate and
competing with one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got it down. We're all working toward the Los Angeles
Coliseum. The competition isn't the other guy now, it's Houston.
And that puts us in a much stronger position than before.''
</P>
<P>
   Broad and Ovitz haven't historically agreed on much, and if that
was the Ovitz interpretation of the meeting, he was keeping it
typically private.
</P>
<P>
   ``We regard the involvement of the state as very productive and
the meeting as very useful,'' Ovitz said through a representative.
Beyond that, he referred all questions to Chadwick. Chadwick could
not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   This new team effort not only includes Broad, Ovitz and suddenly
the governor, but the NFL. Roger Goodell, an NFL vice president who
was also at this week's meeting, could become a regular participant
in future meetings to build a Los Angeles consensus.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL previously granted Los Angeles a conditional franchise,
giving it a Sept. 15 deadline to finalize a winning proposal or
lose the expansion team to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   When the two competing groups presented separate plans for the
Coliseum to owners last month in Atlanta, Los Angeles seemed no
closer to getting final approval than before.
</P>
<P>
   Now Davis has charged Chadwick, an attorney and investment
banker, with coordinating the Los Angeles bid and giving direction
from the state _ which owns the Coliseum and Exposition Park.
</P>
<P>
   Davis has said he won't support state funding to lure the NFL
back, but Chadwick is now exploring ways to justify building the
expensive parking additions by offsetting their costs with
additional revenue and public use.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parking is needed for the 40 or 50 days the stadium is going
to be used for, but it may also be used as a park-and-ride facility
for downtown,'' Broad said. ``We talked about how it could be used
for USC, which has a big appetite for additional parking. This had
not been discussed before. It's a much broader agenda and
discussion than we've had. It isn't just parking for 10 NFL games
any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Broad said there will be a compromise between the 7,000-space
garage he had promoted and the 27,000 spaces proposed by Ovitz. The
NFL has pushed for at least 25,000 parking spaces on-site.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have agreed to a concept that in this city, it's very
important that people park not too far away and feel safe,'' Broad
said. ``Most of it will end up being on the property, with some at
USC. It's going to be a reasonable compromise number.''
</P>
<P>
   Broad said they are also examining using USC's football field as
a practice facility for the NFL team.
</P>
<P>
   This could all prove an uneasy alliance between the two
competing groups. Even if they manage to work as one leading up to
the July 28 meeting, that doesn't necessarily mean they will
ultimately present themselves as one ownership group.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ownership issue is not going to be decided until the
end,'' Broad said. ``We have more or less agreed to work together.
And at the end we either join forces as owners or we don't. If we
don't, the NFL will pick which ownership they prefer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it gets down to it, sure, we'll be competing for who gets
the most votes. But the first thing we have to do is tee this thing
up so we get an NFL expansion team to the Coliseum.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
