<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COMMUTER-TAX-NYT </SLUG>
 
(Attn: N.Y., N.J., Conn.) 
JUDGE UPHOLDS AND EXTENDS REPEAL OF COMMUTER TAX  (jw) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A state Supreme Court judge Friday upheld and even
extended the state Legislature's repeal of New York City's tax on
commuters who live in the state and ruled that the city could no
longer collect the tax from residents of New York, Connecticut, New
Jersey or any other state.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling, by Justice Barry Cozier of the state Supreme Court
in Manhattan, dealt a blow to the city's $35 billion budget, which
stands to lose $360 million a year in commuter tax revenue. New
York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Peter Vallone, the City Council
speaker, who sued the state last month in an attempt to overturn
the repeal, immediately said that they would appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that Judge Cozier was incorrect, that really the
opinion is inconsistent in a number of ways,'' Michael Hess, the
city's corporation counsel, said Friday. ``We are going to appeal
right away.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to prompting the suit filed by New York City, the
repeal was challenged by officials and commuters in Connecticut and
New Jersey, but for quite a different reason. Those suits charged
that the because the Legislature's measure lifted the tax only for
New York State commuters, the repeal was discriminatory and
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   The city, on the other hand, charged that the state could not
eliminate taxes that feed the city treasury without a request from
the mayor and the City Council.
</P>
<P>
   But Cozier ruled that the state needed no such request, because
the repeal did not affect the ``property, affairs and government''
of the city. He also ruled that the Legislature could decide on its
own to repeal the tax because the state had a ``substantial''
interest in regulating tax policy.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Cozier agreed with the plaintiffs from Connecticut
and New Jersey, ruling that the Legislature's attempt to repeal the
tax only for New York state residents violated the equal protection
clause of the U.S. Constitution. He said the selective repeal also
violated the Constitution's commerce clause, because repealing a
tax as it applied to residents of one state but not to others could
disrupt interstate commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``The judge says that's not correct, which was very obvious,''
Hess said of the selective repeal. ``Now it snaps over to a
situation in which nobody has to pay.''
</P>
<P>
   Cozier, who joined all the suits, ruled from the bench Friday
after hearing oral arguments. A written ruling is expected Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The commuter tax, in place for 33 years, is 0.45 percent of
earned income for most people. Nearly 800,000 people pay the tax,
which amounts to about $180 a year for someone who earns $40,000 in
net income.
</P>
<P>
   The repeal infuriated Giuliani and Vallone, who maintained that
commuters should help pay for city services. They also condemned it
as a blatant attempt by state legislators to curry favor with
suburban voters, and in fact momentum for the repeal first
developed when it became an issue in a special election for a state
Senate seat from Rockland and Orange counties. The two major
contenders proposed repealing the tax, and both Republican and
Democratic leaders responded in an effort to help their causes.
</P>
<P>
   The unexpected loss of revenue led the mayor and the speaker to
abandon a number of tax-cut proposals for city residents. In the
end, they included only three relatively modest cuts, worth $348
million, in the $35.3 billion budget for the fiscal year that
starts July 1.
</P>
<P>
   But Gov. George Pataki and numerous state legislators contended
that the repeal was a valid attempt to ease the tax burden on
commuters, particularly when the city has a record budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   The city collects about $210 million a year from commuters who
live in New York State, and an additional $150 million from
commuters who live in other states, mostly New Jersey and
Connecticut. Officials in Albany said Friday that they had not
decided whether to fight the extension of the repeal to commuters
from other states.
</P>
<P>
   But officials in New Jersey and Connecticut appeared confident
that the ruling would stand.
</P>
<P>
   `Tax cuts have been at the core of our economic recovery, and
I'll fight to win them for New Jersey residents any way I can,''
Gov. Christie Whitman said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Blumenthal, the Connecticut attorney general, said that
the ruling ``sends a message that tax wars will not be tolerated
among neighboring states.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
