<SLUG> BC-FED-RATES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC SPOTLIGHT WILL BE ON FED'S ACTIONS NEXT WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK DAVIS  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- Experts generally agree that the Federal
Reserve will raise its targets for interest rates next week. It's
what comes next that has the stock and bond markets and perhaps
even the central bankers guessing.
</P>
<P>
   Monetary policy makers, led by Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan, will
meet Tuesday and Wednesday. It's widely expected they will raise
the federal funds rate -- which banks charge each other for
overnight loans of banking reserves -- to 5 percent from 4.75
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The move would deliver on the Fed's warning in May that it had
taken a ``bias'' toward tightening policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our feeling is that a quarter-point (increase) is as close to
a certainty as you get in this business,'' said Ethan Harris,
senior economist at Lehman Brothers in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Credit markets already have pushed up interest rates on home
mortgages, car loans, business credit and the like. Savers, too,
have seen higher rates on bank deposits and money-market mutual
funds.
</P>
<P>
   By following suit and raising its benchmark fed funds rate, the
Fed hopes to tap the brakes on the fast-paced U.S. economy. A
report Friday showed the economy grew at a 4.3 percent pace in the
first quarter this year, faster than government estimates just a
month ago.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan's concern is that continued rapid economic growth
could rekindle inflation.
</P>
<P>
   That's a sharp reversal from just nine months ago, when the Fed
quickly cut the fed funds rate three times to prevent economic
panic in Russia and Latin America from reaching the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's three rate cuts last fall quickly restored confidence
to badly shaken stock and bond markets. The booming U.S. economy
hardly skipped a beat.
</P>
<P>
   The surprise has been that inflation has continued to decline
despite the economy's 4 percent growth rate in each of the last
three years and the unemployment rate's dip to 4.2 percent. With
joblessness still dropping and the economy still cooking,
policy-makers would have expected to see rising inflation long ago.
</P>
<P>
   But there's no sign that inflation is heating up now.
</P>
<P>
   This apparent breakdown in economic trade-offs has Fed
policy-makers ``flying by the seat of their pants these days,''
Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're trying to sort all that out,'' added Mark
Eveans, chief investment officer at Eveans, Bash, Magrino &AMP; Klein
Inc. in Overland Park, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony before Congress last week, Greenspan laid out his
scenario in which inflation could become a problem.
</P>
<P>
   He explained that two points of the economy's four percentage
points of growth in the last three years had come from rising
productivity. He said an additional one point had come from the 1
percent growth in population.
</P>
<P>
   The final percentage point in growth, Greenspan said, has come
from the ever-dwindling pool of the unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   Harris said Greenspan's prescription is to slow economic growth
to 3 percent as his ``pre-emptive strike'' against renewed
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that the much sharper rise in market interest
rates, higher oil prices and the recently sluggish stock market may
have done the Fed's braking for it already.
</P>
<P>
   But the evidence of a slowdown has not shown up in the economic
reports. And that leaves the Fed and others watching to see whether
next week's step toward higher interest rates will need to be
followed by a second step.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they will move (Tuesday) and wait and see,'' said
Murray Weidenbaum, chairman of the Center for the Study of American
Business in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Harris said economists and the Fed will be watching four
economic reports due between now and the Fed's next meeting,
scheduled for late August.
</P>
<P>
   The next monthly unemployment report will be released Friday and
another is due before the Fed's August meeting. In mid-July and
mid-August, retail sales updates will show whether consumers -- the
biggest source of economic growth -- have slowed their spending
habits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then the Fed has to decide,'' Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meanwhile, Wall Street will have to decide whether next
week's Fed step settles the question.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Eaton, investment strategist at U.S. Bancorp Piper Jaffray,
said the stock market was simply waiting for official word on
interest rates to resume its climb.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the stock market wants to see that Alan Greenspan is
still watching inflation,'' Eaton said. ``I think we'll see a nice
rally and see some new highs.''
</P>
<P>
   Others are less confident.
</P>
<P>
   Rich Jones, a portfolio manager at Mitchell Capital Management
in Kansas City, Mo., said the stock market was prepared for one
step higher by the Fed.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if there's any indication of a second or third leg (to Fed
tightening) I'm not sure market valuations can stand it,'' Jones
said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he wouldn't turn bearish on stocks if the Fed raised
rates again this summer, but he'd tell clients to postpone
additional stock purchases because they would likely see even lower
prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know for sure,'' Eveans said. ``You're always
analyzing on the fly and making your best guess.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
