<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 23:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0294 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOAP-FANS-MOURN-NYT &LR;      06-25 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOAP-FANS-MOURN-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Ky.)  
 ON SOAP OPERA'S LAST DAY, FANS GATHER TO COMMISERATE  (mk) 
 By BARBARA STEWART   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At first, Donna Evers just wanted to have a quiet
lunch so she could mourn with friends as she said goodbye forever
to the people she had loved so long.
</P>
<P>
   But after she posted an invitation on the Internet, the lunch
took on a life of its own. Friday at 1 p.m., more than 100 ardent _
even loving _ fans crammed into the back room at Blondie's
Restaurant on the Upper West Side for the final episode of
``Another World,'' which was the top-rated soap opera in the 1970s
but was being canceled by NBC after 35 years and 8,891 episodes.
</P>
<P>
   The Blondie's goodbye lunch was probably the largest gathering
of fans, but there were other send-offs, too. The waitresses at the
JRS Diner in Brooklyn, across the street from the NBC studio where
the show was filmed for years, dabbed their eyes when Cass
exchanged vows with Lila _ although a few of those tears may have
been shed over the loss of the soap opera's 200 employees,
including several good tippers.
</P>
<P>
   And millions of viewers around the country and Canada were
watching, despite their anger at NBC, and probably could not help
but laugh when a gorilla appeared at the wedding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm obsessed,'' said Tammy Casanova, 33, a waitress at a
``little greasy spoon'' in Pinebush, N.Y. ``This is like losing
family.'' Ms. Casanova had driven down to Blondie's, on West 79th
Street, for the day with a friend, Kathy Davis, a manicurist in
Pinebush, and Vanessa, Ms. Casanova's 13-year-old daughter, who
would go straight home after school every day to catch the last 20
minutes of the show.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting across from Ms. Casanova, Priscilla, a lawyer who just
passed the bar exam and was taking a very long lunch, said, ``I
can't lose this job, but I couldn't stay away.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll understand,'' Ms. Davis said soothingly. ``This is a
one-time thing. It's important.''
</P>
<P>
   In a back room at Blondie's were the actors and actresses of
``Another World,'' unmistakable with their crisp make-up, high
cheekbones and slim physiques. Some had already found new jobs,
some were still looking. A few were taking themselves and their
characters onto ``As the World Turns,'' and ``Guiding Light,'' the
last two soap operas produced by Proctor &AMP; Gamble Productions for
CBS.
</P>
<P>
   For them, the lunch at Blondie's was both a cast party and a way
to help ease the fans' pain, to help them fight off the emptiness
that would surely confront them at 1 p.m. on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans have endured and we're here to share their sadness,''
said Linda Dano, who played the very rich Felicia for 17 years.
``We hope they will find a place for them to go to be happy, to get
over their sadness.''
</P>
<P>
   And where might that be?
</P>
<P>
   ``Lisa would say CBS,'' she said, referring to Lisa Peluso and
her new job on ``As the World Turns.'' ``I would say ABC,'' said
Ms. Dano, who has found work on ``One Life to Live.'' Since the
shows are broadcast at the same time, a smiling Ms. Peluso
suggested: ``Tape one and watch the other. And if you have a
Nielson box, shake it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Actors and fans alike agreed that NBC had made a serious, almost
immoral mistake in canceling the show. The problem, many fans said,
was that ``Another World'' was too good, artistically and ethically
_ too well-written and decent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was about normal-life people,'' said Lisa Pauley, 29, who
was visiting New York with her husband, Bill, a minister of music
and senior activities at Beachland Baptist Church in Louisville,
Ky. ``The characters had normal problems _ weight problems, drug
addiction.''
</P>
<P>
   Pauley, who would get the latest details on the show at dinner
every night, described some of the story lines: ``There was the one
when Brian died. His brother, the mayor, killed him. But he came
back when his fiancee was in trouble to defend her when she was
about to get killed, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The clamor in the crowded room at Blondie's quieted when the
show was on the air. They watched as the characters turned directly
into the camera, ostensibly speaking to the newly married Cass and
Lila, but really seeming to be talking to the viewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``May the road rise up to meet you,'' said Sergei, the Russian
chauffeur, reciting the well-known Irish blessing.
</P>
<P>
   Some fans seemed to have trouble remembering that the characters
on the screen were not, well, real.
</P>
<P>
   Toni, who was moving to Tampa, Fla., to be a police captain,
looked at the camera and said, ``If you're ever in Florida, come
visit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm coming!'' cried Ms. Casanova, her cheeks wet.
</P>
<P>
   And when a young lawyer was being congratulated on being
appointed a judge _ one of dozens of plot line strands neatly tied
up _ Priscilla, who had just passed the bar, cried: ``That's
ridiculous! He's not ready to be a judge! We graduated at the same
time!''
</P>
<P>
   When the last scene rolled around _ Felicia lightly touching
dozens of framed photos of the show's actors _ the sobs were
audible. Pauley, his face grim, put his arm around his wife, who
clenched a tissue.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Morely, 38, a computer programmer from Portchester, N.Y.,
said she had been watching for 28 years with her mother and
grandmother. ``It's a part of how I am,'' she said. ``I talked to
my Mom about it all the time on the phone. I'm worried now. What am
I going to have to talk with her about?''
</P>
<P>
   The show's head writer, Leah Laiman, gave assurances about the
characters' futures. ``We want you to know that these characters
will love happily ever after,'' she said at Blondie's. Pushing her
power a bit, she concluded, ``And so will you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
