r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FATAL-HOGTYING-TEX     06-25 1266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FATAL-HOGTYING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORT WORTH POLICE EXPAND INVESTIGATION OF HOGTYING FATALITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KATHY SANDERS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The internal inquiry into the death of a man
who was hogtied in police custody has been expanded to include
detectives who, by ``intentional action or negligence,'' ignored
crucial elements of the investigation, Police Chief Thomas Windham
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Internal affairs investigators also will question supervisors
and officers who sat on pre-disciplinary panels that exonerated two
of the five officers who were later fired because the case, Windham
said.
</P>
<P>
   The chief said Thursday that the five officers used excessive
force in the arrest that led to the death of Luis Enrique
Hernandez, 31, then lied to cover up their actions. Windham has
asked state and federal officials to look into criminal charges or
the possibility of civil rights violations.
</P>
<P>
   The internal investigation, he said, will focus on why evidence
that Hernandez had been hogtied was ignored, discounted or
disregarded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm most disappointed in the investigation and the review of
this situation,'' Windham said at a morning news conference. ``It
was put in place to get to the facts. ... Because of intentional
actions or negligence, the review process did not reveal the facts
of this situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The fired officers, all of whom have appealed their dismissals,
are David N. Stefanos, 30, an eight-year veteran; David P. Alkins,
27, commissioned in October 1995; Linn William Goodman, 27, an
officer for slightly more than a year; Hector Luis Melendez, 28,
also with a year on the job; and John R. ``John-John'' Ornelas, 25,
an officer since December 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Sterling Gilliland, a Police Explorer Post Scout and police
academy applicant who was with the officers, was also accused by
Windham of participating in the cover-up and lying to
investigators. His application has been rejected by the academy.
</P>
<P>
   Also Friday, attorneys for the fired officers blamed poor
training and supervision and accused Windham of portraying events
in the worst light.
</P>
<P>
   The expanded inquiry will examine the actions of former Lt.
Alice Adams, who supervised the investigation until her retirement
in April, and major case unit Detectives .MDNM/I.V. Haley, the lead
investigator, and Vic Fowler.MDNM/ and James Desmarais..MDNM/
</P>
<P>
   Adams, contacted at her home, said ``it would be inappropriate
at this time'' to comment on the Hernandez case or Windham's
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Desmarais also declined to comment. Fowler and Haley could not
be reached.
</P>
<P>
   City officials expressed support for Windham.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the actions of the chief send a message loud and
clear,'' Assistant City Manager Libby Watson said.
</P>
<P>
   City Councilman Chuck Silcox, a frequent critic of Windham,
said, ``I think he has shown that he is on top of the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney David Sloane, who represents Goodman, said he believes
that the five fired officers are scapegoats for what he described
as inappropriate training and supervision in the use of leg
restraints and hogtying.
</P>
<P>
   The department's rules, regulations and policies ban any form of
hogtying, but the officers' attorneys said the orders contain no
definition of the prohibited restraint.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Terry Daffron Hickey of the Combined Law Enforcement
Associations of Texas, which is providing attorneys for the
dismissed officers, said Windham painted the ``worst possible case
against the officers, whether accurate or not. The letters (of
dismissal) only contain alleged violations of department general
orders and do not allege any criminal wrongdoing by the officers.''
</P>
<P>
   Many departments banned hogtying after national studies showed
that the practice could cause or contribute to death.
</P>
<P>
   Windham and other officers described the procedure Friday as
handcuffing a person behind the back, restraining the ankles, then
binding the ankles to the handcuffs, leaving the victim in a
bow-shaped position.
</P>
<P>
   MedStar ambulance attendants and paramedics said they found
Hernandez in that position when they arrived at his home in the
3200 block of Hale Avenue about 2:30 p.m. on New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   Police responded that day to a report that Hernandez had struck
a child. They scuffled with him, then handcuffed and hogtied him to
restrain him, witnesses said. Hernandez became motionless and
unconscious and was left lying in the street, Windham said.
</P>
<P>
   MedStar attendants ordered officers to release the hog-tie so
they could treat Hernandez, Windham said in dismissal letters sent
to the city's Civil Service Commission. Hernandez died a short time
later.
</P>
<P>
   An autopsy concluded that he died of sudden cardiac death and
aspiration of gastric contents. After learning of the hogtying,
Medical Examiner Nizam Peerwani said he will review his report and
issue a final ruling on the death next week.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors who saw Hernandez scuffle with police told
investigators and reporters at the scene that they had seen
Hernandez hogtied. The officers involved, Windham said, repeatedly
denied that anyone used the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Windham said Gilliland, the Explorer Post Scout, subsequently
told investigators that after Hernandez died, he was drawn into a
circle of officers and admonished not to mention the hog-tie.
</P>
<P>
   Later that evening, while driving to downtown headquarters to
give statements, Ornelas again told Gilliland not to reveal
anything about officers using the hog-tie, Windham said.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing those statements and reviewing the case, Windham
said he determined that the officers had lied, either outright or
by omission, about their handling of Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   After Hernandez died, major case unit detectives conducted the
investigation into what the department calls a crucial police case.
Their work, however, was poor, Windham said. Many witnesses who
said they had seen the victim hogtied were never interviewed again,
the chief said.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, the results of such an investigation are forwarded to
the supervisors of the involved officers. The results and the
supervisors' recommendations are sent to a pre-disciplinary review
board, which usually includes three captains, a lieutenant and a
peer of the officer.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the incomplete investigation, Windham said, the
review boards for Stefanos and Alkins were given flawed
information, and the boards did not sustain the allegations of
excessive force. The review board's recommendations were sent to
the chief in May.
</P>
<P>
   Windham said it became obvious that Hernandez had been hogtied
and that the officers weren't telling the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I then asked internal affairs to conduct a supplemental
investigation,'' he said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Windham U.S. Attorney Paul Coggins this week to investigate the
possibility that Hernandez's civil rights were violated. He will
forward a criminal case to the district attorney's office for
consideration of state charges, such as voluntary manslaughter or
negligent homicide, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you have a serious allegation of civil rights
violations, it will be treated seriously by our office and the
FBI,'' Coggins said. ``When the chief of police calls, we take it
just as seriously, if not more seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Coggins said he cannot recall any prior civil rights
investigation involving Fort Worth police.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Staff writers Yvette Craig, Gabrielle Crist, Bob Mahlburg and
Ginger Richardson contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
