<SLUG> BC-BUDDHIST-TEMPLE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONKS CELEBRATE OPENING OF LARGEST THAI BUDDHIST TEMPLE IN U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN IWASAKI  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ For a handful of Thai Buddhist monks living near a
tranquil pond between Auburn and Federal Way, a double-wide mobile
home served as their ``temporary'' temple for 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Now only their address remains the same. On Saturday, the monks
will celebrate the opening of their new house of worship, a
47,000-square-foot structure that is the largest Thai Buddhist
temple in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very happy,'' Phra Amaramuni, the abbott of Washington
Buddhavanaram Buddhist Temple, said while sitting inside a vast
hall anchored by a 9-foot-tall brass Buddha covered with gold leaf.
``Everybody's happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred worshipers, some from overseas and across the
nation, are expected at Saturday's opening and Sunday's services on
the 7-acre site. Among them are 100 monks here for an annual
conference of the Dhammayut Order in the United States, of which
Amaramuni serves as president.
</P>
<P>
   Construction on the $2.7 million project started seven years ago
and proceeded as money was available. Many of the donations came in
small denominations from Buddhists locally and in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably, the bulk of construction was accomplished by a tiny
crew, just ``three men and a forklift,'' said Boonling Rosehom, a
monk wearing a mustard-colored robe.
</P>
<P>
   The temple counts between 100 and 200 members in the Seattle
area, most of Thai ancestry but also from Cambodia, Laos, Myanmar,
Sri Lanka, Tibet, Vietnam and China.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's open for everybody, not just Buddhists,'' Amaramuni said
of the temple at 4401 S. 360th St., in southern King County, which
he said eclipses the size of Thai Buddhist structures in California
and Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the temple will convert the lower level of the
building into a meditation center, library and classrooms and offer
teachings about Buddhism.
</P>
<P>
   The monks practice the Theravada school of Buddhism, in which
devotees make offerings to an image of Buddha to gain karmic merit
and to be reminded of the Buddha's virtues.
</P>
<P>
   The opening of the temple culminates a 17-year effort that began
when Buddhist monks arrived from Thailand in 1982 at the request of
the local Thai community and rented a house in Federal Way that
doubled as a temple. In 1984, temple members bought their current
property and assembled a prefabricated structure.
</P>
<P>
   The new temple is not only for the here and now, Rosehom said.
</P>
<P>
   Suspended around the perimeter in precise locations are nine
200-pound granite balls serving as boundary markers. Each ball
symbolizes a different blessing, such as long life and happiness.
</P>
<P>
   In Saturday's ceremony, the woody vines holding the balls will
be severed and the spheres will be buried.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1,000 years, the building will be gone but the stones will
still be underground,'' Rosehom said. ``If you can find one, you
can find all the others. ... It means you're successful in building
the temple.''
</P>
<P>
   While still above ground, worshipers rub patches of gold leaf on
the 15-inch-diameter balls and cover them with coins. Some scribble
wishes on scraps of paper and drop them into 4-foot holes beneath
the balls.
</P>
<P>
   Also tossed in are pencils (representing memory, since they're
used to write information) and gold or silver needles (representing
a sharp mind or wisdom), Rosehom said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, worshipers knelt before Amaramuni and presented cloth
pouches filled with coins, dollar bills, needles, thread, locks of
hair and fingernail clippings.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're giving yourself to the temple, so in the next life
you'll be better,'' said one worshiper, explaining the contents of
the offerings. Once the bills are removed _ the temple still has
expenses to pay _ the pouches will be placed in the holes.
</P>
<P>
   The granite balls are symbolic of a mind ``heavy like a stone,''
where confusion is pushed out, Rosehom said.
</P>
</TEXT>
