<SLUG> BC-BKN-SHAQ-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'NEAL WON'T OPT OUT OF CONTRACT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Lakers' greatest offseason
transaction will be the one that didn't happen. Shaquille O'Neal
has decided not to become a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Not that anyone expected otherwise. But he made it official
Friday _ which was the deadline for that decision _ when his agent
announced O'Neal would not exercise an option to terminate the last
four years of his contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaquille has decided to remain with the Lakers,'' Leonard
Armato said in a statement. ``He is excited about the Lakers'
prospects for the future and is looking forward to playing for new
coach Phil Jackson.''
</P>
<P>
   Armato declined to comment further.
</P>
<P>
   Upset over the Lakers' third straight postseason collapse and
frustrated by teammate Kobe Bryant and coach Kurt Rambis, O'Neal
made noise about opting out of his contract, though it never seemed
likely. The hiring of Jackson wiped out any lingering doubt.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Neal had millions of reasons to stay. His seven-year
contract has four years and $81million remaining, starting with
$17million next season. If he signed with another team, NBA rules
would set O'Neal's starting salary at $11million.
</P>
<P>
   Alternatively, O'Neal could have opted out in order to sign a
new long-term deal _ up to seven years and $151 million _ with the
Lakers, but that too would have involved a slight pay cut
initially.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a personal standpoint, I can't tell you how excited I
am,'' Lakers executive vice president Jerry West said of O'Neal's
decision. ``He has yet to get completely to the top of his game. He
just has so much room to improve. And the bottom line is he's a
good guy and he wants to win, and that's why he gets frustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   But not frustrated enough to bail out on one of the NBA's
premier franchises, which just signed one of the league's premier
coaches to a five-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hired the coach with the best credentials that was there,
and someone who has a wonderful way of working with people,'' West
said. ``More importantly, I think it gives us something that from
my perspective is a very stable situation, and I think that's what
Shaquille wants.''
</P>
<P>
   The next personnel decisions will come from the front office.
Jackson will return to L.A. this weekend and will meet with West
and general manager Mitch Kupchak to discuss the coaching staff and
the roster _ including the status of Glen Rice.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers are already negotiating with former Bulls assistant
coaches Jim Cleamons and Jimmy Rodgers to rejoin Jackson, and
Chicago assistant Tex Winter is a strong possibility as well.
Lakers coaches Kurt Rambis, Bill Bertka and Larry Drew are expected
to meet with Jackson, but it appears there will be little or no
room on his staff.
</P>
<P>
   Rice could become a free agent July 1 unless the Lakers exercise
a one-year, $7.1million option by June 30. All indications are that
they will, though Rice has made it clear he wants a new multiyear
contract with a starting salary closer to the $14 million maximum.
</P>
<P>
   West said no decision had been made and that Jackson's input
will weigh heavily.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're I think leaning very heavily toward keeping the same
team we have,'' he said. ``Phil Jackson is coming to town, and we
basically try to do what our coaches want us to do, and get them
the personnel they want.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
