<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-25 23:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0303 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COL-VIRTUE-NYT     06-25 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-VIRTUE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: VIRTUE'S NICE, BUT A REWARD IS MORE HELP
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By DAN BARRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   His admirers say that Eric has concerns about the publicity, and
understandably so. After living on the streets for so long, he does
not want to risk disrupting the peace of his home. Besides, there
are people in prison because of him; no sense in giving them ideas.
</P>
<P>
   So with all due respect, Eric declined to talk about himself.
But his silence does not mute the rare charm of his story. And we
all should know when one of the good guys finally wins.
</P>
<P>
   At first, charm was nowhere to be found. On a March afternoon in
1996, three men burst into a jewelry store in downtown Brooklyn,
flashing guns to clarify their intentions. They made off with
$1,500 and a collection of rings and bracelets, all gold.
</P>
<P>
   When the police began chasing them down Fulton Street, the
bandits opened fire. Although no bullet found its uniformed mark,
the gunmen managed to disappear in the confusing cloud of violence.
</P>
<P>
   A block away, Eric was at his usual station, panhandling. The
homeless are often invisible to society at large; on this day, Eric
was invisible to three men in particular. They scrambled past him,
hustled into a waiting car and sped away.
</P>
<P>
   The gunmen and their driver should not have taken Eric for
granted. He may have been begging on the street, but he is
intelligent and proud; grounded, you might say. When the police
arrived, he asked whether they were looking for three men in a
hurry. As a matter of fact, they were.
</P>
<P>
   Eric volunteered the make and license plate of the getaway car,
as well as which way it went. He then climbed into a patrol car and
joined the hunt for the men who had fired at officers of the peace.
</P>
<P>
   The police soon came upon the abandoned car. Its occupants had
bolted in different directions, judging by the trail of stolen
valuables left in their wake. But no matter where they hid _
whether in that closet on Pacific or in that backyard on Clinton _
the three gunmen and their driver were found and arrested at
gunpoint.
</P>
<P>
   Eric's work was not done. He testified before the grand jury
that indicted the men, and repeatedly offered his services to Hilda
Mortensen, a prosecutor in the office of Brooklyn District Attorney
Charles Hynes. ``He told me I could generally find him on a corner
on Montague Street,'' Ms. Mortensen said.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing the value of Eric's assistance, Ms. Mortensen and
Kevin Gallagher, a Brooklyn detective, recommended to the Police
Department that he receive a $10,000 reward from a nonprofit
organization that sponsors a program called COPSHOT. After all, Ms.
Mortensen said, ``I wouldn't have been able to get any convictions
because without his help, no one would have been arrested.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Police Department decided that Eric's case did not
qualify for any reward, a spokesman said this week, because ``it
was determined at that time that it did not fit the criteria.'' The
primary criterion cited by the spokesman was that the information
leading to the capture of someone who shoots at an officer ``must
be made through a phone call.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Eric was being penalized for relaying his
crucial information in person and in the heat of the moment. His
case for a reward, it seems, would have been strengthened had he
left the scene, used one of the quarters he had bummed, and dialed
1-800-COPSHOT.
</P>
<P>
   The unfairness in this finest of technicalities bothered Eric,
and he began to lobby hard for reconsideration. ``He wouldn't let
go,'' Ms. Mortensen said. ``He was a very determined individual.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years passed, and lives evolved. The four bandits drew
closer to parole. Ms. Mortensen took a maternity leave. Eric found
a place to live and a job to keep. But he kept fighting for that
reward.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, Gallagher asked his superiors to reconsider
Eric's case. This time, for reasons that remain unclear, the Police
Department recommended to COPSHOT's board of directors that a
reward be granted to the man who had helped find four gunmen so
long ago.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Mangione, the spokesman for COPSHOT, said that the board
recently found the case clear-cut. ``The information led to the
arrest and the conviction of the suspects'' who had shot at
officers, he said. ``And that is why the board of directors _
despite his not calling the hot line _ thought he warranted
receiving that reward.''
</P>
<P>
   With money and justice in hand, Eric has moved on. But he has
that worry about publicity. And so he will remain just Eric.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
