<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHEAT-RAIN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAD WEATHER HAS BEEN BAD NEWS FOR KANSAS WINTER WHEAT FARMERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC PALMER and VICTORIA SIZEMORE LONG  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- When Eldon Lawless got up Friday morning, it
looked as if it would be a hot, sunny day in south-central Kansas.
Lawless liked the heat steaming out of the ground. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But by 8 a.m., when the bank vice president and farmer reached
his office in Wellington, it had turned hazy. The sky offered less
promise of drying out the 1,000 sodden acres of wheat that Lawless
is anxious to get harvested. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you quickly what's happening with the wheat harvest
here. Nothing,'' said Lawless, chairman of the Kansas Wheat
Commission, which pays for wheat research and marketing for the
state's most noted crop. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lawless farms in Sumner County on the Kansas border with
Oklahoma, directly south of Wichita. Sumner generally produces more
winter wheat than any other county in the state. This year promised
to be another good one before rain and hail storms damaged crops
and made the ground too mucky for combine crews to get into fields.
The area got 3 1/2 inches of rain Thursday, which followed at least
an inch a few days before, Lawless said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The longer the wheat has to stand in the fields, the greater the
chance of deterioration. That translates into fewer bushels per
acre and lower quality. And that means lower returns at a time when
wheat prices, at about $2.40 a bushel, are running well below the
cost of production. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Closer to home, the weather has raised red flags at Kansas City,
Mo., Interstate Bakeries, the country's largest wholesale
bread-baking company. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very concerned from a quality perspective,'' said Mark
Dirkes, spokesman for Interstate. ``People say the weather this
year is very similar to the weather in 1993, lots and lots of rain
before harvest. In 1993, the most common consumer complaint we
received was people asking, `What have you done with my bread? It
is dry and crumbly.' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Processing tolerances were so low that year if you mixed your
dough a little too much the bread was dry and crumbly. If you
didn't mix it quite enough, it was dry and crumbly.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas hard red winter wheat harvest began two weeks ago in
southern areas, the typical starting point, but has since virtually
stopped, said Sherri Hand, agricultural statistician with the
Kansas Department of Agriculture. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The hard red winter wheat harvest is 2 percent complete. That
compares with 31 percent a year ago and the five-year average of 16
percent. Meanwhile, 55 percent of the crop is ripe, well behind
last year's level of 77 percent, but ahead of the overall average
of 46 percent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The rain delays and other storm damage to plants in many fields
have caused Kansas agriculture officials to reduce their
projections for this year's yield. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Total Kansas hard red winter wheat production now is estimated
to be 395.6 million bushels, down from the May 1 estimate of 408.5
million. That compares with last year's total of 494.9 million
bushels. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Hailstorms either wiped out crops or reduced yields, and many
farmers are plowing the crop under and planting other crops,'' said
Hand. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the rain has made it hard to plant other crops. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the toughest harvest seasons we've faced in a long
time,'' said Kansas farmer Patty Clark, who is director of the
public policy division of the Kansas Farm Bureau in Manhattan.
``We've had nothing but rain since April 1.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Heavy rains, compounded by high winds, have forced many wheat
plants to ``wrap'' themselves and lay flat, said Clark, whose
family farms wheat, corn, soybeans and cotton in southeast Kansas. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``When conditions finally allow you to get in the field, it's
doubly hard to harvest,'' she said. ``There is not as clean a
product coming out of the combine. You take all that's going on
with the harvest combined with already low prices and a lot of
farmers are edgy, and rightly so.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Farm Bureau reported that prices farmers are getting are
running from $2.19 to $2.62 a bushel. That's far below what it
costs to produce a bushel of wheat. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Farm Bureau economist Mark Nelson said variable costs this year
for fuel, seed and fertilizer were running about $78 an acre. When
added to fixed expenses of about $45 an acre, it is costing farmers
about $125 to produce an acre of wheat. Divide that amount by how
many bushels per acre a farmer reaps, and you come up with what a
farmer should get per bushel. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For example, a farmer who gets 40 bushels an acre would have to
get about $3.13 per bushel to cover production costs. A farmer
getting only 30 bushels per acre would need $4.16 a bushel to cover
production costs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those prices don't cover the cost of the farmer's labor or
include any profit. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Each day that farmers can't get into their fields to harvest
wheat or plant fall crops means a day in which yields probably will
fall. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For planting, Clark said, the window each day is getting
narrower and narrower, and could mean a reduction in yield. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Farming is a very intricate and complicated industry that
deals with a tremendous amount of variables,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For example, even as the rain delays harvest of the winter wheat
and the planting of some fall crops -- for the fall crops that have
managed to get planted -- a farmer worries that the chemicals used
on weeds could be too diluted. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are sitting on pins and needles, and each day
those pins and needles are getting a little sharper,'' Clark said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
