<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SQUEEGEE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICER'S INTENT DEBATED IN SHOOTING OF SQUEEGEE MAN
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A day after a police officer testified that fear led
him to shoot an unarmed squeegee man at a Bronx intersection,
prosecutors and defense lawyers battled over the reality of that
fear while the judge in the case tried to pinpoint the officer's
intentions before he fired the shot.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Michael Meyer, charged with attempted murder and being
tried before a judge in state Supreme Court at the Bronx County
Courthouse, has testified that he got out of his car at a ramp of
the Major Deegan Expressway near Yankee Stadium on June 14, 1998,
because the squeegee man, Antoine Reid, refused to step away after
giving his front windshield an unwanted wash. He has also testified
that he shot Reid in the chest after pushing him and engaging in a
momentary but violent struggle that he thought he might lose.
</P>
<P>
   But when Meyer took the stand Friday, he was met by several
questions from Acting Justice John Collins, who wanted the officer
to explain, among other things, what he intended to accomplish by
getting out of his car.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was it your intention to arrest him?'' the judge asked. To
this, the officer replied that he ``just wanted him to get away
from the car,'' adding that the man was looming outside his window
and would not stop cursing in front of his fiancee's 6-year-old
son.
</P>
<P>
   He said Reid seemed ``unpredictable'' as to ``what he would
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark DeMarco, an assistant district attorney, tried to reverse
the characterization and portray the officer as the unpredictable
one, a man whose natural inclination was to get out and confront
Reid. The prosecutor questioned whether Meyer had followed correct
police procedure by getting out of his car and firing a shot on an
exit ramp that was crowded with cars.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer, off duty at the time of the shooting, did not directly
acknowledge whether he had acted according to proper procedures. He
said his decision to get out of his car was based on ``natural
instinct.'' The only thing on his mind before firing the shot, he
said, was that he was faced with an emotionally disturbed man ``who
could do serious damage to me, possibly kill me.''
</P>
<P>
   After a barrage of questions by the prosecution, Meyer's lawyer,
Murray Richman, sought to portray the officer's record in the
Police Department as one of restraint. Meyer said that he had fired
his weapon only once during more than 200 arrests over a nine-year
career on the force. According to the Police Department, most New
York City police officers serve their entire careers without ever
firing their weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Before closing the trial for the day, Collins allowed the
defense to present a surprise witness, a lawyer named Thaddeus
Mcguire, who testified that he had been menaced by Reid in April
1998, in an encounter that so frightened him that he ran a red
light.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution challenged the witness, asking him whether he
saw the squeegee man in the court. Mcguire immediately pointed to a
young black man sitting about three rows back. But Reid was not in
the courtroom; Mcguire had pointed to Reid's brother.
</P>
<P>
   DeMarco rested his case after pointing out the misidentification
for the record. Meyer's defense team later said the two brothers
looked alike and called the prosecutor's move ``dirty pool.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-25-99 2356EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
